<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY OF SECOND CHANCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ They left Southern California for towns such as
Reno, Pullman, Wash., and Fort Collins, Colo. Then they returned
home, mostly humbled and looking for a new start, a better
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Cal State Northridge became that place. The football program,
despite only three winning seasons in the 1990s, has become a haven
for players coming from bigger schools in more prominent
conferences. Thirteen Matadors, about a sixth of the roster, are
Division I-A transfers.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, CSUN's opponent tonight, Eastern Washington, has
only one Division I-A transfer on its roster. Montana, which is
ranked No. 2 in Division I-AA and the Big Sky Conference leader,
has only four.
</P>
<P>
   Several reasons have contributed to CSUN's growing reputation as
Second Chance U., including geography, a quirk in the NCAA's
transfer rules, and fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is luck,'' said CSUN interim head coach Jeff
Kearin. ``They remember us from the recruiting process. We tell
them not to forget us. Also, Division I-A coaches will call us and
say, `Hey, we've got a kid. . .' ''
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened with DeJuan Gilmore and Jermaine Hunsaker,
a pair of transfers from Washington State who are planning to leave
tickets for tonight's game for several former teammates who are an
hour away in Pullman; the Cougars play at 1 p.m. at home against
Arizona and the CSUN-EWU kickoff is 6:05.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsaker, a junior from Pomona, played sparingly at Washington
State and is happy he transferred. Gilmore, a senior from Gardena,
is a little frustrated. He left WSU last January because the
starting running back, Kevin Brown, had two years of eligibility
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, however, was kicked off the team in June when he pleaded
guilty to felony residential burglary. He enrolled at UNLV last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to live with the decision I made,'' said Gilmore, who
rushed for 305 yards and three touchdowns last year. ``I thought a
lot about what happened, but there was nothing I could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore, who could have been a starting tailback in the Pac-10
this season, isn't starting for the Matadors. He's playing behind
Jaumal Bradley, the Big Sky's fifth-leading rusher.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN does have four transfers who start: center Julio Alcala
(Colorado State), wide receiver Terrence Jones (Fresno State) and
defensive linemen Levi Line (Nevada) and Jason Mageo (Oregon
State).
</P>
<P>
   Only Mageo, who came to CSUN because he has a wife and young son
in San Diego, was a starter at his previous school. Not
surprisingly, most of CSUN's Division I-A transfers came to
Northridge looking for more playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not feel I was getting a fair chance,'' said Line, a
former Royal High standout who was low on the depth chart at
Nevada. ``I wanted to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The lure of playing right away makes CSUN an attractive choice
for transfers. The NCAA allows players going from I-A to I-AA to
have immediate eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin admits there is a downside to being known as a I-AA
school that is transfer-friendly: A player who is a troublemaker in
the Pac-10 might seek CSUN as a refuge.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 90 percent of the kids we get are really solid people,''
he said. ``We like to think (the coaches) are good judges of
character. We try to make a calculated decision on their chances of
succeeding here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
