<HEADLINE>
FEVER COULD TAKE TAILBACK OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ Tonsillitis might cost Cal State Northridge a
vital offensive player for tonight's Big Sky Conference opener.
Jaumal Bradley, a senior tailback who leads the Matadors with 201
yards over two games, stayed at the team's hotel and didn't
participate in a light workout Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley missed practice for the third consecutive day. When
asked if Bradley would be ready for CSUN's game against Eastern
Washington, which is scheduled to start at 6:05 p.m., interim head
coach Jeff Kearin said, ``Highly doubtful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless his fever breaks (Friday) night,'' Kearin said, ``he
can't play.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had a 103-degree fever two days ago. He's also battling
nausea.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can barely swallow,'' Kearin said. ``We're going to pump
him full of fluids . . . try some chicken soup.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, an All-Big Sky first-team selection at fullback last
year, had a career-high 109 yards against Kansas two weeks ago. If
he can't play, DeJuan Gilmore, a senior transfer from Washington
State, will split time with redshirt freshman Alan Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   __ Drink it up: A sure bet would be to take the over on
tonight's game. In the last three meetings between the Matadors and
Eagles, the teams have combined to average 924 yards of total
offense, including 736 yards passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate the game to go deep into the fourth quarter,''
Eagles head coach Mike Kramer said, ``and it will be decided by how
much Gatorade one team has left. There will be a lot of points
scored.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Add Kramer: The coach said he is ``intrigued'' by CSUN and
its run-and-shoot offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly wouldn't consider us a favorite anytime we face
Northridge,'' he said. ``Last year we played as well defensively as
we could have against them, and Marcus (Brady) was 21 of 28
(passing).''
</P>
<P>
   Brady must have impressed Kramer; he was actually 17 of 22 in
last year's 38-35 Matadors victory.
</P>
<P>
   __ Looking ahead: Southern Methodist, CSUN's opponent on Nov.
12, is 0-2. The Mustangs lost 26-0 to Arkansas in their opener and
53-19 to Tulane last week.
</P>
<P>
   __ Rankings: CSUN is ranked No. 21 in Don Hansen's Football
Gazette Poll, one of the four major Division I-AA polls. The
Matadors are unranked in the other three. Eastern Washington (1-2)
is unranked.
</P>
<P>
   __ Correction: Due to an editing error, it was implied in
Friday's edition of the Daily News that CSUN defensive back Mel
Miller has been academically eligible throughout the season. Miller
was academically ineligible until Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
