<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-ROOKIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERIENCE BOWS TO INEXPERIENCE, 6-2 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ The Europeans no longer can ignore the charge
that has hounded them since they arrived at The Country Club six
days ago. They are sadly lacking in Ryder Cup experience.
</P>
<P>
   Well, at least they are lacking in sad Ryder Cup experience.
</P>
<P>
   After the first day of this international showdown in which it
was supposed to serve as fodder for the veteran Americans, the
Green Team owns a dizzying 6-2 lead _ almost halfway to the 14
points it needs to accumulate in three days to retain the Cup. And
the Ryder rookies are largely responsible for that plush cushion.
</P>
<P>
   When captain Mark James's 12-man aggregation arrived here
Monday, it appeared better suited for a debutante's ball than this
crucible for world golf supremacy. No fewer than seven of his
players were first-time callers. Six of them automatically
qualified by finishing among the top 10 in the European PGA Tour
point standings. And James added yet more peach fuzz when he made
Scotland's Andrew Coltart one of his two captain's choices,
bypassing Ryder fixtures Nick Faldo and Bernhard Langer.
</P>
<P>
   Friday James employed four of those newcomers, and all they did
was open their Ryder resumes by helping Europe to four victories
and two halves _ 2 1/2 in both the morning foursomes and afternoon
four-balls.
</P>
<P>
   Individually, their records read thusly: Sergio Garcia 2-0-0,
Paul Lawrie 1-0-1, Miguel Angel Jimenez 1-0-1, Padraig Harrington
0-0-1.
</P>
<P>
   After the astounding comeuppance, James was typically
noncommittal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected them to play well,'' he said, ``but you never know
how they're going to do. I don't suppose you can count on (such
success), but they've been playing well and I expected them to keep
playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   In James's low-key lexicon, ``well'' is the equivalent of
``extraordinary.'' And in the American camp, it would translate
into ``disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, at 19 the most ungrizzled Ryder Cupper in history but
already established as a planetary phenomenon, was at the head of
the parade. He teamed with Swedish veteran Jesper Parnevik to
topple Tiger Woods and Tom Lehman, 2 and 1, in the morning and
outlast Phil Mickelson and Jim Furyk, 1 up, in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he claimed Woods, the world's top-ranked player, as
one of his pelts, Garcia's performance couldn't be considered
shocking. But the other rookie contributions were bonuses. British
Open king Lawrie got the day started with a flourish, teaming with
the most venerated European, fellow Scot Colin Montgomerie, to beat
David Duval _ who did perform like the Ryder novice he is, losing
two matches _ and Mickelson, 3 and 2. And only Davis Love's 30-foot
birdie putt on the 18th in the afternoon enabled him and Justin
Leonard to prevent a clean sweep of US foes by Montgomerie and
Lawrie.
</P>
<P>
   The unlikeliest success story, perhaps, was the
Jimenez-Harrington tandem in the morning as they earned a split
with the heavily favored Love and Payne Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington sat out the afternoon because Masters champion Jose
Maria Olazabal, who had been unhappy with his game and declared
himself unready for morning play, joined the lineup. He and Spanish
countryman Jimenez proceeded to dispatch Hal Sutton and Jeff
Maggert, 2 and 1.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought it? The Europeans, apparently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're a great team; that's the first thing,'' said
Garcia. ``I think we're doing good, and that's very important
during the Ryder Cup, to be doing good.''
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't be doing much better. These kids are all right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
