<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OREGON WORRIES USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ Paul Hackett will coach his 16th game for USC
tonight and a compelling argument can be made that this is the most
critical contest of his brief tenure.
</P>
<P>
   A game against Oregon in September that important? It might
sound crazy, but whatever happens in Autzen Stadium could have a
tremendous impact on the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   If the Trojans win, they can legitimately claim to be one of the
conference favorites, with plenty of momentum to face an
increasingly difficult schedule. If USC loses, it will be viewed as
a slightly overrated team with the prospect of road trips to
Arizona, Notre Dame and Cal in October. And no one will think last
week's San Diego State game was a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, this is the kind of game that alters the
confidence of a team for a season. Hackett certainly thinks so.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can win in this environment, that really sends a message
about our football team,'' Hackett said. ``This turns a big corner
for us if we win. Are we good enough?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very important game. This gives us a jumpstart on
the league.''
</P>
<P>
   As proof of the ramifications of tonight's contest, Hackett
believes last year's 17-13 loss to the Ducks effectively ended the
Trojans' hopes of being one of the Pacific-10 Conference's elite
teams and put a damper on the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loss, that was very painful,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   One potential pitfall that USC (2-0) believes it will avoid is
the confusion on offense that caused a delay-of-game penalty and
nullified a fourth-quarter touchdown pass from Carson Palmer to
Mike Bastianelli in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   That touchdown would have tied the game 17-17 instead of forcing
Hackett to go for a controversial field goal that cut the lead to
17-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really shot ourselves in the foot,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer expects to avoid such problems, now that the Trojans run
a simplified plan that combines using a wristband with the plays
and signaling with easier hand signals.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of that is knowing the signals more,'' Palmer said. ``I
know the system better now.''
</P>
<P>
   Oregon (2-1) lost star quarterback Akili Smith, but junior A.J.
Feeley has been extremely solid (seven touchdowns, one
interception) in his first three starts. The defense has also been
above average with the addition of linebacker Peter Sirmon, who
missed most of last season with a torn chest muscle after leading
the Pac-10 in tackles in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a difference on that football team, it's Sirmon,''
Hackett said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
