<HEADLINE>
IN MUSEUM FUROR, MAYOR CRITICIZES `CATHOLIC-BASHING' 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MUSEUM-LEHMAN) 
(lb) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As lawyers for the city plotted strategies to block a
controversial exhibition at the Brooklyn Museum of Art, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani angrily offered another argument on Friday for why
the show is unacceptable: He said it reflects a widespread
acceptance of ``Catholic-bashing.''
</P>
<P>
   On his morning radio show and at a news conference later in the
day, Giuliani reiterated his disgust for one of the works included
in the upcoming exhibition _ a portrait of the Virgin Mary made
from pornographic pictures and elephant dung _ and said that people
who offend Catholics are let off the hook too easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where it comes to Catholic-bashing, this kind of thing is
never treated as sensitively as it sometimes is in other areas,''
Giuliani, a Roman Catholic, said on his radio show, on WABC-AM.
``If this were a desecration of a symbol in another area, I think
there would be more sensitivity about this than a desecration of a
symbol that involves Catholics.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican mayor threatened on Wednesday to cut off all city
subsidies to the Brooklyn Museum unless it canceled the exhibition,
which is called ``Sensation'' and is to open Oct. 2. The city gives
the museum nearly $7 million a year in operating expenses _ almost
a third of its $23 million budget _ and has reserved another $20
million in the budget for capital improvements.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Giuliani warned that the museum could also lose its
lease, because it will not allow children under 17 to view the
exhibition unless they are accompanied by an adult.
</P>
<P>
   The lease states that museums housed in city-owned buildings
``shall at all reasonable times be free, open and accessible to the
public and private schools'' of the city and ``accessible to the
general public on such terms of admission as the mayor'' sees fit.
</P>
<P>
   By late Friday, Corporation Counsel Michael Hess had sent two
letters to the museum's director, Arnold Lehman, warning that the
museum ``cannot proceed with the exhibit as planned.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lehman said Friday night that he had no intention of
canceling the exhibition. He said the museum's board of trustees
would meet early next week to discuss the situation. ``Generally,
the trustees all feel that the museum has a mission to present
important works of art to educate the public.'' Lehman said, ``And
that is the goal of this exhibition.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani repeated his warning Friday that the city might try to
take over the museum's board of trustees to stop it from showing
offensive artwork in the future. ``I'm not going to have any
compunction about trying to put them out of business,'' he said at
a news conference in Harlem. ``Maybe that's the best way to
preserve the museum and the good parts of the museum for everyone
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Vallone, the Democratic speaker of the City Council,
warned Giuliani in a letter Friday that ``the council will not
allow you to de-fund this organization.'' But Vallone can do little
to stop him, because the City Charter gives the mayor the right to
withhold spending if he thinks it is in the city's best interest.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Association of Art Museum Directors, a national group,
released a statement supporting the exhibition. ``Every art museum
in this country is a center for the free exchange of ideas,'' the
statement said. ``If the mayor acts on his intentions, it will set
a precedent that could cripple museums across this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the directors of many of the city's prominent museums,
attending a dinner on Wednesday at the Whitney Museum of American
Art, expressed dismay about the mayor's threats, most refused to
speak publicly about the controversy Friday. Many museums rely
heavily on the city for funds.
</P>
<P>
   An exhibition that opened at the Whitney this week includes
another controversial work: a photograph by Andres Serrano of a
crucifix submerged in a jar of the artist's urine. But aides to
Giuliani said Friday that they had no interest in quashing that
show.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Levine, the deputy mayor for economic development, said
the Whitney was not in the same category as the Brooklyn Museum.
``The Whitney is not in a building owned by the city, and it has
gotten no money from the city this year,'' Levine said. ``It's a
totally different situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
