<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5627 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MUSEUM-LEHMAN-ART-NYT     09-25 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-LEHMAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING BUZZ, A MUSEUM DIRECTOR HEARS A ROAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Arnold Lehman, the aggressive, Barnum-esque director
of the Brooklyn Museum of Art, need not look far for an artistic
expression of what is at stake in his standoff with Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, who has vowed to deprive the museum of public money
because of his distaste for an exhibit of contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, the younger of Lehman's two sons made an
animated film for a class at Dartmouth College. The film, by
Zachary Lehman, is about an artist who struggles to win financial
support for a work of sculpture. Again and again, a committee of
bureaucrats rejects his request for money. Too sexist, they say of
his abstract blob. Too risque, they say. Each time, the artist
changes his sculpture to please the committee, until finally, as a
withered old man, he returns with a perfectly smooth, perfectly
bland rectangular object. It becomes his coffin.
</P>
<P>
   Zachary Lehman, 26, now a law clerk for the chief judge of the
U.S. District Court in Boston, said his film's themes were rooted
in years of passionate family discussions about censorship and
artistic compromise _ both of which, he said, are abhorrent
concepts to his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``My character succumbed to the pressure of money, and look what
happened to him,'' said Zachary Lehman, whose film won a Student
Academy Award in 1996. ``I don't see my father succumbing. There is
no question in my mind. He would not move on this issue, even if
Giuliani offered him twice as much money not to show the exhibit.
He cannot be bought. He cannot be bribed. He cannot be
blackmailed.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Lehman's room for maneuver is constricted by principle,
he has also been hemmed in by his own political miscalculations,
and by his ambition to transform a museum with a world-class
collection but an embarrassingly low attendance rate into a place
where the young and the hip go for cutting-edge art _ and maybe
even a little reggae music.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loves a show,'' said Louise Hoblitzell, former president of
the board of trustees for the Baltimore Museum of Art, where, as
director for 18 years before coming to Brooklyn in 1997, Lehman
raised eyebrows and attendance with exhibits featuring Dr. Seuss
characters and Babar the elephant.
</P>
<P>
   When Lehman, who is 55, tells the story of how he decided to
embrace this show, which includes dead animals suspended in
formaldehyde and a portrait of the Virgin Mary with a breast
fashioned from elephant dung, he cites the importance of the art _
but also the long line he saw outside the first museum that staged
the exhibit, the Royal Academy of Arts in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``It stretched all the way out to Piccadilly, I have to say,''
Lehman said in an interview. ``I absolutely knew that there would
be controversy _ and that the controversy would help to bring more
audience into the museum _ but when they got there the reward would
be that they'd be seeing really first-rate things.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman got more buzz than he had bargained for, something that
surprised colleagues in Baltimore who knew him to be, as one former
City Hall official there put it, ``fabulously political.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman seems genuinely stunned by the fury of Giuliani's
response to the exhibit. On Wednesday, Giuliani said he would cut
off all city subsidies to the museum _ nearly a third of the
museum's operating budget _ unless Lehman ``comes to his senses.''
Lehman said he never dreamed that the mayor would take such offense
to the exhibit, and he is clearly distressed that his determination
to raise the museum's profile has instead led to the museum's
greatest crisis in memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of gutsiness I don't have,'' he said. ``I'm not an
arsonist.''
</P>
<P>
   But now that Lehman is in a fight with a mayor known to play
rough, his friends and families said they cannot imagine his taking
the politically expedient road. In interviews, they repeatedly
returned to the same point as they discussed how his deceptively
genial personality is likely to shape his response to his greatest
professional test.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman is, they said, a man with a tenacious intelligence, a man
for whom there is no compromise when it comes of his essential
beliefs _ one of those being in the right of free expression. And,
they warned, if Giuliani has calculated that he can intimidate
Lehman into canceling or radically altering the exhibit, he has
picked on the wrong museum director.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's tough as nails,'' a close friend, Peter Marzio, director
of the Museum of Fine Arts in Houston, said of Lehman. Pamela
Lehman, his wife of 30 years, said: ``Where does it stop if someone
can tell you what to show? I think he would do anything to work it
out, but I don't think he will back off of the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman recently explained why he is so determined to go forward
with the exhibit, which includes works by young artists such as
Damien Hirst and Marcus Harvey. ``It's part of the challenge that
artists of our time present us with, because they all seem to abhor
complacency and they look at the world differently from you and
me,'' Lehman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
