<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS SPIN CONTINUES WITH 3-2 LOSS TO PHILLIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Chipper Jones was safely ensconced in another
country and there had been a team meeting designed to soothe their
minds and boost their spirits. But the Mets continued their
tailspin Friday night with a 3-2 loss to the Phillies. A game that
had seemed in their grasp was ripped away in a bullpen collapse
that is becoming frighteningly familiar for the Mets as they free
fall toward the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The news got worse when the Mets glanced at the scoreboard. The
Reds had come back to beat St. Louis, 5-4, so their lead in the
wild-card race shrank to one game with eight games to go. The Mets
surely do not need to be reminded that they blew a one-game lead
with five games to go last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're out of gas right now and we've got to try to fill up,''
Mike Piazza said.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a painful three-game sweep by the Braves, the Mets
wanted to use the Phillies as balm for their wounds and recover, in
the process, just a little of the peace of mind the Braves had
snatched from them this week. The news was cheering that the Mets'
bats still had some life in them after they were outscored by Jones
alone in the Atlanta series and the Mets smacked nine hits Friday
night. The smiles faded quickly in the eighth inning, however, when
the bullpen _ the reliable cog of the machine that had rolled
through the second half of the season _ broke down.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Cook walked the leadoff batter, pinch-hitter Kevin
Sefcik, and appeared to yell at the umpire as he was yanked from
the game. Then, after Turk Wendell had retired the two batters he
faced, Armando Benitez _ the fireballing closer _ came in to finish
off the inning. Instead, he gave up a run-scoring double to Bobby
Abreu that tied the score at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Benitez, who did not get a chance to appear against
Atlanta but has been a sturdy closer since John Franco was injured
during the summer, gave up a single to Mike Lieberthal. Abreu,
charging hard, scored what proved to be the winning run and you
could almost hear the air rushing out of the Mets' dugout.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had lost some of their edge after Atlanta _ Piazza
admitted the team was tight and Al Leiter wondered whether the
gloominess would hover for long. But they needed only to face the
Phillies to remind them of just how bad things could be. Once
thought to be a prime rival with the Mets for the wild card, the
Phillies had lost 23 of their previous 27 to plummet so far out of
the race that Mets fans easily outnumbered Philadelphians at
Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets were never able to blow open a lead on the
Phillies, and their play seemed without energy. There were few
mistakes, calm pitching by Masato Yoshii and a burst of offense
that had been missing in Atlanta. From the second inning _ when
Robin Ventura, who was just 2 for 10 in Atlanta, hit a solo home
run to right field _ it was clear that, while the Mets weren't
exactly going to bludgeon the Phillies, they were not facing
Atlanta. They had no trouble hitting, but never strung together
enough to get a runner past second base.
</P>
<P>
   But being the better team has not mattered in recent days. The
Mets have been busy reminding others _ and reassuring themselves _
that the Braves made mistakes too, but that Jones' home runs
quickly erased them from memory, while the Mets' blunders were the
stuff of headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a brief lapse in the fourth inning, when the Phillies
got their first hit and scored their first run, Yoshii was masterly
in his seven innings. He allowed just four hits and two walks and
used his pitches to induce a series of groundouts and pop ups.
Except for a walk and a single in the seventh inning with two outs,
the Phillies did not threaten again until the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii had won his previous five starts and during that span he
had an earned run average of 1.64. If there is a postseason in the
Mets' future, Yoshii _ banished to the bullpen in July _ may in
fact be their trustiest starter. He even scored his team's go-ahead
run on John Olerud's fifth-inning single.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a one-run game and it's one of those hold on games,''
Valentine said. ``There were some wasted opportunities and there
weren't any later in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   There certainly must be grave doubts about the bullpen now. Cook
yielded the game-winning home run to Jones in the first loss to the
Braves, and his walk turned into the game-tying run here. And
Benitez had an ERA of 1.84 entering the game, but at a most
horrible time, he lost the cool that has defined his season.
</P>
<P>
   When the final out was recorded, the Mets barely moved off the
top step of their dugout. They were standing still, motionless _ no
doubt wishing the season could be stopped in time, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
