<SLUG> BC-ENDORSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN CAMPAIGN REVEALS HULL ENDORSEMENT OF BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER, KRIS MAYES AND JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In a maneuver unusual even for the aerial dogfighting
of Arizona politics, former combat pilot Sen. John McCain announced
Sept. 24 that Arizona Gov. Jane Hull had endorsed a rival, Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Hull's office, clearly taken by surprise, denied that the
governor had endorsed Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The twists and turns over the long-awaited Hull endorsement
capped a week of bitter skirmish ing between the two camps, with
each attempting to control the timing of the announcement to its
own advantage.
</P>
<P>
   According to staff people in both camps, Hull would like to wait
for Sept. 28, when Bush will be in Phoenix for a fund-raiser, to
make her formal declaration for the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   By releasing the news Sept. 24, McCain may have blunted the
impact of the announcement next week, when McCain will officially
kick off his presidential campaign with a four-day tour in which he
will lay out themes for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain statement was as simple as it was surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I was disappointed to learn of Jane Hull's decision
to endorse Gov. Bush,'' the late-morn ing statement said, ``I am
extremely confident that the statewide grass-roots organization of
committed Arizonans that supported me in three consecutive
elections to the U.S. Senate will bring me to victory once again in
our state's presidential primary next February.''
</P>
<P>
   But Francie Noyes, Hull's press secretary, said there had been
``no official endorsement at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign apparently learned of Hull's decision to
endorse Bush on its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the kind of secret that keeps very well around the
State house,'' said Dan Schnur, McCain's national director of
communications. ``Our understanding is they have scheduled an event
for (Sept. 28).''
</P>
<P>
   According to accounts from both camps, McCain called Hull the
morning of Sept. 24 to apologize for an aide's comment published
that day in ``Political Insider,'' a column in The Arizona
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The aide, Howard Opinsky, was asked to comment on reports that
Hull might endorse Bush next week. He declined to speculate, saying
that Hull ``could drop dead of a heart attack next week, too.''
</P>
<P>
   During the brief but reportedly friendly conversation, McCain
asked Hull whether rumors that she planned to endorse Bush were
true. Hull said yes, according to sources close to the McCain
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain expressed concern about the timing of the endorsement,
which would come in the middle of his announcement tour. McCain
will begin in New Hampshire and stop in key primary states before
wrapping up the trip with an appearance in Phoenix. Hull told
McCain she could not delay the endorsement because the event with
Bush had been planned for months, McCain campaign sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Noyes would not comment on reports that Hull refused to delay an
endorsement of Bush, although she said the fund-raiser had been
planned months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been in the works for a very long time,'' Noyes said.
</P>
<P>
   Hull aides said privately that they were delighted that McCain
issued the statement, suggesting it would spread the news of the
endorsement over the weekend and into next week, giving the story a
greater chance for national publicity, a hope that underscored the
animosity be tween the two camps.
</P>
<P>
   They suggested that McCain had underestimated Hull, thinking she
wouldn't have the courage to chal lenge the entire elected GOP
estab lishment in Arizona and endorse a candidate from another
state.
</P>
<P>
   One McCain loyalist agreed that it was bold for Hull to endorse
a non-Arizonan.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be tantamount to Jerry Colangelo rooting for the
(San Francisco) Giants in the National League pennant race,'' said
Arizona House Speaker Jeff Groscost, a Republican from Mesa.
Groscost is a paid staff member of McCain's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Bush said the governor would be pleased to have
Hull's endorsement when and if she officially announces it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush has worked hard to have the endorsement of 23 gover
nors, and he would certainly wel come the endorsement of Governor
Hull,'' said Scott McClellan, a spokesman for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   A Hull endorsement of Bush would not come as a complete surprise
to observers of what has been a traditionally lukewarm and
sometimes contentious relationship between Hull and McCain, and
between their staffs.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Hull was left off an invitation list for McCain's Oct.
4 fund-raiser at Bank One Ballpark, despite the fact that GOP
presiden tial candidates routinely invite the governor to their
Arizona events. The McCain campaign sent an invitation after The
Republic reported the snub.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Bush and Hull have been close political allies.
Last September, Bush hosted a fund-raiser for Hull as she was
gearing up her re-election bid for governor. The event raised
$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Hull's support for increased edu cation spending, subsidized
health care for children of the working poor and tax cuts is
comparable to positions Bush has taken.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also backed Hull on her efforts to expand the region's
guest worker program, which seeks to legally import Mexican workers
to work primarily in agriculture and service-industry jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have suggested that a Hull endorsement of Bush could
damage McCain's standing in Ari zona, where he already trails Bush
by double digits in some polls.
</P>
<P>
   Losing the Feb. 22 Arizona primary would almost certainly be a
fatal blow to McCain. Sandwiched between early contests in Iowa and
New Hampshire and the delegate-rich California primary on March 7,
Arizona is a crucial test.
</P>
<P>
   The senator has staked his cam paign on strong showings in New
Hampshire and South Carolina lead ing to a win in California.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, McCain sought to delay the Arizona primary by
several months in an attempt to avoid devoting precious campaign
resources to a costly fight on his home turf. The ploy was defeated
by the Arizona Legislature. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
