<SLUG> BC-NJ-ABORTION-LAW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY ABORTION LIMITS NEAR AS COURT BATTLE GOES ON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., R.I., Pa.)  (rk) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Barring a dramatic last-minute intervention by
the state's highest court, New Jersey will begin Sunday to enforce
a law that requires girls under age 18 to notify at least one
parent before being allowed to end a pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   As abortion clinics and state health officials scrambled Friday
to prepare for the new law, judges in the Appellate Division of
state Superior Court denied an emergency appeal from abortion
rights advocates, allowing the law to take effect as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers from the American Civil Liberties Union, representing a
coalition of New Jersey doctors and abortion clinics, swiftly
submitted yet another appeal to the state Supreme Court and
expressed hope that the seven-member panel would rule on the matter
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to the ultimate option,'' said Lenora Lapidus,
executive director of the state ACLU, after Friday's decision.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Superior Court Judge Marguerite T. Simon rebuffed
the ACLU's request to block the state law temporarily. Her ruling
appeared to catch abortion providers and health officials off
guard.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides scrambled to comply with the measure's requirements,
including the distribution of fact sheets, which detail the steps
staff members at clinics must take to ensure parental notification.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system is not ready,'' said Phyllis Kinsler, president of
Planned Parenthood of Central New Jersey. She added: ``As a
provider, I do not have the fact sheets that I am required to have
to give to a patient before we can provide an abortion. Even if
they drop it through my skylight tomorrow, when exactly was I
supposed to train my staff to do that?''
</P>
<P>
   State officials scrambled Friday to distribute the information.
Friday afternoon, the state Department of Health and Senior
Services announced that it had just mailed the sheets to 700
hospitals and clinics statewide.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has also established a phone line for health care
providers, he said, and a 24-hour number for the public is to be
available on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey is one of 39 states, and the sixth in the Northeast,
to have passed laws requiring pregnant girls either to gain
parental permission or notify at least one parent before having an
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike like similar laws in Massachusetts, Rhode Island and
Pennsylvania, which require parental consent for a minor to have an
abortion, New Jersey's law demands only that a pregnant girl tell a
parent before proceeding with an abortion, said Jessica Waters of
the National Abortion Federation, a nonprofit group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Several exceptions allow a girl to avoid notifying a parent.
Girls who can demonstrate to a judge that they are ``sufficiently
mature'' can bypass the law, as can girls who have been abused by a
parent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
