<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TAMPA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE'S HOMER LIFTS YANKEES OVER DEVIL RAYS, 4-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rookie Alfonso Soriano's first major league hit could
not have been more memorable.
</P>
<P>
   He led off the 11th inning with a home run Friday night to give
the Yankees a dramatic 4-3, 11-inning victory over the Tampa Bay
Devil Rays before 44,932 delirious fans at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Soriano, a slightly built infielder who hit 17 home runs at
Triple-A Columbus before being recalled on Sept. 11, drove an 0-2
pitch off left-hander Norm Charlton into the left-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees trailed by two runs in the ninth inning when Darryl
Strawberry showed why he has become so valuable since being
recalled on Sept. 1. Blasting a 1-1 pitch by Roberto Hernandez off
the center-field wall, Strawberry scored Ricky Ledee to pull the
Yankees within 3-2. Then, Chuck Knoblauch, a Devil Rays killer all
night, singled to score Strawberry and send the game into extra
innings. It was Knoblauch's fourth hit of the game.
</P>
<P>
   With Oakland getting trounced by Texas, 12-4, Friday night, the
Yankees would have clinched a playoff spot whether they won or
lost. Playing down the significance of simply making it to the
playoffs, the Yankees assured reporters before the game that there
would be no postgame celebration after the feat was accomplished.
And there wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to win the division,'' said Derek Jeter, who went
0 for 4 Friday night. ``You don't celebrate when you just clinch a
playoff spot. Our goal is to win the American League East. That's
something to celebrate. Obviously, you want to get into the
postseason. It's a big accomplishment, but our mind is set on the
division.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch was outstanding all night. While the rest of the
Yankees struggled against Bobby Witt, who entered the game with a
5.96 earned run average, Knoblauch hit a leadoff homer in the first
inning, his career-high 18th home run of the season, and went 3 for
4 before the right-handed Witt was lifted with two outs in the
sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The pitching change, which brought Albie Lopez to the mound, was
more precautionary than reactionary because the other Yankees did
little against Witt. They had chances in the second and third
innings, when runners advanced to second base, but each time they
were stranded. Witt left after surrendering Knoblauch's third hit
with eight strikeouts, including two each against Chili Davis and
Scott Brosius.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez was not as hard to solve. The ball seemingly
placed on a tee, he was rocked for seven hits and three runs
through the first five innings before settling down and holding the
Devil Rays without a hit over the sixth, seventh and eighth. Unlike
Saturday's loss to Cleveland, Hernandez, who in that game walked
five batters in seven innings and was hit hard as well, was not
wild Friday night. Barring an intentional walk of Fred McGriff, he
walked only two batters.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez had his problems in the third, which he began by
walking Jose Guillen. Guillen moved to second on a passed ball,
then went to third when catcher Jorge Posada, seeing Guillen stuck
between the bases, ill-advisedly threw to second.
</P>
<P>
   The misjudgment turned out to be irrelevant because Tony
Graffanino tripled to the left-center-field gap to tie the game,
1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Graffanino put Tampa Bay ahead, 2-1, by scoring on a sacrifice
fly by Miguel Cairo, and the next three Devil Rays teed off on
Hernandez. Dave Martinez smacked a line-drive double to the corner
in right field. Jose Canseco slammed a single to center field that
nearly took off Hernandez's ankles en route, and Fred McGriff hit a
hard single to right.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Yankees, Knoblauch and Jeter were able to
turn a double play on Herbert Perry's ground ball to close the
inning at a 3-1 deficit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 0037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
