<HEADLINE>
SHEFFIELD WILL GO TO WORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Gary Sheffield learned a new position, became one
of the few team spokesmen, played with injuries that landed other
players on the disabled list, and is on the cusp of batting .300
with 30 homers and 100 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, for the first time in his career, he's going to begin
an offseason workout in a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel the Dodgers haven't seen the real Gary Sheffield,'' the
Los Angeles Dodgers left fielder said. ``I have a lot more things
to offer than I've been showing. I like putting pressure on myself.
I just feel like I can dominate for two months straight. I think
when the rest of the team isn't hitting well, I can be the guy to
carry us for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, who ices his knees and shoulder after every game,
said conditioning is a big part of dominating next season. He
weighed 228 pounds last spring. A large part of that had to do with
offseason shoulder surgery, which limited his workout ability, but
Sheffield said he could have done more to trim down to 210.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he hasn't been comfortable with the strength of his
shoulder, his legs, and that's conditioning,'' Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson said. ``He's been great, outstanding. He's a special
player. You don't do what he's been able to do in his career
without working at it. It never hurts to be in better shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield rose to prominence in 1992 by hitting .330 with 33
homers and 100 RBI with San Diego. He's motivated by what people
say he can't accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always felt it helped me when people said I couldn't do
anything,'' Sheffield said. ``They said, `He can't steal bases,' so
I went out and stole 20 bases (last season). Now they say I can't
steal 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the late `90s and going into the new millennium, they want
to see power and speed. I want to do everything better in every
category.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield entered the weekend series with San Diego hitting .299
with 29 homers, 93 RBI and a team-high 96 walks while batting third
on a team that rarely moves runners over and lacks frontline
table-setters.
</P>
<P>
   __ FYI: The Dodgers honored Class-A San Bernardino outfielder
Chin-Feng Chen and right-hander Eric Gagne, who pitched most of the
season with Double-A San Antonio, as their organizational player
and pitcher of the year, respectively. . . . For a
major-league-record 14th time, the Dodgers went over the three
million mark in attendance with the crowd of 36,356, bringing the
season total to 3,008,101. The Dodgers have drawn at least two
million in 27 straight and 35 overall seasons, both major-league
records.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
