u k BC-EDIT-ABORTION-NYT &LR;      09-25 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: STRIKING DOWN ABORTION BANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals rendered three crucial
rulings on abortion Friday, striking down as unconstitutional the
so-called ``partial birth'' abortion statutes in Nebraska, Arkansas
and Iowa. The language of the Nebraska and Iowa laws was nearly
identical to definitions used in the federal partial-birth abortion
ban proposed in Congress. The court found that all three state laws
placed an undue burden on abortion rights by outlawing even the
procedures most commonly used prior to fetal viability.
</P>
<P>
   The rulings show that efforts to undermine abortion rights
through the partial-birth ruse will not stand up to constitutional
review. Missouri, which was not a party in the three cases but is
in the 8th Circuit and will be governed by Friday's rulings,
recently enacted an extreme anti-choice law in the guise of a
partial-birth abortion ban. Gov. Mel Carnahan showed political
courage in vetoing the measure, but the Legislature overrode his
veto. The 8th Circuit decision has now shown that Carnahan was
right.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty states have passed statutes prohibiting partial-birth
abortion. These laws have been blocked by federal and state trial
courts in nearly every instance in which they have been challenged.
The proponents usually say their legislation is aimed at a single
method used in late-term abortions. But in fact, the statutes are
so broad that they can be used to criminalize the most common
abortion procedures performed at any point, even prior to fetal
viability.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's new Infant's Protection Act is among the most extreme
of these laws. It does not describe any particular medical
procedure, but makes criminal any abortion in which a fetus is
partially outside the cervix, which may occur in common procedures
used in the first trimester of pregnancy. The law provides no
exception to protect a woman's health. Under the law, the woman, as
well as her doctor and anyone who takes a ``substantial step'' to
aid the abortion, could be charged with a Class A felony. What is
most frightening is that the statute would allow people accused of
anti-abortion violence to claim as a legal defense that their acts
were necessary to protect the fetus from an illegal abortion.
</P>
<P>
   By setting a clear precedent that will render the Missouri law
invalid, the 8th Circuit court will protect women's rights and help
shield doctors in that state from a dangerous invitation to
anti-abortionists to use terrorism and violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
