<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-A'S-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ, SELE LEAD RANGERS CLOSER TO TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers thrust the final dagger deep into
their enemy once and for all. No one pronounced the Oakland
Athletics dead, but only the faintest heartbeat remains.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom suggests that the Rangers' 12-4 victory last
night at The Ballpark in Arlington decided the American League
West.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably over,'' designated hitter Rafael Palmeiro said,
``but until we clinch ...''
</P>
<P>
   That could occur as early as tomorrow. The Rangers extended
their lead on the fading-out-of-sight Athletics to 61/2 games and
reduced their magic number to three with only nine games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Juan Gonzalez drove in five runs on the strength
of three powerful swings that produced only the 10th three-home run
game in Rangers history, and right-hander Aaron Sele (18-8)
surrendered only one unearned run during a gallant, seven-inning
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came out and kicked our \Rbutt\S _ no ifs, ands or
buts,'' Athletics first baseman Jason Giambi said. ``They've been
struggling, but Texas woke up.''
</P>
<P>
   It took only a game-tying, run-scoring single by second baseman
Mark McLemore during the fifth inning before the Rangers unleashed
their fury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like somebody let an animal _ a hungry animal _ out of
its cage,'' Palmeiro said. ``We needed a spark like that, and I
think this team responded.''
</P>
<P>
   McLemore's single scored shortstop Royce Clayton from third
base, and Gonzalez hit the first of his three home runs off
right-hander Gil Heredia (13-8) only minutes later. Gonzalez's
404-foot blast on a first-pitch fastball gave the Rangers a 4-1
lead, and Sele put the Rangers on cruise control with five
consecutive scoreless innings before departing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark McLemore and Juan Gonzalez flat out took this game
over,'' Athletics catcher Mike Macfarlane said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Royce Clayton joined the power display with a two-run
homer of his own during the Rangers' six-run sixth inning, and
Gonzalez punctuated it with the second of his two-run homers off
right-hander Greg McMichael.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight, he put us on his shoulders and said, `Let's go!' ''
McLemore said. ``He's been known to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez received a curtain call from many of the 40,207
spectators after hitting No. 3 off left-hander Ted Kubinski during
the Rangers' final at-bat. Gonzalez made his way to the top step
and received his well-earned ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting for a big night like that for a long time,''
Gonzalez said. ``It's a special night for us because we needed it.
It was a very important game and a big win for us.''
</P>
<P>
   This victory relaxed what appeared to be a tense ballclub that
lost four of its previous five games at The Ballpark to the
sub-.500 Tampa Bay Devil Rays and Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole ballclub feels relieved,'' manager Johnny
Oates said. ``The first four innings, we all were pressing. I saw a
ballclub where everyone was trying to hit a five-run homer. All of
a sudden, after we took the lead, it seems all the confidence that
we've shown all year came back instantly.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
