<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DRINKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE ATTACK ON CAMPUS DRINKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Sept. 25:
</P>
<P>
   Few parents could have missed a tongue-in-cheek advertisement
for ``binge beer'' in 17 newspapers this month that was signed by
the presidents of 113 colleges and universities. Intended to alarm
parents about the ``thousands of college students'' who ``binge,''
it was a novel effort by universities to get parents involved in a
dialogue with their children before they leave home. It is
estimated that half the students who engage in high-risk drinking
in college begin drinking heavily in high school.
</P>
<P>
   The ad is promising evidence that college presidents are taking
this issue more seriously than they have in the past. The most
recent survey of college students by the Harvard School of Public
Health describes 43 percent of American college students as ``binge
drinkers.'' Binge drinkers are defined as students who have
consumed five or more drinks in a row at least once in a two-week
period.
</P>
<P>
   But college administrators are sending out confusing mixed
messages. College students are often advised in alcohol education
classes to pace themselves at one drink per hour. But since
research has shown students often attend social events for five
hours at a time, that rate would fit the definition of binging,
making the students both responsible drinkers and high-risk
drinkers at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Universities are increasingly adopting the so-called ``social
norms'' approach to college drinking, which was pioneered by
Northern Illinois University in 1990. It uses an intensive media
campaign on campus to correct students' exaggerated perceptions
about the degree of heavy drinking among their peers. This approach
is well designed for a group that is swayed by peer pressure and
wary of authorities who preach about the dark side of drinking.
Schools like Northern Illinois University and the University of
Arizona that use the approach have reported a decrease of about 20
percent in the number of heavy drinkers on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing parents into the discussion at an earlier stage and
informing students about the moderate drinking behavior of their
peers might not change the attitudes of the heaviest boozers. But
it just might work with the majority of college drinkers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 0110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
