A5656 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-ZIMBABWE-NYT &LR;      09-25 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ZIMBABWE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PRESS FREEDOMS IN ZIMBABWE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Sept. 25:
</P>
<P>
   As he struggles with economic ills and an unpopular war in
Congo, Zimbabwe's president, Robert Mugabe, is cracking down on the
independent press and its ability to question his authoritarian
rule. The most egregious violations of human rights were committed
against two journalists who were detained and tortured by the
military in January. Mark Chavunduka, editor of The Standard, a
weekly newspaper, and Ray Choto, a reporter for the same paper,
were taken into custody by the military after they published a
report about the arrest of 23 members of the army who were plotting
an overthrow of the Mugabe government.
</P>
<P>
   The two journalists were severely beaten, tortured by electric
shocks and brought near drowning by having their heads submerged in
containers of water. The brutal treatment was conducted in an
attempt to force them to reveal their confidential sources about
the failed coup. Neither man would give up his sources. A court
ordered that the men be released to civilian authorities, but they
have been charged under the colonial-era Law and Order Maintenance
Act, which makes it a crime to publish false information ``likely
to cause fear, alarm or despondency.'' If convicted, they could
face seven years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Chavunduka, who is a Nieman Fellow at Harvard University this
year, will have to return to Zimbabwe for a hearing on Oct. 4. He
has appealed to the country's Supreme Court on grounds that the
charges are unconstitutional. International human rights and
journalistic groups have demanded that all charges against him and
Choto be dropped. But Mugabe has criticized the news media and the
judges who urged the journalists' release. The independent press in
Zimbabwe is small and deeply threatened. Unless the Mugabe
government reverses course and brings the torturers to justice,
this harrowing case will be proof that the government is willing to
destroy basic freedoms to silence dissent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 0111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5658 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-TAX-CUT-NYT &LR;      09-25 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TAX-CUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AFTER THE TAX CUT VETO 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Sept. 25:
</P>
<P>
   Now that President Clinton has vetoed the Republicans' $792
billion tax bill as expected, Congress and the White House can
settle down to the difficult business of negotiating on next year's
budget. Time is short. With the budget year starting officially in
less than a week, few of the spending bills needed for the start of
the fiscal year have even passed Congress. Washington seems poised
for another last-minute showdown or a series of continuing
resolutions to keep the government going.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who rejected any tax cut before other more pressing
matters are resolved on Capitol Hill, reflected how much the
political world has changed in recent years. Tax cuts were once as
popular as kissing babies and knowing the words to ``The
Star-Spangled Banner.'' The problems with this tax bill became
obvious in August when members of Congress went home to find that
for many people their anti-tax rhetoric had a stingy ring to it.
Cutting taxes for the already rich began to sound like cutting
benefits for everybody else. Moreover, stimulating a booming
economy with a tax cut could stir fears of inflation and trigger
higher interest rates, economic developments that can cause near
panic in millions of people who watch the Dow like a relative's
heart monitor.
</P>
<P>
   This week the president noted correctly that the Republican bill
he vetoed was ``too big, too bloated,'' burdening the economy while
rewarding the rich, the lobbyists and campaign contributors. The
veto, however, was the easy part. The president now has a far more
difficult task of finding common ground with a Congress that
prefers the politics of Clinton-bashing. It might help that
Clinton's veto statement had less venom than expected, an unwritten
White House invitation to focus on a decent budget package and a
more reasonable use of the federal surplus. Congress and the White
House should find some agreement on how to preserve Medicare while
relieving prescription drug costs for the elderly, protect Social
Security, retire debt and, as political dessert, offer any modest
tax cut with what is still available. Clinton's veto message
Thursday rightly urged Congress not to ``throw in the towel'' or go
home early while these more complicated matters, especially
Medicare and Social Security, remain untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William Roth, R-Del., chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, and Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., the senior
Democrat on the committee, could push for a ``down payment'' on
Medicare reform. It would offer Moynihan a crowning achievement
before next year's retirement and provide Roth with a crowing point
for what is expected to be his toughest re-election campaign. The
season for working out areas of agreement on these matters is now,
while the president has the budget bills as leverage and before
next year's elections turn complicated issues into political bumper
stickers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
