<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN ONE CLOSER TO 20
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a drama-less season on the field, the Los
Angeles Dodgers finally have some little off-Broadway thing that
could give meaning to a few of their remaining eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Kevin Brown, thanks to his pitching and his bat,
has a chance to be the Dodgers' first 20-game winner since Ramon
Martinez did it in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Brown allowed one run in eight innings and drove in a run to
beat his old team, the San Diego Padres, for the first time in
three tries. The Dodgers' 5-1 win at Dodger Stadium on Friday also
pushed them past the Padres into third place in the NL West.
</P>
<P>
   In his other two starts against the Padres since signing on with
Team Fox for seven years and $105 million, Brown was 0-2 with an
8.05 ERA. That included a horrific nine-run outing in San Diego on
June 30.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Brown allowed five hits and struck out eight. He
walked one.
</P>
<P>
   The win leaves Brown (18-8) with one more start at San Francisco
Wednesday, and if he wins, Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said Brown
will most likely be brought on three days rest in next Sunday's
season finale at Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Brown won 21 games with the Texas Rangers in 1992. His
next-highest total is 18, which he also accomplished last season.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the opportunity to win 20 games doesn't overshadow
the Dodgers' dismal season, but it does demonstrate how well Brown
has pitched on a team that has managed 73 games.
</P>
<P>
   And while Brown shut down the Padres' lineup with another
awesome display _ he was 7-2 with a 1.74 ERA in his previous 12
starts _ it was his sacrifice fly in the seventh inning that gave
the Dodgers a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Beltre led off with a walk, stole second and went to
third on Paul LoDuca's single to left. One of the Dodgers' many
bugaboos this season has been their inability to score runners from
third with less than two outs, but Brown took care of that. He
lined a Sterling Hitchcock (12-13) pitch deep into left field to
allow Beltre to score.
</P>
<P>
   A one-run lead late is usually enough for Brown, but the Dodgers
broke it open with three runs in the eighth. Eric Karros gave the
Dodgers a two-run lead with his team-leading 109th RBI, a single
through the right side of a drawn-in infield.
</P>
<P>
   Two batters later, Devon White smashed a two-run homer to right
off reliever Carlos Reyes. White's 13th homer gave the Dodgers a
5-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres' first two batters reached _ singles by Quilvio Veras
and Tony Gwynn _ and they took a 1-0 lead when Reggie Sanders
grounded into a double play. The next time San Diego had a base
runner was on Veras' two-out single in the sixth. After the
run-scoring double play, Brown retired 15 straight, including six
by strike out.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers weren't exactly lighting up Hitchcock, but they did
break through for a run in the third inning. However, it took four
hits to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Young led off with a single but was caught stealing
(actually, picked off) for the 21st time in 71 attempts.
Grudzielanek followed with a single and eventually scored on Raul
Mondesi's two-out single to right as the Dodgers tied it 1-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
