<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1996 LOSS TO D.C. HAUNTS GALAXY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ As the Los Angeles Galaxy prepares to face
D.C. United tonight at the Rose Bowl, many players wonder what
might have been had L.A. won the inaugural Major League Soccer
championship in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In MLS' most memorable match, the Galaxy blew a 2-0 second-half
lead in the MLS Cup at Foxboro, Mass. United's Eddie Pope knocked
in the game-winner, finishing a Marco Etcheverry corner kick with a
header to the near post to give D.C. a 3-2 sudden-death overtime
victory.
</P>
<P>
   More triumphs followed for United. There was another MLS
championship in 1997 and U.S. Open Cup, CONCACAF Champions Cup and
Interamerican Cup titles.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy, meanwhile, hasn't been able to return to such
heights. It has gone through two coaches, two playoff disasters, a
change of ownership and earned the reputation of winning in the
regular season, but not championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering it's only been four years, I wouldn't compare us
with the Cleveland Indians or Utah Jazz, other pro teams that have
found postseason disappointment in the 1990s,'' said striker Cobi
Jones, one of four Galaxy players left from that '96 team.
</P>
<P>
   Why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because you guys are the ones asking the questions and making
the comparisons, not us,'' he said. ``It was a tough game to lose
and it became the league's first big rivalry, but it's too early to
give us that label. The Indians and Jazz have been at it a lot
longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but others can understand the comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with the fans and media; we haven't won anything
yet,'' said midfielder Mauricio Cienfeugos. ``And that perception
is going to remain the same until we do.''
</P>
<P>
   United (22-7, 54 points) and the Galaxy (18-10, 48 points) still
have the league's best rivalry. They enter today's match with the
best records in their respective conferences. If they stay on
course, they could meet Nov. 21 where it all began _ in Foxboro,
site of this year's MLS Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``That championship (in '96) is hard to forget, especially when
you're reminded of it all the time,'' said Cienfuegos. ``And now
there's a commercial on ESPN that shows images of that championship
game. It just reiterates what happened. All you hear about is D.C.
United because they won the championship. Nobody ever talks about
the second-place finisher.''
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos said the '96 game certainly had a psychological
effect, one that the Galaxy won't rid itself of until it wins it
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it (the '96 loss) definitely may have turned the faith
of our team and organization,'' Cienfuegos said. ``But we can't do
anything about it now. We didn't win it then, but now we have a
chance to go back to the same place and win it in November.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 0116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5662 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-COLLEGE-BOARD-2NDLD-W     09-25 1502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-BOARD-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-925&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
S.A.T. ORGANIZATION IS SET TO JOIN WEB'S EDUCATION GOLD RUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ADDS 4 grafs at end.) (th) 
 By JODI WILGOREN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Under threat by the rapidly growing online industry that helps
students prepare for and select colleges, the College Board, the
nonprofit organization that administers the SAT, voted Friday to
create its first for-profit subsidiary in a move to establish a
flashy full-service Web site of its own.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous vote of the College Board's 24 trustees is a
radical shift for a staid 100-year-old group best known as the
objective overseer of college-entrance exams, thrusting an
institution honored for its dispassionate conservatism into the
big-money world of Internet start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   It follows a spate of new advertisement-driven online ventures _
including an upgrade just this week of the Princeton Review's Web
site _ focusing on the lucrative high-school and college market, a
trend that has raised concerns about the commercialization of
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not willing to give up our not-for-profit expertise to
somebody who's just in it for the money,'' said Gaston Caperton,
who took over as president of the College Board in July. ``We have
the right values. We have the right goals. What we have to do is
have the right capital and expertise to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan for a Web site to cater to a college applicants' every
need, from financial aid forms to SAT tutoring, marks the
convergence of two major trends in education in the 1990s: the
expansion of for-profit enterprises, and the explosion of
electronic endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're living in a world of piranha economics in regard to
education,'' said Arthur Levine, a scholar of higher education who
is president of Teacher's College at Columbia University. ``Every
Wall Street firm, seemingly, has an education department. Venture
capitalists are moving into this very quickly. Any nonprofit that
fails to recognize both the opportunities and the challenges that
come from the digital world is destined for extinction.''
</P>
<P>
   While most experts, including Levine, admired the College Board
for diving into a wave they see as inevitable, some said the
venture presents a conflict-of-interest. The plan calls for
Caperton to serve as the new company's chief executive, and the
trustees to retain majority-control of its board.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a pure educational mission, the organization would
now have the added motivation of money. That means trying to sell
products to students lured to the site, say, to register for the
Scholastic Assessment Tests, with the knowledge that a successful
Website could eventually go public and make everybody involved
rich.
</P>
<P>
   Caperton said it had to be a for-profit subsidiary in order to
entice the $10 million he has lined up in initial investments, and
to attract technological talent in a sphere where stock options are
essential to any job offer. But critics were more cynical.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're doing is drawing on their reputation and the
institutional endorsement they've had over the years and using that
to turn a dollar,'' said Scott Rice, an professor of English at San
Jose State University who is writing a book about the influence of
money in schools. ``A testing agency should be purer than Caesar's
wife. That's hardly the case if they're going to enter the
marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed site, www.collegeboard.com, would offer free or
low-cost tutoring for the tests the College Board sponsors and
guidance in navigating the admissions process.
</P>
<P>
   It would be funded in part by advertisers hawking computers,
cars and credit cards, with commercial links for everything from
opening a bank account to buying and selling furniture for dorm
rooms. Eventually, Caperton believes the new site could be used to
train teachers for Advanced Placement courses, or even to teach
those classes to students.
</P>
<P>
   The organization hopes to unveil the Web site by late spring.
Viewers who log on to the .com address now are logged into the
College Board's current .org site.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed venture comes at the conclusion of the most
competitive college-admission season in history. It would join a
flourishing cyber-crowd _ including the test-preparation giants
Princeton Review and Stanley Kaplan _ attempting to cater to that
throng.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to www.kaplan.com and www.review.com,
collegeboard.com would also compete with CollegeQuest.com,
embark.com and CollegeNet.com, all Web sites trying to serve as a
kind of electronic guidance counselor holding students' hands
through the college-selection process _ and making money along the
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's student loans or computers, a lot of people are
starting up these sites because advertisers want to reach these
kids,'' said John Katzman, the president of Princeton Review, whose
site charges colleges $2,000 to post their sales pitches, and plans
to eventually offer $800 test-prep courses online. ``You're hitting
the most achievement-oriented, brightest high-school seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   In a similar trend, some 500 colleges and universities have
contracted with a new company, Campus Pipeline, to run Web sites,
complete with advertising, on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   And Harvard University is currently pondering five paths it
could pursue in cyberspace, including a harvard.com venture that
would attempt to exploit for profit the school's platinum name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rule nothing out,'' Harvey Fineberg, Harvard's provost, told
the Boston Globe earlier this month. ``The boundaries between
for-profit and not-for-profit are much more flexible than they ever
were.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts estimate that the 56 million Americans between the ages
of 10 and 24 have some $278 billion of disposable income. About 5
million students are currently online, a number projected to
quadruple in the next three years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The College Board's current Website, www.collegeboard.org, gets
about 50 million hits a month, officials said, and if current
trends hold, online registration for the Oct. 9 Scholastic
Assessment Tests will attract about 1 million students, or one out
of every three test-takers.
</P>
<P>
   But the current College Board site _ which will remain active
for guidance counselors and admissions officers _ is
``old-fashioned,'' Caperton said, filled with ``written stuff that
is put on the net.'' Plans for the new site are far more
interactive, with all the bells and whistles of the dot-com world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have to be innovative, aggressive, and use the same
kind of resources our competitors are using,'' Caperton said.
``This is an aggressive step. You've got to be aggressive in
education.''
</P>
<P>
   The venture is a somewhat natural brainchild for Caperton, the
former Democratic governor of West Virginia, whose political legacy
was bringing computers to his state's impoverished schools. After
leaving office in 1996, he also focused on technology when he ran
the Institute on Education and government at Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a departure for the College Board, a membership
organization of some 3,300 schools and institutions that meets its
$250 million budget mainly through test-registration fees, dues and
sales of practice-exam books. It remains unclear what the role of
the colleges and other member institutions will be in the new
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to change the culture,'' said Donald M. Stewart,
Caperton's predecessor at the College Board, who ran the
organization for more than 12 years. ``Rather than having people as
volunteer educator-consultants, they'll have to be paid. If their
information and talent and ideas are being tapped for commercial
purposes, then this is a different culture. It's a different set of
incentives to participate.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's unanimous vote was the crucial nod from the board
necessary to start the company, but Caperton must return to the
trustees, possibly as soon as next month, for another vote once the
details are worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a complete change, but it doesn't take us away from the
business we're about doing,'' said Patricia Martin, a trustee who
also works for the Education Trust, a nonprofit in Washington that
focuses on equality in the move for educational standards. ``I
don't think we can survive in the business that we try to do if we
continue to do business the way we've always done it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jonathan Zittrain, executive director of the Berkman Center
for the Internet and Society at Harvard, said nonprofit educational
organizations would be going down the wrong road if they tried to
compete with Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is out of balance when you have those who should be holding
down the fort for dot-org and dot-edu all jumping on the dot-com
bandwagon when they see what they have merely as a brand to be
exploited,'' Zittrain said. ``The caution for them is if it isn't
your core mission, you're going to get eaten alive by someone for
whom it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 0125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
