<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COLUMN-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ drain energy here.
</P>
<P>
   Information on utility readiness has been gathered by the
government and the electricity trade association, but neither group
will release the reports' raw data, which includes readiness levels
of individual power facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lights will probably not go out. And a prolonged
nationwide blackout will almost certainly not occur,'' said
Bennett, a Republican from Utah. ``But in order for the public to
have as much information as possible, the names of all unprepared
power facilities should be released.''
Yet another scam
</P>
<P>
   A woman in Tampa, Fla., has been charged with trying to con
motorists into paying $15 for a fictitious Y2K state identification
card from a nonexistent state agency.
</P>
<P>
   Under the scheme, Cindy Lou Boyer allegedly sent out
official-looking documents from the ``Florida Agency of Registered
Tags'' to some 2,400 residents in two counties, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The notices, which included specific vehicle information, asked
recipients to pay $15 for a state ID tag magnetically coded with
driving records and personal information, records show. Boyer faces
a felony charge, 15 years in prison and a $10,000 fine.
</P>
</TEXT>
