<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5667 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-Y2K-COLUMN-2TAKES-KAN     09-25 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COLUMN-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTS OF Y2K COMPUTER VIRUSES INCREASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FINN BULLERS and DAVID HAYES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Just when we thought the Y2K hype was dying
down, a whole new Y2K computer scare is causing a stir.
</P>
<P>
   Reports have been surfacing recently about the potential for a
deluge of computer viruses that could be unleashed around the end
of the year. One anti-virus software maker was quoted as suggesting
that ``up to 200,000'' viruses could be released around Jan. 1 _
all triggered by a New Year's date or planned to resemble a Y2K
crash.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, well...maybe. But maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   Two leading anti-virus software makers _ Symantec Corp. and
Network Associates _ have said virus makers will try to take
advantage of Y2K unknowns and create computer chaos. One expert,
Carey Nachenberg at Symantec's Anti-Virus Research Center in Santa
Monica, Calif., was quoted earlier this month using the 200,000
figure.
</P>
<P>
   Nachenberg, chief researcher at the center, said his comments
were taken out of context when he talked about the issue with
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Nachenberg said he said something like ``could be two, could be
200,000.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Friday, Nachenberg said he does expect Y2K to
spark new computer viruses, but he said he doesn't have any idea
how big the problem will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a handful or more,'' Nachenberg said. ``Your
guess as to how many is as good as mine.''
</P>
<P>
   However, not everyone agrees with the two software companies.
</P>
<P>
   A British software company, Sophos, said its competitors were
using Y2K as a ``scare-mongering'' tactic to sell products.
</P>
<P>
   And ICSA Inc., an independent consulting firm that tests and
certifies anti-virus software, said the problem may not be as
severe as the hype would lead us to believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our take is that, while there's a little bit of potential
extra danger, it's nothing extreme,'' said Roger Thompson,
technical director of malicious code research for ICSA.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certainly the possibility that virus writers could
exploit the danger,'' Thompson said. ``But anti-virus companies are
all going to be vigilant around that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, four viruses that target the fear or hype
around Y2K already have been released by virus writers ``out in the
wild,'' Nachenberg said. The most common targets Microsoft Corp.
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft customers have receiving bogus e-mail claiming to be
from ``Support &LR; Microsoft.com.'' The e-mail says it includes a
special Year 2000 countdown clock for Microsoft Windows. The
attachment carries a name like ``y2kcount.exe.''
</P>
<P>
   The attachment actually is a Trojan horse program that, when
opened, loads and executes files that steal a user's personal
information _ including password, login and user name. The e-mail
states:
</P>
<P>
   From: support &LR; microsoft.com
</P>
<P>
   Subject: Microsoft Announcement
</P>
<P>
   To All Microsoft Users,
</P>
<P>
   We are excited to announce the Microsoft Year 2000 Counter.
</P>
<P>
   Start the countdown NOW.
</P>
<P>
   Let us all get in the 21 Century.
</P>
<P>
   Let us lead the way to the future and we will get YOU
</P>
<P>
   there FASTER and SAFER.
</P>
<P>
   Area businesses are taking the Y2K virus threat seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sabotage is what it is,'' said Rick Yarnell, director of
internal audits for the Board of Public Utilities in Kansas City,
Kan. ``And all it takes is some 16-year-old out there who just
can't resist the temptation. Y2K is the perfect time.''
</P>
<P>
   To fight back, the Kansas City, Kan., utility, along with
several other companies across the country, is considering pulling
employees off the Internet a day or two before Jan. 1, Yarnell
said.
</P>
<P>
   No outside e-mail would be permitted, unless it was crucial.
Warnings would be posted telling computer users not to open e-mail
attachments from sources they don't recognize.
</P>
<P>
   The BPU plans to upgrade its virus alert software, and beyond
that has been planning security improvements at all pumping
stations and substations. BPU officials don't discuss specific
security measures, Yarnell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done what we can, we've fixed everything, we're testing,
we're making our contingency plans,'' Yarnell said.
</P>
<P>
   At any given time, 200 to 300 viruses are active somewhere in
the world, said Nachenberg at Symantec. About 45,000 viruses have
been cataloged by researchers over the years.
</P>
<P>
   To combat computer viruses, experts suggest that consumers use
anti-virus software and keep it up-to-date by visiting the software
manufacturer's Web site and downloading updates regularly.
</P>
<P>
   And because viruses most often come as attachments to e-mail,
they suggest that consumers never open an e-mail attachment unless
they know who it came from and why it was sent.
More disclosure
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Senate's top Y2K watchdog is calling on the Department
of Energy and the North American Electric Reliability Council to
disclose the names of power plants unprepared for Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-five percent of all electric utilities do not routinely
share Y2K readiness reports directly with the public, said Sen.
Robert Bennett, chairman of the Senate's Y2K committee.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City is no exception. For example, reports made by KCP&AMP;L
to the North American Electric Reliability Council on the utility's
Y2K readiness are not released to the public, but are shared with
corporate customers.
</P>
<P>
   The documents contain propriety information, utility spokeswoman
Pam Levetzow said, and could give competitors a business advantage.
The more important thing, she said, is that two independent audit
firms have given the utility a Y2K thumbs up.
</P>
<P>
   Through billing inserts and press statements, every Kansas City
electric utility has given assurances they are prepared for the
Year 2000. But with the country's 3,200 utilities connected to a
national grid, outages elsewhere could drain energy here. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
