<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5683 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDERCUP-SPI &LR;      09-25 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDERCUP-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUGH RYDER: U.S. FALTERS, EUROPE ROLLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ If you've got a life ring, throw it. The
Americans are taking on water and bailing like crazy.
</P>
<P>
   The Ryder Cup forecast that called for sunny skies and
dispositions has turned mostly cloudy with a threat of tears from
United States captain Ben Crenshaw.
</P>
<P>
   After the heavily favored Americans fell behind, 6-2, to the
supposed featherweights from Europe Friday, long shadows and faces
dominated the rolling landscape of The Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Europe expanded on its 2{-to-1{ morning lead in alternate-shot
competition with a 3{-{ thrashing of the U.S. in the afternoon
four-ball format.
</P>
<P>
   The European partnership of Jesper Parnevik and Sergio Garcia
won two matches each while Tiger Woods, David Duval and Phil
Mickelson all went 0-2.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, the best player in the world, is now 1-5-1 in Ryder Cup
play. He and Duval, the world's second-best player, lost to Lee
Westwood and Darren Clarke, 1-up, in the afternoon four-ball.
</P>
<P>
   With his Oakleys off in the waning light, Duval played the role
of hacker, hitting a wild drive and chunking a chip on 18. Everyone
was bewildered by his display and by the overall performance of the
U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Sutton and Jeff Maggert were the only American winners
Friday, prevailing over Westwood and Clarke in the morning
alternate-shot.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, while the passionate Crenshaw discussed what
happened, media members took their own shots, directing all
wisecracks toward the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do they adjust the handicaps for tomorrow?'' wondered one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Boston. Do you think they'll boo these guys?''
wondered another.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-2 deficit was supposed to be Europe's predicament. Neither
team has been this far behind after the opening day since the U.S.
was down 6-2 in 1987 at Muirfield. Now Europe can retain the Ryder
Cup if it wins only eight of the next 20 matches.
</P>
<P>
   If this were a fight, the referee would be checking the
Americans' eyes, looking for a coherent response. But European
captain Mark James refused to give the opponents a standing eight
count.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're far too clever, far too solid,'' he said. ``I would
never underestimate their powers of recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   In the other four-ball confrontations, Miguel Angel Jimenez and
Jose Maria Olazabal beat Sutton and Maggert, 2 and 1; Parnevik and
Garcia defeated Mickelson and Jim Furyk, 1-up; and Colin
Montgomerie and Paul Lawrie halved their match with Justin Leonard
and Davis Love III, who prevented a 4-0 European afternoon sweep by
drilling a 30-footer at the 18th hole.
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of fight in the red and white, but blue was
more evident because it described the mood of the U.S. team,
suddenly down in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were playing well, but those guys (Europeans) played
tremendous,'' Crenshaw said. ``That's what happens in match play.
We need to see a few more putts go in.''
</P>
<P>
   All day long, there were shots of adrenaline, games of
one-upsmanship, tit for tat. These guys are better than good. At
the par-4 eighth, Parnevik knocked in an eagle-2 from 140 yards
away, the ball landing and spinning left, directly into the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Then Olazabal made a 30-foot birdie putt only to see Sutton
match it with one from 25 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia pitched one in for eagle at No. 14, where the steady
breeze turned a 534-yard par-5 into an easily reachable hole in
two.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrie eagled the hole with a 30-footer, only to watch Love sink
his eagle putt, another right-to-left bender. After it went in,
Love and Leonard went face to face, jawing at each other, caught up
in the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, naturally, spliced his presence into the highlight reel.
He executed a flop shot from left of the 10th green that ran smack
into the flagstick, causing an eruption audible all over the
course.
</P>
<P>
   But the Americans made too many mistakes and not enough putts.
Mickelson was the tragic figure of the day, losing both of his
matches, the first with Duval, the second with Furyk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lefty'' yanked it right on two birdie putts, both from 5 feet
or less, on the 16th and 18th holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to make those putts and just didn't,'' Mickelson
said. ``They started pretty much in the middle of the hole and just
tailed off. They weren't very aggressive strokes.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Parnevik: ``I was really feeling for Phil on that last
hole. I actually hoped he would make it. No one deserved to lose
that match.''
</P>
<P>
   This is how bad it got for the fans: When Mickelson knocked it
close at 18, chants of ``USA, USA'' ensued, even though the
American team had a chance to win a half-point at most.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Love earned at the 18th, rescuing the Americans, who
for part of the day were just trying to save par and face.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing if we're playing terrible and can't find the
planet, but we're all playing pretty solid,'' Woods said after the
morning round.
</P>
<P>
   That was before Duval nearly drove the 15th green. The only
problem: he was playing the 18th hole, slicing his drive right of
right, out of Brookline and into Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans weren't Yankee doodle dandy in the morning,
either. The only American breakthrough was provided by the least
heralded twosome of Sutton and Maggert, who defeated Westwood and
Clarke, 3 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   The United States' No. 1 combination of Duval and Mickelson were
surprised by Montgomerie and Lawrie, 3 and 2. Montgomerie sank
several key putts and Lawrie did not bogey a hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ryder Cup brings out the best in me, and I'm glad it
does,'' Montgomerie said.
</P>
<P>
   In the premier morning match, Woods and Tom Lehman were upstaged
by Parnevik and Garcia, 2 and 1.
</P>
<P>
   The gallery following this foursome was 10 people deep in
places. At the par-5 14th, the entire hole was lined from tee to
green. If you wanted to see one of the shots, you had to time your
jump, have long tiptoes or be equipped with one of the many black
periscopes available for purchase here.
</P>
<P>
   Former President George Bush and his wife, Barbara, wandered
into the media dining room in time to watch Parnevik on the big
screen, closing out the match with a 10-foot birdie putt at 17.
</P>
<P>
   Fans came to watch the ballyhooed matchup between the two
youngest stars in golf, but Garcia had a reminder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Europe against the USA, it's not Sergio against Tiger,''
he said. ``Everyone needs to understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their intent, the fans were enthusiastic, waving flags,
attempting to rally the home team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're huge crowds and they all want American to win,''
Lawrie said. ``They're all shouting USA. Obviously it's difficult,
but you just have to play your game.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Americans were water in a sink, they couldn't find the
drain. That's what their putting was like Friday. Lehman's
struggles were typical of the team's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I either misread them or read them correctly and had the wrong
speed. Frustrating,'' Lehman said. ``We let it get away.''
</P>
<P>
   Love felt the same way. He and Payne Stewart salvaged a
half-point in their match with Padraig Harrington and Jimenez when
Love's par-saver at 17 circled the hole and dropped.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Moore can be reached at 206-448-8013
</P>
<P>
   or jimmoore &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
