<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5685 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-TRADE-POLICY-2NDTAKE-     09-25 0210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-POLICY-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Kan. _ terms and treaties.
</P>
<P>
   At the partnership's labor-issues seminar Friday, United
Steelworkers of America political director Bill Klinefelter said
denial of fast-track support for Clinton is the high card in
organized labor's hand _ and members aren't hesitating to play it.
</P>
<P>
   The steel industry has been hit especially hard by foreign
trade, Klinefelter said. Some 300,000 production jobs have been
lost in recent years, leaving only 170,000 U.S. workers in the
steel industry.
</P>
<P>
   NAFTA-inspired trade is having the same ripple effect now in
other industries, he said, and the long-term effect should frighten
every American.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we destroy and export these good-paying jobs, we are going
to have a divided society...that will destroy the roots of
democracy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Daley also carried a message that resonated beyond economics
and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In a breakfast presentation to a blue-ribbon audience of local
corporate leaders, a video was shown that promoted NAFTA and the
larger stage of international trade.
</P>
<P>
   Its closing thought: ``International trade may be the most
powerful catalyst for peace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 0158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
