<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5686 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-TRADE-POLICY-2TAKES-K     09-25 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-POLICY-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION PROTESTERS AGAINST U.S. TRADE POLICY GREET COMMERCE
SECRETARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Kan. _ Labor union protesters welcomed U.S.
Commerce Secretary William M. Daley to the Kansas City area Friday
with signs declaring, ``US Trade Policy Stinks'' and ``Put People
Before Profits.''
</P>
<P>
   Seated in a chartered bus that rolled slowly past the small but
vocal crowd outside the Jack Reardon Civic Center in Kansas City,
Kan., Daley glanced at the protesters and sighed deeply. He
acknowledged that the nation's free trade stance causes some
dislocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be winners and losers,'' Daley said.
``There's no doubt about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with unemployment at record lows, with the economy in the
greatest boom in history, I think we've had more winners,'' said
Daley. ``Some people just want to ignore that.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, one of about 30 picketers on hand said she
could not ignore the losers.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Frances Russell, of Our Lady of St. Rose Parish in Kansas
City, Kan., said the 5-year-old North American Free Trade Agreement
has triggered a parade of jobs moving from American to Mexican soil
in search of cheap labor.
</P>
<P>
   But those Mexican workers are often exploited, she said, while
Americans are left to find other work, often at lesser pay.
``(Under NAFTA) some people are making profits and some people are
losing. That's not the American way. It's tragic,'' Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   Daley, the government's ranking business official, brought his
national bus tour to Kansas City this week to attend a three-day
Summit of the North American International Trade Corridor
Partnership, with Kansas City, Kan., serving as host.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership of government and business leaders from the
United States, Canada and Mexico was formed earlier this year after
four years of talks aimed at fostering greater trade from Winnipeg
to Mexico City across a broad swath of middle America that includes
Kansas City, Oklahoma City and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Other regions with international road and rail corridors have
similar pro-trade groups, said Rick Childers, northwest Missouri
manager for the Missouri Department of Economic Development.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this group is farther ahead of any other like it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 cities from the three nations are members; more were
expected to formally be added this week.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting in Kansas City, Kan., also drew Mexico's top trade
official in the United States, Javier Mancera.
</P>
<P>
   American controversy over NAFTA is not lost on officials south
of the border, he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand the wariness'' of American workers, Mancera
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mexico must deal with Mexico's economic problems. And, he
said, the positive effects of NAFTA south of the border have been
``astonishing.''
</P>
<P>
   It is telling, Mancera said, that ``all three countries have the
lowest jobless rates in our histories'' in the post-NAFTA years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the (organized) labor critics are wrong,'' he
said. ``Trade is not a zero-sum game. There is this goal of
increasing the size of the cake so there are more slices for
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   But some critics won't listen, Mancera said. ``Numbers are not
going to convince them. It (NAFTA) is an ideological issue for
them. Some people want to have a protectionist economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their arguments are rational,'' Mancera said. ``But the
numbers have proven them wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Partnership delegates were awash this week in economic
statistics that argue the pro-NAFTA case.
</P>
<P>
   In this region:
</P>
<P>
   - Total exports from Kansas and Missouri of merchandise alone
topped $10 billion last year, up from $6 billion before NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   - Total exports from Kansas City area firms exceed $3.8 billion,
up from $2.2 billion before NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   - Post-NAFTA unemployment is down in Missouri and Kansas and is
well below national averages in both states, while real personal
income is up.
</P>
<P>
   But foes offer numbers, too.
</P>
<P>
   The most alarming, they say, is the NAFTA-fueled U.S. trade
deficit with foreign nations that is running at a record rate this
year of $247 billion _ far ahead of last year's record $164.3
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going on is unprecedented,'' said protester Tom Bogdon
of the Greater Kansas City Fair Trade Coalition, which organized
Friday's demonstration. ``It's like a family living on a credit
card. Pretty soon it's going to mess up the economy pretty badly.''
</P>
<P>
   Another anti-NAFTA rally speaker, Craig Volland of the Kansas
chapter of the Sierra Club, claimed Friday that NAFTA, among other
things, was a scheme to build new highways to Mexico and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Labor representatives and others are holding their own
fair-trade summit Saturday at Royall Hall on the University of
Missouri-Kansas City campus.
</P>
<P>
   Daley's main message Friday to the partnership's estimated 300
attendees was a plea to educate their workers and citizens that
free and open trade among nations will pay long-term dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Deepening controversy _ such as that displayed on the sidewalk
outside the Reardon Center _ is poisoning the U.S. effort, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixty percent of Americans believe that (international) trade
is bad for their jobs,'' said Daley, citing recent poll findings
that prompted his road tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk to your friends and neighbors, your constituents. Tell
them how trade creates more jobs than it costs...Tell them they may
be `invisible' exporters, because they supply companies who export
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without public support, we'll have trouble in Seattle in
November when President Clinton launches a new round of global
talks,'' Daley said.
</P>
<P>
   Those World Trade Organization sessions in Seattle will attract
150 nations' trade ministers, and Daley pledged that workers'
rights, the environment and other issues stirring American emotions
are high on the president's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Without public and ultimately congressional support, Clinton
will not have the so-called ``fast track'' authority he desperately
wants in Seattle that will allow him to negotiate trade terms and
treaties. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
