<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5687 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-GWYNN-LADN-(SLANG     09-25 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GWYNN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GWYNN KEEPS HITS COMING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was a few minutes before 4 p.m. at Dodger
Stadium. One group of Los Angeles Dodgers was playing pepper in
front of the dugout while another was playing a fierce game of
hacky sack. These are the things teams do in September in lieu of a
pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   Several San Diego Padres players were just arriving at the park
for the 7 p.m. start. Only one Padre was in uniform, and he was
running lonely wind sprints in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, it was Tony Gwynn, providing proof, not that anyone
needed it, that 3,000 hits hasn't changed him.
</P>
<P>
   Seven weeks removed from a single in Montreal that etched his
name in baseball history, Gwynn was back doing all of the things
that enabled him to make history working a little harder and
staying focused on his work.
</P>
<P>
   It likely won't surprise you, either, to learn that the Long
Beach product has hit .346 since getting his 3,000th hit, or that
he had a 16-game hitting streak this month, or that he's had eight
multiple hit games in September, or that he would rank sixth in the
National League batting race at .330 if he had enough plate
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, nothing's changed. ``I'm still a scrub,'' he
said with one of his roaring laughs.
</P>
<P>
   There's more truth there than you'd think. When Gwynn looks back
on the 1999 season and how it fits in his career, he realizes that
the two months he was occupied by the march to 3K were an anomaly.
For perhaps the only time in his hit parade, a moment got in the
way of his work.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn was on target to reach 3,000 in May before a calf injury
started playing havoc with his playing time and success. Multiply
that by family concerns and snowballing media attention and you had
one frustrated future Hall of Famer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot,'' said Gwynn before Friday's game. ``I put a
lot of pressure on myself. Because of the injury and fanfare, I
wanted to hurry up and get it done. But it was bigger that I
thought it was. The hardest thing to do in this game is play when
you're putting pressure on yourself. It's a tough enough game to
play when you're relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some success, but I just didn't do the things I normally
do. The whole experience is one I'll remember because of the lesson
I learned. People have a hard time believing it, but you can spend
18 years in this game and still learn some things.''
</P>
<P>
   Free and easy is the way Gwynn had always played. For the most
part, it's the way he's played since No.3,000. He had first-inning
and sixth-inning singles against the Dodgers Friday, giving him
3,057 hits in his career. He recently passed ex-Angel Rod Carew on
the all-time list and currently stands 18th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anything else I could go through that
would be at that level,'' Gwynn said. ``If anything does, I'll know
better how to deal with those demons.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn has thoroughly enjoyed the tributes he's received. Padres
management went over the top celebrating his achievement. The
pregame ceremony for his first game back home lasted more than an
hour and included video tributes from friends and baseball
colleagues and an original song written and sung by his daughter
Anisha.
</P>
<P>
   Early this month, Gwynn attended a postgame party thrown by the
club that turned out to be a surprise roast. Old photos were blown
up into life-size images, including a shot of Gwynn when he was at
San Diego State ``wearing a large Afro and a bad suit,'' said Gwynn
and another when he and one-time teammate Steve Garvey were dressed
in Shakespeare-era garb for a San Diego Globe promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom has a blast,'' Tony said. ``But I almost killed Dave
Winfield for cracking wise with some Luther Vandross jokes.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also knows it's now behind him. As fantastic as that
night in Montreal was, the hit doesn't rank as his most memorable
moment. His two World Series appearances (1984, 1998) meant more,
and so did a few of his batting titles.
</P>
<P>
   He'd love to see the Padres contend for a pennant again next
season, and they've had two streaks in '98 that were promising. The
Padres went 24-7 during a span in May and June, and came into
Friday's game 16-10 in their last 26.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to have another injury-free season. Gwynn, 39, was
hoping 1999 would give him insight into how much longer he could
and would want to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``This season was supposed to be a measuring stick,'' said
Gwynn, who had 220 hits in 1997 at the age of 37. ``Now I don't
know. I can't judge things on 100 games. I'll have to go back to
work this off-season and get my legs sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next year might be the last year, or the first of two or three
more. I truly don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows what he would like. He would like to catch Willie Mays,
who stands 10th on the all-time hit list at 3,282, Gwynn said. With
a few more hits on top of that, he could pass Paul Molitor (3,319)
and become the all-time leader of his generation ('80s-90s).
</P>
<P>
   And only five players in history had 3,500 hits Pete Rose
(4,256), Ty Cobb (4,189), Hank Aaron (3,771), Stan Musial (3,630)
and Tris Speaker (3,514). If Gwynn could play until he's 42 or 43,
he'd have a shot at making it a six-pack.
</P>
<P>
   There's precedence for hits after 40, too. Honus Wagner had 415
more hits and Carl Yastrzemski 410 after reaching 3,000 at the age
of 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting into the top ten would be quite a feat,'' Gwynn said.
``It's reachable.'' Especially for someone who still runs wind
sprints after his 3,000th hit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 0200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5688 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-BKN-CLIPS-ANALYSIS-LA     09-25 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPS-ANALYSIS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS ARE GOING DOWN WITH OWNERSHIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You hereby are sentenced to hard time at the
happiest place on earth ... last place!
</P>
<P>
   That's the marketing battle cry from ``Prisonland,'' which is
what would exist if the Los Angeles Clippers were a theme park.
It's a small-payroll world, after all.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the darkest week in the blistered history of a
franchise that even Ziggy would feel qualified to heckle.
</P>
<P>
   So we have waded through years of refugee horror stories and
decided it's time to embrace the pervasive Clippers-incarceration
analogy. The philosopher who accepted the challenge of pushing this
comparison over the top is David Falk, the NBA's go-to agent.
</P>
<P>
   Falk, who deals with more big stars than the late Carl Sagan,
recently was hired by lame-duck Clipper Maurice Taylor. Taylor
happens to be one of the most-promising power forwards in league
captivity.
</P>
<P>
   Our inspiration for rolling the word ``captivity'' before you
was provided by Falk's observation of Taylor's status.
</P>
<P>
   ``His sentence,'' said Falk of Taylor and pausing between
phone-compromised bites of his Thursday lunch, ``will expire on
June 30. If the Clippers don't want to compound the felony, they'll
trade him now.''
</P>
<P>
   The sentence in question represents the final year of Taylor's
initial three-year contract. By now, even the slightly curious fans
should be aware that Falk and Taylor have demanded the
league-maximum contract extension ($70.9 million for the six
seasons following the imminent campaign). Moderately savvy
observers also should know Clippers owner Donald T. Sterling
publicly backed by the teeth-grinding loyalty of his front-office
staff refuses to fork over the loot.
</P>
<P>
   The Clips in a press release attributed to basketball ops V.P.
Elgin Baylor made the obvious conclusion official Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Falk issued his law-dog rebuttal Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day,'' Falk said, ``it all boils down to one
separate thing: he (Sterling) owns the rights to a 70
million-dollar asset (Taylor), and he's going to get nothing for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Clippers can avoid ground zero by executing a trade
before Falk's undisclosed (to the media), pre-training camp
deadline, but they don't exactly have leverage. When asked if
Taylor will report to camp for the Oct.4 check-in, Falk said he's
still hoping his client will be traded by then.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can get a player, someone who can probably start for them
at power forward, and a (draft) pick,'' said Falk, without naming
names. ``They're not going to get anyone great.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if confronted by a sweet deal their loose salary-cap
position would allow, Sterling figures to shoot it down if the
player in question will earn more this season than Taylor's
bargain-budgeted $1.367 million.
</P>
<P>
   What an ugly way to run a franchise.
</P>
<P>
   If measured against the Clipper drama, ``The Shawshank
Redemption'' would be reduced to the status of a buddy comedy.
Before seeking a solution, let's define the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last 18 years,'' Falk said, ``what's been the one
constant in that organization?''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Sterling, this victory lap is yours. Please run backward.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, an attempt to solicit Sterling's side of this
issue was unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Marching on, we are here to assure the casual Clipper doomsday
theorist that the trail for almost every franchise disaster leads
back to the owner's doorstep. If you think the L.A. Clippers have
represented the best personnel intentions of Baylor, you're as
unplugged as the Sports Illustrated writer who referred to Elgin's
brain as processed cheese food.
</P>
<P>
   So what gives with this Sterling character?
</P>
<P>
   He says he wants to win, but it seems safe to reason that losing
doesn't bother him enough if at all.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't bothered him enough to re-sign seven former Clippers
who were top four picks in lotteries the franchise has had the
dubious thrill of visiting since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   But the current mess smells worse than all of the others.
</P>
<P>
   The Clips now have Lamar Odom and Michael Olowokandi aligned
with Taylor in what could have been the best young frontcourt in
the league.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Sterling has instructed his beleaguered employees to
question Taylor's true value. If he's worth 71 million scoots, why
did the team win just nine times in 50 games last season? Why did
he show up out of shape last season and average only five rebounds
per game?
</P>
<P>
   But if he's not worth the risk, why will a more historically
astute franchise pay him the max next year? And if Taylor is
allowed to leave, can they acquire a player of his caliber to
replace him? No. Who will be your first offensive option? Who will
be the recipient of Odom's superlative passing skill?
</P>
<P>
   If Sterling's hackneyed strategy is sound, why do the Clippers
ride the lottery pony almost every June? Employee morale rivals
that of the poor jokers who were paid to assemble the Ford Pinto.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's value is not determined by last season's stats and a
post-lockout 10 pounds around the midsection. Taylor's value is
determined by what the NBA market will bear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
