observers also should know Clippers owner Donald T. Sterling
publicly backed by the teeth-grinding loyalty of his front-office
staff refuses to fork over the loot.
</P>
<P>
   The Clips in a press release attributed to basketball ops V.P.
Elgin Baylor made the obvious conclusion official Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Falk issued his law-dog rebuttal Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day,'' Falk said, ``it all boils down to one
separate thing: he (Sterling) owns the rights to a 70
million-dollar asset (Taylor), and he's going to get nothing for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Clippers can avoid ground zero by executing a trade
before Falk's undisclosed (to the media), pre-training camp
deadline, but they don't exactly have leverage. When asked if
Taylor will report to camp for the Oct.4 check-in, Falk said he's
still hoping his client will be traded by then.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can get a player, someone who can probably start for them
at power forward, and a (draft) pick,'' said Falk, without naming
names. ``They're not going to get anyone great.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if confronted by a sweet deal their loose salary-cap
position would allow, Sterling figures to shoot it down if the
player in question will earn more this season than Taylor's
bargain-budgeted $1.367 million.
</P>
<P>
   What an ugly way to run a franchise.
</P>
<P>
   If measured against the Clipper drama, ``The Shawshank
Redemption'' would be reduced to the status of a buddy comedy.
Before seeking a solution, let's define the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last 18 years,'' Falk said, ``what's been the one
constant in that organization?''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Sterling, this victory lap is yours. Please run backward.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, an attempt to solicit Sterling's side of this
issue was unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Marching on, we are here to assure the casual Clipper doomsday
theorist that the trail for almost every franchise disaster leads
back to the owner's doorstep. If you think the L.A. Clippers have
represented the best personnel intentions of Baylor, you're as
unplugged as the Sports Illustrated writer who referred to Elgin's
brain as processed cheese food.
</P>
<P>
   So what gives with this Sterling character?
</P>
<P>
   He says he wants to win, but it seems safe to reason that losing
doesn't bother him enough if at all.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't bothered him enough to re-sign seven former Clippers
who were top four picks in lotteries the franchise has had the
dubious thrill of visiting since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   But the current mess smells worse than all of the others.
</P>
<P>
   The Clips now have Lamar Odom and Michael Olowokandi aligned
with Taylor in what could have been the best young frontcourt in
the league.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Sterling has instructed his beleaguered employees to
question Taylor's true value. If he's worth 71 million scoots, why
did the team win just nine times in 50 games last season? Why did
he show up out of shape last season and average only five rebounds
per game?
</P>
<P>
   But if he's not worth the risk, why will a more historically
astute franchise pay him the max next year? And if Taylor is
allowed to leave, can they acquire a player of his caliber to
replace him? No. Who will be your first offensive option? Who will
be the recipient of Odom's superlative passing skill?
</P>
<P>
   If Sterling's hackneyed strategy is sound, why do the Clippers
ride the lottery pony almost every June? Employee morale rivals
that of the poor jokers who were paid to assemble the Ford Pinto.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's value is not determined by last season's stats and a
post-lockout 10 pounds around the midsection. Taylor's value is
determined by what the NBA market will bear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
