<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5690 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-SPRINT-MCI-2NDTAKE-KA     09-25 0446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-MCI-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTWOOD, Kan. _ with the Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Esrey's first obligation is to shareholders,'' said
Ferrugia of AG Edwards. ``From a strategic perspective, WorldCom is
a much better partner for Sprint than Deutsche Telekom.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts think Sprint's primary shares of stock are worth $60 to
$65 a share to a buyer like MCI WorldCom. Sprint PCS may be valued
at more than $100 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the past experiences of MCI WorldCom's chairman,
Bernard Ebbers, much of that value would be justified by projected
costs savings.
</P>
<P>
   A one-time farmer who still keeps his headquarters in the
relative backwater of Clinton, Miss., Ebbers has parlayed a string
of 60 acquisitions into one of the most impressive collections of
telephone businesses in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Most industry observers were astounded when the relatively
unknown WorldCom Inc. made its $37 billion bid for MCI last year.
Wall Street, however, applauded the deal when Ebbers promised
collective savings of $20 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the MCI WorldCom merger savings are projected to come
from the integration of things like service provisioning and
billing, and lowered network costs.
</P>
<P>
   Staff cuts may actually form a smaller portion of the overall
picture. But observers say they have been significant, going well
beyond the combined 2,300 layoffs that the company announced last
December.
</P>
<P>
   Layoffs might be more pronounced with a Sprint acquisition,
analysts say. Projected savings would have to be enormous to
justify a combination of the two companies.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers acknowledge that there would be no need for two
accounting departments, two consumer and business marketing groups,
two network groups, two regulatory and public affairs staff, two
headquarters administrative staff...
</P>
<P>
   MCI did maintain a headquarters in Washington after its merger
with WorldCom. But in the event of a merger with Sprint, it's
unlikely the combined entity would need three.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Marcusse, president and chief executive officer of the
Kansas City Area Development Council, said it was too early to
discuss the implications of a specific deal between Sprint and MCI
WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does show that we can never, ever take something for
granted,'' Marcusse said. ``We can't take Sprint for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not unreasonable to think Kansas City could benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   That means economic-development officials would have to convince
Sprint's merger partner that Overland Park is a better place to
base the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't hesitate to make that case,'' Marcusse said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
