<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5693 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-SPRINT-MCI-2TAKES-KAN     09-25 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-MCI-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT REPORTED DISCUSSING MERGER POSSIBILITIES WITH RIVAL MCI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTWOOD, Kan. _ Sprint Corp. executives are talking with
counterparts at rival MCI WorldCom about a possible merger of the
nation's .MDSD/.MDNM/No. 2 and .MDSD/.MDNM/No. 3 long-distance
carriers, according to people close to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies refuse to comment on what they refer to as
speculation. Indeed, reports of Sprint's impending acquisition are
so common that one spokesman for the company says he often feels
like he's living in the movie ``Groundhog Day.''
</P>
<P>
   But according to one person close to the company, talks have
moved beyond a cursory dialogue between chief executives to staff
discussions about how the two companies would meld operations and
structure a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reported Friday that MCI WorldCom might
acquire Sprint's core long-distance and local phone operations for
stock, and exchange a new MCI WorldCom tracking stock for the stock
that tracks Sprint's wireless company, Sprint PCS.
</P>
<P>
   Any such deal might take months to complete. There's also no
assurance that the companies could come to terms.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, any agreement would be subject to intense scrutiny by
communications and antitrust regulators, who might not be inclined
to see the long-distance industry dominated by the two merged
companies and AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   But for Sprint Chairman William T. Esrey, who has built an
enviable collection of communication businesses, the time may be
right to consider a combination. Analysts say the company lacks the
girth of rivals as they grow through acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, the crop reaches an optimal stage for
harvest,'' said Tony Ferrugia, an analyst with AG Edwards who gives
the deal a better than 50//50 chance of happening. ``After that, it
starts diminishing in value...Sprint needs to look for a partner to
continue to create the kinds of returns for shareholders that it
has in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The combination of the two long-distance rivals would create a
behemoth rivaling AT&AMP;T. It would wield a 30 percent market share in
the $80 billion domestic long-distance industry, compared to AT&AMP;T's
48 percent share.
</P>
<P>
   The company would also control some local telephone operations
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly for MCI WorldCom, which lacks any wireless
assets, Sprint owns one of the fastest growing and best positioned
wireless companies in the country, Sprint PCS.
</P>
<P>
   Such a deal would leave Kansas Citians holding their breath as
they waited for news of headquarters relocations and possible job
cuts as the new company sought cost savings to please Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint is the area's largest private-sector employer, a
significant taxpayer, charitable contributor, and irreplaceable
client for many local businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Next Friday, the company plans to cut the ribbon on its new $920
million corporate campus in Overland Park, Kan., a complex slated
to house 3,500 employees by the end of the year, and 16,000 by 2003
as the company consolidates staff now scattered around town.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of any acquirer completely removing Sprint's
Kansas City area presence is remote. But observers say the impact
of a company like MCI WorldCom buying Sprint would be felt far more
keenly than potential suitors like Germany's Deutsche Telekom,
which has virtually no assets in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be a disaster for Kansas City compared to some of
the other operations that might be considering buying them,'' said
David Scott, president of Birch Telecom and a former employee of
Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's impact on Kansas City's economy is so far-reaching that
it's hard to put a number on. But a recent study by the County
Economic Research Institute attempted to do just that for Johnson
County.
</P>
<P>
   The research institute calculated that the construction of
Sprint's new campus alone was expected to result in 34,877 new or
retained jobs and more than $2 billion in increased industry output
in the county during the duration of the project.
</P>
<P>
   When completed in 2003, Sprint's campus is expected to generate
a total annual payroll of about $1.12 billion, the study concluded.
Sprint puts that number at just below $1 billion, which is still
nearly 10 percent of the county's total personal earnings in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   And that doesn't include an additional 35,000 jobs that the
campus would spin off.
</P>
<P>
   The County Economic Research Institute study calculated an
annual bottom line impact of Sprint's campus on Johnson County of
$6 billion. That number ignores Sprint's impact on the Missouri
side of the state line.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the intangible benefits of having a huge worldwide
corporate headquarters in town, such as the ability to attract new
companies and talent to the city, or Sprint's charitable
contributions, which totaled $5 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``They obviously have an enormous impact on our economy,'' said
Doug Davidson, vice president and director of applied research at
the County Economic Research Institute. ``The hope is that if they
do merge, they would retain their local employment, maybe even
expand here.''
</P>
<P>
   That scenario would be far more likely if Sprint were to merge
with a company like Deutsche Telekom, a move that has been the
focus of consistent speculation for the last six months.
</P>
<P>
   The German company has no assets in the United States, would
need a U.S. headquarters, and would have little incentive to trim
staff in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom and France Telecom each own 10 percent of
Sprint and are partners with Sprint in the troubled international
alliance, Global One. Neither company could block a deal with MCI
WorldCom, according to Sprint spokesman Bill White.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just like any other shareholder,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   From a Sprint shareholder's perspective, a deal with MCI
WorldCom may be more lucrative over the long run than one with the
Europeans. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 0209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
