<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5695 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-FAMILY-REUNION-KAN &LR;      09-25 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-REUNION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEPARATED BY TIME AND DISTANCE, A FAMILY REUNITES IN KANSAS CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN BORMANN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ After 53 years, it was a small, handwritten
airport sign bearing a Russian surname _ Turkin _ that reunited a
family separated by the economy, geography and the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   There were hugs, tears, kisses and questions _ lots of questions
_ when Rhetta Goldstein of Prairie Village, Kan., and her cousin,
Tsilya Makhtyuk, met Friday afternoon at Kansas City International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   To onlookers, it was a typical airport family meeting. To the
Turkin family, it was a reunion half a century in the waiting.
Makhtyuk, formerly of Belarus, made the trek from Milwaukee, where
she had moved in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The women thought they had relatives, but knew nothing of one
another before this year. Makhtyuk had searched for her American
cousins upon arriving in the United States, but the Turkin name
never surfaced. Goldstein knew family members had been left behind
when her father, Morris Turkin, joined siblings in Kansas City
about 1913.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, 78, dreamed of meeting her relatives but never
expected it to happen. The only clues to start a search from were a
few photos and letters. The addresses predated World War II, the
last time family members corresponded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was before the Iron Curtain fell in Russia,'' Goldstein
said.
</P>
<P>
   An aunt in Russia had asked Turkin to send eyeglasses. Her son
was to marry soon, and he also would need a prayer shawl for the
ceremony. A niece wanted Turkin to help her move to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Turkin sent the items, just as he had sent money to his family
for many years. But it was the last letter he would send to Russia,
and he received no more letters from his homeland. The Cold War
began, and Turkin was told he could cause political problems for
his family if a letter with a U.S. address arrived. Helping his
niece move was virtually impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were afraid we would make trouble for them. I don't know if
he even tried to write anymore,'' Goldstein said.
</P>
<P>
   He made the right decision, Makhtyuk, 71, confirmed through an
interpreter Friday. She remembers receiving the letters, and even
wrote one herself. She remembers how dangerous it became for her
family to communicate with Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always invited (the family) to come to the United
States,'' Makhtyuk said through her niece. ``But it was
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   There wouldn't be another invitation until 1996, when
Goldstein's brother, Marshall Turkin of Boca Raton, Fla., went to
central Russia and wrote letters to anyone who might know of a
Turkin.
</P>
<P>
   Two letters arrived from Belarus, but there was no definite
connection until a letter postmarked from Milwaukee reached Turkin.
Makhtyuk had moved there to flee Belarus.
</P>
<P>
   The cousins will spend the weekend catching up with one another
and several other relatives who live in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many questions we have to ask these cousins of
ours. We have to start back 50 years,'' Goldstein said. ``I want to
find out what happened to the others in Russia. It's all very
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   If there are any regrets this weekend, it will be only that the
older generation cannot be here to hear the stories, Goldstein
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late in life, we all decide to find out about our roots,'' she
said. ``We let it go by and let it go by until it's too late.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
