<HEADLINE>
REPORTS OF MISSOURI RIVER COMPROMISE APPEAR TO HAVE BEEN
PREMATURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ There are signs that a Missouri River
compromise _ hailed last month as a historic achievement _ may be
starting to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Missouri officials refused to sign the agreement
until they obtained more information. As a result, the Missouri
River Basin Association has decided to delay submitting the plan to
federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little discouraging that we didn't ink the deal, so to
speak,'' Richard Opper, executive director of the basin
association, said Friday. ``But we're still hopeful.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Opper announced the association was near a
``historic consensus.'' The eight states in the basin association
had agreed on how the river's flows should be managed at times of
drought, the most difficult period in which to get agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But at a meeting Monday in Glasgow, Mont., the association's
directors _ which represent eight states, including Missouri and
Kansas, and a group of American Indian tribes _ decided to delay
until November submission of their plan for operating the Missouri
River.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Missouri hopes the U.S. Army Corps of
Engineers, charged with operating the river's flows, will run new
computer models and answer questions about the proposed compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just waiting on the data,'' said Mimi Garstang, chief of
water resources for the state Department of Natural Resources.
</P>
<P>
   Garstang said the corps provided some data but used an old
computer model and state officials weren't able to determine how
the proposed plan might affect river users in Missouri, primarily
farmers and the barge industry.
</P>
<P>
   But she said the delay shouldn't be taken as an indication that
Missouri opposes the compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``(DNR Director) Steve Mahfood would like to try and stay with
the plan,'' Garstang said. ``He feels there are great benefits from
a consensus plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have to wait until we have the facts to make a
decision,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The states have argued for more than a decade over how the river
should be managed. Differences hardened in the drought of the late
1980s and early 1990s. The corps, using an old Master Manual guide
for controlling flows, continued to release water from upstream
reservoirs to keep downstream barges floating. That left marinas
miles from shore, and it angered upstream politicians.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, not so long after the 1993 flood, the corps proposed
changing the river's operation. It would allow a bigger spring
rise, as the river might naturally do, and benefit fish and
wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   But criticism from many quarters quickly flowed. Lower river
states protested, worrying about barges and farmers. Federal
wildlife officials said it wasn't enough. A year later, the corps
pulled the plan.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the corps had hoped that the basin association would
help it come to a compromise, getting the eight member states to
agree on what to do during the next drought. Last month, corps
officials were elated by the prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the corps, as well as others in the Missouri basin hoping
for a compromise among the states, will have to wait about a month
longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sure hoping this can be overcome,'' Paul Johnston, a
corps spokesman in Omaha, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If it is, Johnston said the corps plans to release to the public
its proposed plan to control flows before Christmas. A series of
public hearings and comment sessions will follow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
