<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINIMED-APPROVAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINIMED GETS GOOD NEWS FOR INSULIN PUMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON Z. COHEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The federal government ruled Friday that Medicare
recipients may receive coverage for external insulin pumps, a
product whose market is dominated by MiniMed Inc.
</P>
<P>
   MiniMed, based in Sylmar, controls 80 percent of the U.S. market
for external insulin pumps, a device that delivers a programmed
dose of insulin to patients with Type I diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said the approval means private insurers
likely will follow the government's lead and pay for the pumps for
their clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``At its basic core, it reflects the growing acceptance of
insulin pump therapy,'' said Eric S. Kentor, MiniMed's senior vice
president and general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Following the announcement, the company's stock jumped $2.8125
on heavy trading volume Friday, closing at $98.25. Investors
believe the approval will result in additional sales for MiniMed,
analyst Kurt Kruger of Banc of America Securities said earlier in
the week.
</P>
<P>
   Kentor said the increase in business is likely but predicting
how much it will be is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of sales, we would understandably expect to get some
incremental sales. We don't have a real good handle on specifically
how many Medicare beneficiaries have Type I diabetes,'' Kentor
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company hopes to marry its insulin pump technology
with another of its products, a sensor that monitors insulin
levels. The idea would be to create a machine that monitors insulin
and blood sugar levels and distributes insulin accordingly,
mimicking the activity of the pancreas.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
