<HEADER>
A5699 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w BC-LAWMAKERS-LOBBYISTS-K     09-25 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWMAKERS-LOBBYISTS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY FIND LIFE AFTER CONGRESS AS LOBBYISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The door never really closes on members of Congress
when they leave office. In fact it's thrown open so wide that many
of them can hardly resist returning to Capitol Hill as lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   With unmatched access to old colleagues and Capitol backrooms,
138 former members of Congress have become lobbyists, according to
a recent report by the Center for Responsive Politics covering the
year 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri has six lawmakers-turned-lobbyists, all former House
members. Only three bigger states _ Texas, New York and Illinois _
have more ex-congressmen registered as lobbyists. Kansas has two,
the study said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Former members have advantages outsiders never have,'' said
Paul Hendrie, who worked on the study as communications director of
the Center for Responsive Politics. ``They know the process inside
out and they've built relationships with colleagues.''
</P>
<P>
   That isn't necessarily bad, Hendrie said, unless a lawmaker
anticipates a future as a lobbyist and so votes in ways that
benefit potential future employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to assume their representatives and senators are
working for them and no one else,'' Hendrie said.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, ex-members of Congress cannot lobby former
colleagues for at least one year after leaving office, although
they can have indirect influence as lobbying consultants.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Sen. Russ Feingold, a Wisconsin Democrat, proposed
extending the one-year lobbying ban to two years. He got the
proposal onto an appropriation bill, but it was removed by a
Senate-House conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   One former member of Congress from St. Louis who is now a
lobbyist said he knew of no colleagues who harbored lobbying
ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, most of them figured they weren't going to leave
unless they were carried out,'' said Jack Buechner, a Republican
who served from 1987 to 1990. ``The second thing is, they had a
greater ambition in life than to become a lobbyist.''
</P>
<P>
   But lobbying is a path more and more former members of Congress
seem to be taking. Reports indicated more than 100 former members
lobbying in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbying has grown as an industry at a time when corporations
and associations need a stronger voice in Washington, said Tom
Coleman, a Republican who represented northwest Missouri, including
Kansas City, North, for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the growing role of government and regulatory control,
business has to be represented to make sure fairness and equity are
involved in the process,'' said Coleman, who represents a chemical
firm, BASF Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Slattery, a former House member from Kansas who left in 1994
to make an unsuccessful bid for governor, said it is understandable
that companies would look to former members of Congress to lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who needs help in Washington is going to want someone
who knows Washington,'' Slattery said.
</P>
<P>
   Former members of Congress are granted lifetime access to the
House and Senate floors, cloakrooms and members-only dining rooms
and other Capitol niches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line between a congressman and a former congressman is
pretty thin,'' said Wendell Bailey, a Republican who represented
southwest Missouri in the House in the early 1980s and now lobbies
part-time. ``You can pretty much do anything a congressman can do
except vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Under House rules, former lawmakers may go on the House floor
but are not supposed to talk about bills they have pending. The
Senate has no such rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people, including myself, consider it bad form to go
lobby members of Congress on the floor,'' said former Democratic
Rep. Alan Wheat of Missouri. Wheat said if he wanted to lobby, ``I
do what other people do: make an appointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Those appointments can be much easier to get if you used to be
in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to buy my way into the office by being a campaign
contributor or taking their staffs out for endless lunches,''
Buechner said. ``You may not win, but you get your time in office.
That's the critical part.''
</P>
<P>
   That type of access, coupled with knowing how to get bills
passed, makes ex-members of Congress extremely marketable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big firms wave obscene amounts of money at them,'' said Bill
Hogan of the Center for Public Integrity. ``For all those who say
what a sacrifice it is to serve in Congress, the truth emerges when
they leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Although lobbyists don't have to report their salaries if they
work for a lobbying company, it is not difficult for someone to
easily exceed their $136,000 congressional salary.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Responsive Politics reported recently that $1.42
billion was spent on lobbying in 1998, and that clients of the top
50 firms paid between $580,000 and $3.6 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Former members of Congress who pursue lobbying do not always do
it as soon as they can. Wheat, for instance, Ieft office in 1994 to
run for Senate; lost; worked for CARE, the international relief
agency; helped manage President Clinton's re-election campaign in
1996; then established Wheat &AMP; Associates, which lists nine
clients.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman practiced law privately for 1 1/2 years before being
asked by BASF to join the company as a lobbyist and adviser.
Coleman said the firm wooed him for almost a year.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Volkmer, a Democrat from Missouri, began lobbying for the
National Rifle Association a little more than a year after being
defeated for re-election in 1996. Volkmer fought gun-control
measures in the House, unusual for a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They contacted me right after I got out,'' Volkmer said.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA paid Volkmer $80,000 to lobby last year, records show,
but he said he does mostly consulting work and only goes to Capitol
Hill occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   For some former members of Congress, lobbying is attractive as a
means of staying in a city they have come to like for its history
and power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thomas Wolfe was right: it's hard to go home again,'' Buechner
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Wheat and Slattery said they'd rather be back in Missouri
and Kansas, if not for the professional opportunities in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   One former congressman from Missouri said he had no interest in
staying in Washington as a lobbyist or anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I left Washington in December of 1996, I never went
back,'' said Mel Hancock, a Missouri Republican. ``I had enough of
it. I saw all the deals cut that I wanted to see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
