<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS STROLL PAST ANGELS IN 10 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Mariners second baseman David Bell said he's never
understood the meaning of ``unsung hero,'' the term engraved on the
award he won before Friday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   Allow Lou Piniella to interpret.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy that really doesn't get the publicity that other players
get, but that's steady, reliable and can be ready to do a good job
every day,'' said the Mariners manager. ``And basically, that's
what David is.''
</P>
<P>
   Unsung as he is, Bell has had moments of glory. Last Friday
night, he homered in the ninth to beat Minnesota. Friday night, his
10th-inning sacrifice fly gave the M's a 4-3 victory over the
Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners nearly were beaten by Anaheim first baseman Darin
Erstad, who singled off Paul Abbott to tie the game in the eighth,
then gave the Angels a 3-2 lead with a solo homer off Jose Mesa in
the tenth.
</P>
<P>
   But Angels closer Troy Percival, pitching with an inflamed right
shoulder, walked Ken Griffey Jr. and Edgar Martinez in the bottom
of the inning. Shane Monahan pinch-ran for Martinez. Percival threw
a wild pitch, putting runners on second and third. Tom Lampkin's
sacrifice scored Griffey with the tying run. Bell's line out to
center off Mark Petkovsek, who relieved Percival, scored Monahan
with the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to do is hit the ball hard and you'll probably
get the job done, because the outfield's in and the infield's in,''
Bell said. ``The key was getting up 2-0 (in the count). He had to
give me a pretty decent pitch to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bell, such humility is typical, and helps explains the
``unsung'' tag. It also belies the quiet confidence he called on
when he was forced to step in for the injured Carlos Guillen the
first week of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Bell had spent parts of four seasons in the majors but failed to
stick as an everyday player until Guillen's injury gave him the
chance. At first, Bell thought it was about time _ but the feeling
didn't last long.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think about that at first, and then it's not that
important, because you realize all the guys out there that deserve
it and never get the opportunity,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never was going to accept it, to myself, to not play every
day. For the good of the team and trying to win games, you know
you're going to have to accept it to a certain extent. But yeah, I
knew the time was going to come. It came a little unexpectedly this
year, but I'm glad I've gotten the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Lampkin, who is batting more than 60 points above his prior
career average, also could have been an Unsung Hero candidate. In
the fourth inning, the catcher hit his ninth homer, a two-run shot
that erased an Angels lead built on a solo homer by Mo Vaughn in
the top of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's homer was the first to reach the right-field upper deck
at Safeco Field, climbing 444 feet over the Hit It Here Cafe and a
level of luxury suites. Only one other player, Toronto's Shawn
Green, has even reached the cafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw it hard, and he hit it hard,'' said Mariner starter
Gil Meche, who otherwise was brilliant over seven-plus innings.
``It was a big-time homer and he's a big-time player.''
</P>
<P>
   PANIAGUA OUT: Reliever Jose Paniagua will miss the rest of the
season with a severe groin pull. Paniagua finished the year with a
6-11 record and 4.09 earned-run average that rose 53 points over
his last three outings as he struggled with the condition.
</P>
<P>
   WINNERS: The local chapter of the Baseball Writers' Association
of America voted Ken Griffey Jr. the Mariners' Player of the Year
and Jamie Moyer Pitcher of the Year before Friday night's game. The
award was Griffey's sixth and Moyer's second. Bell's Unsung Hero
honor was selected by Mariners coaches.
</P>
<P>
   RAIN KEEPS FALLIN': The game began with the roof open, and it
stayed that way despite showers in the top of the first. But by
7:20, the rain had gotten so persistent that president Chuck
Armstrong decided to extend the roof for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last weather report we had said this was going to miss
us,'' Armstrong said. ``But we err on the side of fan comfort. We
took the roof off because this was (supposed to be) a passing
shower.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Tyler Kepner can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or tylerkepner &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
