<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POOR-GORE-CAN'T-SCORE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SIBLING RIVALRY OF AL GORE AND BILL BRADLEY  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 1,075-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 25 Sept. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The contest between Al Gore and Bill Bradley has some of the
bitterness of sibling rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Although they have certain policy differences, at root theirs is
a clash of personalities, not of backgrounds or beliefs. They are
like members of a family who exhibit the same characteristics in
different and hostile guises.
</P>
<P>
   Consider their styles. Both are self-confident and wooden. Their
stump speeches are models of dullness. Neither has faltered in his
desire to be president. They trundle towards one other
relentlessly, like tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gore's determination has a controlled, disciplined character
about it. Perhaps because he has spent so long in a White House
under perpetual attack, or perhaps because as the front-runner he
has so much to lose even from a single gaffe, he has become
habitually defensive and restrained.
</P>
<P>
   Listeners respect, but do not warm to, his slick and competent
speeches. He seems to be sticking to a script someone else has
written.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's uncharismatic relentlessness has a different quality.
He too is sticking to a script _ but one he has written himself,
obscurities and all. His low-key nonchalance, the opposite of
slick, comes across as unvarnished sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   His introspective manner, his maddening refusal not to speak
about the big issues yet, even his decision to run for the
presidency now, when he claims he ``is ready,'' rather than
earlier, when it might have been politically more convenient _ all
these suggest an unflashy but deep self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is even beginning to display, on the evidence of last
weekend, an unexpected talent for good humor on television.
</P>
<P>
   The two men also display different forms of a more admirable
quality: integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has avoided most of the sleaze of the Clinton White House
(though not a certain part of the blame for it). He was a dutiful
son of a senator and is now a stalwart of the moderate wing of the
Democratic Party. His is the integrity of the loyal vice-captain.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's is that of the high-minded independent. He is a man
who, first as senator and now as candidate, likes to carve out a
position on matters that appeal to him and pursue it with dour
scrupulousness.
</P>
<P>
   He is not necessarily loyal. He resigned from the Senate in
1996, abandoning to others the task of defending the Democrats from
the then-rampant Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   He even flirted, a year earlier, with leaving the party, saying
that ``politics is broken'' and complaining that ``neither
political party speaks to people where they live their lives.'' It
is impossible to imagine such words coming from Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between the two men has a bearing on how voters
think they would do one of the most important jobs of a president:
that of commander-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other world leader, the American president must
show good judgment in matters of war and peace. Bradley scores
better (on an admittedly tiny sample) in this dragon-slaying test.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll make an exceptional commander-in-chief,'' says
Bob Kerrey, the only senator to have backed Bradley so far.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has 14 senators in his camp but not one has used this form
of praise in their endorsements. This does not mean that Gore would
be a bad commander-in-chief, but it does suggest that his
supporters do not associate him with the qualities that are needed
when American soldiers have to go into the line of fire.
</P>
<P>
   Now consider the policies of the two men. Both are pushing for a
more energetic and intrusive role for government than anything
Clinton has offered since the Republican landslide of 1994. But
Gore's activism comes in the shape of a swarm of small reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Putting limits on urban sprawl, employing more teachers to cut
class sizes, expanding health insurance for children _ all these
are one cautious step beyond Clintonian micro-initiatives, such as
encouraging school uniforms or boosting parental leave.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Bradley's governmental activism is that of the
broad brush. He wants much tougher gun controls, universal health
care and an overhaul of the campaign-finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   These last two would require nothing less than defeating the
special-interest groups that cling to the status quo and changing
the way the government works.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is an incrementalist, though his many small policies would
add up to a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley wants to transform politics through a few bold strokes.
He is the John McCain of the left _ an outsider with inside
knowledge, determined to clean up a corrupt political system.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Bill Bradley seems more gawkily sympathetic as a man,
higher-minded as a leader and bolder as a policymaker. These
qualities explain why he is now running neck-and-neck with Al Gore
in all sorts of recent opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   But can he win the nomination? That is a different matter. To be
nominated (and to be an effective president) requires
wheeler-dealer skills as well _ the ability to maintain a network
of allies and a knowledge of political trench warfare. In this
respect, Gore has the advantage.
</P>
<P>
   When Bradley was in the Senate, he gained a reputation as the
sort who sees the big picture but overlooks his constituents'
parochial concerns. This has helped him widen his appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Over one-third of Republicans say they would consider voting for
him, a much higher share than would dream of choosing Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But the vice-president has cemented support within his own party
so successfully that he has almost shut Bradley out. Most
Democratic officials support him, and they alone have a fifth of
the vote at the party convention.
</P>
<P>
   Among black voters, two prefer Gore for every one who prefers
Bradley. And in the South, a recent Gallup poll suggested that 72
percent of Democrats support Gore and only 19 percent Bradley. The
vice-president has a big advantage in states that control about a
third of the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   A Gore nomination is not yet a foregone conclusion. Bradley's
success is creating uncertainty among Democratic voters, and is
nourishing the view that he would be better than Gore at winning
Republican and independent votes.
</P>
<P>
   But the delegate arithmetic is powerful. The Democratic race is
evolving into a contest between the man better placed to win the
presidency and the one who is far more likely to win the
nomination. &QL; 
