<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ODD-BALTIMORE-MAYOR-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR MARTIN O'MALLEY: BLACK BALTIMORE'S GREAT WHITE HOPE?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Baltimore, Md.)   (This excellent 800-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 25 Sept. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE, MD. _ Two months ago, it would have seemed nonsense.
A 36-year-old white lawyer who plays electric guitar in an Irish
band, and is almost unknown to most local people, will become the
next mayor of 65 percent-black Baltimore?
</P>
<P>
   Farfetched though it sounds, it is likely to happen. Having
handily won the Democratic nomination in the primary election on
Sept. 14, and with nine in ten Baltimore voters registered as
Democrats, Martin O'Malley will almost certainly be elected mayor
on Nov. 2.
</P>
<P>
   He has the endorsement of some key black leaders. His proposals
for cutting down crime in a city riddled with it are clearly
popular. And he has so far been unspattered by the mud thrown up in
the politics of a city that embodies the worst of urban America.
</P>
<P>
   Can O'Malley save Baltimore?
</P>
<P>
   ``Charm City,'' 35 miles north of Washington, sometimes seems
like one huge crack-cocaine and heroin market; city officials think
that as many as an eighth of its people are addicts.
</P>
<P>
   It has the country's highest venereal-disease rate and its
fourth-highest murder rate, three times that of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   It is also desperately short of money. Each month about 1,000 of
the city's population of 630,000 understandably depart to live in
the suburbs, draining its tax base and causing a projected $153
million budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Until about 30 years ago Baltimore had a strong blue-collar
economy based on a busy port, bustling factories and the fruits of
the vast Chesapeake Bay. No longer.
</P>
<P>
   David Bositis, a political analyst in nearby Washington, thinks
no right-minded person would want to be mayor of such a city.
``Shouldn't we have them take sanity tests?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   There was an unmistakable smile of relief on the face of the
outgoing mayor, Kurt Schmoke, when he announced that he did not
propose to run for another term in office.
</P>
<P>
   For all that, no fewer than 27 people, 17 of them Democrats,
said they wanted the job. But then it turned out that several had
criminal records, three had filed for bankruptcy, and one had
barely a primary-school education.
</P>
<P>
   An attempt was made to draw in some more impressive candidates,
including the president of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People, Kweisi Mfume, who used to represent
central Baltimore in Congress; but none took the bait.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually three front-runners emerged, two black and one white.
One of the blacks, Lawrence A. Bell III, was the youngish president
of the city council and seemed a good prospect. But his campaign
was bumbling, and local journalists accused him of being sloppy
with money; he soon faded.
</P>
<P>
   The other main black contender, Carl Stokes, was a former member
of the school board and offered himself as ``the education
candidate.'' However, it emerged that he had not in fact graduated
from the local university he claimed as his alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   He apologized, and won some useful support, but by then it was
too late.
</P>
<P>
   Enter O'Malley, a fresh-faced lawyer who sauntered into the race
barely three weeks before the filing deadline. O'Malley had been a
vigorous member of the city council, yet few people knew him
outside his constituency in northeast Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   At first, he was dismissed as a white yuppie imported from the
Washington suburbs. But he gained momentum as his opponents
stumbled and as his promise to reform Baltimore caught the voters'
attention.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would immediately clean up the busiest drug markets,
and come down hard on petty criminals. He pointed to his work on
the council, where he had attacked police and housing officials for
corruption and pushed for stiffer punishment of criminals.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted that the city's middle-class northern neighborhoods
got better police protection than its poorer parts, but vowed to
change all that. It was music to the ears of people long accustomed
to hearing gun shots close to their doors.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a racially divided city like Baltimore, even that
might not have been enough. But then O'Malley won the unprecedented
public support of some of the city's top black leaders.
</P>
<P>
   They were called ``race-traitors'' by an angry minority, but the
quiet majority were more interested in sorting out the city than in
voting for someone who looked like them.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Stokes and Bell won 25 percent and 17 percent of the
primary vote, no match for O'Malley's 53 percent. It was one of the
biggest political surprises in the city's history.
</P>
<P>
   Now O'Malley, assuming he wins election in November, faces an
even longer shot: cleaning up Baltimore. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 800-word article, it must be purchased _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 0345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 03:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5745 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-ODD-BALTIMORE-MAYOR-E     09-25 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ODD-BALTIMORE-MAYOR-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
