   For all that, no fewer than 27 people, 17 of them Democrats,
said they wanted the job. But then it turned out that several had
criminal records, three had filed for bankruptcy, and one had
barely a primary-school education.
</P>
<P>
   An attempt was made to draw in some more impressive candidates,
including the president of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People, Kweisi Mfume, who used to represent
central Baltimore in Congress; but none took the bait.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually three front-runners emerged, two black and one white.
One of the blacks, Lawrence A. Bell III, was the youngish president
of the city council and seemed a good prospect. But his campaign
was bumbling, and local journalists accused him of being sloppy
with money; he soon faded.
</P>
<P>
   The other main black contender, Carl Stokes, was a former member
of the school board and offered himself as ``the education
candidate.'' However, it emerged that he had not in fact graduated
from the local university he claimed as his alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   He apologized, and won some useful support, but by then it was
too late.
</P>
<P>
   Enter O'Malley, a fresh-faced lawyer who sauntered into the race
barely three weeks before the filing deadline. O'Malley had been a
vigorous member of the city council, yet few people knew him
outside his constituency in northeast Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   At first, he was dismissed as a white yuppie imported from the
Washington suburbs. But he gained momentum as his opponents
stumbled and as his promise to reform Baltimore caught the voters'
attention.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would immediately clean up the busiest drug markets,
and come down hard on petty criminals. He pointed to his work on
the council, where he had attacked police and housing officials for
corruption and pushed for stiffer punishment of criminals.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted that the city's middle-class northern neighborhoods
got better police protection than its poorer parts, but vowed to
change all that. It was music to the ears of people long accustomed
to hearing gun shots close to their doors.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a racially divided city like Baltimore, even that
might not have been enough. But then O'Malley won the unprecedented
public support of some of the city's top black leaders.
</P>
<P>
   They were called ``race-traitors'' by an angry minority, but the
quiet majority were more interested in sorting out the city than in
voting for someone who looked like them.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Stokes and Bell won 25 percent and 17 percent of the
primary vote, no match for O'Malley's 53 percent. It was one of the
biggest political surprises in the city's history.
</P>
<P>
   Now O'Malley, assuming he wins election in November, faces an
even longer shot: cleaning up Baltimore. &QL; 
