<HEADLINE>
BIFFLE SETS RECORD WITH NINTH TRUCK VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Greg Biffle cashed in a trifecta worthy of this
gambling mecca during the Orleans 250 NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series
race last night.
</P>
<P>
   Biffle set a single-season record with his ninth victory,
increased his lead in the driver's championship by five points, and
locked up Ford Division's first manufacturer's title at the
1.5-mile Las Vegas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Biffle pitted for four tires _ his last set of Goodyear rubber _
117 laps into the 167-lapper. He then survived a door-banging
battle against Jack Sprague with nine laps remaining to finish
0.299-seconds ahead of Sprague.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great strategy to do a four-tire stop and not come in
on the last caution,'' said Biffle, driver of the No. 50 Grainger
Ford owned by Jack Roush. ``We didn't have the best truck, but we
had the best pit strategy. I don't think we could have passed the
16 \Rof Ron Hornaday\S or the 24 \Rof Sprague\S on the track. We
passed them in the pits tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Biffle, who has won eight of the past 12 races, broke the record
of eight single-season victories set by former series champion Mike
Skinner in 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Biffle came into the 22nd of 25 races with a 125-point lead over
Sprague, and increased the advantage to 130. The tour will compete
at Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth on Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need to stay focused for the rest of the year and let
things take care of themselves,'' said Biffle, who led twice for 29
laps _ including the final 28.
</P>
<P>
   Biffle, 29, helped Ford end Chevrolet's four-year run as
manufacturer's champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Jack Roush promised me a new \RFord\S Excursion
for my ninth win,'' Biffle said. ``So maybe I'll call him on
Monday.''  &LR; subheds:Brack eyes CART ride Reigning Indy Racing League
and Indianapolis 500 champion Kenny Brack denied that he has signed
a contract to drive for car-owner Bobby Rahal in the rival
Championship Auto Racing Teams FedEx Series beginning in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Brack's contract with Pep Boys IRL car-owner A.J. Foyt of
Houston expires at the end of this season. The IRL finale is
scheduled for Texas Motor Speedway on Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not signed with anybody for the future, as for now,''
Brack said after a day of practice leading to today's
qualifications for the Vegas.com 500. ``I've been talking to him
\RRahal\S. And I've been talking to A.J., too. So nothing's
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   But IRL regular Jeff Ward, currently employed by Pagan Racing,
met with Foyt late yesterday to talk contract for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Rahal, a former three-time CART champion and Indy 500 winner, is
looking to replace Bryan Herta in the No. 8 Shell Reynard/Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what comes out of it,'' said Brack, driver of Foyt's
new No. 14 Power Team G Force/Aurora. ``For now, I'm trying to
concentrate on doing the best I can in the remaining two races in
the IRL.''  &LR; subheds:Ribbs plans IRL debut Willy T. Ribbs will make
IRL history today as the first black driver to attempt a qualifying
run in the four-year-old series.
</P>
<P>
   Ribbs, who became the first black to qualify for the
Indianapolis 500 in 1991, has signed with team-owner Dennis
McCormack for the Las Vegas.com 500, the season-finale at Texas
Motor Speedway next month and into 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan is to start 2000 now,'' said Ribbs, 43, who has been
without a full-time Indy-car ride since October 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Ribbs logged a combined 70 laps during yesterday's two practice
sessions, his first in the car. His top speed in the No. 30 Cole
Brothers Water-Team Losi G Force/Aurora was 201.305 mph, which will
get him into a field that has only 26 entries.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
