<HEADLINE>
STARS' REGULAR CAST STUMBLES IN DRESS REHEARSAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Stars conducted their first full-fledged dress
rehearsal for the regular season last night. When it was over, they
could only be glad there's still a week before the curtain goes up
on the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars lost to the Detroit Red Wings, 3-0, last night in a
preseason game at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Losing a preseason game isn't that big of a deal. Coaches use
them to look at young players fighting for jobs, to work on
different aspects of the game.
</P>
<P>
   This game, though, wasn't for auditions. The regular cast was in
place, and ready to show they know their lines.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Belfour started in goal and played all three periods. Mike
Modano, Brett Hull and Jere Lehtinen, who didn't make the trip to
Colorado for a 3-1 victory against the Avalanche on Thursday,
skated regular shifts.
</P>
<P>
   The only youngsters to play significant minutes were defensemen
Brad Lukovich and Richard Jackman, and forwards Blake Sloan and
Warren Luhning, and it appears as though they have spots on the
team all but wrapped up.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the defending Stanley Cup champion Stars were hammered by
one of their chief rivals in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not there yet, and there's less than a week to go,''
Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars lost because their power play was awful, and Red Wings
backup goalie Ken Wregget was outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings were whistled for 19:49 of penalties, giving the
Stars almost a full period's worth of power-play time. The Stars,
though, were 0-12 with the advantage.
</P>
<P>
   They had several good scoring chances, but Wregget was equal to
the task. He stopped all 30 shots he faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made some great saves, and some shots we just hit right at
him,'' Modano said. ``But we got a lot of shots, and that's
important. If you keep shooting, some are going to go in.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the optimistic view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its purpose is to get you prepared for the regular season,''
Modano said. ``There's bright spots and there's not so bright
spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock, though, doesn't seem inclined to take
the optimistic view.
</P>
<P>
   He huddled with general manager Bob Gainey and assistant coaches
Rick Wilson and Doug Jarvis late after the game, declining to meet
with the media. He scheduled a practice for this morning, even
though the team is in the midst of playing three games in three
nights.
</P>
<P>
   If Hitchcock was indeed upset with the effort last night, he had
company. Even though the Stars are 4-2-2 in exhibition games,
Nieuwendyk said there's a lot of work to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's been very solid for us,'' Nieuwendyk said.
``The bottom line is you can work all you want, but unless you're
committed to doing the little things we were committed to last year
we're not going to be very good. I think we have to have some solid
workouts this week and get prepared to play. We need to get
mentally prepared to play. It's time we got our heads on straight
and began playing hard in both practice and games.''
</P>
<P>
   The power-play failures were especially glaring considering the
Stars scored twice with the man-advantage against the Avalance on
Thursday, even though most of their big guns didn't make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, with the ``A'' team on the ice, they couldn't dent
Wregget.
</P>
<P>
   It was only a dress rehearsal, but the reviews were awful. The
Stars only have a week to get it right.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
