<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN WITH TITLE IN GRASP, RANGERS SHOULD HOLD THE CELEBRATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Here's a tip, free of charge and likely to be
ignored, to the soon-to-be-crowned champions of the American League
West: Put a cork in the champagne.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' impressive 12-4 victory last night at The Ballpark
in Arlington officially put the A's into sunfish mode _ flopping
like a wall-eyed, gasping bluegill on the dock _ and virtually
locked up Texas' third division title in four years.
</P>
<P>
   Their magic number is down to three and the Rangers can
mathematically put the gritty A's out of their misery by finishing
off the sweep this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow another shower in the bubbly, whether it comes
tomorrow or sometime shortly afterward, seems out of place this
time.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion: Borrow a page from the Indians, who clinched
their fourth straight division crown while on a plane a couple of
weeks ago and celebrated with handshakes all around.
</P>
<P>
   Act like you've been here before and still have places to go
before you're finished.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the Rangers' champagne party plans already have been
made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zack \RMinasian, the Rangers' clubhouse supervisor\S asked me
the other day if we wanted to forget about it this year or do it
again,'' manager Johnny Oates said after watching the Rangers
explode in the A's faces like a trick cigar. ``I told him I've
learned to accept losses, but I'm still learning how to celebrate
wins. It hasn't become so commonplace around here that we take them
for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a veteran club that knows we haven't finished our job
if we win the division. Even winning a World Series doesn't mean
you're finished. You celebrate the moment and come back tomorrow
prepared to go back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be an excellent philosophy to apply tonight. The
Rangers quietly savored last night's victory while understanding
that there's still work to be done.
</P>
<P>
   But last night ... that was special.
</P>
<P>
   For three innings the Rangers played like a team trapped under a
frozen river. Try as they might, they couldn't find a way to break
the surface.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning Tom Goodwin lined into a double play at
first with runners at first and second. Leading off the third, Mark
McLemore tried to stretch a double into a triple and was thrown out
on a perfect relay by A's second baseman Randy Velarde. In the
fourth, with nobody out and runners at first and second, Todd Zeile
whacked a one-hopper back to pitcher Gil Heredia, who started
another double play.
</P>
<P>
   But the fifth, when this year is in the record books, may be
remembered as the Rangers' biggest inning of the season.
</P>
<P>
   When McLemore lined a single through a drawn-in infield to score
Royce Clayton from third, tying the score at 1-1, it was as if the
entire Rangers' team let out a collective sigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like we were a caged animal and somebody opened the
door,'' Rafael Palmeiro said. ``We couldn't do anything right and
then we get the right hit at the right time and we go crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Crazy included three home runs and five RBI from Juan Gonzalez;
three hits each for McLemore and Clayton, including a home run; and
seven strong innings from starter Aaron Sele.
</P>
<P>
   On the Jumbotron during the Rangers' six-run sixth: ``The Fat
Lady is Humming.''
</P>
<P>
   And the champagne soon will be flowing again.
</P>
<P>
   It was long overdue when the Rangers won their first division
crown in 25 years in '96. Every long-suffering Rangers' fan
deserved their own champagne bath.
</P>
<P>
   And last year, clinching in Seattle, it was only fitting that
the Rangers would spray champagne all over that dungeon known as
the Kingdome. I hope the visiting clubhouse still reeks of it when
they tear the place down next March.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, there's unfinished business still on the table.
Winning a division is not, the Rangers hopefully have discovered by
now, what this is all about.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it's their party and they intend to have it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you win a division championship, you've accomplished
something,'' Palmeiro pointed out. ``This is a different year and
you deserve to celebrate. You owe it to yourself. You've worked
seven months to get here.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, said McLemore, this isn't a team that has become as
blase about winning as the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shake hands?'' McLemore said. ``I don't think so. When you win
the division by 25 games, you can do that, I guess. We haven't done
that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough. Go ahead and party. I think I've still got that
smelly, champagne-drenched T-shirt I wore last year in Seattle in
the back of the closet somewhere.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 1017EDT &QL; 
