<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-GREER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREER, GONZALEZ PROVIDE HEALTHIER PICTURE FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers received two pieces of
encouraging news last night.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Greer was back in the lineup and Juan Gonzalez was driving
the ball again. Both were missing pieces vital to the success of
the Rangers' offensive machinery.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez admitted before the game he continues to be bothered by
the bruised left wrist that has been a problem for him most of the
second half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not 100 percent,'' Gonzalez said. ``Sometimes I feel it,
sometimes I don't. It's like 90 percent, but I'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez said the wrist keeps him from driving the ball like he
wants. He entered last night's against Oakland with just one home
run and three runs batted in during his last 13 games. But he ended
that by hitting three home runs in a game for the third time in his
career, and the Rangers won, 12-4.
</P>
<P>
   Greer, who was hit in the eye with a baseball thrown by pitcher
Rick Helling during batting practice on Sept. 13, called manager
Johnny Oates at 1 p.m. yesterday and said he was ready to go back
into the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had some improvement the last three days,'' Greer said.
``Hopefully I can go back and play nine innings. The only way to
find out is to try.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer was hitless in five at-bats with two strikeouts, but he
did make a terrific diving catch on Matt Stairs' short fly ball in
the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the 0-for-5 was more not hitting in nine days,'' Greer
said. ``I was pretty close to normal out there. I felt a lot more
confident and comfortable in the outfield and at the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer, who suffered a broken nose and a bruised retina when he
was hit, had played just four innings since the injury occurred in
Kansas City. He tried to play Tuesday against the Baltimore Orioles
but left the game in the fourth when he had trouble seeing the ball
in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had lost four of five games going into their
American League West showdown with the Oakland Athletics, but Greer
said he wasn't coming back out of a sense of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than the fact we only have 10 games left in the
season,'' Greer said. ``I want to be in there and help us win it.
We have a good ballclub with or without me. I just want to get in
there and complement what we already have.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates said, ``It's his call. It's totally up to him. The doctors
said he couldn't hurt it any more. It's just a matter of him being
able to see. I said, `I'll start you, if you can't see, I'll take
you out.'''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 1017EDT &QL; 
