<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Sept. 26:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-ARMY-INTEGRATION (Bloemfontein, South Africa) _ Last
week, as weeping families buried their dead and government
officials promised a thorough inquiry, the nation embarked on a
soul-wrenching debate over the the racial transformation of the
National Defense Force. Since 1994, more than 22,700 former
liberation fighters and black homeland soldiers have been
integrated into the military, Government statistics show. The
Defense Force, which was then 45 percent white and 38 percent
black, is now less than 31 percent white and more than 55 percent
black. By Rachel L. Swarns. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-CHAMPAGNE (Ay, France) _ Sales of French Champagne have
been setting records for months. But here in the heart of the
Champagne-making region of France, talk of a shortage is laughed
off as nonsense. Why would any smart winemaker mismanage the
millennium? By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   G7-MEETING (Washington) _ With financial markets around the
world rattled by the surprising climb of the Japanese yen against
the dollar, the top economic officials of the world's wealthiest
nations began meeting here Saturday to decide whether to intervene
or to let Japan solve the problem itself. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SCANDAL-ASSESS (Washington) _ Despite the acrimony
between congressional Republicans and the White House, the Clinton
administration emerged relatively unscathed in the past week after
several days of hearings into allegations of Russian corruption and
money laundering at the Bank of New York. By Eric SChmitt.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-PROTEST (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ While calm returned to
Indonesia's capital Saturday after anti-military riots here left at
least six people dead, students took to the streets of another
large Indonesian city and hurled rocks and burning tires at
soldiers and police in a protest over a proposed law that would
grant sweeping new powers to the army. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-RDP (Dili, East Timor) _ When Marcos Napoleao Soares
returned Saturday to his burned-out house he walked on a carpet of
soft grey ash. The place he called his ``sweet home'' was gone:
blackened, empty, partly roofless, filled with the rustling of the
cool bamboo trees outside. But for the moment, none of that seemed
to matter. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-WOMEN (New York) _ It was a dinner for 10 foreign
ministers, held without fanfare on Thursday evening in a quiet,
still unopened sculpture gallery at the Museum of Modern Art. By
dinner's end, the foreign ministers _ all women _ and their host,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright _ had taken one more step
toward creating a lobby for moving women's issues closer to the
center of foreign affairs. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-VOTE (New Delhi, India) _ As India lumbers into the fourth
and final week of marathon national elections, elephants bearing
ballot boxes tramp into dense forests and ponies carrying election
officials clop their way to dizzying heights in the Himalayas, all
to make sure that every citizen _ no matter how remote _ gets a
chance to vote. By Celia Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-DIPLO-OAKLEY (Washington) _ In a profession that prides
itself on obliqueness, Assistant Secretary of State Phyllis Oakley
has always been plain-spoken. She was no more so than on the
occasion last week marking her 42 years as an American diplomat, a
career that has spanned most continents and forged a trail for
women in a man's world. In short, Mrs. Oakley delivered a broadside
on American diplomacy. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA-CANDIDATE (Buenos Aires, Argentina) _ ``They call me
boring,'' says Fernando de la Rua, the mayor of Buenos Aires, in
the opening of his presidential campaign's signature television
commercial. But the blandness appears to be a winning message at a
time of mounting government scandals, street crime and
unemployment. By Clifford Krauss. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-YOUNG-PIONEERS (Beijing) _ Combining elements of the
Scouts, the Safety Patrol and the Hall Monitor, larded with thick,
simple doses of patriotism and Communism, the Young Pioneers
remains a shared experience of China's children. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN-REBIRTH (Berlin) _ Germany's inhibitions being what they
are, the re-creation of Berlin as the home of the government in
recent weeks has been a muted affair: no big rallies, no public
festivities, no showy speeches from the chancellor. And yet,
something is in the air. By Roger Cohen. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-U.S. (Istanbul, Turkey) _ With Greece and Turkey suddenly
seeming ready to end generations of hostility, Prime Minister
Bulent Ecevit of Turkey is due in Washington on Sunday for talks
with President Clinton and congressional leaders. By Stephen
Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HYDRO-DAM-DEBATE (Little Goose Dam, Wash.) _ Of all the ways in
which Americans have reshaped the land to suit their priorities,
none is more audacious than the vast network of hydroelectric dams
that stretches across the Pacific Northwest, taming wild rivers,
opening shipping passages and bringing the region the cheapest
electricity rates in the nation. But whatever their benefits to
man, the great dams have proved lethal on a gigantic scale to the
environment of the region's wild salmon. Here on the lower Snake
River, two federal agencies are exploring a proposal that is
proving to be far more contentious than building the dams was in
the first place, and could have just as enormous consequences:
taking four dams out of service. By Sam Howe Verhovek. (With photo,
map and graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-RDP _ After five years and tens of millions of dollars,
the Justice Department's criminal investigation of the tobacco
industry boiled down to this: one misdemeanor charge against an
obscure biotechnology company. So on Wednesday, when Attorney
General Janet Reno announced a broad civil lawsuit accusing
cigarette makers of racketeering and fraud and seeking to recover
billions in health-care costs related to smoking, Justice officials
also announced that their criminal inquiry was closed. (This
article was reported by Barry Meier, David Johnston and Lowell
Bergman and was written by Meier.)
</P>
<P>
   NC-FLOODS (Rocky Mount, N.C.) _ Like so much of eastern North
Carolina, the Riverside neighborhood has been soaked beyond
salvation in the floods that followed Hurricane Floyd, which have
now killed 47 people in North Carolina alone. At the most, a
handful of homes out of 200 solid brick-and-frame structures here
will be spared from the bulldozer. And by the weekend, as a few
hundred residents in the state began returning to their homes, the
mental geography of a neighborhood and an entire region _ a
people's relationship to its land and its water _ had been
permanently altered. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-CONDORS (Pine Mountain Club, Calif.) _ More than half the
free-flying condors released in California seem to have taken a
shine to this retreat in the San Emigdio Mountains about 50 miles
northwest of Los Angeles. By Barbara Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   LAKE-ERIE-SHIPWRECKS (Lorain, Ohio) _ A decade ago, only a few,
intrepid scuba divers plunged into the murk of Lake Erie. Now, the
lake is clearer than it has been in decades and hundreds of divers
are coming from as far as Florida to explore its best kept secret:
a vast underwater paradise of well-preserved shipwrecks. (With a
photo. No byline.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-POLICE-CORRUPT (Los Angeles) _ A former police officer's
account of abuses of power in a Los Angeles Police Department
station house has shaken the city's political establishment,
renewed calls for increased civilian oversight of the agency and
halted the enforcement of a law promoted as a strong antidote to
gang crime. (No byline.)
</P>
<P>
   COLO-JONBENET-CASE (Denver) _ The grand jury investigating the
killing of JonBenet Ramsey reconvened in Boulder on Thursday after
a four-month hiatus. But with prosecutors having made no request to
finance the panel after its term expires in less than a month, its
future and that of the investigation are unclear. (No byline.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-SPEND (Washington) _ As the new fiscal year approaches, a
financial and political crisis confronts Republicans in Congress.
They may have to break their repeated promises and raid Social
Security to run the government, their own staff and independent
analysts say. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BAY-BUCHANAN-PROFILE (Washington) _ Bay Buchanan sighed a bit in
admitting that her brother Pat, the quixotic presidential
candidate, was essentially a man without a party. A talk with the
strategic half of a brother-sister political team. By Francis X.
Clines. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
