<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5771 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-REPUBS-SPEND-2TAKES-N     09-25 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-SPEND-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS LIKELY TO RAID SOCIAL SECURITY, DESPITE PROMISES
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By TIM WEINER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the new fiscal year approaches, a financial and
political crisis confronts Republicans in Congress. They may have
to break their repeated promises and raid Social Security to run
the government, their own staff and independent analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   For months, the Republican leaders swore they would pass their
spending bills on time, hew to self-imposed spending limits and
leave Social Security alone. Now they may break each of those
pledges in a year when they have achieved little else.
</P>
<P>
   All week, nearly every day, they renewed their vows not to spend
surplus Social Security funds to run the government in the coming
fiscal year, which begins on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to take money out of Social Security,'' House
Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois said on Thursday, as President
Clinton vetoed the Republicans' legislative centerpiece of 1999, a
$792 billion tax cut. Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of
Mississippi said, ``We should not spend one nickel of Social
Security.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the majority whip, who has been his
party's chief spending strategist in the House, said, ``The bottom
line is this: We're not going to spend a dime of the Social
Security trust fund.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as they repeat that mantra, their own spending
strategies are undermining them. The spending bills written by the
Republicans will drain billions of dollars from the Social Security
surplus, according to the latest figures from the Congressional
Budget Office and the calculations of independent experts.
</P>
<P>
   Although the government's budget is better balanced than it has
been for many years, and the amount likely to be siphoned from
Social Security is only a tiny fraction of total federal spending,
the partisan fight over the issue may have political repercussions
far larger than the amount of money involved.
</P>
<P>
   How the battle is resolved could affect whether the Republicans
retain their thin majority in Congress or Democrats manage to
recapture at least the House; and both Republican and Democratic
candidates for president are almost sure to focus on taxes,
spending and Social Security in the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   In past years, when the government ran deficits, Congress
routinely spent extra receipts from Social Security taxes to run
federal programs. But now, with the expected surpluses, Congress
cannot agree with the president whether to cut taxes, expand
government programs or pay down the federal debt. How to account
for the Social Security funds is at the heart of the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   To their acute discomfort, the impasse may force the Republicans
to play into the White House's hands by spending some of the Social
Security surplus they have pledged to protect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spending levels will eat into the Social Security trust fund _
that will be the key thing,'' said Peter Sperry, a budget analyst
with the conservative Heritage Foundation in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office's latest figures show Congress
spending $4 billion to $16 billion out of the supposedly sacrosanct
Social Security trust fund. But those figures are two weeks old,
and the calculation has changed for the worse in recent days as
Republicans and Democrats alike clamor for more money for their
favorite programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one were to take all the demands that have developed here
in the last two weeks, we would definitely be dipping into the
Social Security surplus,'' said G. William Hoagland, the Republican
staff director of the Senate Budget Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., the House minority leader, said
last week, ``We're probably going to edge closer to $30 billion of
actual Social Security money spent.''
</P>
<P>
   That sum may be no more than a rounding error in an $8 trillion
economy, but it is still a lot of nickels and dimes _ every one
potentially politically damaging to the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to frustrate and infuriate their conservative
base,'' said Stephen Moore, director of fiscal policy studies at
the libertarian Cato Institute. ``It's an indication of a breakdown
in discipline in the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Stan Collender, who advises corporate executives on government
spending as head of the federal Budget Consulting Group at
Fleishman-Hillard, a public relations firm, said: ``There's almost
no way the Republicans can come up with a plan for the coming
fiscal year without tapping into the Social Security surplus. They
clearly have opened themselves up to a whole new level of
criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   With so many spending bills still unapproved, tapping Social
Security is not yet inevitable. But it will take extraordinary
discipline, Hoagland said, for the Republicans to restrain their
own ranks. Recent history _ notably last October, when faced with a
similar situation, the Republicans allowed a $21 billion bonanza of
spending _ suggests this will be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   This situation has White House officials in a state of barely
restrained glee.
</P>
<P>
   They clearly believe that the Republicans will do themselves
political damage if they fail again to carry out the only major
legislative task required of Congress by the Constitution: passing
the spending bills. Some said they see it as a key to winning back
control of the House, and perhaps even the Senate, next year _
assuming Americans pay much attention to how Congress spends their
money.
</P>
<P>
   The White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said the Republicans
had created ``a magnificent strategy to box themselves in.''
</P>
<P>
   The only way out of this trap for the Republican leadership is
to hide billions of dollars in spending with budgetary devices.
Their spending plans for next fiscal year call for draining most of
the projected $38 billion general fund surplus for the year after
next, fiscal 2001, and spending it in 2000. Even some fellow
conservatives are calling these tactics risky at best and ludicrous
at worst.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leaders have also declared that $4.5 billion in
funds for the 2000 census, $1.1 billion for a home-heating
assistance program and up to $8 billion in agricultural aid, mostly
unconnected to this summer's droughts, are unforseeable
emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're coming up with gimmicks,'' said the former Republican
chairman of the House Appropriations Committee, Bob Livingston, who
left Congress last year after 21 years in office. ``For crying out
loud, the census has been with us since the conception of the
Constitution of the United States. This is not an emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said Republicans in Congress ``can't make their budget
work or stand on its own without resorting to cheap budget
tricks.''
</P>
<P>
   Declaring spending an ``emergency'' means it technically does
not count against the spending limits, or caps, imposed by Congress
in 1997. But those caps already have been broken, Lott concedes.
</P>
<P>
   And the emergency money has to come from somewhere _ namely, the
$14 billion budget surplus projected for fiscal 2000, which would
have been the first in 30 years. Those three emergency items for
the census, home heating and agriculture would all but wipe out
that surplus.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There were going to be two kinds of surpluses in the fiscal 2000
spending scheme. One was that $14 billion surplus in the operating
budget of the government, the so-called ``on-budget'' surplus,
which is like a checking account.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office says that money is gone, with or
without the emergency spending.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the other projected surplus for fiscal 2000 _ $147
billion in the Social Security trust fund, which is like a
retirement account. Though Congress has tapped into that fund for
decades, the Republicans vowed repeatedly that this year would be
different, and now fear they will pay a political price if they
cannot keep that promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid that's the one thing that seems to have sunk in
with the American people,'' Hoagland said. ``They don't want us to
spend Social Security. That's the one issue that does seem to bear
fruit. ``
</P>
<P>
   There is only one escape from this conundrum for the
Republicans, but it is a tightrope walk across a political chasm.
</P>
<P>
   The new fiscal year begins at 12:01 a.m. Friday. As Congress
left town for the weekend, nine of the 13 spending bills were not
ready to be sent to the president for his signature _ or his veto,
if Clinton keeps his promise to reject seven of the bills for their
deep cuts in favorite White House programs.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, most of the spending bills will not be signed into law
by Oct. 1. In the next five days, Congress must pass stop-gap
measures called continuing resolutions to run government agencies
lacking legal spending measures. In the meantime, the incomplete or
unsigned measures will be rolled into one big package, called an
omnibus spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   But continuing resolutions lasting two or three weeks are a
fragile architecture. They must be shored up with good-faith
negotiations between the White House and the Republican Congress on
reshaping the spending bills. But the Republican leaders have said
many times that Clinton cannot be trusted, and some in the White
House feel the same way about the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   If that process collapses, a repeat of the 1995 government
shutdown is possible. That would be a political disaster,
Republicans fear. They believe the public blamed them for the 1995
shutdown, which closed everything from national parks to passport
offices.
</P>
<P>
   The more likely result is a huge omnibus spending bill that adds
tens of billions of dollars in new spending _ which is precisely
what happened last year, also to the embarrassment of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   There appear to be only two ways to avoid a deep dip into the
Social Security funds. One is for Congress to pass a tobacco tax
proposed by the White House, which is unlikely at best.
</P>
<P>
   The other is for the Republican leaders to order their members
to stop demanding more spending, to pass as many bills as possible
before Oct. 1 _ and to hope that they can outfox Clinton at the
negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see a way out,'' Hoagland said. ``The key is discipline.
The key is leadership.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
