<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-RDP _ After five years and tens of millions of dollars,
the Justice Department's criminal investigation of the tobacco
industry boiled down to this: one misdemeanor charge against an
obscure biotechnology company. So on Wednesday, when Attorney
General Janet Reno announced a broad civil lawsuit accusing
cigarette makers of racketeering and fraud and seeking to recover
billions in health-care costs related to smoking, Justice officials
also announced that their criminal inquiry was closed. (This
article was reported by Barry Meier, David Johnston and Lowell
Bergman and was written by Meier.)
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   HYDRO-DAMS-DEBATE (Little Goose Dam, Wash.) _ Of all the ways in
which Americans have reshaped the land to suit their priorities,
none is more audacious than the vast network of hydroelectric dams
that stretches across the Pacific Northwest, taming wild rivers,
opening shipping passages and bringing the region the cheapest
electricity rates in the nation. But whatever their benefits to
man, the great dams have proved lethal on a gigantic scale to the
environment of the region's wild salmon. Here on the lower Snake
River, two federal agencies are exploring a proposal that is
proving to be far more contentious than building the dams was in
the first place, and could have just as enormous consequences:
taking four dams out of service. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
