<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 11:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5776 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-FRANCE-CHAMPAGNE-ART-     09-25 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-CHAMPAGNE-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 CHAMPAGNE MAKERS PROMISE PLENTY TO CRY INTO ON DEC. 31 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AY, France _ Sir Winston Churchill, who knew a thing or two
about fine living, used to say of his favorite champagne, ``In
victory I deserve it, and in defeat, I need it.'' This New Year's
Eve, partygoers apparently have decided that when it comes to
French champagne they, too, have to have it.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of French champagne have been setting records for months.
The fact that the American economy is booming, along with a taste
for luxury goods, is one reason. So is the notion of ringing in the
millennium with a flute full of the real stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Wine merchants in the United States say French champagne is
being rationed to them month by month. Advertisements from
champagne makers are warning people to prepare for their parties by
laying in a supply early. Food and wine writers have been debating
the possibility of a shortage for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   But here in the heart of the champagne-making region of France,
talk of a shortage is laughed off as nonsense. Why would any smart
winemaker mismanage the millennium?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a few makers who don't have any champagne left,''
said Rene Goutorbe, who took a moment off from directing tractors
to his wine presses as the 1999 harvest arrives here. ``But they're
the same ones who didn't have any left last year at this time, and
they won't have any next year, either.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably have the same problem with money,'' he said,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, the champagne houses and the growers of the
three grapes essential for the genuine bubbly _ pinot noir, pinot
chardonnay and pinot meunier _ agreed to produce enough grapes to
make an average of 270 million bottles of champagne a year for the
rest of the 1990s, about 50 million bottles more than they had been
selling in the recession years early in the decade.
</P>
<P>
   The producers also agreed to draw down the equivalent of 132
million bottles of reserve wine, normally saved for years with a
poor harvest, and use it to put more champagne on the market in
1999 than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that there will be plenty of nonvintage wine to go
around. Champagne sales this year will most likely far surpass 300
million bottles and set a record, up to 15 percent more than last
year's figures, according to executives at Champagne
Laurent-Perrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``All our expectations have been surpassed,'' said Christian
Pol-Roger, whose Champagne Pol Roger company in Epernay is one of
the few French houses in private hands. ``There'll be enough for
everybody. All that saying `Buy now or there won't be anymore' does
is stimulate even more sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Champagne, like so much in France, is a subtle and delicate
business, with as many layers of complexity as the sparkling wines
that take their name from the eastern French region. ``What we sell
is tears of happiness,'' Pol-Roger said down in his cool
brick-walled caves, some lined with bottles of his Sir Winston
Churchill vintage wine that will stay here for years. ``They have
to go to university, study at Oxford and get a good education
before they go out into the world,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   But he and other champagne makers do not like to talk about the
number of bottles they produce, any more than people of refined
manners like to talk about how much money they make. Any suggestion
of a glut on the market might cheapen the luxury image, and
besides, makers and growers are eager to keep prices stable. They
suffered a sharp decline in sales when high prices in the early
1990s collided with an economic recession in Europe and the United
States after the Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   As 2000 approaches, champagne companies seem to be trying to
encourage people to celebrate with serenity _ preferably with
champagne, which is made only here, not the sparkling wines made in
Italy, Spain, Germany and the United States, where real champagne
still accounts for only 10 percent of the sparkling wine market.
</P>
<P>
   Early this month, Veuve Clicquot invited more than 600 customers
and celebrities, including descendants of Louis XIV, to his Chateau
de Versailles, rented by the company for the evening. Ladies in
evening gowns and gentlemen in tuxedos sipped Veuve Clicquot La
Grande Dame 1990 in the garden before going into the Orangerie to
eat their way through lobster ravioli, veal and roast figs, to
champagne accompaniment highlighted by a 1979 La Grande Dame.
</P>
<P>
   The great lady's 19th century namesake, the widow Clicquot,
invented the ``riddling tables'' that are still used to tilt
champagne bottles upside down as they approach the end of the aging
process, so that the yeast sediment can collect around the cork to
be popped out before the bottles are recorked and sold.
</P>
<P>
   Mireille Guiliano, president of the American subsidiary Clicquot
Inc., said the company would not have thought of putting on such a
show if there were any prospect of running out of product to sell
before New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   But Veuve Clicquot, like other makers, rationed some big
wholesale distributors this year, doling out consignments month by
month a little at a time rather than all at once in January and
February.
</P>
<P>
   For American retail liquor store owners like Michael Correra in
Brooklyn, this meant that his distributor, Paramount, told him in
early September that it could not supply him with any more Veuve
Clicquot yellow-label nonvintage champagne until October, Correra
said.
</P>
<P>
   He still had plenty on the shelves, at $31.99 a bottle, early
this month, but he said: ``With champagne, you can buy it one week,
and then the distributor is out another week. I don't know if
people are squirreling it away or what, but there's 60 percent more
demand this year and only 20 percent more supply.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Guiliano said: ``You can't just turn the faucet on, of
course. There are customers who would like to have three times as
much as they will get, but I'm persuaded that if you go to the
stores on Dec. 30 you'll still find a wide choice available.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In advertising campaigns earlier this year, Moet &AMP; Chandon,
which is the biggest champagne seller in America and, like Veuve
Clicquot and many other houses, is owned by the LVMH Moet Hennessy
Louis Vuitton conglomerate, was urging customers to ``prepare.''
But, as Philippe Pascal, president of Champagne Veuve Clicquot
Ponsardin in Reims, said, ``We foresaw the increased demand, and we
said let's get ready, because we wanted to avoid too much tension
with prices.''
</P>
<P>
   French government regulations and longstanding cooperative
arrangements in the champagne trade provide ways of controlling
both quantity and quality that came into play to insure adequate
supplies for the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Nonvintage champagne is produced by blending wines made from
pinot noir, pinot chardonnay and pinot meunier grapes that come
from many different vineyards. In good years, around 20 percent of
this still wine is held in reserve, ``blocked'' in bottles or vats
to be mixed with wine from poor harvest years, to even out the
hills and valleys of the production cycle.
</P>
<P>
   But in the years leading up to 1996, according to Jacques
Peters, Veuve Clicquot's cellar master, growers agreed with the
champagne houses to produce enough grapes to increase production to
an average of 270 million bottles each year until 2000. At the same
time, they agreed to draw down the equivalent of up to 132 million
bottles of wine previously built up in reserve stores. This would
add to the mix in the ``assemblage,'' as the process is called in
French, that would make the nonvintage champagne that went on sale
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, after all the millennium parties, they expect demand
to fall again and plan to build up their reserve supplies over a
few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year's 1999 vintage champagne should be a great one,
unless we get hail or something before the harvest is over,''
Peters said, ``but it won't be ready to drink until 2006 or 2007.''
Vintage champagnes are made only from grapes from the harvest of
the vintage year, which is on the label, and usually also have a
special name, like La Grande Dame or Sir Winston Churchill.
</P>
<P>
   Distributors in the United States still have special bottles of
the acclaimed 1988 and 1990 vintages of many houses, and most
makers keep a few hundred or even a thousand bottles of other great
years like 1978 and 1983 around for special occasions. These wines
go for premium prices; a magnum of 1988 Dom Perignon goes for about
$250 this year in New York City, for example.
</P>
<P>
   As for such wines, Frederic Panaiotis, another vintner with
Veuve Clicquot Ponsardin, advised: ``If you must have a specific
vintage from a particular year, don't wait until November to buy
it. I personally wouldn't wait until Dec. 24, either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
