<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-TERRORISM-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MOSCOW: political consequences.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On one level, Russians appreciate the stakes. Moscow's efforts
to repulse Chechen rebels in Dagestan have drawn displays of
nationalism, even from Russian politicians who once sought to
impeach President Boris N. Yeltsin over the Chechnya fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   But it has not taken long for cracks to open in that front.
Within days of the first apartment bombings, Kremlin leaders were
hinting that their chief rival for the next Russian presidency,
Mayor Yuri Luzhkov of Moscow, had bungled counterterrorism efforts.
Luzhkov's supporters just as quickly spread the word that Yeltsin
was losing Russia's grip on the south.
</P>
<P>
   More ominous is the bleak undercurrent of doubt coursing through
everyday Russia. It is openly speculated by citizens and experts
alike that the Dagestan invasion and the terrorism are masterminded
by a government desperate for a crisis that would allow a
declaration of emergency and cancellation of elections.
</P>
<P>
   Add to this the prospect of a protracted twilight conflict _ a
Russian Lebanon or Belfast, already buzzwords among the political
elite _ and the mixture could become explosive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, unfortunately, that terrorism acquires its own logic
once it emerges,'' Iskandaryan said. ``It turns into a disease on
its own, an independent disease, and it's difficult to cope with it
if it takes such a form _ as it did in Palestine, in Ireland and
other places.
</P>
<P>
   ``What may happen to political stability in Russia after the
50th bombing,'' he said, ``is hard to imagine.''
</P>
