<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5786 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-SAFRICA-ARMY-INTEGRAT     09-25 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-ARMY-INTEGRATION-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLING OF 8 ILLUSTRATES LINGERING RACIAL TENSIONS IN S. AFRICAN
ARMY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLOEMFONTEIN, South Africa _ In the beginning, they were just
two little boys who shared the same dream.
</P>
<P>
   In his ramshackle township, the black boy strung sticks into
pretend pistols and shouted, ``Boom, boom, boom!'' The white boy
pictured himself in spit-shined shoes and crisp green uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   But under South Africa's white government, only one of these two
strangers could rise through army ranks. And so while the white boy
studied military history, the black boy learned to build bombs,
joining an exiled guerrilla army intent on destroying the regime
that stifled his ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   With the end of apartheid in 1994, the two enemies finally
became allies. The guerrilla, Lt. Sibusiso Madubela, rejoiced as he
donned his army fatigues and tested his military rifle. ``We will
all be equal now,'' he told his family proudly.
</P>
<P>
   The soldier, Sgt. Eric ``Dougie'' Douglas, told his relatives he
would call his black troops ``gentlemen.'' And together, at the
Tempe military base here, they vowed to fight under one flag, for
one country.
</P>
<P>
   What they found, however, was that, at the base, some whites and
blacks still fought each other.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, a white officer here locked three former freedom
fighters in a room and sprayed them with tear gas. In 1998, another
white soldier here robbed and killed two black soldiers who were
transporting a truckload of weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Madubela told his family he had been stabbed by a white
subordinate, and disrespected by others who refused to recognize
his rank. And when his pay was docked for overstaying a five-day
leave he was granted to attend his father's funeral, he snapped.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 16, he cocked his rifle and sprayed the base with
bullets. He spared more than 20 black soldiers who crossed his path
that morning, witnesses say. But when he was done, six white
soldiers and a white civilian were dead, including Douglas, 29. A
seventh soldier, injured in the shooting, died last week.
</P>
<P>
   No one will ever know precisely what touched off the violence _
the trauma of the integration process, fury over the loss of a
desperately needed paycheck, psychological instability or some
combination of factors.
</P>
<P>
   Madubela, 28, who had a clean military record, died in the gun
battle.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as weeping families buried their dead and government
officials promised a thorough inquiry, the nation embarked on a
soul-wrenching debate over the racial transformation of the
National Defense Force.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, more than 22,700 former liberation fighters and
black homeland soldiers have been integrated into the military,
government statistics show. The defense force, which was then 45
percent white and 38 percent black, is now less than 31 percent
white and more than 55 percent black.
</P>
<P>
   Military analysts say the integration process has gone
remarkably smoothly, given the inevitable challenges of merging the
white, Afrikaans-speaking conventional army troops with their
former rivals, the black, underground insurgents. Government
officials emphasize, and experts agree, that most of the 80,000 men
and women in the military serve peacefully and cooperatively.
</P>
<P>
   But pockets of tension and resentment clearly remain,
particularly among soldiers in the lower ranks who, reflecting
their enforced lowly status under apartheid, are overwhelmingly
black, and their supervising officers, who are overwhelmingly
white. In a confidential report that became public last year,
military officials documented troubling disparities in the
disciplining of black and white soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The officials described ``a marked change in attitude toward
integration'' and ``a hardening of attitudes'' among top white
officials toward former liberation fighters, who are sometimes
viewed as less disciplined than white soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   These raw issues inevitably resound differently among the
friends and mourners who buried their dead, separately, in their
black and white worlds last week.
</P>
<P>
   White soldiers carried the coffin of Douglas, a rugby player, a
carp fisherman and a father of two, into the brown-brick Afrikaner
church here. Inside, the minister preached, the organ wailed and
hundreds of white mourners wept and sang hymns in Afrikaans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something isn't done now about these grudges and tensions,
it will happen again,'' said the dead soldier's widow, Annelize,
24, referring to the black soldiers at Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, in a township near the east coast town of
Umtata, black mourners filed into the single-room, tin-roofed shack
where Madubela grew up. They sang a capella, their voices rising
and falling in their Khosa language, their only accompaniment the
murmuring wind and drizzling rain. Madubela was to be buried in the
red, rocky soil just footsteps from the hut where he was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to love them,'' said his mother, Tiny Madubela, 59,
of the white soldiers at Tempe. ``But they would never accept
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Jan Steenkamp, an officer at Tempe, feels for the families
of the dead. Some of his friends were among the slain. He says the
debate over integration weighs heavier still on the shoulders of
soldiers, who must now ask themselves: Can blacks and whites rely
on each other to survive on the battlefield?
</P>
<P>
   Steenkamp's aching left arm rested in a sling, with slivers of
metal embedded in the shoulder, where Madubela's bullet hit him. He
oversees black soldiers, and since the shooting he has been haunted
by a gnawing anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot of guys working for me, a lot of good guys,''
he said. ``But they all see how easy it is now. I can't stop
wondering, if they develop a problem, will they resort to
violence?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tempe is a dusty, windblown military base, the second-largest in
the country. Its motto, emblazoned on a sign above the checkpoint
entry, reads, ``Together we accomplish more.''
</P>
<P>
   Blacks make up about 85 percent of the soldiers. They stand
guard over the gate in green camouflage fatigues, rifles slung over
their shoulders. They address visitors in cheerful Afrikaans, but
laugh nervously when asked about race relations. All military
personnel, black and white, have been barred from discussing racial
aspects of the shooting and tensions on the base, soldiers say.
</P>
<P>
   But military officials have made no secret of the challenges
they confront as they try to transform the military.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last five years, for instance, the government has
embarked on an ambitious program of cultural diversity and civic
education. Black and white soldiers watch videos that vividly
depict the apartheid regime: the pass laws that restricted blacks
from moving freely, the signs that barred nonwhites from bathing on
public beaches and the racist pronouncements of previous government
officials. And they study the new constitution and aspects of
international law.
</P>
<P>
   The government also offers military training, literacy classes
and other courses for black soldiers, who were denied those
opportunities under white rule. They offer classes in English,
instead of only in Afrikaans, which is viewed by many blacks as the
language of oppression. And they have begun translating training
manuals into English as well, although, some complain, at a slower
pace.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Government officials have pledged that within the next few years
the defense force _ all ranks _ will more closely mirror the
population, which is about 76 percent black, 10 percent white, 9
percent mixed race and 3 percent Asian. Even the changes to date
are quite impressive, some analysts say, given the painful budget
cuts and structural reorganization that the military has undergone
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe there is sufficient appreciation for the
extent of the transformation challenge,'' said Jakkie Cilliers,
head of the Institute for Security Studies, a Pretoria-based
research institution. ``It is massive.''
</P>
<P>
   Thandi Modise, chairwoman of the Parliament's Committee on
Defense, said the government was working very hard to propel the
pace of change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your whole culture of the military is changing,'' she said in
a radio interview last week. ``It has not fully changed, because
otherwise we would not be having Tempe. But there has been change
in the National Defense Force. It is not adequate. It is still
slow, but definitely it is there.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the killer and his victim had been living out the
transformation. Both were members of the same unit, the 1st South
African Infantry Battalion; both loved the military, both loved
their families. They knew each other by sight, but the similarities
seem to end there.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas earned $440 a month, a salary supplemented with income
from his wife's job, and spent his free time with his wife, son and
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Madubela, who with less service time earned about $333 a month,
could not afford to live in town and rented a room in the nearby
black township. Relatives said he sent half of his monthly paycheck
to support the unemployed adults in his family, his parents, his
sister, his fiancee and 3-year-old daughter in Umtata, which is an
11-hour bus ride from Bloemfontein.
</P>
<P>
   Madubela's white colleagues never dreamed he would become
violent, but they said he could be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   While in exile in Tanzania in the early 1990s, he served as a
ground-to-air missile specialist for the military wing of the Pan
Africanist National Congress, which was banned in South Africa at
the time. The Congress was known then for its slogan, ``One
settler, one bullet,'' meaning that white settlers should be shot.
And it sharply criticized the African National Congress for
embracing whites, Indians and mixed-race voters and diluting what
they insisted was a black nationalist struggle.
</P>
<P>
   White soldiers said Madubela never expressed racist views to
them, but demanded respect and precise explanations whenever an
order was given. He refused, for instance, to stand when a superior
office walked into his office. (``He's coming into my office,''
Madubela said, according to his colleagues. ``Why should I
stand?'')
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a little bit of a difficult bloke most of the time,''
said Lt. Col. Jan Wessels, who commands the unit and said he
personally liked the lieutenant. ``He would like to challenge
authority. He loved doing that. You had to explain every order.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Madubela's family said he complained that white soldiers treated
him with disrespect, that they tried to diminish his authority and
often insisted on checking on his work. But Wessels said soldiers
in the unit were friendly, like family. He said he never heard
racial complaints from blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, it was not strained at all,'' he said. ``The black
people are a friendly nation, with a great sense of humor. The
moment you start joking, they respond to that. That is the way I
perceive most of them. We are busy in the process of
transformation. Everybody knows there will be changes,
mind-switches we have to make. But this unit was far on the way to
making those changes.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Madubela was about to explode. On Sept. 15, the day
before the shooting, he learned that he would not receive his
salary for a month. He had been classified as absent without leave
for overstaying his visit to Umtata.
</P>
<P>
   He was furious, his family said, because he said he had received
verbal authorization to extend his leave until his father was
buried. Military officials say they have no record of such
authorization.
</P>
<P>
   Madubela was angry, the white soldiers said, but rules were
rules. No one was surprised to see him storm off. Who would be
thrilled to struggle for a month without pay?
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him, how would we get by without the money?'' recalled
his 25-year-old sister, Grace Nondumiso, describing her last
conversation with him. He told her not to worry. And the next
morning, he loaded his rifle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 1220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5788 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-CLINTON-FATIGUE-REVIE     09-25 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FATIGUE-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU MAY OR MAY NOT HAVE CLINTON FATIGUE  
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(js) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington _ President Clinton made an extraordinary confession
at an intimate dinner with a handful of his biggest fund-raisers at
the Hay Adams Hotel across from the White House last week: The
American people are tired of him and of his administration.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding more like an outsider seeking the White House than a
fixture there for seven years, Clinton asked rhetorically: ``Do we
need a change? The answer is, yes we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was making a case for the elevation of his vice
president, Al Gore. But in doing so, he broached a notion
articulated mostly by Republicans, but also by Democrats, that a
``Clinton fatigue'' has infected U.S. politics. And while Clinton
did not use the phrase itself, he might as well have when he
explained the ``great challenge'' for Gore: ``People think at
election time they're supposed to vote for change.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton fatigue is essentially a catch-all to describe a general
sense that people have had enough of Bill Clinton. It was bound to
happen. He has pulled the public through an excruciating journey of
scandals. The most distasteful was the Monica Lewinsky matter, of
course, but new ones seem to keep cropping up all the time: The
fracas over Puerto Rican terrorists one day, the Russian
money-laundering imbroglio the next.
</P>
<P>
   With the explosion of 24-hour news on television and the
Internet, Clinton has been more in the face of Americans than any
of his predecessors. The Clintons, still craving the spotlight, do
not seem to have learned the oldest trick in show business: Always
leave them wanting more. Hillary Rodham Clinton's expected run for
Senate from New York will keep the Clinton act on stage even
longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The history of this century shows this is really a unique
phenomenon,'' said Michael Beschloss, the presidential historian.
``You have both the disquietude of the president in office plus the
added element of him having been there all those years.'' He
contended that while people would be uneasy about a third Clinton
term, if he were allowed to run again, they would not have had such
qualms with other two-term presidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no Eisenhower fatigue in 1960,'' Beschloss said.
``He would have been elected to a third term by a huge landslide.''
Ronald Reagan might have been elected to a third term as well; many
Republicans said they viewed President George Bush's tenure as the
third term of the Reagan administration. Other modern presidents
were not as popular, perhaps not so much because of general fatigue
but because of catastrophic events that undermined their
presidencies. President Lyndon B. Johnson, unable to climb out of
the Vietnam War, did not dare seek re-election. President Richard
M. Nixon did, but was soon forced from office by Watergate. Jimmy
Carter was the beneficiary of Watergate fatigue, but could not
survive the malaise of a foul economy and the Iranian hostage
crisis when the sunnier Reagan came along.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are delighting in their diagnosis of Clinton
fatigue. Sen. Sam Brownback of Kansas said former Sen. Bill Bradley
has crept up on Gore in polls in some states because ``he doesn't
have the baggage of the Clinton presidency around his neck.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the ferment about fatigue may be overblown, stirred up by a
restless press and pundits longing to begin the millennium with a
fresh presidential story line instead of what has seemed the
inevitable faceoff between Gore and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
In addition, critics of Clinton and Gore may find it easy to lump
the administration's troubles under the ``fatigue'' umbrella _ and
try to drag Gore down with them.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Fred Steeper, the pollster for Bush, the
Republican front-runner, said: ``Fatigue is too weak a concept to
fit the public attitudes about the White House. I call it Clinton
disgust.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every voter may be so disgusted. Polls show evidence of a
Clinton fatigue, but one that is not particularly potent. Clinton's
robust job approval ratings have barely budged.
</P>
<P>
   And it is not entirely clear that Clinton fatigue is ailing
Gore. In a Washington Post/ABC News Poll this month, 53 percent of
respondents said they were ``plain tired'' of Clinton, but 45
percent disagreed with that statement. Respondents were evenly
split over whether Gore was too close to the president ``to provide
the fresh start the country needs.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
