<HEADER>
A5790 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-G7-MEETING-NYT     09-25 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-G7-MEETING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS YEN RISES, FISCAL POWERS DEBATE MERITS OF INTERVENING
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With financial markets around the world rattled by
the surprising climb of the Japanese yen against the dollar, the
top economic officials of the world's wealthiest nations began
meeting here Saturday to decide whether to intervene or to let
Japan solve the problem itself.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting of the finance ministers and central bank chiefs of
the Group of Seven nations does not carry the high drama of their
session a year ago, when Russia's currency had collapsed and
markets around the world appeared on the precipice of disaster.
Asia has since begun a slow recovery, and even Japan has showed
signs of pulling out of a recession that began more than seven
years ago. In fact, the renewed interest of investors in putting
their money back into Japan is one of the reasons that the yen has
risen by more than 15 percent against the dollar since mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   But big currency moves can also cause big problems: It was the
steady rise of the dollar from 1995 to 1997 that indirectly helped
start the Asian financial crisis. And in this case Japanese
officials fear that a rising yen, which makes their cars,
electronics and other products more expensive in the United States,
could kill their economic recovery. Conversely, a weaker dollar
makes American goods more competitive abroad, but it also threatens
to revive inflation.
</P>
<P>
   American officials, led by the new treasury secretary, Lawrence
Summers, share Japan's worries. But so far the United States has
been unwilling to join Japan in meddling with the currency markets
by pouring in yen, and trying to reduce the currency's value
against the dollar. Instead, the United States has been pushing
Japan to lower its interest rates further _ no easy trick in a
country where interest rates are hovering just above zero _ and to
force Tokyo to keep spending heavily on new roads and other
projects to stimulate the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But the newly independent Bank of Japan declined to lower
interest rates earlier in the week, outraging Japanese politicians.
And the Japanese government is now running up such huge deficits
that it threatens to get itself into the same kind of fiscal
problem the United States fell into in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The standoff on how to respond to the problem has become the
first big test for Summers, a former Harvard economist who became
treasury secretary in July. Working through the psychology of the
currency markets was a specialty of his former boss, Robert Rubin.
``This will be an interesting moment to see how much Larry learned
about timing, about how to keep the markets guessing, and about how
to keep the Japanese guessing,'' a senior administration official
said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Planning _ or feigning _ currency interventions is a bit like
threatening military strikes: Governments want to keep the markets
guessing about the timing and size of the attack, in hopes that
just the fear of intervention will be enough to change the market's
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of the yen will dominate the discussions, but it is not
the only problem on the agenda. Russian officials will be invited
to sit in on the end of the G-7 meeting, chiefly to receive a
warning that the wealthy nations will not be willing to extend
further aid unless Russia agrees to regular, far more intrusive
audits into how it makes use of loans from the International
Monetary Fund. Congressional hearings last week focused political
attention on the widespread corruption in Russia, though so far
there has been no evidence that the fund's money was diverted.
</P>
<P>
   The financial leaders are also expected to approve a financial
sleight-of-hand by the fund to pay for billions of dollars in debt
relief for poor countries. An initial plan to sell off a portion of
the fund's gold supply on the open markets met enormous resistance,
both in Congress and from gold-producing nations like South Africa,
for fear that it would further depress gold prices. Now the fund
has come up with a bookkeeping scheme that would allow it to lend
part of its gold supply, which is kept on its books at World War II
prices, to the poor nations and allow them to give it back to the
IMF _ at current prices _ to pay off their debts.
</P>
<P>
   But the big problem is the yen. Summers kept the pressure on
Japan last week, deflecting all questions about whether he would
join Japan in intervening in the markets. Instead, he would repeat
the mantra that Rubin used so often _ ``A strong dollar is in the
national interest of the United States'' _ because it keeps down
inflation, restrains interest rates and allows American consumers
to purchase more imported goods. But in the next breath he would
make clear that the United States thought Japan should address its
fundamental problems ``until a solid, self-sustaining recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan has tried on its own to slow the yen's climb in recent
times, but it has repeatedly failed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
