<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5792 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-TOBACCO-SUITS-REVIEW-     09-25 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SUITS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG TOBACCO GREW LONG NOSES, BUT IT'S NOT A CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(js) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There are people who believe in little green men. A
flat earth. Looming Armageddon. There are others who believe, or at
least say they believe, that cigarettes cause neither addiction nor
disease.
</P>
<P>
   After the executives of the nation's largest cigarette companies
testified about their unconventional beliefs at a congressional
hearing five years ago, Democrats in Congress cried foul and asked
the Justice Department to launch a criminal investigation into
whether they had perjured themselves. After all, the claims ran
counter not only to common sense and mainstream scientific
research, but the industry's own internal documentation.
</P>
<P>
   But in the eyes of the law, ``truthful'' testimony does not
necessarily gibe with what most people know to be true. Even though
little green men do not exist, the earth is not flat, life goes on
and cigarettes are addictive and deadly, those who make such false
assertions under oath or otherwise tap dance around the truth do
not necessarily run afoul of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course they weren't telling the truth,'' said William
Farone, a former research director at Philip Morris who has since
testified against the tobacco industry. ``That's obvious. Whether
that's against the law or not, you'd have to ask a lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers at the Justice Department, at the same time they were
trumpeting a sweeping civil lawsuit last week against the tobacco
industry, mentioned almost as an afterthought that their criminal
inquiry was dead. Officials never provided the precise reasons for
dropping the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Yet to many at the time of the executives' April 1994 testimony,
it seemed pretty obvious that they were lying under oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that nicotine is not addictive,'' said Andrew H.
Tisch, then chief executive of Lorillard Tobacco Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that nicotine is not addictive,'' said Thomas
Sandefur Jr., then head of Brown &AMP; Williamson.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I, too, believe that nicotine is not addictive,'' said
Donald S. Johnston, then head of American Tobacco Co.
</P>
<P>
   The department's criminal investigation, begun soon afterward,
was no cursory review. The department assembled a team of
prosecutors, convened a grand jury and interviewed scores of
witnesses. After years of work, the Special Task Force on Tobacco
even went so far as to notify some executives of possible
indictments, an indication of the seriousness of the probe.
</P>
<P>
   Tapping into documents unearthed in other lawsuits, the Justice
Department used the industry's internal documents to show that
executives did not really believe what they were saying. For
instance, a 1963 memo from a lawyer at Brown &AMP; Williamson had said,
``We are then in the business of selling nicotine, an addictive
drug.''
</P>
<P>
   But just listen to Mark Smith, a Brown &AMP; Williamson spokesman
speaking in 1999, to get an idea of how slippery the truth can be:
``In the '90s, some people are addicted to chocolate. Some people
are addicted to sex. Some people think cigarettes are addicting.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that witnesses before Congress can believe
whatever they want. ``What those executives said before Congress
was basically an opinion,'' said Joseph DiGenova, a former federal
prosecutor in Washington. ``They can believe whatever they want to
believe, even in the face of scientific evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the executives probably did tell whoppers. Four years
after their testimony, another generation of industry heads
appeared before the same panel to say that nicotine was addictive.
</P>
<P>
   But proving beyond a reasonable doubt that the first batch of
executives had committed perjury was as complicated as any cancer
study. A further complication: a 5-year statute of limitations that
lapsed this year.
</P>
<P>
   Perjury cases are about more than just the truth _ which became
abundantly clear during the tortured legal discussions during
President Clinton's impeachment trial. Prosecutors must show an
intent to mislead, a difficult-to-prove standard. Falsehoods pop up
regularly at congressional hearings. Perjury convictions do not.
</P>
<P>
   ``The criminal division devoted a great deal of effort to this
investigation,'' said a Justice official. ``They decided it was not
a case they were likely to win, which is obviously a factor they
have to consider.''
</P>
<P>
   But the government is not finished using the tobacco industry's
words against them. As part of the civil lawsuit filed on
Wednesday, the Justice Department is alleging that the industry has
engaged in fraud and racketeering over the past four decades in
deceiving the public about smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, which has a lower burden of proof than a criminal
matter, lists what the government contends is one lie after another
by the tobacco industry _ like the newspaper ad from 1970, in which
several companies claimed that ``the question about smoking and
health is still a question.''
</P>
<P>
   The civil case may pry loose huge sums of money from company
coffers and force the industry to come clean once and for all on
the dangers of cigarettes. Rep. Martin Meehan, D-Mass., who first
urged the criminal investigation back in 1994, said his goal may
well be achieved even if no executive is ever charged with a
felony.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was never personal with me,'' Meehan said. ``I didn't
want to put anybody behind bars. I want to save lives and get these
executives to finally acknowledge what we all know to be the
truth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
