<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-PROTEST-495&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS RIOT IN PROTEST AGAINST INDONESIAN MILITARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ While calm returned to Indonesia's capital
on Saturday after riots against the military left at least six
people dead, students took to the streets of another large
Indonesian city, hurling burning tires and rocks at soldiers and
the police to protest a proposed law that would grant the army
sweeping new powers.
</P>
<P>
   There were no immediate reports of injuries as a result of the
riots Saturday in Medan, a city of 1.2 million people on the
northern Indonesian island of Sumatra. But Indonesian news agencies
reported fierce street clashes between nearly 2,000 student
demonstrators and a joint force of soldiers and the police.
</P>
<P>
   The new riots suggested that President B.J. Habibie had not
satisfied many of his critics when he announced Friday that he
would delay signing the unpopular security law.
</P>
<P>
   The law, hurriedly adopted by Parliament earlier last week,
would give new authority to this nation's increasingly unpopular
military commanders to declare martial law and suspend civil rights
during so-called national emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   The students in Medan were quoted Saturday as saying that
Habibie's announcement did not go far enough, and that Parliament
should revoke the law.
</P>
<P>
   The military, which is widely seen by Indonesians as brutal and
corrupt, has blackened its image most recently in East Timor,
backing widespread violence by anti-independence militias. The
small territory is now being patrolled by an Australian-led
international peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   In Jakarta on Saturday, the military apologized for an episode
on Friday in which at least two people were killed in street riots.
The violence was some of the worst in Indonesia since last year,
when demonstrations led to the ouster of President Suharto after he
had been in power for more than three decades.
</P>
<P>
   In the violence, witnesses said, a convoy of 10 troop carriers
escorted by motorcycles approached the gate of a hospital and fired
randomly into a crowd gathered outside, killing a 9-year-old boy
and a teen-ager and wounding dozens of others.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman for the Indonesian armed forces, Maj. Gen.
Sudrajat, issued the apology through the official Antara news
agency. ``On behalf of the armed forces and the police,'' he said,
``we regret the event and ask for forgiveness. There will be a
thorough investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager killed at the hospital was a student at the
prestigious University of Indonesia, and fellow students wearing
their yellow university jackets carried his coffin in a peaceful
procession from his family home in Jakarta to a funeral service.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the others killed in the violence in Jakarta were
civilians. In addition a police officer was killed when he was hit,
apparently intentionally, by a car driven by one of the protesters.
Smaller anti-military protests were also reported Friday in
Surabaya and Bandung, the nation's second- and third-largest
cities, and on the island of Bali.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The riots have compounded the problems faced by Habibie. One of
these is a major vote-buying scandal involving several of his
closest advisers; the other is the crisis in East Timor, which
appears to have pitted him against the military. He is seeking
re-election by the National Assembly in November.
</P>
<P>
   The street demonstrations in the capital's financial district _
and the scene on Saturday of city workers sweeping streets littered
with tear-gas canisters, burnt-out cars and plastic bullets _ have
recreated the image of a fragmenting nation. The nation's currency,
the rupiah, lost nearly 5 percent of its value during the two days
of riots.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the only good news for the Indonesian government on
Saturday was the failure of the U.N. Commission on Human Rights in
Geneva to decide whether to open an international investigation
into atrocities committed in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, which had been called into special session as a
result of the violence in East Timor, has adjourned until Monday
after two days of heated debate, in which Indonesia and a group of
Asian and Latin American countries opposed the idea of a U.N.
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has backed a European Union resolution calling
for an investigation by the United Nations. Indonesia, backed by
China and several other Asian nations, says that the inquiry would
be a violation of its sovereignty, and that it should be left to
conduct its own investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The vote by the rights commission, which could come on Monday,
is expected to be close. Bishop Carlos Filipe Ximenes Belo of East
Timor and the Timorese resistance leader Jose Ramos-Horta, the
co-winners of the 1996 Nobel Peace Prize, joined last week in
urging the commission to act.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sentiments to the republic of Indonesia are the same as the
Jews toward Nazi Germany and the Kuwaitis toward Iraq,''
Ramos-Horta said, arguing that the human rights commission would be
``an accomplice to impunity, an accomplice to genocide and war
crimes'' if it failed to conduct an international investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 1251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
