<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5795 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-COURTS-ABORTION-ART-N     09-25 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURTS-ABORTION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION-METHOD RULING MAY SPUR SUPREME COURT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Iowa, Neb., Minn., Va., Ark., Pa. Maine)   (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (nk) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal appeals court ruling striking down bans
of a particular late-term abortion procedure represents the first
significant legal step that may compel the Supreme Court to
determine the constitutionality of laws barring the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel of the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
struck down such laws in Arkansas, Iowa and Nebraska, declaring on
Friday that the statutes were so broadly written that they also
banned common abortion procedures that are used in the second
trimester of pregnancy. As a result, the appellate panel said, the
laws placed an ``undue burden'' on a woman's right to terminate a
pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first circuit after trial to issue a final
decision on the partial-birth abortion law,'' said Janet Benshoof,
president of the Center for Reproductive Law and Policy in New
York, which sued to overturn the Arkansas, Iowa and Nebraska laws.
</P>
<P>
   Laws banning the procedure, in which a fetus is partially
extracted from the womb and then killed by the insertion of a tube
into the skull and the extraction of the brain, have passed in 28
states and in Congress. President Clinton has vetoed the federal
legislation and federal courts have either struck down or stayed
implementation of 20 of the state laws.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision striking down the Nebraska law, the appeals
court noted that while many lower courts have heard constitutional
challenges to state laws intended to block this abortion method,
only one lower court so far has upheld any of the laws. That case
involved Wisconsin's law.
</P>
<P>
   The three decisions, issued on the same day because the cases
were so similar, were unanimously agreed to by a three-judge panel
comprising Richard S. Arnold, Roger L. Wollman (the court's chief
judge) and Paul A. Magnuson of the Minnesota district court.
</P>
<P>
   Congress still is considering a bill that closely mirrors the
language that the appeals court struck down last week, and as a
result the ruling signals that even if such a federal statute were
passed and signed into law it might be found unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only the 4th Circuit Court of Appeals has allowed one
state ban _ that of Virginia _ to remain in force while the appeals
process runs its course. Abortion rights advocates believe that the
4th Circuit may uphold Virginia's ban.
</P>
<P>
   Should that happen a split in the circuits would probably occur,
all but insuring that the Supreme Court would hear a case on the
constitutionality of the abortion ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what these other circuits do and ultimately this
issue will reach the Supreme Court which has not spoken on the
issue of partial-birth abortion,'' said Douglas Johnson,
legislative director of the National Right to Life Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Even before such bans are ruled on by other circuits, abortion
rights advocates say the decision may have an impact on the
political process, perhaps changing the minds of legislators who
normally support abortion rights but voted to bar the procedure.
President Clinton has twice vetoed legislation that would ban such
late-term abortions, and in both cases he narrowly escaped having
his veto overridden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will give a lot of strength to the Democrats who
have had a lot of pressure from states and from the right wing,''
Ms. Benshoof said. She added that it would also provide political
cover for moderate Republicans like Sens. Susan Collins and Olympia
J. Snowe, of Maine, who favor abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is scheduled to vote next month on new legislation
sponsored by Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., that would ban the abortion
method. House Republican leaders say the House will take up the ban
next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate and House bills are virtually identical in language
to those in the three states that were struck down on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, anti-abortion leaders dismiss the idea that the
court ruling will influence the votes of lawmakers when the bills
are considered again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I doubt that this ruling yesterday will change a
single vote,'' Johnson said. ``The senators take an oath to uphold
the Constitution, not the ruling of a three-judge panel.''
</P>
<P>
   In striking down the three states' laws, the appeals court panel
relied heavily on the wording of the statues that made it a crime
to perform an abortion in which the physician ``partially vaginally
delivers a fetus before taking the life of the fetus and completing
the delivery.''
</P>
<P>
   The judges noted that several other types of commonly used
abortion procedures, including suction-curettage and dilation and
evacuation, may also be banned. In both cases the fetus is in
essence dismembered in the womb and removed. In both cases, the
court noted, that in some stages of the procedure, parts of the
fetus may still be alive in the womb while other parts have already
been extracted.
</P>
<P>
   Under the wording of the laws like that of Arkansas, such common
procedures would become crimes. ``The central difficulty with the
Arkansas statute is that it covers too much,'' Arnold wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In the Nebraska case, he wrote that the law ``would prohibit in
many circumstances the most common method of second-trimester
abortion. Such a prohibition places an undue burden on the right of
women to choose whether to have an abortion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 1255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5796 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-YOUNG-PIONEERS-     09-25 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-YOUNG-PIONEERS-665&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 50 YEARS, CHINA YOUTH REMAIN MAO'S PIONEERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Each year, nearly every second-grader in China goes
through a solemn rite of initiation.
</P>
<P>
   Lined up before an audience of classmates, teachers and perhaps
some beaming parents, the school band playing at the side, they
stand at attention as sixth-graders march up and place red
kerchiefs around their necks. An older student leads them in the
pledge:
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a Young Pioneer. I pledge under the Young Pioneer flag
that I am determined to follow the guidance of the Chinese
Communist Party, to study hard, work hard and be ready to devote
all my strength to the Communist cause.''
</P>
<P>
   From that day on, through the sixth grade, the students wear
their kerchiefs to school every day _ except in hot weather, when
they wear a red pin instead.
</P>
<P>
   As Young Pioneers, along with their normal studies they learn
about the Communist Party's glorious creation of a strong China,
the importance of respecting authority and the merits of doing good
deeds.
</P>
<P>
   Supervised by a schoolwide Young Pioneer instructor, students
organize themselves into teams, elect their most upright classmates
as leaders, raise the national flag and inspect one another's dress
and discipline. They read about model Pioneers who gave their lives
while saving sheep from the cold or foiling robbers. They
participate in after-school activities like music, dancing or
chess.
</P>
<P>
   Combining elements of the Scouts, the safety patrol and the hall
monitor, larded with thick, simple doses of patriotism and
communism, the Young Pioneers remains a shared experience of
China's children.
</P>
<P>
   For a beleaguered Communist Party preparing to celebrate, and
whitewash, 50 years of rule on Oct. 1, this schoolhouse club is
about the only place now where communism can be offered and
received as a pure, idealistic force for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every child is a blank paper,'' said Wang Chunxin, the
22-year-old Young Pioneer organizer at the Yonganli Primary School
in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to teach them that China is a socialist country and
the Communist Party is our leader,'' she said on the school grounds
the other day, with evident sincerity. ``We help children grow up
better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When students first put on the red scarf they feel very
proud,'' said Ms. Wang. ``Because in this society, everyone should
be in some kind of organization, and the Young Pioneers is the best
one for young people.''
</P>
<P>
   In today's buoyant, fast-developing China, the Communist Party's
reach into daily life has drastically shrunk. For children, though,
grade school and the party's Young Pioneers club are practically
indivisible. Asked where one begins and the other leaves off, Ms.
Wang and the school principal had trouble comprehending the
question. Since all the students become Young Pioneers, they said,
how can you make a distinction?
</P>
<P>
   After grade school, the next step up the Communist ladder is the
Communist Youth League, which a majority of students join by the
end of high school for social if not political reasons. Then in
college or workplaces, a select minority _ including active leaders
from the Youth League _ are accepted as members of the party, which
now has 61 million members, or one in 20 Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Most Chinese today are cynical about communist ideology, and
many younger people are simply indifferent, suggesting that the
fervent message propounded by the Young Pioneers does not entirely
stick. But in more subtle ways, many Chinese say, those years of
hearing about the party's all-embracing and benign role may have
lasting effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little kids don't really understand the talk about `loving the
party,' and later you may think some of the Young Pioneer stuff was
funny,'' said a professional woman in her 30s. ``But that kind of
talk gets into your blood.'' The woman said the patriotic and
nationalistic elements of that constant childhood message had the
deepest impact _ so that nearly everyone, for example, gets
emotional about China's claim of sovereignty over Taiwan or Tibet.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In this respect, the role of the Young Pioneers may resemble
that of schools, youth groups and founding myths in any country,
all working to imbue youngsters with patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a difference: In the Young Pioneers, patriotism is
equated with devotion to the party and the nation. And this
message, delivered to generations of youngsters in the same
cheerful spirit as lessons on how to add and subtract, may help
make it seem natural to many Chinese that a single organization
should maintain such unrivaled power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chairman Mao founded China, Deng Xiaoping made us rich and now
Jiang Zemin is leading us into the future'' was the capsule view of
the last half-century given by 12-year-old Li Jia. Ms. Li, an
earnest sixth-grader, is one of 15 top Young Pioneer leaders among
more than 700 students at the Yonganli school. She was selected by
authorities to meet a visiting journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Li was not prepared to discuss the ins and outs of Deng
Xiaoping Theory, but she easily rattled off the weekly schedule of
Young Pioneer activities, from ceremonies to raise the flag, salute
young martyrs and inspect students' kerchiefs to more relaxed
after-school hobbies.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a leader, I have to be a good student, get good grades and
be willing to serve the other students,'' she said. ``I feel that
we are the future masters of our country, so we have to study hard
to build our country stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned that before the founding of the People's
Republic, China was a very poor country,'' Ms. Li said when asked
what the anniversary meant to her. If nothing else, it was clear
she was a good student of the party's take on history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Liberation, under the leadership of the Communist Party
and with the efforts of our people, China's economy and defense and
people's lives have greatly improved,'' she continued. ``Now China
is a strong country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 1304EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
