<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5798 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BAY-BUCHANAN-PROFILE-     09-25 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAY-BUCHANAN-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN'S SISTER SHEPHERDS INSURGENT RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bay Buchanan sighed a bit in admitting that her
brother Patrick, the quixotic Presidential candidate, was
essentially a man without a party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in no man's land,'' said Ms. Buchanan, who sounded,
however, far from forlorn at the risks and opportunities as her
brother considered casting aside a lifetime of Republican labors to
switch his presidential candidacy to the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in political limbo,'' said Ms. Buchanan, a lean and
avid political operative clearly relishing the long odds as she
plays chief strategist, fiery alter ego and grass-roots shepherd
for her brother in his threatened party switch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't ask people to give him money,'' she said in an
interview at her brother's campaign headquarters last week. ``I
can't build a staff until we know where he's running. It's a very
delicate time.''
</P>
<P>
   In this time, with no formal hustings to welcome him, Buchanan
has been publicizing a new book, ``A Republic, Not an Empire''
(Regnery Publishing), and teasing out the party-switching question
in a dozen broadcast interviews a day. He is well into one of his
signature ``America First'' controversies over his views in the
book of Hitler and World War II _ just the sort of verbal
fisticuffs that assure both Buchanans that the rebel fire is
returning to their quest.
</P>
<P>
   But the harder work in the political trenches has fallen to Ms.
Buchanan as she telephones Reform Party officials to make the
necessary overtures and to master the arcane procedures for getting
on dozens of state ballots.
</P>
<P>
   In their parallel efforts, the Buchanans are far from sibling
rivals. They are respected even by their critics as a classic
inside-outside political team practiced in the art of insurgent
mischief. And Ms. Buchanan, while a familiar sight on the
cable-television political circuit, has returned to her strong suit
behind the scenes as campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am now feeling knowledgeable about the Reform Party
system,'' she said, hardly discouraging the likelihood of the
Buchanans' defection from the Republican Party, about which they
have promised a decision by mid-October. ``Technically, I will be
able to tell Pat that it can be done and I would be able to raise
the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Battle-hardened from running the fractious Buchanan presidential
campaigns in 1992 and 1996 against the Republican Establishment,
Ms. Buchanan sounds almost enchanted that, after months of her
brother's barely registering in this year's Republican pre-primary
polls, she is scouting a fresh political Rubicon for him to cross.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Buchanan is the daughter of a successful Washington
accountant who offers a backwoods sort-of twang and sharp-edged
glance _ much the way her brother, one of the capital's
longstanding conservative elite, savors riffs of blue-collar
rhetoric. The two seem united by an appetite for contrariness.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '92 people would ask, `You're his daughter, right?'''
recalled Ms. Buchanan, a veteran political consultant who is 10
years younger than her 60-year-old brother. ``By '96 they were
asking, `Who's older?'''
</P>
<P>
   For all that wear and tear, Ms. Buchanan _ christened Angela
Marie and called Bay in a family of nine children steeped in
dinner-table conservatism _ seems addicted to cutting fresh swaths
in the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   It was Ms. Buchanan, a fierce political warrior with a master's
degree in mathematics from McGill University, who first explored
the Reform gamble for her brother. Buchanan critics suspect that
she mainly had her eye on the $12.6 million in federal matching
funds that await whoever may be the Reform Party nominee next year.
</P>
<P>
   William Kristol, the conservative Republican commentator, has
sarcastically denounced Buchanan as ``Pat the Bunny,''
opportunistically ``hopping around on the fringes of American
politics'' and sniffing out ``whatever carrots our political system
offers up.''
</P>
<P>
   In rebuttal, Ms. Buchanan scoffs at ``Billy'' Kristol for ``not
understanding the movement Pat represents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an anguishing decision,'' she said, speaking as a
Republican who, through her brother's patronage, served in the
Nixon and Reagan White Houses. ``This is not a decision you make
for money, for goodness' sakes. It takes enormous courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Heeding the different drummer may be more second nature to her
than to her brother. Seventeen years ago, Ms. Buchanan stood up to
her staunchly Roman Catholic family, including Pat, in converting
to Mormonism and marrying in that faith. Now she survives as the
divorced working mother of three teen-aged sons, heading home to
them in the Virginia suburbs after long days in the Buchanan war
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's terrific with the boys,'' said Pat Choate, a longtime
friend and Reform Party leader who was Ross Perot's running mate on
the party's ticket in 1996. Choate is in daily contact with Ms.
Buchanan now as the two strategize about how to nail down the
Reform nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bay goes home, takes care of her sons and turns off the
politics,'' Choate said. ``People don't know she also took care of
her mother in her home until she died in '96. Talk about a manager
_ Bay's the real thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Others describe her as less an ideologue than her brother and
more his devoted agent, as scrappy in the back room as he is on
television. In a 30-minute interview, she was interrupted four
times by cellular phone calls from her brother with urgent
importunings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's panicking because of where he is,'' she calmly explained,
referring not to any position her brother has taken but to the
logistics of his rushing to the next television interview.
</P>
<P>
   At the campaign headquarters, Ms. Buchanan offered a no-nonsense
sketch of the Reform Party terrain she felt she could master. She
emphasized that her brother would be pushing for the reforms in the
economy, foreign trade and government that the Reform Party is most
concerned about, without abandoning his anti-abortion stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a real good shot for the Reform nomination if
Pat chooses to go. But we'll have to fight for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take $6 million in 30 states,'' she said, summarizing
the effort in having the required petition drives under way by the
end of this year in the 30 states where they are needed to get him
on the ballot. The Reform Party is already established in 20
states. ``For the first $4 million,'' she said, ``I can get $2
million in matching funds. But my goal is to raise more than the $4
million.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Buchanan said she had been in touch with a dozen state
Reform organization leaders so far, with another dozen on her list.
``Lenora Fulani asked to speak to us,'' she noted. Ms. Buchanan
hardly sounded flustered by the strange-bedfellow aspect of
politics in her brother's having to deal with Ms. Fulani, a New
York Reform Party figure who was once an ally of Louis Farrakhan,
the firebrand leader of the Nation of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intellectually, there's no question Pat's moved very
dramatically in the direction of the third party,'' Ms. Buchanan
said, clearly warming to a fresh field of political combat that
would begin with the Buchanans' defection from the party that first
inspired their fealty and lent them celebrity. ``If your heart is
in it, if you really feel the decision is made for the right
reason, then you can get through the fire.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
