u e BC-KIDS-TV26-COX     09-25 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-TV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Experts suggest children have say in setting TV limits
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ How can Ponce de Leon, Carl Sandburg and John
Quincy Adams ever compete with Dawson Leary, Tommy Pickles and Bill
Nye the Science Guy?
</P>
<P>
   That's the dilemma parents face as the new television season
gets under way, and the kids clamor to check out the new shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're recommending that kids watch a couple of hours a day
maximum during the week,'' suggests Joan Bergstrom, author of
``School's Out!: Resources for Your Child's Time: Afternoons,
Weekends, Vacations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If kids watch for a block of time on Saturday or Sunday, they
should get out and do other things the rest of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Finley, 11, thinks TV rules are OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone watches 24 hours a day, they're not going to have
time for homework,'' says the Harrison Twp. sixth-grader, who is
permitted one to two hours of television on weekdays, more on
weekends. ``I can't watch TV or do electronics till I have my
homework done.''
</P>
<P>
   Because TV viewing is passive, nonstop watchers can fall behind
in language and social skills, Bergstrom says. ``They aren't out
trying and doing new things. Compare a kid that's watching TV all
day to one who is swimming, reading, playing board and strategy
games.''
</P>
<P>
   The best limits may be those that come from the kids themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Jasmine Ng of the Texas Agricultural Extension Services says the
appropriate TV amount varies with each child, and that parents who
veto a particular show should have done their homework.
</P>
<P>
   But don't outlaw TV altogether, Bergstrom says.
</P>
<P>
   ``A kid feels left out,'' she says. ``I knew about five kids who
would go to other people's houses to play ... and the only thing
they wanted to do was watch television.''
</P>
<P>
   And parents should mind their own TV habits, says Anne-Marie
Welsh, who writes a parenting column for the Erie Daily News in
Pennsylvania. ``They need to make the commitment and to set a good
example,'' she says. ``If children have already formed poor viewing
habits, ease them out of it. During the times when they would
normally gravitate to the television, beat them to the punch by
suggesting an outdoor activity you can enjoy together.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
