<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5800 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-AMERICAN-BEAUTY26-COX     09-25 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-BEAUTY26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Director debuts with quirky 'American Beauty'
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When ``American Beauty,'' the new biting
satire of suburban America, eventually gets released on video, it
will present a dilemma. As a dark morality tale with underlying
comedy and a murder mystery conclusion, store owners will have no
idea where to shelve it. But that's exactly what director Sam
Mendes likes about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so much of Hollywood is defined by what shelf in the
video store you're going to put something on, to the point where if
you see a script that you can't define, you don't make it,'' says
the 34-year-old Brit of his acclaimed feature film debut, which
opened in Palm Beach County on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty'' is about a middle-aged magazine writer named
Lester Burnham (Kevin Spacey). He's stuck in a meaningless job,
trapped in a loveless marriage to a manic real estate agent (played
by Annette Bening) and hated by his teen-age daughter. Yet, these
downbeat details are handled with a sly comic edge. And when Lester
develops a sexual obsession for his daughter's Lolitalike
cheerleader friend, it sets events in motion which lead to his
death.
</P>
<P>
   Murky territory has become Mendes' hallmark. He is best known
for such theater productions as the raw revival of ``Cabaret'' and
``The Blue Room,'' a sensationalist series of sexual encounters
which brought a nude Nicole Kidman to Broadway earlier this year.
No wonder DreamWorks thought of him for ``American Beauty,'' the
unconventional script by Florida State University graduate Alan
Ball, who breaks into features after writing for ``Cybill,''
``Grace Under Fire'' and the new television sitcom, ``Oh Grow Up.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendes was a bit taken aback that he was offered the assignment.
``I thought, 'My gosh, more nudity and dark territory. Why me?' On
the other hand, it's a great story.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes the studio was looking for a first-time director.
``I think they wanted somebody who was not going to obey the rules,
because effectively the script doesn't obey the rules,'' Mendes
says. He also thinks the movies have done well by turning to
directors with theater experience, citing Nicholas Hytner (``The
Madness of King George'') and Danny Boyle (``Trainspotting'').
``It's nice to have people who are used to telling stories and
holding audiences' attention for two hours in some form, rather
than directing commercials or videos,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mendes describes his first few days on the movie set as
terrible. ``It took me a while to translate what was in my head to
what was on the screen,'' he says. ``I did three terrible days of
shooting the first three days. I reshot one day and the other stuff
I cut. Not because it was badly shot, ironically, but because I
felt I didn't need it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, DreamWorks executives could afford to be patient
with him. ``One of the great things about this is they've made it
for a very small amount of money (a reported $15 million), relative
to normal studio movies. That allowed us a certain amount of
freedom. Not only did they leave the script alone, they also left
me alone, which, given the fact that I was a first-time director,
is kind of astonishing in retrospect,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Mendes likens a movie set to being in the midst of a
construction site, ``with all these people banging and crashing
around. It's so unromantic,'' he sighs. ``The theater is a very
romantic process, well, at least rehearsals are a very romantic
process. In the theater, if you say 'I don't know' in the rehearsal
room, it can be the most releasing moment. You can say, 'Let's
rehearse and try this, try that.' If you say 'I don't know' on a
film set, that's the end of the movie. They'd look at you as if you
were insane.''
</P>
<P>
   So Mendes learned to deal with the volleys of questions the same
way most film directors do _ he guessed at the answers. ``A lot of
the time, the most crucial moments are when you see something and
know in your gut that it's wrong, and you have to stand up and say,
'This is going to take us another half-day, which is $100,000 or
whatever it is, but I have to have it another way. I've made a
mistake.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mendes credits his growing up as an only child for the fantasy
life that led him to become a director. ``If you're an only child,
you constantly are living in your head,'' he says. ``You become
very good at being self-contained and alone. The flip side of that
is it's a very solitary existence. And directing is very solitary.
You're surrounded by people all day, but in the end, it's just
you.''
</P>
<P>
   As an only child, he was particularly drawn to the emotional
plights of the teens in ``American Beauty'' _ Lester's daughter
Jane and her next-door admirer, a drug-selling, technological
Peeping Tom named Ricky. But Mendes stops short of labeling his own
family as dysfunctional.
</P>
<P>
   ``This name 'dysfunctional,' I don't kind of like it,'' he says.
``I've never met a functional family, put it that way. Functional
families only exist in clothes catalogues, do you know what I
mean?'' His parents divorced when he was young, but he quickly
adds, ``I certainly would not classify my childhood as filled with
hardship and devastation. It was a middle-class childhood in
suburbia,'' not far psychically from life in ``American Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendes also brings an outsider's eye to this distinctly American
story, but he feels that much of it would translate to an English
setting. ``What I can't imagine being set in England is anything
having to do with guns, because we don't have guns in England,'' he
notes. ``What I find incredible as a foreigner is the gun situation
in this country. But everything else, the contemporary debate about
older men and younger women, the sense of what goes on behind
closed doors in suburbia, I feel would transcend where it was
set.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendes sees ``American Beauty'' as an antidote to the way young
people are usually portrayed in movies these days. ``It treats
children seriously,'' he says. ``They're not idiots, they're not
people who go around having sex with fruit pies, frankly,'' he
says, referring to the summer hit ``American Pie.'' ``They are
adults. In fact, in many ways they're much wiser than their
parents. And that was one of the things that appealed to me most
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that ``American Beauty'' is opening around the nation to
fawning praise, scripts for future films have started arriving at
Mendes' doorstep. ``The difficulty after having made a script that
I loved so much as this is finding something else that I love
deeply,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Next, he heads back to the theater, to stage the new,
long-awaited Stephen Sondheim musical, ``Wise Guys.'' No, it's not
about the Mafia, but brothers Addison and Wilson Mizner, the
architect and promoter team that left its mark on South Florida at
the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   As Mendes puts it, ``It's Palm Beach rogues out on a prowl. It's
about what America offers you, how it can make you and how it can
kill you.'' Sounds like more Mendes territory.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
