<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5801 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-GARTHBROOKS26-COX     09-25 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARTHBROOKS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's Garth Brooks, bad boy
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like Michael Jordan or Mickey Mouse, Garth Brooks is
one of those rare American icons whose image is so distinct he can
be recognized simply by silhouette. Sweeping platter of a cowboy
hat. Cheeky round face. Pudgy belly strapped behind a western belt
buckle that holds up Wranglers two sizes too small. It's a look so
etched into the collective consciousness that a mere glance makes
most people say, ``Ah, Garth.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Brooks' latest career move is so puzzling. On
Tuesday, the singing superstar is going to blow up the look he has
so meticulously crafted for 10 years when his new CD, ``Garth
Brooks in ... The Life of Chris Gaines,'' arrives in stores. Then,
as if to reintroduce himself to the public, he starts making the
rounds: Leno, Letterman, Conan and Rosie, culminating in a one-hour
NBC special at 8 p.m. Wednesday in which he sings pop/rock and
doesn't even wear a cowboy hat.
</P>
<P>
   By now, most everyone who follows entertainment news is aware
that Chris Gaines is a fictional pop artist Brooks has created to
explore territory beyond country music. The CD not only has the
37-year-old star singing 13 pop tunes, but it morphs Brooks into an
Australian-born, angst-ridden rock idol who looks like he spent a
lot of time smoking British cigarettes and listening to the Clash.
The country singer even lost weight, donned a black wig and applied
inky mascara for the album cover and video for the first single,
``Lost in You,'' which was released to Top 40 radio stations in
late July. The whole project was created for a yet-to-be-written
movie, ``The Lamb,'' which centers around the character Chris
Gaines, who dies tragically.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks himself seems to realize he's got a lot of explaining to
do to the four-wheel-drive, boot-scootin' crowd that made him
commercially bigger than the Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys, it's a character,'' he says in a surprisingly soft, FM
radio voice. ``It's the same as Tom Hanks. He can play a lost,
wonderful guy in `Sleepless in Seattle,' then he's a character
dying of HIV in `Philadelphia.' I guess the thing I don't get here
is people didn't sit down and write him and tell him, `You're gay!'
Chris Gaines is simply a character.''
</P>
<P>
   But wait a minute. Garth Brooks isn't an actor, or at least we
didn't think he was. Part of his appeal has always been a
perception of ``aw shucks'' sincerity, so it's not surprising that
the public is scratching its head at the somewhat bizarre arrival
of Chris Gaines. The whole project is kind of like having your
cuddly teen-ager show up from college at Christmas with a shaved
head or a nose ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand why he didn't just make the kind of new
music he wanted to make as Garth Brooks,'' says country singer
Vince Gill. ``But I've known Garth for a long time, and I can tell
you this. When he decides to do something, he's determined.''
</P>
<P>
   New York writer Bruce Feiler, who parlayed an Esquire profile of
Brooks into a critically acclaimed book (1998's ``Dreaming Out
Loud''), thinks Brooks has created Gaines to protect his well-known
image like a specimen in a bell jar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garth is both incapable and unwilling to transform himself
slightly into a pop star as Shania (Twain) did _ change his dress,
change his instrumentation or songwriters and basically slowly
morph himself into a pop artist,'' Feiler says. ``What he has done
is cut himself down the middle, trying to preserve like jelly the
old Garth, which has changed almost none in 10 years. He's creating
the pop persona because what Garth wants ultimately is not money or
fame or groupies. It's power. He wants to be this icon. He's got
two-thirds of the country with him, but there is this other third.
Garth thinks he is protecting the franchise of Garth Brooks by
making Chris Gaines. In fact, he's making Garth much more
vulnerable by opening up the recesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks concedes it's a leap that may be hard for the public to
make.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it might be a fear thing that people don't like their
Garth doing this, and that's cool,'' he says. ``But they need to
realize there's a lot of instances like this that have happened
before. Hank Williams was also Luke the Drifter. The Statler
Brothers did the Road Hog (a fictional character named Lester
``Roadhog'' Moran). I stopped defending it so much after I played
the stuff live out in California (for the television special). When
the taping was through, I strapped on a guitar and played `The
Dance' as a way to say thank you. The reaction I got to Chris was
the same reaction I got to Garth. It hit me that whether it's `Low
Places' or Chris, it's all Garth music.''
</P>
<P>
   In the months Feiler spent observing Brooks for his book, he
noted that the singer always refers to himself in third person. He
believes Gaines is indeed the singer's alter ego, a darker yin to
Brooks' bubbly yang.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's showing his controlled schizophrenia to the world. It's
exactly what I was talking about in the book, that there are two
Garths,'' Feiler says. ``In the early '90s, when I first started
writing that he had a dark side and was fascinated by early death,
it was considered so out there. Look at the lyrics to `The Dance,'
to `If Tomorrow Never Comes' or `The Beaches of Cheyenne.' Now it's
basically coming true. Here's Chris Gaines, a guy who gets killed
off and is resurrected by Garth. This is the inner recesses of
Garth's imagination, and a lot of fans are scared about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the first Chris Gaines single created a flurry of
curious attention when it was released, it hasn't become a hit.
However, J.R. Ammons, music director at Atlanta Top 40 station Star
94, says it's premature to say Garth-as-Gaines is a flop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's way too early to predict whether or not it's
going to be a success. Quite often record companies will send out
an introductory single and save the good stuff for later. They
don't want a Ricky Martin kind of thing, `Livin' La Vida Loca' and
nothing after that. The next single (``Right Now,'' a kind of
rap/protest/folk song) comes out Sept. 27, and I think it's going
to fly. But if this second single doesn't do well, this project is
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Feiler isn't sure that's a status Brooks will take very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say one of the first things Garth ever said to me was,
`You only get a certain time. Elvis had seven good years. The
Beatles had seven years before the breakup.' I think one of the
chief motivations here is to try to rewrite the rules of fame. To
try to give himself another shot at it. It's fair to point out that
he hasn't put out a lot of new music, and certainly not successful
good music, in the last five years. This (Chris Gaines) is an
admission of creative waning.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
