<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tips for controlling TV time
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _
</P>
<P>
   _ Involve your child in setting television limits by using a
family meeting or weekly calendar.
</P>
<P>
   _ Television should come after other priorities: homework,
meals, sports and hobbies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Try to watch television with your children. Discuss programs
with them, follow up with books and tapes if the topic interests
them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Learn more about the shows your child wants to watch. If you
don't have time to watch them, check out reviews, the Internet,
etc.
</P>
<P>
   _ Television shows for kids don't need to be academic. Shows can
be fun, uplifting and entertaining as well as educational.
</P>
<P>
   _ When a particular television show is over, turn off the set.
Discourage children from flipping from one show to another.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep a log of how much television your child is watching.
</P>
<P>
   _ Try to help children understand the way television shows and
commercials are produced. Help them become more critical viewers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be flexible. For example, allow extra time for specials that
are worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep kids away from shows such as habit-forming soap operas.
</P>
<P>
   YOU WON'T GO WRONG ... with this quality programming aimed at
kids.
