<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5804 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-PICASSO26-COX     09-25 2250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PICASSO26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The spirit of modern art
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's as plain as the nose pushed to the side of your
face. The labyrinthine history of visual art in the 20th century is
embodied in the career of Pablo Picasso.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish-born virtuoso, who often represented himself as the
mythological Minotaur, charged through that art maze for almost
three-quarters of the century. In the early years, he added
important turns himself, such as cubism, or worked with innovators
like the surrealists, who forged new directions as well.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Picasso contributed in more subtle ways, sometimes as a
symbol to react against. Whether he contributed as isolated genius
or comrade, whether he's viewed as adored mentor or Oedipal enemy,
he wielded vast influence on modern and contemporary art and on the
public's conception of the artist.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the High Museum of Art's 1997 Picasso exhibit,
director Ned Rifkin called him ``the Michael Jordan of 20th-century
art.''
</P>
<P>
   As in all aspects of cultural life, art has undergone a series
of dizzying changes during the past 100 years. Disparate
expressions, philosophies and aesthetic strategies have emerged,
held sway, submerged and popped up again, coexisting with their
polar opposites. Figuration and abstraction, for instance, have
played dueling banjos.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1970s, it seemed that the art object was evolving out
of existence, with the rise of ephemeral or more word-oriented
genres like performance and body art, earth art and conceptualism.
Yet we close out the century with artists like Martin Puryear
making beautiful, lovingly crafted sculptures and kitchen-sink
installations that are almost as academic as Guillaume-Adolphe
Bouguereau's 19th-century nudes.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from diversity, the overarching theme for this century is
the expansion of art's parameters. Artists have continued to find
new materials for art, be it someone's trash or videotape.
</P>
<P>
   They have also continued to break down boundaries between
traditional art mediums as well as between art and life itself.
Robert Rauschenberg famously asserted that he was acting in the gap
between art and life. But it's a good bet that even he didn't
imagine that a French woman named Orlan would make gallery fodder,
including live footage, out of her cosmetic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Picasso (1881-1973) never altered his famous face, though he
manipulated bodies aplenty in his art. His output was so rich and
varied that it has served as a bottomless well of inspiration to
artists throughout the century. You can go to galleries in Atlanta
today and find painters who still depend on his cubist fragments,
surrealist amoebic forms or galumphing classical figures.
</P>
<P>
   But forget the slavish followers: Many important artists of the
first half of the century _ from Piet Mondrian to Marcel Duchamp _
went through a ``Picasso period'' before finding their own
directions.
</P>
<P>
   His legacy is no less important in the second half of the
century. At that point, his philosophy and example mattered more
than his vocabulary. Jackson Pollock, always in awe of Picasso's
innovations, invented a language for himself, which we call
abstract expressionism. Obviously, Pollock's achievement was not a
simple cause and effect. Still, Picasso scholar Pepe Karmel made a
point about Picasso's towering presence when, in a recent
interview, he recalled a story in which Lee Krasner, Pollock's
wife, ran into his studio upon hearing a loud crash to discover
that Pollock had thrown a Picasso book across the room.
</P>
<P>
   He was supposed to have exclaimed, swearing, ``that Picasso
thought of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the most current art has roots in Picasso. The modern
master is the oldest of the 37 mostly contemporary artists included
in ``Regarding Beauty: A View of the Late 20th Century,'' opening
next month at the Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are exploring the relationship of ugliness and beauty, and
Picasso went against the Greek canon of beauty so early,'' said
associate curator Olga Viso.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Joseph) Beuys and Duchamp are more immediate role models to
contemporary artists, but Picasso is crucial to this time _ the way
he went against tradition and was constantly reinventing himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlantan Michael Pittari, curator of the summer exhibition
``Double Vision'' at Nexus Contemporary Art Center, traced a
different theme back to the eminence grise as well. As he wrote in
the catalog, ``So much 20th-century art, from Pablo Picasso to
Barnett Newman to Cindy Sherman, has been consumed with the
examination or consideration of the self.''
</P>
<P>
   This focus on self bespeaks Picasso's monumental ego, but it
also relates to his involvement with surrealism and its basis in
Freud's theories of the unconscious. As Picasso said, ``Art gives
form to our terrors as well as our desires.''
</P>
<P>
   Picasso's surrealism and autobiographical symbolism were
influential, but his greatest impact came through his most
revolutionary contribution to art: cubism. Heralded in the 1907
painting ``Les Demoiselles d'Avignon'' and developed in
collaboration with Georges Braque over the next few years, cubism
was a new visual language that exploded time and space by depicting
objects as fragments assembled from multiple perspectives. A number
of artists' groups, including the Italian futurists and Russian
constructivists, recognized its importance and implications
immediately and adapted its vocabulary to suit their ideologies.
</P>
<P>
   A host of individuals also riffed off cubism to create their own
expression, among them Frenchman Fernand Leger's celebration of the
machine, Russian expatriate Marc Chagall's fantasies and American
Stuart Davis' jazzy American scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Not all who fell under his spell were painters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Photographers such as Paul Strand took formal components of
cubism, while others, such as Alvin Langdon Coburn, were more
concerned with its conceptual aspects,'' explained Tom Southall,
High Museum of Art photography curator. ``David Hockney made the
most inspired homage in his montages of multiple images.''
</P>
<P>
   Hockney, who began his ``joiners'' in 1972, did a suite of
memorial prints after Picasso's death.
</P>
<P>
   The stuff of real life
</P>
<P>
   In 1911, Picasso created the collage by pasting a piece of
oilcloth that looked like chair caning onto an oval canvas
depicting a cubist still life and framing it in rope. In so doing,
he brought the materials of the daily world into the realm of fine
art.
</P>
<P>
   Collage became ground zero for much of the art of the 1950s
onward. Jasper Johns' ``Flag.'' Rau-
</P>
<P>
   schenberg's seriographs using newsprint and fabric. Andy
Warhol's Campbell Soup cans. They're all unthinkable without the
collage and its implications. Similarly, the idea that any material
is fair game for art links Dan Flavin's fluorescent light
sculptures, Robert Smithson's mud and stone ``Spiral Jetty'' and
Ann Hamilton's installations, which involve anything from work
shirts to live canaries.
</P>
<P>
   Picasso's sculpture was equally resonant. Would Henry Moore have
poked holes in his figures if Picasso hadn't abandoned the
traditional solidity of Western sculpture?
</P>
<P>
   Would David Smith have made his abstractions but for the
openwork welded pieces of Julio Gonzalez and Picasso?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the real spoon in Picasso's painted ``Glass of
Absinthe,'' one of 125 works in the High Museum's 1997-98 exhibit
``Picasso: Master Works From the Museum of Modern Art,'' paved the
way for all manner of assemblages _ from John Chamberlain's
compositions of smashed car parts to David Hammons' ``Higher
Goals,'' composed of basketball hoops, poles painted with patterns
and bottle caps.
</P>
<P>
   The collage-into-sculpture issue suggests another aspect of
Picasso's legacy. He routinely collapsed boundaries between art
mediums. We think nothing of Frank Stella's high reliefs, which
straddle the line between painting and sculpture. But at the time
Picasso was drawing in space with his wire sculpture of the '20s,
mediums were primly cordoned off into their own territories.
</P>
<P>
   Picasso didn't stop with conflating two and three dimensions. A
man with a voracious and expansive aesthetic curiosity, he worked
in any and every medium, from ceramics to set design. If the
camcorder had been invented when he was younger, he would have
tried that, too. In addition, he often made a contribution to the
field. No less an experimental photographer than Man Ray praised
Picasso's work in that medium in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   In his survey of contemporary ceramics, author Garth Clark cites
the clay work of Miro and Picasso as ``crucial'' to the development
of the craft movement of the mid-'50s, in which the boundary
between craft and fine art melted away.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Picasso's contribution was to see himself as an
artist rather than, say, a printmaker or painter.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, historians like to divide the spoils of influence
between Picasso and Duchamp, who is credited with the conceptual
direction of the 20th-century art labyrinth. Yet there is not a
great leap from Picasso's found-object sculptures, like the
sculpture of a bull made out of a bicycle seat and handlebars, to
Duchamp's ``ready-mades,'' such as ``Fountain,'' for which he did
nothing but turn a urinal upside down and sign it R. Mutt.
</P>
<P>
   If you try, you can even give Picasso some credit for
abstraction. Think about Mondrian, who played with cubism and took
it to what he considered its logical end. Then there's Ellsworth
Kelly. According to Yve-Alain Bois, the Harvard University
professor who wrote the catalog for the recent Kelly show of
drawings at the High Museum, Kelly turned to abstraction as a way
of erasing his self because he felt there was no way to out-Picasso
Picasso.
</P>
<P>
   The artist and celebrity
</P>
<P>
   If his art has been endlessly dissected, so has Picasso's
``self.'' The first modern art celebrity, Picasso has defined the
public's conception of the artist, even while contradicting it at
most every turn. We expect an artist to create out of passion and
be happy to starve in a garret. If one tries to make a living as
well, he is a careerist. Picasso's fecundity demonstrates that need
to create, but the one-time communist displayed a capitalist
canniness in manipulating dealers and working with them to further
his career.
</P>
<P>
   We think of artists as outsiders. Picasso considered himself so,
yet the Minotaur enjoyed a bull market for his art and groveling
adoration for most of his life. Stereotypically, artists ignore
social strictures. In this case, Picasso complied with the public
vision. His love life is legendary: The man in the sailor shirts
acted like one on perennial leave.
</P>
<P>
   Feminist artists, from Judy Chicago to the Guerrilla Girls, who
have made themselves heard since the late '70s, probably used the
visage of male chauvinist pig incarnate as target practice. Yet
other women _ from Cindy Sherman, who stars in her own photographic
tableaux, to Elizabeth Murray, who makes oddly shaped
autobiographical abstract paintings _ have reaped the benefits of
his aesthetic adventures as much as their male counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   More contradictions: Picasso earned kudos for his originality,
yet we know that he felt free to borrow or learn from _ some would
say plunder _ anything or anybody. He had a dialogue, or
competition, going with the old and modern masters Velazquez and
Matisse, the only peer he felt occupied the same stratosphere.
(Matisse looked over his shoulder as well, and both were influenced
by the other.) In the formation of cubism, the influence of tribal
arts, particularly African masks (and, as new information suggests,
postcard photos of West African peoples), is legendary.
</P>
<P>
   Many African-American artists and contemporary critics have
accused Picasso and his peers of engaging in aesthetic colonialism.
Certainly, when members of the Harlem Renaissance and contemporary
artists such as Rene Stout and Atlantan Radcliffe Bailey have
looked to Africa for inspiration, they have done so with a
different emotional attachment and perspective.
</P>
<P>
   It seems a bit anachronistic, however, to expect Picasso to
stand outside his times in this respect. One could take the other
side and thank him and his colleagues for seeing the magic and
aesthetic sophistication in artifacts otherwise consigned to
ethnology museums.
</P>
<P>
   For all his accomplishments, he was as capable of drivel as the
next artist. Unfortunately, the same cult of celebrity that sends
people scavenging in Bob Dylan's garbage can is evident in the way
Picasso's every scrap of paper is treated like a piece of the true
cross.
</P>
<P>
   That blinkered veneration has caused its own backlash. New
Yorker critic Adam Gopnik asserted that Picasso was only important
during early years of cubism, after which he basically wallowed in
``vulgar imagination.'' It has been said that he was the world's
greatest artist for the first half of the century and, for the
second, merely the most famous.
</P>
<P>
   True, he didn't lead the pack for all of his 92 years, but he
contributed mightily by example. When all complaints are aired and
hyperbole taken down a peg or two, however, it's difficult to deny
that Picasso, with his border crossings, his anything-goes attitude
and his definition of the artist as a creative being that
transcends any medium, casts a long shadow across the century.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
