<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5808 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.S.-DIPLO-OAKLEY-ART     09-25 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-DIPLO-OAKLEY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAREER DIPLOMAT, YES, BUT SHE SHOOTS FROM THE HIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a profession that prides itself on obliqueness,
Assistant Secretary of State Phyllis Oakley has always been
plain-spoken. She was no more so than on the occasion last week
marking her 42 years as an American diplomat, a career that has
spanned most continents and forged a trail for women in a man's
world.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Mrs. Oakley delivered a broadside on U.S. diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department, she said, is stuck in a rut, financially
ill equipped and without enough people having the skills to deal
with the post-Cold War era. The lofty ideal of the United States'
leadership and spreading the message of democracy and free markets
cannot be accomplished, she said, when ``we cannot staff our
embassies, let alone the department.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, she has watched as money for the CIA and
the Pentagon increased but the budget at the State Department
stagnated.
</P>
<P>
   She despaired, she said, as smart foreign service officers were
passed over for a galaxy of outsider, big-name special envoys who
were sent as troubleshooters to the Balkans, Cyprus, Korea, Africa
and other hot spots around the world. Morale is as much of a
problem now, she added, as it was when she joined in 1957 _ when
there were too many foreign officers. Now there are too few.
</P>
<P>
   None of this was news to the crowd assembled for Mrs. Oakley's
farewell party in the top-drawer reception area of the State
Department, the Benjamin Franklin Room. But usually these
sentiments are aired more discreetly.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview later at the home that she and her husband,
former Ambassador Robert Oakley, have slipped in and out of as they
went to Khartoum, Kinshasa, Paris, Beirut and Islamabad, and then
returned to the department, Mrs. Oakley had more to say. She
described U.S. diplomacy as ``threadbare.'' The State Department,
she contended, needs to be ``strengthened'' in relation to the
Pentagon and the Treasury Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing we have left is the military, so we use it in
Iraq and Kosovo,'' she lamented. ``The raids into Afghanistan and
Sudan _ that's using military means for diplomatic purposes,'' she
said, referring to the cruise-missile attacks last year against
sites in Afghanistan and Sudan allegedly linked to the man wanted
for blowing up U.S. embassies in Africa, Osama bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   In her last job, as assistant secretary for intelligence and
research, which she leaves Thursday, Mrs. Oakley said she felt the
impact of the slim financial resources most keenly. In the last
five years, the intelligence and research bureau, which compiles
intelligence for the secretary of state but which is also
supervised by the director of intelligence, has been a special
target for cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not be secretary of state without my own intelligence
unit,'' said Mrs. Oakley. `It's too important when you're dealing
with terrorism and weapons of mass destruction.'' It is a basic
rule that good intelligence is produced by ``competitive
analysis,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competitive analysis is essential,'' she said. ``Nobody gets
it absolutely right.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Oakley passed the foreign service exam at age 21, joined
the State Department at 22 and a year later married Robert Oakley.
He was assigned on his first overseas post _ newly independent
Sudan _ as third officer, and according to the regulations of the
time, Mrs. Oakley had to give up her job.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, Khartoum was a small city on the banks of the
Nile where foreigners could live as much like the locals as they
wanted. Because of the heat and lack of air conditioning, sleeping
on the roof is common in Khartoum. Mrs. Oakley recalls going to the
market and having a bed custom made: a pillow-soft mattress stuffed
with locally grown cotton resting on a rope mattress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first night we went up there and there was not a cloud,
just the moon and stars. I said to Bob: `It's too bright, I can't
sleep.'''
</P>
<P>
   After several overseas assignments serving as a diplomat's wife
_ and taking a college teaching job in the United States when her
husband was sent to Vietnam and dependents of U.S. diplomats were
not allowed to go _ Mrs. Oakley landed her first real job at the
State Department. By 1974 the department had lifted its ban on
working spouses.
</P>
<P>
   She jumped ahead when Philip Habib, the undersecretary for
political affairs at the time, asked her to work as his staff
assistant. Though the ban on spouses had been lifted, some
attitudes had not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would walk into Phil Habib's office in the morning with
stacks of memos and papers,'' Mrs. Oakley recalled. ``He would
shout at me, `Why aren't you home cooking breakfast for your
husband?'
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a Lebanese from Brooklyn, rough and gruff. He was a
chauvinist. He loved Bob. He thought I wasn't doing my job by not
looking after one of Phil's boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Oakley's career took off in its own right when Secretary of
State George Shultz noticed her performance on the McNeil-Lehrer
television show on the subject of Afghanistan. As the desk officer
for Afghanistan, Mrs. Oakley outshone the other guests and Schultz
called to tell her so. He chose her as deputy spokesperson to
Bernard Kalb and then Charles Redmond.
</P>
<P>
   Because Redmond had a more retiring personality and traveled
frequently with Shultz, Mrs. Oakley took over the State Department
podium, fielding questions as serious as Iran-Contra and as
frivolous as on what part of Shultz's anatomy his tattoo was
placed. (``I'm not in a position to comment,'' Mrs. Oakley
demurred).
</P>
<P>
   Walking the fine line of policy at the end of the Reagan
administration was not easy, she said. ``I found the toughest
problem the arms-control policy,'' she said. ``It was a political
hot potato. There were those of us who wanted us to be tougher on
the Soviets. The guidance was so carefully worked out you couldn't
deviate a word.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Mrs. Oakley was offered an ambassadorship
but she declined. ``The thrill of being an ambassador doesn't hold
luster for me, because I've been an ambassador's wife,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, who was known as one of the strongest ambassadors
for tough spots, said he would go along. But in fact, she said with
some self-effacement, the notion of Ambassador Phyllis Oakley with
Bob Oakley serving in the same embassy ``does not pass the giggle
test.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 1321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
