<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5811 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-WOMEN-NYT &LR;      09-25 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT INVITES WOMEN LEADERS TO WORK WITH HER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was a dinner for 10 foreign ministers, held
without fanfare on Thursday evening in a quiet, still unopened
sculpture gallery at the Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   While a chamber ensemble played classical music, the ministers
worked their way slowly through a dinner of poached quail eggs with
artichoke and caviar, mahi-mahi in tarragon butter and a cake of
chocolate souffle with sorbet and ice cream on spun sugar.
</P>
<P>
   After three hours, they emerged with hugs and kisses and a
letter to Secretary-General Kofi Annan asking him to put on the
agenda of the U.N. General Assembly their concern about ``the
repulsive trafficking in human beings, predominantly women and
children.''
</P>
<P>
   The foreign ministers _ all women _ and their host, Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright _ had taken one more step toward creating
a lobby for moving women's issues closer to the center of foreign
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent three-quarters of the dinner basically talking about
the trafficking-in-women letter that we signed,'' the secretary of
state said as her car sped back to the Waldorf Astoria to the wail
of police sirens.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was blunt: ``On the edge of the 21st century,'' it
said, ``it is unacceptable that human beings around the world are
sold into situations such as sexual exploitation, domestic
servitude and debt bondage that are little different from
slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   The ministers asked that governments start taking seriously the
negotiations now in progress on adding a prohibition on human
trafficking to a convention on international organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all had the feeling that while it was very important to
press women's issues, unless you make them central to your foreign
policy, then they get kind of shunted aside,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright has been working to build strong relations among women
in foreign affairs since her days as chief representative at the
United Nations during the first Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with 14 women worldwide holding the portfolio of foreign
minister, she has continued the tradition at a higher level. One of
her guests at the dinner on Thursday evening has been with her from
the beginning. Foreign Minister Rosario Green of Mexico was an
assistant secretary-general in the U.N. political department when
she met Albright.
</P>
<P>
   The others at the dinner were Maria Eugenia Brizuela de Avila of
El Salvador, Tarja Halonen of Finland, Andrea Willi of Luxembourg,
Lydie Polfer of Liechtenstein, Lila Ratsifandrihamanana of
Madagascar, Aichatou Mindaoudou of Niger, Nkosazana Zuma of South
Africa and Anna Lindh of Sweden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
