<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDIA-VOTE-980(TRIMS)     09-25 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-VOTE-980(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA'S ELECTION MARATHON LUMBERS INTO FINAL WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ As India lumbers into the fourth and final
week of marathon national elections, elephants bearing ballot boxes
tramp into dense forests and ponies carrying election officials
clop their way to dizzying heights in the Himalayas, all to make
sure that every citizen _ no matter how remote _ gets a chance to
vote.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth stage of voting was Saturday. By the time the last
vote is cast in the fifth and final round next Sunday and the last
indelible ink stain has been swabbed on the last voter's finger, as
many as six out of every 10 adult Indians _ more than 350 million
people _ will have exercised their franchise, election officials
say.
</P>
<P>
   If exit polls and political analysts are to be believed, the
kaleidoscope of Indian politics will then settle into a pattern
similar to the last coalition government, though different in
certain crucial respects.
</P>
<P>
   The Hindu nationalist-led alliance will most likely still be in
power, but probably backed this time by a more powerful collection
of 23 parties and probably commanding a stronger majority than it
did in April, before it lost the confidence of Parliament by a
single vote.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee, 73, seems certain to head
the new government, as he has the old one for the past year and a
half, and will hope to have consolidated his position as the
undisputed centrist leader of the coalition, the only man who can
hold its disparate parts together.
</P>
<P>
   The exit polls differ over the size of the coalition's margin of
victory _ a margin crucial to determining how forcefully the
alliance can govern. In its last incarnation, the coalition's
majority was so thin that even the smallest parties had the power
to threaten its demise by withdrawing. Much of Vajpayee's energy
was consumed by the dispiriting job of placating mercurial,
petulant allies.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts and Western diplomats believe that a resounding
victory this time would give the government more room to take
politically risky steps. On the domestic front, it could move more
aggressively, for example, to shut down money-losing state
enterprises and encourage foreign investment. In foreign policy, it
would have more leeway to reopen talks with Pakistan, sign the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty and improve relations with the United
States on trade and security issues.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But most agree that even gaining a big majority would not free
Vajpayee's Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party, the largest
partner in the coalition, to pursue its religiously divisive
agenda, which includes building a Hindu temple on the site of a
destroyed mosque and subordinating Muslim personal law to India's
civil code.
</P>
<P>
   The party will still be dependent on regional allies _ for
example, the Telugu Desam Party in southern Andhra Pradesh _ that
count on the votes of Muslims, are committed to secularism and
would almost certainly quit the coalition if the more vociferous
Hindu nationalists were given free rein.
</P>
<P>
   The factors underlying the coalition's apparent electoral gains
are various. The soaring price of vegetables that had led to such
disastrous results for the Hindu nationalists in state elections
last November have come down. In fact, inflation, a potent
political issue here, is low.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial growth is on the upswing and this season's normal
monsoon will help insure that agricultural production in this
predominantly rural nation is strong.
</P>
<P>
   Much attention has been lavished on Vajpayee's deft diplomatic
handling of a small war in Kashmir that ended with India's
repelling Pakistani-backed forces from its territory, and that
victory does seem to have burnished his popularity.
</P>
<P>
   But in interviews in villages and cities in southern, western
and northern India, voters almost never raised the Kashmir conflict
as a decisive issue. Usually, they were motivated by local,
bread-and-butter issues or the interests of their own caste or
religious group. They often said that they would support regional
or caste-based political parties.
</P>
<P>
   The days of one-party rule under the Congress Party are long
gone. It is the Bharatiya Janata Party that has wholeheartedly
embraced the necessity of building a coalition and sharing power
with its partners in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
   ``The BJP has tied up with more heavyweight regional allies in
state after state,'' said E. Sridharan, a political analyst at the
University of Pennsylvania Institute for the Advanced Study of
India, based here. ``That is a huge strategic advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The Congress Party, led by Sonia Gandhi, the widowed,
Italian-born heir to the Nehru-Gandhi dynasty, has continued to
organize its campaign around the notion that it is the natural
party of governance and the only force that can provide political
stability, while minimizing the need for allies. But that position
is increasingly implausible.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Congress Party itself has been weakened internally by
disputes over the foreign origins of Mrs. Gandhi, 52. Sharad Pawar,
the party's chief power broker in the large state of Maharashtra,
left the party earlier this year over that issue and set up a new
party that has significantly weakened Congress in a state where it
would otherwise have made substantial gains.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The regional and caste-based parties that have proliferated in
India over the past decade or two _ some of which had joined with
leftists to form a third political force _ are now increasingly
allying themselves with either the Bharatiya Janata Party or the
Congress Party as the best hope of winning a share of power at the
national level.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regional parties have realized that they can share in
power only through alliance with one of the two major party
blocs,'' said D.L. Sheth, a political sociologist at the Center for
the Study of Developing Societies in New Delhi. ``This is a
multiethnic, diverse society and it expresses itself through
coalitions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 1350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5824 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-R-NC-FLOODS-ART-TRIMS     09-25 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NC-FLOODS-ART-TRIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.C. FLOODS RETURN A LAND NO ONE KNEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Refiling to add photo advisory. No other change.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)
(nk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ Guy Bunn thought he knew his neighborhood of
40 years, the familiar slope downward from his picture window, and
then one day last week everything that was solid in his life became
liquid. A friend pulled up to his front door in a bass boat, and
Bunn, rescued, pulled an apple off his tree and knew he would never
live there again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had been living on high ground,'' he said
Saturday, as he returned for the first time to view his ruined
house and useless possessions. ``But there wasn't any high ground.
The whole neighborhood was water.''
</P>
<P>
   Like so much of eastern North Carolina, the Riverside
neighborhood that was home to Bunn and hundreds of others has been
soaked beyond salvation in the floods that followed Hurricane
Floyd, which have now killed 47 people in North Carolina alone.
</P>
<P>
   At most, a handful of homes out of 200 solid brick-and-frame
structures here will be spared the bulldozer. And by the weekend,
as a few hundred residents in the state began returning to their
homes, the mental geography of a neighborhood and an entire region
_ a people's relationship to its land and its water _ had been
permanently altered.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the week's simple exhaustion and sorrow, the prevailing
emotion in this part of North Carolina has been sheer astonishment.
No one could believe that water could rise so high, and stray so
far from its natural courses. People can accept the random winds of
a hurricane or a tornado, but a torrent raging out of a backyard
creek half a mile away makes no sense to a homeowner or a farmer
who has never seen a drop of high water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why on earth would we ever have thought of flood insurance?''
asked Robert Mullett, a manager at Bill's Barbecue and Chicken
Restaurant, an enormously popular institution in the town of Wilson
that was wiped out under 7 feet of water from a creek he had not
known existed. ``Nothing has ever flooded here. It would have been
like asking for avalanche insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   But these waters defied history and everything that generations
had passed down about where it was safe to live and farm. Most of
the 30,000 homes damaged or destroyed in the state were not on the
coast, where residents knew the risks of storms; the houses were
occupied by people whose lives had very little to do with water,
until suddenly it was upon them, in the wrong place.
</P>
<P>
   In Greenville, what appeared to be a very large and attractive
lake had installed itself across a main bridge between the north
and south halves of town, cutting off all passage. It looked like
an ideal recreational lake, except that the water was teeming with
bacteria and chemicals, and happened to be on top of the airport,
the water treatment plant and several adjacent neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   It may be a week before the flood subsides, along with those in
cities like Kinston and Goldsboro. But in cities further inland
that are now drying out, including Rocky Mount and Wilson, the
extent of the damage is becoming clear in neighborhoods like
Riverside, where residents stood warily outside their properties
Saturday as if they no longer quite trusted anything they had once
believed.
</P>
<P>
   Allie Winstead, 81, who lives alone a few blocks from Bunn on
East Duke Circle, paced around her front yard, too depressed to go
in her house, but not quite willing to leave. Everything she owned
in the world had been dragged outside by cleanup crews and left
moldering in a large pile at the curb: broken Corningware, a green
glass lamp, all her clothing, the furniture her parents had handed
down.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Winstead was sleeping a week ago Thursday morning when her
neighbor phoned and told her to get out. By the time she got to the
front door, water from the overflowing Tar River was up to her
knees and she could not open the door above the swollen carpet. For
an hour, she frantically waved a flashlight through her window
until someone saw it and rescued her.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what God took instead of taking me,'' she said,
gesturing at her possessions and the muddy water line above her
head on her house. ``None of us have anything left, but we took
care of each other, and not one person died here. And that's what
I'll remember about this neighborhood after it's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Winstead has been living with friends since she was forced
out, and like most people here, she has no notion of her long-term
plans. Some of the residents here are among the nearly 2,800 people
around North Carolina still living in shelters, while a few others
have moved into trailers provided by the federal government.
Because the water has ruined the foundations and supporting walls
of most houses here, almost no one will be able to move back in,
and there was little interest among most residents in rebuilding
near a river that had betrayed them.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Tar River's natural basin is about five blocks from Mrs.
Winstead's house. Over the years, it would rise now and then, never
inflicting any significant damage. But Saturday, on block after
block, stretching a full half-mile from the river, there was a dull
muddy crust on every car and sidewalk, on every dining room window
and tree. Carefully tended flower beds were now painted brown, and
people in brown pants and brown shoes ruefully compared the
high-water marks on their brown homes.
</P>
<P>
   There were piles of once carefully collected possessions, now
junk, in front of every house, and the neighborhood stank
powerfully of mildew and mold. A large garbage bin had been lofted
by the waters onto a telephone pole spike, seven feet above the
ground. Some people wore gloves and filtering masks over their
mouths as they entered their houses in search of a stray piece of
jewelry or maybe a picture album on a top shelf that might have
been spared.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   George Ramey Jr. walked through his mother's house next door to
Bunn's, but found little to salvage. He had brought his mother out
of the house a few days before the flood, so that she could stay
with his family when the hurricane passed over, only to find his
own neighborhood a few miles away filling up with water two days
later. He and his son became two of the town's many impromptu
saviors, jumping in their canoe and paddling several neighbors to
safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you call that being a hero,'' Ramey said. ``It's a good
thing I actually like to hunt and fish.''
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in his mother's house, and found it painful to look
at the warped floorboards, the spongy walls and the gooey piles of
dye that were once treasured photographs. It should all be torn
down, he said, returned to the wetlands it must have been long ago,
before it was real estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The houses here were like a chapter in this neighborhood's
life, and now it's over,'' he said. ``You know, a bunch of us grew
up here, and this morning a friend of mine got us all together for
a picture. It was like one last time before we all go in different
directions and start a new life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
