<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5828 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CARTER-MILLENNIUM26-C     09-25 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARTER-MILLENNIUM26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carter: U.S. has become `the stingiest nation in the world'
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jimmy Carter, on the verge of his 75th birthday, has
been peering into the 21st century and he doesn't much like what he
sees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem that the world faces in the next
millennium is already apparent to us here at the Carter Center,''
the former president said in an interview, ``and that is the
growing chasm between the rich people on Earth and the poor people
on Earth. And that chasm is increasing every year. And the trends
seem to be, so far, irreversible.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who will turn 75 on Friday, said the United States,
which he wishes were leading the fight against poverty and hunger
around the globe, is not doing its part.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, it has become ``the stingiest nation in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The growing gulf between the haves and have-nots carries
dangerous ramifications in a globalized world where people know
what's going on in other places, Carter said. It fosters civil
wars, which engender totalitarian reactions, which lead to even
greater disparities in wealth, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the United States is dragged into those conflicts, as
it was in Somalia in 1993. Other times, the nation looks the other
way, as it did in 1994, when more than half a million people were
slaughtered in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   In 1900, people living in the 10 richest countries in the world
made nine times as much money as those living in the 10 poorest
countries, Carter said. By 1960, they earned 30 times as much. Now,
he said, the ratio is 65 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, every time an American makes $65, someone in Ethiopia
makes $1,'' Carter said. ``And out of that, they have the need to
buy the same food and clothing and medical care.''
</P>
<P>
   The former president, who became known during his administration
for his support of human rights, has spent much of the nearly 19
years since he left office founding and leading the Carter Center.
The nonprofit organization works to increase agricultural
production and eradicate diseases in the world's poorest countries,
and to monitor elections and strengthen newborn democracies.
</P>
<P>
   That is the kind of work he wishes the government he once headed
would support on a global scale. But he is dismayed that the U.S.
government's ``benevolent assistance for the world's suffering
people'' is decreasing every year. ``We've seen a great
embarrassment, for me, in the United States becoming the stingiest
nation in the world,'' Carter said. ``Compared to our gross
national product, we give less than any other (developed) nation in
the world. On a per capita basis, we're at the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. spending on international affairs, when adjusted for
inflation, has been declining steadily since 1980, the last year of
Carter's administration, according to an article published this
month by Robert Borosage, director of the Campaign for America's
Future, a liberal think tank. From 1992 through 1998, Borosage
wrote, funding for international programs dropped an average of
about 6 percent annually. Under possible balanced budget
agreements, he reported, it is slated to be cut another 13 percent
by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Carter noted that a large portion of U.S. foreign aid goes to
countries with which we have special relationships or strategic
interests _ such as Israel, Egypt, Pakistan, Turkey, Greece and
Russia. Many countries, he said, direct the bulk of their foreign
aid to the most needy nations in the world, such as Liberia, Sierra
Leone and others.
</P>
<P>
   The political climate in the United States is such that the
phrase ``foreign aid'' has become an epithet, and anyone who ran
for Congress promising to increase foreign aid would be defeated,
Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   And now that it is freed from the need to compete with the
Soviet Union for the affection of Third World countries, America
has become more ``arrogant,'' he said. U.S. aid is important
because many countries around the world need help making themselves
stable, he said. Often, decolonization has left them in the hands
of former revolutionaries with little experience in governing.
Those governments, Carter said, often do not have the internal
respect and legitimacy they might enjoy had their electoral
institutions been in place for 50 years or so. The Carter Center
has worked to nurture fragile democracies, but Carter said U.S.
government support for democracy around the world needs to be much
greater.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true with world hunger. The Carter Center works in
more than a dozen countries to fight hunger by teaching small
farmers to double or even quadruple their crop yields and to grow
more nutritious grain. Carter, who once hoped that hunger would be
eliminated in his lifetime, now acknowledges that it will not
happen. But he holds out hope that it can soon be dramatically
reduced. That prospect, he said, would be increased if a major
corporation would make a commitment to introduce high-yield seed
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   But he remains discouraged by America's lack of global
engagement.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would like to see the United States, the only
remaining superpower, become known as the world's foremost champion
of peace, rather than as a country that is ``so ready to send
troops to bomb people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see our nation become the champion of human
rights and freedom and democracy,'' he said. ``Whenever a nation
has an opportunity to move toward an honest election, I would like
to see the United States providing the strongest possible support.
... I'd like to see us become the champion of all these things so
that the people in these poorest nations can say, `I not only
admire America because it's rich, and because the people live an
exotic life, but because the United States is interested in helping
us solve our own problems.' That hasn't happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
