<P>
   NORTH CAROLINA FLOODING
</P>
<P>
   FLOODWOES _ North Carolina is the nation's largest producer of
turkeys, second-largest producer of hogs and third-largest producer
of chickens in the United States. That adds up to a recipe for
disaster with Hurricane Floyd's flooding overflowing animal waste
holding tanks throughout the eastern third of the state.
Environmentalists, of course, are saying ``I told you so,'' as
farmers and agribusiness officials try to contain the problem. And
state and federal health officials are monitoring the situation,
advising most people in that area of the state to boil their water
before using. Will this lead to any change in regulation of
livestock and poultry industries. (Seabrook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH AJC PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   RECYCLE _ WASHINGTON _ Complaints by environmentalists that the
Coca-Cola Co. reneged on a promise to recycle its plastic bottles
raises questions about the economic validity of recycling. When
homeowners carefully separate their plastics, glass, paper and cans
to be recycled, are they helping establish what could eventually
become a truly self-supporting industry of frugality, or are they
merely going through a useless mandated exercise that costs
everybody time and money with little gain? (Nesmith, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   RECYCLE-BOARDS _ WINCHESTER, Va. _ Plastic grocery bags, melted
down and mixed with sawdust, produce a type of never-rot deck
planking, and a Virginia company is having trouble filling the
demand. (Nesmith, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDS: MOVED Thursday in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRATION-CHILDREN _ WASHINGTON _ Thousands of unaccompanied
children who enter the United States illegally each year are
deported without receiving legal counsel, according to immigration
officials and human-rights groups. U.S. law does not require the
Immigration and Naturalization Service to provide legal counsel for
youths who enter the country illegally. Volunteer lawyers and human
rights groups are seeking to change the law. (Smith, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: No photos as originally planned.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: MOVED Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   HDTV _ WASHINGTON _ Under FCC rules, high-definition TV
transmissions will be mandatory by 2006. But nearly a full year
after the first over-the-air signals were turned on by pioneering
big-market broadcasters, only a few thousand Americans own the
pricey new sets needed to enjoy a digital picture. To surmount the
classic chicken-and-egg dilemma which has stalled adoption,
Mitsubishi is teaming up with CBS to underwrite the conversion of
most of the network's fall evening schedule to high definition
television. Still another set-maker, Panasonic, offers similar
subsidies for ABC's Monday Night Football. A deep look at the
overall picture, providing some digital clarity. (Glass, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   HDTV-EXPLAIN _ A consumer guide to HDTV shopping.
</P>
<P>
   HDTV-DATA _ How HDTV compares to conventional TV.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BOMBINGS _ MOSCOW _ Beware of the watermelons. Keep your
eyes on those stray dogs. Nothing is above suspicion in Moscow
these days. Rattled by a string of devastating bombings this month
that has left nearly 300 dead, Russians are on edge. They are wary
of their own neighbors and fearful that their apartment building
could be the next target. Perhaps not since the dismantling of the
Soviet Union in 1991 have Russians felt so strongly, and vocally,
about anything. Reports of rampant corruption bring a shrug and a
yawn. Russians have become all too accustomed to expect the worst
of their officials, from the ubiquitous streetcorner cop who
demands bribes from passing motorists to the bandit capitalists who
have pumped billions of dollars out of Russia and into Western
banks. (Holmes, Cox News Service). 30
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Tuesday, Sept. 21 in (i) International/ and (k)
Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: With Photo Mug of Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-ECONOMY _ CARACAS, Venezuela _ Soaring unemployment,
political unrest, restive labor unions, a declining middle class,
stifled consumer spending: the portrait of Venezuela's economy
isn't one to invite a stampede of foreign investment. Yet American
companies are already here in a big way, their names gracing
Caracas' soaring skyscrapers or plastered over billboards lining
the country's modern interstate-like highway system: Ford, IBM,
Coca-Cola and dozens of others. (Williams, Cox News Service). 30.
WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Tuesday, Sept. 21 in (i) International and (f)
Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-GMFOODS _ LONDON _ The panic over genetically-modified
food is reaching deep into everyday life in Britain. Seizing on the
public's suspicions about these scientifically manipulated
products, supermarkets are jumping all over themselves to be the
first to offer the most pure products _ those with ``absolutely
no'' GM ingredients. Now pubs and other restaurants must disclose
whether their fare contains ``Frankenstein'' food. All this even
though there is no genetically modified food grown in Britain, and
the only exposure Britons have is when they consume a few products
from the United States, where people have long been accustomed to
the presence of GM food. What gives here, and what are the
implications for the U.S.? (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
