<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5831 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT     09-25 0400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Sept. 26, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dry and warm conditions will cover the Middle Atlantic and
Northeastern states Sunday as a large high pressure system moves
over New England. After a cool start with patchy fog, abundant
sunshine will help boost temperatures to above seasonal levels
across the region. Indeed, readings will eclipse 80 degrees from
southern Michigan to Maryland and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   A cluster of showers and thunderstorms will cover the Florida
peninsula and the Southeast coast as breezes from the east and
southeast direct copious Atlantic moisture into the region. A few
of the showers will be heavy, which may lead to flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Farther west, a slow-moving jet stream disturbance will spawn
numerous showers and isolated thunderstorms across the lower
Mississippi Valley and over far eastern Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The day will dawn very mild with sunshine over the western Great
Lakes. Clouds will increase during the afternoon, however, as a
cold front approaches from the west. Showers and thunderstorms will
accompany the front as it progresses eastward through the Middle
West and central Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Brisk breezes from the north and west will direct much cooler
air into the northern Plains and eastern Rockies on Sunday. Daytime
readings will be between 10 degrees and 20 degrees below seasonal
values. Meanwhile, abundant sun and offshore breezes will bring
unseasonable warmth to the California coast and the interior
Southwest. Cool conditions will persist over the Northwest, though
it will be a bit milder in southern Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: THE TYPHOON CONNECTION
</P>
<P>
   Typhoon Bart, which lashed Japan on Friday, seemed distant, but
the storm is about to contribute to a change in the weather over
North America. Weather systems around the globe are connected by a
serpentine high-level wind pattern called the jet stream. The jet
stream is the conduit for the exchange of heat between north and
south. When a strong typhoon leaves the tropics of the western
Pacific it infuses the jet stream with energy. Typically, several
days after a typhoon reaches the middle latitudes of the west
Pacific, eastern North America turns much cooler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
