<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5833 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ARGENTINA-CANDIDATE-A     09-25 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-CANDIDATE-ART-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BORING' CANDIDATE ROUSES ARGENTINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ ``They call me boring,'' says the
mayor of Buenos Aires, Fernando de la Rua, in the opening of his
presidential campaign's signature television commercial. The spot
then cuts to some more exciting personalities: first, President
Carlos Saul Menem posing in a flashy Ferrari, and then an actor who
it implies is a political ally of Menem pocketing bribe money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to end this party,'' de la Rua promises. ``Those who
are bored with me are on their way out.''
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua takes every opportunity to contrast himself with Menem
and to tie his principal opponent, the Buenos Aires governor,
Eduardo Duhalde, to the departing president and his glitzy style of
politics. De la Rua's campaign offers few detailed proposals beyond
the promise of a more sober future, but the blandness appears to be
a winning message at a time of mounting government scandals, street
crime and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   With just a month until the Oct. 24 vote, de la Rua has a gaping
lead in the polls over Duhalde, and there is virtually no Argentine
political analyst who has not already declared him and his
center-left Alianza opposition coalition the winner over the
governing Justicialist Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``You already talk like a president,'' a radio talk-show host
told de la Rua during a recent interview in the city of Cordoba.
The 62-year-old mayor replied matter-of-factly, ``I'm convinced I
will win.'' Then he made the rather modest promise of selling Tango
01, Menem's Boeing 757 presidential jet, and flying on commercial
airliners whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to project austerity,'' de la Rua concluded. ``And the
first person who needs to tighten his belt is the president.''
</P>
<P>
   As de la Rua left the radio studio, Agostina Toranzo, a
74-year-old retired seamstress, lunged at him and threw her arms
around him. ``Finally an honest man!'' she cried. ``Finally an
honest man!''
</P>
<P>
   Austerity seems to come naturally to de la Rua, a dour man of
few words who appears uneasy kissing strangers or even exchanging
small talk on the campaign trail. His nickname, ``chupete,'' or
pacifier, originated from the teasing he got as a child for his
bulbous nose, but now it has come to be the proud moniker for his
bland personality. His campaign van, known as the chupete-mobile,
is undecorated save for a single photograph beside a couch of a
statue of the Virgin Mary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really a university professor more than a politician,''
said de la Rua during an interview in the chupete-mobile driving
across sprawling cattle ranches in central Cordoba province. ``I do
serious things and I do them seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that as president he would work to bring down the
government deficit by cutting waste and graft, and increase tax
receipts by prosecuting evaders. Such policies, he said, would
increase the confidence of foreign investors and lower interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he added, ``my obsession is creating jobs,'' pledging
to bring down the 14.5 percent unemployment rate by subsidizing
debt interest payments of small and medium-sized businesses so they
can employ more people.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping out the door of the chupete-mobile to speak to a throng
of ranchers in the town of Sacanta, de la Rua bellowed into a
microphone, ``We're here to create a distinct Argentina, one where
a worker feels secure at his job and feels secure walking the
streets.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But while de la Rua promises change, he also promises
continuity.
</P>
<P>
   He promises not to devalue the peso, or otherwise touch an
8-year-old policy put in place by Menem of pegging the peso
one-to-one with the dollar. And with the Justicialists certain to
control the Senate, the Supreme Court and most of the gubernatorial
offices for years to come, it is doubtful whether de la Rua will
put many officials of the current government in prison or do
anything else very spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people want a change of government but not a fundamental
change in policies,'' said Manuel Mora y Araujo, an independent
political consultant who made public a poll recently showing de la
Rua leading Duhalde by 19 percentage points. ``De la Rua is saying
`Have confidence in me,' and that's what people want _
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua's political career is one of unspectacular
accomplishment but steadiness. He has written five books on legal
procedures, and as a longtime member of Congress sponsored
legislation to increase Indian rights and fight discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   As mayor of Buenos Aires, he extended the subway, provided
shelters and services for battered women and the handicapped, and
brought a gaping city fiscal deficit under control.
</P>
<P>
   As for outside interests, he said in the interview, ``I
recognize that I am not No. 1 in soccer, chess or golf, but I enjoy
them all.'' He is said to dance a decent tango, but his aides say
Argentines can be sure that, unlike Menem, he will not dance cheek
to cheek with starlets in low-cut dresses on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Argentines want to leave behind the Ferrari driver who drives
to Mar del Plata at 125 miles per hour, avoiding fines and not
paying tolls,'' said Sen. Carlos Alvarez, de la Rua's vice
presidential running mate, referring to a famous stunt by Menem a
few years ago. ``They now want a driver who drives a standard car
with his family, obeys the speed limits and pays the tolls just
like everyone else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
