<HEADER>
A5836 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-BILLIONAIRE-CHILDSUPP     09-25 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILLIONAIRE-CHILDSUPPORT-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IS ENOUGH TOO MUCH? 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By DAVID ROHDE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patricia Duff knows what a 4-year-old girl needs to live a
``moderately luxurious'' life on a ``rough parity with an Upper
East Side family'' _ about $4,400 a day. That covers lodging in a
$5 million 10-room apartment on the Upper East side and a house in
the Hamptons, $2,500 worth of ``prints'' for her closet and $1,450
a month for dining out.
</P>
<P>
   To the delight of New Yorkers disgusted by the spectacle and to
the dismay of New Yorkers dazzled by tales of fairy-tale opulence,
the child support battle between Ms. Duff, a multi-millionaire
Democratic fund-raiser, and her ex-husband, the billionaire Revlon
chairman Ronald O. Perelman, concluded last week in state Supreme
Court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Now Justice Franklin R. Weissberg, a man who brings bag lunches
to court, will decide whether to grant Ms. Duff's request for $1.6
million a year in child support. It is by far the largest request
ever made in New York, and probably the country. ``That is off the
Richter scale of any state I know of,'' said Michael McCurley, a
Dallas lawyer who is president of the American Academy of
Matrimonial Lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989 the New York Legislature established guidelines for
setting child support that used a formula and other criteria to
create uniformity and make sure that the children of divorced
parents don't suffer financially, particularly among the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines have encouraged settlements and discouraged ugly
courtroom brawls like the Duff-Perelman scrum, which so far has
generated over $3 million in legal fees. After Weissberg decides
the child support issue, another state Supreme Court justice will
decide which parent gets full or partial custody of their daughter,
Caleigh.
</P>
<P>
   In his decision, expected this fall, Weissberg must decide how
to apply guidelines for ordinary incomes to extraordinary amounts.
``Believe me, when the statute was put together it didn't
contemplate a billionaire,'' said Susan Bender, a Manhattan divorce
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Under the guidelines, 17 percent of pretax parental income is to
be paid in support for one child. Twenty-five percent is paid for
two. Weissberg can also order Perelman to pay for additional items
like private school, tutors and art lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Divorce lawyers say that no matter what the parents' wealth, New
York judges have generally awarded no more than $56,000 a year (17
percent of $300,000 in annual income) in support for a single
child.
</P>
<P>
   But Perelman, with an estimated worth of $3.8 billion and an
annual income of $40 million, is far from your run-of-the-mill ex.
The secretive corporate mogul is one of New York's richest men, and
his taste for the good life is said to be rivaled only by that of
Ms. Duff.
</P>
<P>
   Richard D. Emery, the 21st lawyer to represent Ms. Duff, cited
past rulings that held that a child should not have to pass between
two parental homes where one parent's lifestyle is far more
luxurious than the other's. He said for psychological and other
reasons Caleigh should also not have to live worse off than her
sister Samantha, Perelman's daughter from an earlier marriage.
(Samantha's mother, Claudia Cohen, received an $80 million
out-of-court settlement after her 1994 divorce.)
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're talking about creating a psychologically sound world
for a child, then those disparities should be eliminated,'' Emery
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   But divorce lawyers said those rulings surely didn't have Ms.
Duff and Perelman in mind. ``Like the kid is supposed to have five
houses around the world like her father,'' said William C. Herman,
a Manhattan divorce lawyer. ``Not going to happen. No way.''
</P>
<P>
   In the realm of the ultra-rich, Ms. Duff's divorce settlement
seems relatively modest. In a move that might be expected from a
corporate raider, Perelman had Ms. Duff sign a pre-nuptial
agreement before their two-year marriage began in 1996. Emery
insisted that the requested child support was intended for Caleigh
alone and not to supplement what Ms. Duff receives herself.
</P>
<P>
   Several divorce settlements in New York involved wives receiving
$50 million to $100 million, and McCurley said he once negotiated a
$1 billion settlement. In her divorce settlement, Ms. Duff received
$21 million and $1.2 million in annual alimony. ``You hate to sound
tacky about $20 million,'' McCurley said. ``But that's a drop in
the bucket compared to $4 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   Some divorce lawyers say Ms. Duff will be lucky to get the
$144,000 a year she currently receives in temporary child support.
With judges generally ruling that child support is not to be used
as way to redistribute wealth, Weissberg is unlikely to change
precedent by granting Ms. Duff her version of ``rough parity with
an Upper East Side family,'' the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Child support is not meant to be anything more than child
support,'' McCurley said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
