<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5859 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BERLIN-REBIRTH-ART-97     09-25 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERLIN-REBIRTH-ART-970(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERY IN, VERY BERLIN, AND ALTOGETHER NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Imagine finding a vacant lot on the banks of the Seine,
opposite the Louvre, and using it periodically as a discotheque.
Unthinkable, of course. But not in Berlin, where the Kunst und
Technik club opens its doors from time to time and demonstrates
that right now, in this city, anything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   On the banks of the Spree, in the early hours, revelers dance,
gazing out at the magnificent dome of the Bode museum of
antiquities on the island opposite. Several young men urinate into
the dark water. The city's choicest real estate has been given over
to a makeshift techno club, and nobody can quite believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heidelberg was so boring,'' said Mathias Santelmann, a law
student who moved recently from the old university town to the new
German capital. ``This place is going to be to Germany as New York
is to the United States.'' He pointed to the mesmerizing river and
dome, and exclaimed, ``Look, we're here at the creation!''
</P>
<P>
   Germany's inhibitions being what they are, the re-creation of
Berlin as the home of the government in recent weeks has been a
muted affair: no big rallies, no public festivities, no showy
speeches from the chancellor. ``We're still fearful of the wrong
images, so we like to pretend that nothing is happening,'' said
Peter Schneider, a writer.
</P>
<P>
   And yet. As diplomats and civil servants unpack, as embassies
hold ``Welcome to Berlin'' parties, as newspapers offer ``Berlin
supplements,'' as completed buildings emerge from a labyrinth of
cranes, as an immense show opens on German art in this century,
something is in the air. Perhaps it could best be called the spark
of the unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin, it has long been said, is damned: The city is so busy
becoming, it never gets around to being. Cataclysm has intervened
too regularly for that. But everyone seems to sense that this fifth
attempt in this century at Berlin-as-capital _ after the Kaiser,
Weimar, Hitler and the East German communists _ is the last best
chance for the city to overcome its curse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a great city of the next century, but it still
has to be created,'' Karl Kaiser, the director of the German
Institute for Foreign Affairs, said as he moved into his new Berlin
premises this month. ``And I think it is the open-endedness that
creates this strong sense of intrigue.''
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps the intrigue lies in the almost physical sense today
of a German future being dragged from a still-cloying past. After
Bonn, an escape from history, Berlin offers a daily confrontation _
with imperial pomposity, with Nazi madness, with East-West
division. And in this encounter Germany's hope of an elusive
reconciliation may lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most young Germans now going to Berlin, our history starts
in 1945 or with the Holocaust,'' said Hans Mommsen, a historian.
``National pride, in so far as it exists, has nothing to do with
the Bismarckian Reich. It has to do with the constitution and the
democracy of the federal republic. We have developed a new national
consciousness, one forged from the terrible legacy of Auschwitz.''
</P>
<P>
   It is this reformed nation that will be tested in Berlin. For
the consciousness of old Germans and young Germans, of east Germans
and west Germans, is by no means at one, and this city is the
symbol of the traumas that have divided them.
</P>
<P>
   From his anonymous Bonn office, Kaiser has moved into a building
that was constructed as the Royal Yugoslav Legation in the 1930s.
After the war, the building housed a restitutions court for
property stolen by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   That is Berlin: History is everywhere, inescapable as the
construction sites hoisting the new city into being, visible in
buildings or graves still bullet-scarred from Hitler's war, written
on the surviving pieces of the wall.
</P>
<P>
   A pervasive history, menacing, grandiose or just plain hideous,
as in Honecker's Palace of the Republic _ a building strangely
close to the heart of many easterners _ or Ossis _ even as it is
loathed by Wessis who want to rebuild the castle of the old
emperors on that very site.
</P>
<P>
   Can any national pride emerge from such a history? ``Patriotism
is not a word you use easily in Germany,'' said Michael Naumann,
the country's top cultural official. ``But yes, I am a patriot. I
take pride in what we have become, in our language, in our legal
system. And I think Berlin offers a chance for this new German
patriotism.''
</P>
<P>
   Germans had a phrase for the situation at the end of World War
II: They called it Stunde Null, or zero hour. Then, when the Berlin
wall came down a decade ago, it was Stunde Null again, a new
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, quiet as they are, these balmy fall days amount to a
third zero hour, a moment when Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder has
declared unabashedly that his country is a ``great power'' again,
an hour of emancipation, as if this return to Berlin 54 years after
Hitler's Reich symbolized the end of an unseen but powerful
tutelage.
</P>
<P>
   So it seems, at least. But this city is scarcely ``great'' or
``normal'' yet; nor is it the booming place imagined when the
decision to bring the capital back here was made in 1991. Then,
predictions suggested that the population would swell to 4.5
million by the year 2000 and to between 5 million and 6 million by
2005.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the population _ now 3.4 million _ has stagnated, as
new arrivals have been offset by Berliners migrating to the lower
taxes of the surrounding state of Brandenburg. A predicted business
boom has also failed to happen, leaving the center of the city
littered with unoccupied office space. More than 250,000 Berliners
are unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of the imagined meeting place of East and West here in
Berlin, the city is merely the largest used-car dealership for East
Europe,'' Thierry Chervel commented recently in the Sueddeutsche
Zeitung.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He had a point. Berlin was hypnotic in the 1920s _ the charged,
menacing sensual city of Otto Dix's canvases. During many of the
Cold War years, West Berlin was hip, an edgy, energetic place of
refuge for those fleeing the oppressive conformity of many of the
cities of the old West Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even then, Berlin was far from the metropole so often
dreamed-of. Today, the city often looks seedy and cheap. Stroll
east down the central Kurfuerstenstrasse and the classy prostitutes
at one end give way to ragged young women clearly just arrived from
countries farther east.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet gentrified like Paris or much of New York, Berlin
remains raw and continues to offer cheap enough housing close to
the center to retain its proletarian touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Berlin is definitely the world capital of bad taste,'' said
Michael Mussotter, an architect. ``I love the city for that bad
taste, for the mix of classes, for the cheap public housing amid
the grand new developments.''
</P>
<P>
   Those developments _ most visibly the new Potsdamer Platz with
its Walt Disney productions, its Tony Roma's, its immense mall _
have been overwhelmingly commercial, a sign that the hour is one of
marketing rather than social or political ideals.
</P>
<P>
   The city has already changed immensely. Much of west Berlin,
once so lively, now seems a dowdy and forgotten place. The
Kurfuerstendamm, that mecca of shopping conceived to show Cold War
escapees from the east what they had been missing, is simply
dismal. All the energy is in eastern districts like Mitte or
Prenzlauer Berg.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, these shifts have not produced a whole _ what Mark
Braun, an architect, called ``the urban grain you have in London or
in Paris, the grain that was lost in the demolition that Berlin has
known.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that grain is nothing other than civilization, its
slow and patient accumulation, in stone after stone.
</P>
<P>
   And when Berliners talk incessantly about their dreams of a
Weltstadt, or world city, the German thirst for a civilized,
cosmopolitan norm is palpable.
</P>
<P>
   Such an achievement _ a great city, open to the world, to east
and to west, showing its history but unthreatened by it, powerful
but unthreatening to others _ would, it seems, represent the
ultimate healing of Germany's many wounds.
</P>
<P>
   For now, whatever Schroeder may say, that reconciliation remains
some way off. In its place is a jagged energy, an edginess, an
openness that leaves a piece of formerly eastern riverside property
in the hands of an association of artists who, for reasons best
known to themselves, open the premises as a club on every date
divisible by six.
</P>
<P>
   That place is Kunst und Technik, very in, very Berlin. Julia
Tanzer, 23, comes here regularly. ``This city is my future,'' she
said simply.
</P>
<P>
   And what of the city's painful past? ``You know, we see it for
the first time in schools, when we are 9 years old, we see
Auschwitz, and what do we feel? Horror, of course. It's terrible,
terrible _ but it's not my fault.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
