<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5872 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CALIF-CONDORS-515&AMP;ADD     09-25 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-CONDORS-515&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA CONDORS LEARNING WHAT IT MEANS TO BE WILD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BARBARA WHITAKER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINE MOUNTAIN CLUB, Calif. _ Perched on a roof in this small
wilderness community, California condor W0 is a sight to behold.
Weighing in at about 20 pounds, with a wingspan around 9 feet and
history going back to the time of the mastodon, his presence is
awe-inspiring. But Mike Barth, a wildlife biologist, would rather
he just went away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have to flush him,'' said Barth, a supervisory
biologist with the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, after examining
the bird with binoculars and watching it for about five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Before he got the chance, however, W0 obligingly lifted off and
sailed across the valley to his cohorts resting on dead trees
across the way. But chances are he will be back.
</P>
<P>
   More than half the free-flying condors released in California
seem to have taken a shine to this retreat in the San Emigdio
Mountains about 50 miles northwest of Los Angeles. They have been
visiting regularly over the last month, confounding wildlife
officials, captivating residents and creating mischief by ripping
up deck furniture, doormats and, in one case, tearing through a
screen and into a bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Once threatened with extinction, the condors are part of a group
born in captivity after their dwindling numbers led officials to
capture the last of the California condors in 1987. At that time,
there were only 27 California condors in existence.
</P>
<P>
   So successful was the breeding program that officials began
reintroducing them to the wild in 1992. There are now 162
California condors, with 113 in captivity, 29 flying free in
California and 20 more in Arizona near the Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   While the condors have shown up in communities before, never
have there been so many that have been so persistent in their
presence in one area. One day this month, 15 condors showed up on a
Pine Mountain Club roof, and they have continued to visit,
generally in lesser numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The new boldness has led to concerns and ultimately some debate
about how to address the situation.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Fish and Wildlife biologists move the birds along by waving
their arms or lobbing pine cones in their direction, and community
meetings have been held in many areas to encourage residents to do
the same. But some residents object to running the birds off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made my property off limits to fish and wildlife officials
because I don't like them harassing the birds,'' said Les Reid, a
former board member of the Sierra Club, who lives in Pine Mountain
Club. ``As far as I'm concerned they should leave the birds alone.
They're a great addition to our community.''
</P>
<P>
   This from a man who has had the most invasive visit to date.
This month Reid, who is 83, was working at his computer when he
heard a racket upstairs in his bedroom. He went to check, and found
that eight condors had torn through a screen door and were wreaking
havoc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't mad, I was just astonished,'' Reid said. ``I looked
at them. They looked at me. It was as if we were having a meeting.
I said, you have to go the same way you came, and they filed out.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Reid and his wife, Sally Milhauser Reid, who has advanced
Alzheimer's disease and lives in a Bakersfield institution, had
opposed efforts to take the California condors out of the wild,
urging the authorities to focus more on securing their habitat.
Their fear at the time was that the birds bred in captivity would
become too tame.
</P>
<P>
   He points to the condors' behavior as proof that he and his wife
were right.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Mesta, the condor-program coordinator for the Fish and
Wildlife Service, said it remained to be seen whether the
California condors bred in captivity would be different birds from
those that were captured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the population is heavily manipulated to maintain
it in the wild, there is a certain amount of evolution that has to
occur,'' Mesta said. ``These guys are going to have learn to be
wild condors.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems being confronted now are not unlike those that
occurred when the birds were released, only to be killed or injured
when they came into contact with electrical lines. In response,
wildlife officials introduced an exercise in the pre-release flight
pens, in which the birds received mild shocks when they sat on
utility poles.
</P>
<P>
   Puppets have been used in raising the chicks to avoid human
contact, and now officials have also introduced a program to make
the first contact with humans unpleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Mesta said, ``It wasn't as successful as the
power-pole aversion.''
</P>
<P>
   To some extent the birds' nature presents a problem. California
condors have existed in the wild with no predators and, as a
result, no real natural fears. In addition, the condors that fared
best in the wild were the best foragers; these were also the ones
with the most curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   Pine Mountain Club, a community of 1,900, is on a flight path
historically used by the condors, and many homes sit enticingly on
ridges where the condors can catch updrafts that allow them to
soar.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've never had any parents out here as role models, so
they've kind of learned everything on their own,'' Barth said. ``So
when they land on a house I try to make it feel wrong to them.''
</P>
<P>
   His concern is not so much that the birds will hurt humans, but
that they will hurt themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife officials are hoping that the birds' interest in humans
will disappear once they come of breeding age, which is 6 to 8
years old. Eleven in the group of 20 staying in the southern part
of the California habitat are 5{ and could possibly begin mating
next spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping they have to think more about having another
mouth to feed and they won't have time to go curiosity-seeking as
much, if at all,'' Barth said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, wildlife officials and bird enthusiasts said
they would continue to try to strike a balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dilemma, it really is,'' said Clark Moore, a volunteer
condor monitor who conducts community education programs that
encourage residents to shoo the birds away. ``My philosophy is just
keep doing what we're doing until they get to be adults and have
some responsibility. I suppose it's not all that different than
raising a teen-ager.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
