<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5873 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     09-25 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 SPORTS COLUMN: FRIDAY NIGHT LIGHTS COME TO THE BRONX 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The sun was just setting, the sky still bright, when
the kids began asking for the lights. ``Miss D.,'' a boy in a red
Kennedy High School football jersey called out, ``we've got to turn
them on.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary DeCesare, emerging from the football office inside the
hulking building set off Tibbett Avenue, waved him away. ``We've
got time,'' she said, but she understood what the rush was, what
the glow of lights on a balmy Bronx night meant, and not just for
the kids on the field, loosening up for the urban version of Friday
Night Lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lights make them all feel part of a happening, an event,
and they need it and they deserve it,'' she said. ``Why shouldn't
they have the chance to feel good about where they go to school,
like those kids who have everything?''
</P>
<P>
   That was a relative comparison, something of an overstatement,
Susan Wagner High School, Kennedy's opponent Friday night, being as
public a New York City school as Kennedy. But there are
night-and-day differences within a city of haves and have-nots that
typically, sadly, have everything to do with race and class. After
two decades at Kennedy of teaching math and helping the veteran
football coach, Jerry Horowitz, count pennies, Mary DeCesare has
developed her own special formula to calculate the differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to play Wagner out in Staten Island last year,'' she
said. ``They must have had 40 parents at the concessions. I
couldn't believe it _ they were selling nachos with melted
cheese!''
</P>
<P>
   In the Public Schools Athletic League, those kinds of toppings
add up to the amenities far beyond the bare chips. When Wagner came
to play Kennedy on Friday night, to win the latest meeting of
traditional city heavyweights by 20-8, it came not by school bus,
but by coach. It came with an elevated platform stand for its
assistant coaches. It brought its own bench, a commodity the home
team did not have.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, at least, had a home.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after its old turf field had been condemned, after
Horowitz and his phalanx of unpaid helpers dragged the program
along on black-top cement and his 1996 team to a city championship
without the benefit of one game at home, Kennedy this season moved
back into its own $2.5 million facility. On the scale of high
school athletic accommodations, Kennedy now ranks much closer to
Susan Wagner than it does to the unfortunate cases like Manhattan
Center, which begins every practice shoveling dog waste off the
hash marks.
</P>
<P>
   All over a city whose mayor can't wait to build grand sports
palaces for the rich and corporately connected, high school kids
tackle each other on wastelands of dirt and rocks. As it somehow
took three years to lay Kennedy's new field after Bronx Borough
President Fernando Ferrar organized a coalition of underwriters,
the needy should know not to hold their breath. And this being New
York, even the Kennedy story concludes with no Hollywood flourish,
only a functional home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' said Mary DeCesare, ``it feels like we gave birth
to an elephant.''
</P>
<P>
   The scoreboard and clock could have worked better Friday night.
One of the goal posts faded right, like an errant kick. The incline
from the football turf to the track that has already wrecked one
ankle could be smoother. One of the banks of lights was dark and
the others could have been brighter, and fate could have most
certainly been kinder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The field itself is a dream,'' said Horowitz, who added that
no one deserved to play on it more than Ariel Delosangele.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-year-old senior put in two years of practice at fullback
and linebacker on the cement and gravel. ``Over there by the tennis
courts,'' he said, ``we couldn't tackle, couldn't hit. It killed
your ankles.''
</P>
<P>
   But this was going to be Delosangele's year, until Aug. 28, the
day after his birthday. The Knights were playing their
red-and-white intrasquad scrimmage. Delosangele was carrying the
ball. ``I planted my foot and it got struck in the turf,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Three tacklers converged. The ligaments in his right knee
ripped. His season was shattered, his dream was gone, the way of
Vinny Testaverde's. Delosangele limped along the sideline in his
red No. 21 jersey Friday. He wore some of his teammates' jewelry
around his neck and screamed encouragement at them when they fell
behind, 14-0, in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The bad comes with the good. You learn that fast in the New York
schools. Horowitz has put in 20 years coaching at Kennedy, watching
the financing dry up, the turf die, the kids disappear into the
streets. He could have left several times, but he is from the area
and his wife, Wendy, teaches there, too. An 83-year-old Kennedy fan
and neighborhood guy named Mac Faro said Horowitz worked every
spare minute to get the new field, to keep his baby alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most guys would have said to heck with it,'' Faro said near
the Kennedy bench, ``but he wouldn't let it go.''
</P>
<P>
   Up the hill from Kennedy is fashionable Riverdale, where the
money is, and across the Metro-North Railroad tracks is Columbia
University's Wien Stadium, what the money buys. But the students
and the parents and the stragglers from the area filled up the
bleachers, and the kids from the school's environmental club sold
the hot dogs, and the game went on Friday night as night fell, and
the home of the Knights lighted up the Bronx.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
