NYT-09-25-99 1447EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5874 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-PREVIEW-FRASER26-     09-25 1990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PREVIEW-FRASER26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers' first coach expecting intensity from team
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tap, tap, tap . . . . The locker room in Orlando,
Fla., was quiet, except for the sounds of a head coach doing a slow
burn. It was another bad period of hockey. The players knew it. The
coach knew it. The players knew the coach knew it. They tried not
to stare when he picked up a hockey stick and methodically began
tapping it on the floor, as if testing its weight. Tap, tap, tap .
. . .
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as he grabbed the stick, everybody tensed up,'' said
Hubie McDonough, the former minor-league player from Orlando.
``When he started tapping it, you knew it wasn't going to be long
before it started helicoptering around the room. Then he picked it
up and threw it against the wall. Then he picked up another one and
threw it in the other direction like a javelin.''
</P>
<P>
   From the other side of the wall, Don Waddell, the Orlando Solar
Bears general manager, could hear the tirade. Waddell knew his
coach, Curt Fraser, was prone to explosions but this one sounded
worse than usual. Then again, Waddell could only guess, because he
was in an adjacent trainer's room at the time and didn't actually
see anything until ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard this bang, crash, and all of a sudden the butt end of
a stick comes through the wall,'' Waddell said. ``It was legendary.
We kept that stick in the wall for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Curt Fraser does leave his imprint on hockey teams. The walls at
the Orlando Arena have been patched since that memorable outburst a
few years ago. But even today, the IHL's Solar Bears hand out a
player-of-the-game award dubbed, ``The Winning Wand,'' a taped-up
stick remnant that survived the between-periods chucking.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Fraser gets an embarrassed look on his face
when asked about the incident. He is quiet for a while, then
finally says, ``I might've been a little rough around the edges
before. I wasn't as polished as I am now. But I was winning 50
games a year, so I couldn't have been too far off the mark.''
</P>
<P>
   The NHL season is on the verge of beginning, and Fraser is
facing as big a challenge as when he carried a stick as a 433-point
left winger, dropped it as one of the league's best brawlers or
threw it as one of the minor league's best but most combustible
coaches. He had never so much as interviewed for an NHL
head-coaching job before the Thrashers hired him as their first
bench boss just six weeks before training camp.
</P>
<P>
   After eliminating several candidates with NHL experience,
Waddell concluded that what worked on one level in Orlando could
work on the next level here. A check of references indicated that
Fraser had, if not mellowed, at least recognized that there were
other ways to achieve 50 wins _ ways that didn't have players
asking out at the end of the season. ``When I hired him in Orlando,
he was always on the edge of boiling over too quickly,'' Waddell
said. ``That's not a fault; that's just something you have to learn
from. Players need to be driven but can't be driven every night.
Curt knows that now. Two or three years ago, he would not have been
ready for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyrants and expansion teams don't mix in the NHL. Coaches who
walk around with a perpetually lit fuse generally lack patience, an
important trait when you are trying to infuse confidence in an odd
collection of players. No NHL expansion team has made the playoffs
on merit. Four _ Philadelphia, Los Angeles, St. Louis, Minnesota _
made it in 1968, only because the league mandated that four of the
six teams in the all-expansion former West Division be granted
berths. Edmonton and Hartford reached the postseason in 1979, but
both were whole teams absorbed from the World Hockey Association.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser might not have been ready to make the transition if he
had not, as he put it, ``smooth out the rough spots.'' Hockey, he
knew about. Things like team dynamics and communication, he had to
learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``From his first year to his fourth year here was like night and
day,'' said McDonough, who played for Fraser and now is an Orlando
assistant coach. ``It used to be guys were afraid to go in and talk
to him. There was one incident between he and I when I thought he
was being unfair with the guys in the room. He left and I whacked
something, and then he came back and we had it out. But after that
game, we talked and our relationship changed.''
</P>
<P>
   John Weisbrod, the Orlando general manager who followed Waddell
two years ago, is credited with persuading Fraser to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Curt had a difficult time understanding the modern athlete,''
Weisbrod said. ``He thought every player would approach the game
the same way he did. He wasn't a real touchy-feely kind of guy. I
spent a good part of that first year trying to convince him that he
could make an effort to relate to the player a little more and it
wouldn't compromise his intensity or his authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the problems were inevitable. When a kid grows up in
rugged Western Canada with moderate skills and overachieves to
become one of the best players in the juniors, when he agrees to
accept a role as the team's enforcer because that's what the coach
felt was needed to win, that same person later in life naturally
expects his players will carry the same passion.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser never knew any other way. He was born in Cincinnati but
was raised in the northern provinces. His father, Barry Beatty, was
a pro hockey player just starting out in his career for the
minor-league Cincinnati Mohawks. But when he was only 22 years old,
he was tripped on a breakaway and slid head first into the
goalpost. Fraser's father, who was not wearing a helmet at the
time, required brain surgery that saved his life, but he was forced
to retire.
</P>
<P>
   The family moved to Western Canada. Fraser grew up a rink rat.
His mother, Jean, was a figure skater and, according to Fraser,
``She would've been in the Ice Capades if she didn't have me.'' The
family moved to within two blocks of an ice rink in Vancouver.
Fraser, his two brothers and their mother were there daily, the
three boys playing hockey, the mother teaching figure skating.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser's parents divorced when he was young, and both remarried.
Hockey remained a constant in his life. He played in the juniors
for the Victoria (British Columbia) Cougars at a time when the
Western Hockey League was notorious for physical play and brawls.
Often, there were fights not only during the games but before them,
during pre-game skates. Pre-game fights became so commonplace in
the WHL that a few years ago the league mandated that teams warm up
at separate times.
</P>
<P>
   ``My intensity probably comes from my days in junior hockey,''
Fraser said. ``I had a coach, Patty Ginnell, who was a very
intimidating man. He was known for being real tough and disciplined
with the players but also putting a lot of guys in the NHL. We were
all a bunch of prairie boys, big strong kids. You had to play with
an edge. You had to be rugged and durable, especially traveling on
those 32-hour bus rides. To Flin-Flon. Lots of snow, lots of miles
on the road. For a 16-year-old kid starting out, it was a great
learning experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Fraser fought, yes, piling up as many as 256 penalty minutes in
his final season of juniors in 1977-78. But he wasn't devoid of a
scoring touch, collecting 125 goals and 149 assists for 274 points
in his final three years at Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver drafted him in the second round, and Fraser went on to
play 12 seasons with the Canucks, Chicago and Minnesota. He was not
quite the ``plumber'' some have made him out to be. Not everybody
scores 193 NHL goals and has five 20-goal seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But overshadowing the scoring was Fraser's blue-collar work _
the collisions in the corners, the brawls, the shot-blocking, the
leadership in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who ever saw him play knows there's nothing he can ask
a player to do that he didn't do himself,'' Vancouver general
manager Brian Burke said. ``Because he was a marginal player from a
skill perspective, he really worked hard on the intellectual side
of the game. He was a smart player, and historically the marginal
players in this league who could think the game have made some of
the best coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Fraser's fighting ability was not marginal. Asked if he ever
took a beating, he responds, ``No.'' He compiled 1,304 penalty
minutes in 704 games. He had plenty of opponents. Former
Atlanta/Calgary Flame Willi Plett remembers the two squaring off
``at least 10 times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I still have some lumps from him,'' Plett said. ``One
year in Calgary, I had 38 goals, and I swear his only
responsibility when we played was to try to neutralize me.''
</P>
<P>
   With body checks?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm talking fights,'' Plett said. ``There was one time I
might've hurt him, but there were definitely times he hurt me. One
time, I don't even know if the puck had dropped yet, and he dropped
his gloves and hammered me.''
</P>
<P>
   Fraser said, ``When I was in the juniors I was a scorer. But in
Vancouver I was put into a role of a more physical player. I
focused on what I could bring to the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Fraser claims the most punishment he ever took in a fight came
in juniors from Dave Hoyda. ``I thought, `Holy mackerel, I've been
hit by a truck. My eye was closed shut and my head was spinning.
Afterward, I ran into Hoyda as I was leaving. He had 14 stitches
above his eye. So I gave him something to remember, but I could
barely see him.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Fraser's most lopsided brawls came in the playoffs one
year when his Blackhawks were facing Minnesota. As Burke recalls,
``Bobby Smith made a poor business decision to challenge Curt
Fraser to a fight. It wasn't a lucid moment for Bobby Smith. He
needed 30 facial stitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's brief recollection: ``All I will say about that is Curt
Fraser was a better fighter than I was, and he proved it that
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Fraser never thought of himself as a coach until somebody
offered a job. He retired in 1990 because his shoulders and his
knees couldn't take any more pounding. Burke, then the Canucks'
assistant GM, offered him a job as assistant coach with the team's
IHL affiliate in Milwaukee. Fraser accepted and said, ``I loved it
from Day 1. I knew I wanted to be a head coach some day.''
</P>
<P>
   He eventually took over as head coach, going 89-47-27 in two
seasons. That was followed by a season as an assistant in Syracuse
(AHL), then four in Orlando, where Fraser's teams went 192-111-25
and advanced to the finals twice.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through last season, Waddell told Fraser that he was
looking to hire somebody with NHL coaching experience for the
Thrashers. Fraser's response: ``I told him, `That's fine. But if we
win the (IHL's) Turner Cup, I deserve a shot.''' Fraser was
half-joking. But within two days of the Solar Bears losing in seven
games in the finals, Waddell called to request an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Weisbrod, meanwhile, filled in Waddell on the new Fraser, the
one who communicated with players and shuffled nameplates around in
the locker room to create the right chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trademark of Curt's teams (was) resilience,'' Weisbrod
said. ``That made him a perfect fit for an expansion team, because
there's going to be some tough days, but his players will not lay
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is a long way from Victoria. But Fraser, while saying he
has changed for the better, is not going to stray too far from what
got him here. Discipline comes in all forms. It doesn't have to
arrive like a harpoon or a stick through a wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to just expect things before,'' Fraser said. ``I just
thought the players would do what I did. I changed to more of a
commander, a captain. I'm still steering the ship. But I make sure
now everybody is on board and rowing in the same direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
