<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5875 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-PREVIEW-COMISH26-     09-25 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PREVIEW-COMISH26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Ownership, arena will be without rival'
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ NHL commissioner Gary Bettman will attend the
Thrashers' opener Saturday in the new Philips Arena. Staff writer
Jeff Schultz interviewed Bettman about Atlanta and the league.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I assume you didn't grow up an Atlanta Flames fan. But what
are your feelings about the league returning to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm very excited about it, for a variety of reasons. First,
the Flames did quite well and had a great following. The reasons
the club moved were unrelated to the support it received in the
market. Second, as good a town as Atlanta was, it's an even better
town now, and it's grown. Finally, the ownership and the new arena,
we think, will be without rival.
</P>
<P>
   Q: To what extent does bringing in a multimedia conglomerate
like Time Warner and Ted Turner help the league.
</P>
<P>
   A: That tends to be overstated. But they'll do a great job
running the franchise, and a strong franchise makes the league
stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Atlanta no longer is alone among NHL franchises in the
Southeast, but Tampa Bay and Carolina are having severe financial
problems. Does this signal any problems to you.
</P>
<P>
   A: You have to look at specific franchises. You can't generalize
and say, `The South.' Tampa Bay is not experiencing what I would
call problems. The franchise had an ownership situation (with
Japanese owners) from the outset that finally got resolved. You
can't have absentee ownership. Bill Davidson is at the helm now,
and I view that as a positive. Carolina again is a unique situation
because of the relocation (from Hartford) and having to play home
games (in Greensboro) 100 miles from their (base in Raleigh).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Carolina lost $55 million in its first two seasons. But even
with a new arena in Raleigh this season, tickets sales reportedly
are slow. Do you have any lingering concerns about the market.
</P>
<P>
   A: No. That franchise will be fine. They've had to operate under
difficult circumstances. That's a great market with good ownership
and a good building.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The league has seen unparalleled growth in recent years, but
there are several franchises struggling financially. What is your
viewpoint on the strength of the league.
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't think the league has ever been stronger. Ownership
has never been stronger. Our footprint has never been stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any lingering feelings about the fact your
centerpiece event, the Stanley Cup Finals, ended on a disputed
goal.
</P>
<P>
   A: It didn't end on a disputed goal. It ended on a perfectly
fine goal. There are plenty of sports events that are decided on
the wrong call. The Dallas-Buffalo game ended on the right call.
The fact is some people at the time didn't understand that it was
the right call. It's a nonissue.
</P>
<P>
   Q: To what extent does Wayne Gretzky's retirement affect the
league, from a visibility standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't think anybody can overstate Wayne's importance to the
league as a whole. He's indicated his intentions to stay close to
the game, remain visible and bring attention to the game.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The six Canadian franchises continue to struggle financially
because of Canadian tax laws and the country's devalued dollar.
What is the outlook for the franchises.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's an important priority for us to keep the six Canadian
franchises in Canada and keep them not only viable but successful.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some have projected that only the teams in the three major
markets, Montreal, Toronto and Vancouver, will survive, while
Calgary, Edmonton and Ottawa will move. Do you agree.
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't believe that. As I said, I'm committed to finding a
way to maintain six franchises in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How strong are your desires to place franchises in Portland
and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   A: At some point, they might represent an opportunity in the
right circumstances. But there are no further plans for expansion
on the horizon. I'm of interest in those cities, but there's
nothing we can do right now.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You have expressed concerns about the rate of increasing
salaries in the NHL. But the collective bargaining agreement with
the NHL Players Association runs through 2004. So, is there really
anything you can do about it.
</P>
<P>
   A: What I've said is that for the last couple of years, salaries
are increasing at a faster rate than revenues. If that continues,
it's a concern. But I also believe economics can be pendulumlike
and swing back in the other direction. Revenues can start to
increase faster than salaries. If salaries have to slow down,
that's something the individual teams have to address.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If you had to do it over again, would you have negotiated the
collective bargaining agreement differently.
</P>
<P>
   A: That's not a question anybody can answer. When it gets to be
time to negotiate the next CBA, we'll take stock of the total
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The NHL's five-year, $600 million contract with ABC and ESPN
is a record deal for the league, but there are still a limited
number of games on network television. Is that satisfactory for the
league's visibility.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's only that way in the first year. ABC had some scheduling
issues in the first year. The number of broadcasts will grow over
time. When we made the deal, ABC already had some contractual
agreements in place.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where do things stand on the league's participation in the
2002 Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   A: We're waiting to hear from the Players Association in terms
of whether they're prepared to go. They've proposed a series of
things, a number of which are unrelated to the Olympics themselves,
and some might construe that as an attempt to renegotiate the CBA.
If they want things unrelated to the Olympics, then I have to
question their desire to go.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the issues.
</P>
<P>
   A: I'd rather not get into it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there a ``drop-dead'' date.
</P>
<P>
   A: That's something the International Ice Hockey Federation has
to establish. I can live with more time, but it's up to them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Given the pre-medal eliminations of the United States and
Canada in Nagano and the dorm trashings by some U.S. players, would
you consider the experiment a failure from both a public-relations
and a marketing standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   A: If you believe that the only way we could be successful was
for the U.S. to play Canada in the gold-medal game, then your
question makes sense. But this was probably the most-viewed,
most-competitive hockey tournament in the world. It didn't hinge on
the success of the U.S. or Canadian teams.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
