<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5876 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-PREVIEW-FERRALL26     09-25 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PREVIEW-FERRALL26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ferrall's amusing, irreverent style to cover Thrashers
play-by-play
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Thrashers broke with convention in picking their
radio voice and the station on which he will be heard.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Ferrall, the outspoken former nationally syndicated
sports-talk-show host, had not done play-by-play work on an NHL
game until he was hired by the Thrashers. And if his two exhibition
broadcasts are any indication, Ferrall's irreverent,
push-the-envelope style will not be corralled by the demands of his
new job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to be entertaining. I want to make it exciting to
listen to,'' said Ferrall, who during his game calls has offered
references to sissies, enemas, urine, major-league baseball players
and the fictional character in Al Pacino's movie ``Scarface.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is lining up to listen to hockey broadcasters,'' he
said. ``No one's watching on television. It's time to try something
different to make it more popular to listen to. I can't worry about
what some guys who've called hockey for 20 years think.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferrall concedes, however, that his biggest challenge will be
identifying the players for listeners, many of whom are as
unfamiliar with the Thrashers as they are the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that's what they're pounding into me,'' Ferrall said.
``I need to do a better job of saying who has the puck and whose
team he's on. And I'm going to work hard to get better at that,
because I don't want to let this franchise down.''
</P>
<P>
   After choosing Ferrall, the team then pulled another surprise by
selecting ``SportsTalk 790 The Zone,'' WQXI (790-AM,) as its
flagship station, and adding WLKQ (102.3) as the FM partner.
</P>
<P>
   While the Ferrall decision got the team a recognizable name, the
latter generated the most crucial question in local radio: Will
people be able to hear the games at night?
</P>
<P>
   To offset The Zone's weak signal after dark, Thrashers director
of radio operations Dan Kamal put together a network of affiliates
that he hopes will provide adequate coverage in the eight-county
metro Atlanta area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very good about it,'' said Kamal, who also plays the
straight man as Ferrall's partner on the game broadcasts. ``I think
we've saturated the metro area to the best of our ability. We did a
lot of driving around, and there may be small pockets where there's
a problem, and people might have to work to pick up the games by
either getting a better radio or re-positioning their radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in those few areas where there's not a clean signal, all
we can do is apologize and promise we'll keep working to get 100
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers will be responsible for the game broadcast, but
the Zone chose John Kincade as the director of the station's hockey
operations, and Kincade will host the half-hour pre-game and
post-game shows.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
