<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5877 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-PREVIEW-FIGHTS26-     09-25 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PREVIEW-FIGHTS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers believe altercations will always be part of hockey
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Skates. Sticks. Gloves. Hockey. To many hockey
players, them's fightin' words. Hey, fights happen.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, fighting is an integral part of the game, as essential
as the brushback pitch in baseball, the crack-back block in
football, buying a vowel on ``Wheel of Fortune.'' Fighting always
has been, ever since the NHL's inaugural season of 1917-18. And it
always will be. At least if guys like Denny Lambert have any say
so. And they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got the right guy,'' Lambert said, his smile a 1,000-watt
spotlight warming to the topic: the role, and status, of fighting
in today's NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're never going to eliminate fighting, I don't care what
you say,'' said Lambert, a Thrashers left winger. ``If you go out
there and play a 60-minute game, and somebody whacks you over the
elbow with their stick, you're going to walk away? No. You're going
to protect yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not alone. ``Fights do happen. It'll always be part of the
game,'' said Thrashers forward Matt Johnson, nicknamed ``Moose''
not only for his size (6 feet 5, 235 pounds) but also his
propensity for _ hockey term here _ mucking it up in the corner.
``Toughness will never be out of the game. There will always be
tough guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fast game. There's sticks in your hands. Hockey's a
very emotional game, a lot of adrenaline flowing. Fights do break
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Not nearly as often as they once did. Not in the early- or
mid-'70s, in the heyday mayhem of the Broad Street Bullies, the
Philadelphia Flyers who terrorized the NHL and won two Stanley
Cups. Not nearly as often as the 1987-88 season, when a NHL record
of 1.07 fights per game broke out on average.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1996-97 season, fighting in the NHL had declined 27
percent, another 20 percent last season. Those figures are partly
because of instigator rules implemented by the league in 1992 and
the emphasis on a more skilled, skating style of play. But fighting
is not going away. Not only because it's an intrinsic part of the
game _ indeed, hockey is the only sport, besides boxing, that
allows fighting _ but because of its fan appeal and, more
important, the role it actually plays as a deterrent to dirty play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always going to need guys to protect people,'' said
Johnson. ``When you're with the Rangers, you never want Wayne
Gretzky to get hit. ... I think it makes a team feel more
comfortable going into a game knowing they're not going to be taken
advantage of. That somebody will let the skill guys play.''
</P>
<P>
   When Gretzky played for the Edmonton Oilers, dave Semenko played
the role of Lord Protector of the Great One. He was Gretzky's
bodyguard, a vital role on any team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at Anaheim,'' said Lambert, ``they go out (before
last season) and sign two guys (Stu ``The Grim Reaper'' Grimson and
Jim McKenzie) to protect the 50-goal man, (Paul) Kariya.'' As well
as Teemu Selanne. And opposing teams know they'd best leave Kariya
and Selanne alone, or else answer to ``The Grim Reaper'' or a real,
live hockey McKenzie Brother.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey, of course, has always been reluctant to outlaw fighting.
It's not only too imbedded in the game's psyche, but also very
popular with many fans while serving a practical, protective-shield
purpose. ``The fans seem to enjoy it,'' Johnson said, smiling.
``When you look at a fight, it's like a goal being scored.
Everybody's on their feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially when one guy's knocked off his skates. But the
widespread, bench-emptying, everybody-into-the-ring donnybrooks of
the past are largely gone. ``The days of the big brawl that all the
people could remember about hockey are gone,'' said Ray Ferraro, a
Thrashers veteran center. ``That stuff doesn't have any place
(anymore).
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to be a sideshow,'' he said. ``We're not
wrestling. Not that wrestling's a sideshow, but it's
entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Hockey fights are, too, for many fans. And a means of employment
for guys like Patrick Cote of Nashville, Tenn., who led the NHL in
fighting last season _ a goal he set once he took the lead ``... as
long as my hands hold up.'' But then, fighting's been in Cote's
blood ever since his youth hockey days.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my friends back home (Lasalle, Quebec) fight on the street
and all they get is arrested,'' Cote told The Hockey News last
March. ``I fight on the ice and look at the money I make.'' His
salary last season: $375,000.
</P>
<P>
   It's players like Cote, though, who make the ``Greenpeace
pukes'' cringe. That's the euphemism hockey types use for those
opposed to fighting, who would clean up the game, and the rink, by
abolishing fighting. That's highly unlikely. NHL President Gary
Bettman has not publicly taken a pro or con stand on fighting; he
knows better. Indeed, when Brian Burke, a former NHL player and now
general manager of the Vancouver Canucks, was the league's senior
vice-president last season, he said he'd quit if fighting was ever
abolished, or warranted an automatic ejection.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, fighting is on the decline. Last season's average of
1.2 fighting penalties per game was the NHL's lowest in more than
20 years. While players still occasionally rearrange the facial
furniture, the game is played differently. Especially when two
referees are calling the action, like they will be for all games in
the 2000-2001 season. Each team will play 50 games with two
referees this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the games are anywhere near as physical as they
used to be,'' Ferraro said. ``The skill level is much better today.
It's deeper now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the one-dimensional guys _ I guess you call it goon _
you're seeing less and less, where he plays one minute and gets in
a fight,'' Lambert said. ``You're getting bigger, stronger guys who
can play eight, 10 minutes a game and can also play. Any time you
get a half-decent player who's also tough, coaches are very happy.
That's a bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a bonus Curt Fraser can appreciate. The Thrashers coach
appreciates, and values, toughness. Not only in Lambert and
Johnson, but also guys like Chris Tamer, Steve Staios and Kelly
Buchberger.
</P>
<P>
   In a 12-year NHL playing career, Fraser scored 193 goals and had
1,306 penalty minutes. And had numerous fights, especially with
Willi Plett, the 1977 Rookie of the Year with the Atlanta Flames.
It was '82, though, when the Flames had moved to Calgary, that
Fraser set the tone for a Vancouver-Calgary playoff series by
one-punching, and flooring, Plett just eight seconds into the
series opener. That set the tone for the series; the Canucks swept
Calgary and reached the Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
