<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5878 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-PREVIEW-FLAMES26-     09-25 1533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PREVIEW-FLAMES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Players from Atlanta's first NHL team are still popular
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They are, in every sense, old Flames. Most are in
their 40s now, some pushing 50. All once skated for the first NHL
franchise in the Deep South. And now, as hockey arrives for the
second time, as the Thrashers prepare to face off in Philips Arena,
it's the old Flames who have kept this town's hockey heartstrings
taut for nearly two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thrill of my life,'' Bernie ``Boom Boom''
Geoffrion says about the Thrashers and hockey's NHL rebirth in
Atlanta. Boom Boom should know. A Hockey Hall of Famer with the
Montreal Canadiens, Geoffrion was the Flames' first coach and one
of the Thrashers' most eloquent advocates in their pursuit of an
expansion franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, they deserve to have another chance,'' said
Geoffrion, 68, who still lives in Marietta, 24 years after
resigning as the Flames' coach midway through their third season.
``We were drawing more than the Hawks, more than the Braves. Like I
told (NHL President) Gary Bettman last year, `Mr. president, if
there's a city that deserves a second chance, it's Atlanta. We can
prove we can play the game, and we can draw.' Especially now, with
the man, Ted Turner, and the new arena.''
</P>
<P>
   Play the game and draw _ two things the Flames did well, too,
from the first official faceoff in Atlanta on Saturday, Oct. 14,
1972. Opening night in the old Omni, then new and decked out like a
night at the opera house. ``It looked like you were going to a
ball,'' Geoffrion said. ``Every game was like that. Every game.''
</P>
<P>
   Men in suits. Women in long dresses, bejeweled if somewhat
bewildered by what unfolded on the ice below.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was strange in the beginning but really fun growing with
the fans here,'' said Randy Manery, a defenseman that first season.
``I guess it was understanding their level of passion for their
understanding of the game. Not everybody in Atlanta was totally
naive, but ...''
</P>
<P>
   Like that opening night audience, for the Flames-Sabres
inaugural. ``They took a couple of early long shots, basically
dumping (the puck) in, that happened to go on net,'' Manery
recalled. The reaction? Wild applause. ``The fans thought it was
great. That sort of thing was amusing, but energizing.''
</P>
<P>
   The players scratched their heads _ helmets weren't mandatory
back then _ but quickly warmed to a nascent hockey crowd. Even Tim
Ecclestone, who'd grown up near Toronto and played the first three
seasons with the spectacularly successful expansion St. Louis Blues
before going to his hometown Maple Leafs and then coming to Atlanta
in the Flames' third season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toronto was like the history of the game,'' said Ecclestone, a
forward who still lives in Atlanta and owns TJ's Sports Bar and
Grill in Alpharetta. ``Like Montreal. Then I got traded down here
and ...''
</P>
<P>
   And it was different. In the old Maple Leaf Gardens, there was
no guy standing and waving a Rebel flag, as there was at the Omni.
And Canadian hockey fans not only appreciated hockey fights, they
knew authenticity when they saw it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had wrestling down here,'' Ecclestone said. ``But some
people would ask you, `Those hockey fights, they're fake, right?'
I'd say, `Listen, buddy, if they were fake, I'd have been in a lot
more of 'em.' But people here picked it up pretty quickly. They
were pretty knowledgeable by the mid-'70s.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a social event the first few years,'' said Eric Vail, a
left wing who was nicknamed ``Big Train'' and won the Calder Trophy
as the NHL's Rookie of the Year in 1975. ``The people were all
dressed up. They would cheer icing. But what they did know to cheer
was whether the Flames won the fight or not.''
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-'70s, the Flames had established themselves as one of
the better teams in the league and perhaps the best expansion team
in NHL history. After entering the league with the New York
Islanders, the Flames made the playoffs in their second season.
They would do so six times in their eight seasons in Atlanta,
although they never advanced beyond the first round. In all eight
seasons, they easily outdrew the Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kinda scared at first,'' Geoffrion said, ``because you
were down South. Our (home) games were on Friday. You had to fight
high school football. But we con-quer dem. We outdrew high school
football. The Hawks and Braves were terrible. I told (general
manager) Cliff Fletcher, `If we keep winning our share of games,
we're gonna draw.'''
</P>
<P>
   They did, and they did. The Flames immediately had good
goaltending in Dan Bouchard and Phil Myre. Bouchard was the only
man to play all eight seasons in Atlanta, and now he coaches the
Life University hockey team, which he founded. Center Tom Lysiak
played 13 years with Atlanta and Chicago and now lives with his
family on a farm in Newton County, where he owns a landscaping
business. Forward Curt Bennett became the highest-scoring
American-born player in the NHL and still lives in Atlanta. Willi
Plett was the 1977 Rookie of the Year and a fan-favorite fighter
extraordinaire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to compete, to help the team win,'' said Plett,
the right wing on a line with Vail and Lysiak that became one of
the league's most potent. ``If it meant getting in a few fights and
being physical, I did it. I took it personal. When my name gets
mentioned (now), people go, `Yeah, goon. Enforcer.' But I think I
averaged more goals a season than Train (Vail) did.''
</P>
<P>
   Plett scored 222 career goals. He could play and fight, much
like a contemporary _ and frequent opponent _ of that era: Curt
Fraser, the Thrashers' coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had lots of fights,'' said Plett, who regularly fought Behn
Wilson of the Flyers, the Islanders' Clark Gillies and Gary Howatt
and Philadelphia's Paul Holmgren. But Fraser had a special place on
Plett's fight card. One recent night at Willi's Sports Grill,
Plett's restaurant and golf complex in Woodstock, he showed a tape
of his 10 best hockey fights. Three were against Fraser.
</P>
<P>
   That rivalry escalated once the Flames moved to Calgary after
the 1979-80 season and especially after Plett was traded to
Minnesota. By then, Fraser was with the Chicago Blackhawks. ``He
was tough, really tough,'' Plett said. ``Toughness is all mental.
You've got to have strength but you've got to know when to stir it
up. And he did. I respected him for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Plett never got to play for the popular Geoffrion, whose name
brought instant credibility to a foreign hockey land, even if he
sometimes spoke in tongues. ``We always said, `We've got a coach
who speaks two languages _ broken English and broken French,'''
said Vail, still in Atlanta and still close friends with Ecclestone
and Plett. ``We'd always ask the French Canadians, `What did he
say?' They'd say, `I don't know.' So we knew he was bilingual.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1979, Geoffrion was long gone, having quit out of frustration
in early '75. Fred Creighton succeeded him and the Flames were very
successful on the ice and fairly successful at the gate but, like
their jerseys, in the red financially. The late '70s was hardly a
boom time in real estate, where Flames owner Tom Cousins had made
his first fortune. When some of his partners sold out, Cousins was
forced to sell the team after the 1979-80 season to Canadian Nelson
Skalbania. He moved the Flames to hockey-hungry Calgary, where the
franchise won the Stanley Cup in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the Canadian dollar plummeting, Calgary could lose the
Flames. Atlanta, meanwhile, is basking in the return of NHL hockey.
The old Flames are carrying a torch for the Thrashers, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be their biggest fan,'' Vail said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a big fan of Don Waddell,'' Ecclestone said. ``I think
he's done a wonderful job of putting a new team together, and
they'll be more competitive than people think. They've got finesse,
toughness and goaltending. If his goaltending is as good as I think
it is, well, goaltending is like pitching (in baseball).
Goaltending keeps you in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing couldn't be better,'' Plett said. ``If it had
happened 10 years ago, it might've been too soon. Atlanta has just
exploded after the Olympics. People have money. And they couldn't
have picked a better coach. The talent pool now in the NHL is low.
If you score 20 goals, you're a goal-scorer. The majority of Curt's
players are going to be grinders. And he can relate to that, and
appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they'll have a good team,'' Geoffrion said. ``I
honestly think they'll do as well as the Flame did the first year.
We won 25 games. They drafted young guys and veterans; I like that.
You just put them together and that's how you put together a team.
And I honestly believe, with Mr. Turner, they won't have any
problems whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   So drop the puck Saturday _ opening night at Philips Arena. The
New Jersey Devils and the Thrashers, Boom Boom's new favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider that my team'' Geoffrion said. ``I love the game so
much. All of a sudden, the NHL is coming back to Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
