<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5880 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-THRASHERS-GOALIE2     09-25 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS-GOALIE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Competitive outlook hangs on goaltending
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Parker MacDonald said it. Right after another lopsided
defeat in the Los Angeles Kings' inglorious history, the coach
pleaded to anybody in earshot, ``The guy between the pipes killed
us.''
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald's hockeyspeak didn't specify which guy he was talking
about _ his goalie or the opposition's. But both seemed to have a
major impact. After 42 games in 1981-82, MacDonald's team had only
13 wins, and he lost his job. Some guy between the pipes killed
him.
</P>
<P>
   When the Thrashers make their regular-season debut against the
New Jersey Devils on Saturday at Philips Arena, the first-year team
will be no different from 27 others in at least one respect:
Goaltending will make or break them.
</P>
<P>
   Forechecking schemes and power plays and unidentified flying
elbows won't make a big difference if Damian Rhodes and Norm
Maracle are letting the puck fly over the glove hand, past the
blocker or through the five-hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expansion teams that have been successful right off the
bat were so because of their goaltending,'' said Florida Panthers
President Bill Torrey, architect of the New York Islanders in 1972
and the Panthers in 1993. ``We had problems in the beginning in New
York, but then we got Chico Resch. It takes a while to build four
good lines. But one goalie makes a difference right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Torrey knows the history all too well. His first-year Panthers
were 33-34-17 in 1993-94 and missed the playoffs by one point.
Florida even made the finals as third-year toddlers. The reason:
goalie John Vanbiesbrouck.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the Islanders posted the third-worst record in
expansion history, 12-60-6. Gerry Desjardins had a miserable
goals-against average of 4.68. The worst expansion record was
Washington's 8-67-5 in 1974-75, when starting goalie Ron Low's GAA
was 5.45.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New York'' Torrey said,``I knew we would sell tickets for a
while, so I could take time in developing the team through the
draft. But in Florida, we had to sell the team and be competitive
right away. That's why it was more important to get an established
goalie and get some older players to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Relaxed rules of the expansion draft allowed the Thrashers to
get Rhodes in a pre-draft trade with Ottawa, which rotated Rhodes
and Ron Tugnutt last season. His career goals-against average of
2.58, including 2.34 and 2.44 the past two seasons, bodes well for
the Thrashers. The team in front of him probably won't match the
talent level of the Senators. But when Rhodes joined them from
Toronto midway through their fourth season in 1996, the Senators
were a mess, having won only 20 percent of their games in 3 1/2
years.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about being the key to the success of a first-year team,
Rhodes said, ``When I was in Ottawa, it was a similar situation. I
really just stayed focused on my game and let the other things fall
into place. . . . It's the same as everything else in life. You try
to think about the good times more than the bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The same day Rhodes arrived in a trade, coach Dave Allison was
fired and replaced by Jacques Martin, the team's third coach in two
months. Rhodes went only 10-22-4 the rest of the season, but his
goals-against average (2.77) was almost the same as it was in
Toronto (2.79).
</P>
<P>
   The goaltending of Rhodes and Maracle has been the Thrashers'
strength in training camp and the preseason. It will have to be the
strength during the regular season because this roster was not
built to win 8-7 games, even though general manager Don Waddell and
coach Curt Fraser have preached an aggressive, attacking style from
the outset.
</P>
<P>
   Maracle, an expansion-draft pick from Detroit and Rhodes'
24-year-old heir apparent, figures to play in about 30 of the 82
games. He probably had the strongest camp of anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started playing goalie when I was 7, and I didn't like it,''
Maracle said. ``My team had a scrimmage, and I was just in there
fooling around, and the next thing I know the coach sits me down
and says, `You're going to be our goalie.' I started crying. I
wanted to score goals like Wayne Gretzky. But after a while, I grew
to like it. I like the pressure of being the last guy on the
line.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense in front of Rhodes and Maracle should be fairly
solid, led by veterans Darryl Shannon and Gord Murphy. The offense?
``I'm excited about the direction we're headed,'' Waddell said. ``I
want to be careful because this is just the preseason, but our
skill level is better than I thought it would be in June. And our
goaltending has been outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell refuses to set the bar at 28 wins, Nashville, Tenn.'s
total last season, even though he knows others will draw the
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe some will say that's our goal,'' he said. ``Or maybe
that's low.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida's near-.500 mark?
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a phenomenal first year,'' Waddell said. ``When they
came in, goaltending was the strength of that (expansion) draft.
Vanbiesbrouck was the strength of that team. But that's one area
we're very pleased with right now.''
</P>
<P>
   A guy between the pipes can kill you. But good goaltending makes
an average team competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
