<HEADER>
A5881 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-TURNERSOUTH26-COX     09-25 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-TURNERSOUTH26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New network scrambles to get cable connection
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As the Thrashers prepare to take the ice for their
first regular-season NHL game, the heat is on local cable operators
to find room for Turner South.
</P>
<P>
   With 46 games on the new regional cable network, if Turner South
is unable to muscle its way onto such systems as MediaOne, the
Thrashers first season on television will be almost as spotty as
the NHL's four-game, regular-season package on ABC, its new network
partner.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, with 15 games on WUPA in Atlanta, the Thrashers won't
be that invisible on ``free TV,'' but for a first-year team trying
to carve its niche in a marketplace with three other established
pro teams, 15 games won't cut it.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers and Turner South are confident that most of the
cable customers in the metro area will be able to see the first
telecast Saturday against New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Fox Sports Net South) lawsuit did cloud the issue and
made conversations with cable operators more difficult,'' Turner
South President Bill Burke said about its rival's failed attempt to
prevent the network from having a sports component. ``But we're
coming along. Advertisers love the concept of the whole network,
and while the Thrashers are new and a bit more unproven than the
other teams, they've been very well received in the advertising
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt McConnell will be the television voice of the Thrashers,
with former NHL goalie Darren Eliot the analyst. McConnell, a
graduate of Michigan State, previously worked for the Anaheim
Mighty Ducks and the Penguins. Eliot, a graduate of Cornell, also
worked Mighty Ducks games. He played with the Kings, Red Wings and
Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   Coordinating producer Bill Kunz is taking the approach that the
game will be as new to the viewers as the uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get people to know the players,'' Kunz said.
``The second dimension is education. There's a fine line you can
walk between bringing people into the game and not alienating the
people who know the game.''
</P>
<P>
   After watching Fox try everything from a glowing puck to
animated robots in a futile effort to expand hockey's relatively
small audience, ABC decided to all but write off the regular
season. The network made that decision even though its new
five-year, $600 million contract is 400 percent over the $31
million Fox averaged annually for NHL rights over the past five
seasons. After the All-Star Game on Feb. 6, ABC will only devote
four afternoons to the regular season _ March 18 and 26, and April
1 and 9.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
