</P>
<P>
   A: That certainly happens. Still, there are cases in North
America. Parents sometimes write me and say, ``My child is now 12
years old. I wish I knew about you when he was 2 or 3. He said he
was an airline pilot, and we told him to stop telling lies and now
he doesn't remember anything.'' That's a fairly common opening. We
found that 40 percent of people even in India suppress their
children. It's not that they disbelieve them. It's that they have
various ideas, one that it's harmful to remember a previous life.
Sometimes, they object to the content of what the child is saying.
The child might show snobbishness. He'll say, ``I was, am, Brahmin
and won't eat your polluted food. I have to have food cooked by a
Brahmin.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Q: Were many of your subjects haunted by their memories?
</P>
<P>
   A: Some are tormented, struggling with torn loyalties between
two families. They often want to go back to the other family, and
reject their parents. Very often the child is placated by meeting
the previous personality's family. That's especially true in the
case of girls who remember having left behind very young children.
They often ask: Who's feeding my children?
</P>
<P>
   Q: Which aspects of past-life memory are uniform across
cultures?
</P>
<P>
   A: A very young age of speaking. Forgetting at ages between 5
and 8. High incidence of violent death in the life remembered. And
the frequent mention of the mode of death in the previous life.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What ratio of cases don't pass muster compared to those that
you consider authentic?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are very few cases where one would favor an explanation
of fraud or self-deception, though there are some. Occasionally, a
parent becomes attached, even intoxicated, by the publicity, so
they inflate the case a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What troubles you most about your work?
</P>
<P>
   A: If I were coaching a skeptic I would emphasize the difficulty
in reaching the cases before the families concerned have met. They
can sometimes enthusiastically credit the child with more correct
statements than the child actually may have made. That's a
weakness. But we've done a comparison of a small number of cases,
maybe 25, in which someone had made a written record of what the
child had said before the families had met. We compared them to
cases where the written record had been made after the families had
met. Turned out there were no differences. There were the same
number of statements _ and correct statements _ in each group.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If you had a dinner party, and could invite anyone, alive or
dead, who would make the guest list?
</P>
<P>
   A: St. Francis of Assisi, William Harvey, who discovered the
circulation of the blood. Michael Faraday. Johannes Brahms. And
Abraham Lincoln. I'd like to meet Dr. Johnson but I think he'd be a
bore as a dinner companion.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Humans are said to use just a small percentage of our brains.
Couldn't memories of past lives be attributed to ESP? Would ESP be
easier for Americans to accept than reincarnation?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, it would be. Trouble with ESP, it doesn't explain the
cases where relevant birthmarks and birth defects are present.
These birthmarks that we (find) are not like other birthmarks.
Ordinary birthmarks that everybody has are areas of increased
pigmentation. They are usually flat. The birthmarks that are of
particular interest to us in these cases may have some increased
pigmentation but they're usually scar-like, elevated or depressed,
and much larger than the average, ordinary birthmark.
</P>
<P>
   Q: These birthmarks correspond to the wounds on the previous
personality?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. We've been able to find in more than 40 cases
verification of the location of the wounds from post-mortem
reports.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If reincarnation were widely accepted, how would it change
the world?
</P>
<P>
   A: It would lessen guilt on the part of parents. They wouldn't
have as much of a burden that, whatever goes wrong with a child is
all their fault, either through genes or mishandling during the
child's infancy. People themselves would have to take more
responsibility for their own destinies. ... I don't expect any
great moral transformation. On my first trip to India I met a
respected Indian monk, a swami. I told him I had come out to see
what evidence there was in India for reincarnation. He remained
silent for a long, long time. Then he said, ``We here in India
regard it as a fact that people are reborn, but, you see, it
doesn't make a difference because we have just as many rogues and
villains in India as you have in the West.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 1454EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0159 </DOCNO>
