<HEADER>
A5886 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-BALLPARK-2TAKES-N     09-25 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BALLPARK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NATIVE DETROITER'S FAREWELL TO TIGER STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Calif., Ill., Wis., Mass.)  (mk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As it became increasingly clear that Detroit's historic baseball
stadium might be abandoned, a grass-roots group called the Tiger
Stadium Fan Club resisted. In 1988 and again in 1990, fans
surrounded the ballpark and linked hands to hug the big, gray
structure at the corner of Michigan and Trumbull on the frayed
fringe of downtown. These embraces, lasting about 15 minutes,
generated sympathetic publicity and helped delay the inevitable.
Now, the days of warm hugs and lingering looks have grown short.
Autumn is here and, Monday afternoon, the Tigers will play their
final game on their home ground of more than a century. Next
spring, they open a new stadium, Comerica Park, about a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   Named for a bank, Comerica is one of many spiffy sports
facilities rising across the continent. Also to be replaced next
season are the former Candlestick Park in San Francisco and the
Astrodome in Houston. County Stadium in Milwaukee has one year
left. But Detroit's park is older and its closing generates the
most sentiment. On the site of a hay market, it opened as Bennett
Park in 1896, the year Henry Ford drove his first horseless
carriage on nearby streets. The current configuration of
grandstands and diamond was set in 1912 and renamed Navin Field.
</P>
<P>
   To some, Tiger Stadium feels like an ancestral homestead. My
oldest son, Marc, and I, born in Detroit 30 years apart, saw our
first major league games at Tiger Stadium. My dad and his brothers
took their sons there every Father's Day in the 1950s and 1960s and
reminisced then about coming there, young and single, in the 1940s.
Despite living on the East Coast for almost a decade, I have
visited Tiger Stadium at least once each year, along with other
baseball stadiums along the vacation trail. This summer, because my
son is seeking a college, we journeyed from coast to coast, from
campus to campus, and from ballpark to ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Such serendipity! The Bay Area of California gave us the green
lawns of Palo Alto and Berkeley and the playing fields of the
Giants and the Athletics. The Midwest meant the bricks and ivy of
both Wrigley Field and the University of Chicago, with visits to
Northwestern and Comiskey Park, plus a 100-mile side trip to
Milwaukee. Then came stops at the University of Michigan, Wayne
State University and, best of all, two nights at Tiger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   There sat Ernie Harwell, 80 years old, a broadcaster there since
1960, when it was still called Briggs Stadium. Harwell began his
career in the 1940s, with the Brooklyn Dodgers at Ebbets Field and
baseball's New York Giants at the Polo Grounds. He has perspective
on baseball and time and change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of nostalgia floating around. Everybody is
bringing back their memories,'' Harwell said. ``We've had a lot of
people from all over the country come in. I've had people tell me,
`I'm from West Virginia' or `I'm from Arkansas' or `I'm from
Georgia' or `I'm from Oklahoma' and `I wanted to see the ballpark
for the last time.'''
</P>
<P>
   Harwell will miss the closeness of Tiger Stadium's stands,
``that intimate feeling, like in Ebbets Field, where you could
reach down and touch the players.'' But he said Detroit's old park
lacks amenities for fans and revenue-generating luxury boxes for
ownership, both necessary for the 21st century baseball business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to move on,'' Harwell said. ``I don't want to look
back. We've got to keep the memories and treasure them in our
hearts and souls and minds and let it go at that.''
</P>
<P>
   The old place has dozens of steel posts that obstruct the views
from thousands of chairs. My son and I spent one game in the lower
deck, the other in the upper. From between the obstructions, the
posts and roofs frame a charming and intimate view, like a George
Bellows painting on a museum wall. Because the upper deck hangs
over the lower, the sounds from the field _ bats, balls, gloves and
voices _ reverberate through the aisles while the shouts of the
fans carry out across the grass. Throughout both games, cameras
flashed. Bill Dow, an organizer of the Tiger Stadium Fan Club, said
strangers have asked him to photograph them all summer, just
standing there.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this year of the long goodbye, it's just starting to sink
in,'' Dow said. ``I feel a mixed emotion of sadness and anger.'' He
said the old park could have been preserved and renovated, but ``it
was never appreciated as much as Wrigley Field or Fenway Park
because the Tigers didn't market it as much. The fans are paying
their last respects. People are making pilgrimages. People stand
outside the stadium and stare at it. It is a melancholy feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Other ballpark visits were not as sentimental but still great
fun. Dreading the legendary foul weather in San Francisco, we were
pleasantly surprised by the ambiance at Candlestick Point.
Alongside blue water and golden hillsides, fans arrived early for
tailgate picnics. When evening winds chilled the air, customers
added layers of clothing or blankets. A female voice announced the
batters and the speakers played ``Let's Spend the Night Together.''
Before a Sunday afternoon game, during an AIDS awareness event, the
Village People performed from the same site as the final concert of
the last Beatles tour in 1966. We drove by the new stadium, under
construction at China Basin, closer to downtown. No wind problems
there, they promise.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Milwaukee, during a night game, we saw costumed characters in
the ``Sausage Race'' between innings: Bratwurst vs. Polish vs. Hot
Dog. During the seventh-inning stretch, the fans sang ``Take Me Out
to the Ball Game'' but voiced more gusto for ``Roll Out the
Barrel.'' Before the game, we photographed the new Miller Park,
directly behind the center-field fence, the work site decorated
with baseball paintings by children. A fatal crane accident has
delayed completion until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Like other new parks _ in Baltimore, Cleveland, Seattle, Texas,
Denver _ Miller has the retro effect that evokes the past. Harwell
said these designs beat the round ``cookie cutter'' stadiums in
Cincinnati, Pittsburgh, St. Louis, Houston and Philadelphia, built
in the 1960s and 1970s, where ground balls skipped across
artificial turf for cheap doubles. ``Two-sport facilities that
didn't do well for either sport,'' Harwell said. ``I'm certainly
glad to get rid of that era and move into this one.''
</P>
<P>
   The emerging period, he said, ``will be compared with the era
that came around in 1910 or 1912, when Forbes Field and Shibe Park
and Comiskey Park and Navin Field were called palaces.''
</P>
<P>
   Of that group, we visited Wrigley in Chicago and Fenway in
Boston, the two surviving museum pieces. While too many sports
arenas bombard their guests with heavy-metal music and noisy sound
effects, Wrigley uses organ music and a strolling Dixieland band.
</P>
<P>
   The outfield scoreboard is hand-numbered each inning as it was
when games were monitored by telegraph ticker. Fans watching from
apartment roofs would look at home on the edges of a Norman
Rockwell painting. Unlike most parks, Wrigley is almost free of
advertising, easy on the eyes, even when the Cubs aren't. While
Fenway has a video screen in the outfield _ and did I mention that
my daughter Michelle worked at Fenway as a tour guide this summer?
_ there was no way in Wrigley to see a replay of three Cub fielders
barely avoiding a collision as a pop fly fell among them. But it
would have been nice to get a second look at Sammy Sosa's home run
on that crisp, sunny afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe not. Baseball's highlights replay best in the movie
memories of the mind. Late on our last night at Tiger Stadium, I
climbed to the last row of the upper deck along the first-base
line, where I worked as a teen-age usher in the 1960s. From that
high perch, I saw not the game in progress between the Tigers and
Texas but instead an old one in which Al Kaline threw out a cocky
rookie who tried to take an extra base on a single to right.
Instead of empty seats around me, I saw old pals, family members,
lovers and co-workers. Through the mist on this clear night, I
again saw Willie Horton throw out Lou Brock at home in the pivotal
play of the World Series victory over St. Louis in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Looking beyond the left-field roof, I saw again the thickening
clouds of black smoke from the 1967 riot, which grew in fury during
a Sunday afternoon game that July. Peering through the back vents
of the upper deck, I saw and smelled an overturned police car
burning in the celebration that followed the 1984 World Series. I
saw the revved-up Mark Fidrych, with long and curly hair, drawing
shrieks from a capacity crowd by pitching two-hour victories in
1976. Closing my eyes, I saw Ty Cobb steal home, spikes high, and
Hank Greenberg hitting a long home run to left.
</P>
<P>
   But my transistor radio jolted my ears and eyes back from the
past as Harwell's Georgia voice excitedly described Tony Clark's
two-run double off the right-field wall, the clinching hit of that
night's victory. Checking both the hour on my watch and the late
inning on the scoreboard, I left my high seat and walked back down
the steep, concrete steps and into the present, back to my son and
my friend and his son, to stroll down the long ramp from the upper
deck for the last time to the red bricks of the street and out
toward the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 1508EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
