<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5889 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-PREVIEW-EAST26-CO     09-25 3108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PREVIEW-EAST26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NHL Eastern Conference capsules
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHEAST DIVISION
</P>
<P>
   1. FLORIDA PANTHERS
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 30-34-18 (second place), missed the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: None.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: The biggest plus is the return of Pavel Bure from a
knee injury. ... General manager Bryan Murray has cleaned house of
some older high-priced veterans, including D Gord Murphy, F Johan
Garpenlov and F Kirk Muller, but he added G Trevor Kidd to replace
Kirk McLean and back up Sean Burke. D Lance Pitlick also was
signed.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: The Panthers have missed the playoffs the past two
seasons and have only one postseason win since making the finals in
their third season. ... Bure returns to Vancouver on Nov. 5 for the
first time since being traded. ... Florida had a woeful 13.4
power-play percentage . ... Viktor Kozlov will be asked to be the
No. 1 center and needs to improve on his 16 goals.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 350 _ the Panthers league-high total of games
played by rookies.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: The Murray brothers. Does Bryan fire coach Terry if
going with younger players fails _ or will he be canned himself?
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: A healthy Bure and the goalie tandem of Burke and Kidd
should lift the Panthers to the division title.
</P>
<P>
   2. WASHINGTON CAPITALS
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 31-45-6 (third place), missed playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: None.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: There's a new owner, Ted Leonsis, and increasing
pressure on GM George McPhee and coach Ron Wilson for a turnaround.
No transactions of significance: Subtract Dale Hunter (retirement)
and add G Craig Billington (trade), F Ulf Dahlen (free agency) and
Joe Sacco (free agency).
</P>
<P>
   Note this: The Capitals have been Team Band-Aid over the past
four seasons, losing 1,571 games to injuries. ... In the past three
seasons, the Caps pulled off this rarity: missed playoffs, made
finals, missed playoffs. ... Talent remains up front with Peter
Bondra (31 goals) and Adam Oates (42 assists), but younger forwards
must develop and stay healthy. ... The Caps gave up the first goal
in 49 games and won only nine.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: Wilson has a better record in the playoffs
(12-9) than in the regular season (71-75-18).
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: Oates, who has been chosen captain but scored 12
goals, his lowest total in 12 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: The odds have to be with the Capitals in the injury
department, and they should make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   3. CAROLINA HURRICANES
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 34-30-18 (first place), lost in first round of playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: None.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: Hurricanes must recover from the death of D Steve
Chaisson in a car crash. They added a new arena, backup G Mark
Fitzpatrick and not much else. The team lost G Trevor Kidd in the
expansion draft, is missing holdout Keith Primeau and did not
re-sign Kevin Dineen or Ray Sheppard.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: The Hurricanes will start with a nine-game trip,
while Raleigh Sports Arena is finished. The first home game is Oct.
29. ... Finn Sami Kapanen (24 goals) has emerged as a top scorer.
Ron Francis is coming off a 21-goal season but is 36. ... Primeau
led the team in goals (30) and points (62). ... Arturs Irbe is
coming off a career-best GAA of 2.22.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: $55 million _ Hurricanes' claimed losses in
their two seasons in Greensboro.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: GM Jim Rutherford, who is facing sluggish ticket
sales, mounting financial losses and had a suspect offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: Look out below. Canes benefited from the problems of
others to win the division but should miss the playoffs this time.
</P>
<P>
   4. TAMPA BAY LIGHTNING
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 19-54-9 (fourth place), missed playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: None.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: Lightning might as well be an expansion team, with
new owner (Bill Davidson), GM (Rick Dudley), coach (Steve Ludzik),
goalie (Dan Cloutier from Rangers) and a number of other players.
Biggest losses: D Rob Zamuner, sent to Ottawa as compensation for
signing Dudley, and leading scorer Wendel Clark was traded late
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: All eyes will be on C Vincent Lecavalier to see
progress from his first season (13-15-28). ... Lightning will
attack more under Ludzik than it did under GM-coach Jacques Demers.
... Before selling, former owner Art Williams voided a trade for
Roman Turek, who would have been the starting goalie.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 36-109-19 _ the Lightning's record over the past
two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: Cloutier, who played behind Mike Richter, was the key
in a draft-day trade and must help maintain order on the ice while
Dudley tears apart and rebuilds team.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: Lightning might be headed in the right direction, but
it won't translate into victories immediately. Tampa Bay could
repeat a last-place finish, which would be pleasing for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   5. ATLANTA THRASHERS
</P>
<P>
   Replay: First season.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: None.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: GM Don Waddell squeezed the most out of the
expansion draft process, getting two quality goalies (Damian Rhodes
and Norm Maracle) and a solid defense. He also swung a trade to get
the only prime draft pick he wanted _ Patrik Stefan. The one
debatable move was dealing highly touted minor-league forward Randy
Robitaille to Nashville for Denny Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: Coach Curt Fraser, physical as a player, will have
his team play the same way. ... Goals could be hard to come by,
with Ray Ferraro and Nelson Emerson (13 each) as leaders from
1998-99. ... The team says it won't rush No. 1 pick Stefan, but
he'll get plenty of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 0 _ the number of non-WHA expansion teams that
have made the playoffs since 1970. Florida went 33-34-17 in
1993-94. More recently, Nashville went 28-47-7 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: Rhodes, the clear No. 1 goalie and the team's best
shot at respectability in the first season.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: Last place is most realistic. But the Thrashers could
pass Tampa Bay if Rhodes stands out, mistakes are kept to a minimum
and a couple of goal scorers are found.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHEAST DIVISION
</P>
<P>
   1. TORONTO MAPLE LEAFS
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 45-30-7 (second place), lost in Eastern Conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: The biggest changes are in the front office, where
top personnel Mike Smith and Anders Hedberg are out. President Ken
Dryden increased the power of coach Pat Quinn, who now also is GM.
Leafs lost D Yannick Tremblay (expansion draft) but added backup G
Jimmy Waite (free agent).
</P>
<P>
   Note this: The Leafs appeared to be on the way to the Cup finals
but managed 10 goals in four losses against Buffalo's Dominik Hasek
in the Eastern Conference finals. ... Leafs led the league in goals
(268) for first time in 52 years, led by Sergei Berezin (37) and
Mats Sundin (31). ... Defense (231 goals against) needs to improve
in front of G Curtis Joseph, who faced almost 30 shots per game and
was runner-up to Dominik Hasek in Vezina voting.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 256 _ Berezin's draft position in 1994. A lot of
scouts goofed.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: Dryden, who made the decision to ship out Smith and
will take more blame than Quinn if things go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: Deep at forward and strong in goal with Joseph and
Glenn Healy, Leafs will make another strong run at the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   2. OTTAWA SENATORS
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 44-23-15 (first place), lost in first round.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: None.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: Hard to imagine that one of the youngest, most
talented teams in the league could have had a worse offseason. The
Senators lost their general manager (Rick Dudley) for the second
season in a row, half of their goaltender rotation (Damian Rhodes)
and two players to free agency (Nelson Emerson and Lance Pitlick),
and they might be without their best player, Alexei Yashin, who
wants a contract extension. One plus: Defenseman Rob Zamuner
arrived from Tampa Bay as partial compensation for Dudley's exit.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: A franchise-best record didn't help in the
first-round series loss to Buffalo. Senators are extremely talented
but need to be more physical. ... Losing Rhodes to Thrashers
elevates Ron Tugnutt as the clear No. 1 goalie. Tugnutt is coming
off a career year (1.79 GAA, .925 svs.). ... If Yashin stays out,
Magnus Arvedson (21 goals), Andreas Dackell (15) and Radek Bonk
(16) must pick up the slack. ... Shawn McEachern's numbers
(31-25-56) could drop without Yashin on his line.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 22 _ Equals win totals by Rhodes and Tugnutt.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: Tugnutt, with coach Jacques Martin scrapping his
goalie rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: The Senators won't approach 44 wins, but they could
match last year's first-round playoff elimination if things don't
settle down.
</P>
<P>
   3. BUFFALO SABRES
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 37-28-17 (fourth place), lost in Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: None.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: Did not re-sign F Joe Juneau and lost D Darryl
Shannon in the expansion draft. Biggest transaction is yet to come:
Goalie Dominik Hasek announced his retirement, effective after this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: There's no reason to believe Hasek will change his
mind, so the Sabres, after coming close, suddenly have one season
to win the Stanley Cup. ... Hasek has led the league in saves
percentage six seasons in a row and has won Vezina in five of the
past six. ... Miroslav Satan had a 40-goal season but disappeared
in the finals, partly because of an ankle injury. ... C Michael
Peca has emerged as one of the top all-around players in the game.
... The Sabres are one of the league's smartest positional teams
but lack scoring depth.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 11/3/99 _ the date of the only game this year
between Cup finalists Buffalo and Dallas, at Dallas. No word
whether Sabres coach Lindy Ruff will bring a video-replay machine
with him.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: Hasek. As always, team's chances hinge on his
acrobatics.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: Expect usual roller-coaster and another strong playoff
run, but Sabres will fall short of the finals.
</P>
<P>
   4. BOSTON BRUINS
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 39-30-13 (third place), lost in second round.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: A disastrous offseason: The team dropped top
goal-scorer Dmitri Khristich because GM Harry Sinden didn't like a
$2.8 million arbitration award. Also lost Tim Taylor to free agency
(Rangers) and top prospect Randy Robitaille (expansion draft).
Goalie Byron Dafoe also remains unsigned. Only significant
addition: Dave Andreychuk.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: Expect coach Pat Burns, among the league's best, to
get fed up with the franchise's personnel decisions. ... Even
without Khristich, the team still has a terrific core of young
forwards: Jason Allison (23 goals), Joe Thornton (16), Sergei
Samsonov (25) and Anson Carter (24). ... Dafoe is coming off his
career season (32-23-11, 1.99, .926). ... Ray Bourque is in his
21st season with the Bruins. Only Gordie Howe (25) and Alex
Delvecchio (24) have been with one club longers. ... The Bruins
were the league's best penalty killers (89.2 percent) and were a
plus-26 on special-teams ratio.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 214 _ Bruins' goal total, their lowest since
1966-67.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: Sinden, whose decisions are holding this team back.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: Should be division's best but will struggle to get
into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   5. MONTREAL CANADIENS
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 32-39-11 (fifth place), missed playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: Big gain: Acquired Trevor Linden from Islanders for
a No. 1 pick. Big loss: Stephane Quintal signed with Rangers as a
free agent. Montreal also lost Brett Clark in the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: Linden has six 30-plus goal seasons in 11 years. ...
The Canadiens need improved seasons from Martin Rucinsky (17 goals,
minus-25), Brian Savage (16, minus-14) and Shayne Corson (12,
minus-10). ... Goalie Jeff Hackett played well after coming over
from Chicago late last season (.914 saves pct. with Canadiens, .871
with Blackhawks). ... The Habs were hurt by injuries: Six of the
top eight scorers missed at least 12 games. ... Canadiens were the
No. 1 road penalty-killing team but No. 27 on power play and gave
up 10 short-handed goals.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 184 _ The Canadiens' goals ranked next to last
in 1998-99. They didn't have a 20-goal scorer for the first time
since 1941.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: Coach Alain Vigneault. It's not unusual for a
Montreal coach to be under fire, but in this case the problems are
more the result of management and finances.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: Les last-place Habitants.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTIC DIVISION
</P>
<P>
   1. PHILADELPHIA FLYERS
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 37-26-19 (second place), lost in first round.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: Biggest plus is return of Eric Lindros from a
collapsed lung. Biggest loss was death of D Dmitri Tertyshny,
killed in a boating acceident. Few other changes: F Mike Maneluk
signed, G Ron Hextall retired, F Jody Hull lost in the expansion
draft.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: The lingering concerns: suspect defense, goaltending
and John LeClair's back problems. ... GM Bob Clarke made 12 deals
during last season, resulting in 14 new players. ... Coach Roger
Neilson is 10th on the career victory list (414) but still has his
detractors. ... The team is deep up front with Lindros, LeClair,
Mark Recchi, Mikael Renberg, Rod Brind'Amour, Keith Jones, et al.
... The Flyers hope for an impact from young C Simon Gagne.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 36 _ the age of goalie John Vanbiesbrouck, who
could be entering his last season with the Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: Clarke is a local hero, but how many coaches can one
man hire and fire before he gets his pink slip?
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: Flyers might have taken a run at the Cup with Lindros
last season. If defense and goaltending hold up, Philly could be
looking at its first title in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   2. NEW JERSEY DEVILS
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 47-24-11 (first place), lost in first round.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: A quiet offseason saw the retirement of Bobby
Carpenter and the loss of Dave Andreychuk (free agency) and Kevin
Dean (expansion draft). No significant acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: Devils finished with the best record in the Eastern
Conference under first-year coach Robbie Ftorek but tumbled in the
first round of the playoffs. ... Jersey is short of stars but deep
in young, talented, two-way players. ... Devils had nine players
with at least 31 points past year. ... Goalie Martin Brodeur has
won 34 or more games each of the past four years. ... Petr Sykora
doubled his point total, 36 to 72.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 30 _ as in a 30-goal season. Devils haven't had
one since 1993-94.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: Ftorek. Don't laugh. Another 47-win season won't go
far with fans if the Devils fail to advance past the second round
of the playoffs for the fifth season in a row. If Ftorek doesn't
last, look for reclaimed assistant Larry Robinson to step in.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: GM Lou Lamoriello hardly was aggressive in the
offseason but the Devils still have enough to challenge for the
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   3. NEW YORK RANGERS
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 33-38-11 (fourth place), missed playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: If general manager Neil Smith goes down, he's going
to do it running up a heck of a bill on the Rangers' gold card. Six
free agents were signed _ Theo Fleury, Sylvain Lefebvre, Valeri
Kamensky, Stephane Quintal, Kirk McLean and Tim Taylor. But the
losses were big, as well. Wayne Gretzky and Jeff Beukeboom retired,
Dan Cloutier, Niklas Sundstrom and Marc Savard were traded, and
Chris Tamer was lost in the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: Deals might not mean much, especially if Fleury wilts
again in the playoffs as he did in Colorado. ... Coach John Muckler
must try to create chemistry on a team that was a strange mix of
too old and too young. ... Rising F Manny Malhotra could have a
breakthrough season. ... Rangers could be less physical this year
with the absence of Tamer, Beukeboom and Ulf Samuelsson, traded
late last season to Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: $67 million _ total of guaranteed contracts of
six free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: Smith and Muckler, whose Rangers have missed the
playoffs the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: Spending spree won't pay off, and CEO David Checketts
will clean house.
</P>
<P>
   4. PITTSBURGH PENGUINS
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 38-30-14 (third place), lost in second round.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: Mario Lemieux rescued the team from bankruptcy.
That's a plus. But the financial paralysis and uncertain future
prevented GM Craig Patrick from fixing roster holes.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: F Jaromir Jagr is coming off MVP season with
league-leading 127 points (44 goals). ... Patrick did good job
re-signing key free agents, including Martin Straka (35 goals),
Alexei Kovalev (23) and Robert Lang (21). ... Defenseman Kevin
Hatcher enters the last season of his contract and could be traded
before unrestricted free agency. ... Defense might not be great,
but not so bad that G Tom Barrasso's goals against ballooned from
2.07 to 2.55. ... Coach Kevin Constantine did a good job holding
team together but has a shaky relationship with Jagr.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 343 _ Jagr's shots on goal, double that of any
teammate.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: Barrasso, who missed 31 games with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: Lemieux can't help Penguins anymore, unless he comes
back to play.
</P>
<P>
   5. NEW YORK ISLANDERS
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 24-48-10 (fifth place), missed playoffs
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: Butch Goring enters a mess as coach he didn't
witness as a player on Long Island. Six-player, three-draft-pick
trade included Ziggy Palffy going to Los Angeles and top young F
Olli Jokinen heading to Isles. Also gone: Trevor Linden to Montreal
for a No. 1 pick, Joe Sacco (free agency) and David Harlock
(expansion draft). Incoming: free agents Tony Hrkac and Chris
Ferraro.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: GM Mike Milbury did well in the Palffy trade. But
forget any chance of serious rebuilding program as long as three
(stooges) owners Howard and Eddie Milstein and Steve Gluckstern are
ordering Milbury to trim payroll. ... Kenny Jonsson is top
defenseman, but he had two concussions last season. ... Goalie
Felix Potvin was not brilliant after coming over in a trade from
Toronto. Potvin's save percentage (.893) wasn't significantly
better than backup's Wade Flaherty (.892).
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 6 _ number of Islanders coaches since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: Potvin, who had injury problems and walked out on the
Leafs last year, has a full season to show whether he still has it.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: Islanders have missed playoffs five consecutive
seasons. This season will be the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
