<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NHL West Conference capsules
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL DIVISION
</P>
<P>
   1. DETROIT RED WINGS
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 43-32-7 (first place), lost in second round.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: The Wings did not re-sign three of the four players
brought in at the trading deadline last season _ D Ulf Samuelsson,
F Wendel Clark and G Bill Ranford. They signed goalies Ken Wregget
and Manny Legace to replace Norm Maracle (expansion draft). Biggest
plus was re-signing D Nicklas Lidstrom.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: D Chris Chelios looked old in playoff series vs.
Colorado. ... Without Lidstrom, Wings' defense would have been a
major problem. Even with him, team wants to improve on last year's
10th place in goals-against (202). ... If coach Scotty Bowman
didn't think Lidstrom would return, he might have retired.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 15-2-1 _ Wings' record in 18 games (9-2-1
regular season, 6-0 playoffs) until losing four in a row to
Colorado in the Western semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: Forwards Brendan Shanahan and Sergei Fedorov, both of
whom fizzled in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: Wings still have talent to challenge for the Cup, but
age and slipping defense could ruin hopes.
</P>
<P>
   2. ST. LOUIS BLUES
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 37-32-13 (second place), lost in second round.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: None.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: The Blues landed new No. 1 goalie Roman Turek from
Dallas for only a second-round pick after the Stars' pre-expansion
draft deal with Tampa fell through. Grant Fuhr was shipped to
Calgary to clear roster room. Blues also lost F Terry Yake in the
expansion draft and didn't re-sign enforcer Tony Twist, later
injured in a motorcycle accident.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: Without Brett Hull, F Pavel Demitra took over as the
top scorer (89 points). ... The offense is not overpowering but
will be deep enough if F Geoff Courtnall (concussions) and F Jim
Campbell can bounce back from off years. The two combined for 53
goals two years ago but only nine last season. ... Turek was 16-3-3
with a 2.08 GAA last year. ... Al MacInnis and Chris Pronger are
among the league's top defensemen, but MacInnis turned 36 in July.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 30.6 _ Pronger's minutes per game last season,
tops in the league. MacInnis was fourth at 29.1.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: Turek. All scouts think he's ready. Now he has to
prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: Terrific team that can skate and hit. If Turek
blossoms as the No. 1 goalie, this team is the dark horse to go to
the finals.
</P>
<P>
   3. CHICAGO BLACKHAWKS
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 29-41-12 (third place), missed playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: The Blackhawks wanted F Nelson Emerson as a free
agent but were outbid by the Thrashers, so they settled on F Wendel
Clark. They also added D Bryan McCabe in a draft-day trade with
Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: Hawks were 13-6-4 after Lorne Molleken replaced Dirk
Graham as coach. ... Motivator Molleken gave each player an
arrowhead to ``point'' them in the right direction. ... What
Chicago really needs is goal-scoring: F Tony Amonte accounted for
44 of the team's 202. ... Hawks goalie coach Vladislav Tretiak
believes Jocelyn Thibault (2.71 GAA, .905 svs., after trade with
Montreal ) can become one of the league's top goalies ... The team
needs to improve the penalty-killing unit that gave up 80
power-play goals last season.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: Minus-16 _ Free-agent bust Doug Gilmour's
team-worst plus-minus ratio last season.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: F Eric Daze, whose 42 points last year were not
commensurate with a $2 million salary.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: Molleken stopped the leaking, but he would need to
work miracles to make this team a playoff team.
</P>
<P>
   4. NASHVILLE PREDATORS
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 28-47-7 (fourth place), missed playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: None.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: They made two trades with the Thrashers, dealing F
Andrew Brunette, after a disappointing 11 goals, for a draft pick
and F Denny Lambert for top minor-league prospect F Randy
Robitaille.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: Robitaille had 102 points in the AHL last season and
could added needed scoring punch. ... Goalie Mike Dunham is coming
off a solid first season but was missing from training camp as a
restricted free agent. ... Expansion draft pick F Cliff Ronning led
the Predators with 53 points. ... Last year's No. 1, F David
Legwand, played only one game and spent most of the year in the
juniors. Nashville expects some contributions. ... Dramatic
improvement is needed on special teams: The penalty-killing team
finished 27th (79 percent), and the power play was 25th (12.3).
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 4-12-1 _ Dunham's record after returning from a
groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: F Sergei Krivokrasov, who is coming off a career-best
25-goal season but faced charges of spousal abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: The 28-win total was fifth-best for expansion teams in
the modern era, but topping that will be difficult unless more
scoring is found.
</P>
<P>
   PACIFIC DIVISION
</P>
<P>
   1. DALLAS STARS
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 51-19-12 (first place), won Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: Stars did not re-sign a number of older free agents
_ forwards Pat Verbeek, Tony Hrkac, David Reid, Craig Ludwig. They
also dealt coveted backup goalie Roman Turek to St. Louis before
losing him in the expansion draft and dealt F Jason Botterill to
the Thrashers for D Jamie Pushor.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: After 51 victories in the regular season and a
Stanley Cup, GM Bob Gainey and coach Ken Hitchcock both thought
significant changes necessary to stay on top. ... Jon Sim, Juha
Lind and Brad Lukowich are among younger players who might land
roster spots to replace unsigned veterans. ... The big news is that
Hitchcock, master of the 2-1 win, vows his team will open up the
offense. That change would thrill Mike Modano, Joe Nieuwendyk,
Jamie Langenbrunner, et al. ... Words G Ed Belfour won't have to
hear anymore: can't win the big one.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: The Stars have averaged 109 points over the past
three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: Gainey. The only thing harder than winning is winning
through a transition in personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: If Hitchcock succeeds in opening up the offense
without leaving Belfour exposed, nobody can touch the Stars. Either
way, Dallas has the talent to challenge again.
</P>
<P>
   2. PHOENIX COYOTES
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 39-31-12 (second place), lost in first round.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: None.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: Bobby Francis replaces Jim Schoenfeld as coach. More
minuses than pluses in the personnel area: Subtract F Mike
Stapleton (expansion draft), D Oleg Tverdovsky (traded to Anaheim
for Travis Green) and G Jimmy Waite (free agent). Only significant
addition was D Todd Gill (free agent).
</P>
<P>
   Note this: Phoenix was the story of early last season, starting
17-3-3, but it was under .500 thereafter (22-28-9). ... Francis
wants to beef up the offense, but it is limited after Keith Tkachuk
(36 goals), Jeremy Roenick (24) and Rick Tocchet (26). ... Warning:
Tocchet is 35. ... If Francis opens things up and Coyotes aren't as
protective in their end as they were with Schoenfeld, the pressure
will be on G Nikolai Khabibulin (2.13 GAA, .923 svs.) to equal his
success. But he remains unsigned. ... The Coyotes' 41 power-play
goals last season ranked as second-fewest in the league to
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 1987 _ the last season Winnipeg/Phoenix won a
playoff series. The Jets/Coyotes are 0-for-7 since and missed the
postseason five times.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: GM Bobby Smith. It wasn't an active offseason, and
the Green-Tverdovsky trade seems lopsided the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: Strong goaltending and Tkachuk and Roenick should keep
Coyotes in second, but Francis will need to find more scoring for
the team to do damage in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   3. SAN JOSE SHARKS
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 31-33-18 (fourth place), lost in first round of
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: None.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: Acquired F Niklas Sundstrom from Tampa Bay, which
acquired him from N.Y. Rangers on draft day, for four players,
including D Andrei Zyuzin. The Sharks also get back D Gary Suter,
who missed all but one game last season with a torn triceps. Free
agent Joe Murphy (25 goals) was not re-signed.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: The Sharks must improve on a power play that
converted on a franchise record-low 13.3 percent of chances. ...
The team kept F Vincent Damphousse, acquired late last season from
Montreal, from departing as a free agent. ... Coach Darryl Sutter
seems to have the respect of players and has an impressive streak
going: 18 consecutive seasons in the playoffs as a player or coach.
... Goaltending was divided between Mike Vernon and Steve Shields,
but Shields (2.22 GAA, .921 svs.) might be ready to take over as
starter. ... F Jeff Friesen led the Sharks in scoring with only 57
points.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 196 _ San Jose's goal total last season, the
fewest in league history for a playoff-qualifier since Minnesota's
191 in a 78-game season in 1970-71.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: Sundstrom and Damphousse, a former 30- and 40-goal
scorer with Toronto and Montreal, both of whom are being counted on
to strengthen the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: Sharks could challenge for second and pose a threat in
the playoffs. They took Colorado to six games in the first round
last season.
</P>
<P>
   4. ANAHEIM MIGHTY DUCKS
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 35-34-13 (third place), lost in first round.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: None.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: Most significant additions were D Oleg Tverdovsky
from Phoenix for F Travis Green and F Ted Donato from Ottawa for G
Patrick Lalime. Biggest losses were F Tomas Sandstrom (returned to
Sweden) and D Jamie Pushor (expansion draft).
</P>
<P>
   Note this: The Ducks are coming off only their second winning
season and improved by nine wins (18 points) over the previous
year. ... The highly skilled Tverdovsky will help a power play that
already clicked at a league-best 22 percent last season. ... Craig
Hartsburg is among the new wave of coaches whose system stresses
aggressive forechecking. ... Biggest problem is finding balanced
scoring. After Teemu Selanne (107 points) and Paul Kariya (101),
the next closest Duck was Steve Rucchin (62). ... Goalie Guy Hebert
is coming off his career season (31 wins, 2.42 GAA, .922 svs.).
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: $30 million _ value of Kariya's three-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: Donato, a former 20-goal scorer who dropped to 16 and
11 the past two seasons and is being counted on to balance the
scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: The Ducks are ascending under general manager Pierre
Gauthier and could rise as high as second place. But they're not
quite ready to challenge for the Western Conference title.
</P>
<P>
   5. LOS ANGELES KINGS
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 32-45-5 (fifth place), missed playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: None.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: Larry Robinson is out as coach, replaced by Andy
Murray. Numerous changes in personnel include acquiring F Ziggy
Palffy and F Bryan Smolinski in a trade with the Islanders, for a
package including Olli Jokinen, and persuading D Aki Berg to return
from Sweden. Kings lost F Ray Ferraro and D Doug Bodger as free
agents, and F Matt Johnson in the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: F Luc Robitaille's 39 goals last season nearly
matched his output the previous seasons combined (40). ...
Injury-prone D Rob Blake missed two games and has played only one
full season in the past four. ... Stephane Fiset and Jamie Storr
are a great goalie tandem if they can stay healthy. ... F Jozef
Stumpel needs to bounce back from an off-season. ... Finnish import
Jere Karalahti should help the defense.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 9 for 103 (8.7 percent) _ Kings' power play in
one- and two-goal losses last season.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: General manager Dave Taylor, who is banking on a
relatively obscure coach to turn around an underachieving team and
also needs to fill seats in a new arena.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: Palffy should improve offense, but its hard to imagine
L.A. moving up in a division in which everybody else is
significantly better over last season.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHWEST DIVISION
</P>
<P>
   1. COLORADO AVALANCHE
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 44-28-10 (first place), lost in Western Conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: The Avalanche was the biggest victim of the Rangers'
offseason shopping spree, losing F Theo Fleury, F Valeri Kamensky
and D Sylvain Lefebvre. Also, F Dale Hunter retired, F Warren
Rychel was not re-signed, and backup G Craig Billington was traded
to Washington. And incoming? Goalie prospect Marc Denis is Patrick
Roy's new backup.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: The worst news was not the defections of Fleury and
Co. but F Peter Forsberg's shoulder surgery, which will wipe out at
least the first month of his season. ... Roy had ``minor'' surgery
to remove debris from his right hip but is expected to be recovered
by the opener. ... Despite the losses, the team still is talented
and deep, just younger. Calder Trophy winner Chris Drury, Milan
Hejduk and rookie Alex Tanguay inherit bigger roles in the offense
with Fleury, Kamensky and Rychel gone.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 412 _ Roy's victories, fourth on the career list
behind Terry Sawchuk (447), Jacques Plante (434) and Tony Esposito
(423). Heat's on: Forsberg, whose offense and leadership will be
missed.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: Colorado seemed to be spent after taking a 3-2 series
lead against Dallas last season in the Western finals. A younger
team could put the Avalanche over the top and back in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   2. EDMONTON OILERS
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 33-37-12 (second place), lost in first round of
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: Former defenseman Kevin Lowe is in as the new coach,
replacing the fired Ron Low. The Oilers lost captain Kelly
Buchberger in the expansion draft and are in the middle of a
contract squabble with leading scorer F Bill Guerin (64 points).
Backup G Bill Ranford was signed after being released by Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: Dallas offered G Roman Turek to the Oilers for F Ryan
Smyth (31 points), but GM Glen Sather declined, believing that
Smyth will develop into a star. ... Another reason Sather said no
to Turek: G Tommy Salo went 8-2-2, 2.31 after being acquired from
the Islanders. ... Penalty-killing ranked 21st in the league and
must improve. ... D Tom Poti made the league's all-rookie team, but
it's a matter of time before he gets too expensive to keep.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 67 _ power-play goals allowed by Oilers last
season, most of any playoff team.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: F Doug Weight. He led the Oilers in scoring five
seasons in a row (1993-98), but missed 43 games with knee problems.
A 20-goal/70-point season is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: The Oilers probably will sneak into the playoffs, but
they won't go far. It would be interesting to see what Sather,
perhaps still the league's best, could do with a decent budget.
This could be his last season.
</P>
<P>
   3. VANCOUVER CANUCKS
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 23-47-12 (fourth place), missed playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: None.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: Drafted its hockey and marketing centerpieces, twins
Daniel and Henrik Sedin of Sweden. But both elected to return to
amateur teams for one more year. GM Brian Burke dealt D Bryan
McCabe to Chicago on draft day and signed two free agents _ D Doug
Bodger, who bombed out in L.A., and F Andrew Cassels.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: F Mark Messier has only 35 goals and 108 points in
two seasons with the Canucks. Messier had 83 goals and 183 points
in his final two seasons with the Rangers. ... More production is
needed from F Alex Mogilny, whose goal total (14) was not on the
same level as his salary ($4.2 million). ... F Markus Naslund is
coming off career-best 36 goals. ... The Canucks haven't made the
playoffs the past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 5 _ Number of Canucks head coaches in the past
four seasons: Rick Ley, Pat Quinn, Tom Renney, Mike Keenan, Marc
Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: Burke. The team is for sale and is losing money, and
his golden-boy draft picks are in high school. The GM will take the
most heat.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: No worse than last season, but probably no better.
</P>
<P>
   4. CALGARY FLAMES
</P>
<P>
   Replay: 30-40-12 (third place), missed playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Last sip from Cup: 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Plus/minus: Acquired G Grant Fuhr from the Blues and F Marc
Savard from the Rangers. Finally signed 1997 No. 1 pick Daniel
Tkaczuk. Lost G Ken Wregget and F Andrew Cassels to free agency and
F Ed Ward in the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Note this: The Flames probably overachieved to win 30 games,
which tells you something about their talent level. ... The Flames
have high hopes that Savard can develop into a top scorer, but he
has only 51 points in 98 games. ... Valeri Bure (26), Cory Stillman
(27) and Jarome Iginla (28) are the only returning 20-goal scorers.
By the numbers: 0 _ number of playoff series the Flames have won
since winning the Stanley Cup in 1988-89.
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on: Sutter. The contract aside, this wasn't a 30-win team
last season, and the coach will be targeted.
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: Yuck.
</P>
