<SLUG> BC-HKN-PREVIEW-STARS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stars fade, best still rises in West
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wayne Gretzky's first season in the NHL was Atlanta's
last. Twenty years later, the Flames have been replaced by the
Thrashers and the league bears little resemblance to the one
Gretzky crashed as an 18-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL opens its regular season Friday, having ballooned to 28
franchises. Whether having T-shirts stands in multiple markets can
compensate for the loss of the league's No.1 ambassador is the big
question. Gretzky retired after last season, was rammed into the
Hall of Fame and will be honored in opening night ceremonies when
his first team, Edmonton, plays host to his last, the New York
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   That matchup serves as a microcosm for the NHL's problems.
Edmonton is forever a team loaded with young talent but is too
cash-poor to keep the players. The Oilers and other Canadian teams
continue to struggle financially and threaten to move somewhere
south of the U.S. border, where $1 in revenues is not worth 65
cents.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, conversely, spent $67 million on six free agents in
the offseason, including forwards Theo Fleury and Valeri Kamensky,
both of whom were deemed too expensive for still-loaded Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole tradition of seeing guys come out of your farm team
and play with your team for 10 or 12 years really hasn't been the
case for a few years now and it's going to become less so,''
Toronto Maple Leafs coach Pat Quinn said. ``It's just what's
happening in the game today.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Dallas, Colorado, Detroit, Philadelphia and
Toronto will be among the teams challenging for the Stanley Cup. If
Buffalo makes another run, it better hurry. Goalie Dominik Hasek
says this will be his last.
</P>
<P>
   Another star gone.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
