<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASTER THAN A SPEEDING DIVISION CHAMPIONSHIP 
LET THEM COUNT THE WAYS 
BORING AND FLASHY 
THE SEARCH FOR TALENT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Yankees had never gone to the World Series with free
agents like Reggie Jackson, Catfish Hunter, David Cone and David
Wells, if the Atlanta Braves had never won division championships
with free agents like Greg Maddux, Fred McGriff and Terry
Pendleton, if the Florida Marlins had not won the World Series with
free agents like Kevin Brown, Moises Alou and Bobby Bonilla, the
Arizona Diamondbacks could be accused of buying themselves a
division championship.
</P>
<P>
   But the Diamondbacks, who won the National League West title
Friday night, have gained their place in baseball history the
old-fashioned way _ they have earned it.
</P>
<P>
   Playing by the rules of the game, just as George Steinbrenner
did so well in restoring the Yankees to the top of the game in the
mid-1970s when free agency began, the 2-year-old Diamondbacks have
vaulted to the top far faster than any expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in their second seasons, seven of the other 13
expansion teams finished in last place, four lost more than 100
games, four others lost more than 95 and eight finished more than
30 games from first place. Only one had a winning record. But in
establishing a standard for expansion teams, the Diamondbacks have
done it with far greater dexterity than the use of a checkbook.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Diamondbacks, who could play the Mets in the playoffs _
if the Mets join them in the playoffs _ signed free agents like
Randy Johnson, Todd Stottlemyre and Steve Finley. But they traded
for Luis Gonzalez, Tony Womack, Matt Mantei and Dan Plesac, not to
mention Matt Williams last year, and they plucked Omar Daal, Brian
Anderson and Hanley Frias in the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Bell was a free agent the Diamondbacks signed for their
first season. Asked when he thought people would begin saying
Arizona bought a championship, the second baseman said, ``They've
already said it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, he added: ``That may be the case; we went out and got some
players. But everybody talks like we signed 40 free agents. We
didn't. We made some good trades.''
</P>
<P>
   If Jerry Colangelo, the team's managing partner, sanctioned _
make that encouraged _ spending for free agents, the baseball
people, from General Manager Joe Garagiola Jr. to Manager Buck
Showalter, made shrewd personnel decisions. The key contribution
was made by Sandy Johnson, the baseball lifer who is the assistant
general manager.
</P>
<P>
   An executive of another club said Johnson was the force behind
the trades for Gonzalez, the NL leader in hits; Womack, the league
leader in stolen bases; and Mantei, the closer, without whom the
Diamondbacks would not be heading for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took prospects and traded them for players who could help
the Diamondbacks now,'' the executive said. ``He's about winning
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also pushed to keep Frias in the major leagues when the
young shortstop was having trouble keeping his batting average as
high as .170. Johnson knew the 23-year-old, from the Dominican
Republic and out of the Texas organization, would be certain to
blossom.
</P>
<P>
   A flower grows in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   When Andy Fox, the team's regular shortstop, was out from Aug.
28 through Sept. 18 with a rib injury, Frias filled in most of the
time and hit .396 in 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, Matt and Jay had to carry the load and it was
tough,'' Johnson said. ``This year it seems like everybody stepped
up and everybody stayed healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   A seven-game winning streak in the last week of May catapulted
the Diamondbacks into first place, where they remained through
June. The San Francisco Giants supplanted the upstart
southwesterners at the top of the division for the first three
weeks of July, when the Diamondbacks lost 12 of 18.
</P>
<P>
   But then Arizona reeled off a string of winning streaks, and 30
victories in 38 games. The Diamondbacks were not only back in
first, but they also had an 8{-game lead.
</P>
<P>
   During that stretch, the Diamondbacks, dissatisfied with the
offensive production of first baseman Travis Lee, summoned Erubiel
Durazo from the minors. The move has turned out to be as good as
all of the others. In less than 40 percent of the number of
at-bats, the 25-year-old Mexican has two more home runs than Lee
and half the runs batted in. Durazo, at .316, is also outhitting
Lee by 79 points.
</P>
<P>
   As a team, the Diamondbacks are one of the most well-rounded
crews in the league, ranking second in runs scored, possessing one
of three earned run averages under 4.00 and fielding one of the
three best defensive teams.
</P>
<P>
   Individually, Randy Johnson is No. 1 in ERA, strikeouts, innings
pitched and complete games, while Gonzalez leads in hits, Womack is
tops in stolen bases and Williams ranks third in RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Bell. At the age of 33, he has turned into a home
run hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``My year probably stands out more than anyone else's,'' Bell
said, by no means speaking immodestly. ``I don't think anyone
considers me, and I don't consider myself a home run hitter. It's
just kind of happened this year.''
</P>
<P>
   He attributed his unexpected power to his place in the lineup,
behind Womack and ahead of Gonzalez and Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Tony gets on first,'' Bell said, ``it puts a lot of
pressure on the pitchers to speed up their delivery home. Instead
of making a quality pitch, they leave the pitch out over the plate.
With Gonzo and Matt hitting behind me, it puts pressure on the
pitchers to throw strikes to me to try to get me out instead of
facing those guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is more shocked than I about what's happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks, on the other hand, have not shocked anybody.
They have just impressed everybody. They have gone from last place
with a 65-97 record, to a division championship with more than 90
victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put together a team that looked like it was going to be
competitive,'' Bell said. ``It has turned out to be everything you
want from a competitive team.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Let Them Count the Ways
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has always thrived on statistics, but computers are
responsible for escalating statistics to absurd levels. Latest
example:
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones of Atlanta, the Braves report, can become the
first player in history to hit .300, score 100 runs, drive in 100,
hit 40 home runs and 40 doubles, walk 100 times and steal 20 bases.
Why not throw in the one triple and the six sacrifice flies he has
and see where that places him?
</P>
<P>
   It recalls Mickey Mantle's reaction about 10 years ago to Jose
Canseco's feat of becoming the first player to have 40 home runs
and 40 stolen bases in the same season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had known it was going to be such a big deal,'' Mantle
remarked, ``I would have done it four or five times.''
</P>
<P>
   Boring and Flashy
</P>
<P>
   Robin Ventura, the Mets' third baseman, was talking about the
low-key, boring baseball personality he and his infield teammate,
John Olerud, possess. Another of their infield partners, Ventura
said, is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously,'' he said of Rey Ordonez, ``Rey is like any other
Latin shortstop. He's flashy and loud, the epitome of the Latin
shortstop. He has more of the flair and the energy that the rest of
us don't have.''
</P>
<P>
   The question was raised later about whether Ventura was guilty
of the kind of ethnic stereotyping that has put some sports people
in trouble. Ozzie Guillen of Atlanta, a veteran shortstop from
Venezuela, was asked what he thought. Not only wasn't he offended
by Ventura's remark, but he also confirmed Ventura's
characterization.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we stay in this game,'' Guillen said. ``I think
Latin shortstops, when they come up here, they have to do a little
extra. They don't have the power of Garciaparra or Jeter or Ripken.
When people go scout in Latin America, they're looking for flashy
shortstops. They're not looking for a power hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Guillen added, plays made by Ordonez and his
contemporaries, including himself, are overrated. ``Sometimes they
make plays look tougher than they are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then Guillen made a startling admission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather play like Robin Ventura and never make a mistake
like he does,'' Guillen said. ``We're going to make more mistakes
than him. Ordonez will make more mistakes than Robin because of the
way he plays. I don't think he can play different. He has to play
the way he plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Why do Latin American shortstops play the way they do?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think because the infields where they play growing up are
real bad,'' Guillen said. ``They got to be ready to catch the ball.
American kids have nice facilities. They're always playing at nice
fields. They have all the equipment. Their parents take them to the
ball game. We play on sandlots, on streets, in the middle of the
weeds, all kinds of rocks all over the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's why we have to be flashy, because we don't know
when the ball's going to take a bad hop.''
</P>
<P>
   The Search for Talent
</P>
<P>
   The Milwaukee Brewers, in desperate need of an infusion of
talent, puzzled some baseball executives by hiring Dean Taylor as
their general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a rules and contracts guy,'' an executive of another club
said. ``He's never been involved in player development or scouting.
He's going to have to put together a whole group for development
and scouting. They need someone who's aggressive in getting
talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor served as assistant general manager with the Braves under
John Schuerholz for nine years. He was the executive who in 1991
discovered a loophole in the rules governing post-season rosters
that has allowed teams to put an injured player on their 40-man
major league rosters, then substitute a healthy player for him and
use him in the post-season.
</P>
</TEXT>
