<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5895 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD26-COX     09-25 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield fighting for a legacy
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ With three heavyweight championships in his career
portfolio, Evander Holyfield believes his position in boxing
history is already solidified. But how? As a quality fighter who
beat an underwhelming cast of foes? Or as an all-time great who
conquered all challengers of his generation? Or somewhere in
between?
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield contends: ``I don't fight for history. I fight for my
love of the game.'' Yet, how he's remembered as a fighter matters
to him. A lot. And he knows what he does in his Nov. 13 rematch
with Lennox Lewis could go a long way toward solidifying his
status.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason he's so committed to overcoming the physical
issues of the first fight, which ended in a controversial draw
although Lewis controlled the bout in most observers' minds.
Holyfield complained of leg cramps and general lethargy. Now,
Holyfield is into a three-times-a-day training regimen since
shifting his workout headquarters from Atlanta to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   In the early morning, he jogs. He lifts weights in afternoons
and works with a ballet instructor on stretching in the evenings.
In two weeks, he'll add sparring to that mix. All the while, he's
on a diet emphasizing nutrition and balanced food groups. This with
an eye on the fight _ and his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing training right now that I'd usually complain
about,'' he said. ``But not this time. It has to be done to get
ready, to give myself every chance to jump into (Lewis') chest.''
</P>
<P>
   And to elevate his historical position. Talk to Holyfield about
it, and it's clear it's something he's given considerable thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just my opinion,'' Holyfield said. ``You look at
everybody in boxing who is called `great.' Look at their records
and then look at mine. Let's take Muhammad Ali. Ali was great. No
question. He was a three-time heavyweight champion. Well, Evander
did that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, who'll be 37 next month, rose from the bar stool
then. He grabbed the remote control and turned down the sound on
his projector screen television. His excitement was evident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you look at the tough guys Ali fought,'' he added.
``Well, there was Joe Fraizer, George Foreman, Sonny Liston. Those
were his biggest fights. Now, who did Evander fight? Well, there
was Mike Tyson twice, Riddick Bowe (three times), Michael Moorer
twice and Lennox Lewis _ all who were champions.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has yet to be beaten, but Holyfield considers that a
formality. ``He will get punished,'' he said of his British
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   But back to history. ``Ali traveled the world and touched and
inspired a lot of people,'' Holyfield went on. ``Well, Evander has
inspired a whole lot of people, too, around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he's inspired to fight because it's his passion and he's
mastered it. But he backed off from his July proclamation of four
more fights and going on a ``world tour'' promoting boxing before
one finale bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will leave the game because there's no one who can beat
me.... I've fought every guy who was good, every champion in the
'90s,'' he said. ``Who didn't I fight? Tyson was the champion from
'86 to '90. Buster Douglas beat Tyson. Well, I beat Buster Douglas.
I beat Bowe. I beat Michael Moorer. I beat Foreman. Next is Lewis.
Then who's left?''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield understands who paved the way for his career; he
reveres the past champions. ``Ali, Fraizer, Foreman, Floyd
Patterson set the ground work,'' he said. ``It would be wrong to
put my name with theirs. I learned from them. That _ and the modern
times _ have given me an advantage. I'm supposed to be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a better, easier path than Ali. There's no war for me
to contend with like he had. I learned from Joe Louis that you can
retire and have money.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield certainly will do that, whenever he quits. ``Even in
earnings,'' he said, ``no one has made more money in the game than
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is to know when to get out of the game. No need to
take an unneccessary chance for peanuts _ $10 million _ and fight
some young guy who might beat me. Not because he's better, but
because he's younger. I want to be remembered as I am, not as I
was. I don't want people to say I stayed too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of stuff I've done over the years that people
haven't looked at. I guess when I'm gone, they'll give me my due.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
