<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Orioles' streak comes too late
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   AL EAST
</P>
<P>
   Don't ask about Baltimore's recent 13-game winning streak.
Manager Ray Miller still is going to be fired after the season. Cal
Ripken is out with back surgery. The roster is still littered with
aging, used-up players.
</P>
<P>
   So why now? Right-hander Scott Erickson, who started 1-8, has
gone 14-3 since. Rookie Jason Johnson has five wins in a row, and
Sid Ponson could win 15 games. Two rookies, second baseman Jerry
Hairston and center fielder Eugene Kingsale, have brought life to
the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're having a lot more fun playing,'' pitcher Mike
Mussina said. ``We've mixed some youth in with veterans and we're
getting some better pitching.''...
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's Pat Hentgen reads in every town that the Blue Jays
will dump him this winter. ``I'd like to play my whole career
here,'' he said. ``I mean, I've been a Jay now for 14 years, and I
don't see how anyone in my shoes would like to keep reading it.
I've been a Blue Jay since I was 17.''
</P>
<P>
   AL CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove touchy on Yankees
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland has gone 10-22 against playoff candidates New York,
Texas and Boston. Manager Mike Hargrove, who has driven this club
harder than past editions, called a team meeting after a 9-4,
four-error drubbing by the Yankees _ to praise the team for the way
it ``had accomplished a lot, and for them to go out and have some
fun the rest of the way, and let's finish this up.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hargrove was touchy about losing seven of 10 to the Yankees.
Asked about the kind of message that sent to New York, he snapped,
``If I want to send a message to Joe Torre, I'll write him a
letter.''...
</P>
<P>
   Sign of the times in Kansas City: With Jermaine Dye (114),
rookie Carlos Beltran (104) and Mike Sweeney (101), the Royals have
three 100-RBI seasons for the first time in their history. They
also have no pitcher with a winning record on the active roster.
</P>
<P>
   AL WEST
</P>
<P>
   Hudson catches fire for A's
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland A's liked Tim Hudson enough in the 1997 draft that
they selected him in the sixth round out of Auburn. However, they
also liked three other pitchers enough to draft them ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   In two seasons, Hudson made it to Class AA, but he lost nine
games at Huntsville in '98 and wasn't among the 26 pitchers the A's
invited to spring camp. At 160 pounds, he did not look impressive,
and while he had good action on a splitter and slider, he needed
seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   On June 13, the same Tim Hudson won his first major-league game
and then reeled off 10 wins in his first 11 decisions. Without him,
the A's would not be a playoff contender. With him next season,
Oakland has another young contributor on what should be a dangerous
team in coming years....
</P>
<P>
   Former Toronto and Baltimore general manager Pat Gillick already
has had a clandestine ``informal'' interview for the Seattle
general manager spot. Ex-Yankees and Astros GM Bob Watson
interviews this week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
