<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fan-friendly Marlins owner
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   NL EAST
</P>
<P>
   Baseball let in a live wire when it approved the sale of the
Florida Marlins to John W. Henry. He is opinionated, he's rich, and
he has a heart. An episode at Pro Player Stadium during last week's
sparsely attended Montreal doubleheader proves the point.
</P>
<P>
   Ryne Richardson, a fan from Washington, was visiting Miami and
decided to take in the games Tuesday, one of a handful of fans
buying upper-deck general-admission seats, with maybe 1,000 people
in the stadium. Suddenly, an usher introduced Henry, who invited
the whole section to sit in some $110 seats behind home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the most down-to-earth guy, being a millionaire,''
Richardson said. ``The usher said that he was the owner. I thought
he was just joking with us.''...
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, Philadelphia manager Terry Francona said the
next 20 games, all against playoff contenders, would be a gauge of
the Phillies' competitiveness. The team promptly ripped off 17
losses against three wins.
</P>
<P>
   NL CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   Brewers consider managers
</P>
<P>
   Dean Taylor's next trick, after landing Milwaukee's general
manager job, is to heed his boss' father. Wendy Selig-Prieb,
Brewers president and daughter of commissioner Bud Selig, has some
pressure to hire a minority manager, because her father put out a
directive to all clubs to give serious consideration to minority
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   New York Yankees hitting instructor Chris Chambliss has been
reported as a primary candidate, and Atlanta hitting coach Don
Baylor's name also is circulating. Others drawing consideration are
Cincinnati coach Ken Griffey Sr., Philadelphia coach Hal McRae, San
Diego coach Davey Lopes and New York Yankees coach Willie
Randolph.... Houston is doing its best to avoid worrying about the
standings and on-charging Cincinnati. Outfielder Carl Everett said,
``I don't believe you should look back. Ask Lot's wife.''
</P>
<P>
   NL WEST
</P>
<P>
   Rockies might land Reds' Bell
</P>
<P>
   Colorado had identified Buddy Bell as a primary managerial
candidate, which will push Cincinnati to determine if it really
wants to keep him on as a director of player personnel. Bell is
viewed as the Reds' most logical choice to replace manager Jack
McKeon, who doesn't seem ready to retire but is haggling with
management over a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   New Rockies general manager Dan O'Dowd has raided Cleveland's
front office, where he once was an assistant GM. O'Dowd had hired
Bill Schmidt, the Indians' national cross-checker, as his new
scouting director and Cleveland scouting director Josh Byrnes as
his assistant general manager. Boyd Coffie, minor-league field
coordinator the last two years in Cleveland, has the same post with
the Rockies....
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield has advised the Dodgers not to trade away right
fielder Raul Mondesi, despite his demands to leave. ``If you give
Mondy some more positive influences in here, that will help,'' he
said. Sheffield's comments came the same day he missed batting
practice because he thought the Dodgers had an off-day.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
