<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Saving face after Shulock-Alvarez situation
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It will take time before the John Shulock-Wilson
Alvarez situation is forgotten. Alvarez, the Tampa Bay left-hander,
swears he wasn't trying to take Shulock's head off last week when
his misguided fastball blasted Shulock in the mask. The 20-year
umpire said cryptically, ``He's going to get his.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Anaheim on Monday, Alvarez was losing 7-1 when catcher
Mike DeFelice signaled for a fastball. DeFelice said later he
called for a breaking ball, but Alvarez threw a heater that hit
Shulock in the face.
</P>
<P>
   Shulock began ranting at Alvarez, so much that manager Larry
Rothschild pulled him. Shulock then began poking DeFelice in the
chest protector while venting during the pitching change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Wilson would try to hurt somebody,'' Rothschild
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have a way of evening out in this game,'' Shulock said,
``and one of these days somebody is going to hit a line drive off
the side of his head, and I'll be the first guy laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   Shulock was suspended by the league Friday for the final three
games his crew is to work this season and fined him an undisclosed
amount.
</P>
<P>
   RUSTY HURTING
</P>
<P>
   What the Texas Rangers had hoped would not happen has come to
pass. Outfielder Rusty Greer, struck near his left eye in the Sept.
13 with a thrown ball during batting practice, has failed in his
first attempts to return to action. Greer complained that he cannot
see the ball while in the field.
</P>
<P>
   After ophthamologists first had said that his eye would suffer
no lingering damage, they subsequently determined he had a bruised
retina. After sitting out a week, Greer lasted just four innings in
his return game before coming out. He has spent games watching from
the bullpen and trying to reacclimate himself, but doctors now have
no idea when he might return.
</P>
<P>
   BREAKING BARRY'S HEART
</P>
<P>
   Should the Arizona Diamondbacks clinch the NL West in San
Francisco this weekend, eliminating the Giants from postseason
contention, left fielder Barry Bonds will have witnessed seven
clinchings by his opponents. ``I don't want to be on the field,''
he says. ``I've seen enough of that.'' A recap of Barry's
elimination games:
</P>
<P>
   Season_ Team_ Opponent_ Score_ Comment
</P>
<P>
   1990PittsburghCincinnati2-1Reds clinch NLCS in six; Bonds hits
.167
</P>
<P>
   1991PittsburghAtlanta4-0 Up 2-3, Bucs lose NLCS; Bonds hits .148
</P>
<P>
   1992PittsburghAtlanta3-2Bonds can't throw out plodding Sid Bream
</P>
<P>
   1995San FranciscoColorado10-9Rockies clinch wild card in last
weekend
</P>
<P>
   1997San FranciscoFlorida 6-2Dumped by expansion team in division
series
</P>
<P>
   1998San Francisco Chicago5-3SF loses wild-card tie-breaker;
Bonds 0-4
</P>
<P>
   1999San Francisco Chicago11-3D'backs clinch West with week to
spare
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
