<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-TRAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TESTING TIME ON THE TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Sept. 26:
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a week in the presidential campaign, and although
skeptics might say that the news has been dominated by money and
the horse race, we find encouragement in the vibrant
unpredictability of the entire scene. Not only are voters learning
a lot about the candidates, the candidates themselves are being put
to school on the hard realities of running.
</P>
<P>
   For no one have the lessons been ruder than for Vice President
Al Gore. Like former Vice President Walter Mondale in 1984, he is
beginning to learn the downside of an entitlement strategy. There
is something in grass-roots Democrats that rebels against
nomination by pre-emption.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Bill Bradley is reaping an outsized benefit as the
only name Democrat willing to play against what looked like a
stacked deck. Bradley capped the week by tightening the money race
and by forcing the Gore campaign to send President Clinton to rally
the Democratic National Committee. Bradley also got endorsements
from Rep. Jerrold Nadler and Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, both of
New York, who celebrated the event by hurling the dread ``can't
win'' label at Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But an insurgency campaign like Bradley's has risks that will
come more fully into play in the weeks ahead. He has his own
charisma gap, and Gore, for all his stiffness, is extremely
dangerous in one-on-one debate. Also, by trying to pass Gore on the
left, Bradley risks depiction as a panderer on the Old Democrat
model. As Al Hunt showed in a Wall Street Journal column last week,
both the press and politicians will be looking hard at such Bradley
cave-ins as his endorsement of the ethanol tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the bottom line for the Democrats is a surprising one. In
New Hampshire, New York and just possibly across the nation, the
party is preparing for a highly competitive two-way race rather
than a simple coronation of Gore. Right now, Bradley has the hotter
hand. The vice president, for his part, must repair his gasping
organization and then confront a much stronger opponent than he or
anyone else expected.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, things seem almost sedate among Republicans, and
the policy debate on that side is more fully developed. Gov. George
Bush of Texas tried to move up the substance ladder with a
workmanlike speech on national security. He criticized the
``unfocused deployments'' of the Clinton administration, but failed
to answer fully a question that dominated his father's term, which
is when and where to intervene in foreign conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain is testing whether a campaign driven by
reformist principles rather than ideology can prevail in the modern
GOP. Steve Forbes continues to illustrate that while money is not
everything, it is the one thing that is making Iowa competitive.
After massive expenditures, he is in second place there, polling 16
percent to Bush's 38.
</P>
<P>
   Even a two-ring circus needs a sideshow, and that brings us to
Pat Buchanan and Ross Perot. Perot has been worried that
Minnesota's wrestling governor, Jesse Ventura, was about to take
over the Party of Ross. So Perot's emissaries have been trying to
clear the way for the badly tarnished Buchanan to get the Reform
Party nomination. This would, of course, change the party ethos
from populist protest to nativist rage. It would also provide
Buchanan a chance to play out his Republican intramural class
grievances against yet another George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Our main point here is that one should not be taken in by the
conventional wisdom that campaigns do not matter, that issues do
not get discussed and that citizens do not pay attention. Attention
is being paid, in large part because Americans have before them a
cracking good campaign that will shape the political landscape of
the first decade of the new millennium. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
