<SLUG> BC-FLOODWOES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dirty drinking water drives fear in N.C.
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TARBORO, N.C. _ Simmering for years, the witch's brew was
finally unleashed.
</P>
<P>
   All it took was 30 inches of rain over two weeks in flood-prone
areas of the state, overflowing lagoons of hog waste, 2 million
dead chickens, unearthed caskets, spilled sewage, junked
Oldsmobiles and more than 30,000 drowned pigs.
</P>
<P>
   On their way to the sea, Hurricane Floyd's toxic flood waters
washed through Tarboro's water treatment plant and shut it down.
The taps might not flow clean again for a month.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Dozier won't even touch a cup of coffee unless he knows
where the water came from.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're scared,'' said the 32-year-old Tarboro parks worker,
who has followed the city's advice and had a tetanus shot. ``Even
when they do get clean water, people are going to think it's
contaminated. I'm scared myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Unprecedented flooding has damaged more than 7,000 homes. The
deluge polluted more than 200 sewage treatment plants and nearly
400,000 private wells. Coastal fisheries could continue to be
fouled well into the next year. Agricultural losses may exceed $1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, environmentalists say, unchecked development in
North Carolina's river basins from Raleigh east to New Bern helped
lead to the worst natural disaster in state history.
</P>
<P>
   For generations, farmers have drained wetlands of eastern North
Carolina and turned them into valuable fields of hogs, chickens,
turkeys, tobacco and cotton. Developers transformed abandoned
farmland into industrial parks, golf courses and subdivisions.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Raleigh, construction in places like Crabtree Valley,
something like the Buckhead of North Carolina, dumped sediment in
the Neuse River, which winds more than 230 miles to the Pamlico
Sound.
</P>
<P>
   With every ditch dug, every Wal-Mart parking lot paved, the flow
of rainwater and storm runoff gained a new and easy path to the
river's edge. Nothing could stop it from taking with it animal
waste, farm pesticides or the oil leaking from neighborhood cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rainfall may be an act of God,'' said Marion Smith, executive
director of the Neuse River Foundation, an environmental watchdog
group in New Bern. ``But God doesn't drain the wetlands and God
doesn't build in the flood plain.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the boom in eastern North Carolina comes from
agriculture, a staple of the state's economy, especially east of
Interstate 95. The state leads the nation in production of turkeys
and flue-cured tobacco. It ranks No. 2 in hogs, behind Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   For years, hog farming has angered environmentalists, fearful
that waste escaping from lagoons and being sprayed on fields
created ecological dynamite. The nutrients deplete oxygen, kill
fish in rivers and streams and render drinking water foul and even
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   State lawmakers are certain to examine how well hog lagoons
fared during Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   But Marc Basnight, president pro tem of the North Carolina
Senate, said the environmental review will encompass general
planning, not just one industry. Everyone may need to move out of
flood plains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be the kind of review you have in San Francisco after
an earthquake. Do you build back or do you not?'' said Basnight, a
Democrat from Dare County on the Outer Banks. ``We will look at all
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Goldsboro, the barrage of environmental complaints infuriates
hog farmer Bob Ivey.
</P>
<P>
   The Neuse River flooded four or five of Ivey's hog lagoons. He
said they worked to specification, keeping their contents until the
Neuse spilled in.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way you can engineer and plan for what we've been
through,'' Ivey said.
</P>
<P>
   National Guard trucks have helped the 45-year-old farmer feed
hogs and move them to higher ground. Upstream and downstream,
municipal sewer plants have failed. His home is flooded. Friends
have drowned.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you died from dadgum hog manure, I'd have died a long time
ago,'' Ivey said. ``Would you want to be exposed to dadgum manure
or dadgum exposed to water people urinated in and defecated in?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, what do you want us to do? We've had back-to-back
hurricanes, and we're trying to save what we've got. They want to
try and shut me down when everyone else around me is flooded.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Floyd, even modest rains had caused lagoon breaches in
the eastern third of the state. In the early 1990s, a blue-ribbon
panel was appointed to review hog waste disposal. Hog farmers
traditionally dig earthen pits to create lagoons to contain sewage
and other waste. Waste from the lagoons is then sometimes sprayed
on croplands as fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   One recommendation adopted by the state several years ago was
that hog farmers maintain a minimum distance between the top of the
lagoon and the soil level in an effort to prevent the lagoons from
overflowing.
</P>
<P>
   But the report took into account only the type of flooding that
could occur several times in a century, said atmospheric scientist
John Sigmon, a gentleman farmer appointed to the panel. Floyd's
rains caused flooding that occurs once every 500 years, according
to federal hydrologists.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there were not federal and state programs to help rebuild,
you might solve the problem,'' Sigmon said. ``Land use has changed.
There are more parking lots, more houses, more shopping centers
that would have been flooded land. If this same thing would have
happened 75 years ago, you might not even have known about it.''
</P>
<P>
   After fish kills on the Neuse River and flooding caused by
Hurricane Fran in 1996, the General Assembly forbade new swine
operations in the state. Last session, it extended the moratorium
through July 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jim Hunt said his administration would work to phase out
the lagoons, though there's no timetable. Because of North
Carolina's hog farm woes, Georgia environmental authorities this
year imposed strict new rules for controlling pollution from large
hog operations in the Peach State. Similar rules for poultry farms
and other livestock operations in Georgia are being crafted.
</P>
<P>
   For now, North Carolina officials are concentrating on animal
disposal. Three incinerators heated to 3,000 degrees _ capable of
burning 4,000 pounds an hour _ are roaring in hog country. For dead
poultry, front-end loaders are scooping up the birds and composting
them with wood chips and dry waste. Cattle and horses will be
buried.
</P>
<P>
   There's little anyone can do about the pollution. Ultimately,
Mother Nature will flush the waste through the Pamlico Sound and
into the Atlantic. No one's going to skim sewage or catch diesel
fuel or pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once it's out of the barn, it's gone. There's nothing you can
do,'' said Doug Lair, chief of the Emergency Response Branch of the
federal Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   If consumed, the toxic cocktail could cause untold health
problems. Coliform bacteria are in the water and could cause fever,
diarrhea, cramps and vomiting. The vast flood waters form an ideal
habitat for mosquitoes that may carry equine encephalitis, a rare
but sometimes deadly disease. Planes will spray 3 million acres
with malathion and other pesticides to keep the insect population
down. Officials recommend residents in flooded areas boil drinking
water three to five minutes before use.
</P>
<P>
   ``You name it and you could probably catch it if you drink the
water,'' said Dr. John Hamilton, chief of the infectious diseases
department at Duke University Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Initial assessments of the environmental damage won't be ready
until the water recedes more this week. Rivers still are cresting,
and some won't fall significantly for a few days. The damage is
more widespread than the flooding that consumed southwest Georgia
in 1994, when Tropical Storm Alberto lingered for five days near
Albany.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only when the water goes down can we get an idea of the scope
of the problem and assess the real environmental problem,'' Lair
said.
</P>
<P>
   Down the street from Tarboro High School, which is sheltering
3,000 stranded people, the 63-room Comfort Inn struggles to stay
open without running water _ just like the other buildings in town.
McDonald's is closed. So are Burger King and Pizza Hut. The Dairy
Queen made a go of it before inspectors shut it down.
</P>
<P>
   Comfort Inn guests flush their toilets by dumping garbage cans
of water they've scooped from the swimming pool. A handwritten
warning is taped to the ice machine: ``Do not use ice for drink or
eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Guest Martha Plemmer heats her water in the coffee maker and
pours it in the sink. Then she dabs that on her and finishes with
alcohol to take a bath. ``It's like that through the whole town,''
said Plemmer, an evacuee from nearby Princeville, where coffins are
floating, house tops poke through the water and her 20 cats may
have drowned.
</P>
<P>
   There are tobacco fields, cotton crops, chicken coops and hog
lagoons all around Tarboro. Like many places in the South, new
industry is blending with the rural charm. A distribution center
for the QVC shopping network is coming. A Wal-Mart Super Center is
planned.
</P>
<P>
   Not far from it all is Frances Liverman's On the Square
restaurant downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Country roads went forever to nowhere when Liverman was a kid.
But the hamlets and town now are strung together like pearls:
Nashville, Rocky Mount, Tarboro, Wilson, Greenville. ``It tells me
things are changing when towns are growing together,'' said
Liverman, 39.
</P>
<P>
   Liverman is like thousands in the flooded region. There's water,
water everywhere but only the mop can drink.
</P>
<P>
   She treats water like the plague. She wears rubber boots and
powder blue Rubbermaid gloves as she scrubs her plank floor with
water and Murphy's Oil Soap. Last weekend, the flood creeped into
her brick building and rose 6 inches, leaving a dingy brown mark on
a display case.
</P>
<P>
   Without running water, the Health Department won't let her open.
She normally serves sandwiches to the courthouse employees who are
regulars. At the curb of her shop, a narrow two-story brick
building with a striped, sky-blue awning, flooded supplies sit in a
trash heap. Ruffles potato chips, lemons, Dill's French dressing,
Styrofoam cups.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors sweep out their shops. Live oaks line the sidewalks.
The rumble of portable generators fills the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just worries me that there's so much in the water,''
Liverman said. ``When the water finally goes down, you don't know
what you're going to find.''
</P>
<P>
   She'll be closed at least two weeks, maybe longer. How she'll
make a living, she doesn't know. Inspectors will be back to tell
her how to disinfect the store.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're putting our lives in their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Charles Seabrook contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
