<HEADLINE>
OK, CLASS, OPEN YOUR BOOKBAGS AND DIG IN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The reading season has just opened, and here's your fall list.
Pop quizzes to come.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Zimbalist, a Smith College economist (yes, even a coach
there asked him to be lenient with an athlete), locates the end of
intercollegiate sports innocence in 1852 when a railroad offered
``lavish prizes'' and ``unlimited alcohol'' to lure Harvard and
Yale rowers to a race on a New Hampshire lake. The lures have
worked ever since, although most of the prizes seem to be going to
coaches and schools. Nothing is as heartbreaking as the $8 million
in post-season bowl revenue Notre Dame missed out on when a kicker
missed an extra point.
</P>
<P>
   In remarkably clear and clear-eyed prose (even his charts are
readable), Zimbalist follows the money instead of the ball in the
emotion-charged world of college sports. ``Unpaid Professionals''
(Princeton University Press) uses this basic starting point _ ``No
other industry in the United States manages not to pay its
principal producers a wage or salary'' _ to survey the compromised
standards of academia and suggest reforms, which include outright
professionalization of teams. One provocative innovation would be
requiring the National Basketball Association and the National
Football League to support their college ``minor leagues''
financially.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbalist will be joining such reformers as Professor William C.
Dowling, architect of the Rutgers 1000 campaign _ which is devoted
to de-emphasizing sports at the university _ and Professor Murray
Sperber of Indiana at an extraordinary conference at Drake
University in Des Moines on Oct. 21 and 22 ``for those who are fed
up with the corruption, exploitation and hypocrisy in collegiate
athletics and are willing to work to end it.'' Created by Professor
Jon Ericson, the gathering is unusual in that it not only starts
with the consensus that the system is wrong, but that the ultimate
responsibility to fix it is in the shaky hands of a faculty that
either ignores sports or is besotted by it.
</P>
<P>
   One wrinkle in the student-athlete system is the role of the
traditionally black colleges, before and after integration, in
creating leadership. Did anyone think all their coaches and
quarterbacks were white? As African-American institutions, those
colleges were far more important than the relentlessly
sentimentalized Negro baseball leagues. And the colleges still
exist and have influence. ``Never Before, Never Again,'' (St.
Martin's Press, $24.95) is the autobiography of Coach Eddie
Robinson of Grambling, written with Richard Lapchick, the founder
of the Center for the Study of Sport in Society. Since both men are
determinedly friendly (George Steinbrenner wrote the foreword,
Jesse Jackson the afterword), the criticisms are muted, but the
sense of place and history, and ``the winningest'' football coach's
own story are happily preserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside Sports,'' edited by Jay Coakley and Peter Donnelly
(Routledge), is a basic sociology text heavy on ethnographic
methodology. But there is enough truth to the title to make this
interesting to the general reader.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Saltzman Chafetz and Joseph A. Kotarba follow Little
League mothers ``doing gender,'' working harder at fulfilling their
stereotypes than the ``son gods'' they are servicing. Todd Crosset
describes the almost familial relationship between female pro
golfers and their fans.
</P>
<P>
   Beckey Beal reports on the subversive dogmas of skateboarders;
they believe they are combating mainstream competition with
cooperation. Alan M. Klein contributes a timely piece on the North
American socialization of Dominican baseball players, and Douglas
E. Foley goes to South Texas to study Friday night rites, including
the ``ritual of reversal'' called ``powderpuff football'' in which
the cheerleaders don pads and try to play seriously and the players
don drag and mock women. This experience leads Foley to return to
Iowa after more than 40 years and interview the Indian
``hellraiser'' who starred on his own high school team.
</P>
<P>
   A hockey wife, writing under a pseudonym to protect her
husband's career, and Bette McKenzie, a hockey daughter and former
football wife, write revealingly about the culture of celebrity
sports families. Each deserves a book of her own.
</P>
<P>
   The coffee-table gift book on the list is ``Glory'' (William
Morrow, $45), a collection of Richard Corman's startling
photographs in which the obvious subjects _ Muhammad Ali, Cal
Ripken Jr., Michael Jordan, dancers, Special Olympians _ seem to be
moving in previously unseen and revealing ways.
</P>
<P>
   For pure fun and apocalyptic nightmares, there is ``Roller Derby
to Roller Jam: The Authorized Story of an Unauthorized Sport'' by
Keith Coppage (Squarebooks, $19.95), as much promo as history of an
exhibition that is trying to reinvent itself on the model of pro
wrestling, with characters and story lines. I always liked roller
derby because the sex and violence was right up front.
</P>
<P>
   There were mom-and-son combos (the ``diabetic housewife,''
Josephine Bogash, and Billy, stars of the '30s and '40s) and
matinee idols (Charlie O'Connell and Joan Weston) and an inspired
silliness that seemed only a putsch away from the fascist image of
Rollerball. Now it's all back, cable ready, and a good, small,
accessible, metaphorical subject for some of those apprentice
sports sociologists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
