<HEADER>
A5921 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-COLO-JONBENET-CASE-34     09-25 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-JONBENET-CASE-340&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND JURY IN RAMSEY CASE RECONVENES, AT LEAST FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The grand jury investigating the killing of JonBenet
Ramsey reconvened in Boulder Thursday after a four-month hiatus.
But with prosecutors having made no request to finance the panel
after its term expires in less than a month, its future and that of
the investigation are unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Financing will expire on Oct. 20 for the grand jury, which has
been investigating the killing of JonBenet, a 6-year-old beauty
queen, off and on for a year.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney's office has not made a request for
additional financing, and a Boulder County commissioner said last
week that if such a request were made, the grand jury and the
county's district attorney, Alex M. Hunter, would have to produce
``compelling reasons'' to justify spending more money on the
inquiry, which has cost Boulder and Boulder County more than
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the grand jury's term expiring in October is a
natural point of closure,'' said Paul Danish, one of three members
of the Boulder County Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The death of JonBenet has raised suspicions and criticism about
her parents, John and Patsy Ramsey, the police and prosecutors. The
girl's strangled body was found in her family's Boulder home on
Dec. 26, 1996, after her parents reported that she was missing and
that they had found a ransom note.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter impaneled the grand jury after critics and some police
officers said he was dragging his feet on the case. But the
investigation has been impeded by what many have called sloppy
police work.
</P>
<P>
   Despite skepticism about the investigation, Henry C. Lee, a
prominent forensic expert who has worked on the case and who is now
the head of the Connecticut Department of Public Safety, said the
inquiry could go on with or without the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't really set the deadline to solve the case,'' Lee
said in an interview on the Fox Network. He noted that there is no
statute of limitations on murder. Lee, who joined the case in 1997,
met with Hunter last week in Denver.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The grand jury has heard from Boulder police detectives and
officers, handwriting analysts and JonBenet's brother, Burke. The
parents have not been called to testify, but their videotaped
remarks are thought to have been shown.
</P>
<P>
   Although police have said the parents are under an ``umbrella of
suspicion,'' the Ramseys, who now live in Atlanta with Burke, have
maintained their innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Because of grand jury secrecy, it is not known whether the
jurors took the summer off to wait for more evidence or test
results, or whether they will hear more testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter has said he will soon impanel a new grand jury, to comply
with a state law that requires an active panel at all times. The
new grand jury would convene after Oct. 20, when the current grand
jury is scheduled to complete its work, he said. The new grand jury
will probably deal with other matters, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under Colorado law, the grand jurors can indict a suspect in the
killing, agree they have not reached a conclusion, or decline to
indict someone, in which case they can file a report on their
findings. But any such report would probably be sealed.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Silverman, a Denver lawyer who is not involved in the
case, said of such a report, ``If it's released to the public it
could be available to the killer and presumably compromise chances
that person is brought to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Silverman is among many critics who say that a steady flow of
leaked information and crucial errors made in the early hours of
the investigation may have jeopardized chances of solving the
killing.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, a former Boulder police detective, Linda Arndt,
appeared on national television and said that she knew who the
killer was, although she did not name anyone. Ms. Arndt, who was
the first detective on the scene the day JonBenet's body was found
and whose work in the case has been widely criticized, is suing
former Chief Tom Koby of the Boulder police and the City of Boulder
over how she was treated in the aftermath of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting to hear Linda Arndt say she knows with
certainty who killed JonBenet, also say she is certain there will
be no indictment,'' Silverman said. Ms. Arndt testified before the
grand jury several months ago. ``She had a chance to see and hear
from the grand jury, and she came to that conclusion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
