<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURIES TO KEY PLAYERS LEAD TO POOR STARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, Dan Reeves, the Atlanta Falcons' coach, made a
comment that not only made him look slightly foolish but also
angered some of his players. Reeves suggested, on the day after
running back Jamal Anderson suffered a torn anterior cruciate
ligament in his knee, ending his season, that the injury occurred
because of Anderson's two-week contract holdout during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was furious with Reeves' words. His holdout was
relatively short, and he still participated in five weeks of
training camp and played in several preseason games. Players have
hurt their hamstrings because of holdouts. They do not tear up
their knees because of them.
</P>
<P>
   While Reeves' comment was absent-minded and insulting to his
star player, it might have been made out of frustration. He has a
lot of company; this season has been frustrating to many teams.
Injuries, parity and the rise of young stars have turned the
National Football League upside down.
</P>
<P>
   Last season's final four are a combined 1-7 going into Sunday's
games _ the Jets (0-2), Denver (0-2), Atlanta (0-2) and Minnesota
(1-1). That is the worst combined start by a previous final four
since the 1970 merger between the American Football League and the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries have devastated the defending division champions. The
Jets were heavy Super Bowl favorites until they lost quarterback
Vinny Testaverde to a ruptured Achilles' tendon and wide receiver
Wayne Chrebet to a broken foot. The Falcons are forced to play
without Anderson, and quarterback Chris Chandler missed last week's
game with a hamstring injury.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his denials, Terrell Davis, the Denver Broncos' running
back, is hurting because of the constant pounding he is taking,
since teams are focusing on stopping him since there is no John
Elway to burn them deep. Davis may not be seriously hurt, but after
the opening-season loss to the Miami Dolphins, he had a large
bruise on the back of his neck.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings are the only final-four team without any of their
star players spending extra time in the trainer's room. But they
have their problems. Last season Minnesota averaged 34.8 points a
game. This season, they have scored a total of 34 points.
</P>
<P>
   There is no conspiracy theory about why there are a high number
of injuries to key players. It is simply bad luck. Ernie Accorsi,
the general manager of the Giants, a smart football man and
football historian, recalled one season in the early 1970s when
O.J. Simpson, Joe Namath and Gale Sayers, the biggest stars at the
time, were all seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a pretty wild situation with all the injuries so far to
key players,'' Accorsi said, ``but it is not unusual. It has
happened before.''
</P>
<P>
   What may be unusual is that the injuries are running deep, not
just to the stars, but across every position and every team. In
week two, eight backup running backs saw significant time because
of injuries to starters, including James Stewart from Jacksonville,
who had 124 yards rushing and two touchdowns against Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   And four backup quarterbacks played, including two former Jets,
Glenn Foley for Seattle and Neil O'Donnell for Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   The injuries have been a reason why teams such as the Detroit
Lions are 2-0. But the rise of young stars have also fueled the
strong starts in Detroit, Washington and Indianapolis. Stephen
Davis, the Redskins running back who was once better known for how
his teammate Michael Westbrook pummeled him during a fight in
practice, is playing well. Lions quarterback Charlie Batch is
making people forget about Barry Sanders. For the Colts, wide
receiver Marvin Harrison and running back Edgerrin James are top
players.
</P>
<P>
   As for parity, there are two ways to look at why there is no
dominant team. One, there is mediocre football being played. Two,
there will be a number of exciting races down the stretch. Late in
the season, it is not unrealistic to think that many teams in the
more competitive divisions will have similar records, fighting for
a division title and playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   DEION SANDERS TO RETURN
</P>
<P>
   The most famous toe in football will be on the field next week.
Dallas cornerback Deion Sanders, who had toe surgery during the off
season, is scheduled to go against the Arizona Cardinals on Oct. 3.
Sanders wants to play because he feels the Cardinals do not respect
the aging Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders has another reason to return. He earns a $1.5 million
bonus if he plays in 70 percent of the defensive plays and makes
the Pro Bowl team. That's a pretty good incentive.
</P>
<P>
   PROGRESS IN HIRING BLACKS
</P>
<P>
   With only three black head coaches in the NFL, the league
obviously has a long way to go before the playing field is level
for blacks trying to break into head-coaching positions. But
Sunday's Minnesota-Green Bay game shows that progress is being
made.
</P>
<P>
   The game features eight blacks, four on each team, in
high-ranking coaching or front-office positions. This season, Green
Bay became the first team in league history with a black head coach
(Ray Rhodes) and two black coordinators (Sherman Lewis on offense
and Emmitt Thomas on defense). In the Packers' front office, Reggie
McKenzie is the club's director of pro personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Black coaches and personnel men have said for years that what it
takes to get more blacks in key positions is to have more
open-minded people doing the hiring. Race has never been a factor
with Ron Wolf, the Green Bay general manager.
</P>
<P>
   In Minnesota, in addition to Coach Dennis Green, who is also the
vice president of football operations, there are three blacks in
key positions: Ray Sherman, the offensive coordinator; Alex Wood,
the quarterbacks coach, and Frank Gilliam, the vice president of
player personnel.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   In Green Bay there is concern about the injured thumb of
quarterback Brett Favre. How much it is hurting will not be truly
known until he throws the ball under game conditions. ... The
Dolphins love their newly-acquired wide receiver Tony Martin, who
spreads the field and is the first true deep threat the team has
had in years. ... After hearing Falcons cornerback Ray Buchanan
accuse him of receiving preferential treatment from the officials,
Vikings wide receiver Randy Moss replied: ``If they're not scared
to put you out there one-on-one, then get on out there. That just
shows you that any guy with a lot of talk needs a lot of safety
help over the top.'' ... Barry Sanders remains resigned to the fact
that he will never again play for the Lions. One thing about
Sanders: He is stubborn. ... The San Diego Chargers' victory over
Cincinnati last Sunday was impressive. About 20 players had the
flu, and some members of the coaching staff vomited on the sideline
during the game. Still, San Diego committed no turnovers and forced
five.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 1548EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
