<SLUG> BC-LA-POLICE-CORRUPT-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAIMS OF POLICE CORRUPTION FUEL CRITICISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A former police officer's account of abuses of
power in a Los Angeles Police Department station house has shaken
the city's political establishment, renewed calls for increased
civilian oversight of the agency and halted the enforcement of a
law promoted as a strong antidote to gang crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last few days we have seen a dark shadow cast over
the Los Angeles Police Department,'' Mayor Richard J. Riordan said
at a Police Academy graduation ceremony on Thursday. ``The news is
grim. The department's reputation is being questioned. The
integrity of our officers is in doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   The department has suspended or fired 13 officers based on
information from former Officer Rafael A. Perez, who pleaded guilty
this month to stealing eight pounds of cocaine from an evidence
locker. Perez agreed to tell what he knew in exchange for a lighter
sentence in the cocaine case and immunity for his confession on
another matter. He told investigators that he and his partner shot
an unarmed gang member, Javier Francisco Ovando, and planted a gun
on him. He also said that another incident, in which two suspects
were shot and one died, was ``dirty,''meaning the police may have
concealed what actually happened.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a judge suspended enforcement of an injunction that
bars individual members of the 18th Street gang, to which Ovando
belonged, from associating with each other. The suspension was
based on the belief that declarations filed by officers in support
of the injunction may have been perjured.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights groups, lawyers and one prominent state politician
have criticized the Police Department's handling of the case and
expressed doubt that the department could effectively settle its
own problems.
</P>
<P>
   The local chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union called
for the appointment of a special prosecutor to handle corruption
prosecutions and the creation of an independent panel to conduct a
department-wide inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We strongly believe that an internal police mechanism,
although warranted in this case, is wholly inadequate to look into
a scandal of this magnitude,'' said Elizabeth Schroeder, a lawyer
for the ACLU.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Bernard C. Parks has said he will convene an
investigative team of 60 command officers to examine the way the
department handles shootings involving officers and allegations of
corruption and how well officers are supervised, among other
things.
</P>
<P>
   The department has rejected criticism of its handling of the
case, noting that it was the department's original investigation of
Perez that led to his prosecution and ultimately to his giving
details of abuse of power among his peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chief has stated that we're doing everything in our power,
and we're the ones that initiated this investigation 17 months
ago,'' said Sgt. John Pasquariello, a department spokesman. ``We
can do the job thoroughly and efficiently, and we're not going to
leave any stone unturned.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But in a direct challenge to the chief's authority, the city
attorney's office published an opinion last week stating that the
appointed civilian Police Commission, not the chief, is the head of
the Police Department. That reverses decades of practice in which
the chief has exerted complete control over police matters.
</P>
<P>
   The opinion also gave broad authority to the department's
inspector general, a public watchdog position created in the wake
of the 1991 police beating of Rodney King, allowing him access to
any department document he seeks. The issue has been the subject of
debate for the last year, leading to the resignation of the
previous inspector general. Parks opposed that requirement, and in
recent weeks the new inspector general, Jeffrey Eglash, has
expressed concern that his access will be blocked.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Tom Hayden, a Democrat, has criticized the department
for keeping Ovando in protective custody when he will likely file a
multimillion-dollar lawsuit against the department and the city.
``It's a very troubling conflict of interest because he will be a
potential plaintiff against the department that is now debriefing
him, caring for him, housing him, feeding him,'' Hayden said in an
interview. The department said Ovando was free to go but had chosen
to stay.
</P>
<P>
   And the district attorney has been criticized by the County
Board of Supervisors for closing the ``roll-out'' unit of
prosecutors who went to the scene of police shootings to
investigate. Gil Garcetti, the district attorney, told the
supervisors that budget constraints forced him to choose between
the roll-out team and other law enforcement basics.
</P>
<P>
   The case has also sparked renewed interest in the report that a
suspect, Ismael Jimenez, was beaten in the Rampart station house in
February 1998 until he vomited blood. The officer accused in the
beating, Brian Hewitt, was fired after an internal affairs
investigation. Investigators presented the case to the district
attorney's office for prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The report included physical evidence from the interview room
carpet, analysis of blood spatter patterns on a wall and statements
from a doctor saying that Jimenez's injuries were consistent with
choking. The district attorney's office declined to prosecute the
case, citing Jimenez's varying accounts of the incident. Federal
officials are now said to be looking at the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
