<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROKEN DREAMS (AND PUTTERS) ARE DISPERSED AMID THE PRESSURE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ During his 1987 Ryder Cup singles match, Ben
Crenshaw walked over to Jack Nicklaus, the American captain, and
confessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I broke my putter,'' Crenshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You broke what?'' Nicklaus replied.
</P>
<P>
   In his anger at falling behind Eamonn Darcy of Europe, the 1984
Masters champion had slammed his putter into the acorn-strewn
ground as he stomped off the sixth green at Muirfield Village in
Ohio. For golf's best putter, it was as if Michelangelo had broken
his only brush while painting the ceiling of the Sistine Chapel, as
if Mozart had smashed his only piano. But that's what Ryder Cup
pressure can do.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of that match Crenshaw putted with his 1-iron or
with the blade of his sand wedge, and he putted well. But he lost,
1 up. So did the U.S. team, 15-13.
</P>
<P>
   In breaking his putter, Crenshaw, now the American captain here
at The Country Club, had succumbed to pressure unlike that in any
other golf event. Especially in Sunday's 12 singles matches when
it's mano a mano.
</P>
<P>
   And especially the pressure on the 12 U.S. golfers to justify
their reputations as the world's best. You can be sure that
Crenshaw will tell his golfers not to slam their putters.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 singles pairings emerge from a blind draw. Crenshaw will
submit his list of 12 golfers, in order.
</P>
<P>
   Mark James, the European captain, will submit his list of 12
golfers, in order.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, there's no strategy involved in the pairings, but there
should be. It would be more interesting if the captains were to
match the golfers as if playing gin rummy. Let one captain name a
golfer, then the other captain names his selection. It would even
add to the pressure that makes the Ryder Cup so special.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, pressure. It's something golfers seldom talk about _ except
at the Ryder Cup, because they feel it more there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt a little bit of pressure out there,'' Davis Love III
acknowledged Friday, ``that I don't normally feel.''
</P>
<P>
   That was after Love's alternate-shot morning match when his
birdie putt on the 17th hole salvaged what would be one-half point.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Ryder Cup, the pressure is different than it is even
at, say, the U.S. Open or the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   In those two major championships, a golfer is out there on his
own. If he doesn't win, he lets himself down. If he finishes second
or third, he still has earned substantial prize money.
</P>
<P>
   But with a loss at the Ryder Cup, a golfer lets down his
teammates and, in a sense, his country. And the pressure for the
Europeans is the same as it is for the Americans, as Bernhard
Langer learned at Kiawah Island, S.C., in 1991's last singles
match.
</P>
<P>
   Langer needed to hole a 6-foot putt on the 18th green to retain
the cup for Europe, but when his ball slid to the right, the United
States won. In 1995 at Oak Hill outside Rochester, N.Y., Curtis
Strange was 2 up on Nick Faldo on the 16th tee, but he bogeyed the
last three holes as Faldo holed a 6-foot par putt on the 18th to
win, 1 up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was shaking,'' Faldo said later, ``except the
putter.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time the United States won the cup, in 1993 at The
Belfrey in England, the oldest American golfer, 51-year-old Raymond
Floyd, won a critical singles, 2 up, over Jose Maria Olazabal of
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Tom Kite had the best American singles record,
5-0 with two halved matches.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Snead was 6-1, Lee Trevino and Billy Casper each were 6-2-2,
Arnold Palmer 6-3-2, Gene Littler 5-2-3. Among the Europeans, Peter
Oosterhuis, now a television golf announcer, was 6-2-1, Faldo
6-4-1, Langer 3-3, Tony Jacklin 2-8-1.
</P>
<P>
   Jacklin's halved match developed in 1969 at Royal Birkdale in
England in a duel with Nicklaus that went to the 18th green.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus holed a 4-foot putt for par, assuring not only half a
point for a halved match but also a final 14-14 score that assured
the Americans' retention of the cup.
</P>
<P>
   Jacklin still had a 2-foot putt. If he missed, it would have
lifted the Americans to a 14{-13{ victory. But in a grand gesture,
Nicklaus conceded Jacklin's putt, preserving the 14-14 score, the
closest the Great Britain team had come to winning since 1957.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave Tony the putt because he was a hero in Great Britain,''
Nicklaus recently told Golf World magazine. ``I didn't feel Tony
would have missed the putt, but I was not going to give him the
chance to miss it. I didn't want to take any chance of having
Tony's stature in the game or in Great Britain diminished by a
short putt in the Ryder Cup. We were going to retain the cup either
way. I just felt it was the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the Ryder Cup pressure-cooker, it was.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
