<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-MIRER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIRER SEEKS FLOURISH AGAINST THE REDSKINS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It will be different today, Rick Mirer promised.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about him, Vinny Testaverde insisted.
</P>
<P>
   It will take time, Curtis Martin admitted, but it's coming.
</P>
<P>
   We've got the weapons, Keyshawn Johnson added.
</P>
<P>
   The wraps are coming off, Bill Parcells announced.
</P>
<P>
   It was Friday, and a certain amount of optimism about the Jets'
newly retooled offense was beginning to surface, as quarterback
Rick Mirer slowly adjusted to his new role as the club's No. 1
signal-caller.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the pressure of an 0-2 start bearing down on them,
with the surging Redskins returning to the Meadowlands Sunday, with
the backup quarterback, Mirer, having played a full game, the Jets'
offense is going to be asked to, finally, score a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   It has not happened in five-plus quarters, including last week's
one-field-goal game against the Bills in Mirer's first start as a
Jet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that we played vanilla last week,'' Mirer conceded.
``We're ready to move on from there. I anticipated we weren't going
to take chances early in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   In fairness to Mirer, he did lead the Jets to within six inches
of Buffalo's goal line with less than three minutes remaining in
the first half. But Jerald Sowell failed to punch the ball in.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the offense Sunday turns from vanilla to rocky road, or
even to rainbow sherbet, may have to do with how many weapons Mirer
can use. He has the redoubtable Martin as his running back. He will
have the blocking, pass-catching tight end, Eric Green, returning
from a pinched nerve. He has the speedy Dedric Ward learning more
about being a starting wide receiver. He has the supremely
confident Johnson, and he has the sophisticated offenses
blueprinted by Charlie Weis.
</P>
<P>
   When Mirer has made things work in past years, it has been with
a steady, conservative attack. Nothing in his seven-year pro career
suggests that the Jets will try anything different Sunday other
than permit him to scramble if all else fails.
</P>
<P>
   In 55 pro starts, Mirer has connected only six times on
touchdowns of 50 yards or more. He has never collaborated on a
touchdown pass of 60 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde, by contrast, did that three times last season. And
in Game 3 against Indianapolis, when Testaverde made his Jets debut
as a starter, he had help in a third-and-2 situation from the
versatile Ray Lucas, who scrambled for 8 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas has been at the ready whenever the Parcells' Jets have
needed a little razzle-dazzle _ first for the stolid Neil
O'Donnell, then for Testaverde.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 he spelled O'Donnell in Game 12 against Minnesota and
picked up 15 yards on one play. In Game 15, against Tampa Bay, he
ran twice, gaining 1 yard and 9 yards. Against Detroit at the
season's end, he was on his way to a starring role with three runs
for 30 yards and a 3-for-4 passing performance for 28 yards, but
then threw an interception near the Lions' goal line that kept the
Jets from making the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Mirer, Lucas' role will be modified Sunday.
The erstwhile backup is likely to be listed as the third
quarterback, a designation that could keep him from seeing any
action until the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Gadget plays aside, the Jets' plan Sunday will no doubt rely
heavily on the run. It was the base of their 12-4 season last year.
It was so effective, in fact, that even when Martin was halted, the
Jets won. The reason was the brilliant play-fake orchestration
between Testaverde and Martin. Testaverde would fake a handoff, the
seven or eight defenders bunched up at the line for Martin would
move, and suddenly there would be a Testaverde pass.
</P>
<P>
   Defenses were so consistently frozen that the Jets won the two
poorest rushing games Martin had as Testaverde starred.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like that between Martin and Mirer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably not at its best right now,'' Martin admitted.
``It's something you develop. Vinny and I had it. I'm still
developing it with Rick.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin explained how both runner and passer have to look at the
field while looking at each other as if a handoff is about to take
place.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer, meanwhile, understands that he must start connecting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that right now Curtis is waiting for me to throw
completions, but the defenses are bunching up because it's kind of
vanilla,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer said he has ``no problem with Curtis on the play-action.''
</P>
<P>
   If there isn't, and the offense sings as it did last year, the
Jets' recovery could start Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer will be playing without any advice from Testaverde on the
sideline. Testaverde said it could be dangerous for him to stand
there on crutches, and in any event his left foot starts to throb
whenever he stands for a while. He has to keep it elevated to
offset the repair on his torn Achilles' tendon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody's a little more comfortable and a little
more confident in Rick,'' Testaverde said. ``I'm sure you will see
a different Jets team out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells promises this much: ``Mirer is more comfortable this
week than last week. We can be a little more expansive this week.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Martin, Parcells said, ``What we have to do is create
balance in our attack.'' Martin had only one second-half carry last
Sunday, and only nine for the game _ the fifth-lowest number of his
career. The Jets were able to create third downs only twice in 11
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday begins a new week, however, and it may be important from
a comfort factor that it's Mirer's second as the Jets' starter _
twice as many as he has ever had before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
