<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON ROAD-TESTS A STUMP SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. _ In a pair of trial runs at a stump speech,
Hillary Rodham Clinton sounded out the themes of her expected
campaign for the U.S. Senate on Saturday, listing the weak upstate
economy, affordable health care, education, the environment, Social
Security and gun control as the most important issues facing New
York.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Mrs. Clinton has done more listening than talking on her
visits to the state, often taking positions only when prodded by
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday she gave a spirited run-through of her agenda to
welcoming audiences, first at a fund-raising breakfast for the
Schenectady County Democratic Committee and then at a labor union
rally in Albany. She also made some of her most overtly partisan
remarks of the year, assailing Republicans in Congress for passing
a tax cut that she said put social programs at risk, and for
blocking an increase in the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to about 300 people at the Schenectady Museum in this
faded industrial city, Mrs. Clinton spoke at length of the need to
revive the anemic upstate economy and stem the migration of people
from the region. ``If upstate New York were a separate state, it
would rank 49th in job creation and income growth,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to the social policy issues with which she has been most
closely identified, she touched on support for education, and
pledged, ``We will figure out a way to provide quality, affordable
health care to every American.''
</P>
<P>
   She took a swipe at congressional Republicans' bid to cut taxes
by nearly $800 billion over 10 years, a bill that is supported by
her likely Republican opponent, New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
and that was vetoed by her husband, President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to use the budget surplus that has been created by the
good policies of this Democratic administration to make sure that
Social Security and Medicare are on stable financial ground into
the next century,'' she said. ``Are we going to be responsible or
are we going to go for the short-term, quick-fix political gimmick?
Well, I was very proud of my husband when he vetoed that
short-term, quick-fix political gimmick.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, Mrs. Clinton's campaign spokesman, said her
remarks were as close as she had come yet to making what will
become her standard stump speech. ``Those are the themes being
road-tested right there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally attended by a few thousand cheering union members in
a park in Albany, Mrs. Clinton focused on issues dear to organized
labor, including her support for raising the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe with all my heart that no working American who goes
to work 40 hours a week, who is there being a responsible worker
and citizen, that no working American should live in poverty,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that the Republican leadership in Congress had
recently blocked a vote on a minimum wage increase. And, with an
implicit dig at Giuliani, who has declined to state a position on
the issue, she added, ``It is wrong, and we should take a stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Through her several public appearances Saturday, Mrs. Clinton
did not take questions from reporters, who were unable to ask her
about the two most recent controversies involving Giuliani: his
threat to block funds for the Brooklyn Museum of Art because of its
scheduled exhibition of controversial art works, and his
administration's plan to cull Medicaid records of welfare
applicants to find those who have been treated for substance abuse,
and insist that they receive continued treatment in return for
welfare benefits. She did not raise either subject.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani did not make any public appearances Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Clinton did edge closer than ever to confirming what
has, for months, seemed evident: that she will formally become a
candidate for the seat being vacated by Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, a Democrat. ``I haven't announced anything,'' she said,
``but I'm leaning so far toward running that I'd fall over if I
leaned any further.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
