u s BC-FBN-GIANTS-ARMSTEAD-2     09-25 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-ARMSTEAD-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTEAD WALKS THE WALK AND TALKS THE TALK
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifteen-year-old Jessie Armstead would be asleep, at home in the
Oak Cliff section of Dallas, a harsh, combative place where
street-corner conflicts were settled with knives and baseball bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``But not guns,'' Armstead, the Giants' Pro Bowl linebacker,
said last week of his old neighborhood. ``We were lucky. Just
knives and bats.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstead's older brother Bobby would come through the bedroom
door some nights to wake Jessie.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a guy at the park, he's about your age and he told me
he can whup you down there,'' Bobby would tell his only brother.
``Let's go. You need to walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Jessie would put on his clothes. He would walk down the hill to
Birdie Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, you'd have to fight him for as long as it took,''
Armstead said. ``It was rough down there. But that's the way things
were. Guys would come get me out of my house all the time. What are
you going to do? You can't lie in bed. You need to walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it was. You can wake me up at 2 in the morning
and say, `Let's go.' I'll go. I can't back down.''
</P>
<P>
   If that were all there was to Armstead, it would explain why he
plays football the way he does _ as though he were still warring at
Birdie Park, hurling himself into savage collisions, talking trash
nonstop as he gestures and challenges opponents, teammates, even
fans in the stands to meet the intensity he has brought to the
playground.
</P>
<P>
   He's 28 now, but somebody woke Jessie up and told him there are
11 guys about his age down at the stadium who say they can whup
him. His brother Bobby is at the door: You need to walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jessie is the Tasmanian Devil out there,'' said Michael
Strahan, Armstead's teammate and friend.
</P>
<P>
   But growing up tough and staying that way doesn't explain nearly
enough about Armstead; indeed, it too easily suits the image that
has grown up around his career, an image epitomized by his
on-the-field warrior persona.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people think they know Armstead from what they see on
the field, or because he went to the University of Miami, where the
football program relished an outlaw image.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen people scared off in Jessie's presence,'' Strahan
said. ``They'll go, `There's Jessie Armstead. He must be nasty.'''
</P>
<P>
   He is so nasty, he sends his ailing father, Bobby Sr., roses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants his father to enjoy some of the nice things in
life,'' Strahan said.
</P>
<P>
   Armstead calls his mother, Mary, every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``From wherever he is in the world,'' Mary said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what makes her most proud of her son, Mary Armstead
answered at once: ``That he's well-mannered. And he got his college
degree in three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Which Armstead did, in criminal justice.
</P>
<P>
   Armstead said he has never tasted alcohol, does not smoke, and
has not used drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was at Miami, guys would be drinking,'' Armstead said.
``They'd say: `You one of the guys or not?' I'd say: `I'm one of
the guys who drinks Sprite.'''
</P>
<P>
   He is, in fact, a goody two shoes. He says he has never had so
much as a speeding ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that,'' Mary Armstead said. ``He drives me crazy
when I drive with him. I want to put my foot over to the
accelerator and push on it. I'll ask him to please go a little
faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll say: `Nope, I don't want to get a ticket.'''
</P>
<P>
   He has had two run-ins with the law, both when he was 15. He was
detained by police for illegally racing his dirt bike, and later,
was caught stealing clothes with friends at a mall. ``He knew he
broke my heart,'' Mary Armstead said.
</P>
<P>
   Jessie promised his mother he would never be in trouble again.
``There's never been anything else,'' Mary said. ``He's always had
respect for his promises.''
</P>
<P>
   He is, for all the yelling he does at the offense, one of the
most respected Giants. He is, despite the running commentary he
delivers to opponents in every game, respected by players around
the National Football League, who have voted him to the Pro Bowl
for two consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He's the guy who took all the lessons his rough-and-tumble
neighborhood taught him and found a place where they belonged _ the
football field _ without letting those lessons intercede in ways
that might ruin the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard football players say they can't just turn the
aggression on and off,'' Armstead said. ``That's going to get you
in trouble and I don't think it's true. I have two sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as his wife, Channon Armstead, who has known Jessie since
they were 15, and who like the rest of the Armstead family calls
Jessie by his nickname, Jay, said: ``There's No. 98, and there's
Jay. Two different people.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a gentle, kind family man with our two daughters. But if
someone even accidentally bumps into one of the kids when we're
out, he'll turn into that football man in a second. He's going to
protect them.''
</P>
<P>
   The two sides of his personality, Armstead said, evolved
naturally. His father, a retired bus-company owner, convinced his
sons they would have to fight for everything in life. Mary Armstead
managed a pharmacy and encouraged her boys to study, be courteous
and think about turning the other cheek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be reading them the Bible and my husband would be telling
them to get back out there and take no hostages,'' Mary said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Dad put the `t' in tough,'' Bobby Jr., said of his father,
whose kidney problems have put him on dialysis as he awaits a
kidney transplant. ``Jay takes after my father. Neither one ain't
scared of nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   Jessie didn't play organized football until eighth-grade, but he
played the game at Birdie Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Full contact games on a rocky field,'' Jessie said. ``Guys
were separating their shoulders and bleeding because they hit their
face on the rocks. It wasn't no smooth, pretty game.''
</P>
<P>
   At Dallas' Carter High, he was an instant star, with a national
recruiting magazine naming him the best high school player in
America as a sophomore and in each of the two years that followed.
</P>
<P>
   At Miami, he played immediately as a freshman, then blew out his
knee as a sophomore. Although he returned to play well in both his
junior and senior seasons, pro scouts thought he was too small to
play linebacker in the NFL. He's 240 pounds now but carried just
225 pounds on his 6-foot-1-inch frame coming out of college. Plus,
his knee injury worried teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Armsteads watched the 1993 draft in their Dallas home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watched all 206 picks over two of the longest days of our
lives,'' Bobby Jr., said. ``Then the Giants, with the last pick of
that draft, took Jessie.''
</P>
<P>
   Strahan believes Armstead has never gotten over those two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jessie plays with a chip on his shoulder,'' Strahan said. ``It
comes from being picked last.''
</P>
<P>
   It took Armstead four seasons, but by the beginning of 1996, he
had convinced the Giants he was their best weakside linebacker. In
the next three years, he helped convince coaches around the NFL
that what they needed was more linebackers like him _ smaller,
quicker outside defenders for a quicker, pass-happy game. It has
started a trend, and Sunday night, when the Giants play the
Patriots at Foxboro Stadium, Armstead will be starting his 51st
consecutive game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been proving to people that they're wrong about me all my
life,'' Armstead said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And there is a history to that claim, too. Like many of
Armstead's life stories, it begins in Birdie Park.
</P>
<P>
   One night, when Jessie was 13, the fisticuffs at the park spread
to the front of a nearby house.
</P>
<P>
   Jessie and Bobby Armstead were brawling with a set of brothers
until a third brother emerged from the house with a 10-inch butcher
knife in his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw it at me and the blade went in through my hip and
stuck all the way into the pelvis bone on the other side,'' Jessie
Armstead said.
</P>
<P>
   With the wooden handle sticking out from his hip, Armstead got
on his bike and rode home. Struggling to get into the door, the
wooden knife handle caught on some iron burglar bars protecting the
front of the Armstead house. The handle snapped off, leaving the
blade inside Jessie's hip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jessie had left the house with white pants, socks and shoes,''
Mary Armstead said. ``When I looked up at him, his pants, socks and
shoes were completely red with his blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Surgeons entered Armstead's hip from both sides, removing the
blade in two pieces in two separate surgeries. During the month
that Jessie spent in two hospitals, doctors told Mary and Bobby
Armstead that their son would never walk without a cane, maybe not
walk at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were wrong about me,'' Armstead said last week. ``You
know? Like we used to say, you need to walk.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
