<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-MATCH1-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGGERT THE ONE   TO FINALLY FIRE   A WINNING SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ From the start, Jeff Maggert and Hal Sutton
knew something was different.
</P>
<P>
   The galleries, sensing the urgency of the moment, cheered halves
of holes as if they were wins.
   And, surely, through the first part of Maggert and Sutton's
Ryder Cup foursome (alternate-shot) match against Colin Montgomerie
and Paul Lawrie Saturday morning at The Country Club, that was all
the Americans could do _ make putts for halves, to prevent a repeat
of the carnage of Friday when the Europeans had roared to a 6-2
lead.
</P>
<P>
   But with that strategy came something else, a growing sense of
confidence, which finally was justified when Maggert and Sutton
posted a stirring 1-up victory over the previously unbeaten British
duo.
</P>
<P>
   It was only 1 point in a long, uphill struggle to regain the
Cup, but it was also a table-setter that caused American captain
Ben Crenshaw to raise his feet in exultation when Maggert's
conversion of a 22-foot birdie on the par-4, 370-yard 17th hole
gave the Americans the advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to do something good,'' said Maggert, who was
the star of the match with his birdie putt and a marvelous second
shot on the par-4, 436-yard 18th that landed 2 feet from the pin,
giving the Americans a conceded birdie on the hole. ``Hal had been
playing so well and carried us.''
</P>
<P>
   Beating the Europeans _ especially Montgomerie and Lawrie, who
won their first two matches in Friday's competition _ was a
daunting challlenge.
</P>
<P>
   So fragile was the confidence of the gallery that when Sutton
pulled his second shot on the first hole into a greenside bunker,
while Montogmerie hit his second shot 8 feet from the pin, someone
in the gallery murmered: ``Down 1 already.''
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't happen then, as Maggert hit a sand wedge 8 feet
past the pin, and Sutton made a hole-saving par after Lawrie had
missed the Europeans' birdie attempt.
</P>
<P>
   There was little reason for confidence after the second hole
when the Europeans went 1 up after Lawrie rolled in a 6-footer for
a birdie.
</P>
<P>
   But the Americans hung around, making saves until the par-5,
513-yard ninth hole when Maggert, chipping out of the rough in
front of the green, chipped the ball inside 3 feet.
</P>
<P>
   When Montgomerie, who had to back off his 8-foot birdie putt
after a fan snapped a flash camera from the hill above the green,
eventually missed his birdie attempt, the Americans finally were
able to square the match when Sutton rolled in his 3-footer.
</P>
<P>
   Now it was will against will, and the Americans showed they were
just as tough as the Europeans, going 1-up on the 11th, giving it
right back on the 12th, and then going 1-up after 17.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans had a chance to at least get a half, but Maggert
took care of that with the Americans' second shot, which resulted
in a 2-footer.
</P>
<P>
   With the Europeans unable to hole a tricky 40-foot downhiller,
Montgomerie and Lawrie conceded the hole, and, for the first time,
a match. ``It was just a great day,'' Sutton said. ``Jeff did
everything. We're fortunate to be on top.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
