<HEADER>
A5935 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-HOLING-BOS &LR;      09-25 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-HOLING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTS DIDN'T FALL, BUT   O'MEARA-FURYK DID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Ben Crenshaw said it best Friday night after
watching his American Ryder Cup team stumble out of the gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holing out is the name of the game in match play,'' he said.
``That's what determines holes.''
</P>
<P>
   That proved so very true Saturday morning, when Mark O'Meara and
Jim Furyk, two of the better putters on the PGA Tour, failed to
make a birdie and fell to Darren Clarke and Lee Westwood, 3 and 2,
in their foursomes match.
</P>
<P>
   Both were guilty. If it wasn't O'Meara sliding putts wide right,
it was Furyk sliding them left. And it didn't matter whether the
putt was from 20 feet or 10 feet. They just couldn't drop the ball
into the hole when it counted.
</P>
<P>
   That made things so much easier for Clarke and Westwood, who
beat Tiger Woods and David Duval, 1 up, in Friday's four-ball
match.
</P>
<P>
   Not that they set The Country Club course afire. The European
duo had only three birdies, but with no pressure from O'Meara or
Furyk, they could be content with pars _ especially after going 2
up after 12 holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing,'' said O'Meara, who is averaging 3.47
birdies per round on the PGA Tour. ``We didn't play poorly, but we
didn't make any putts. We didn't really ever have it close enough
to make any birdies. They birdied the two par-5 holes where we had
good drives and didn't make the birdies. It was difficult. They
played well, they putted well, and they're doing all the things to
win. Unfortunately, we're not doing those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Furyk said the ninth hole, where Westwood and Clarke grabbed the
lead for good, was the turning point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had similar putts, pretty severely breaking putts,'' he
said. ``Lee Westwood made his birdie putt and I missed. I missed
some other putts that went right over the edge. Once again, we
never really had it that close.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara and Furyk took a 1-up lead on the third hole when Furyk
made a 3-footer for par, and Westwood and Clarke bogeyed from 20
feet. But the Euopeans squared the match and then forged ahead for
keeps when Clarke drilled a birdie putt on the sixth (15 feet) and
Westwood on the ninth (10 feet).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good performance, steady,'' said Westwood. ``We
didn't make too many mistakes. We're pleased with the point. We
came out stronger after the rain. I don't know why. Maybe I needed
to sit down and rest for five minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Clarke, ``We're just playing well together. We enjoy
playing together. We play a lot of practice rounds and there was no
reason not to stick us together. We're both playing well and Lee
(Westwood) had some great putts at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   That's something O'Meara and Furyk couldn't say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 1644EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
