A5936 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-COURTS-ABORTION-NY     09-25 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-COURTS-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY'S NEW ABORTION LAW REGARDING MINORS IS BLOCKED 
</HEADLINE>
  (With COURTS-ABORTION) 
(js) 
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A New Jersey Supreme Court judge temporarily blocked a law
Saturday that would have required girls under age 18 to notify at
least one parent before getting an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Gary Stein blocked enforcement of the law, which would
have gone into effect Sunday, until it could be reviewed early this
week by all seven members of the court, the state's highest. The
ruling came in response to a last-minute appeal by the American
Civil Liberties Union, which had unsuccessfully appealed to two
lower state courts last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means it's not going to start tomorrow,'' said Jennifer
Dalven, a lawyer for the ACLU, after a telephone conference call
Saturday with Stein and a representative from the state attorney
general's office. Ms. Dalven said she expected the full court to
hear the case either Monday or Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are relieved,'' Ms. Dalven said. ``We are trying to strike
it down, you just have to move slowly in the lawsuits. We're
seeking to have the law declared unconstitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Superior Court Judge Marguerite T. Simon rejected
the ACLU's effort to delay enforcement of the law. Abortion rights
advocates filed an emergency appeal with the Appellate Division of
state Superior Court, but judges there declined to overturn the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Although Saturday's ruling disappointed many abortion opponents,
at least one remained confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``This in no way is the last word,'' said Marie Tasy, the
legislative director for New Jersey Right to Life. ``I think this
is a very temporary decision. We're confident that the Superior
Court of New Jersey will rule in favor of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey is one of 39 states, and the sixth in the Northeast,
that have passed laws requiring pregnant girls either to gain
parental permission or notify at least one parent before having an
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike similar laws in Massachusetts, Rhode Island and
Pennsylvania, which require parental consent for a minor to have an
abortion, New Jersey's law requires only that a pregnant girl tell
a parent before proceeding with an abortion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 1645EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
