<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SCHOOL-BUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SCHOOL BUS SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Sept. 26:
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board has recommended some
sensible design changes for school buses to prevent injuries in
side-impact collisions and rollovers. School buses are already one
of the safer modes of transportation for youngsters. Last year
there were only 29 school bus-related fatalities, six involving bus
occupants and 23 involving pedestrians. Those figures seem small
when compared with the 41,471 people killed in motor vehicle
crashes in this country. But inadequate data collection at school
bus accident sites has made it difficult to determine the number of
injuries in school bus accidents, leaving the overall safety record
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   With this in mind, the safety board has called for a better
system of data collection and for crash data recorders on buses,
the rough equivalent of ``black box'' data recorders in airplanes,
to improve accident investigations.
</P>
<P>
   The board has also urged the Department of Transportation to
strengthen the sides and roofs of buses and improve the seating
compartments, much as one might pack china for shipping in a box
with strong sides and extensive padding to keep it from shifting.
</P>
<P>
   This would entail a seat design with lap and shoulder restraints
and more cushioning. Many school buses do not have seat belts, and
there has been much head-scratching over this issue in the last two
decades. The slick 1970s bench seat in place today was never
designed to be used with seat belts. Lap belts used with this seat
may actually increase injury in some crash scenarios by allowing a
child's head to hit the seat with more force than if the child had
been unrestrained.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it is not enough to increase safety within the buses.
Most fatal accidents occur outside the bus, suggesting that the
main gains in safety will come from improvements in loading,
unloading and driving the buses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
