<HEADLINE>
GENTLE BEN SHOULD HAVE BEEN MORE AGGRESSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Phil Mickelson was heading to the first tee
in Saturday afternoon's matches when US captain Ben Crenshaw
spotted him and gave him some words of encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to him, `Just trust that putting stroke,' '' said
Crenshaw. ``I said, `Make it (his putting stroke) a sweep and hit
it solid.' ''
</P>
<P>
   All Mickelson needs, Crenshaw said, ``is for one or two to go
down and he's off.''
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw's words were fine _ even if 16 hours too late _ but
actions would have spoken louder than words for the US captain.
Putting has been the bane of the US team (``Putt up or shut up''
could have been the team's epitaph after the early matches),
leaving Crenshaw frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   So much so that the US captain trotted out a team for Saturday's
morning matches _ Mark O'Meara and Jim Furyk _ that would have even
furrowed the brow of George Washington or Abraham Lincoln, the
Americans' chances of winning were that slim. Meanwhile, Mickelson
was sitting on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson asked Crenshaw Friday night to sit him out after
Mickelson missed two crucial putts on the 16th and 18th holes that
afternoon. Mickelson was crushed by missing the short putts and
conceded the obvious, that his putting ``is certainly a concern.''
</P>
<P>
   The misses on 16 and 18 were inexcusable, but to get into
position to miss those putts, Mickelson had to hit three of the
more magnificent shots of his match. His drive on 16 left him 5
feet away, and on 18, a huge drive and short iron _ the best shot
of them all _ also left him 5 feet away. ``I felt I'd played
extremely well,'' said Mikelson, except, of course, for those
putts.
</P>
<P>
   So Mickelson asked out of Saturday's morning matches, as did
Davis Love and David Duval. Love's absence was understandable _ he
is coming off a neck injury _ while Duval had played so poorly on
Friday that his absence shouldn't have caused a stir.
</P>
<P>
   But Crenshaw never should have agreed. For one, Mickelson needed
to be back on the course as soon as possible after missing putts
that crucial, much as the best remedy for getting thrown by a horse
is get aboard again as soon as possible. Otherwise, fear builds.
</P>
<P>
   Even more, Mickelson should have been told forcefully by
Crenshaw that he was needed by the US team, that his game had been
magnificent Friday and the Americans could not win without him.
Missed putts or no missed putts, Mickelson was indispensable to the
US team, Crenshaw should have said so.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Mark O'Meara went onto the course and missed no crucial
putts. There will be no tales of gruesome misses by O'Meara
precisely because the remainder of O'Meara's game did not put him
in position to miss crucial putts. O'Meara and Furyk seemed out of
their match after the fifth hole and lost to Darren Clarke and Lee
Westwood, 3 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mickelson sat. And a man with true putting problems _
Payne Stewart _ played. Stewart missed five makeable putts inside 5
feet that might have saved his team, including a 3-footer.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mickelson asked to sit and Gentle Ben agreed. The gentle
seldom win the Ryder Cup, and Mickelson is too good a golfer to
miss any match.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
