<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-BACKLASH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTISANSHIP LIMITED   FOR AMERICAN TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WALTER V. ROBINSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ When Jim Furyk hit an iron shot to within 12
feet of the pin on the par-4 fourth hole Saturday, the largely
American crowd cheered loudly. In contrast, the European supporters
groaned when Darren Clarke put his ball in a greenside trap.
</P>
<P>
   But when Lee Westwood, Clarke's teammate, blasted out to within
2 feet of the cup, both Americans and Europeans cheered lustily.
When the next pairing came through, Tiger Woods's looping birdie
putt fell, and the crowd roared. But when European Padraig
Harrington answered with a 15-foot birdie, the loud cheers were
noticeably nonpartisan.
</P>
<P>
   To most spectators, applauding great golf _ by either side _ is
only polite. But other American fans, and some Europeans, detect a
certain coolness toward the US team by American spectators,
impressed by the scrapiness of a Europeam team that came here as
decided underdogs; and put off by the preoccupation with money by
some of the American Ryder Cuppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American fans are quite enthusiastic, but some of them are
quite disenchanted with some of their own players,'' remarked Brent
Mason, a British fan from Leeds. ``I've heard more than a few
Americans say, `Why can't our guys behave like the Europeans?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Some of that disenchantment, boorishly expressed, was evident
late Friday as America's two marquee players, Woods and David
Duval, were on their way to defeat as the sun set. When the
Americans misplayed the 18th hole, one piqued American fan heckled
Duval for having likened the Ryder Cup to an exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think of the exhibition now?'' the spectator
yelled. ``This is a long way for you to come for a whipping.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the American players' wives, clad in their
fashionable matching outfits, were heckled.
</P>
<P>
   But for reasons as complex as Furyk's unorthodox takeaway, the
American team has not been carried by its fans. To be sure, there
was not much for Americans to cheer about all day Friday and
Saturday morning. Many spectators were literally neutralized by
their inability to see much of the golf on a course that was not
designed with spectating in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, fans were quick to point to a certain reserve among
American fans, in sharp contrast to the partisan support European
players have come to expect when the matches are played on their
home ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not unlike a gallery at a regular US pro tour event.
There's just not a lot of partisanship,'' said Phil Schneiders, a
Scottsdale, Ariz., golfer who has been to two Ryder Cup
championships in Europe. ``The crowds over there are much noisier
and much more behind their team.''
</P>
<P>
   Schneiders said he doubts there's much animosity toward the
American players because of their pampered image. Instead, he said,
fans seem impressed by the European team spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Parr, a member of the Loch Lomond Golf Club near Glasgow,
said he thought the European team neutralized much of the potential
fan support for the home team.
</P>
<P>
   ``All week long, the European players have worked quite hard to
establish good relationships with the crowd, signing autographs and
speaking to fans,'' Parr said. ``They're more relaxed, and they're
smiling more often. The crowd appreciates how they work together.''
</P>
<P>
   Then too, he said with a smile, there is a natural American
inclination to root for the underdog.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the crowd is not actively wanting the Europeans to
win,'' he said. ``But I think they're happy to see them doing
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
