<HEADLINE>
ODD DUET PRODUCES A VICTORY FOR THE US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Desperately in need of finding someone to
match Tiger Woods's pace and stride _ not to mention his long,
daunting shadow _ the Americans Saturday summoned Steve Pate, a
38-year-old fellow Californian with limited Ryder Cup experience,
and the unlikely duet danced off with an impressive and gritty 1-up
victory in the morning foursomes at The Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Woods and Pate, who entered with a combined mark of 1-5-1 in
Ryder play, took a commanding 3-up lead over the first three holes,
the start to what looked like a runaway victory for the beleagured
American team.
</P>
<P>
   But after watching the European pair of Padraig Harrington and
Miguel Angel Jimenez chip away and pull even over the next eight
holes, the Yanks needed Woods's 25-foot putt for an eagle-3 on the
14th to provide what would be the winning margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really jelled well today,'' said Woods, who suffered a pair
of losses in Friday's opening matches when the Yanks dropped six of
eight matches. ``More than anything, our personalities jelled
really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about that partnership, Pate initially said they both
asked for the pairing, before kiddingly (and emphatically) adding,
``We demanded it!''
</P>
<P>
   Given how the match started, the Americans came out seemingly
winning on demand, striking strong second shots and feathering in
soft putts. They birdied the first four holes, winning 1, 2, and 3.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight on No. 1 was the second shot, by Woods, an iron
that he stuck two feet from the pin. The Europeans conceded the
putt. On the par-3 second hole, Woods's iron off the tee landed
eight fee short of the pin, with Pate adding the soft touch for the
birdie. On No. 3, Woods was back with another great iron shot that
left the Yanks with no more than 12 feet, and Pate once more added
the finger-roll finish.
</P>
<P>
   After a day of hell Friday, when the Yanks lost everything but
the anchor to Old Ironsides, suddenly the Americans had a helluva
twosome. Pate and Woods, the Golden State's golden boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a good margin early,'' said US captain Ben Crenshaw,
who paired Pate and Woods again for an afternoon round of
four-ball. ``Steve played some very fine shots on the back. I
wanted to send them back out because I think they have a feel for
the course.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez and Harrington slowly chipped their way back to all
square, beginning with a birdie on No. 6, another on No. 8 and an
match-tying par-4 on No. 11. Pate hit the third shot on No. 11 for
the US, a chip from 50 feet that rolled 15 feet beyond the flag _
which would prove too difficult for Woods to salvage par. When
Jimenez rolled a 20-footer just left of the hole, the Yanks
conceded the par, and effectively, the hole.
</P>
<P>
   The dastardly 12th provided the round's best entertainment,
starting with Harrington's deep drive that exited to the right of
the fairway and landed in a tire rut along a stonedust path.
Jimenez made two drops, but finally had to settle for a lie not
much better than the tire rut, before following with a brilliant
shot from the rocky road. Both sides were now lying two, all of 12
inches from each other in tall grass surrounding a bunker at the
right edge of the green. Ultimately, the Yanks and Euros halved the
hole _ and two holes later, the match would be settled, punctuated
by Woods clenched right fist, held high for gallery and glory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
