<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-MATCH2-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE`S THE BEEF? AMERICANS FIND OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Friday afternoon's victory may have been more
prestigious, but Saturday morning's was more appetizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``More time for lunch,'' observed Lee Westwood, savoring the
prospect after he and Darren Clarke had feasted on Mark O'Meara and
Jim Furyk, 3 and 2, in their Ryder Cup foursomes match. The victory
helped the Europeans seize an 8-4 lead over the United States,
before the teams stopped to break bread. ``That'll be nice.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a matter of priorities, and food certainly is one of them
for Northern Ireland's 220-pound Clarke and England's 195-pound
Westwood, beefy best buds who put the ``united'' in United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to an appreciation of gustatory pleasures, they
share a rakish sense of humor, complementary games, and an obvious
aversion to the PGA fitness trailer. And if someone offered them a
pint of stout, chances are they wouldn't run away in horror.
</P>
<P>
   When Westwood was asked what exhortation captain Mark James had
employed to maintain their focus in the wake of their epic 1-up
victory over the world's top two players, Tiger Woods and David
Duval, in Friday's four-ball play, the Briton responded, ``Don't
drink too much.''
</P>
<P>
   He was just kidding, as usual, but the one-upmanship of
America's finest Friday, which gave Europe an improbable 6-2
first-day lead, certainly merited a toast or two. If nothing else,
it was an elixir for the duo's spirits, which had been jolted
Friday morning when they dropped their opening foursomes match, 3
and 2, to Hal Sutton and Jeff Maggert _ the man who had rankled
Westwood by calling the Americans ``the world's 12 best players.''
</P>
<P>
   Westwood, who happens to be ranked fifth in the world, had to
defer his revenge, but he and Clarke took it out on Woods and
Duval.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gave us a lot of confidence, beating the No. 1 and 2
players in the world,'' he said. ``It made us feel we could beat
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara and Furyk aren't just anybody _ they are rated 11th and
14th, respectively, in the world _ but they were no match for the
Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both hitting the ball great,'' said Clarke. ``We try to
hit the fairways and greens and take it from there.''
</P>
<P>
   They certainly took it to Furyk and O'Meara. The latter had
volunteered to sit out Friday morning's matches because he was
displeased with his game, but had been sorely disappointed when US
captain Ben Crenshaw bypassed him in the afternoon. O'Meara
probably wished he'd stayed on the practice range by the time
Westwood and Clarke were through.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing,'' said O'Meara. ``We didn't play poorly,
but we didn't make any putts.''
</P>
<P>
   Westwood missed one for par on the third, putting the Europeans
1-down, but that was their only misstep of the day. Westwood evened
matters when he dropped a 22-foot birdie putt on the par-4 sixth
and O'Meara missed from 15 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The match turned the Europeans' way on the par-5 ninth. Clarke
hit a magnificent chip from behind a bunker and Westwood deposited
a 12-foot birdie, then watched O'Meara push his 10-foot bid to the
right.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was huge,'' said Clarke.
</P>
<P>
   The margin kept growing after a 25-minute delay caused by the
threat of lightning on the 10th. ``Maybe I just needed five minutes
to sit down,'' said Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   He and Clarke proceeded to revel in the sunshine that supplanted
the rain by capturing the par-4 12th (on a 7-footer for par by
Clarke) and par-5 14th (a 15-footer for birdie by Clarke). When
Furyk's 20-foot birdie attempt didn't fall on 16, the match was
over.
</P>
<P>
   It may have qualified only as dessert after their Friday
afternoon epic, but Westwood and Clarke aren't fussy about what's
put in front of them on the table.
</P>
</TEXT>
