<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-GAYS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICAN GAYS HOLD FIRST OPEN PILGRIMAGE FOR TOLERANCE AT SHRINE
TO VIRGIN MARY
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY Clutching roses, dahlias and a lavender banner,
Mexican gays on Saturday conducted their first open pilgrimage to
pray for tolerance at this country's revered Virgin of Guadalupe
Basilica.
</P>
<P>
   ``God doesn't exclude us. He made us this way. And if we expect
others to overcome their fear of us then we must overcome our fear
to appear in public,'' said Guadalupe Lopez, 36, a lesbian who
dared join the controversial procession of about 150 people down a
main avenue here leading to the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virgin of Guadalupe, bless us,'' proclaimed a lavender banner
that pilgrims carried as they entered the crowded basilica at
midday on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Pilgrimage organizers said they came to pray for an end to hate
crimes against homosexuals and transvestites in Mexico _ including
the killings of a gay couple they said occurred in Mexico City two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Although many said they were afraid they might be harassed in
this mostly socially conservative country, participants met with no
difficulties as they sang and walked several kilometers toward the
basilica.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors of the march _ including the ecumenical Metropolitan
Community Church here _ said they received threats after the
pilgrimage was announced earlier this week. The Catholic Archbishop
of Mexico also put out a disapproving press release distancing the
Catholic Church from the gay procession.
</P>
<P>
   The Virgin of Guadalupe Basilica is the second most visited
Catholic shrine in the world. The Virgin of Guadalupe, a
dark-skinned Mary who legend says appeared to a Mexican Indian in
1531, is considered the patron saint of Mexico and is also dear to
other Latin Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mother who protects all of us from oppression in Latin
America is the Virgin of Guadalupe,'' said the Rev. Gabriel Sosa of
Mexico's Metropolitan Community Church, which called for the
pilgrimage with a group here known as the Committee for Sexual
Diversity.
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Community Church is an ecumenical Christian
organization with about 300 churches that welcome gays around the
world, Sosa said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the office of the Archbishop of Mexico
reacted to news of the gay pilgrimage by rejecting the procession
as an act of faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Catholic Church does not reject people who have problems
or confusion with the sexual identity that God naturally gave
them,'' the church said in a press release. ``All human beings are
considered children of the creator subject to love and pardon.
However, church doctrine rejects the disorderly use of sexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa shrugged at the Catholic hierarchy's position and said he
knows of many clergy who accept homosexuals as they are.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the archbishop, Esteban Gonzalez, 32, pointed at
the sky and said, ``What is there to pardon? The only one who can
pardon anyone is that person who is up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez said he came to the pilgrimage because he wanted to
feel ``closer to God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I also think events like these are important to helping gays
gain respect here,'' he said. ``Change here is very slow.''
</P>
<P>
   As a symbol of the purity of their devotion to the Virgin, the
gay pilgrims wore white to the procession. They also carried tiny
Mexican flags and bouquets of flowers, particularly roses, a
traditional offering for the Virgin.
</P>
<P>
   Lilith Reyna, a 22-year-old student and member of the Committee
for Sexual Diversity, said many gays decided not to attend the
pilgrimage out of fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are risks,'' she said, explaining that the committee has
counted about 150 violent ``hate crimes'' so far this year against
gays in Mexico City, including killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Catholic and I feel bad that the church doesn't open
itself up more,'' she said. ``In time, we hope that will change.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those who joined the procession, which drew Mexican
media coverage, were mothers or other supporters of gay liberation
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my sons died of AIDS four years ago,'' said Angela
Castro. ``Since then I've marched against discrimination.
Discrimination begins at home. I've fought with my husband and my
in-laws over this.''
</P>
<P>
   Observers of the procession appeared more tolerant than the
church hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have different ways of living, but we're all believers
in the Virgin,'' said Ana Maria Casteneda, who sells balloons to
worshipers on their way into the shrine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should we judge them?'' said Rutilio Salazar, an elderly
photographer who earns a living snapping souvenir shots of
pilgrims. ``When one comes to the holy sanctuary of the Virgin one
should never be rejected or judged.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
