<HEADLINE>
MAGGERT CONSPICUOUSLY ABSENT IN US FOUR-BALL EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Not to second-guess our earnest American
captain, but where exactly was Jeff Maggert for Saturday
afternoon's four-ball matches?
</P>
<P>
   You don't throw Fred out there without Ginger. You don't send
Bethune out there without Cookman. You don't suit up Johnson
without Johnson. So what was Gentle Ben doing, anyway? didn't he
notice that the team _ that's T-E-A-M _ of Hal Sutton and Jeff
Maggert had been his most formidable duo during the first day and a
half of Ryder Cup competition?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't emphasize enough that we are doing this as a team,''
asserted Sutton after the Americans had won holes 17 and 18 in
dramatic fashion for a 2-up triumph over Colin Montgomerie and Paul
Lawrie. That victory gave the US a valuable point _ in this fierce
competition every point is valuable _ in the opening match of the
day. It was a true clutch performance by Messrs. Sutton and
Maggert, given that the scoreboard was already bearing the grim
tidings of two more American disasters before their own match was
over.
</P>
<P>
   The victory made Sutton and Maggert 2-1 in the first two days of
competition. Compared to any other American grouping, that made
them a veritable Hogan and Snead.
</P>
<P>
   This much we know: European captain Mark James would never have
broken up a winning combo. In days one and two he has only used
nine of his 12 players. Jean Van de Velde, Jarmo Sandelin and
Andrew Coltart have been relegated to Christian Laettner/Dream Team
status (everyone gets to play in  &UR; Sunday's  &LR; singles matches,
however). And had current Masters champion Jose Maria Olazabal not
volunteered himself out of the morning match on both Friday and
Saturday, Captain James wouldn't have made any changes at all.
Padraig Harrington would not have been paired with Spaniard Manuel
Angel Jiminez; he'd have joined the aforementioned trio in the role
of cheerleader.
</P>
<P>
   But Crenshaw did it his way, replacing Maggert with Justin
Leonard for the afternoon four-ball match with James's kilted
warriors, Montgomerie and Lawrie.
</P>
<P>
   The Crenshaw explanation has something to do with Leonard
perhaps getting hot with his putter. Perhaps the mentor simply
thought the talented Leonard was due. After all, with the morning
loss he and partner Payne Stewart had sustained to The Kid and The
Kook (sometimes known as Sergio Garcia and Jesper Parnevik),
Leonard's Ryder Cup career record was 0-3.
</P>
<P>
   The fact remains that Maggert and Sutton had been working well
together. ``Jeff and I play similar games,'' analyzed Sutton. ``We
both drive the ball straight, and we're both good iron players.''
</P>
<P>
   You can say it was circumstance, but the fates conspired to make
Maggert the hero of the morning match, for it was the Texan who
rammed home a birdie putt on 17 that altered a match that had been
all square since the 11th hole in favor of the Americans, and it
was the Texan who sealed the match with a sparkling second shot
7-iron that rolled to a concedable distance on the final hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``The putt was not normally a putt you think about making,'' he
maintained. ``I had a good read on it. It was uphill. I didn't have
to worry about the ball rolling real far past the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the dramatic 7-iron, Maggert had this to say: ``I was
just thinking, `Knock it in there tight for a birdie,' '' he
explained. ``Paul (Lawrie) had hit his shot over to the right. I
just wanted to hit a solid shot and give Hal an opportunity for a
birdie in case he needed it. I had a perfect (7-iron) yardage
there, and just tried to hit a solid shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Maggert isn't exactly regarded as the warm and cuddly type in
his homeland, and that's nothing compared to his current status
across the pond, where he and Stewart have been portrayed as
Villains 1 and 1A. Stewart earned his status by declaring that he
couldn't wait to start earning Ryder Cup points so he could defend
the 1999 Cup, while Maggert became a pariah when he said that
America had the ``12 best players in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Or did he?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where all that came from,'' he protested. ``Go
look at the PGA's transcript.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, let's. Here is what the transcript has Maggert saying at the
general interview session last Tuesday: ``I think alternate shot is
a little more crucial on how you pair guys together. Let's face it,
we've got the 12 best players in the world and if they just go out
and play golf and hit golf shots, it's hard to mess up putting two
guys together.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the British journalists have picked up on this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I mean is that we have to think we're the 12 best
players, or why even bother to compete?'' he pleaded. ``If we don't
believe that, there's something wrong. If anything, it's a
compliment. We will have to play well together to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll never buy this explanation over there, but no matter.
What's indisputable is that Jeff Maggert has contributed mightily
to the American's cause, so much so that it was a bit odd not to
see him paired with somebody Saturday afternoon, even if it wasn't
Hal Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Ben it's tough to play five matches and be as fresh for
singles,'' said a diplomatically-inclined Maggert. ``I struggled
Saturday in the four-ball format (he and Sutton lost, 2 and 1, to
Jimenez and Olazabal), and didn't hit the ball as well as I would
like to.''
</P>
<P>
   All we know is that the last time we saw Jeff Maggert strike the
ball it landed about a foot and a half from the hole from 175 yards
out. That's a tough memory to shake.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
