<HEADLINE>
ON THE 6TH, GOING FOR A DRIVE   WASN'T THE BEST ROUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA MATSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ The easiest hole on the course might be the
par-4 sixth. Or maybe it just looks easy.
</P>
<P>
   Its perched green sits on top of a hill only 310 yards from the
tee. Even with tall pines standing sentry along the back of the
tiny green, and bunkers guarding the left front and the right side,
it remains a seductive target. So close.
</P>
<P>
   On the tee, the Americans puff their chests and flex their
muscles and reach into their golf bags. Driver. Driver. Driver. US
captain Ben Crenshaw even had the narrow up-slope between the
bunkers short of the green cut at less than an inch so that long,
accurate drives might bounce onto the green.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans seem to see a different possibility: An iron off
the tee to lay up, a wedge close to the pin, a good chance for an
easy birdie.
</P>
<P>
   It looks like a hole a professional could quickly wrestle to the
ground. But when accuracy is essential, does a driver give any
advantage over a precise iron? In best ball strategy, long hitters
expect to aim for the green. But in alternate shot play, a more
conservative approach seems to work better.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's morning foursomes, three of the four American duos
lost the hole, driving into big trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods and Steve Pate came to the sixth 3 up over Miguel
Angel Jimenez and Padraig Harrington. Woods hit his drive into the
rough short of the left side of the green. Pate chipped to 13 feet,
but Woods missed the birdie putt.
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez, meanwhile, laid up in the fairway and Harrington stuck
his wedge to 5 feet for an easy birdie.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Woods made the same mistake, again driving into the
rough and scrambling for a bogey with Tom Lehman, while Sergio
Garcia and Jesper Parnevik took their par and won the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Justin Leonard's drive landed in the left rough and
Payne Stewart's sand wedge left the team with a three-putt from 25
feet for bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, however, hit a 5-iron off the tee to 89 yards and
Parnevik dropped a wedge onto the green. The ball spun back 2 feet
from the hole and the Europeans has another smart victory on No. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard and Stewart, all square when they stood on the tee, left
the sixth green 1 down.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Furyk and Mark O'Meara lost the hole, too, to Darren Clarke
and Lee Westwood, but theirs was a simple two-putt from 15 feet
after Westwood sank a birdie putt of 20 feet.
</P>
<P>
   After their opening day 6-2 lead, European captain Mark James
spoke about his team's approach. ``We're going to maintain the
focus and go out and shoot the lowest numbers we can and just try
to play our normal golf games: Hit fairways, hit greens.''
</P>
<P>
   Seems easy enough, doesn't it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
