<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-MATCH4-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ILL WIND BLOWS FOR STEWART, LEONARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ That wasn't a frontal system that moved
across The Country Club Saturday morning. It was a nasty European
weather pattern _ El Nino packing a Swedish deep freeze.
</P>
<P>
   After sweeping through the Americans twice Friday, Sergio Garcia
and Jesper Parnevik came back again to blow away Payne Stewart and
Justin Leonard, 3 and 2, in the second set of foursomes and picked
up a critical point for the defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played very, very well again,'' said Parnevik, after he and
his 19-year-old partner went 4 up after 11 and closed out the Yanks
on the 16th hole. Meanwhile, Stewart and Leonard, who hadn't played
together in the Friday foursomes, performed as though they'd been
thrown together on the practice range.
</P>
<P>
   After claiming the second hole when Garcia missed his par putt,
the Americans didn't win another until the 13th, when Stewart sank
a birdie putt from the fringe. By then, they were already on life
support. ``We just didn't play all that well,'' Leonard said with a
shrug after he and Stewart had bogeyed five holes.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Americans didn't have their chances. Leonard left a
beautiful long putt an inch short that would have won the seventh.
Stewart had a winner lip out on the 12th, missed another winner on
the 15th, and ended the match watching a 6-footer slide by.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans, meanwhile, followed the match-play book as though
they'd memorized it in nursery school. They sank key putts on the
front nine to halve holes they might have lost. They played well
within themselves. And when the chance came, Garcia and Parnevik
got their hosts in a hammerlock and slowly squeezed the life out of
them.
</P>
<P>
   All they needed was a bit of American bungling on the par-5
ninth. Stewart hooked his tee shot into the woods, then put his
approach into the rough. Leonard chipped past the hole, Stewart
missed the putt, and the Europeans were 2 up at the turn.
</P>
<P>
   Had Leonard's 30-foot putt not stopped just short on the 10th
and Garcia not made a pressure 15-footer for birdie, the US might
have been able to scramble back. Instead, after losing the 11th
when Stewart's chip from the rough ran comically long, the Yanks
were in deep trouble, 4 down with seven to play.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Europeans were marking anything up. ``Everybody
thinks 4 up is a huge gap but it's not,'' said Parnevik. ``All of a
sudden they make two birdies and we're only 2 up and anything can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, it looked as if anything might. Stewart sank a
putt from the fringe to win the 13th, then dropped another on the
14th to halve. But when Stewart missed and Garcia made to halve the
15th, the Europeans were dormie and the Yanks needed a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   When Leonard knocked his tee shot onto the green within reach of
the pin on the par-3 16th, it looked as if the US might stay alive
for at least another quarter hour. But Stewart watched the bird
take wing and El Nino and his Swedish playmate had another point in
their pockets. ``We're hanging in there and won on the 16th,''
mused Parnevik. ``And that's pretty good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
