<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-WOODS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATE A BOOST FOR WOODS' MORALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ The awkward look of terror and torment on
Tiger Woods's face finally melted away Saturday. Coupled with new
partner Steve Pate, the world's No. 1 golfer played day No. 2 of
the Ryder Cup, with his trademark confidence and courage.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, looking relaxed yet focused, made sensational iron shots
and ultimately clinched a 1-up victory in morning foursomes with a
clutch 25-foot putt on No. 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved it,'' said Woods, when asked what he thought of being
paired with the steady Pate, who was dropped into the Yanks' lineup
after sitting out Friday's matches. ``I absolutely loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pate, known for his sense of humor and well-liked by his peers,
at times appeared blase on The Country Club's lush loop Saturday.
Leading Miguel Angel Jimenez and Padraig Harrington 3 up, Pate
munched on an apple while scaling a hill on the sixth hole. Perhaps
this was the World Series of golf, but Pate had the air of a man
headed to a company picnic. Any second, his caddy might have pulled
a papier-mache red-and-white tablecloth from his bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood is pretty good,'' said Pate, who, in his only prior
Ryder Cup appearance in 1991, teamed with Corey Pavin for a loss,
only to exit when he was involved in a car crash in Kiawah Isle
(South Carolina). ``We know what we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Pate walks with a comfortable, leisurely swagger, the ying to
Woods's ramrod straight yang. It looked at times as if Pate were
providing Falstaffian relief for Woods, who, at 23, is
unquestionably talented, but also undeniably young.
</P>
<P>
   Woods wears an icon's crown and already is wealthy beyond
imagination, but the Ryder Cup has shown him to be uncomfortable,
unsettled, unsure. His suit of expectation needs tailoring, and
with Pate by his side, it appears he found a partner who fits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood is pretty upbeat,'' said Pate, who for a day was the
Yanks' pschological maestro. ``We're just ready to keep playing
golf.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
