u s BC-GLF-RYDER-MONTY-BOS &LR;      09-25 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-MONTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTGOMERIE PUTTING UP THE POINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ When European coach Mark James sent Colin
Montgomerie to the leadoff match with partner Paul Lawrie Saturday
morning at The Country Club, he was hoping to put a quick end to
any thoughts of a United States comeback.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen in a 1-up loss to Hal Sutton and Jeff Maggert,
but Montgomerie, in particular, made the Americans sweat down the
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colin's a wonderful player,'' said James. ``And the players
look to him for inspiration and leadership and respect his game
immensely. And he does set the tone, no question.''
</P>
<P>
   The 36-year-old Montgomerie took a 4-1-2 record from the 1997
and current Ryder Cups into Saturday's foursome match as well as
his usual repartee with a gallery whose pro-American slant really
got his competitive juices flowing.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Friday, when he and British Open champ Lawrie
dispatched Phil Mickelson and David Duval, then went all square
with Davis Love and Justin Leonard when Love sank a miracle
30-footer at 18, it was the Americans who finally knocked off
Montgomerie in team play.
</P>
<P>
   But this most veteran of European Ryder Cuppers didn't go down
without a fierce, and sometimes emotional fight.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie stepped away from a birdie putt at the sixth hole
when the some in the gallery hadn't stopped clapping and cheering
following a successful Sutton birdie.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton wasn't impressed with that display. ``I didn't want them
to call out to Colin,'' he said. ``What I wanted them to do was get
behind us a little bit more. I want the best for the European team.
I don't want anyone to treat them negatively in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   Monty answered the negative, loquacious few with a perfect putt,
then threw his arm and fist in the air. At 10, when his long chip
helped save par, there was a smile of acknowledgment, quickly
replaced by a determined look that there was serious work to do.
</P>
<P>
   That work was interrupted for 20 minutes when play was
suspended, and it appeared the Europeans would benefit: A poor
Sutton drive set up a winning par for Montgomerie and Lawrie to
even the match.
</P>
<P>
   It stayed that way until Maggert's heroics on 17 and 18, as the
American supporters, along each fairway, cheered ``USA, USA,'' in
counterpoint to the smaller bands of fans who yelled ``Monty,
Monty.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't let them down.
</P>
<P>
   At 15, Montgomerie put an iron shot a foot from the pin, forcing
Maggert to make an 8-footer for a matching birdie. At 16, he nailed
a 6-footer, dead-center for par to keep things even and at 17, he
put his approach shot 20 feet from the pin.
</P>
<P>
   But that's where Monty was finally upstaged. Maggert made a
clutch, 22-foot twisting birdie to win the hole and followed it
with a 7-iron to 18 that finally proved a Montgomerie team could
indeed be beaten by the Yanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's a very tiring week, mentally more than
physically,'' said Montgomerie. ``I just hope that I can get as
many points as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, that's been a lot of points for Montgomerie, who teed it
up again in the afternoon with Lawrie against Steve Pate and Tiger
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Four down, one to go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 1713EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
