<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5963 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-INDIANA-PENNSTATE     09-25 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-INDIANA-PENNSTATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASEY HAS THE RIGHT MOVES IN QUARTERBACK MATCHUP
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATE COLLEGE, Pa. _ All the publicity surrounding Penn State's
new wide-open passing offense was just talk Saturday against
Indiana. But the No. 2-ranked Nittany Lions received plenty of big
plays elsewhere to win, 45-24, in the Big Ten Conference opener for
both teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions' best weapon in heart-stopping victories over
Pittsburgh and Miami was resourcefulness. But Saturday, on a sunny
afternoon before 96,416 at Beaver Stadium, Penn State needed an
unexpected amount against the surprisingly game Hoosiers (1-3).
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Branch's 90-yard punt return for a touchdown and Rashard
Casey's 31-yard scramble for a score on Penn State's next
possession helped turn a 17-10 nail-biter into a 31-10 cushion in
the third quarter. Indiana stayed close behind its option
quarterback, Antwaan Randle El, but the Lions never led by less
than 14 in the final period.
</P>
<P>
   For all the hype accompanying Randle El into this game, Casey
was the dominant multiple threat. He completed 13 of 15 passes for
two touchdowns, and ran for 66 yards and a touchdown while still
alternating with Kevin Thompson (7 of 12 for 86 yards).
</P>
<P>
   Casey, of Hoboken, N.J., thrilled the crowd with his moves. The
Nittany Lions were leading by 24-10 early in the third quarter when
the Lions' Askari Adams recovered Derin Graham's muffed catch of a
punt at the Indiana 31. On the next play, Casey rolled right, cut
up field, broke a tackle, then switched fields again. For his
closing move, Casey swan-dived over the cone for a touchdown;
ninety-eight yard kickoff returns have taken less time.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions' defense had a trying day chasing Randle El. Penn
State Coach Joe Paterno had hoped his team would have a dominant
performance before next week's bye, but it did not happen.
</P>
<P>
   Randle El, who ran for 67 yards on 17 carries and completed 11
of 23 passes for 204 yards and two touchdowns, froze the Nittany
Lions on defense one last time, allowing him to throw a 27-yard
touchdown to Versie Gaddis to close Penn State's lead to 38-24 with
10 minutes 54 seconds left in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The first half was closer, and Penn State held an uncomfortable
17-10 lead going into the locker room. The Nittany Lions expected
to resurrect their rushing attack against the Big 10's worst
defense, but found themselves sputtering. Penn State managed just
78 yards on 24 carries before the half, and had to rely on a gift
turnover to get on the scoreboard after Indiana took a 3-0 lead on
Andy Payne's 40-yard field goal on the first drive.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana's second drive was rumbling along when Randle El threw
right to Adams as if he were part of the pass pattern. Adams then
weaved 37 yards down the left sideline for a touchdown with 8:11
left in the first quarter. The kick gave Penn State a 7-3 lead but
did nothing to assuage the unease of Paterno and crew.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson and Casey, who had shown big-play capability, relied on
short passes to combine for 11 of 12 completions for 152 yards. In
completing just 1 of 5 passes for 4 yards, Casey prematurely
released bullets that fluttered away from his receivers. But he was
exciting on the option.
</P>
<P>
   And his throw to tight end Tony Stewart at the start of the
second quarter stretched into a 30-yard gain that set up the
Nittany Lions with a first-and-goal at the Indiana 5.
</P>
<P>
   Fullback Aaron Harris backed 1 yard into the end zone two plays
later to increase the Nittany Lions' cushion to 14-3.
</P>
<P>
   Randle El, who is the Hoosiers' point guard on the basketball
team, leads the football team in passing, rushing and scoring. As a
quarterback he made a better running back in the first half. He
also has a propensity to make decisions at the last moment, even
while in a tackler's grasp. His derring-do guided Indiana on a
12-play drive of all running plays that he capped with a 1-yard
high-step for a touchdown to pull the Hoosiers within 14-10.
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions thought they had recovered a Randle-El fumble
a play earlier, but they were whistled for being offside.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nittany Lions last possession of the half, Penn State
turned to kicker Travis Forney. His 26-yard field goal was good to
make it 17-10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
