<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5964 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-BLEND-BOS &LR;      09-25 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-BLEND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARNEVIK-GARCIA MAGIC WONDERFUL TO WATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ One of them was 15 when the other was born.
One speaks Swedish, the other speaks Spanish. One eats herring, the
other eats (itals)huevos(unitals). One brought his wife here, the
other brought his mother. One is a captain's pick, the other a
wonderchild who made the team in a whirlwind five months. One
provides the chill, the other the duende.
</P>
<P>
   What Jesper Parnevik and Sergio Garcia have together is a
wondrous alchemy, a balance of skills and styles that has made them
the stars of the European team and the darlings of the gallery at
The Country Club this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Him and Sergio have just clicked,'' said European captain Mark
James, who put the 34-year-old Parnevik and the 19-year-old Garcia
together at their request as soon as they arrived here and has been
shrewd enough to leave well enough alone as they've ripped through
the American team.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia amuses Parnevik with his easy grin, his fist-pumping
enthusiasm, and his adolescent disregard for stress. ``Everyone
thinks he's just a rookie, but he's been around a long time,'' said
Parnevik. ``He made his first cut on the European tour when he was
15. Every time I need him, he's right there. Every time he needs to
hit a good shot, he does it. He's doing everything he has to do.
You can't ask for anything more.''
</P>
<P>
   And Parnevik, studying lies and lines interminably beneath his
flipped-up cap, settles and stabilizes ``El Nino.'' ``I'm so
confident with him,''' Garcia said after he and Parnevik had wiped
out Payne Stewart and Justin Leonard to remain unbeaten after
Saturday morning's foursomes. ``I'm so confident that he's going to
hit good shots and make some good putts. He's just perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   They are endearing co-conspirators, walking side by side along
the fairways, chatting and nodding and tipping their caps to the
R-dropping hordes on the far side of the ropes who've adopted them
as their favorite foreigners. ``I think it's the emotion,'' Garcia
said. ``They like us and that's very good. They're taking good care
of us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 1717EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5966 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-DEMS-0926-COX     09-25 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-0926-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHALLENGED BY BRADLEY, GORE MAKES EMOTIONAL PLEA FOR DEMOCRATIC
SUPPORT
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore shed his trademark formality
in an unusually emotional speech that energized powerful Democrats
on Saturday, the strongest indication yet that Gore understands the
formidable challenge he faces from Bill Bradley for the party's
2000 presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's performance at the close of the Democratic National
Committee's fall meeting was like no other in his campaign to date,
and it contrasted sharply with the low-key, plodding address that
Bradley delivered to the Democrats only minutes before.
</P>
<P>
   It came only one day after the release of a new CNN/Time poll in
which Gore, for the first time in the Democratic contest, trailed
Bradley in New Hampshire, the state that holds the first primary in
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, upon arriving at the hotel ballroom where
the DNC was concluding its three-day meeting, waded through the
crowd to reach the stage as the 1973 O'Jays classic ``Love Train''
added a pulse to the air. He did not even wait for Party Chairman
Joe Andrew to formally introduce him.
</P>
<P>
   And once on stage, Gore abandoned the lectern that had been
fixed with the vice presidential seal and wandered about the stage
in the style of a TV talk-show host, jabbing the air for emphasis,
especially when criticizing Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the
Republican presidential frontrunner.
</P>
<P>
   And while Gore did not mention any of the recent polls showing a
surge in Bradley's popularity, the vice president vowed that he
intends to ``work my heart out'' in order to win the presidential
nomination that only months ago seemed his for the taking.
</P>
<P>
   His exit followed a similar script. He shook hands with as many
of the 428 DNC members as he could. As he did, hundreds of Gore
campaign workers, confined to a ``guest'' area in the back of the
ballroom, waved ``Gore 2000'' placards in time with Shania Twain's
``Rock This Country,'' the informal theme song of the Gore
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, on the other hand, made a non-descript entry to the
stage after a formal introduction by Andrew. Bradley, too, brought
hundreds of poster-waving ``guests''' to the meeting. And he also
waded through the crowd after speaking.
</P>
<P>
   But the scholarly former senator, who has prided himself on his
plodding manner in the campaign, spoke in an understated delivery
with reading glasses perched atop his nose. And much of his speech
was designed to spell concerns about his allegiance to the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Gore supporters have occasionally raised that issue by citing
Bradley's criticism of the party at the time of his retirement from
the Senate in 1996 and his briefly flirtation with an independent
run against President Clinton that same year.
</P>
<P>
   They made their point at the DNC meeting Saturday by wearing
buttons that read, ``ALways a Democrat'' - with ``AL'' in blue and
the rest of the letters in red.
</P>
<P>
   The back-to-back speeches by Gore and Bradley marked the first
time the two foes have made a joint appearance before the same
crowd. And it occurred in an unusually charged atmosphere. Hotel
hallways, bars and restaurants were jammed with campaign officials
and activists trying to analyze the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It also produced the kind of logistical jockeying normally
expected later in the primary season. Gore was originally scheduled
to address the DNC first, but at the last minute demanded the final
speaking slot, apparently in an effort to leave the DNC members
with a lasting impression before they return to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley told the DNC members that he became a Democrat in 1964
after watching Barry Goldwater, the GOP's presidential nominee that
year, vote against the Civil Rights Act in the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Aware that much of the party establishment is backing Gore in
the two-man race, Bradley insisted that a ``spirited debate of
ideas'' between the two of them would help energize the party for
the general election contest against the GOP nominee.
</P>
<P>
   He congratulated the new general chair of the DNC, Philadelphia
Mayor Ed Rendell, who had previously endorsed Gore, and reported
Rendell's promise that ``things will be fair'' in the Democratic
contest.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that such party luminaries as House Leader Dick Gephardt
and Senate Leader Tom Daschle are supporting the vice president, he
added, ``I want you to know. . . whether you are for me or against
me that we share that same goal of mutual respect.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Democratic contest should be conducted in a manner
that shows disaffected voters that ``politics doesn't have to be
about negative campaigning, that it could be about ideas.'' And he
said the nominee should be chosen by ``the people,'' not the party
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley credited the Clinton-Gore administration with being ``a
good steward of a good economy,'' but asked, ``What else is there
to do?'' He promised to champion gun control, expansion of health
insurance coverage, campaign finance reform, anti-poverty programs
and improving race relations.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore did not mention his challenger by name, he seized
on the fact that Bradley had not mentioned abortion rights, Social
Security, Medicare and collective bargaining rights. He vowed to
make all of them a priority in his administration.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also offered a veiled criticism of his challenger's having
once supported a limited experiment with vouchers in trying to
improve public schools. ``I have never been for vouchers,'' he
declared.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's sharpest criticism was aimed at Bush, with his most
direct reference to the Texas governor yet. He questioned the
decision of the ``the current Republican frontrunner'' to oppose
hate crime legislation in Texas or to support a state law
protecting gun manufacturers from lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   He reminded the audience of Bush's comment that ``a wave of
evil'' was responsible for recent shooting tragedies in schools and
churches around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is evil stalking the land ... evil has always been with
us,'' he said. ``We have the power to overcome evil with good.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I would say to the current Republican frontrunner _
Why don't you join us in the effort to take the weapons of evil out
of the hands of evil-doers. That would do a lot of good in this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 1736EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
