<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5968 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-TOBACCO-RDP-1STLD-WRI     09-25 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1050(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE GOVERNMENT'S INQUIRY INTO TOBACCO LOST ITS STEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to delete `tens of' from lede graf and to make changes in 3rd
and 4th grafs for precision. Inserts William Hendricks in 14th
graf. Deletes half of 19th graf. Rewrites 2nd and 3rd grafs of 2nd
take for precision. Deletes 3rd name from byline.)  (mk) 
 By BARRY MEIER with DAVID JOHNSTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After five years and millions of dollars, the Justice
Department's criminal investigation of the tobacco industry boiled
down to this: one misdemeanor charge against an obscure
biotechnology company.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had scrutinized whether industry executives lied and
perjured themselves in 1994, when they testified before Congress
that cigarettes were not addictive.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators had plowed through corporate documents for
evidence that cigarette makers manipulated the level of nicotine in
their product. Whistle-blowers were interviewed by prosecutors, and
company scientists testified before grand juries.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, Attorney General Janet Reno announced a broad
civil lawsuit accusing cigarette makers of racketeering and fraud
and seeking to recover billions in health-care costs related to
smoking. Justice officials also publicly acknowledged a decision
that had been clear for months _ that the criminal inquiry had been
closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a case that the criminal division decided they were not
likely to win,'' said a Justice Department official.
</P>
<P>
   How the government's investigation of an entire industry came to
an end without producing indictments is the story of an ambitious
effort made more difficult by the complex science of cigarette
making, disagreements between federal officials, disappointing
witnesses and an unfavorable court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, prosecutors faced the problem of proving beyond a
reasonable doubt that cigarette makers had knowingly misled the
public and regulators about the health risks of smoking and the
addictive nature of nicotine. Faced this spring with expiring
deadlines for filing a criminal action, the government chose an
easier course, a civil lawsuit in which its burden of proof would
be lower.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the criminal inquiry began, cigarette companies have
denied that they misled the government about their knowledge of the
health hazards of smoking or that they manipulated nicotine levels
to keep smokers smoking. In the last two years, the nation's
biggest tobacco companies have agreed to pay $246 billion over 25
years to settle lawsuits filed by states to recover health care
costs related to smoking and signed consent agreements not to
misrepresent the hazards of smoking.
</P>
<P>
   In responding to the government's lawsuit last week, tobacco
companies asked why the Justice Department had chosen to charge
them with crimes in a civil suit, when it had dropped its criminal
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``One cannot help but question the department's motives in
making those same allegations under the guise of a quasi-criminal''
case, said Kenneth Handal, associate general counsel for Philip
Morris Cos., ``after it found no basis for bringing those same
charges in its criminal investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   With Philip Morris, the other defendants in the civil suit are
Brown &AMP; Williamson, a division of BAT Industries PLC; R.J. Reynolds
Tobacco Co.; Lorillard Tobacco Co., a division of Loews Corp.;
Liggett Group, a division of the Brooke Group, and two now-defunct
trade groups, the Council for Tobacco Research USA Inc. and the
Tobacco Institute Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's criminal inquiry goes back to April 14,
1994, when seven top executives of cigarette companies stood before
Congress during the hearing about the risks of their products and
swore that nicotine was not addictive and that no one had proved
that smoking caused cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after, Rep. Martin Meehan, D-Mass., sent a memorandum to
Reno urging her to investigate the executives for possible perjury
because of the mass of scientific evidence on the addictiveness of
nicotine and the link between smoking and cancer. The assignment
was passed on to Jimmye Warren, a senior trial lawyer in the
Justice Department's fraud section, who decided to look into the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Proving perjury, however, is extremely difficult, and the
tobacco industry wasted little time mounting a counteroffensive.
Three lawyers hired by cigarette makers, including Robert Fiske,
the original Whitewater prosecutor, and William Hendricks, a former
top Justice official, soon went to the Justice Department to argue
that lawmakers had asked broad questions and that the executives
had expressed their beliefs, for which they could not be
prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than ending, the investigation mushroomed. By 1995,
thousands of secret Brown &AMP; Williamson documents taken from a law
firm by a paralegal, Merrell Williams, suggested that the company
had long known about the risks of smoking. States including
Mississippi, Minnesota and Florida had sued cigarette makers, and
the discovery process would produce millions more documents. And
whistle-blowers like Jeffrey Wigand, a former top executive at
Brown &AMP; Williamson, had also appeared to accuse industry officials
of lying about their products' addictive nature.
</P>
<P>
   By 1996, federal prosecutors had convened grand jury inquiries
in Alexandria, Va.; Brooklyn and Manhattan in New York; the
District of Columbia and New Orleans, to investigate the tobacco
industry.
</P>
<P>
   One Justice task force was investigating whether Philip Morris
had illegally manipulated the level of nicotine in cigarettes to
keep smokers addicted. A second group was investigating whether
R.J. Reynolds, despite its denials, was aiming its advertising at
underage smokers. A third was looking into whether Brown &AMP;
Williamson had made false statements to federal officials about
efforts to genetically engineer seeds to produce plants with higher
nicotine levels.
</P>
<P>
   After infighting among the different jurisdictions, top
officials at the Justice Department in Washington took control of
the grand jury investigations in mid-1996 and consolidated them. It
became the government's most significant prosecutorial effort aimed
at a single consumer product.
</P>
<P>
   The potential criminal violations under investigation were
broad, including accusations of fraud, conspiracy, racketeering,
obstruction and perjury against tobacco executives.
</P>
<P>
   But law enforcement officials said that the criminal inquiry led
into a succession of dead ends. Several prosecution theories were
tried, including sweeping charges of a pattern of deceitful
conduct. Senior officials concluded that they were not likely to
prevail in a criminal trial.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At one point, prosecutors weighed whether they could file a
criminal racketeering complaint, using a federal law usually
applied against organized crime and drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   That approach would have permitted authorities to use industry
documents dating back decades that showed company officials
plotting strategies over how to deflect public concerns about
smoking risks. And a senior FBI official involved in the tobacco
inquiry said he and other agents had urged such an approach.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Department officials decided to bring a simpler
fraud case. It would show a more recent pattern of misconduct, but
it also had a problem: Any indictment would have to be brought this
year because of the statute of limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually that approach was also abandoned because of the
difficulties in showing that executives had intentionally and
fraudulently misled the government about the dangers of tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators unearthed evidence showing that the executives had
maneuvered carefully in their communications with regulators around
issues like nicotine addiction, often guided by lawyers who advised
them on nearly every major action. At one point, government
prosecutors considered bringing charges against those lawyers but
then dropped that possibility because it would have been a
difficult legal hurdle, said one plaintiffs' lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Osdene, the head of research at Philip Morris for nearly
two decades, was viewed by many plaintiffs' lawyers as a witness
whose testimony in the criminal inquiry might spell doom for the
industry. Documents indicated that Osdene had shifted the company's
sensitive nicotine research abroad, apparently to avoid scrutiny by
regulators, and possibly destroyed important records. Two FBI
agents arrived at Osdene's home in Richmond, Va., in 1996 with a
subpoena for any Philip Morris documents he had retained.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Osdene tried to strike an immunity deal with the
Justice Department, but his offer was rejected. Several lawyers
knowledgeable about the case said that he later reached such an
agreement with prosecutors, but added that any testimony he might
have given did not affect events. Osdene did not return telephone
calls. His lawyer, John Nields, declined to comment on whether
Osdene had been granted immunity.
</P>
<P>
   The company that faced the greatest danger was Brown &AMP;
Williamson, because it was the only producer notified by the
government that it was a target of its investigation. Prosecutors
were looking at whether company officials had, among other things,
lied to the Food and Drug Administration during meetings in 1994
when they said they had not developed genetically engineered
tobacco seeds with enhanced nicotine levels.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators discovered that such a seed, code-named Y-1, had been
developed for Brown &AMP; Williamson by a small biotechnology company,
DNA Plant Technology Corp. of Oakland, Calif. And in the first and
only charge brought in the criminal case, Justice Department
officials accused the firm of conspiring with a cigarette maker to
produce nicotine-enriched tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, DNA Plant Technology pleaded guilty to a
misdemeanor count of conspiring to illegally export the Y-1 seeds
and agreed to cooperate in the government's continuing inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Brown &AMP; Williamson officials were soon brought to testify before
a grand jury in Washington. But that inquiry also died. Raymond
Marshall, a lawyer in San Francisco who represented DNA Plant
Technology, said he never heard from Justice Department officials
again.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the government's inquiry suffered a setback when a
federal appeals court ruled that the FDA did not have authority to
regulate tobacco, raising doubts about the ability of prosecutors
to bring charges that companies had made false statements to the
agency. In a separate ruling, another judge declined to give
prosecutors access to certain Brown &AMP; Williamson records, saying
that they were confidential.
</P>
<P>
   Both enthusiasm and time were running out. By early this year,
prosecutors were assigned to different jobs, and it was clear, said
industry lawyers, that indictments were highly unlikely because
statutes of limitations were expiring.
</P>
<P>
   In January, President Clinton abruptly announced during his
State of the Union address that the Justice Department planned to
file a civil lawsuit against the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic lawmakers like Sens. Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts
and Kent Conrad of North Dakota had met with Reno to urge such
action last year, after the collapse of tobacco legislation in the
Senate. And for a time, officials in the Justice Department's civil
division had debated whether to bring such a suit.
</P>
<P>
   But G. Robert Blakey, a Notre Dame University law professor who
consulted with Kennedy and Conrad, said the president's speech had
sounded the starting bell that resulted in last week's filing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the president hadn't told them to do it, they would still
be debating,'' Blakey said. ``It was basically a thunderclap.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
