<HEADER>
A5971 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-COLOMBI     09-25 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-COLOMBIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOMBIA'S TRAGEDY, CAPTURED IN CLOSE-UPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By TINA ROSENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an Editorial Observer piece on
Sunday, Sept. 26:
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to be numbed by the panorama of violence raging in
Colombia. Drug killings, paramilitary massacres, guerrilla
kidnappings, death squad murders and street crime have all
intertwined. Diarrhea and tuberculosis get less attention in some
public health reports than the disease of the sicario, or hired
killer _ which often takes the form of two young men, a motorcycle
and a .38.
</P>
<P>
   Violence becomes human and real, however, in the films of Victor
Gaviria. Gaviria has made two movies set in what is perhaps the
world's most deadly neighborhood, the slums of the northeastern
hills surrounding Medellin. ``Rodrigo D.: No Future,'' which came
out in 1990, and last year's ``Rose Seller'' depict the aimless
brutality suffered by, and inflicted by, young people in these
slums. The films are fiction but have an authenticity because the
actors are themselves the criminals, gang members and street
children they portray. They often meet the same fates as their
characters. Since ``Rodrigo D.'' was filmed in 1986 _ a year when
Medellin's leading cause of death was multiple gunshot wounds _
nine of its leading actors have been murdered.
</P>
<P>
   The films tug at reality in other ways. ``Rodrigo D.'' _ which
won various prizes _ shocked Medellin and Colombia, and sparked a
national attempt to help the children. But violence still dominates
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Gaviria, from Medellin's middle class, was told about life in
the slums a short distance from his house by the grandson of an
actor in one of his earlier films. Few in beautiful, green and
prosperous Medellin knew of the city's slums. By Colombian
standards, the slums, with their sturdy brick houses, are not poor.
</P>
<P>
   The question of why entire neighborhoods seem bent on dying in
the street has produced a local science called violentology.
Colombia's violentologists believe that the breakdown of community
values matters far more than income. Medellin's slums were mostly
settled by some of the 3 million people who fled political violence
in Colombia's countryside during the 1950s, an uprooting that
stripped them of their traditional way of life and sense of
community. Then came the rise of cocaine in the late 1970s. The
employer of choice in the slums, where there were few other jobs,
became the legendary drug lord Pablo Escobar.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs led to another sort of breakdown, the absence of a working
government. Crime swamped Colombia's courts, which were never
functional, and now the slums feature a form of privatized justice.
People settle scores not with trials, but by hiring sicarios. Drug
addiction is terminated not in treatment clinics, but by death
squads with names such as ``Death to Addicts,'' which enjoy wide
popular support.
</P>
<P>
   The character of Rodrigo D., a sullen boy of 17 who wants to
start a punk band, was played by Ramiro Meneses. Meneses, now in
his early 30s, has become a successful actor in Bogota. But nine
other actors were murdered, some in acts of revenge for their
crimes. One actor, who habitually robbed bus drivers, was murdered
by sicarios hired by a group of drivers, Gaviria said. Another, who
helped write the film script, was killed by sicarios hired by the
family of a man he had attacked.
</P>
<P>
   For ``The Rose Seller,'' an adaptation of Hans Christian
Andersen's ``Little Match Girl,'' Gaviria spent two months looking
for actors among the neighborhood's street children. He then rented
a house for his actors, and put them through nine months of
improvisational exercises and training in such basics as not
looking at the camera. He asked them about their lives _ ``What
would you do if someone stole your boyfriend?'' _ and fed the
answers back into the developing script. It centers on the day
before Christmas in the life of 13-year-old Monica, a runaway from
a sexually abusive home who lives by selling roses to diners in
posh restaurants and the occasional purse-snatching. Filming took
five more months.
</P>
<P>
   The actors were a challenge. ``These are very disorganized kids
who live completely in the present,'' says Gaviria. ``You couldn't
call a meeting for tomorrow because they'd forget.'' But he found a
wealth of talent. ``Street children are already actors,'' he says.
``They spend all day putting on masks, fooling people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaviria feels that the filming affected them. ``With all their
hyperactivity, their focus on the present, they don't reflect much
on what happens to them,'' he says. ``They told me that
participating made them examine where they are.'' Some went back to
school. A rose seller named Lady Tabares, who played Monica, now
lives in a house paid for with money collected by local
journalists. She still sells flowers, although she and her
colleagues are now celebrities to their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Gaviria's films have had a wider impact as well. ``There was an
imaginary Berlin wall we had built between the rich city and these
northeastern neighborhoods,'' says Maria Emma Mejia, a co-producer
of ``Rodrigo D.'' who became the nation's commissioner for the
security of Medellin just after the film's release, and later
foreign minister. The strategy for Medellin was originally based
purely on increasing the security force presence in those
neighborhoods, she says. `` `Rodrigo D.' shocked us into realizing
that this would have been a terrible mistake.'' She created drop-in
centers, better schools, classes in auto mechanics and sewing,
micro-enterprise projects, discussion groups and a television show
with neighborhood youths talking about their problems.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she says, some of the schools and other projects are
still there, but the budget is gone for most. The slums are no less
violent. The right-wing paramilitary leader Carlos Castano has
replaced Pablo Escobar, now dead, as the local patron. Slum youth
not only kill each other, but are also hired to kill union
activists and other leftists. There is also, Gaviria says, a small
left-wing guerrilla presence. ``I would say I got to know 100 kids
as friends during my time as commissioner,'' says Ms. Mejia. ``Four
or five of them are still alive today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
