<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIVORCE-SCANDAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVORCE-COURT SCANDAL SPURS FEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Metin Erkin responded to the news with a single,
panicked question: ``What are you telling me, that my divorce is no
good?''
</P>
<P>
   And Svim Erkin, who thought she became the former Mrs. Erkin
months ago, responded with equal fright. ``I don't want to go
through it again,'' she pleaded. ``I don't want to be married in
any way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Erkins, a Staten Island couple who thought they divorced
last year, are among hundreds of New York ex-couples ensnared in a
bribery scandal in the Manhattan divorce court. Their lawyer,
Joseph Canepa of Queens, is accused of paying Steven Singer, the
chief divorce court clerk in Manhattan, $100 to $150 to expedite
and not closely review their uncontested divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Singer, who pleaded guilty to three counts of
bribery on Sept. 17 in state Supreme Court in Manhattan, is at the
center of a bribery network under investigation that may involve as
many as 20 other lawyers and court officials. They said the bribes
_ which were largely paid by low-cost, high-volume law offices and
businesses known as ``divorce mills'' _ totaled tens of thousands
of dollars and involved hundreds of cases dating from 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Court officials said that the divorces like the Erkins' that are
now being reviewed by prosecutors and court auditors will remain
valid unless problems are uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have said they fear that some spouses, particularly
poor and immigrant women, may have been victimized by spouses who
forged their signatures on divorce settlements that involved scant
child support or alimony. Another unintended consequence of the
scandal could be that in a handful of cases, people who thought
they were divorced and have remarried may now be unwitting
bigamists.
</P>
<P>
   As news of the bribes spread last week, several anxious people
called the court system to see if they were, in fact, divorced,
court officials said. ``We are reassuring them, to the extent we
can, and indicating to them that these matters were also
individually reviewed by judges,'' said John Werner, chief clerk of
the Manhattan state Supreme Court's civil branch.
</P>
<P>
   Jewell R. Wilson, 42, a Bronx woman who said she never received
any divorce papers from her estranged husband, was one of those who
called. She wants court officials to investigate her case. ``I have
absolutely no idea if I'm divorced,'' she said Friday. ``The only
reason I think I'm divorced is that my daughter was at his
wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she did not know if Wilson used one of the lawyers or
law offices accused of making bribes. She said she received
court-ordered child support. Divorce records are sealed, so it was
not possible to confirm any link to the investigation. Efforts to
reach her former husband, Benjamin Wilson, 45, by telephone were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read about this, it just sounded so much like the man I
used to be married to,'' Ms. Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Yi Chen of Commack and his presumed ex-wife, Yan Yu Chen,
are another couple ensnared in the scandal. Canepa, the Queens
lawyer, is accused of bribing Singer in June 1998 to expedite the
Chens' uncontested divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Yi Chen's daughter said in a telephone interview on Thursday
that her father was not home but that he had remarried after her
parents divorced. Ben Yi Chen did not return repeated calls to his
home or office requesting comment. Efforts to reach Yan Yu Chen
were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach other couples listed in the indictment filed
against Singer were also unsuccessful. But the Erkins, the Staten
Island couple, probably summed up the group's feelings. The
ex-husband and ex-wife agreed that they did not want to relive
their divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Erkin, 31, a payroll manager for a Manhattan company, said he
had no knowledge of the reputed bribes and said his wife fully
agreed with the terms of their divorce. The couple had no children
and little property to divide, he said. (She got the apartment.)
</P>
<P>
   ``She wanted it more than I did,'' he said, referring to the
divorce. ``I brought her the papers. She went to the notary and did
everything. Let the district attorney call my ex-wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Erkin, 28, an administrative assistant, also said she had no
knowledge of any bribes and signed the divorce papers herself. ``I
actually had it notarized,'' she said, her voice tinged with dread.
``I hope everything is all right. I hope this doesn't affect me in
any way.''
</P>
<P>
   But court officials said that in cases in which the couples
agreed to the terms, the divorces should remain legal and valid.
</P>
<P>
   That was welcome news to Ms. Erkin. She and her ex-husband live
near each other and occasionally bump into each other on the bus.
The two get along fairly well, she said, but revisiting such a
tender subject is something that she, like so many divorcees, would
definitely prefer to avoid. ``We're still friends _ we talk,'' she
said. ``We don't hate each other, not that much anyway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
