<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREAN MINISTER URGES U.S. TO LIFT ECONOMIC EMBARGO 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Following its decision to suspend missile
testing, North Korea demanded Saturday that the United States
respond with its own ``good deeds,'' including an end to
Washington's longstanding economic embargo against Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is fortunate that the United States has recently decided to
partially lift economic sanctions,'' North Korean Foreign Minister
Paek Nam Sun said in a speech during the annual debate at the U.N.
General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``However,'' Paek continued, ``we look forward to the
comprehensive and actual lifting of all economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Once the United States stops treating North Korea like an enemy,
Paek said, ``and moves toward improved relations, we will also
respond with good faith.''
</P>
<P>
   North Korea has promised not to test any long-range ballistic
missiles during its current talks with the United States. The
official Korean Central News Agency said Saturday that the tests
would be suspended ``in order to create a more favorable
atmosphere'' for the talks, which are scheduled to resume next
month.
</P>
<P>
   The North Koreans tested its last long-range missile by firing
it over Japan, frightening the Japanese. There have been fears that
North Korea might mark its 50th anniversary as a Communist state by
firing a newer missile that is believed to have a longer range and
to be able to reach Hawaii and Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Paek reiterated Pyongyang's contention that it
intended only to launch a peaceful satellite in order to catch up
with its neighbors in the field of peaceful space activity. ``We
would be ready for discussions on the missile issue at any time if
hostile nations are sincere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Responding cautiously to questions at a news conference later,
the foreign minister insisted that Pyongyang has ``thoroughly
frozen'' its nuclear activities. But he left little doubt that the
moratorium on testing missiles was temporary. If North Korea
decided that it needed to launch a missile, he told reporters, ``we
will launch.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Paek described Japan's reactions to North Korea's
last missile test as ``hysterical''. He called the protests a ruse
to cover up Japan's failure to make moral and financial amends for
``crimes'' against Koreans who lived under Japanese occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a tougher line against Japan than against the United
States, Paek accused Tokyo of ``fabricating threats'' in order to
re-arm itself and re-emerge as a military power.
</P>
<P>
   But Paek emphasized that his country did not consider the United
States a permanent enemy, and said that Pyongyang had shown good
faith in five years of bilateral talks with the Americans. In
addition to lifting the trade embargo, Paek said that the United
States should sign a peace treaty with North Korea, ending their 50
years of belligerency.
</P>
<P>
   Asked later what Pyongyang specifically expected of Washington,
the North Korean foreign minister said that the lifting of
sanctions should be ``comprehensive,'' and ``should be translated
into action.'' This seemed to imply that in addition to food and
economic aid, Washington should promote trade with Pyongyang, which
was brought to the brink of collapse by famine and ideological
mismanagement of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the extended olive branch, Paek returned several times
to the saber-rattling that characterized North Korea's posture for
so many years. If the United States tried to test his country's
military power or subjugate its people, he said, ``Such reckless
acts will surely be inviting our strong self-defense measures,
eventually causing catastrophic consequences.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
