<SLUG> BC-STORING-STUFF-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: STORING ALL THAT EXTRA STUFF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Vt., N.J., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Is your stuff getting to be too much for your
apartment? Maybe it's time to rent an apartment for your stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all seem to have so much extra stuff,'' said Chris McGrath,
president of the New York Self Storage Association, a trade
organization based in Albany. ``And after a while most folks,
especially folks in the city, find they need just a little more
space for their things.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrath, who owns self-storage businesses in upstate New York
and Vermont, said that storage facilities can range from
bare-bones, no-frills affairs at bargain-basement rents to
structures with electrical service, 24-hour availability and
security systems using motion detectors, closed-circuit television
and pass-key-activated entry gates and doors. Some high-rent units
are even climate-controlled to protect valuable furniture and
furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you need will often depend on who you are and where you
are,'' McGrath said, explaining that those who vacation in the same
area every year but do not own a vacation home might want to rent a
small no-frills storage locker nearby to avoid having to transport
clothes, beach chairs, skis, fishing gear, bicycles, rubber rafts
and even rowboats.
</P>
<P>
   Those who may need to store fine furniture, artwork or antiques,
he said, might want to spend the extra money for a
climate-controlled storage locker _ one designed to eliminate
excess humidity _ to insure that their valuables are not damaged by
mold or mildew.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath said that someone who has to store lots of furniture for
a short period probably should rent the smallest locker necessary
and pack it as efficiently as possible. But, he said, those who
need long-term storage and access on a fairly regular basis might
want to rent a slightly larger locker and pack it for ease of
access. ``You might want to leave an aisle open down the center and
not pile things up too high,'' he said, adding that it is also wise
to try to anticipate what will be needed most often and load those
things closest to the door.
</P>
<P>
   But how does one estimate how much storage space is enough?
``That's what we're here for,'' said Tom Tresnan, general manager
of Lackland Associates, a self-storage facility in Middlesex, N.J.
``Our managers are trained to consult with people when they come in
and give them a good idea of how much space they need.''
</P>
<P>
   Tresnan, who is also president of the New Jersey Self Storage
Association, said that there are some basic guidelines for
estimating space. For example, he said, a person with three or four
rooms of furniture could probably get by with a storage unit as
small as 10 by 10 feet, if the items are packed efficiently. ``But
different units have different ceiling heights,'' he said, and
renters should try to find lockers with the highest ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   Other things to look for, he said, are hours of operation,
security measures and cleanliness. ``Is the place well-lit and
well-fenced?'' he said. ``Do they have a computerized gate access
system and surveillance cameras? And will you be able to get access
to your goods when you want to?''
</P>
<P>
   Most storage facilities in urban and suburban areas, Tresnan
said, do not provide 24-hour access. Many have extended hours, he
said _ generally from 6 a.m. to 9 or 10 p.m. _ and some will allow
off-hours access if arrangements are made in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Customers should also find out if extermination services are
provided on a regular basis. ``We tell all our tenants that they
cannot store any foodstuffs or perishables in their lockers,''
Tresnan said. ``But once somebody puts their lock on the door, we
have no way of knowing what's inside.''
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, Tresnan said, rents for storage lockers are paid
monthly, in advance. Generally speaking, he said, rents in suburban
areas can run from $40 a month for a five-by-five-foot locker with
a seven-foot ceiling to about $130 a month for a 10- by 10- by
10-foot unit.
</P>
<P>
   In urban areas, of course, the rents are typically higher. Neal
Eisenstein, vice president of sales and marketing for Manhattan
Mini Storage, a storage company with 13 locations in Manhattan,
some of which are open 24 hours a day, said that his prices can
range from $48 a month for a four-by-four-foot locker five feet
high to $700 a month for a 9-by-18-foot unit with a 10-foot
ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenstein said that since homeowners' insurance policies in New
York generally do not cover personal possessions not on the insured
premises, his company encourages customers to make sure they get
additional insurance for items in storage. If customers do not have
homeowners' or renters' policies, he said, they can purchase a
Keepsake Protection Plan from Manhattan Mini Storage for as little
as $6 a month per $1,000 of stored goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people think about most when putting their things in
storage is peace of mind,'' he said. ``Sometimes people find that
when they put stuff into storage it gives them a new feeling of
freedom from clutter. Some people even think of their storage
locker as an extra closet down the street. And then there are
others who put the lock on the door and don't come back for
years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
