<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METEOROLOGY LEAVES SOMETHING TO BE DESIRED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ The rains started Saturday as an annoying
drizzle, and then turned into a dangerous downpour. Fans headed for
the nearest overhand, pulled out their ponchos and put up their
umbrellas. Due to the weather and threat of lightening, PGA
tournament officials suspended play at 9:45 a.m. for 20 minutes.
The rain caught many spectators unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched the Weather Channel (Friday night) and was here
(Friday),'' said Brian Manton of Lisle, Ill. ``The Weather Channel
said today would be even better than (Friday) with a passing shower
in the morning. I thought it would rain for 10 or 15 minutes. I
left my one waterproof jacket back at the hotel. The Boston
meterologists leave a lot to be desired.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Teacher's pet
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He is a professional golf instructor, but there are days when
Shawn Callahan goes to work and stops what he's doing to watch the
student. That's because the student is Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan, 37, whose father Don is the longtime head pro (now
director of golf) at The Country Club, is on the staff at the Butch
Harmon School of Golf in Las Vegas. In that capacity, Callahan has
had many opportunities to watch Woods, whose incredible talents are
even more impressive when viewed close up, said the teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes out 8 to 10 times a year. He likes to relax, fool
around, then work out. People don't know how hard he works.
Amazing, but every time I see him he strikes it better. I don't
know how he does it.''
</P>
<P>
   There was the round of golf they played recently when Callahan,
a solid 3-handicap who can move it pretty good off the tee, slammed
one about 310 yards on a par 5 that measured 630 yards. ``We were
trash-talking all around,'' said Callahan, ``and I said, `Don't
even try to catch that one. You'll hurt yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Woods answered with a ferocious swing. ``He nailed one
and we stepped it off at 396 yards.'' Callahan was laughing.
``Unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, Don Callahan served as the assistant under the
legendary Claude Harmon, Butch's father.
</P>
<P>
   Claude, the former Masters champ, was beloved in the industry
and Don Callahan found his way in this business thanks to his
guidance. From Winged Foot in the summer, Harmon and Callahan would
work winters at Thunderbird in Palm Springs, Calif. Callahan took
the job at The Country Club and eventually replaced Harmon as head
pro at Thunderbird, too.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Don Callahan has been friendly with Butch Harmon for
years. ``When I had the offer to work for (Butch), I went to see
him to make sure the job was for me and not because I was Don's
son,'' said Shawn.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously he heard something he liked because he joined Harmon's
staff nearly three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I took the job in Houston, Butch said, `Don't buy
furniture because I'm going to set up a golf school in Vegas.' I've
been there since Christmas of '97 and everything is going well.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Painful memories
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He will be watching the Ryder Cup Matches from his home in
Texas, and Jacky Cupit will be thrilled if the US wins. But pardon
him if he watches with bittersweet thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest memory I have (of The Country Club) is a bad
memory,'' said Cupit, whose double-bogey on the 71st hole cost him
a chance to win the 1963 US Open. He parred 18 to get into a
playoff, which he lost to Julius Boros.
</P>
<P>
   Though it is a bad memory, it is very clear one.
``Communications were not as good as they are today. I had a
one-shot lead, but didn't know it, so I hit a 3-wood off the tee.''
</P>
<P>
   Cupit, who was 25 at the time and an unheralded player, drove it
directly at the infamous Vardon Bunker at the corner of the dogleg
left 17th. Just ahead of him, Arnold Palmer had three-putted, so
Cupit now had a two-shot lead. He didn't know that, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had stayed in the sand I would have been OK, but it went
through and into rough on a very steep slope where the grass was
real tall. With the lie, my only shot was to get it back to the
fairway.''
</P>
<P>
   Cupit did, but he got too cute with his third shot from 80
yards, and it ended up 30 feet from the pin. Three putts later, he
had made a double and dropped into a tie for the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said it cost me the tournament,'' said Cupit, 61, who
still plays a lot of golf after undergoing major heart surgery four
years ago, ``but who knows what would have happened on 18 had I
made par at 17? And at 18 I had a putt to win, from 15 feet, but it
just stayed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big disappointment. A huge disappointment. But I
really didn't get down on myself because I was young and thought I
would have a lot more opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I never did get that chance again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Campbell paved the way
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If there is one sure winner in these 33d Ryder Cup Matches, it
would have to be Willie Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Campbell?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Willie Campbell, the first golf professional at The Country
Club, who credited for the original design of this classic layout
in 1894. That should be memorable enough, but he also moved down
the street and convinced Boston officials that the city needed to
encourage the game. Thus, the city's Franklin Park golf course was
born.
</P>
<P>
   History, all of it, has become the passion of Brian DeLacey of
Jamaica Plain. He became intrigued about the course at Franklin
Park and started looking into its history, which led him to
Campbell and The Country Club, and to Musselburgh, Scotland.
Musselburgh, along with Prestwick and St. Andrews, is important to
the history of golf, and DeLacey has been there several times to
research a book on Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   To pay tribute to Campbell, who died at age 38, DeLacey put
together a small ceremony Friday night. It began at the gates of
The Country Club, with a procession to the golf course at Franklin
Park, then to Forest Hills Cemetery, where Campbell is buried.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Police Gaelic Column of Pipes &AMP; Drums took part in
the ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Faces in the crowd
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Bush was back for the second day of Ryder Cup competion
and spotted in the media tent area . . . Financial guru Peter Lynch
could be seen on tiptoes trying to get a view of hole No. 15. He
was wearing a patriotic stars and stripes Polo shirt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Shira Springer and Jim McCabe of the Globe Staff contriubted to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
