<P>
   WACO-JUDGE _ WACO, Texas _ The Branch Davidian case will be U.S.
District Judge Walter Smith's signature. The son of a Marlin
doctor, Smith, 59, tried law school while waiting to get back his
tests for med school. He liked the law so much he forgot all about
medicine. He's got a pro-government reputation but predicting his
rulings isn't as easy as some think. A Republican in McLennan
County when it wasn't cool, he nonetheless once headed the Waco
Legal Aid Clinic. (England, Waco Tribune-Herald) WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   FOSTERCARE _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Bruce Maag, the founder and
president of a private foster-care agency responsible for 1,300
children in seven states, surrendered his license to take kids into
his own home just before he pleaded guilty in 1987 to contributing
to the delinquency of a minor. (Jasper/Jaspin/Wagner, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CARTER-BDAY _ Jimmy Carter's 75th birthday comes this week. He
talks about his life today, and how he remains active and vigorous.
He says he understands his lifespan, does not grieve over it, and
does not fear death. This, he says, is the happiest time of his
life. He's working to ensure that the Carter Center outlives him,
and working to preserve the history of his family. Those who know
him say he is comfortable now with the Jimmy Carter life story, and
this is a mellower, happier Carter than in the past. (Melvin, Cox
News Service). 65. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CARTER-MILLENNIUM _ Jimmy Carter has been peering into the new
millennium, and he doesn't like what he sees. The chasm between the
worlds rich and the world's poor, he says, widens every year and
the trend looks irreversible. And he is embarrassed that the United
States has become ``the stingiest country in the world,'' and that
``foreign aid'' has become a political epithet. (Melvin, Cox News
Service). 20. MOVED
</P>
