<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-HUNTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: OPEN SEASON FOR HUNTERS IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NELSON BRYANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Late summer's searing persistence made it difficult for hunters
to think of tramping the woods in quest of deer or upland birds, or
huddling in a duck blind on a cold, gray dawn. But Canada goose and
ruffed grouse hunting is under way and the seasons for other
species are about to begin in some areas of New York state.
</P>
<P>
   The state's huge area and varied topography and wildlife habitat
call for a complicated set of hunting regulations, and all nimrods
are urged to peruse those regulations with care. One cannot sally
merrily forth to hunt without knowing the boundaries of the zone
one is in and the seasons for that zone. As an example, the state
has five waterfowling zones _ Northeastern; Lake Champlain;
Western; Southeastern, and Long Island _ each with its own seasons.
Things get even more complicated in the pursuit of deer, where
there are not only four zones with varying bag limits, but also
different seasons depending on whether the implement of choice is
bow and arrow, modern firearms or muzzleloading ones.
</P>
<P>
   Waterfowl hunting should be rewarding this year. The U.S. Fish
and Wildlife Service's spring survey of breeding duck populations
in North America has indicated that a record number of birds will
be flying south this fall and winter. This season's basic daily bag
limit of six ducks reflects this optimistic assessment. There are
separate regulations for sea ducks and mergansers.
</P>
<P>
   In New York state, opening day for duck hunting ranges from Oct.
2 in the Northeastern Zone to Nov. 19 in Long Island. Hunters
should remember that the daily limit for the highly prized black
duck, which has been in trouble for years, is one, and that within
each zone's regular seasons for ducks there are periods when black
ducks cannot be shot.
</P>
<P>
   The regular Canada goose seasons, which are split, begin in
early November in the five zones, except on Long Island. The daily
bag limit in the Long Island regular season (Nov. 19-Nov. 28 and
Dec. 2-Dec. 31) is four. In addition, there will again be a late
Canada goose season _ Jan. 15-Feb. 15 _ five birds a day, in
portions of Chemung, Tioga, Broome, Delaware, Sullivan, Orange,
Rockland, Putnam, Dutchess, Westchester, Nassau and Suffolk
Counties.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a state hunting license, those in quest of
waterfowl or any other migratory game bird, including woodcock,
must purchase a federal duck stamp (some states require a state
duck stamp also, New York does not) and must also register with the
state's Harvest Information Program (888) 427-5447. You will be
asked to answer a few questions and will then be assigned an HIP
number. The federal government requires states to implement this
system, and also requires hunters to register in each state in
which they plan to hunt migratory birds.
</P>
<P>
   In New York state, the basic season's limit for a deer hunter
using a modern firearm is one antlered animal, but it is
theoretically possible for a resident with special permits or a
nonresident with a combination license and special permits to take
a total of five animals. Archers may shoot a deer of either sex. In
many instances, primitive weapon (muzzleloading) buffs may take a
deer of either sex. New York also allows muzzleloaders to hunt deer
with a smoothbore weapon; rifling is no longer required.
</P>
<P>
   All of New York state's hunting regulations, except for those
applying to waterfowl, are contained, including maps, in the
state's current Hunting and Trapping Regulations Guide, which is
available at license-issuing agencies and regional offices of the
state's Department of Environmental Conservation.
</P>
<P>
   For deer hunters, New York's Northern Zone _ which comprises the
state's northeast quadrant _ is divided into three portions for
muzzleloading hunters. The northwestern strip has two seasons, Oct.
16-Oct. 22 and Dec. 6-Dec. 12, and one deer of either sex may be
taken in the later season; the same is true in the southeastern
strip. The zone's central area, which permits taking a deer of
either sex, has a single muzzleloading season, Oct. 16-Oct. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Muzzleloading hunters are permitted to shoot a deer of either
sex during the single Dec. 15-Dec. 21 season in the state's west
and southeast zones. There are five relatively small areas in the
southern zone _ among them Suffolk and Westchester Counties _ where
this muzzleloading season is not allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Even as waterfowl and big-game hunting gets under way,
small-game and upland bird hunting is also starting up. The fall
turkey season opens Oct. 1 in some areas and Oct. 25 in others.
Unlike the spring season, which is for gobblers only, a turkey of
either sex may be taken and hunting is from sunrise to sunset.
Three of the four regions in the state in which turkey hunting is
allowed, limit a hunter to one bird for the season. In what could
be roughly described as the southeastern portion of the state, the
season has its longest run, Oct. 1-Nov. 21, and one may take two
birds, both in one day.
</P>
<P>
   The ruffed grouse season started Sept. 20 in the northern half
of the state and opens Oct. 1 in the lower half. It closes Feb. 29
in both areas. The daily bag limit is four birds. Grouse hunters _
particularly if they use a dog _ often have opportunities to shoot
woodcock, and if they wish to do this they should remember that
they will need an HIP number. The statewide woodcock season is Oct.
6-Nov. 4 and the limit is three a day.
</P>
<P>
   Hunters of varying hares (snowshoe rabbits) will have their
first opportunity to hunt these winter woodland ghosts Oct. 1 in
the northern portions of the state, where the season ends March 19.
For some, a late winter quest, which requires snowshoes or skis,
for varying hare in the foothills of the Adirondacks, is the proper
way to bring the year's hunting season to a close.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
