<SLUG> BC-NY-KILLER-SEARCH-745&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETECTIVES STILL SEEKING STUDENT'S KILLER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN.: Kansas)  (lb) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It has been more than six months since Amy Watkins, a
26-year-old graduate student from Kansas, was stabbed in the back
as she trudged with groceries toward her apartment in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the New York City Police Department has spent
thousands of hours searching for her killer. By this week, they
said, their leads had dwindled to zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at day one,'' said Lt. John Cornicello, commander of
the 77th Precinct's detective squad. ``We haven't lost hope. We are
trying to make our own breaks instead of waiting for them to come
to us. But the case has turned into a brick wall.''
</P>
<P>
   The slaying of Ms. Watkins, who friends say had planned to
devote her life to social work, represents one of the department's
most difficult and frustrating types of cases: a murder committed
by a stranger who leaves little physical evidence and is seen by
virtually no one.
</P>
<P>
   In cases like Ms. Watkins', the police basically have three
hopes for capturing the killer: He turns himself in; he talks about
the crime to someone else, who turns him in; or he attacks someone
else in the presence of witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Watkins was murdered at 9:45 p.m. on March 8, shortly after
taking the subway home from a Bronx community center where she
worked with battered women, the police said. They said she got off
at the Seventh Avenue stop in Brooklyn, got cash from an automated
teller machine on Flatbush Avenue and then bought groceries at a
nearby store before starting down Prospect Place toward her
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   When she was between Vanderbilt and Underhill avenues, the
police believe, Ms. Watkins was attacked from behind.
</P>
<P>
   The police say Ms. Watkins' attacker left his weapon _ a large
carving knife _ in her back but took the time to grab her tote bag
and pull it from under her body. They believe he then ran toward
Washington Avenue, where he sifted through it and stole her money,
although it is possible that someone else moved the bag after he
dropped it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat down with a profiler from the violent crimes program at
the FBI,'' Cornicello said. ``It appears we have a random
encounter, motivated by robbery and probably some sort of drug
addiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Watkins' father, Lawrence Watkins, a teacher at the
Dominican Academy in Manhattan, said that he was not looking for
retribution, but that he hoped his daughter's killer would be
caught to spare another family his pain.
</P>
<P>
   Since his daughter's murder, he has been attending monthly
meetings of New York Parents of Murdered Children, a support group.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you lose a child by violent means, you begin to feel a
vague anxiety and fear, a feeling that life is not safe,'' he said.
``There is a tremendous feeling of guilt _ why we were not there? _
things like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The detectives on the case have ruled out theories that Ms.
Watkins was killed by someone she knew or by someone who might have
been stalking her from the shelter where she counseled battered
women. It does not appear that her work ever brought her into
contact with an irate husband or boyfriend of any of the women
there.
</P>
<P>
   Cornicello said it was unclear whether the man who killed her
followed her from the automated teller machine, noticed her at the
grocery store or simply waited in a dark corner on Prospect Place
for a likely victim to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins said that his daughter had been outgoing, but not naive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was cold, and her head was probably down as she walked,
with the cold and the wind,'' he said. ``I suspect she was not in a
position to react quickly to someone who would have been waiting.
She would have been easy prey.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many people got in touch the police early in the case,
with some claiming to have seen a distant figure running away,
Cornicello said his detectives had received little information in
recent months. They have reinterviewed witnesses, he said, and were
looking for the woman who found Ms. Watkins' tote bag. The hope is
that she might now recall a detail originally overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the detectives have spent most of their time
interviewing suspects picked up in other cases, particularly those
involving knife attacks. The police believe that Ms. Watkins'
killer was proficient with the weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Cornicello said he hoped that the killer would tell someone
about the crime, and that the killer's confidant would tell the
police. A reward of more than $10,000 has been offered by the city
and private institutions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Watkins said small things reminded him of his loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``The murdered leave behind unpaid bills, loose ends that are
difficult to pick up,'' he explained. ``She recently got a letter
from a friend who did not know she had died, and her bed was not
made when we went to her apartment. These are little things, but
you have to walk in and deal with that, and it is difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Watkins was attending the Hunter College School of Social
Work, which has commissioned a mural in her memory and is trying to
put together a scholarship fund in her name.
</P>
<P>
   ``These terrible events can certainly bring out good things,''
Watkins said, ``and I think Amy's life has made an impression on
many people. It has brought home to them the reality of death and
that young people must do with their lives before they end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
