<SLUG> BC-FBC-RUTGERS-BC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUTGERS, 0-3, LOSES TO BOSTON COLLEGE, 27-7 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PISCATAWAY, N.J. _ Boston College had the best runner on the
field in Cedric Washington. It had the more efficient quarterback
in Tim Hasselbeck. And it did not drop passes or throw
interceptions the way Rutgers did.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a comfortable 27-7 victory for Boston College
Saturday in the opening game of the Big East football season. A
crowd of 27,330 at Rutgers Stadium watched the Eagles improve to
3-0 and Rutgers fall to 0-3.
</P>
<P>
   Washington had 147 yards rushing on 21 carries and scored two
touchdowns. Hasselbeck finished 17 of 22 for 168 yards passing,
including a touchdown. Rutgers receivers dropped six passes, and
the Scarlet Knights were hurt further by three interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers made only two scoring threats. In the third quarter,
trailing by 13-0, the Scarlet Knights struck on Mike McMahon's
56-yard touchdown pass to Errol Johnson. Boston College followed
that with a quick three-pass drive, with Hasselbeck's 21-yard pass
to DuJuan Daniels raising the Eagles' lead to 20-7. Late in the
third quarter, on a 37-yard field-goal attempt, Steve Barone of
Rutgers kicked a line drive wide left.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon completed 16 of 32 passes for 228 yards. After 11 sacks
in the first two games, the junior quarterback was sacked only once
Saturday, but he still took a beating.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College dominated the first half more than its 10-0 lead
showed. Hasselbeck passed efficiently and Washington and Carlton
Rowe ran well, but Rutgers proved its own worst enemy.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon's first interception, on the fifth play of the game, was
made by Eagles linebacker Scott Bradley on a ball that bounced off
the hands of Rutgers fullback Dennis Thomas. Nine plays later, John
Matich kicked a 31-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the second quarter, Boston College drove 87 yards
in 11 plays. Washington carried on the last three plays _ 11 yards,
17 more and then 8 _ for the touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Although it seemed too early in the season for a must-win game,
this was close to one for Rutgers. In Terry Shea's fourth year as
head coach, the Knights have been desperately trying to shed their
reputation as Big East doormats.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, they did not win a game and lost by such scores
as 59-19, 48-14, 48-0, 50-3 and 49-7. Last year, they improved
dramatically, to 5-6, and Shea's colleagues voted him the
conference's coach of the year.
</P>
<P>
   This season has not started well for Rutgers. In the opener, it
gave up seven sacks and lost, 21-7, to California. Next, Rutgers
let a good Texas team get off to a 24-3 lead, and the Longhorns
went on to a 38-21 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College's opening two victories did not come easily. The
Eagles beat Baylor by 30-29 in overtime and Navy by 14-10. The
Boston College offense had been good, averaging 427 yards a game
overall, 224 yards a game rushing, but the defense had been porous.
</P>
<P>
   That defense had been expected to be tested here by Jacki Crooks
of Rutgers, who rushed for 108 yards against Cal and 84 against
Texas. But there was no Crooks Saturday because of a disciplinary
measure by Shea. The coach suspended Crooks and four other players
(none of the four had played this season) for an unspecified
violation of team rules. Shea would not be specific, though it was
common knowledge that the players had missed practice last
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, Saturday is game day, but Rutgers had no game listed
on its schedule for Sept. 18. It had practices planned for Thursday
and Friday, with the players off on Saturday. But when Hurricane
Floyd washed out practices on Sept. 16 and 17, Shea scheduled a
workout for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   No one connected with the team would say why the players were
absent. But one person did point out that flood waters prevented
people from getting from one end of campus to the other, and that
telephone service was affected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
