<HEADLINE>
EXPANSION OF RAIL TRANSIT PLANNED FOR NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In an anxiously awaited financial blueprint, the
Metropolitan Transportation Authority on Wednesday will propose
spending $17 billion in a five-year capital plan, with provisions
for work on a new Second Avenue subway and other expansion
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Flush with the tax revenue that pays for most of its operations
and encouraged by sharp increases in ridership on its buses and
subways, the MTA will propose spending $5 billion more than its
current spending plan, which expires Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposed plan leaves unanswered how the MTA will pay for
all the projects it proposes. The plan, according to several people
familiar with it, relies on more than $2 billion that must be
raised in ``new government assistance or other MTA resources,'' a
provision that transit advocates say could result in a fare
increase.
</P>
<P>
   Although details of the five-year plan have not been disclosed,
a senior MTA official, who spoke on the condition that his name not
be used, said Saturday that the spending plan would allocate $14
billion for maintenance work on buses and subways and the
completion of projects that are already under way, including the
renovation of several subway stations in all five boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   He said the remaining $3 billion is designated in the plan for
``moving the system forward,'' mainly through the acquisition of
new subway cars, commuter rail cars and buses, and several subway
construction projects.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would provide $700 million for a Second Avenue subway,
a proposed expansion that has the support of many Manhattan
residents and elected officials. The MTA official said the proposed
amount would cover environmental studies and engineering work, with
some money left for initial construction.
</P>
<P>
   Although several versions of the Second Avenue subway have been
proposed, with some advocates insisting that it be built from the
Bronx to lower Manhattan, the capital plan is more modest,
proposing a new subway tunnel from 125th Street to 63rd Street. A
new underground walkway at 63rd Street would connect to the N and R
lines to enable passengers to transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the groundswell of public support for a new Second
Avenue line, the version proposed in the five-year plan could be
its most politically divisive element. An unusually broad
coalition, the Empire State Transportation Alliance, which includes
labor unions, environmental groups, the New York City Partnership
and others, has been lobbying the MTA to make the Second Avenue
project a higher priority.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Silver, the speaker of the New York Assembly, who
represents the Upper East Side, has said in recent weeks he would
block approval of the five-year plan if it did not provide money
for a line running the full length of Second Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the MTA board, which is expected to vote on
Wednesday, the five-year plan would go to Gov. George Pataki, who
is expected to endorse it. The state Legislature would then
consider it.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The largest project in the plan, budgeted at $1.6 billion, is a
new tunnel for the Long Island Rail Road to Grand Central Terminal,
giving commuters direct access to the east side of midtown
Manhattan. The MTA official said Saturday that the amount provided
for that project, which has long been advocated by Pataki, would be
enough to complete it by the end of the five-year spending period.
</P>
<P>
   Other large projects envisioned in the plan, both advocated by
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, would extend the N line in Queens to La
Guardia Airport, and extend the No. 7 line from Times Square west
to the Jacob K. Javits Convention Center and other developments on
the west side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The MTA official declined to say how much would be allocated for
those projects. He said another major expense covered in the plan
is a $1 billion allocation for the Triborough Bridge and Tunnel
Authority, which would include the $300 million replacement of the
deck on the Triborough Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for the MTA to buy 1,000 new subway cars and
1,050 new buses, of which 300 would be powered by natural gas or
other fuels that emit fewer pollutants than diesel, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the plan is being proposed during what is widely
regarded as a period of renaissance for New York City public
transportation, it seemed certain Saturday to provoke questions
over whether the sharp increase in spending can be sustained.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the uncertainty is that the increased popularity
of the MTA's buses and subways has not resulted in an increase in
fare revenues, because the recent introduction of fare discounts
and unlimited ride Metrocards has enabled frequent users of the
system to ride for less.
</P>
<P>
   In August, anticipating an MTA plan for new subway construction
and sharp increases in spending, New York City's Independent Budget
Office, a nonpartisan research group that advises the City Council,
warned that the MTA could face looming budget deficits if the
economy sours.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Russianoff, staff lawyer for the Straphangers Campaign, a
riders advocacy group, noted that the MTA had not ruled out fare
hikes to pay for the increased spending. ``They have laid out their
choices, and they are not easy ones,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One aspect of the plan that seemed certain to draw opposition
from environmental groups was the MTA's proposal to buy far more
diesel-powered buses than those powered with alternative fuels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diesel pollution is the No. 1 environmental issue in New York
City,'' said Richard Kassel, senior lawyer for the Natural
Resources Defense Council. ``By saying two out of three new buses
will be diesel, they are taking two steps in the wrong direction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
