<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5986 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VA-URBANREFUGE-REAL-N     09-25 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VA-URBANREFUGE-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: URBANITE REFUGE IN BACK-COUNTRY VIRGINIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: D.C., Md.)  (js) 
 By JAMES R. HARDCASTLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Va. _ Because it is in the rugged Blue Ridge
Mountains and is not served by railroads or major highways,
Rappahannock County's residential and commercial growth has lagged
far behind the counties that abut it on three sides, which are
considered part of the Baltimore-Washington metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   This suits most people here just fine because the county's
natural beauty and relaxed pace of life are what makes it such a
good place to live, says John McCarthy, the county administrator.
Between 1930 and 1970, the county's population declined from 7,717
to 5,199 as the move from farms to the cities continued.
</P>
<P>
   However, slow but steady construction of new homes since _
currently at a rate of about 50 a year, with some costing more than
$1 million _ has brought the population of the 267-square-mile
county to about 7,200 as it becomes an important getaway for
affluent city dwellers and a year-round home to urban refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Werner Krebser, the chairman of the County Planning
Commission, said there had been general agreement between old-time
landowners and newcomers on a slow-growth policy. Since 1966, the
county zoning ordinance has required a minimum residential lot size
of 25 acres on most of the land outside its four hamlets and the
town of Washington, the county seat.
</P>
<P>
   There are no supermarkets, convenience stores, fast food
restaurants or stoplights in the county. Day-to-day needs are met
by traditional general stores, which also serve as community
gathering places. (The county does, however, have a widely known
and luxurious restaurant and hotel, the Inn at Little Washington.)
</P>
<P>
   The absence of these amenities is one of the main reasons why
James Abdo, a Washington, D.C., real estate developer, said he
bought a 60-acre farm south of Sperryville from David Brinkley, the
retired news commentator. ``I hope I don't live to see them
there,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Abdo, who is 39 and single, says he drives the 80 miles from the
nation's capital to the 60-acre farm he bought seven-and-a-half
years ago for $335,000 nearly every weekend. He said he wanted to
expand the main house, but that he been holding off until he meets
``the woman of my dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very special place to me,'' he said. ``It's part of
the fabric of my life. I want it to be a special place for that
person, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Brinkley, who owned the farm for more than 30 years, wasn't the
only notable to find the county a convenient place for a hideaway
or a year-round home.
</P>
<P>
   The conductor Lorin Maazel has built a house, guest cottages and
a recording studio on a 193-acre farm here. He is also a key
supporter of the Hearthstone School, which was built on his
property and which his young children attend. Former U.S.Sen.
Eugene McCarthy, the political cartoonist Jeff MacNelly and the
political commentators Rowland Evans and James Kilpatrick also
maintain homes here.
</P>
<P>
   David Adoff, a real estate agent, and his wife, Hildy Teegen, an
associate professor at George Washington University in the nation's
capitol, decided to settle here after driving through the county on
their way to the Shenandoah National Park four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   What clinched their decision to buy a home here was a chance
stop at the Mountainside Market, a 4,000-square-foot general
store/deli/laundromat built along the road to the national park
that serves as the community hangout for the artists, musicians and
alternative culture element in Rappahannock County.
</P>
<P>
   After the couple looked at the store's eclectic deli menu and
inspected its diverse stock _ which includes art objects and
shelves of vegetarian foods, herbal and homeopathic medicines and
150 types of beer _ ``we decided that if the community can support
this kind of food and drink, this is a place we want to live,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Adoff, a former home builder who publishes an online guide to
the county and works part-time for a real estate firm, and his wife
have since purchased three lots along a hollow leading up to the
Skyline Drive. They have also built a 2,000-square-foot,
cedar-sided home with views of the surrounding mountains on one
five-acre lot and a 1,000-square-foot guest house, which they rent
out to tourists, on a four-acre lot. All three of the lots were
laid out prior to the passage of the 25-acre zoning ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the couple put the house up for sale for $279,000 and
the cabin for $160,000 so they can build a new house elsewhere in
the county.
</P>
<P>
   Adoff said that because of the 25-acre zoning, Rappahannock
County homes are expensive. Residential lots will sell for $3,000
to $5,000 per acre, depending upon the view. To this must be added
the cost of digging a well, installing a septic field and building
a driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the expense of housing, the typical buyer is a
professional in his or her 50's or 60's who wants to spend weekends
in the county until moving there permanently at retirement, Adoff
said.
</P>
<P>
   A powerful visitor's draw to the county is the Inn at Little
Washington, an 80-seat restaurant and a 14-room inn that is
consistently ranked as one of the finest country inns in the
nation. The inn draws its name from a local name for the town of
Washington, population 190. It is named for George Washington, who
as a young surveyor laid out its five-block by two-block street
grid in 1749.
</P>
<P>
   The inn's co-owner and chef, Patrick O'Connell, a native of
Washington, D.C., said he had fallen in love with the county's
countryside as a child in family drives to Luray, Va. In 1967, the
self-taught chef purchased a three-acre property near here while he
was still in his early 20s.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, he purchased a 100-acre farm at the foot of
nearby Old Rag Mountain, where he raised vegetables for sale to
health-food shops in the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   His vegetable business soon evolved into a catering enterprise
that took him into the homes of many well-to-do families in the
Virginia hunt country, which includes the eastern part of
Rappahannock County.
</P>
<P>
   Learning of his clients' need for a place where they could
entertain, he and his partner, Reinhardt Lynch, leased half of an
old garage in the Town of Washington for $200 month and converted
it into the restaurant. The inn opened in 1978, and over the years,
the lush rooms, with rates of $340 to $640 a night, not including
meals, and a $5 million kitchen wing have been added.
</P>
<P>
   All along the way, the Inn has eagerly sought out specialty
products, such as smoked trout, fallow deer, exotic vegetables,
mushrooms and rabbits from local farmers. In recent months, David
Cole, the former president of America Online's Internet services
unit, announced plans to convert two historic buildings across the
street from the inn into a center that would retail organic food
items such as the Kobe beef and premium berries he is raising at
his nearby Sunnyside Farm.
</P>
<P>
   One of the buildings would also become headquarters for
walnutacres.com, an online organic-foods store that would sell
products from Sunnyside and Walnut Acres Organic Farms, a leading
provider of organic foods based in Penns Creek, Pa., that Cole
acquired a controlling interest in this summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
