<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-PAIRS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAIRING STRATEGY SEEMS TO FAVOR THE EUROPEANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE _ It is a difference of opinion as striking as the
Vardon grip vs. the interlock. Neither is wrong, both can work.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Crenshaw has chosen to use all 12 of his players in the
first two days of the Ryder Cup Matches at The Country Club,
sticking with a philsophy that is typical of a United States
captain. Mark James, on the other hand, has ridden nine horses, and
won't introduce the remaining three members of his European team
until Sunday's singles matches. (Trust us, Jarmo Sandelin, Jean Van
de Velde, and Andrew Coltart have checked in and are present and
accounted for.)
</P>
<P>
   For years, US captains have had the luxury of a team so dominant
they could sit out key players, get everyone in the lineup, and
still win. Thus in 1977 did US players yawn when Tom Weiskopf _
arguably one of the game's great players at the time _ said he
would not play for personal reasons. The US won anyway, 12 1/2-7
1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Then Europe developed a nucleus _ Seve Ballesteros, Ian Woosnam,
Bernhard Langer, Nick Faldo, and Sandy Lyle were dubbed the ``Fab
Five'' _ that embraced the Ryder Cup as their personal crusade.
Whatever it took to win, they would do, and when that meant playing
five matches every time, they did not flinch. If that meant taking
a partner and dancing with him for three or four matches, they
said, ``Start the music, give us matching shirts, and show us to
the first tee.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fab Five is no longer part of these festivities, but the
philosophy lives on. Stronger than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1985, the first time in 28 years that the US lost the
Ryder Cup, the Europeans essentially have said, ``We know you have
more depth. Now hand us the Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, with Lyle being replaced by Ryder Cup rookie Jose Maria
Olazabal as a key team member, the Europeans used five players
(Ballesteros, Faldo, Langer, Woosnam, and Olazabal) in all five
matches. Four players went the distance in '89, three in '91, four
in '93, four in '95, and five in '97. James will establish Ryder
Cup history Sunday when seven players take part in their fifth
match. (In that same period, the US used more than one player in
all five matches only once, in 1991 when it played three thanks in
part to Steve Pate's injury.)
</P>
<P>
   So some players had to laugh when Jeff Maggert, after his
morning foursomes win with Hal Sutton over Colin Montgomerie and
Paul Lawrie, said, ``It's a lot to ask to play five matches.''
European workhorses Lee Westwood, Darren Clarke, Sergio Garcia,
Jesper Parnevik, Miguel Angel Jimenez, Colin Montgomerie, and Paul
Lawrie might take exception.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking up the Maggert-Sutton team after three solid efforts
raised eyebrows. So did Crenshaw's explanation for putting Leonard
in with Sutton for afternoon play: ``It's a hunch.''
</P>
<P>
   James cannot be accused of relying on a hunch. He came in with
one game plan and one game plan only _ ride eight or nine players
to a two-day lead and hope to win enough singles matches to reach
the magical number of 14.
</P>
<P>
   The only decision he had to make was whether to play Olazabal
with Jimenez in foursomes, and even that became easy because
Olazabal took himself out of that phase of the competition. Enter
Padraig Harrington to complete the roster, at least the roster
James is counting upon.
</P>
<P>
   Singles has never been the European strong point (Oak Hill, 1995
excluded) and James knows this. Just as European captains
Ballesteros, Bernard Gallacher, and Tony Jacklin knew it before
him. Since 1987, a European has played in all five matches 25
times; Europe's singles record in those instances is 8-13-4.
</P>
<P>
   But that hasn't really mattered as the Europeans have found a
successful strategy. That is, putting players together and sticking
with them, even at the first sign of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Oak Hill in 1995? Gallacher threw out his iron _
Montgomerie and Faldo _ in the first match, a rather daring move
considering there wasn't much iron to throw out. Faldo and
Montgomerie were beaten twice on the first day, 1 up, and 3 and 2.
So on Day 2, facing a 5-3 deficit, what did Gallacher do? He stayed
with his plan, again leading off with Faldo and Montgomerie. The
veterans, well aware of the burden placed upon them, came through
with a 4-and-2 triumph over Jay Haas and Curtis Strange, a match
that helped put in motion a 3-1 morning advantage in foursomes. We
know what happened the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   This year? Westwood-Clarke, Parnevik-Garcia, Montgomerie-Lawrie
have been glued to each other. The strategy could very well blow up
in James's face, but, quite honestly, it was the only game plan he
could go with.
</P>
<P>
   And, if it works again, perhaps future US captains will start
thinking about finding permanent partners for their stars like
Tiger Woods. Saturday, he played with his fifth different partner
in eight Ryder Cup team matches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
