u a BC-SLAVERY-REMEMBRANCE-A     09-25 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAVERY-REMEMBRANCE-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RITE HELPS SLAVES' DESCENDANTS PURGE ANGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For hundreds of years, millions of blacks were
captured in Africa and forced to cross the Atlantic Ocean to the
Americas, where they became slaves.
</P>
<P>
   Early Saturday morning, more than 1,000 black descendants of
those slaves made a symbolic trip from St. Paul Community Baptist
Church in East New York, Brooklyn, to the shores of that same ocean
to pay homage to their ancestors, as part of a religious
remembrance of the trans-Atlantic slave trade.
</P>
<P>
   The travelers arrived on the beaches of the Rockaway peninsula
about 4 a.m. for a sunrise service led by the Rev. Johnny Ray
Youngblood, the pastor of St. Paul, who organized the tribute,
which is held every year.
</P>
<P>
   As African drums played in the background, those who gathered _
most of them dressed in white garb to symbolize their desire to
cleanse the sting of slavery _ heard Youngblood and others speak
about their belief that the roots of modern-day racism and hatred
can be found in the slave trade.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's gathering focused on how to escape being victims of
``Maafa,'' the Kiswahili word that means unspeakable horror and
that is now being used to describe the slave trade, which
Youngblood calls the ``middle passage holocaust.''
</P>
<P>
   The participants seemed to share Youngblood's beliefs that black
Americans are still affected by the slave trade that flourished
centuries ago and that the best way for black Americans to recover
from the wounds of the past is to mourn, which allows them to move
forward.
</P>
<P>
   The process, he said, helps blacks deal with much of the anger
that many of them feel.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Hyatt, a 38-year-old bus driver from Brooklyn who
attended the sunrise service, said blacks should always remember
their ancestors' suffering. ``In certain respects we need to be
like the Jews and say, `Never forget' _ even more than that, `Never
again.'''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Henry, a church member who works as a funeral director,
said that before going to the event for the first time in 1997, she
was ``pent up with anger'' and ``felt like dirty laundry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Giving us the knowledge of the struggle we went through,'' she
added, ``felt like dirt being loosened from laundry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the washing stage,'' Ms. Henry said. ``We still have
more to do, but are getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   As the ceremony continued, participants spoke about their
lingering pain, sang and wept. As the orange sun began to rise, the
participants threw carnations into the ocean as a symbol of their
respect for those who came before them.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are hungry to connect to their roots,'' said Janet
Bigot, a junior high school counselor who lives in East New York.
``But one cannot help but be angry because of our conditions in a
society that has thrived on the blood, sweat and tears of our
ancestors. Angry is normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bigot said she was most moved by the participants'
reflections on the slave trade. ``We are saying to our ancestors
that although we have not experienced what you had to go through,
we understand and we will not forget,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Youngblood called for the U.S. government to pay reparations to
all black Americans for their ancestors' enslavement.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the government has paid reparations to
Japanese-Americans who were kept in internment camps during World
War II, Ms. Bigot, a member of Youngblood's church, said slavery
reparations would ``show respect, pay some mind for what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The sunrise service was part of a weeklong observance of the
heritage of slavery in many black churches across the nation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The week of events at St. Paul's included remarks from a variety
of black Americans, including Leonard Jeffries Jr., a professor of
African-American studies at City College, who spoke on Monday about
``Historical and Political Context of the Healing of African
People'' and Alton Maddox, who spoke about racism and the law. Both
men are controversial: Jeffries has been criticized for
anti-Semitic statements, and Maddox was one of the lawyers at the
center of the Tawana Brawley case.
</P>
<P>
   The events at St. Paul's included a workshop called ``Undoing
Racism,'' examining how to achieve that goal in a nonviolent and
practical way.
</P>
<P>
   Orville Froome, a businessman from Valley Stream, compared the
lingering effects of slavery to child abuse. ``It is almost like
someone who has been mistreated as a child and they are carrying
all this pain because of slavery,'' Froome said. ``Yes, we are
hurt, and what an event like this does is help us heal.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Paterson, who lives in Brooklyn and attended the week's
events, said she left ``on an emotional high.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Youngblood hopes to hold the event in Central Park,
which is not fraught with the symbolism of the ocean, but which
might draw more participants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 1836EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5994 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-FLOOD-PLAN-2TAKES-     09-25 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-FLOOD-PLAN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY FLOOD-CONTROL PLAN STALLED FOR DECADES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOUND BROOK, N.J. _ Ever since six men died in a flash flood in
1973, the Army Corps of Engineers has been planning a vast
construction project to tame Green Brook and other flood-prone
streams around this borough and a dozen nearby communities.
</P>
<P>
   But work has been delayed over and over _ by federal budget
cuts, by drastic changes demanded by Congress, by the corps'
cumbersome bureaucracy, by environmental questions, and by
political tussles over how to apportion the costs and benefits of
the $330 million flood-control plan.
</P>
<P>
   And now, as thousands of residents pick through the ruins of
precisely the kind of flooding the corps set out to prevent a
quarter-century ago, officials are left to contemplate both a
meteorological nightmare and a bureaucratic one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had better foresight, that project could've been done
now and Bound Brook wouldn't have been flooded,'' said Clark
Gilman, 60, the chief of flood-plain management for the New Jersey
Department of Environmental Protection, who has been working on the
plan for 25 of the 30 years he has held the position. ``It's real
sad. Nero fiddled and now Rome's burned.''
</P>
<P>
   Corps officials who assessed the damage this week found that
flooding from Tropical Storm Floyd rose 2 feet higher than even the
theorized catastrophe that they had used as a worst-case scenario.
What had been a computer-generated line on their maps was now drawn
on the town's streets and buildings in rainbow stains of oil and
brown smudges of sewage and mud.
</P>
<P>
   As Bound Brook, Green Brook Township, Middlesex and other
communities in the low plains of northern New Jersey tallied losses
from the floods, debate intensified over the long-planned, but
never-executed Green Brook Flood Control Project.
</P>
<P>
   It was only out of respect for the two people who died when the
Raritan River and Green Brook combined to immerse this place that
some officials refrained from saying, ``I told you so.'' But
several came close.
</P>
<P>
   William Slezak, the civil works chief in the corps' regional
headquarters in New York, said that despite the epic dimensions of
this deluge, it would have been largely held back by the planned
network of levees, channels and flood walls. The corps, saddled
with a reputation for excessive building and wasteful spending,
this time appeared to have the right idea. The plan called for
levees with an extra three feet of height, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just tears your heart out, the fact that we just weren't
able to provide the protection in time,'' Slezak said.
</P>
<P>
   The long, strange history of the Green Brook Flood Control
Project is a study in the tortuous course that must be run by
complicated engineering projects, particularly when they span 3
counties and 13 municipalities, as this one does.
</P>
<P>
   Over two decades, competing political interests at the
downstream and upstream ends of Green Brook pressed different
representatives in Congress either to drop aspects of the plan or
to change its focus, each time causing delays. Communities with
fewer flooding problems questioned whether they should have to
share costs with those, like Bound Brook, that faced the biggest
risks.
</P>
<P>
   The debate played out year after year in The Courier News and
other local newspapers. Even though the federal government would
pay 75 percent of the costs and the state 19 percent, elected
officials focused on the impact on municipal and county budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Another impediment was the peculiar kind of amnesia that settles
in after disasters, said Eric Evenson, the New Jersey district
chief for the U.S. Geological Survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my personal observation that the public at large, between
droughts and floods, tends to forget,'' Evenson said. ``The level
of urgency for dealing with rare events just isn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has ever doubted the potential for devastation when the
lacework of rivers and brooks that feed into the Raritan River
swells during extreme storms.
</P>
<P>
   The flat plain below the 500-foot ridges known as the Watchung
Mountains has flooded at least since Colonial times, with Green
Brook developing a particularly nasty reputation as an amplifying
funnel for water cascading from the hills.
</P>
<P>
   Through the late 1880s and into this century, floods along Green
Brook occurred regularly. Finally, in August 1932, New Jersey
officials took the first stab at finding ways to hold back the
waters, publishing a report titled ``Control of Floods on Green
Brook in the Counties of Middlesex, Somerset and Union.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing came of it.
</P>
<P>
   It took back-to-back severe floods in 1971 and then 1973, and
the loss of six lives in the 1973 flash flood, which occurred on a
tributary of Green Brook, to prompt new action. Altogether, floods
along the Green Brook watershed from 1900 to 1996 caused $2.4
billion in damage, the Army Corps of Engineers has calculated.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, with strong local support, the corps began assessing
whether levees, concrete channels and other means could minimize
damage.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, New Jersey empowered communities that shared
flooding problems to form flood control commissions, and the Green
Brook Flood Control Commission was formed. It remains the only such
commission in the state, Gilman said.
</P>
<P>
   The group, comprising representatives from each county and town,
met 10 times a year, year after year, working as a prod to the
corps and as a lobby in Washington to try to push Congress to keep
the money moving.
</P>
<P>
   It took the corps seven years to devise a preliminary plan. In
1980, the experts concluded that a project tightly focused on
preventing flooding in the hardest-hit areas, like Bound Brook,
could save lives and money. That conclusion met the agency's rules
that economic benefits outweigh costs.
</P>
<P>
   But prosperous suburbs farther up the Green Brook watershed,
like Berkeley Heights and Scotch Plains, were upset that they were
left out. They, after all, had suffered some of the worst effects
of past floods, recalled Vernon Noble, 80, a former mayor of Green
Brook who has been chairman of the flood commission since its
inception.
</P>
<P>
   The commission pressed members of Congress to force the Army
Corps to redo its plan.
</P>
<P>
   But it had to wait six years to get its wish.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure for the plan ebbed as memories of the floods faded. At
the same time, as part of a war on pork-barrel spending, President
Reagan cut nearly all money for water projects around the country.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Noble and other commission members _ who are unpaid _ made
annual pilgrimages to Washington to testify about the need for
protection. They got their five minutes, sandwiched between
delegations from other states.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Congress authorized money for the Green Brook project,
but only if the Army Corps expanded it to include protection for
communities all along the stream, not just at the soggiest end.
</P>
<P>
   The engineers had concluded that this was not economically
justified, but Congress essentially demanded that they find a way
to justify it, said Gilman, the New Jersey flood official.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sent us back to square one,'' said Slezak of the Army
Corps regional office. By the late 1980s the plan had to
fundamentally change anyway, he said, because so much time had
passed that the entire area had changed. There were corporate
parks, parking lots and shopping centers where there had been
vacant land _ some in spots where levees were supposed to go. More
years slid by.
</P>
<P>
   Private environmental groups also began to fight more
vigorously, opposing two big flood-control reservoirs that were
planned for wooded, wild areas at the base of the Watchung range.
Such basins hold back flood waters temporarily and release them
slowly.
</P>
<P>
   The groups also contended that the plan might encourage more
development close to rivers, said Sunil Somalwar, a physics
professor at Rutgers University who is a vice chairman of the New
Jersey chapter of the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a lot of people, there's this promise that once the Army
Corps steps in, floods will disappear, so let's go build close to
the river,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The project also lost steam within the corps as managers came
and went, lured to higher-paying jobs in industry, Slezak said.
Other water experts in the project point to the frequent rotation
of officers through the top corps post in the region, which caused
a loss of momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Budgets also tightened again as the Clinton administration cut
federal money for flood projects within individual states, New
Jersey and corps officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A bad flood in October 1996 reinvigorated the flood plan.
</P>
<P>
   But the following summer, it was changed once again. Sen. Robert
Torricelli, after strong lobbying by residents of Berkeley Heights,
pushed through a law prohibiting the corps from building the basins
at the upstream end. Over the years, the upstream communities had
become more focused on environmental issues and less on the flood
threat.
</P>
<P>
   That part of the project was put on hold so that construction
around Bound Brook could begin. Many officials involved in the plan
say they doubt the upper part of the Green Brook project will ever
be built.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, a flood-control plan that began in 1980 as a focused
effort in the lower portion of Green Brook, then was expanded at
the behest of Congress, now reverted to its original dimensions.
Along the way, a decade was lost.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Gov. Christie Whitman and federal officials gathered
in a Bound Brook park to announce that ground would finally be
broken in the spring of 2000 on the first stage, the replacement of
a 68-year-old bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Now that park is a swamp, and the curbs of adjacent streets are
banked high with discarded furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Until late this summer, some residents of Bound Brook were still
trying to block parts of the plan. And even now, others along the
watershed, including some officials from neighboring Middlesex
County, still question the need for the levees and pumping
stations. Local environmental groups, and the state's Sierra Club
chapter, still oppose the plan, saying the government would do
better if it bought homes and businesses in harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   In case the project drags on, corps officials this week said
they were planning to update the old brochure promoting the flood
plan _ adding photographs of the latest disaster.
</P>
<P>
   As the remains of Floyd blew in on Sept. 16, J.B. Wiley Jr., an
engineering consultant for the local flood control commission, was
in his house in Bedminster Township, 20 miles upstream from Bound
Brook, watching the upper Raritan River rise.
</P>
<P>
   After the water began lapping against the road, he jumped in his
car and drove toward the borough. ``I was thinking about all those
nice people who'd said this would never happen, therefore we didn't
need the project,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived at Bound Brook as the evacuations began. ``Watching
all those poor people,'' he said, ``really fired up my
determination to see this thing through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
