<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5996 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CONSTRUCTION-SHORTAGE     09-25 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSTRUCTION-SHORTAGES-REAL-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: SHORTAGES ARE SLOWING CONSTRUCTION OF HOMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.J., Pa., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By DENNIS HEVESI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From the pipes in the trenches to the trusses for the
roof, from the panels for the walls to the insulation between the
beams _ and, just as acutely, in the search for skilled workers to
hammer it all together _ home builders are struggling with
shortages of supplies and labor.
</P>
<P>
   In coping with the scarcities, the builders find themselves
engaged in frenetic juggling acts that have consequences for their
profit margins and for homebuyers' budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Squeezed by bottlenecks for one material, then another,
developers are realizing just where they rank in their suppliers'
pecking orders, their allocation for a particular product dependent
on how much they bought last year _ a serious circumstance for the
little guy. Stymied by delivery delays, some find themselves
staring at foundations without frames, frames without walls. Others
turn to alternative materials or methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, I've got war stories,'' said Jeffrey Levine,
president of Levine Builders, a Queens, N.Y.-based corporation that
has built about 3,000 housing units over the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Shaft walls for three elevators in a 240-unit co-op building
going up at 95th Street and Second Avenue in Manhattan were
supposed to be lined with fire-resistant coreboard, Levine said,
``but due to its lack of availability, time constraints dictated
that we make a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Masons will now have to build brick firewalls, Levine said _ at
a not inconsiderable extra expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The masonry costs about $2.50 more per square foot than the
coreboard,'' Levine said. ``The elevator is 10 by 10, and it's 10
feet from floor to floor, so that's 400 square feet per floor. At
$2.50 extra a foot, that would be $1,000 per floor for each
elevator.'' There are three elevators in the 11-story building, or
33 times $1,000, for a total added cost of $33,000.
</P>
<P>
   In the New York suburbs, according to one estimate, increases in
the cost of lumber can add $4,000 to the price of a typical home
and $10,000 to a luxury residence.
</P>
<P>
   Some developers pass along those extra costs to the homebuyers.
But, said Levine, ``depending on the circumstances of the
contractual agreements, if it's a fixed-price contract I bear the
burden.''
</P>
<P>
   What the developers cannot avoid passing along are the delays in
completion dates _ postponements that have sent buyers packing for
motel stays or to the homes of relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Mutinsky is president of the New Jersey division of Centex
Homes, a company that last year built 15,000 houses around the
country. ``When I moved from Florida to New Jersey in 1985,''
Mutinsky said, ``the home-building market was very active. And, at
that time, the same types of delays were occurring'' _ including
for the home Mutinsky had ordered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ended up in a hotel with my children and a dog,'' he said,
``and here I am almost 15 years later, causing that same problem to
my homeowners. I never wanted to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutinsky estimates that the panoply of delays he faces these
days has pushed back completion dates on his projects by at least
three months.
</P>
<P>
   At Island Estates at Shoreham in suburban New York, where 140
houses are pushing toward completion, the builders are also feeling
the squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had one supplier say, `OK, I'll give you Sheetrock if you
buy lumber from me,' '' said Lennard Axinn, a partner in Island
Estates. ``We were desperate. It was a different form of ransom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly are houses delayed by the shortages,'' Axinn
said. ``That has an impact when the homeowners are counting on
moving in by a certain date, getting the kids into school. Of
course, they were screaming at us.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the builders require an excess of sympathy, since their
problems are the product of a booming, profitable housing market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're operating at sales levels that are, basically,
records,'' said David Seiders, chief economist for the National
Association of Home Builders. There were 886,000 new homes sold in
the country last year, ``an all-time high,'' Seiders said. The
previous record was 819,000 in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   And through July of this year alone, 577,000 new homes were
sold, Seiders said. ``Compared to the first seven months of last
year, that's an increase of 6 percent,'' he said. ``So it was a
record year last year, and the first seven months this year we ran
above last year's pace _ that's red hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Demand, as usual, is reflected by prices. In New Jersey, for
example, said Patrick O'Keefe, executive vice president of that
state's Builders' Association, ``prices are surging.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you that the average price of a new home in New
Jersey is about $250,000, up more than 10 percent from a year
ago,'' O'Keefe said. ``It's attributable to the robust demand, and
constrained supplies.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of supplies and labor, said Seiders, ``tops the problem
list for builders at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey of 400 members of the association, 72
percent nationally and 77 percent in the Northeast _ the nine
states from Pennsylvania through New England _ said they were
experiencing shortages of materials. Asked about labor, 75 percent,
both nationally and in the Northeast, said they were experiencing
shortages.
</P>
<P>
   The builders' concerns about supplies surpassed even their
reaction to the fact that the Federal Reserve has twice raised
interest rates in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that he did not want to sound like ``a cheerleader for a
slowdown,'' Seiders pointed out that ``usually when the Fed is in a
tightening mode, that's enough to throw the builders into a state
of panic.'' However, he said, builders are ``pretty sanguine about
that right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is supposed to be the most interest-sensitive sector of
the economy,'' he said. ``So, obviously, when the Fed has tightened
policy a couple of times, they really do want this sector to lose
some steam. But the builders are not carrying on about the
tightening. It's hard to operate in a market where you have trouble
getting decent workers and things like gypsum wallboard. So a
rebalancing of supply and demand in this market would not be a bad
thing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, for those in the trenches of the building business,
keeping their balance can require a juggler's touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you've got me going,'' said Mutinsky of Centex Homes in
New Jersey when asked about the pitfalls of the current
construction cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, in developing the land, we have a problem getting
ductile iron water main,'' Mutinsky said. ``That has added a
three-week delay. And once the water main comes in, the
subcontractor doesn't have the manpower to make up that three
weeks' difference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We also have a problem with the availability of PVC pipe,'' he
continued, referring to sanitary sewer pipe made from
polyvinylchloride. ``We have just been informed that the prices are
going up; they won't tell us how much and there may be a shortage.
This is what they're telling me.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the actual construction of the home, Mutinsky said: ``In
the permit process, municipalities in New Jersey have 20 days to
review and comment on and/or approve your plans. But they're so
swamped with applications and no manpower to handle them that on
the 19th day you get an additional list of deficiencies from the
municipality. It's either a true deficiency or a delaying tactic to
give them more time to review the application.'' That alone,
Mutinsky said, adds a month's delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, framing the house,'' he said. ``I have an additional
one-month delay receiving the pre-manufactured panels and trusses _
these are the wooden floor and wall panels and what holds up the
roof. Again, because of the demand, we wait an additional month for
the delivery of those. And again, the framer does not have the
additional crews to make up that lost time.''
</P>
<P>
   But, by far, the greatest shortage confounding the industry is
of gypsum wallboard _ otherwise known as coreboard, drywall or by
its trademarked name, Sheetrock. ``We used to be able to get it in
two days,'' Mutinsky said, ``but due to the allocations, it's now
up to almost 14 days.''
</P>
<P>
   The delays are not sequential, but overlap.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we go to contract with a customer,'' Mutinsky said, ``we
used to anticipate a six-month delivery of that home. But because
of all of the above, we now state anywhere between eight to 10
months out. That's an average of an additional three-and-a-half
months.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not for lack of trying that the wallboard industry has not
filled all of its orders, said Pam Kassner, spokeswoman for USG (G
for gypsum) Corp., the nation's largest manufacturer of wallboard.
``The industry and USG, we've been running 24 hours a day since
last summer,'' Ms. Kassner said. ``The demand is at record
levels.'' Last year, the industry produced 28 billion square feet,
and expects to exceed 30 billion this year, Ms. Kassner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're shipping, but it's never enough,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the price has gone up. The cost to a distributor for
1,000 square feet of wallboard was $149 at the end of July, 17
percent higher than the year before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will get better toward the end of the year,'' Ms. Kassner
said. ``We have new plants from us and our competitors coming
online.'' But demand, she said, will not dip. ``We think it's going
to be just as strong in 2000 as in '99, and the repair and remodel
market is growing gangbusters.'' Potent, too, is the office market,
which also uses wallboard.
</P>
<P>
   The supply-price equation for lumber is also vexing for
builders, though more difficult to quantify because lumber is much
more of an international commodity, subject to the vagaries of many
a national market. In some parts of this country, builders are
befuddled by price fluctuations; in others, they are hamstrung by
actual shortages.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the strong demand for new homes, lumber prices in the
United States actually slackened somewhat last year, primarily
because profound weaknesses in Asian economies undercut the demand
in those nations _ particularly Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we were able to consume a huge amount of lumber at pretty
attractive prices last year,'' said Seiders. ``But then prices
spiked up from last year's low.''
</P>
<P>
   The average price for 1,000 board feet of lumber was $349 in
1998. By mid-July of this year, it had bounded up to $490.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, according to Joanne Carroll, president of JMC
Resources, a housing research firm, lumber costs for a typical
2,000-square-foot home have risen by about $4,000 since last year.
For a trophy house in a swank Connecticut suburb, the price of
lumber spiraled up by about $10,000, she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the lower end, said Norton Wheeler, the lumber buyer for
United Builders' Supply in Waterford and Niantic, Conn., ``a sharp
rise in lumber costs could knock a first-time buyer out of the
box.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last two months, however, the average national lumber
price has slipped back to $390 per 1,000 board feet _ still
considerably above last year's mark. ``Lumber prices are very
volatile,'' Seiders said, ``a lot of ups and downs, a lot of
speculation. Usually when you talk about shortages, the symptom is
high prices, but you can still get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got 12 houses out here in East Windsor,'' Mr. Mutinsky
said of one of his projects in New Jersey. ``I had to wait 10 weeks
for delivery of the wall panels when the normal delivery is five.
If I can't put lumber on a foundation, it sits.''
</P>
<P>
   At least it has something to sit on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amount of approved, developable land is dwindling
rapidly,'' O'Keefe of the New Jersey Builders Association said,
``and, consequently, we may see a trailing off in production in
2000.''
</P>
<P>
   To meet incessant demand, some builders are turning to
commercial or industrial sites that can be rezoned for residential
use, or to previously ignored parcels passed over because they were
too difficult to build on. For example, Brian Stolar, president of
Pinnacle Communities of Millburn, said his company was buying a
35-acre site on a hilltop in Wayne, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Scarce land coupled with high demand can be costly. John Udell,
president of Weichert New Homes, a land broker, estimates that land
today constitutes 35 percent to 40 percent of the cost of a new
home, compared with 30 percent just a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But, even assuming that all the land and all the supplies can be
acquired according to a reasonably coordinated schedule, there's no
telling whether the developer will be able to hire workers capable
of doing the pipe-fitting, the cementing, the wiring, the sawing,
the hammering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost worse than these material problems are the labor
problems,'' said Axinn of Island Estates in Suffolk County. ``It's
been sort of a balancing act so we aren't getting creamed.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, 80 percent of Axinn's workers do the basic building
and 20 percent perform what he calls customer service, like
touching up paint and fine trim work after the house is up. ``We've
had to reallocate those resources so that people in customer
service can help complete the homes,'' Axinn said.
</P>
<P>
   Mutinsky said that when he first came to the New York area in
1985, hard times had hit the Sunbelt states, ``and the skilled
labor from down there came north, so that all these Texas license
plates showed up on the sites here.''
</P>
<P>
   During the recession of the late '80s and early '90s, however,
many small- to medium-sized builders went out of business in the
New York area. ``Thus, the license plates went back to Texas,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Residential developers have also been losing workers to the
booming commercial segment of the building industry, said Seiders
of the national home builder's association _ adding, somewhat
sheepishly: ``Right now, in fact, we're adding four stories and a
wing to our headquarters building here in Washington, near the
White House, and the contractor is luring workers from the
residential area.''
</P>
<P>
   In the view of Carl Goldberg, a partner in Roseland Property Co.
of Roseland, N.J., which builds about 1,500 homes a year in the
region, the industry must do more to expand the labor force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last 19 months, the scarcity of qualified workers has
become a crisis,'' Goldberg said. ``It's not only a problem in
numbers, but also because people haven't had full training.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing the lack of trim contractors _ those carpenters who do
the fine finish work _ Goldberg said, ``I often hear people saying
these days, `Gee, they don't do things like that anymore.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Fewer and fewer students are choosing to go to vocational
school, Goldberg pointed out, and trade union apprenticeship
programs are running at about about 60 percent of capacity. The
industry needs to create outreach programs and provide scholarships
to entice young people into trade schools, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to communicate that there are opportunities in being a
licensed electrician or a licensed plumber, financial
opportunities,'' Goldberg said. Take, for example, a carpenter, he
said: ``Four or five years ago, a carpenter would make $16, $17 an
hour. Now, most of the time, it's upwards of $25 an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, residential development is a profitable enterprise
these days. Still, all the crunching and juggling has taken its
toll on builders.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn how not to lose sleep,'' Mutinsky said, ``but it
does bother you when you come to work in the morning. It's
frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   And as Marshall Davis, president of Carlton Construction in New
City, N.Y., put it, ``Yes, we are pulling our hair out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Business is good,'' Davis said, ``but it's not a fun job
anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
