<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DEION-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BYE WEEK IS TIME OF JOY FOR PLAYERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEION SANDERS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Cowboys cornerback Deion Sanders' column, as told to staff
writer Clarence E. Hill Jr., will appear in the'' Star-Telegram
``every week during the season.''
</P>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Super Bowl week is unforgettable. The hype
that surrounds the game. The fans welcoming you into the host city,
the red-carpet treatment for the team that's expected to win.
</P>
<P>
   The midweek controversy. The game. The postgame interviews. The
parties _ yeah, I used to do the parties. The flight back home to a
huge welcome. And finally the parade _ oh yeah, I missed that _ but
I'm sure it was awesome.
</P>
<P>
   In all 11 years as a professional football player there is only
week that could come close to the Super Bowl week. It's a week that
gets players and coaches equally excited. It's called the bye week.
</P>
<P>
   My first year in the league I noticed some guys got more excited
about this bye week than any other week we had on the schedule, so
I called the NFL and asked if they could put that bye team in our
division so we could play them twice.
</P>
<P>
   We were 3-13 in Atlanta that year, so please understand I was
just trying to help.
</P>
<P>
   Bye truly means bye for most players and coaches. Traveling to
wherever or doing whatever that gives an escape from the rigors of
the NFL. I'm either fishing, sitting on the beach with family, or
honeymooning for the second time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Praise the Lord'' for this column. In a conjunction with the
bye week, I decided to devote time this week entirely to answering
some questions from fans.
</P>
<P>
   Q: As a deeply religious person as well as a football player,
what were your thoughts on the shooting at Wedgwood Baptist Church
in Fort Worth?
</P>
<P>
   DS: Sadly, I've arrived at the conclusion that bad things do
happen to good people, i.e., Martin Luther King Jr., John F.
Kennedy Sr. and Jr. and the teens at Columbine High School, just to
name a few. Somewhere in the midst of these tears and pain we must
believe that there ``is'' a silver lining in this cloud. Too often
it takes tragedy to bring our homes, families, schools, churches
and communities closer. Instead of dwelling on what happened, I'm
more focused on what we could do to prevent this in the future.
While I'm still searching, I'll start with one of Jesus'
commandments _ love thy neighbor as thyself.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How tough has it been sitting on the sideline being a
cheerleader rather than being the person creating the cheers? What
do you do on the sideline to keep you from not going nuts over not
being out there?
</P>
<P>
   DS: I've come to realize that life presents you with many
moments. Some of which you must maximize in order to obtain the
success in which you seek. I really don't get anxious for anything
because I know how important timing is in life. It's not my time
yet, but when it comes again, and it will soon, I will maximize my
moments.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Your toe injury and subsequent rehab has resulted in some
people calling you injury-prone. Do you think that's a fair
assessment?
</P>
<P>
   DS: No, I don't. But it is a fact that in 1997 I broke two ribs
and missed games. And, of course, I missed time last year and this
year with my current toe situation. But it is so easy to forget I'm
the same man who played 120 snaps a game offensively and
defensively for my team in 1996. The truth is that this is the
first time-consuming injury that I've sustained in an 11-year
career. I'd rather not suit up than suit up and not show up.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several new high-profile cornerbacks have come into the
league the past couple of years, led by the Redskins' Champ Bailey
and the Raiders' Charles Woodson. How good are they, and how do
they compare to you?
</P>
<P>
   DS: Obviously, the most recognized are Bailey and Woodson
because of the accolades out of college. They are the truth; what I
mean is they have all the tools for success and big-play potential.
Both are blessed with veteran cornerbacks tutoring them, such as
Darrell Green and Eric Allen. What has always separated me was
knowledge of myself, my opponent and the game within the game. When
they get that, look out.
\Ntagtop:Deion Sanders will answer one question every week. E-mail
your questions to cehill\Nstar-telegram.com.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
