<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6001 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-ASTRODOME26-COX     09-25 3154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTRODOME26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The fading glory of Houston's Astrodome
 &HT;    By Brad Buchholz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A few days after we moved to Houston in 1966, my
father loaded the family into the Chevrolet and drove us to see the
Astrodome. Nothing was happening at the stadium that day. The idea
was simply to go _ and behold it.
</P>
<P>
   The Astrodome, after all, had been dubbed the ``Eighth Wonder of
the World.'' The man who envisioned it, Judge Roy Hofheinz, had
brazenly compared it to the Colosseum in Rome. In this golden age
of can-do, will-do Texas _ an era of NASA space shots, Big Oil and
Lyndon B. Johnson in the White House _ it was our duty, as new
Texans, to consider the glory of it all.
</P>
<P>
   The great dome sat alone in the wild against a flat, treeless
horizon. It was as if no other structure was worthy to rest in its
shadow. I remember silver glints of sunlight against the arched
roof. The Dome conveyed more power from a distance; there was a
silent, solitary grandeur about it. A Texas Giza, on pale
grasslands.
</P>
<P>
   What was it that we were seeing that day? Urban and rural Texas
at the crossroads? Nature, subordinate to man? The future of
baseball? The future? We didn't see the inside of the Dome that
afternoon, but it was more fun to imagine: They play baseball in
there! In air conditioning! ``The Eighth Wonder of the World.''
</P>
<P>
   Three decades later, the Astrodome no longer is referred to as a
``wonder'' _ unless, of course, the word is spoken with a hint of
sarcasm. The world no longer beholds it. LBJ is dead. The moon
shots have ended. Oil no longer propels the economy. And the Dome
is no longer unique.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of this baseball season, the Houston Astros _ the
Dome's first tenant_ will leave the Astrodome and move downtown
into a baseball-only facility with a retractable roof. While the
Dome will remain open, for now (the Houston Livestock Show &AMP; Rodeo
is booked there, in the spring), it will no longer serve as a venue
for professional sports. The Astros' final regular-season homestand
begins Tuesday, and a banner near the right field foul pole has
begun the countdown: ``Five Dome Games Left.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Astrodome is like an old car,'' says Astros second baseman
Craig Biggio, who has played in the Dome for 12 major-league
seasons. ``It's dependable. It's reliable. It still gets you to
work every day _ even though it may make a lot of noise along the
way. But the thing is: We have a brand new car now, sitting right
next to it. I have to admit: The thought of driving it is pretty
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   I laugh along for a moment, charmed by the vivid metaphor. But
I'm sure that Biggio catches me when I close my eyes and sigh. For
I remember, yesterday, when the Astrodome was as sleek and modern
as the rockets at Cape Kennedy _ and all of Houston was eager to
join the ride.
</P>
<P>
   THE PLEASURE DOME
</P>
<P>
   When the Astrodome opened _ April 9, 1965 _ it was a national
event. President Johnson and his family were there, seated beside
Judge Hofheinz in a private box. Gov. John Connally was there.
Astronaut Gus Grissomand his family were there. And of course, the
Houston Astros and the New York Yankees _ with Mickey Mantle _ were
there. It was a spectacle, an event covered by 175 print
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not even Jules Verne or Walt Disney, in their most fantastic
moments of genius, ever conceived anything quite like this
unbelievable palace of baseball luxury,'' wrote John Steadman of
the Baltimore News-American. ``Words and pictures cannot begin to
adequately describe the majestic view which overwhelms the visitor
comparable to the first time we viewed Niagara Falls. Awesome
beyond belief.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days of its fresh paint, the Astrodome was a delightfully
entertaining place _ rich with color, Lone Star braggadocio, and
allusions to space. It was Texas busting its buttons. The outfield
scoreboard _ 474 feet wide and four stories high _ was wildly
famous. After Astro home runs, fans were treated to a 40-second
multicolored montage of Texas chest-thumping _ with its snorting
steers, cowboys and six-guns, and a calf-roping sequence. A few
strains of ``The Eyes of Texas'' reminded opposing teams this
wasn't Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   The Astrodome took itself very seriously. Ultimately, the hokey
self-reference became a large part of its charm.
</P>
<P>
   The guy who greeted you in the parking lot was dressed in space
gear. The attendant who showed you to your seat was a Jetsonlike
``Space-ette.'' The crew that dragged the infield _ the Earthmen _
were dressed as astronauts. These were heady days in Texas; the
Astrodome was nothing if not a reflection of its time.
</P>
<P>
   The Astrodome, the largest clear-span building of its day, was
also a forerunner. The idea of the private luxury suite, in the
form of the custom-designed sky box, began in the Astrodome. When
grass wouldn't grow inside the Dome, the Astros and Monsanto Co., a
St. Louis chemical manufacturer, collaborated to develop AstroTurf,
the first artificial grass. The Astrodome built the longest dugouts
in baseball, installed cushioned theater seats, developed the idea
of a scoreboard that mixed information, advertising and
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   There were five restaurants in the Dome those first years _
including the Domeskeller, a 2,000-seat picnic area behind the
outfield wall decorated in an Austrian beer garden motif, and the
Trailblazer, on the loge level, where visitors could order
full-course meals. Such ideas are common today, but they were
revolutionary in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   In the heyday of the Astrodome, the structure always assumed top
billing over the featured event. It was baseball, in the Astrodome.
Elvis, in the Astrodome. Judy Garland, in the Astrodome. Bullfights
and chuck wagon races and Bob Hope and Doc &AMP; Festus and Evel
Knievel and the Final Four, in the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   The building had its own electronic personality _ and people
reacted to it. As a mock tribute to the home run sequence on the
scoreboard, the New York Mets once lit sparklers and danced in the
dugout after they hit a home run. Spectators weren't just
encouraged to cheer; they were instructed. One ``rally'' call on
the message board was simply the silhouette of a pair of arms,
clapping. As obedient children of a TV culture, we watched and
responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was in awe of the building. There was no way you
couldn't be,'' recalls Houston manager Larry Dierker, who was an
18-year-old pitcher on the '65 Astros. ``It was so unlike anything
anyone had ever seen before that huge, open span. It was
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astrodome freed man from the inconvenience of nature. The
temperature was always 72 degrees, the humidity was always 50
percent, and there was no rain or wind. The scoreboard told us so _
while reminding us, during sporadic weather reports, that it was
hot as hell outside.
</P>
<P>
   When the games were over, my father and I would walk to the car
in the north end of the parking lot. Along the way, my eye would
catch sight of the abandoned Colt Stadium _ the Astros' first home,
their temporary home, during the Astrodome construction, from 1962
to 1964. I couldn't take my eyes off the place. It was the past.
And it gave the Astrodome a strange sense of scale.
</P>
<P>
   The old place looked dusty and gray. I felt the pull of its
ghosts and forgotten games. Nature already had begun to reclaim it.
Behind its outfield wall, I imagined weeds and faded paint. I
wished I could go in there. Whenever we drove from the parking lot,
I found myself looking over my shoulder, hoping to catch a glimpse
of the life behind its walls.
</P>
<P>
   THE JUDGE
</P>
<P>
   If the Astrodome was the reflection of its time, it was also the
reflection of the man who envisioned it. Judge Roy Hofheinz was a
dreamer and a bully, proud of his reputation as a huckster, a man
of great imagination and precious little tact. Although it has
never carried his name, the Astrodome is forever his house.
</P>
<P>
   When Hofheinz introduced the idea of the Astrodome in the late
1950s, he already was famous _ though not necessarily popular. A
child of Texas, raised in poverty, he'd passed the state bar exam
at age 19, won a seat in the Legislature at 22 and begun an
eight-year run as Harris County judge at 24. In the 1940s, he built
a personal fortune _ dealing in real estate, buying and selling
radio stations, developing his law practice. In 1952, Hofheinz
re-entered politics and served as mayor of Houston through 1955 _
though his own council tried to impeach him along the way. The
Judge loved circus and spectacle. His Galveston Bay retreat _ ``The
Huckster House'' _ was a childlike showplace, with rooms decorated
in distinct themes: the Circus Room, the Temple of Chance, the
Brig. During a visit to Rome, he had been intrigued to learn that
the ancient Colosseum had a curtain that scrolled across the top of
the building during harsh weather. Soon afterward, he became a
devotee of Buckminster Fuller, the inventor of the geodesic dome.
He said Fuller convinced him ``it was possible to cover any space
if you didn't run out of money.''
</P>
<P>
   When he heard about Houston's bid for a major-league baseball
team, Hofheinz and his friend and real estate partner, W.E. (Bob)
Smith, approached the Houston Sports Association and encouraged
them to think big.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I would come in for 1 percent, provided they adopt
my theories about how we should go about it,'' Hofheinz told the
National Observer in 1968. ``I didn't want anything to do with
knocking at baseball's door like a pauper. I wanted to get this
place (the Astrodome) and use it like a credit card.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge showed the National League his model of the Harris
County Domed Stadium in 1960 _ and Houston got the franchise.
Construction of the Dome began in March 1963. Cost of the
structure: $35.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Hofheinz was the godfather of the Dome throughout construction.
He involved himself in all decisions _ from china patterns, to
staff and team uniforms, to restroom design. The scoreboard was a
pet project; he called it ``my $2 million toy.'' He picked the
specific colors of each section, he said, to best complement a
woman's complexion. When copyright problems arose over the team's
original name _ the Colt .45s _ the Judge decided his ball club
should be called the Astros. He decided the building should be
called the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was a very hard-headed person. He would draw a line
and never cross it,'' recalls Fred Hofheinz, who served as a vice
president of the HSA under his father in the 1960s and later served
two terms as mayor of Houston. ``You couldn't negotiate with him.
But he was generally right.''
</P>
<P>
   In time, the Astrodome became a Hofheinz empire, and eventually
he controlled 88 percent of the Houston Sports Association. His
Astrodomain grew to include the Astrohall exhibition center, the
Astroworld amusement park and the surrounding hotel-motel complex.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Astrodome, the Judge built a fantastical complex of
VIP suites beyond the right-field pavilion. His six-story, 24-room
AstroSanctum included a lavish presidential suite, bowling lanes, a
projection theater, a barbershop, a six-hole putting course, a
circus-style playroom and puppet theater.
</P>
<P>
   Within the themed rooms, there were grand chandeliers, Louis XIV
antique furniture, zebra-upholstered chairs, gold-plated toilet
handles, telephones with Hofheinz's picture inside the circular
dial. The Judge loved to play. There was a trick bathroom elevator
that rattled and clanked and led to a room that was equipped with
little more than a barrel, a hose and a bucket of water.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm through, no man will be able to copy what I've
built,'' he once said. ``What you see now is only a small part of
my plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The Judge did not have long to enjoy it. When his wife, Dene,
died suddenly in 1966, he moved out of the family residence and
lived inside the Dome for years _ a modern King Ludwig, alone in
his fantasy castle. He once said he would spend entire weeks in the
building without going outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Though Hofheinz eventually remarried, he suffered a massive
stroke in 1970. Partially paralyzed,he lived another 12 years,
though he no longer had the vigor to maintain his empire. The
baseball team enjoyed only two winning seasons in 15 years.
Attendance sagged. The building fell into disrepair. Heavily
leveraged, Hofheinz was forced to sell his empire in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Roy Hofheinz died in November 1982, at age 70. On the day
of his burial, the funeral procession circled the Astrodome twice
and then proceeded to the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   THE STRETCH RUN
</P>
<P>
   In these final days of the Astrodome, I find myself daydreaming
about the Judge _ and things past _ as I visit for the last time. I
haven't been to the Dome very often since my father's death in
1990. He loved the place, simply adored the Astros and held a
season ticket at the end. But it hurt too much for me to come alone
after he passed away.
</P>
<P>
   The Dome is no longer the place I remember. On the field, before
a game with the Mets, Larry Dierker is thinking much the same thing
as he recalls walking into the Dome for the first time in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I feel as though I've walked into the next century.'
And now, as we go into the next century, we need a new ballpark! It
makes you think twice about the idea of `ahead of its time.'
</P>
<P>
   ``This may not be the most complimentary thing to say, but the
Astrodome created the prototype for the multiuse stadium. And since
then, frankly, all the multiuse stadiums have proven inadequate. .
. . It's much the same with artificial grass, which seemed great at
the time: no worry, no water. In those two ways, it broke ground _
but maybe it wasn't the right ground.''
</P>
<P>
   As the game begins, I wander the stands. There's nothing but
dead air in straightaway center field _ site of the old scoreboard,
which was dismantled in the renovation project of 1988. In its
place: rows and rows of plush, cushioned seats where no one sits.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping with the times _ following trends, no longer setting
them _ the Astrodome has opened a brew pub, Lefty's, near the left
field foul pole. The object here seems to be to drink lots of beer
and taunt Mets outfielder Rickey Henderson. There's an
old-fashioned scoreboard where the keepers update scores by sliding
numbered markers into wooden slats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's come to this,'' I say to myself. ``The Space Dome has
gone retro.''
</P>
<P>
   In the box seats, Astros fan Ted G. Kennedy wonders about the
Dome's future after the Astros depart. ``There's always the
temptation to hold onto it, like an antique, and keep it on the
mantle. But you can't do that,'' he says. ``From now on, it's
basically going to be little more than a stockyard for the rodeo.
It's sad. It's bittersweet. The building is outdated. It's time to
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the home team dugout, I find 83-year-old Miriam Smith, a
season ticket holder since 1965. In front of her, carved on top of
the dugout, is a message: ``Nolan Ryan wuz here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hate to see us move,'' she says sadly. ``I've been
going to games in Houston since Texas League days _ in Buff
Stadium, then Colt Stadium. I remember the mosquitoes and the rain.
And I hope the mosquitoes bite all the people who voted for that
new stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Roaming the concourse in the late innings of a Phillies game, I
watch people. Once in a while, I see people connecting with the
past. A gray-haired couple holding hands, taking the long, last
look. In the mezzanine, I spot a middle-aged man in a ball cap,
alone, leaning on a rail. At the end of the inning, he pulls away,
wipes a tear, and heads to the door.
</P>
<P>
   Could this be my last time? I walk back downstairs, determined
to find the place where my father sat. I'm pretty sure I can find
it _ except that they've reconfigured the front rows a bit, changed
the angle of the protective net behind home plate _ so I can't
quite place it. Is it this row? The next? Too much time has passed.
I'm so frustrated that I can't find it.
</P>
<P>
   This is the essence of the Astrodome in 1999 _ the impassioned
search for things that are long gone. The tour
</P>
<P>
   When I was a child, the Astrodome tour was a big deal. Millions
of people visited the Dome during the 1960s and 1970s. I never
imagined that the tours still existed _ and yet retired high school
teacher Alma Slawinski drags open the gate every morning at 11
o'clock to lead the first of two excursions.
</P>
<P>
   I know it's a bad idea. But I pay my $4. It's my last chance.
</P>
<P>
   It's a small tour today. Me and a family of five from France.
Anne-Marie Bousch, the mother, is the only one who speaks passable
English. Alma tries hard _ but the tour is a disaster. The family
Bousch understands only a fraction of the presentation. Alma
doesn't know the Dome well. And of course, there's nothing to see.
The Judge's secret quarters were destroyed in the renovation. The
scoreboard is gone. The sky boxes are locked, and besides, they've
lost their magic. The baseball dugouts have been cut in half. There
are no secret places. Nothing in the building shouts ``Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   We watch a film that is out of focus and out of date. The
Houston Oilers are still referred to in the present tense. The
Astrodome Museum is locked. Alma says a sign indicates a siren will
sound within 45 seconds if she tries to open the door. We're
reminded the Dome is no longer the tallest, the largest, the
newest. But wait. I stop in front of a kitschy European-style
crest, made of wood, painted on each side, attached to wooden cross
supports. It's out of place. Alma stops me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sir, before you ask, let me tell you that I have no idea where
that coat of arms came from.''
</P>
<P>
   But I know! It's a piece of the Domeskeller! The Judge's old
Austrian beer garden! Redemption! One last fragment of the Hofheinz
myth!
</P>
<P>
   As we prepare to leave the Dome, the Family Bousch is polite _
but unimpressed. ``Maybe if we'd come last year,'' Anne-Marie tells
me. ``You see, we have a grand new stadium in Paris. It seats
65,000 people.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside in the Texas heat, husband Jean lights a pipe;
Anne-Marie calls the family together to translate the experience
into French. I start to walk away _ but I can't do it. I can't
fight the urge to explain on the Astrodome's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand Texas, and know the time, to truly
understand this place,'' I find myself saying to Anne-Marie. ``When
this was built, Texans were flying to the moon. A Texan was
president of the United States. When this was modern _ when this
was brand new _ there was nothing in the world quite like it. And
all of Texas was proud.''
</P>
<P>
   On the way out, I drive past the site of Colt Stadium. The old
ballpark isn't even there; it was dismantled years ago and shipped
to Mexico. Not even a footprint remains. Nature has taken its
course.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
