<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6002 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-TAXES26-COX     09-25 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TAXES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rising property taxes effect Bush's tax cut propsal
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ About one in three Texas school districts is
considering raising or already has increased its property tax rate,
bringing into question the value of a $1.3 billion tax cut that
Gov. George W. Bush routinely touts in his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The changes come as property values around the state continue to
rise. Taxable property values increased significantly in most
Central Texas districts, including Austin, meaning even higher
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's office says _ and some school board officials agree _
that without the $1 billion cut, more school districts might have
raised their rates or rate increases might have been greater.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokeswoman for Steve Forbes, another GOP candidate for
president, says the tax rate increases shed needed light on Bush's
record as governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on reports out of Texas, (Bush's tax cut) has been
illusive,'' said Forbes spokeswoman Juleanna Glover Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers this year adopted about $3 billion in measures meant
to lower and hold down state and local taxes, including $1.3
billion in local school property tax relief. But much of that money
was set aside for districts growing at above-average rates and
districts with outstanding construction-related debt. ``If your
district doesn't fall into one of those categories, you're not
going to get as much benefit,'' said Rep. Paul Sadler
(D-Henderson). Sadler is chairman of the House Education Committee
and was a key architect of the education spending bill that Bush is
now touting.
</P>
<P>
   That bill resulted in higher state spending and was aimed at
forcing districts to lower their local tax rates. For example, in
order to get the additional state money to pay off debt, districts
had to lower local tax rates that are earmarked for that purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The law also set aside $1.7 billion to increase salaries for
teachers, school nurses and librarians.
</P>
<P>
   Some districts, such as Austin, are growing and have
building-related debt. But those districts either aren't growing as
fast as others or, like AISD, get more money from their local taxes
than the state will replace.
</P>
<P>
   Austin's school board adopted a 12 cent hike earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The school finance bill that passed this session made real
strides forward in increasing teacher salaries and helping school
districts to pay for bonds to pay for new facilities,'' said Dick
Lavine, a policy analyst for the Center for Public Policy
Priorities. ``But the increase in tax rates by so many districts
indicates that most schools still lag far behind where they need to
be in terms of paying teachers and providing the programs that our
children need.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavine, whose group advocates for more spending on public
services, said he believes much of the bill was intended to improve
education, and that any tax cuts were an added benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The fight over additional education spending versus tax cuts
pushed passage of the bill to the brink of the legislative session,
which ended in May.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler supported efforts to target tax cuts to so-called
fast-growth and high-debt districts. But he also warned fellow
lawmakers that Texas school districts need discretionary money to
cover other programs. He held out for a bill that included money
for early-education programs and unencumbered state dollars until
late on the last night that the bill could be passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do a tax cut, but if you don't leave a cushion of
discretionary dollars, the school districts are going to have to
raise taxes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Dunn, a spokesman for the Texas Association of School
Boards, said the lack of discretionary dollars is exactly the
reason many districts are increasing rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tied strings around that money so tightly,'' Dunn said.
``They earmarked it for teacher pay raises and debt service and
they left some, but districts are having to meet the costs of
increasing technology, rising health insurance cost and any pay
raises for administrative or non-teaching staff. It's all having to
come out of the small part of discretionary money or tax
increases.''
</P>
<P>
   According to information gathered by the TEA, 378 school
districts have adopted or are proposing property tax rate increases
averaging 7 cents per $100 of value.
</P>
<P>
   Another 378 districts have or are considering tax rate cuts
averaging about 5 cents.
</P>
<P>
   There are 1,042 school districts in Texas. The TEA didn't have
information on about seven districts and 279 said they were
considering no changes to their tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Scott McClellan, said voters should hold
their local school boards accountable if they are unhappy about
tax-rate increases. He said the governor and lawmakers did what
they could to cut taxes and voters appreciate the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
