<SLUG> BC-BBO-FEATURE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Farewell to Tiger Stadium
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On April 20, 1912, Navin Field, which Detroit Tigers
owner Frank Navin had graciously named for himself, opened for
business, and Ty Cobb did the rest. The Tigers beat St. Louis 6-5
in 11 innings. Cobb went for a couple of singles, engineered a pair
of double steals _ he stole home in the Detroit first _ that swayed
the game, the first historic episode in what had become one of
baseball's most historic venues.
</P>
<P>
   In 1938, Navin Field became Briggs Field (for new owner Walter
Briggs), which in 1961 became Tiger Stadium (by somewhat more
modest owner John Fetzer), which after Monday becomes an abandoned
antiquity on the corner of Michigan and Trumbull avenues. The
Tigers conclude their last home schedule at the old house against
Kansas City, finishing 87 years of baseball that will not be
duplicated.
</P>
<P>
   Cobb established his gnarly reputation there. Lou Gehrig played
his first game there, and bowed out of his last. Al Kaline ran down
everything in the gaps. Mark Fidrych redefined flake there. Reggie
Jackson poked one through one of the light towers on the right
field roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a feel and an ambience to these old parks that the new
ones don't have,'' said former Tigers third baseman Travis Fryman,
who has six old Tiger Stadium seats installed in his family room.
``This is a great old place.''
</P>
<P>
   Emphasize the old, because for all the fans and players that
mourn the old place's passing, a world of others are happy to see
it slip away. It is crumbling and dilapidated and deserves a decent
funeral. Whereas Boston's Fenway Park, opened on the same day,
remains one of the game's true cathedrals, Tiger Stadium' years
have sagged upon it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a couple of buddies who came in from Chicago,'' recalled
Minnesota pitching coach Rick Strelmaszek. ``And they were watching
the game, and the Detroit fans were rocking. My buddies were in the
first level, and they were drinking beer _ even though it was cold
_ and paint flakes fell into their beer as the people in the second
deck were stomping their feet.''
</P>
<P>
   No park, Wrigley Field included, had deeper grass, a condition
that Jack Morris, with his sinker and the Allan Trammell-Lou
Whitaker middle infield, exploited shamelessly. Baltimore manager
Ray Miller several years ago tested the stuff for camouflage
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took a ball, and they put it right between the mound and
second base at the end of batting practice,'' Miller said. ``Nobody
discovered it until about halfway through the first inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaline remembers when he first saw the place in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first impression was when we came into the old train
station,'' Kaline said. ``I was sitting by Johnny Pesky and he said
we'd be passing the stadium on our way in. It looked almost like a
battleship from the outside.''
</P>
<P>
   It still does. And it is sad when a great ship goes down.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 1913EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6006 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     09-25 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIEUWENDYK FOLLOWING HUMBLE PATH BLAZED BY GREER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a mythical concept, void of fanfare, monetary reward, or
even a cheap wall plaque.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I just made it up, kind of like ESPN did with those
absurd ESPYs.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean, however, the Rusty Greer Award isn't
important. Here in the Chicken-Fried Kingdom, once you wade through
all the jock egos, and the monster money that drives those egos,
you come to appreciate the rare ``old school'' personalities in
local professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   And by the way, ``old school'' was used to describe Greer long
before it became a cheesy Madison Avenue advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   I don't remember exactly, but I think it was former Rangers
general manager Tom Grieve, who some six years ago was thinking
hard in an attempt to give a just-up-from-the minors Greer the
proper compliment. What came out was something about the way this
kid played the game being ``old school.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, of course, has been Greer ever since. No jocks around
here could touch him when it came to being underappreciated,
underpaid, unassumed with the big league spotlight, and in general,
an on-and-off-the-field example of what the public loves.
</P>
<P>
   Greer won the Rusty Greer Award so often it was almost retired.
But this year there's been a sudden news flash.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the Rusty Greer Award is not Rusty Greer, due to
no fault of Rusty.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there have been several challengers, including Michael
Finley of the Mavericks. But then Finley's $8 million a year
contract kicked in, and he was eliminated in the underpaid
category. Otherwise, Finley still qualifies in all other good-guy
departments. He's a hard working talent on a bad and basically
forgotten NBA team.
</P>
<P>
   No member of the Cowboys has ever been seriously considered. In
local precincts, no member of the Cowboys is ever underappreciated.
The deep snapper is even a star. So was the blocking fullback.
</P>
<P>
   But because defensive end Greg Ellis will always be defined by
``they took ``him'' instead of Randy Moss,'' it means Ellis remains
obscure. But in reality, he's got the look of a big-time player,
plus, there's off-the-field class galore. And if you're scoring
along at home, Ellis has one more touchdown than Moss this season.
</P>
<P>
   But to replace Rusty Greer as the local winner of the Rusty
Greer Award, you've got to be ultraspecial.
</P>
<P>
   Move it on over, Rusty. Say hello to Joe Nieuwendyk.
</P>
<P>
   Be voted the NHL's Conn Smythe Trophy as the league's most
valuable player in the Stars' playoff run to the Stanley Cup; have
six game-winning goals in the playoffs; lead the NHL in playoff
goals (11); make the team's second line of
Nieuwendyk-Langenbrunner-Reid the most productive in the playoffs;
do all that, yet very quietly and very humbly concede that the
stars of the Stars are named Modano and Hull. That's Joe
Nieuwendyk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very comfortable with my role and with my job,'' he said
last week. ``I don't need the attention. I don't think of it as not
being appreciated on this team. I know in my own mind what I bring
to the team, and I know that's also recognized by the right
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a great player who is often overlooked is one thing. But
for this season, Nieuwendyk will also be underpaid. In the final
season of his contract, Nieuwendyk's salary of $2.6 million is a
steal for the Stars. Both Mike Modano ($6 million) and Brett Hull
($5.5 million) will be paid over twice as much.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk, who just turned 33, could be kicking and screaming
about renegotiation, but any winner of the Rusty Greer Award is
above such behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I signed the contract. There's a year left on the contract,''
said Nieuwendyk, shrugging. ``I want to stay here. I'd like to
finish my career here. But the contract stuff can wait.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have told Nieuwendyk they want him back. But
negotiations won't take place until the season is over. Do
remember, however, that to start last season, Nieuwendyk was coming
off double knee surgery. His regular season started building in
January and February. By playoff time in the spring, he was fully
healthy and on fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will start this season as healthy as I've been in years,''
Nieuwendyk said. Based on that, a return to the 40-goal level (he
had 28 for the regular season last year) is a strong possibility.
The Stars might be sorry they didn't get a contract extension done
over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what the Rusty Greer Award is all about _ being
underpaid, underappreciated and whine-free. Joe Nieuwendyk fits in
all categories. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
