<HEADER>
A6007 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS-ADVANCE26     09-25 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-ADVANCE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No ground zero: Falcons' target St. Louis
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ It wasn't supposed to be like this, the Falcons 0-2
and reeling, minus their big-money running back, and with so many
problems popping up that trying to get on a winning track almost
seems like a secondary focus.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XXXIII is still in the rear-view mirror, but it seems
like a mirage.
</P>
<P>
   When the Falcons try the Rams (1-0) today in perhaps the most
important September game in franchise history, the good news is
that quarterback Chris Chandler is likely to return from his
strained right hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Still, much of the country seems ready to write off the Falcons
since running back Jamal Anderson is out for the season with a torn
anterior cruciate ligament in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Anderson is merely saying what's politically correct,
he's not among the doomsayers.
</P>
<P>
   He's mindful of the fact his primary replacement, the smaller (5
feet 11, 200-pound) and quicker Byron Hanspard, just three years
ago rushed for 2,084 yards at Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Hanspard missed all of last season after a
serious left knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're two very different runners, and I think ... our offense
will try to include more things that are Byron's strengths,''
Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody that accomplished what he did in college, rushing for
2,000 yards in a season, is capable of getting the job done. I hope
he doesn't break my records right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for Hanspard to plow between the tackles two dozen
times, like Anderson sometimes did. He'll get a few cracks, but
more of his action will swing wide, and second-year back Ken
Oxendine (6-0, 230) will get some of the dirty work.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, though it's not like Chandler to agree with the
common-sense approach, even he concedes that Anderson's absence
could place more pressure on him and the passing game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be if we can't run the ball,'' he said.
``Sometimes, teams pass to loosen things up for the run game
(instead of the other way around). San Francisco has done that for
years, partly because they're usually receiver-rich, and
runner-poor.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons, though, are not receiver-rich, in part because
speedy Tony Martin was waived.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, the defense is playing well, allowing just 17
points per game, one point better than in the Super Bowl season.
The offense, though, has been erratic, and seven turnovers have set
up 31 of the opponents' 41 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offense has to get it going, and they can,'' linebacker
Henri Crockett said. ``It's not up to me to get mad at them because
I don't know what's going on on the offensive side of the ball.
I've got enough problems on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   There are problems off the field, too, something the Falcons did
not face last season.
</P>
<P>
   Contracts have become a contentious issue with some of the
agents for nine starters, including defensive end Lester
Archambeau, who can become restricted and unrestricted free agents
after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lester is like the Rodney Dangerfield of the Falcons,'' said
Archambeau's agent, Alan Herman. ``He doesn't get any respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything became surreal in the middle of the week when ESPN
took comments made by coach Dan Reeves, and edited them to make it
look as though he said Anderson's injury was attributable to his
14-day contract holdout in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't appear to be what Reeves meant, but Anderson fell
for the ESPN version.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all took it as a shot,'' said Ali Anderson, one of his
brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the gloom, the Falcons are not dead.
</P>
<P>
   The NFC, and NFC West are lame.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit running back Barry Sanders retired, wide receiver Herman
Moore is injured, and second-year quarterback Charlie Batch is at
the helm. Yet, the Lions are 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997 season, the Falcons started 1-7, yet entered the
15th game with a mathematical shot at making the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   There is hope, particularly if the Falcons can hang onto the
ball for a change, and get a few takeaways, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no team in the league good enough to turn the ball
over, and not control the clock and win,'' defensive end Chuck
Smith said. ``There's a lot of parity. I don't see the '78 Steelers
out here.''
</P>
<P>
   No last season's Falcons, either.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
