<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK-ADVANCE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Challenge for Buick is keeping big names
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ While the need for a post-Ryder Cup respite has
removed some prominent names from this week's $1.8 million Buick
Challenge field, the tournament will not lack news value or star
quality beginning Thursday at Callaway Gardens in Pine Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   On one side of golf's spectrum, the tournament has four Ryder
Cup players and coach Ben Crenshaw in the field.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, also playing is John Daly, dropped last week
by Callaway Golf _ whose frustrated CEO, Ely Callaway, comes from
nearby LaGrange _ for violating stipulations of his contract that
prohibit gambling or drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Although executive director Dick Ellis presumed he would be
seeing seven Ryder Cup players at the Mountain View course,
reconsidering after verbal commitments and pulling out before
Friday night's deadline were David Duval, Payne Stewart and Hal
Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   Still in the field, which last year was the 13th best in golf,
are Brookline participants Davis Love III of Sea Island, the 1997
champion; Justin Leonard, Jeff Maggert and Steve Pate.
</P>
<P>
   Also playing are 13 of the top 30 money winners (eight of the
top 20) and a list that includes defending and two-time champion
Steve Elkington of Australia, Atlanta's Stewart Cink and Billy
Andrade, England's Nick Faldo, almost-Ryder Cup player Bob Estes,
Bob Tway, Paul Azinger, Curtis Strange and Glen Day.
</P>
<P>
   Recently turned pro Ryuji Imada of Georgia and 1998 U.S. Amateur
champion Hank Kuehne are playing, along with Northwestern's Luke
Donald, the 1999 Fred Haskins Award winner, who received a sponsor
exemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``The field is pretty darn close to last year,'' Ellis said.
``The Ryder Cup is tough (to overcome). We'd love to have a couple
more of them, but we feel good about things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mountain View Course is in typically fabulous condition,
after being closed since Sept. 13. It is regularly voted as one of
the most popular courses by PGA Tour players.
</P>
<P>
   Daly's presence might be surprising in that he just last week
declared that he can no longer function without drinking and
gambling. He was dropped by Callaway after refusing to enter a
treatment facility.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1991 PGA and 1995 British Open champion has a good
reason to play. He needs the money. Daly, 33, has millions in
gambling losses and was fired from a contract that had $3 million
in remaining compensation through 2001. He owns a monthly
obligation of near $40,000 for mortgage, alimony and child support
payments.
</P>
<P>
   His severance from Callaway was not surprising considering
reports that Daly had been drinking at the Irish Open last month
and seen gambling in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
