<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRENSHAW FOLLOWS A HUNCH ON LINEUP  
 A TARGET PLAYER IS BEATEN  
 WOODS OFF ON HIS DRIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ It sounded like a foregone conclusion. When
Jeff Maggert came off the 18th green at The Country Club on
Saturday after teaming with Hal Sutton for a stirring victory in
the first morning match, he was asked about going out again for an
afternoon four-ball match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``Five matches is a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, Maggert was a spectator Saturday afternoon as the
U.S. captain, Ben Crenshaw, sent out Justin Leonard with Sutton,
despite the fact that Maggert and Sutton had been the Americans'
most consistent and successful pairing. Explained Crenshaw, ``I
have a hunch about Justin Leonard.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no guesswork involving Maggert and Sutton. They scored
the only U.S. victory on Friday, in the morning foursomes, or
alternate shot, competition. After losing a four-ball match in the
afternoon, they came back Saturday morning and knocked off Europe's
undisputed leader, Colin Montgomerie, and his partner, Paul Lawrie,
in a key foursomes match.
</P>
<P>
   If like personalities and golf games make for a successful
pairing, then Sutton and Maggert seem like obvious partners. They
are the epitome of steadiness and consistency, especially off the
tee, and set each other up well. When the Americans practiced here
late last month, the American captains asked whether Sutton and
Maggert would feel good about playing with each other, and they
did, getting an early taste of their partnership at Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came here this week realizing that's what we wanted to
do,'' said Sutton, ``so we practiced together all week and we're
comfortable playing with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   As pro golfers, of course, they keep a little bit of the
spectacular in reserve. They drew on it at just the right time
Saturday morning, with Maggert sinking a 25-footer on the 17th hole
to go 1 up, and then sticking his approach shot to a foot and a
half on No. 18 to close out the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hal drove it perfect there on the last hole,'' Maggert said,
``leaving me with perfect yardage for a 7-iron.'' An almost-perfect
pairing. Until Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   A Target Player Is Beaten
</P>
<P>
   In winning the first match Saturday morning, the United States
cracked ``the rock,'' the first step in what they hoped would be a
wholesale crumbling of the European team.
</P>
<P>
   In short, they finally beat Colin Montgomerie, the undisputed
leader of the Europeans, the first man out for them in each round,
taking the point in hostile territory. Despite his noted testiness
with American crowds, which surfaced again Saturday morning,
Montgomerie, the 36-year-old Scot, had played superbly. ``Like a
rock'' said Paul Lawrie, his playing partner in every round .
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie has seemed determined to succeed almost in defiance
of the Brookline galleries, which have treated him with a tough,
competitive edge or a striking lack of civility, depending on your
viewpoint. On Friday he complained to an official who several times
called out the incorrect winner of the hole, and stepped away from
putts from time to time to let the crowd calm down.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the strained relations continued, as Montgomerie
stared into the crowd several times, irritated by a camera flash or
an extended roar for the Americans. At the sixth, he stepped away
several times at the par-4 sixth hole as he waited to putt, then
finally stepped up to make the putt. He told Hal Sutton as they
walked off that the crowd's actions only made him more determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want them to call out to Colin,'' Sutton said. ``What
I wanted them to do is get behind us a little bit more. I want the
best for the European team. I don't want anyone to treat them
negatively. `'
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie is the No. 3 player in the world rankings, but has
never won on U.S. soil, and has had problems with what he felt were
overzealous galleries. On Saturday morning, it was Sutton and
Maggert who gave him the most trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Woods Off on His Drives
</P>
<P>
   Before the competition started, there was much speculation about
whether Tiger Woods would try to drive the short, par-4 sixth hole.
At 310 yards, it is reachable, but all the players carry, because
of a row of bunkers that protect the front of the green. Woods had
said it would depend on the wind, and the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the situation was right, in Woods' mind, in each of the
first three rounds. Each time, standing on the tee, Woods pulled
out his driver and launched into a long, arcing swing with the
power that only he can bring to it.
</P>
<P>
   The results were hardly spectacular. In Friday's foursomes, he
flew long past the pin into the light rough, and he and his
partner, Tom Lehman, ended up making bogey and losing the hole. It
was a turning point as Sergio Garcia and Jesper Parnevik, 2 down at
that point, won the hole and went on to win the match. In the
afternoon, Woods blocked his drive way right and was out of the
hole, leaving it to his partner, David Duval, to tie the hole, and
they, too, went on to lose.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday morning, playing with Steve Pate, Woods blasted his
drive into the wet rough on the left, and again the Americans lost
the hole, although they held on to win the match.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
