<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PLAYOFF-TIX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VYING FOR METS TICKETS WITH FINGERS CROSSED 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's tough being a Mets fan these days.
</P>
<P>
   First, the team hits the skids, putting its playoff hopes in
doubt. Then Saturday, to add to the pain, Mets management opened
its playoff ticket sales at Shea Stadium by selling the very first
batch to Joe Garruba, a die-hard Yankees fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking to trade them for Yankees tickets,'' bragged
Garruba, 27, of Bethpage, N.Y., clad in a Yankees jacket and
Yankees cap, as he held up his seven tickets for the news cameras.
``Don't miss the Yankees logo,'' he instructed the photographers
jockeying for position.
</P>
<P>
   Overhearing all this, Mets fans waiting in line behind Garruba
began loudly volunteering their thoughts on Garruba's wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   But, aside from a few shouts of ``Go Mets!'' the fans behind the
blue police barricades at the stadium Saturday morning proved to be
a mostly somber bunch. Losing has that effect on people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every fan here has faith that the Mets will make the
playoffs,'' said John Hammer, 17, of Brooklyn, who arrived at the
stadium at 3 a.m. with two friends. ``Valentine might choke,'' he
added, referring to the Mets acerbic manager, ``but the Mets
won't.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid a days-long buildup of fans camping overnight, the Mets
offered chances to buy playoff tickets through a lottery system, in
which Met, the team mascot, randomly selected numbered balls from a
large bin. The balls corresponded to numbers on the wristbands
arriving Mets fans received.
</P>
<P>
   But by 10 a.m., when ticket windows slid open and police
officers began funneling Mets fans through a series of narrow
chutes and barricaded holding pens leading to the windows, not all
that many Mets fans were around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were equipped for about 2,500, and I'd say there's only
1,300 here,'' said Eddie Enterlin, a Mets employee directing the
human traffic in front of Gate C Saturday. Asked about the dearth
of bodies on this, a usually frenetic first day of playoff ticket
sales, Enterlin shrugged. ``They're watching the scoreboard, these
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Most fans buying tickets at the stadium Saturday said they would
simply get refunds if the team misses the playoffs altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of horrified that they're maybe not going to make
it,'' Dennis Guyadeen said after buying four tickets for the first
home playoff game (if there is one). ``I don't know how they lost
to Philadelphia yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like they lost steam,'' said Guyadeen's friend, Sylvester
Harriett, of Patterson, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mets gave out a trophy to the most devoted fan, Kenneth
Reese, 24, of Ozone Park would probably win it.
</P>
<P>
   Between 8 p.m. Thursday and shortly after 10 a.m. Saturday,
Reese lived on a small red lawn chair outside Gate C, commiserating
with police officers, listening to his portable radio and getting
to know a few other ``wackos,'' as other Mets fans called the
sleep-over crowd.
</P>
<P>
   His booty: eight field-level tickets, at $40 each, and a
sunburned nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a huge Met fan,'' Reese, in a Mets jersey and Mets cap,
said, still clutching his red chair and his Mets blanket. ``It's
the only team I'll do this for. It's my life, my love.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Garruba, the Yankees fan who had arrived at only
6:30 a.m. Saturday and still got to the ticket window first, Reese
shook his head in disgust and said, ``It made me sick.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
