A6016 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-NASCAR-ADVANCE26-     09-25 0297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ADVANCE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brother crew chiefs on front row
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, Del. _ Jerry Nadeau's stunning crash in ``Happy Hour''
practice on Saturday evening caused a history-making moment for
today's MBNA Gold 400 to lose its luster.
</P>
<P>
   Nadeau offically will line up at the No. 2 position next to pole
sitter Rusty Wallace. Nadeau's crew chief is Ryan Pemberton, and
Wallace's team is directed by Robin Pemberton, his older brother.
</P>
<P>
   It marks the first time in NASCAR's 51-year history that
brothers who are crew chiefs have their cars starting on the front
row together at a Winston Cup event.
</P>
<P>
   However, Nadeau's stay up front won't last long. Because Nadeau
has to use a backup car, he must drop to the back of the pack
during the final warm-up lap before the green flag is waved.
</P>
<P>
   Nadeau's accident during the last practice session was
heartbreaking for the No. 36 team, which is co-owned by Atlantans
Read Morton, Nelson Bowers and Tom Beard. Nadeau lost control of
the car on the front stretch and collided into the inside retainer
wall. He was uninjured and finished practice in the backup car.
</P>
<P>
   The Pembertons have been competing against each other since
their childhood in Ballaston Spa, N.Y., and say nothing will change
for the historic race day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perfect way for (today) to end would be for us to win the
race and Rusty get his 50th (career) win and for those guys to
probably run second or third,'' said Robin, who is 13 years older
than Ryan. ``I've got the pull for (Wallace's teammate, Jeremy
Mayfield) too, but somewhere in that mix would probably be one of
the greater days in my life for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
