<HEADER>
A6017 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES26-CO     09-25 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Younger Petty's wreck has clan fuming
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, Del. _ Casey Atwood was the winner of the MBNA 200 on
Saturday, but the Busch race will be more remembered for what
happened before the finish.
</P>
<P>
   The event featured two controversial wrecks, including one that
ignited an angry exhange of words between third-place finisher Jeff
Green and NASCAR's most famous family.
</P>
<P>
   On lap 181, Green appeared to bump into the rear of Adam Petty,
grandson of legendary driver Richard Petty. The younger Petty, who
was running third at the time, was sent spinning into the outside
wall and then rolled back down the track, where he was T-boned by
Mike Skinner.
</P>
<P>
   Petty was taken by ambulance to Dover's Kent Hospital and
complained of soreness in the areas of the ribs, elbows, and hips.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little bit disappointed with the way (Green) handled
himself out there,'' said fuming father Kyle Petty. ``I guess that
is why Jeff Green doesn't have a Winston Cup car ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Replied Green, ``(Petty) was using his foot instead of his head
a little bit, I think. I'm not going to spin out anyone in any
shape or form, especially at Dover.''
</P>
<P>
   The other incident involved the two top drivers in the Busch
points standings, leader Dale Earnhardt Jr. and Matt Kenseth. They
were battling it out side-by-side for the lead on lap 120 when
Earnhardt ran into Kenseth, who wrecked and did not return to the
race. Earnhardt, who repeatedly apologized for the accident, had
brake problems the rest of the way and finished 33rd, gaining only
10 points on Kenseth.
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of the end?
</P>
<P>
   Today's MBNA Gold 400 should reveal more information on Ray
Evernham's future as crew chief for Jeff Gordon. Will mechanic
Brian Whitesell make the race-day calls in place of Evernham? Will
Evernham step down as crew chief after the race or wait until the
end of the season?
</P>
<P>
   The Evernham saga has dominated conversation in the garage area
since last weekend. Evernham has spent most of his time at Dover
dodging reporters, while Gordon is mum on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Racing death
</P>
<P>
   As usual with a racing death, the fatal accident of Kevin
Gobrecht in a World of Outlaws event on Friday night in Eagle,
Neb., sent shock waves through the Dover garage area. Gobrecht was
operating a sprint car owned by Busch driver Dave Blaney, who
requested no interviews Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Unfortunately, death can be the) nature of the beast,'' Ward
Burton said. ``Everybody knows we try to go fast, we run our
vehicles on the ragged edge a lot of times and things happen around
you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my life being cut short would be... I'd leave things
undone that I would want to accomplish in my life. The biggest
(worry) is that my children would not have a father and my wife
wouldn't have a husband. I think all the drivers tend to position
things so that our family is protected in case of a career-ending
accident or (death).''
</P>
<P>
   Extra laps
</P>
<P>
   The Winston Cup schedule for the 2000 season is being held up
while last-minute TV broadcast rights are being finalized. The
following year's schedule is traditionally released in early
September. ``I have to be honest _ we're a little bit behind,''
NASCAR czar Mike Helton said, ``but we're anxious to get it out so
that everybody knows what the deal is. We've simply been working on
a lot of details, and those details take time. Sometimes we're not
as punctual as we'd like to be, but we're very near to putting it
out.''... Ward Burton said he is ``just now 100 percent'' after
recovering from a concussion at the Michigan race on Aug. 22...
Darrell Waltrip and Todd Bodine were among five drivers failing to
earn a spot in today's race.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
