<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, A CHANCE FOR EVERYONE TO GET INTO IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ They sit and wait and cheer, just like the
galleries that have given the European Ryder Cup team a sense of
belonging at The Country Club this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   For European team members Andrew Coltart, Jarmo Sandelin, and
Jean Van de Velde, all of whom sat out for the second consecutive
day Saturday, it was patience, patience, patience. All will play in
Sunday's individual matches.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a solid lead on the first day, European captain
Mark James did not want to disturb the team's chemistry. So the
trio had to play cheerleader again.
</P>
<P>
   If the Europeans were trailing and the teams weren't working out
well, there might be some grumbling.
</P>
<P>
   But the Europeans have made this a team game. All for one and
one for all seems to mean more to the members of the European team,
who were given little chance to retain the Ryder Cup before the
matches started.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a team game,'' said Van de Velde. ``It's not an
individual ego track. The captain picks the pairings he feels most
confident with.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I just play one game and put a point on the board, it would
be great.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always expect to play,'' Van de Velde said. ``If they want
me, I will be there. I'm ready. All I care about is carrying that
cup around on Sunday night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
