<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-MATCH1P-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GOOD MORNING'S REST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL HARBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Ryder Cup captain Ben Crenshaw's selection of
Tom Lehman and Phil Mickelson for four-ball proved to be a good
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Both sat out the morning foursomes and were more rested than
opponents Lee Westwood and Darren Clarke, who were playing their
fourth round in 36 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw had hoped Lehman and Mickelson would get off to a fast
start and lead the way to a US afternoon sweep, something that
hadn't happened since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to put numbers up there so that the rest of the team
could see it and spur them on,'' said Lehman. ``You've got to give
my partner credit. I started slowly and he carried me until I got
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw's hunch paid off as the Americans rode to a 2-and-1
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans were steady, never letting their opponents win a
hole until 16, when they stood dormie.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson and Lehman were paired during the 1997 Ryder Cup at
Valderrama, Spain where they earned two halves. It was a happy
reunion. They started the afternoon off right for the Americans,
going 1-up on the third hole.
</P>
<P>
   Before the match, Crenshaw took Mickelson aside for a talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Phil this afternoon to trust his putting stroke,''
Crenshaw said. ``I told him, `Make a sweep and hit it solid.' All
he needs to do is for one or two to go down and he's off.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson, who missed short putts on Friday afternoon that
contributed to a four-ball loss, sported a new putter Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed a different look, something to gain confidence with.
I've carried it in my bag and have done this before,'' said
Mickelson.
</P>
<P>
   The putts went down for Mickelson on the front nine to help give
the Americans a 2-up lead at the turn.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson was the only player in the match to hit the third
green in regulation when he knocked a 180-yard 5-iron to 25 feet.
While others were scrambling to make par, Mickelson drained his
putt for a birdie-3.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson put his team 2-up on the eighth hole when he rolled in
a 15-foot downhiller from the back fringe.
</P>
<P>
   The European duo put on a charge on the par-5 ninth when Clarke
knocked his second shot onto the green. He lagged his sidehill putt
to 3 feet for a sure birdie.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mickelson was in the high rough and Lehman was on the
back fringe. Lehman imitated Mickelson's feat on No. 8 by draining
the tricky downhiller before putting on a fist-pumping exhibition
that resembled the Funky Chicken.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody was laughing; they were the only Americans leading
their match.
</P>
<P>
   The momentum carried to the next hole where Mickelson nearly
holed his approach shot and was treated to a bear hug by Lehman.
The Europeans conceded the birdie and the Americans walked from the
green 3-up.
</P>
<P>
   Westwood and Clarke made things interesting on No. 16. Both
Lehman and Mickelson had the opportunity to make matching-winning
birdie putts, but neither came through, and Clarke drained a
15-footer from the back fringe to keep the match alive.
</P>
<P>
   On 17, Clarke and Westwood had putts for birdie and a chance to
extend the match to the 18th. But they missed, Westwood's last
attempt hitting the hole and squirting out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 1944EDT &QL; 
