u s BC-GLF-RYDER-MICKELSON-B     09-25 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-MICKELSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGE OF PUTTERS HELPS MICKELSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WALTER V. ROBINSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Just like Friday, when he missed two critical
putts, Phil Mickelson was tentative as he stood over a 25-foot
birdie putt on the third hole Saturday afternoon. He backed away,
the uncertainty evident on his face.
</P>
<P>
   Then, his lips pursed, Mickelson stepped up to the ball and
stroked it into the hole, giving himself and partner Tom Lehman the
first lead of the match.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Mickelson's nerve and Lehman's steel, it was an
advantage they never relinquished. The American team took the first
match of the afternoon, beating Lee Westwood and Darren Clarke, 2
and 1.
</P>
<P>
   Again on the short, par-4 eighth, Mickelson _ who changed
putters overnight _ calmly dropped in a 15-footer for another
birdie to put the Americans 2 up. The US captain, Ben Crenshaw, all
but leaped onto the green to thump Mickelson on the arm.
</P>
<P>
   After Lehman rolled in a downhill 30-footer for a birdie to
halve the par-5 ninth hole, Lehman nearly hit the pin with his
second shot on the par-4 10th. But his ball spun 6 feet from the
cup.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently that wasn't good enough for Mickelson. From 131
yards, Lehman took out a wedge, and all but holed the shot: His
ball stopped 2 inches above the cup. The birdie, conceded, gave the
Americans a 3-up lead. It was a lead that survived a European
challenge on the par-5 14th when Mickelson halved the hole with a
birdie.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Mickelson played a better round of golf on Friday _
except for the short putts he missed at 16 and 18 _ Lehman said
afterward that his partner's play Saturday was phenomenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He held me up when I was really struggling,'' Lehman said.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, too, gave the men a boost with constant shouts of
encouragement. But no spectator gave Mickelson more of a boost than
Dave Gannon, a 32-year-old golf professional from the Golf Club at
San Leandro in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   When Mickelson hit his second shot over the green at 13, and
behind a square boulder that was not embedded in the ground, Gannon
obligingly stepped forward, picked up the boulder and moved it
aside. Mickelson chipped his shot through the green, but he holed
another chip from 30 feet to halve the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his solid play, Mickelson said after the match concluded
on 17 that he and Lehman could have closed out the Europeans
earlier had they made more putts.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, who missed a 4-foot birdie putt at 13 that would have
put the Americans 4 up, clapped his partner on the back, and said,
``We might have won 7 and 6 if i'd made any putts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
