<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6025 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-MATCH4P-BOS     09-25 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-MATCH4P-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEANS STEADY IN THEIR DOMINANCE OF WOOD, PATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ The match swayed back and fourth all
afternoon, and in the end it swayed toward Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Posting birdies on two of the last four holes, Colin Montgomerie
and Paul Lawrie bested the US pair of Tiger Woods and Steve Pate, 2
and 1, in their four-ball (best-ball) competition Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans began aggressively, just as they had in their
morning foursomes (alternate-shot) match against Miguel Angel
Jimenez and Padraig Harrington, again carding a birdie on the first
hole.
</P>
<P>
   Pate performed the early heroics, chipping in from to send an
immediate message to Montgomerie and Lawrie that this was going to
be just as tough a match as the British duo had had with Hal Sutton
and Jeff Maggert in the morning foursome match.
</P>
<P>
   But by the third hole the Europeans had squared the match, as
Montgomerie rolled in a 12-foot putt on the 451-yard par-4 after
Pate and Woods had missed birdie chances.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie's putter stayed hot on the 335-yard, par-4 fourth,
where he almost routinely sank a 10-foot putt for another birdie.
Woods then missed his from 9 feet, giving the Europeans the hole.
</P>
<P>
   But then it was Pate who got hot, making birdies on the sixth
and seventh, the latter courtesy of a marvelous 5-iron to 2 feet,
and the US was 1 up.
</P>
<P>
   Not for long. On the 378-yard, par-4 eighth hole, Montgomerie
sank another 10-footer from above the hole to square the match once
again.
</P>
<P>
   As the last foursome of the afternoon moved to the back nine,
the round was looking like a basketball game, with scoring surges
and lead changes.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans went ahead again on the 447-yard, par-4 10th hole
when Montgomerie almost holed his second shot from 177 yards, then
tapped in for a birdie. The Americans almost halved the hole,
however, as Woods's gallant chip from just off the green rolled to
within 2 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Advantage, Europe, once again.
</P>
<P>
   Woods's self-confidence _ or perhaps overconfidence _ almost
hurt him on the 11th. With Pate safely in the fairway, Woods chose
driver instead of 3-wood and pulled his tee shot into the woods,
194 yards from the hole. However, his brilliance got him out of
trouble, as he hit a low flier that hooked over the pond, landed in
light rough, and rolled onto the green.
</P>
<P>
   The shot apparently shook up Montgomerie, who badly pulled his
second shot, putting the pressure on Lawrie, who responded with a
brilliant shot that flew over the pin and settled 10 feet past.
</P>
<P>
   Next it was Pate's turn, and he was up for the challenge. He hit
a 6-iron to just outside of Lawrie's, giving the Americans two
legitimate birdie attempts to the Europeans' one.
</P>
<P>
   Pate missed his, as did Wood, but Lawrie as well. The Europeans
were still 1 up headed to the 486-yard, par-4 12th, the most
difficult hole on the course.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans took advantage. Both Woods and Pate reached the
green in two on their way to pars, while Montgomerie and Lawrie
failed to reach the green in regulation, then missed long par
putts. The US pair had squared the match once again.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans had an opportunity to take the lead on the
534-yard, par-5 14th when Woods put his second shot 10 feet above
the pin, but his eagle attempt rolled just past.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie kept the pressure up on the 432-yard, par-4 15th,
rolling in a 15-foot birdie putt after Woods and Pate had missed
theirs. The Europeans were 1 up with three to play.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans went dormie on the 186-yard, par-3 16th. Lawrie
hit his tee shot 3 feet from the pin for a birdie, putting the
pressure on the Americans. First, Pate's drive hit the crown of the
green but didn't release to the hole the way Lawrie's had. Then
Woods put his tee shot into the gallery on the right.
</P>
<P>
   When Pate missed his putt, the Americans were done.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 1947EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
