<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-MATCH3P-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JIMENEZ' HOT PUTTER GIVES EUROPEANS AN EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Miguel Angel Jimenez, the 35-year-old
Spaniard playing in his first Ryder Cup, displayed a cool demeanor
and a hot putter Saturday afternoon at The Country Club, giving him
and countryman Jose Maria Olazabal a jump-start against Justin
Leonard and Hal Sutton in their four-ball match.
</P>
<P>
   And he was pretty solid at the finishing hole as well.
</P>
<P>
   With Olazabal out of the par-4, 436-yard 18th with a bogey 5 and
the Americans in ``gimme'' range after two superb shots out of the
front bunker, Jimenez, the only member of the foursome to reach the
green in regulation, rescued his partner and got a point for his
team by halving the hole and the match.
</P>
<P>
   After stepping away from the 25-foot putt because of crowd
noise, Jimenez nearly sank it for a birdie and a win. But he
settled for a tap-in par, thwarting a gallant US comeback that
nearly included an ace by Sutton at 16.
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez, who carried his team all afternoon, was hot early on.
He sank birdie putts at Nos. 4, 5, and 6, turning a 1-up US lead
into a two-hole advantage the Europeans would need.
</P>
<P>
   There has never been a question about Jimenez's tenacity: Last
year, he won the Turespana Masters despite kidney stones so painful
he required midround injections. He approached these Ryder Cup
Matches humbly, saying, ``I thank God to be here. I'll try to help
my partners with my game. That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   That was an understatement. Just ask Leonard and Sutton, who
took the early lead when Olazabal missed a 4-footer for par at the
par-3 second, and narrowly missed extending their advantage at the
third when Sutton's 30-footer hung at the lip, but didn't fall.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Jimenez went to work.
</P>
<P>
   He canned an 8-footer dead-center on 4 for his first birdie, a
12-foot curler from the back of the fifth green for his second, and
an authoritatively struck 9-footer on the sixth for birdie No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The teams halved the par-4 eighth, then Leonard canned his
team's only birdie of the front nine, a 3-foot job for a 4 on the
513-yard hole after a superb sand wedge.
</P>
<P>
   The back nine started as a sparring match.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton's 25-foot birdie effort on the 10th slid past, then
Olazabal's 15-footer for a win curled around the cup.
</P>
<P>
   The teams halved the next three holes, with the most dramatic
moment Sutton's saving putt for a par 4 on 11.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared the Americans would square the match at the par-5
14th. Leonard and Sutton both had birdie putts, while Olazabal was
out of the picture and Jimenez's third shot had rolled off the
undulating green and well onto its collar.
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez pitched to about 8 feet, then sank a tricky putt that
just held the right edge of the cup for par. That was good enough
as neither Leonard nor Sutton came particularly close on their
birdie tries.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard redeemed himself at the par-4 15th while keeping his
team from going 2 down. After the Spaniards made routine pars,
Sutton couldn't escape trap woes and bogeyed, but Leonard calmly
stroked in a 7-footer for the halve.
</P>
<P>
   That wound up being important because Sutton nearly holed his
tee shot on the par-3, 186-yard 16th, as his ball bit two inches
from the pin. The putt was conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal couldn't connect from 40 feet, but Jimenez, who had
wielded the hot putter earlier, had a chance to halve from 12 feet
and barely missed.
</P>
<P>
   The match stayed even after 17 when Leonard's 9-foot birdie
attempt died short of the cup. Jimenez made a comeback 3-footer for
par.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
