   (NYT11) BUENOS AIRES, Argentina -- Sept. 25, 1999 --
ARGENTINA-CANDIDATE, 9-25 -- Fernando de la Rua, a candidate in
Argentina's presidential race, exits his campaign vehicle to meet
supporters in Luque in Cordoba Province. He leads in the polls and
says, ``I'm convinced I will win.'' With just a month until the
Oct. 24 vote, de la Rua has a gaping lead in the polls over
Duhalde, and there is virtually no Argentine political analyst who
has not already declared him and his center-left Alianza opposition
coalition the winner over the governing Justicialist Party.
(Horacio Paone/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 25, 1999 -- COURTS-ABORTION, 9-25 --
Janet Benshoof, president of the Center for Reproductive Law Policy
in New York, which sued to overturn abortion laws in three states.
A ruling on Friday by a federal appeals court, struck down a
particular late-term abortion procedure, a procedure in which the
fetus is partially extracted from the womb and then killed by the
insertion of a tube into the skull and the extraction of the brain.
The ruling represents the first significant legal step that may
compel the Supreme Court to determine the constitutionality of laws
barring the procedure. (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 25, 1999 -- BAY-BUCHANAN-PROFILE,
9-25 -- Bay Buchanan, a lean and avid political operative, says she
and her brother Patrick, the presidential candidate, are in
``political limbo'' while he considers switching parties. Buchanan
may abandon the GOP to seek the reform Party's nomination. ``I
can't ask people to give him money,'' she says. ``I can't build a
staff until we know where he's running. It's a very delicate
time.'' (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 25, 1999 -- U.S.-DIPLO-OAKLEY, 9-25
-- Assistant Secretary of State Phyllis Oakley, who is preparing to
retire after 42 years, at home in Washington. Oakley says the State
Department lacks the skilled people it needs to deal with the
post-cold-war era. The lofty ideal of the United States' leadership
and spreading the message of democracy and free markets cannot be
accomplished, she says, when ``we cannot staff our embassies, let
alone the department.'' (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) ROCKY MOUNT, N.C -- Sept. 25, 1999 -- NC-FLOODS-2, 9-25
-- In the aftermath of the floods that followed Hurricane Floyd,
Emily Hathaway ponders the daunting cleanup job in her neighborhood
of Riverside in Rocky Mount. Beyond the week's simple exhaustion
and sorrow, the prevailing emotion in this part of North Carolina
has been sheer astonishment. No one could believe that water could
rise so high, and stray so far from its natural courses. (Karen
Tam/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) ROCKY MOUNT, N.C -- Sept. 25, 1999 -- NC-FLOODS-2, 9-25
-- Steve Burn tries to salvage some family photographs as he sorts
through his parents' flood-soaked possessions in the neighborhood
of Riverside in Rocky Mount. At most, only a handful of homes out
of 200 solid brick-and-frame structures in the region will be
spared the bulldozer in the aftermath that followed Hurricane
Floyd. Beyond the week's simple exhaustion and sorrow, the
prevailing emotion in this part of North Carolina has been sheer
astonishment. No one could believe that water could rise so high,
and stray so far from its natural courses. (Karen Tam/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ROCKY MOUNT, N.C -- Sept. 25, 1999 -- NC-FLOODS-1, 9-25
-- Carol Brinkly returning home to her neighborhood of Riverside in
Rocky Mount. Rocky Mount, attempts to find any possessions left
untouched by the floods that followed Hurricane Floyd. At most, a
handful of homes out of 200 solid brick-and-frame structures in
Rocky Mount will be spared the bulldozer. Beyond the week's simple
exhaustion and sorrow, the prevailing emotion in this part of North
Carolina has been sheer astonishment. No one could believe that
water could rise so high, and stray so far from its natural
courses. (Karen Tam/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LORAINE, Ohio -- Sept. 25, 1999 -- LAKE-EERIE-SHIPWRECKS,
9-25 --Sue and Russ MacNeal, scuba-diving enthusiasts on Lake Erie,
remember when the murky water limited visibility to a few feet.
Now, they say, they explore wrecked ships that can be spotted from
50 feet away. The lake is clearer than it has been in decades, and
hundreds of divers are coming from as far as Florida to explore its
best kept secret: a vast underwater paradise of well-preserved
shipwrecks. (Barney Taxel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ICE HARBOR DAM, Wash. -- Sept. 25, 1999 --
HYDRO-DAM-DEBATE-3, 9-25 -- Darrol and Lois Timmons look at fish in
the fish ladder section of the Ice Harbor Dam near Kennewick, Wash.
Great dams generate cheap power but also add to the decline of
salmon. Efforts to save the Northwest's endangered wild salmon
include a proposal to breach four dams on the Snake River. The
earthen portions would be removed, allowing the river to return to
a free-flowing state. (Jackie Johnston/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LITTLE GOOSE DAM, Wash. -- Sept. 25, 1999 --
HYDRO-DAM-DEBATE-2, 9-25 -- The ladder on which fish bypass the
Little Gosse Dam on their way to the Pacific Ocean and back up
Washington's Snake River to spawn. Efforts to save the Northwest's
endangered wild salmon include a proposal to breach four dams on
the Snake River, including the Little Goose Dam. The earthen
portions would be removed, allowing the river to return to a
free-flowing state. (Jackie Johnston/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) LITTLE GOOSE DAM, Wash. -- Sept. 25, 1999 --
HYDRO-DAM-DEBATE-1, 9-25 -- A steelhead trout being directed to the
current of Washington's Snake River by John Cummins of Walla Walla,
Wash., who found it under a rock at Little Goose Dam. Great dams
have proved lethal on a gigantic scale to the region's wild salmon,
striving to complete their own remarkable journey from the rivers
out to the Pacific Ocean and back again to spawn, right where they
were born. (Jackie Johnston/New York Times Photo)
</P>
