<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6035 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-SHAUGHNESSY     09-25 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US NEEDS HERCULEAN EFFORT TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ The Europeans are putting into cups the size
of paint cans. Our Guys are aiming at thimbles.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods is the best golfer in the Nike world, but he is the
Roger Clemens of Ryder Cups, winning only twice in nine starts
(2-6-1). The ``I'' of the Tiger seems in conflict with team
matches.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans, according to their captain, are ``somewhat
chuffed,'' which we think means ``pleased.'' Our Guys are gagging
on their wallets, their rankings, and some of their comments.
</P>
<P>
   When the sun went down over The Country Club, there was a bad
moon rising and the Ryder Cup scoreboard read, Europeans 10, Our
Guys 6. Play resumes this morning, and unless Our Guys stage an
unprecedented rally (they need 8 1/2 of 12 remaining points), the
Europeans will put the Cup back on the Concorde and take it across
the pond sometime Monday.
</P>
<P>
   There was little Saturday to alleviate American fallout from
Friday's European rout. US wonderboys Woods, David Duval, and
Justin Leonard continued to struggle against the likes ot
19-year-old Spaniard Sergio Garcia and the ever-maddening Colin
Montgomerie.
</P>
<P>
   Monty no doubt will be the cleanup batter in Mark James's lineup
Sunday. The wide-body leader loves nothing better than beating
Woods, which he (along with teammate Paul Lawrie) did in Saturday's
best-ball match.
</P>
<P>
   Monty was somewhat riled by the local crowd and said, ``That's
the best thing we can do _ silence the crowd by outplaying them. .
. . They need pumping up because they're losing and they're losing
badly.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. Start with Woods, who had a good excuse when he was
a Ryder rookie in Spain two years ago but has dropped three of four
matches in Brookline. He was playing well coming into the
tournament, but the Ryder Cup is becoming his personal nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've hit it beautifully all week and I've putted well too,''
said Woods. ``Unfortunately, it's just not enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Leonard, a one-time British Open champ who is
winless (0-3-4) in seven career Ryder matches. The US had a good
thing going with the Hal Sutton-Jeff Maggert duo (two wins), but
team captain Ben Crenshaw elected to rest Maggert for the afternoon
session and replaced him with Leonard, who struggled mightily.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's David ``the Ryder Cup is an exhibition'' Duval.
The No. 2 player in the world, Duval was on the bench in the
morning but played in the nightcap and managed to halve a match
against Europe's awesome tandem of Garcia and Jesper Parnevik.
Credit Duval with 1 point of a possible 6 thus far, while Garcia
and Parnevik have rung up 7 of 8 possible points.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a business luncheon Friday, the great Arnold Palmer
_ a veteran of nine Ryder Cup teams _ said, ``Maybe our guys are
too businesslike about what's happening. Maybe they're taking it
too seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Folks following the morning match pitting Payne Stewart and
Leonard against Garcia and Parnevik might have come to the same
conclusion. Garcia and Parnevik are of different generations
(Sergio is 19, Jesper 34) and speak different languages, but they
enjoyed one another while the grim-faced Americans barely spoke.
Messrs. Woods, Duval, and Leonard walk the course like they're en
route to an appointment with their dentist.
</P>
<P>
   Duval and Davis Love appeared to have the Swede and Spaniard
beaten in the four-ball, but Garcia won the 18th hole and the US
had to settle for half a point. It was devastating, emotionally and
numerically.
</P>
<P>
   Love said, ``No matter what we do, it seems like they do us one
better. It seems like a loss to us, and I'm sure it seems like a
win to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Droll Euro captain Mark James, who says he keeps his troops
fresh by feeding them chocolate, has used his roster much like K.C.
Jones with the 1985 Celtics: He's played only nine of his 12
players. Scotland's Andrew Coltart, Sweden's Jarmo Sandelin, and
France's Jean Van de Velde have not yet played. It's unprecedented
for a captain to keep three players on the bench Friday and
Saturday, but the Euros don't care about sparing players' feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Sunday's play, the US has more rested players and a
reputation for dominance in singles match play. Two years ago at
Valderrama, the US was hopelessly behind going into the final day
but made things close by winning eight of 12 one-on-ones. They'll
need more than that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
