<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-MATCH2P-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL-LOVE WRING OUT A TIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA MATSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ David Duval did a little jig on the 10th
green Saturday afternoon. After sinking a long, difficult downhill
putt for a birdie that won Duval and partner Davis Love a second
straight hole from Sergio Garcia and Jesper Parnevik, the normally
dour Duval spun and punched the air.
</P>
<P>
   But Duval's dance was nothing compared to the air-punching,
hip-swiveling moves Garcia put down on the 18th hole after nailing
a 6-foot putt to win the hole and halve the match.
</P>
<P>
   In the second match of the best-ball foursomes, everybody
danced. And everybody led.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a frenetic match of shuffling leads, each team had
earned a point.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth match in two days for Garcia and Parnevik, who
have earned 3 1/2 points to lead the European effort.
</P>
<P>
   Love, who got a chance to sleep in Saturday morning after a
draining two matches Friday (two halves), and Duval, who lost twice
Friday, had a chance to win. Several chances.
</P>
<P>
   But a quick, strong start by the Americans _ 2 up after four
holes _ was countered by a putting streak from the Europeans. The
teams were all square after nine holes and though the American
three times wrested a one-hole lead, each time Garcia and Parnevik
took it back.
</P>
<P>
   On 18, after Love missed a 12-foot birdie putt that would have
won the match, Garcia ripped the heart out of the American team by
sinking his birdie to square the match one last time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it feels like a loss to us but I'm sure it feels like a
win to them,'' said Love.
</P>
<P>
   Love opened the match with a 10-foot birdie putt on the first
hole and Duval's 10-footer on No. 4 gave the Americans confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia started the Europeans' run with a 10-foot birdie putt on
the difficult fifth green. Parnevik topped that with a 25-foot
uphill putt on the sixth, and when Garcia slipped in an 8-footer to
win the eighth hole, putting the Europeans 1 up, Love and Duval
looked a little weary.
</P>
<P>
   But Love put the spring back in their step at No. 9. His tee
shot on the long, torturous hole landed on the rock outcropping
that cuts into the right fairway. His ball was lying quietly in
trampled fescue and after Duval knocked his approach shot from a
nearby perch on the same hill onto the green, Love uncorked a
powerful shot.
</P>
<P>
   The green was too far ahead to see clearly, about 230 yards, but
the noise from the crowd made it plain: Love's ball landed next to
the pin. When the players reached the green, Garcia and Parnevik
immediately conceded the eagle and walked on to the 10th tee.
</P>
<P>
   The reeling and wheeling was not over.
</P>
<P>
   Duval's putt on No. 10, with celebrities and US team members
crowding the fairway to watch, might have given the Americans a
final boost.
</P>
<P>
   But again Parnevik, who has played this Ryder Cup as if he was
the world's best player, sank a slippery 20-foot putt on 11 to
square the match. Duval's 12-foot putt into the heart of the 13th
restored the US lead, just in time for Parnevik to sink another
putt, this one from 10 feet, on No. 14.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans took their last lead at 16, when Love watched
Parnevik and Duval miss birdie putts before slowly setting his
8-footer into the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Love missed a birdie putt on 17 before the heartbreaker on 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish I'd had a putt on the last two holes,'' Duval
said. ``It's a little disappointing right now. Like Davis said,
once they had a chance to get out of something they did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
