<SLUG> BC-BBA-BAVASI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAVASI SOON WILL KNOW FATE WITH ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW BAGGARLY  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ In two weeks, Bill Bavasi will know his future
with the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The executive vice president and general manager either will
oversee the housecleaning in Anaheim, or he will become a victim of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Angels president Tony Tavares has said that every individual in
the organization will be scrutinized following one of the worst
seasons in franchise history. That includes Bavasi, the team's
general manager for six years, whose contract will expire following
the season.
</P>
<P>
   The season ends Oct.3. A decision on Bavasi is expected Oct.4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be done quickly,''' Tavares said. ``We need to make a
lot of decisions about a lot of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Tantamount to any other personnel decision is Bavasi's fate. He
either will be re-signed or pink-slipped.
</P>
<P>
   What does Bavasi think of the situation? Fully in character,
he's revealing nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi is one of the best poker players among baseball's GMs. He
keeps his cards close to his chest at all times. He never discusses
potential trades, never addresses rumor. Even after the fact, he
won't say what deals were on the table or what the sticking points
were.
</P>
<P>
   He is protective of his information. Except this time, it's
Bavasi who's in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't know what's going to happen any more than the rest
of us,'' Angels vice president and longtime friend Tim Mead said.
``So he's going to conduct himself every day like he's the general
manager. He will work with the thought in mind that nothing will
change. That's what he has to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is what Bavasi has done, busying himself with next
season's preparations, even bringing in former Milwaukee field boss
Phil Garner this week to interview for the Angels' managerial
opening.
</P>
<P>
   He's interviewing candidates at a time when, two weeks from now,
the candidates for his own job might begin lining up.
</P>
<P>
   During Bavasi's tenure, the Angels have zero division titles,
zero postseason games and three horrific September collapses. The
last one, in 1998, might have been averted had Bavasi pulled the
trigger on a trade-deadline deal to bolster the pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   But if Bavasi has a spot to hang his hat, it is his ability to
tie up home-grown players to long-term contracts at or below market
value.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are in position to clean house because they have
movable contracts. The Dodgers, with bloated, multiyear deals
committed to nags like Eric Young, Carlos Perez and Devon White,
have no such flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   And Bavasi has the loyalty of most of the team's core, if that
means anything. Gary DiSarcina, Troy Percival, Tim Salmon and
Garret Anderson are among the players developed and wrapped up to
long-term contracts by Bavasi.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's given me the opportunity to play in the big leagues and
I'll always be loyal to him for that,'' DiSarcina said. ``It's been
an aberration of a season. It's unfair to put all the blame on one
or two people. Obviously, Billy will step up and say it's his fault
because he put the players here. That's honorable, but not exactly
appropriate. The players are to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an unfinished job here. As a player, I hope I'm here
to finish with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Player opinion won't matter much to Tavares. Many of them might
not survive the purge anyway.
</P>
<P>
   One who will is Mo Vaughn, the Angels' franchise player, whose
disenchantment with Terry Collins had an impact on the manager's
resignation last month.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was enticed to Anaheim largely on the strength of a
pages-long letter from Bavasi that expressed admiration and respect
for the slugging first baseman. Vaughn signed a six-year, $80
million contract on Nov. 15, and despite a hobbled ankle, he has 29
homers and has topped the 100-RBI mark.
</P>
<P>
   His happiness is a primary concern, and because Vaughn signed to
play for Bavasi, he might take issue if the Angels opt to make a
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't make those decisions, so it's not my business to
comment on them,'' Vaughn said. ``But personally, I think we're
starting to get things straight in here. (Bavasi) can turn this
around. In the right circumstances, he could still do a very good
job here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi also has league-wide respect. Some GMs believe he isn't
willing to compromise, but then, that's also the reason Bavasi has
made just two fatally flawed trades in his six years -- the Damion
Easley and Jim Abbott deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my dealings with him were very professional,'' said Former
Dodgers GM Fred Claire, who discussed several trades with Bavasi
since 1994 but never agreed upon one. ``He would come straight at
his objective. There was never any dancing around with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi's level approach to negotiating contracts has worked the
same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was his first long-term deal and he was a tough nut,''
DiSarcina said. ``He's pretty good at what he's doing. He's honest
as Abe Lincoln, and a player can't ask for anything more than
honesty.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing is for certain. Despite rumors of the franchise's
impending sale to Broadcom CEO Henry Nicholas III, the decision to
retain or fire Bavasi will be squarely in Tavares' hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can speculate all they want, but I have to make a
decision,'' Tavares said, ``and I won't until the season is over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
