<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BAKER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUSTY BAKER Q &AMP;A
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAMIAN SECORE  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Though Dusty Baker was always labeled as a Dodger
during his playing career, he's always thought of himself as a
Northern California guy. It's where his family and livelihood is,
his job being manager of the San Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   His association with the rival Giants may have prompted the
Dodgers entourage to ask, `Why the Giants?' when Baker accepted the
position Dec. 16, 1992. Baker's response would be, `Why not?'
</P>
<P>
   He's twice been NL Manager of the Year. He took the Giants to
the playoffs in 1997, to a one-game, wild-card playoff last year,
and kept them in the hunt this year despite a rash of injuries to
those like Barry Bonds (47 games missed), Jeff Kent and Ellis
Burks, and handling a young pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   He's never felt like a traitor towards the Dodgers. Meanwhile,
he's carved his reputation as one of the game's elite managers.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun: With the injuries, how had your team been able to stay
in the pennant race for so long?
</P>
<P>
   Baker: I think it's a testament of their intestinal fortitude,
their desire, the fact that these guys come out and play hard. You
know, most teams don't play hard everyday. You play hard, you get
good pitching, you got a good chance to win. Plus the fact that we
lost Barry (Bonds) for those days and we had a guy like Armando
Rios come up and play. We lost Ellis (Burks) and Armando got to
stay and play some more. Then we lost Jeff (Kent) and we had Ramon
Martinez fill in. A lot of it we got to give to our bench players,
guys that came up from Triple-A, so I got to commend our minor
league system for being so deep and talented.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What improvements or changes are needed for next year?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think staying healthy and the fact that our young pitchers
are gonna have to mature and get better _ Shawn Estes, Joe Nathan,
Russell Ortiz and the other young guys we have. We have to shore up
our bullpen. But it gives me a lot of satisfaction to know that
these guys don't quit, and just knowing that with any kind of luck
or any kind of year where we have everybody healthy that soon we'll
be knocking on the door and going all the way.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you still feel like a Dodger in any way?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, not really. None of me is Dodger blue anymore because I
haven't been here since 1983. Things change and things become a
memory in your mind. I enjoyed the days that I played here. I
enjoyed the guys that I played with here. I love it up North. My
folks are there. We moved from Riverside in 1965 to Sacramento, so
the majority of my life has been spent there even though all of my
early days were spent in Southern California, which I enjoyed a lot
too. But I like to fish and hunt, and these are things that are
most conducive to my personality and are a lot easier to do in the
North than it is in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are your fondest Dodgers memories?
</P>
<P>
   A: Probably the guys that I played with and going to the World
Series and the playoffs. Just knowing that when you went to spring
training, that you had a real good chance of going to the World
Series. Playing with Davey Lopes and Reggie Smith and Garvey and
Cey and Yeager and Ferguson and Darrel Thomas, Lee Lacy, Manny
Mota, Jose Morales, and all the other guys; we were a very
close-knit team. We hung together, we ate together, we had a couple
beers together, guys would stick around and talk baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How have you perceived the Dodgers-Giants rivalry to be
during your playing days and now?
</P>
<P>
   A: Twenty years ago, there wasn't much of a rivalry, I don't
think, because we were winning most of the time. It's hard to have
a rivalry when we were doing most of the winning. At that time, our
main rivals were the Cincinnati Reds and the Houston Astros; those
were the good teams. Since I've been here, it's been more of a
rivalry from Northern California from the Giants fans to the
Dodgers fans than from the Dodgers fans to the Giants fans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
