<SLUG> BC-DEMS-MEET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DUELING SPEECHES, GORE AND BRADLEY TRY TO COURT DEMOCRATIC PARTY
LEADERS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In back-to-back speeches before the year's biggest
gathering of Democratic power brokers, former Sen. Bill Bradley
sought Saturday to loosen Vice President Al Gore's grip on the
Democratic Party's leadership, while Gore staved off the challenge
with a lively appeal on issues dear to the rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two contenders were on stage separately at the fall
meeting of the Democratic National Committee, this was the first
time party loyalists had compared them so directly in what has
become an unexpectedly hard-fought campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Belying their reputations as less than exhilarating speakers,
Gore and Bradley delivered dueling presentations that made for the
most dramatic party meeting in years. The crowd gave enthusiastic
receptions to both men as they avoided direct assaults on each
other and vied for the party's heart.
</P>
<P>
   The audience was stocked with White House officials and other
political luminaries eager to witness the face-off at the last
formal party meeting before the Democrats pick their nominee in Los
Angeles next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's pitch was well received, as he sought to persuade
Democrats that he shared their goals _ and was not looking to rip
apart the party. But then Gore won many over with an unusually
lively appeal that he had the heart to champion Democratic issues
like education and health care.
</P>
<P>
   The audience applauded Bradley especially enthusiastically when
he named party leaders who back Gore and would be elevated if the
Democrats won control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie Rangel may not be for me, but I sure want him to be
the chairman of the Ways and Means Committee,'' he said of the New
York congressman. ``Dick Gephardt may not be for me, but I sure
want him to be speaker of the House of Representatives. Tom Daschle
may not be for me, but I sure want him to be the Senate majority
leader.'' Gephardt is minority leader in the House, Daschle in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 428 members of the Democratic National Committee _
whose support is crucial at the party's convention _ have already
signed up with Gore. He has cultivated them for seven years and
been a fixture at party gatherings. Bradley had not attended a
national party meeting in years.
</P>
<P>
   His reading glasses perched on his nose, Bradley offered an
understated address that was full of wry lines. For example, he
said his father did not want him to be a professional basketball
player _ until he learned how much the job paid. Even Gore
loyalists, who sat in the front of the vast ballroom at the
Washington Hilton, rose to their feet at the end of Bradley's
speech, in which he touched on themes like controlling handguns and
lifting children out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore, who in recent weeks has been confronted with polls and
other evidence suggesting that Bradley is emerging as a potent
rival, was greeted like a conquering hero to the strains of the
O'Jay's hit, ``Love Train.'' Leaving the lectern (a move that
obscured the vice presidential seal) and referring only
occasionally to notes, Gore acknowledged his friends in the
audience and vowed ``to work my heart out'' to win the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he had had no use for politics after serving in
Vietnam and after his father lost his Senate seat from Tennessee.
But later, he said, when he was working as a journalist, he
experienced ``the thrill of watching democracy in action'' that was
``almost impossible to describe _ and it never left me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, seeking to strike out on his own, did not mention
President Clinton even once, although Bradley referred to Clinton's
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   And neither foe mentioned the other. The closest Gore came to
criticizing his challenger was in a reference to school vouchers,
which Bradley once supported on a trial basis. ``I have never been
for vouchers,'' Gore declared. ``We need to invest in our public
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Both men saved their sharpest criticism for the Republican
front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, and his reluctance to
expand his state's hate-crimes law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm for affirmative action because it's still needed,'' Gore
said. ``And I am also for the passage of a hate-crimes law. When
James Byrd is dragged from the back of a pickup truck because of
his race. When Matthew Shepard is crucified on a split-rail fence
by bigots, how can any political leader in either party say that
there is a difference between hate crimes and other crimes?''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said, ``The governor of Texas had let it be known that
this bill would not reach his desk.'' If he is the Democratic
nominee, Bradley said, ``I will make it an issue in the
presidential election in the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   They both touched on many of the same red meat issues _ like gun
control, Social Security, health care and campaign-finance reform.
Gore went so far as to promise high-quality preschool for every
child in America. And Bradley said: ``There is no reason we can't
dramatically reduce the number of children living in poverty in
this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the fierceness of the competition for the nomination, the
behind-the-scenes maneuvering, and intrigue, was limited. Hours
before the program began, party officials shifted the schedule so
Gore could speak last.
</P>
<P>
   Party officials insisted that the schedule change was intended
to give more prominence to the election of Mayor Ed Rendell of
Philadelphia as the party's general chairman. The program was also
designed so that Bradley was safely off stage and out of the hotel
before the vice president appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's loyalists did make a subtle move to remind Democrats that
Bradley left the Senate in 1996 with bitter parting words for the
American political system. They passed out red, white and blue
buttons that said, ``ALways a Democrat!'' _ with ``AL'' in big
letters. But Bradley's forces e-mailed young supporters,
encouraging them to attend the meeting and arming them with
placards. Both sides turned out roughly the same number of
cheerleaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bradley did an admirable job,'' said Bob Ream,
chairman of the Montana Democratic Party. ``But it was a remarkable
improvement in Gore's performance. Is it going to be a real race?
It is a real race.''
</P>
<P>
   But the speeches were only the beginning. Even after he left the
ballroom Saturday, Bradley abruptly returned to shake hands with a
longtime Democrat whose support he desperately needs: John J.
Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   The federation has been leaning toward endorsing Gore, but
Sweeney said Bradley has ``a good message'' and ``has shown he
wants to run a high-level campaign here and wants to come out with
a victory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
