<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-LEAD26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tough course left for Americans
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Heavy underdogs given little respect a few
days ago, they have put the pressure on the underachievers at the
Ryder Cup. After a break-even Saturday at The Country Club, Europe
takes a 10-6 lead into today's closing singles of the 33rd Ryder
Cup at The Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to avoid a third consecutive defeat by the Europeans, the
Americans played more to their games Saturday after a nervous start
Friday, but still face a tough task today.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time the Americans have trailed entering the
final day on U.S. soil, the other two occasions occurring in
England in 1949 and 1993. At The Belfry in '93 _ scene of their
last victory _ the Americans trailed 8 1/2-7 1/2 after two days,
dominated the singles 7 1/2-4 1/2 and won the match 15-13.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 6-2 after Friday's opening competition, the Americans
split the Saturday morning foursomes (alternate shot) matches to
trail 8-4, then held their ground in afternoon best ball, winning
one match and halving another.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans need just four points in the 12 singles matches to
retain the cup, bringing odds that don't favor the United States.
Only once in the past 40 years has the European team failed to win
at least four points in singles, limited to 3 1/2 in 1979, when the
U.S. pulled out a 17-11 win.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lehman and Phil Mickelson won the only match for the
Americans in best-ball Saturday, defeating Darren Clarke and Lee
Westwood 2 and 1. Mickelson missed crucial putts on 16 and 18
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for the rest of the team to see that lead group doing
some damage was real important,'' Lehman said.
</P>
<P>
   Europe's star team of 19-year-old Sergio Garcia and Jesper
Parnevik, who have sunk putts and chips from everywhere, salvaged a
half against Davis Love III and David Duval in best-ball. Garcia
and Parnevik were 3-0-1 over two days after Garcia made a 7-foot
birdie putt at the 18th, matching a birdie Love made on the 16th
for the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have fun, I play well,'' said Garica, the youngest player
in Ryder Cup history. ``I've been getting crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great two days,'' said Parnevik, who pitched in
for a surprise matching par at the 14th. ``Unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Europe's only best-ball win came from their consistent Scottish
team of Colin Montgomerie and Paul Lawrie, who defeated Tiger Woods
and Steve Pate 2 and 1 in the anchor match. Miguel Angel Jimenez
and Jose Maria Olazabal halved their match with Americans Justin
Leonard and Hal Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
