<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-DAY-TWO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS CAN'T CLOSE THE GAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ There was a trace of electricity in the air
Saturday as the 33d Ryder Cup matches resumed with the European
side in command, 6-2, after Friday's opening matches.
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks broke quickly from the gate, but the brief dousing of
the course, which delayed things a bit, seemed to cool them off and
the morning foursomes ended with each side earning 2 points.
</P>
<P>
   It left the Europeans with an 8-4 advantage, the same as they
enjoyed after the rain-delayed second day two years ago at
Valderrama, Spain, where they ended up celebrating a 14 1/2-13 1/2
victory that kept the Cup in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the team of Phil Mickelson-Tom Lehman building a
3-hole through No. 10 and never looking back except for a little
scare on the par-3 16th when Lee Westwood ran in a sizable putt for
a birdie to keep things interesting, the closest the US side could
close the gap was 8-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the guys to look up on the board and see us go 1-up, 2-up,
and 3-up, they could say, `Let's keep on going,' '' said Lehman.
``I think for the rest of the team to see the lead group doing some
damage was very important.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, but it wasn't quite enough to lift the troops completely
out of the doldrums. Momentum definitely shifted back across the
pond in the four-ball matches when Tiger Woods missed from 6 feet
on the 17th, allowing the irrespressible Colin Montgomerie and
British Open champion Paul Lawrie to chalk up a huge point over him
and Steve Pate, America's other winning combination in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Garcia, who had missed makeable birdie putts on 15 and
17, sank the one that really counted on the 18th. His birdie from
just outside 6 feet enabled him and Jesper Parnevik halve their
match with Davis Love-David Duval and remain undefeated for the
weekend with 3 1/2 points.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's team matches ended with Miguel Angel Jimenez
watching his potential winning putt die on edge of the cup on 18,
which locked up a halve for him and fellow Spaniard Jose Maria
Olazabal with Hal Sutton-Justin Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   So, with all said and done, the day ended as it began _ with the
Europeans up by 4 points. They led 10 1/2-5 1/2 entering singles
matches two years ago at Valderrama.
</P>
<P>
   There were some brilliant shots over the closing holes Saturday.
Sutton, who had been absent from Ryder Cup play for 12 years,
nearly holed his tee shot on 16, and the Spanish Armada once again
ruled supreme: Garcia and Parnevik went 3-0-1 in four matches.
Jimenez, who was an assistant captain two years ago, completed a
1-0-3 trip, and Olazabal, whose career was in jeopardy just a
little over two years ago with a serious foot problem, has been
2-0-1. The Spanish have contributed to a total of 9 points.
</P>
<P>
   Woods and Pate started their morning with four straight birdies
in the alternate-shot competition, and would have surged to a 4-up
advantage had Dubliner Padraig Harrington not rolled in a birdie
putt to halve a hole. The visitors then proceded to win the 6th,
8th, and 11th to pull all square. This was the way it went until
Woods rolled in a putt for an eagle and a 1-up edge on the par-5
14th.
</P>
<P>
   In that match the 17th, the most notorious hole a the Country
Club for swinging momentum, proved key again when Harrington's
approach shot to the severe slope in back of the pin refused to
spin bck to the hole. ``I got robbed,'' said Harrington. ``I
couldn't believe it when the ball stopped on the slope. It was
obvious it would have been stone dead if it had rolled back. That
was an important point at the end of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The 18th wasn't pretty, but Woods lagged his putt to the lip for
a conceded par and the 1-up victory that left the Europeans with an
8-4 lead entering the afternoon fourball competition.
</P>
<P>
   After lunch, the US picked it up early and led all four matches.
Montgomerie put a temporary end to that holing a birdie putt on the
third with partner Paul Lawrie at his side to square things with
Woods and Pate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am happy to maintain our lead,'' said European captain Mark
James, who played on seven teams and made a run at making it an
eighth this year. ``We achieved our objective to play some good
golf today, and to win points they had to play well. They know what
they are up against, and we know what we are up against.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a question of relying on big guns. I have a feeling
that some players are playing slightly better than others and are
slightly more capable of shooting lower. It's a very narrow margin,
and I'm going with those players because they are doing a good job.
To change tactics would be dangerous. It's something we've all
discussed. I think we're happy doing what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The team of Jim Furyk and Mark O'Meara, who are generally
regarded has having two of world's best short games, failed to
register a single birdie in their 3-and-2 foursomes setback to
Westwood and Darren Clarke. ``It's disappointing,'' said O'Meara,
who sat out the first two matches and didn't play in the afternoon.
``We didn't play poorly, but we didn't make any putts. They birdied
the two Par 5s (9, 14), where we had good drives and didn't make
any birdies. That was the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   And the overall difference between the teams still stands at 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
