<SLUG> BC-BBA-LAMB-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAMPA BAY'S LAMB LEARNS THE ROPES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ No player on the Tampa Bay Devil Rays roster has
started fewer games this season than David Lamb, but the rookie
infielder doesn't despair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not greedy,'' said Lamb, 24, a former star at Newbury Park
High. ``I realize I'm not the number-one guy here, so I just wait
my turn and do the best I can when I'm in the game. I know I will
get my opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamb, a Rule V selection from the Baltimore Orioles last winter,
made the Devil Rays' 25-man roster on the last day of spring
training and has been with the big club all season.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb has appeared in 52 games (including 27 starts) and is
batting .227 with one home run and 13 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the ideal situation for a young player, who might be
better served by playing every day in the minor leagues, but Lamb
wouldn't trade his seat on the end of the Devil Rays' bench for any
starting job in Triple-A.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great ride and this is my dream come true,'' Lamb
said, ``but yeah, it has been a difficult role to get used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been times when I played a week straight, then had a
month off, then played a week straight again.... So it's been
different, but I've definitely learned a lot just from watching
some of the veteran players.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Larry Rothschild recognizes the difficult role in which
Lamb has been placed, and is pleased with the rookie's progress and
his willingness to play both shortstop, his natural position, and
second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk to him periodically, just to let him know what his
situation is,'' Rothschild said. ``He understands it, and he has
handled it beautifully. He is always prepared whenever he gets a
chance, and that's because he works very hard between at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always out hitting early and taking ground balls, working
on all phases of his game. For a guy with limited Triple-A
experience, he's done a fine job.''
</P>
<P>
   Selected by the Orioles in the 1993 Draft out of Newbury Park,
where he also excelled as a quarterback, Lamb spent his first four
seasons bouncing between Single-A clubs. Midway through the 1997
season, he was promoted to Double-A Bowie, where he hit .331 in 73
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles intended to promote Lamb to Triple-A before the 1998
season, but didn't because of an injury to Bowie's starting
shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't real happy with the way everything was going with the
Orioles,'' Lamb said. ``I felt like I was getting ... not buried,
but kind of pushed aside for some reason, because I was doing well
and I wasn't getting any hype.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamb was selected to the Double-A All-Star Game after hitting
.303 in 66 games, and finally the Orioles moved him up to Triple-A
Rochester, where he hit .298 in 48 games, including .354 in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then the season ended, and they left me off the (40-man)
roster again,'' Lamb said. ``At that point I knew I had a pretty
good chance of being a Rule V selection.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Rule V draft, players may be drafted by other
organizations, but if they do not make the 25-man roster of their
new teams, they are sent back to the original organization. On Dec.
14, the Devil Rays came calling for Lamb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked in the front door one day, and the phone rang,'' Lamb
said. ``It was the Orioles, congratulating me and telling me that
I'd been added to the 25-man roster of the Devil Rays. You hope
something like that happens, and you hope somebody realizes all the
hard work you put in, but that wasn't a guarantee of a roster
spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamb went to spring training and battled for a spot as a utility
infielder. The competition was tough, and in the eighth inning of
the final spring training, infielder Aaron Ledesma broke his thumb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting in the dugout, and I was like, `What's going to
happen now?' '' Lamb said. ``At that point I still didn't know what
they were going to do with me. But Larry and (general manager Chuck
LaMar) called me in and said, `Congratulations, you made the team,
and don't think it's because Aaron got hurt, because you played
well and you earned a spot.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I was speechless, and all I could do was thank them for the
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Lamb looks around the clubhouse and sees the players he
previously knew only by reputation. The Devil Rays, a second-year
expansion team, have a mix of young players and veterans such as
Wade Boggs, Jose Canseco and Fred McGriff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up watching these guys, and now all of a sudden I'm on
a first-name basis with them,'' Lamb said. ``I grew up collecting
their cards, now I'm playing catch with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learn a lot just by watching them. You can see why they have
been in the big leagues for 15 or 16 years, just by the way they go
about their business and are professional in everything they do.''
</P>
<P>
   So this year has been watch-and-learn time for Lamb, who looks
forward to the day when he can roam the infield every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I have a good chance of coming in next year and
winning a spot on the team again,'' Lamb said. ``I don't plan on
ever going back down to the minors, but if it happens it happens.
It's been a good ride, and if I never play up here another day,
it's still been extremely exciting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
