<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-CUP-ART-2TA     09-25 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-CUP-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT UNDERDOGS? EUROPE OPENS A FORMIDABLE LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (HLW)  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ With one day left in the Ryder Cup
competition, the United States is running out of time, running out
of matches and running out of opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Outplaying the United States for the second consecutive day, and
winning two crucial four-ball matches in the afternoon, Europe took
a commanding 10-6 lead into Sunday's 12 singles matches at The
Country Club. Europe needs just 4 of the 12 points on Sunday to
retain the cup and to win the biennial event for the third
consecutive time.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, as the challengers, need 14{ points to win the
cup, meaning they need 8{ points on Sunday to avoid another
disappointing loss.
</P>
<P>
   No team has ever come back from a 5-point deficit on Sunday to
win, and considering what has transpired so far, the United States
faces a formidable task. Jesper Parnevik and Sergio Garcia have
been brilliant for Europe, winning three matches and earning a
crucial half-point Saturday afternoon. And the Europeans have
continued their winning formula, making remarkable chip shots and
pressure putts, and securing momentum-building victories that have
inspired their teammates and deflated their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Favored to win, but frustrated by the events, the U.S. players
refused to give up, but they knew it would take a heroic effort to
avoid another defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything they do, they do it one better,'' said Davis Love
III, who is in danger of playing on his third consecutive losing
team.
</P>
<P>
   Splitting Saturday's foursome matches, 2-2, and the four-ball
matches, 2-2, Europe protected the 6-2 lead it started the day
with. The most deflating loss of the afternoon for the United
States was absorbed by Tiger Woods and Steve Pate, who were beaten,
2 and 1, by Colin Montgomerie and Paul Lawrie. Montgomerie,
Europe's best player, outperformed Woods, the world's best player.
</P>
<P>
   With the match all square through 14 holes, both Montgomerie and
Lawrie stepped forward. Montgomerie won No. 15 with a sensational
16-foot birdie putt. Then at the par-3 186-yard No. 16, Lawrie hit
his tee shot to within 2 feet of the cup, leading to a birdie that
put his side 2 up with two holes to play.
</P>
<P>
   But the most emotional and well-played match Saturday afternoon
was Love and Duval against Garcia and Parnevik, a roller-coaster
ride of sensational shots. It was Garcia who fired the final salvo,
with an extraordinary birdie at the par-4, 436-yard No. 18 that won
the hole and secured a crucial half-point for Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Love had a 15-foot putt to win the match at No. 18, but missed,
leaving Garcia with his putt. Though Parnevik's ball was farther
from the hole, Parnevik asked Garcia to putt first. And when
Garcia's ball dropped in the hole, his body shook in celebration
and he knew that he had once again done something important and
dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I like to do,'' Garcia said. ``I like playing
golf, and I like playing for my continent. I like having fun, and
if I have fun, I play well.''
</P>
<P>
   Love and Duval felt as if they had let a half-point slip away
despite their strong play. Love hit one of the competition's most
incredible shots, a 220-yard approach shot at the par-5 ninth hole
that almost went in the hole for an eagle. Duval also made an
improbable 35-foot downhill birdie putt in the match, but none of
that was enough to beat Garcia and Parnevik. And knowing his team's
dire situation, Love didn't feel that a half-point in his match was
good enough.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps, but we gave them an out, and they got out of it,''
Love said. ``David played great, but it feels like a loss to us.
And I'm sure it feels like a win to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The other afternoon four-ball match that ended even was Justin
Leonard and Hal Sutton against Miguel Angel Jimenez and Jose Maria
Olazabal. Sutton has been the American's most productive player
with 2{ points, and he saved a half-point for the United States at
No. 16 when he hit a wonderful tee shot that was almost a
hole-in-one, stopping within a foot of the cup, leading to the
birdie that evened the match for good.
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez had a chance to win the match at No. 18, but his 18-foot
birdie putt stopped just inches from the cup, and the Americans
escaped with a half-point.
</P>
<P>
   The first afternoon match was the most one-sided, as Phil
Mickelson and Tom Lehman defeated Darren Clarke and Lee Westwood, 2
and 1. The Americans built a 3-up lead after 10 holes, with
Mickelson hitting an approach shot at No. 10 that nearly went in
for an eagle. The Europeans conceded the tap-in birdie to
Mickelson, and they never got closer than 2 points the rest of the
match.
</P>
<P>
   It was redemption for Mickelson, whose two missed short putts
Friday afternoon cost his team a match.
</P>
<P>
   ``My confidence wasn't as high as I would have liked,'' said
Mickelson, who switched putters Saturday. ``I feel like after
making a few putts today that I'm ready for singles.''
</P>
<P>
   The pageantry in the gallery made for a special atmosphere, with
fans holding American and European flags, Michael Jordan and the
former President George Bush following the action from inside the
ropes, and roars echoing through the trees with every shift in
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   But the Europeans remained rock solid and set the tone by
splitting the morning matches. It was not the hard-charging
comeback the United States had hoped for, but it could have been
far worse. At one point, the United States was in danger of losing
all four matches, which would have virtually ended any hope for a
United States victory. But thanks to victories by the teams of
Maggert and Sutton and Woods and Pate, the United States remained 4
points behind heading into the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. captain, Ben Crenshaw, elected to break up the team of
Maggert and Sutton Saturday afternoon, resting Maggert and
replacing him with Leonard. It was a risk, because Sutton and
Maggert had played so well together, winning two of three matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a complete hunch,'' Crenshaw said of his decision to
bench Maggert and to play Leonard. ``I think Justin is going to
have the feel of the goal course, and I'm banking on his putter
getting hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning it took heroics just for the United States not
to fall further behind. The Maggert-Sutton victory over Montgomerie
and Lawrie was the morning's most intense match.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie, who has a history of losing his temper at key
moments, had his first Ryder Cup confrontation with hecklers at the
sixth hole. After Sutton made a 14-foot birdie, the crowd roared,
chanting ``U.S.A.! U.S.A.!'' Montgomerie needed to make his 10-foot
birdie putt to halve the hole, and he waited about 30 seconds for
the crowd to quiet. But as he settled over his putt, someone from
the gallery yelled something. Montgomerie backed off and looked
toward the gallery. But when he finally regrouped, he made the putt
to halve the hole. And when the ball fell in the cup, he looked
toward the gallery and defiantly pumped his fist.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sutton, as they walked toward the No. 7 tee,
Montgomerie said, ``What these people are too stupid to realize is
that this only makes me more determined.''
</P>
<P>
   After the loss, Lawrie seemed upset that on several occasions,
Sutton had urged American fans to cheer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their behavior was just ridiculous,'' Lawrie said of Sutton's
and Maggert's encouragement of the fans. ``I don't mind it when
we've both played, but to do it before the next opponent hits a
shot? If it means that much to them, then all the best to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, emotions were more intense Saturday, as the U.S. team
arrived inspired after a team meeting Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all echoed the same thing,'' Maggert said. ``I've
been on two losing Ryder Cup teams and it's no fun. A lot of my
teammates feel the same way. I know the guys on the last two Ryder
Cup teams are not ready to face that again.''
</P>
<P>
   But unless the Americans enjoy a glorious Sunday, they will face
another loss. Seven Europeans will be playing their fifth match in
five days, compared with just two Americans, so the United States
may be fresher. But as motivated and confident as the Europeans
were, that may not matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played a lot of holes the last two days,'' Clarke said.
``But I'll be ready tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
