<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6072 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-MICHIGAN-WISCONSI     09-25 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MICHIGAN-WISCONSIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN BEATS WISCONSIN, 21-16  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADISON. Wis. _ They have a poor running game but somehow find a
way to grind out the yards they need. Their coach cannot decide on
a quarterback but seems to get timely plays from both of them. And
now, after outlasting Wisconsin, 21-16, Saturday, the unbeaten
Michigan Wolverines and Coach Lloyd Carr have won four games and
are in the national title picture.
</P>
<P>
   While the Michigan defense contained the big Badger, Ron Dayne,
a couple of Wolverines who many believe Carr does not like that
much made a case to keep their jobs: halfback Anthony Thomas and
quarterback Tom Brady.
</P>
<P>
   In a third-quarter drive that gobbled up 91 yards and 3 minutes
38 seconds and put Wisconsin away, Thomas and Brady took turns
keeping it alive on crucial third downs.
</P>
<P>
   From Michigan's 12-yard line, Brady rocketed a sideline pass to
Marcus Knight for 11 yards and a first down. On third-and-1 at the
32, Thomas bulled up the middle for 3 yards and a first down. And
on third-and-7 at Wisconsin's 23, Brady dropped back, pump-faked
and delivered a touch pass to DiAllo Johnson in the end zone for an
emphatic score. Brady finished 17 of 27 passing for 217 yards and 2
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't pretty. It wasn't exciting. It really wasn't even that
close _ the freshman quarterback Brooks Bollinger scrambled 13
yards for a Wisconsin touchdown with 1:29 left to make it 21-16.
But that was it for the No. 20 Badgers (2-1).
</P>
<P>
   The No. 4 Wolverines (4-0) held Dayne to 88 yards _ all in the
first half _ in a stifling defensive performance in the teams' Big
Ten opener. In the second half Dayne had zero net yards on eight
carries and twice failed to get critical first downs.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne came into the game 1,193 yards shy of the National
Collegiate Athletic Association career rushing record set last year
by Ricky Williams of Texas. Dayne needs to average better than 155
yards a game to break the record.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolverines, who have averaged a dismal 125.7 yards a game
rushing, went to the air immediately behind Brady on the opening
drive. The 6-foot-5-inch senior, who continues to battle the backup
Drew Henson for Michigan's quarterbacking job, precisely marched
the Wolverines 90 yards on a 13-play drive that drained nearly six
minutes from the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Brady was 7 of 8 passing for 67 yards on the drive and, most
impressively, was 4 for 4 on third-down plays. His offensive line,
perhaps the best in the Big Ten, kept the Badgers' defense clear of
Brady, who stood back with ample time and picked Wisconsin's
secondary apart.
</P>
<P>
   On third down and 3 on the Badgers' 8-yard line, Brady had a
full seven seconds to survey the field. He shuffled slowly up in
the pocket, then lofted a pass to the back of the end zone, where
fullback Aaron Shea had slipped by himself. The touchdown gave
Michigan a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   When Dayne, who had only six fumbles heading into his senior
season, put the ball on the ground at Wisconsin's 46-yard line,
Brady and the Wolverines wasted little time putting more points on
the board. Dayne, who last week fumbled on his way into the end
zone in a 17-12 loss to Cincinnati, muffed a handoff from
quarterback Scott Kavanagh that Michigan nose tackle Rob Renes
smothered.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, Brady pitched right to Thomas, who handed the
ball to Marcus Knight, who in turn tucked it in the stomach of
David Terrell for a double reverse. Terrell cut inside a wall of
blockers and zigzagged down the field and into the end zone for a
45-yard score and a 14-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne, who was held to 20 yards in the first quarter, rumbled
the Badgers awake in the second quarter. On second-and-10 at the
43, Dayne broke his first big run of the afternoon, 19 yards, to
put the Badgers into Michigan territory for the first time. Then
Kavanagh hit Chris Chambers on a sideline route at the Wolverines'
20. Two plays later, the pair seemed to have hooked up for a
touchdown, but a wide-open Chambers dropped the pass in the end
zone. So the Badgers settled for a 32-yard field goal by Vitaly
Pisetsky.
</P>
<P>
   While the Wolverines stalled with Henson quarterbacking the
second quarter, the Badgers and Dayne seemed to find their big-game
equilibrium. Wisconsin cornerback Jamar Fletcher blocked a 36-yard
field-goal attempt by Jeff Del Verne that his Badgers teammate Mike
Echols recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Dayne, who had 44 of his 68 second-quarter yards on this
drive, the Badgers bashed their way down the field. On third-and-3
from Michigan's 34-yard line, Dayne stumbled through the middle of
the line, shook off a tackle attempt by Tommy Hendricks and rolled
into the end zone. But Pisetsky's extra-point attempt, was blocked
and at halftime Wisconsin trailed, 14-9.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
