<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS SHARE THE WEALTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's tough being a Ranger in Cowboy country, but
the AL West leaders are doing more than getting ready for the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers players raised approximately $55,000 among themselves to
donate to a fund for the victims of last week's shooting at a Fort
Worth church. Both the club and owner Tom Hicks are expected to
match the amount.
</P>
<P>
   Within the organization, the Rangers are working toward becoming
more of a family. Last Monday, Hicks gave manager Johnny Oates and
GM Doug Melvin two-year contract extensions. Both already were
signed through next year, meaning the new deals will take them
through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are on their way to their third division title in
the five years Melvin and Oates have been in charge. But they have
yet to take the team past the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes: It matters little that the Yankees are
preparing to defend their World Series title by winning nine of
their past 10. Owner George Steinbrenner has shuffled his chain of
command, with GM Brian Cashman now reporting to VP of player
development Mark Newman.
</P>
<P>
   Cashman has guided the Yankees to 219 wins in less than two full
seasons. This year they set a franchise-attendance record _ 3.07
million _ which also is tops for any team in New York history.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever is running the Yankees in 2000 will be busy. Decisions
must be made on whether to re-sign David Cone, whether to pick up
the option on Paul O'Neill, whether to trade Andy Pettitte, and how
much to spend on long-term contracts for closer Mariano Rivera and
shortstop Derek Jeter. DH Chili Davis!of! is expected to retire
this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of good seats left: Oakland fans must have sensed the A's
were starting to finally fade after they couldn't gain ground on
Boston in their remarkable wild-card run. In the three-game series
against the Twins that ended Wednesday, the A's drew a grim 22,905.
Total.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland's attendance, while up 173,938 over last year, has been
awful in September for a team in contention. Even though the Red
Sox dropped their third straight Friday night, the A's were still
4{ back with just over a week to go. ``I don't understand it,''
said first baseman Jason Giambi. ``This is the best product in
baseball. We've got a $20 million (payroll) team that wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Going broke?: The Tampa Bay Devil Rays are talking with veterans
Roberto Hernandez, first baseman Fred McGriff and catcher John
Flaherty about deferring parts of their salaries. The reason, the
Rays say, is they need the money to be players in free agency or
trading this winter. Hernandez is owed $6million for each of the
next two years. Flaherty actually can be a free agent after this
season but the Rays are actively trying to lock him up. They
already agreed to a two-year, $12 million extension with McGriff.
The reason for all this, the Rays say, is disappointing attendance
(they'll end up about 1.6 million compared to 2.4 last year). Also,
as part of their expansion agreement, the Devil Rays and
Diamondbacks don't share TV money for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Making a pitch: David Wells, who beat the Red Sox on Tuesday,
isn't buying all the talk about how the Blue Jays will have to dump
pitching to pay for Carlos Delgado and Shawn Green, who can become
free agents after next season. ``You can have all the guys you want
hitting 50 homers but you're not going to win,'' Wells said.
``You've got to have pitching and good defense.'' Wells points to
the Jays' $43 million payroll as a bargain. He also knows rookie
Roy Halladay came out of Sunday's start with a strained right
pectoral muscle. Toronto already has lost Joey Hamilton and Chris
Carpenter for the season. Halladay, a promising 8-7 with a 3.92
ERA, is now 0-3 for 10 starts dating back to his last win, July 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
