<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6077 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WACO-JUDGE26-COX     09-25 1921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-JUDGE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge earns renown for Branch Davidian cases
 &HT;    By Mark England
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ U.S. District Judge Walter S. Smith Jr. of Waco
has a decidedly no-nonsense image. But friends such as 170th State
District Judge Joe Johnson and attorney Noley Bice firmly insist
Smith is ``a good guy'' who can take a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson does add the disclaimer, ``Not that I would try that in
his court.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Marlin doctor, Smith, 58, tried law school at
Baylor University while waiting to get back his tests for medical
school. He forgot all about medicine and graduated in 1966 with a
law degree. A long line of achievements followed: Smith became a
partner in a law firm and received appointment as Waco's 54th State
District judge and, later, as U.S. magistrate. Topping it off, in
1984 the U.S. Senate confirmed Smith as Waco's first federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   But presiding over the Branch Davidian cases will be Smith's
signature.
</P>
<P>
   Smith received national exposure in 1994 during the criminal
trial of 11 Branch Davidians accused of conspiring to murder the
ATF agents who raided their residence outside Waco. A jury cleared
the Davidians, although convicting seven of them of lesser charges.
Smith earned the wrath of some people when he upheld a prosecution
motion to reinstate the weapons charges, adding as much as 30 years
to the sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Predicting his rulings in the upcoming wrongful-death lawsuit by
surviving Davidians may not be as easy as some may think, however.
</P>
<P>
   His history shows that it's best not to make too many snap
judgments about Smith.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Smith was a Republican in McLennan County when it
wasn't cool but also once worked at the Waco Legal Aid Clinic _ at
a time when some conservatives saw such clinics as borderline
subversive.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't surprise me,'' said Bice, for whom Smith once
worked. ``If you sat down and talked to Walter, you'd find out that
he's all for people without means being represented. However, I'm
sure he wasn't a rubber stamp for everything they did.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're wondering what Smith thinks about his time there,
you'll have to ask him. But not if you're with the media.
</P>
<P>
   An Associated Press reporter who recently tried to surmount the
wall of silence around Smith found herself pondering whether she
remembered the way out of the federal courthouse or needed an
escort by security.
</P>
<P>
   People like J.C. Chatmas of Marlin, however, don't mind talking
about Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good, clean-cut kid,'' said Chatmas, who once owned
the Marlin Daily Democrat. ``Played in the band. Never got into
trouble. His grandfather was a doctor. His father, Walter Smith,
was a doctor, too. His mother was a schoolteacher. They were
leaders in Marlin, both civic and socially.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bice gleefully notes, the family also raised pigs _ with
Smith and his brother Jack doing most of the work.
</P>
<P>
   Chatmas confirms it, albeit a tad reluctantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, they raised pigs,'' Chatmas said. ``Although I don't know
if I ought to be telling that about the family of a federal judge.
I do remember they were the first ones around here to have an
air-conditioned pig sty. I used to write a one-liner column. I had
a few gibes in there about that. It was in good fun.''
</P>
<P>
   After Smith came to Waco and received his law degree, he
practiced law for a short time at the law firm of Dunnam &AMP; Dunnam.
Bill Dunnam said he hired Smith for one reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was smart,'' Dunnam said. ``He had a damn fine legal
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunnam said Smith was active politically, eventually becoming
chairman of the McLennan County Republican Party. His activism in
1980 got Smith appointed to replace Carl Anderson as the judge in
Waco's 54th State District Court.
</P>
<P>
   It also led to Smith getting beaten two years later at the polls
by George Allen, Dunnam said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he ought to run on the Democratic ticket,'' Dunnam
said. ``He said that he had told the governor (Bill Clements) that
he'd run on the Republican ticket. He had enough honor to keep his
word, although he knew he couldn't win. At the time, no Republican
had won a county-wide race.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Waco Mayor Bob Sheehy was Smith's campaign manager in
that race _ although a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew him and his family and thought he was a good judge,''
Sheehy said. ``Obviously, there weren't enough Republicans in
McLennan County to get him elected, and he needed help on the other
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith also lost a race for state representative. But his
political ties paid off again with an appointment as a federal
magistrate. After Smith served a year in the job, Sen. John Tower
of Texas nominated him to become Waco's first federal judge. Smith,
who had not yet put a gag order on himself, candidly summed up his
right stuff for the Waco Tribune-Herald: ``You have to be a strong
supporter of the senator making the recommendation; the right party
has to be in the White House; and you have to live in the area
where the judgeship is being created.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunnam remembers being questioned by the FBI on Smith's fitness
to be a judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were concerned whether he had any prejudices,'' Dunnam
said. ``I told them that he was the first lawyer in Waco to file a
lawsuit on behalf of a woman for sexual discrimination. The woman
worked at General Tire. That seemed to satisfy them.''
</P>
<P>
   After his appointment, Smith quickly became known as a stickler
for judicial decorum.
</P>
<P>
   His friend, Robert M. Campbell, former associate justice of the
Texas Supreme Court, poked fun at Smith's air of formality by
addressing him at a roast as, ``Your Excellency.''
</P>
<P>
   Smiles, by and large, are left at the door to Smith's courtroom.
Men must wear a coat; women, dresses or a suit. A slew of blue
coats line the wall outside for the forgetful. Media trying on one,
however, get a shake of the head from security. Smith hasn't
forgotten that coats flew out of the courthouse when a flock of
national media descended on the federal courthouse following the
raid on Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   That long memory sometimes extends to grudges. Smith once
snubbed a public official, a political foe, offering to shake his
hand at a Waco restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith can also be disarmingly cordial, said Gary Coker, the
attorney who in 1988 successfully defended David Koresh and seven
of his followers from the charge that they attempted to kill
Koresh's rival, George Roden.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's unfailingly polite,'' Coker said. ``I had a case before
him the other day. After everyone had left, he shed his robe and
just sat down and talked for awhile. I appreciated that.''
</P>
<P>
   Those coming across Smith's stern countenance, though, may
question friends' description of him as ``a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He and his wife and I and my wife happened to sit together at
the dance celebrating Waco's 150th anniversary,'' Sheehy said. ``We
liked the music enough that we were all dancing when everyone else
had gone home. I'm not talking cheek to cheek. I'm talking about
getting out there and jumping around. He's a real human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Bice said Smith likes to hunt and work with wood. He built an
addition onto his Woodway home, Bice said, joking that he had to
buy up all the redwood in McLennan County to finish it. Now, Smith
and his wife, Brenda, are making stained-glass windows for the
addition.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the kind of guy who if he gets it in his mind he wants to
do something, he'll read a lot about it and then set out to do it
on his own,'' Bice said.
</P>
<P>
   Court personnel said they are always struck by the deference
Smith shows the jurors in his courtroom. The impatience sometimes
evident in his voice when dealing with attorneys vanishes, replaced
by tones of warmth and sincerity as he carefully explains to jurors
their duties and thanks them for their service to the community.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Smith's reverence for jurors, he's not shy about
overturning their decisions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, a jury awarded former Waco Police Sgt. Mike Nicoletti
$1.4 million after he accused former police Chief Larry Scott of
illegally transferring him after a falling out between them. Smith
threw out the award, calling it excessive. Two years later, a trial
was held for damages only. The plaintiffs weren't allowed to
present any witnesses to portray what they considered the
vindictive atmosphere of the police department.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney John Cullar compared it to trying a case ``to some
degree in a vacuum.'' Nicoletti's award was slashed to $35,601.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has also tossed out awards given to employees suing the
Waco Independent School District and the Salado Independent School
District _ earning him a reputation as a pro-government judge.
</P>
<P>
   Bice doesn't think that's a fair judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe he rules based on what side you're on,'' Bice
said. ``I do think he is not as out to allow runaway damages. I
think if you proved $600,000 in medical damages, he would not
hesitate to award that to you. But he's not as sympathetic toward
awarding damages for pain and suffering. He strives to award what
the law considers fair and reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Even attorneys who have clashed with Smith have called him fair
_ although some like Doug Tinker of Corpus Christi qualify their
response.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said before that I don't think he can escape his
rearing,'' said Tinker, who represented Davidian Brad Branch five
years ago. ``He's a very conservative man. He went into the trial
thinking the Branch Davidians tried to kill the ATF agents and
couldn't get away from it. I think from the outcome, he was
obviously disappointed in the jury's verdict.''
</P>
<P>
   Tinker credits Smith for giving the Davidians a fair shake
during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a serious question as to whether we were
entitled to a self-defense instruction as far as the murder
conspiracy charge,'' Tinker said. ``I was convinced he really
didn't have to give that instruction. It was a close question of
law. I think he was trying to be fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Tinker did criticize Smith during the Davidian criminal trial,
however, for not making government attorneys produce evidence that
the plaintiffs were seeking.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mr. (Bill) Johnston or Mr. (Ray) Jahn said, `We don't have
anything like that,' that was the end of it,'' Tinker said.
</P>
<P>
   In light of the FBI admitting after six years that it used
incendiary devices at Mount Carmel, Smith won't be as likely to
take the government's word at the upcoming civil trial, Tinker
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a man who, I think, tries to be fair,'' Tinker said.
``When a man like that finds out he was misled, he can become very
angry. He takes it as a reflection on him.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent letter to John Danforth, who is heading the
investigation into the FBI's actions at Mount Carmel, Smith wrote
that he hopes the civil proceedings in Waco _ which have been
postponed _ will ``help restore the public's confidence in the
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Bice said he would only bet that Smith tries to live up to his
sense of right and wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first time before him, he kicked me right in the teeth,''
Bice said. ``It was a civil rights case. He ruled 100 percent
against me. I thought he was in the wrong then, I think he was in
the wrong today. We don't talk about it, but I know he believes in
his heart he was right. ``And we were allowed to present our case.
My only problem with Walter is that he always has the last word,
and I have to live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 2104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
