<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6078 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     09-25 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: VALENTINE PLACES HIS HEAD ON THE LINE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Managers say a lot of things _ it's part of their
job _ but Bobby Valentine said something Saturday that went totally
against the managers' handbook. He said that if the Mets do not get
into the playoffs, he should be fired, dismissed, sacked, canned.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't get into the playoffs, I shouldn't come back,''
the manager offered, essentially out of nowhere after the Mets
stumbled to a 4-2 loss to the Phillies. ``If we don't get there,
that will be an easy decision for someone.''
</P>
<P>
   This was an astonishing statement for any manager, any time, but
particularly considering the Mets' current swoon _ five straight
losses, now caught in a tie with Cincinnati for the wild-card
position, both with 92-63 records.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we have is seven games,'' Valentine said. ``All we have to
do is play better than one team,'' referring to the Reds, their
only rival. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even a few old crocks in the press, whose memories are
relatively intact, could not recall ever hearing a manager
volunteer that he should not be back if his team lost its edge in
the closing days. Not Charlie Dressen with the 1951 Brooklyn
Dodgers, not Gene Mauch with the 1964 Phillies, not Don Zimmer with
the 1978 Red Sox. And, for that matter, not Bobby Valentine with
the 1998 Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine also made out the lineup cards last year when the Mets
lost five straight at the very end of the season. If they had won
even one of those five games, they would have finished in a tie.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly one year later, his team is giving every impression of
doing exactly the same thing. They got lethargic pitching from
Kenny Rogers, almost no hitting, and a few bad breaks Saturday, to
squander all of their lead over the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Valentine did everything but take out a sword from
his locker and promise it would be used in a week or so if the Mets
do not win. Valentine, who has a year left on his contract, did
give himself one modest out, however. He said he would not fall on
the symbolic sword.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never walked away from anything in my life and I'm not
walking away from this,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, that means he would expect to be fired by the Mets,
either by the general manager, Steve Phillips, or by the owners,
Fred Wilpon and Nelson Doubleday.
</P>
<P>
   He's got a good point. What message would management be sending
to the players if they retained a manager who presided over a
couple of September swoons? What would be going through their heads
next September?
</P>
<P>
   Still, managers just don't predict their own downfall. But then
again, it was Valentine who predicted, after three of his coaches
were given the chop 55 games into this season, that he himself
would be fired after the next 55 games if the Mets did not
straighten themselves out. They did, and he was not. But now he is
heading for the final week of the season, and putting his neck on
the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like a question to be answered,'' Valentine said,
referring to his blurting out that he should be let go if the Mets
fail to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   This morbid prediction caused the general manager to shake his
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Bobby is doing is showing his leadership,'' Phillips said
with what could be construed as a tight smile of chagrin. ``I'm
glad it's nothing I'm ever going to have to consider. We have seven
great days left in a great season.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips was asked if a manager could be theoretically blamed
after two consecutive collapses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Phillips said. ``Has any team ever had
collapses two years in a row?''
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, none come to mind. And certainly, no manager has
the label of having suffered through two straight collapses. But
then again, no manager has left timeless quotes about his deserving
to be fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever heard of a manager saying that,'' said
John Franco, who, as a media-savvy New Yorker, has absorbed the
lore of a baseball century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby wants to win as much as any of us,'' Franco added.
``He's not alone. You win as a team, you lose as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Robin Ventura called the manager's words ``a nice gesture'' but
could not quite get a handle on what the words were supposed to
produce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Effective for what?'' Ventura replied to a question. ``No,
it's us. We have to get hits. The manager can't do it for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine suggested that was not necessarily true. Last fall, a
less capable squad seemed to run out of gas, and Valentine
deflected second-guessing of himself, but Saturday he conceded he
had browbeaten himself because ``I thought I could have done
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, he admitted he should have removed Rogers after the
pitcher walked in a third run, but instead Rogers walked in a
fourth run, too. Asked what other decisions he was questioning,
Valentine shrugged it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm optimistic,'' he said. ``We haven't had a bounce in a
week. We're due for some bounces.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Mets do not get the lucky bounces, there well could be
one more bounce after the season _ the manager's head plopping onto
the floor. That would be nothing new. What would be totally weird
about this beheading is that the manager himself will have called
for it, an absolute first for baseball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
