<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-CFLA26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia edges victory from Central Florida
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ ``We might not be as good as everybody wants us to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Georgia coach Jim Donnan's assessment following
Saturday's game. It seemed an understatement, given the 11th-ranked
Bulldogs' harrowing 24-23 victory over Central Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia was a four-touchdown favorite over the winless Golden
Knights, who had been out-scored 146-50 in their three previous
games. But the Bulldogs needed a missed extra point and a
controversial offensive interference call to secure the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still 3-0. We can learn from this,'' said Donnan,
knowing how such statements are received by Georgia's fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gonna need an armed guard to get back to the dorm,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Central Florida was in position to attempt a short, game-winning
field goal in the final seconds. But it never got to try the kick.
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Knights had reached the Georgia 20 with 22 seconds
remaining on quarterback Vic Penn's scramble. They could have
kneeled twice and given Javier Beorlegui a 37-yard field goal
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   But coach Mike Kruczek wanted another crack at the end zone.
Penn's pass for Kenny Clark was broken up by cornerback Jeff Harris
in the left front corner of the end zone and Clark was called for
offensive pass interference.
</P>
<P>
   UCF thought the call should have gone the other way. ``I saw
face-guarding. Defensive pass interference, plain and simple,''
Kruczek said. ``And 86,000 thousand people saw the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a good call,'' Donnan said. ``Even if it was
a bad call, I thought it was a good call _ very apropos.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a thinly veiled reference to 102 yards in penalties
against Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   After another penalty and a sack, UCF was backed up to its 45,
too far out for a field goal. Penn's desperation pass on the last
play was intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   Kruczek said he went for the end zone because ``I'm not
overwhelmed with confidence in our field goal kicking.'' Beorlegui
missed the extra point that would have tied the score and had a
27-yarder blocked in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
