r s BC-BBN-NLNOTES-LADN     09-25 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS STEP ON SOME TOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Arizona Diamondbacks might have won the NL
West on Friday night by winning in San Francisco, but the team
still is angry the Giants are saying the D'Backs are headed to the
American League.
</P>
<P>
   Although realignment is not scheduled for several years,
baseball is planning a massive shifting of franchises to promote a
more balanced schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a good chance of that happening for 2001,''
Giants owner Peter McGowen said. ``The (players') union, the AL and
I think the NL supports it. Everybody but Jerry Colangelo supports
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo, Arizona's managing general partner, snapped back at
McGowen, saying ``I didn't realize Peter spoke for the league.''
</P>
<P>
   McGowan said he believed realignment would entail placing the
D'Backs in the AL West, moving Texas to the AL Central and placing
Tampa Bay in a new NL South. The plan is to have four four-team
divisions in the NL and two four-team and one six-team division in
the AL.
</P>
<P>
   As part of their expansion agreement, the D'Backs and Tampa Bay
can be moved at any time in their first five seasons. Sounds like
fun.
</P>
<P>
   Best of the best: Although Kevin Millwood's no-decision Friday
night cost him a chance to win 20, Atlanta's blossoming
right-hander is expected to be the Braves starter Oct. 5 for Game 1
in the division series. In a rotation dominated by Cy Young Award
winners, Millwood has been the club's best pitcher, going 6-0 since
Aug. 8. Millwood, 22, would have become the third-youngest Brave
this century to reach 20 wins, the youngest since Bill James went
26-7 for the 1914 ``Miracle Braves.''
</P>
<P>
   Vindication: With his team just a game behind the Mets for the
wild card, Cincinnati's Greg Vaughn has more on his mind than
revenge. But because Vaughn became history's only player to be
traded after hitting 50 homers, which he did last year to help San
Diego win the National League pennant, he is enjoying the 42 homers
and 111 RBI he has this season just a little more. Though Padres
officials said that they doubted they could re-sign Vaughn, who's
eligible for free agency after this season, Vaughn admitted feeling
slighted when the two teams played earlier in the week. With 13
homers in September, Vaughn is one short of tying the Reds'
one-month record established by Hall of Famer Frank Robinson in
August, 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to deal: Although he won't be as hard to move this winter
as the Dodgers' Carlos Perez will ($12 million left through 2001),
Colorado right-hander Darryl Kile will bring some baggage to the
trade market. Kile, who signed a three-year, $24 million contract
as the top free-agent pitcher two seasons ago, has $8 million left
and plenty of lousy numbers. Kile, who flourished with the Houston
Astros, has been shut down for the year with a sore shoulder after
allowing 18 runs in 16 innings in three winless starts. Kile
finished the season 8-13 with a 6.61 ERA, and an amazingly bad 109
walks and 225 hits allowed in 190.2 innings. Throw in six hit
batters, and that's 340 baserunners in 190.2 innings, 1.78
baserunners per inning. In two years with the Rockies, Kile is
21-30 with a 5.84 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Swan song?: Cubs veteran third baseman Gary Gaetti decided at
the last moment not to have surgery to repair torn cartilage in his
left knee, which had been scheduled for Wednesday. He had played in
2,498 games through Tuesday and wants to become the 40th player to
play 2,500 games. But that doesn't mean he's retiring. Gaetti
hasn't ruled out playing next year, especially if Tom Kelly will
take him back for a sentimental journey in Minnesota, where the two
helped win a World Series in 1987. Should Gaetti not play again
after this year, it would be the end of an era. He is the only
player who hits wearing a helmet without an earflap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
