<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6089 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT     09-25 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-STRUNG METS READY TO SNAP  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Bobby Valentine's face was riven with tension
after the Mets lost by 4-2 to the Phillies Saturday _ their fifth
loss in a row _ and dropped into a tie with Cincinnati for the
National League wild-card berth. Valentine has been drawn tight as
a piano string in the last few weeks, but now the manager seized
the anxiety and twisted it into something surreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't go to the playoffs,'' he said, ``I shouldn't come
back next year.''
</P>
<P>
   If you just returned from, say, a trip to a normal baseball
city, Valentine's statement brings you up to date on the state of
the Mets. They are reeling. They are tense. They are in big
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine's proclamation came on the heels of another
devastating Mets loss in which their once high-powered offense eked
out only four hits, one of them John Olerud's two-run homer in the
eighth. And a four-game lead for the wild-card spot has disappeared
in five days.
</P>
<P>
   As for Valentine, he has squeezed two provisional dismissals
into one season. The first came in June after three of his coaches
were fired and immediately before his team engineered the
remarkable turnaround that has brought them so close to the
post-season. But that time, Valentine had given himself a much
longer deadline _ the same amount of time his coaches had, 55
games. Now, with just seven games remaining, three against the
dreaded Braves, Valentine threw his arms around the blame and
clutched it.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he suspected that General Manager Steve Phillips and his
players would quickly dismiss his mea culpa. But whether his
sentiments were deeply felt or the latest motivational tactic, two
facts remain: a collapse now would cast a long shadow on last
season's fade-out in the final week, and the Mets are doing
everything in the unwritten baseball book to stop their runaway
tumble toward a second disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ''I try not to worry about the guys,'' Valentine said. ``I try
to support them. They're searching for something and I haven't been
able to give it to them. I believe deep down in my bones that we're
going to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   About 10 minutes before the Mets were due to begin stretching
before the game Saturday, a few veterans had the clubhouse
attendants dismiss the visitors and lock the doors. No manager, no
coaches, no reporters. Just a few minutes of frank talk about
attitude and desire and the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   The players-only meeting came two days after Valentine summoned
them together for a meeting after the Braves' three-game sweep
earlier this past week. This meeting seemed to have the same effect
as Valentine's _ none.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the players feel a little cuddlier about each other and
they won't strain so hard to project levity, but their play belies
them. With each day, no amount of group therapy seems to help. Of
course, they're scared.
</P>
<P>
   They have lost what seemed like a sturdy grip on the wild-card
slot.
</P>
<P>
   When the Braves' series started last Tuesday, the Mets were just
one behind in the division and up by four games on the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Mets were not in the top wild-card spot _ or
when they didn't briefly hold the division lead _ was July 21, when
they trailed the Reds by three percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Ventura has been instrumental in setting the tone for this
team all season. It is he who adopted the phrase from a song by The
Doors _ ``the mojo's rising'' _ to describe what had been the
ascending season. ``L.A. Woman'' hasn't been heard in the clubhouse
for the last few games _ it's saved for victories _ and Ventura was
asked what's become of the mojo.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's stunted,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   It's stopped, along with every other aspect of the Mets' game.
Even Valentine conceded that his players are tight, but if the
failure to overcome the Braves proved embarrassing for them, the
results in this series should be appalling.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies are terrible _ they had won just four games this
month until the Mets arrived _ and the Mets are making them look
like the cloning of Chipper Jones and company.
</P>
<P>
   ''You find yourself spinning your wheels,'' said Mike Piazza,
who was 0 for 3 Saturday. ``It's obvious we're at that stage now.
If we're able to get one big hit or one break to get out of the
rut, we can go back to playing the way we know we can. But we're
stuck in neutral.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Kenny Rogers has been in reverse since he tweaked his
hamstring in his last start. Since then, he has a 12.26 earned run
average in the two starts.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Rogers _ who said his hamstring was not a problem _
simply could not find the strike zone. He gave up back to back home
runs to Mike Lieberthal and Rico Brogna in the second inning and in
the third, with two out, walked in two runs.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine had held off calling on rookie Octavio Dotel, not
wanting to insert him after the third run was in and with the bases
still loaded. Afterward, he admitted he may have waited too long
because Dotel and three other relievers held the Phillies off for
the rest of the day.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the most high-powered lineups in baseball _ seven of
their regulars have been over .300 for most of the season _ has
produced just 10 runs in their last five games. Saturday, the Mets,
one day after scoring just two runs on nine hits, were held to just
four hits, and only two runs, both of which came on an
eighth-inning Olerud home run. The winning pitcher was Robert
Person, who had never won nine games the majors before.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had plenty of chances, the best in the eighth, after
the home run. With Piazza and Ventura on, Darryl Hamilton tried a
bunt to move the runners over, only to hit into a force play that
got Piazza at third.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch hitter Benny Agbayani then hit a hard liner toward second
base that seemed headed for right field. Ventura took off for
third.
</P>
<P>
   But Dave Doster leaped high and grabbed the shot for one out,
then flipped to shortstop Desi Relaford to finish the inning-ending
double play. It has been that kind of week.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's rip it all up and start from here,'' Valentine said of
the deadlock in the wild card. ``All we have to do is play better
than one team.''
</P>
<P>
   After the sixth inning, in which the Mets left the bases loaded,
the Veterans Stadium loudspeakers blared a song by Bruce
Springsteen: ``I'm Going Down.''
</P>
<P>
   Not, it seems, as fast as the Mets' fortunes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 2119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
