<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-TV-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC   CAPTURES THE IMPROBABLE, DISAPPOINTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Money time came on the 17th. Ben Crenshaw had
a hunch and he played Justin Leonard instead of Jeff Maggert in the
four-ball matches. Johnny Miller, NBC's lead Ryder Cup analyst,
didn't like the decision but it didn't matter. It wasn't his to
make.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard's putt would have put his team 1 up with one hole to go.
NBC showed a closeup of Leonard, but he didn't make the shot and
Miller was incredulous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it was short,'' Miller snapped. ``It's time to
get a shovel, dig a hole and get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller later softened his ire by saying Leonard faced immense
pressure. But that, too, didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, the United States faced the same deficit
it started with, but it wasn't for a lack of trying and there was
no one better than NBC to capture the moments. And there were
plenty of them Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Jesper Parnevik's improbable fourth shot on the 12th. Tiger
Woods's crazy second shot on the 11th, between the trees, around
the water, to the green about 200 yards away. Hal Sutton's tee shot
on the 17th and chip shot on the 18th. All of the near-miss putts.
Sergio Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours after Ryder Cup play started, NBC's Dick Enberg had
already struck a pessimistic tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``No side has ever rallied from such a deficit,'' Enberg said.
``The Americans will have to make history.''
</P>
<P>
   They didn't. It didn't look good in the morning. At the time
Europe was up in two matches, even in a third and had whittled down
Tiger Woods and Steve Pate's lead to 1 up. Even after Sutton and
Jeff Maggert beat Colin Montgomerie and Paul Lawrie to win only the
second match for the Americans, Enberg remained realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The celebration is more out of desperation,'' Enberg said.
``The other matches don't look so good.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for the morning foursomes.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the story of the day was the score. But televison
viewers had the benefit of instanateous updates, unobstructed views
and commentary on match play's ``ebb and flow.''
</P>
<P>
   Enberg was good telling viewers of the back-and-forth scoring,
or as he called it, ``the shifting of the flags.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the afternoon, the Americans led in all four four-ball
matches. ``Lots of red, white, and blue on the scoreboard,'' Enberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   Before you knew it, the Europeans were all square in two
matches, with the Americans leading 1 up in the other two.
</P>
<P>
   The score had almost reversed within 30 minutes. Miguel Angel
Jimenez scored birdies on the 4th, 5th, and 6th, highlighting the
European surge in front in three of the matches. Only Phil
Mickelson and Tom Lehman had a lead, and they eventually gave the
Americans their fifth point.
</P>
<P>
   NBC caught the rapid-fire action by combining live shots, a
sparing use of split-screens and briefly delayed tape. (Gotta run
those PGA.com commercials.) In one five-minute run, for instance,
NBC had a good shot of Mickeleson hitting a putt and high-fiving
spectators. The next shot was of Parnevik nailing a putt on the
sixth, prompting Miller to say, ``That's not what the US needed for
him to get confidence back in his putter.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller was at his candid best throughout the day. When he
learned that US captain Crenshaw had selected Leonard to play
during the afternoon instead of Maggert, Miller was openly
displeased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leonard doesn't have anything going for him,'' Miller said.
``It must have been something where Maggert needed to be fresh for
the singles and didn't want to play in the afternoon. My hunch is
that Leonard needs to go home and watch it on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller was hard on David Duval as well. ``Maybe it was a good
idea to sit him down for the morning,'' Miller said. ``Give him
some time to work on his game.'' Colin Montgomerie didn't escape:
``He is the best player in Europe. . . but a head case in the US,''
Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no shoratge of analysis and interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Maltbie said that the Americans are playing as if they
have something to lose. ``It's the Europeans that have the Ryder
Cup,'' Maltbie said. ``But the Americans are playing tentative,
their putts are not being hit firmly enough, thus causing them to
constantly come up short.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC's Gary Koch was more direct. ``The Americans needed more
clutch putts.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the interviews were insightful. Enberg and Miller had a
good one with Lanny Wadkins, the former Ryder Cup player and coach.
Next to Arnold Palmer, Wadkins has the most Ryder Cup appearances
of any American.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the problem is that the Americans tend to take the
Europeans lightly because they don't know the accomplishments of
the Europeans,'' Wadkins said.
</P>
<P>
   In another good interview, former European team captain Bernard
Gallagher explained that he thought it was a good idea in the
pairings to ``keep playing the winners.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher further said that ``poor play'' caused numerous
changes in the American pairings.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Gray talked with Mario Lemieux, the owner of the Pittsburgh
Penguins and a scratch golfer, who related the Americans'
predicament at the begining of Saturday. When a team is behind and
starts pressing hard, Lemuieux said, it tends to make bad decisions
and mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably the same thing in golf,'' Lemieux said. ``You
try to force things, you tend to take more risks and make bad
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
