<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-REFORMPARTY-SPLIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPLIT OVER BUCHANAN SPLINTERS REFORM PARTY CONVENTION  
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn._ The national chairman-elect of the Reform Party
briefly walked out of the party's Connecticut state convention
Saturday after organizers refused to admit a wing of the party
worried about the rising influence of Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of just such a debacle had caused Reform Party leaders in
New Hampshire to postpone a state convention scheduled for
Saturday, after they learned that Buchanan's forces planned to
deploy enough people to determine the outcome of elections for six
statewide offices.
</P>
<P>
   The internal squabbling long preceded Buchanan's statements that
he might abandon his bid for the Republican presidential nomination
to seek the Reform Party nomination. But the passion for and
against Buchanan has drawn starker and deeper lines in a young
party that is struggling to become a fixture in national politics.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman-elect, John Gargan, has become a big star in the
party since Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota endorsed his candidacy.
But Gargan never got to the head table of Saturday's banquet, held
in the Art Deco splendor of the Polish National Home. After
organizers refused to let a group of dissidents listen to his
speech unless they paid $25 to eat, Gargan left and said he was
going to ``go get a hot dog.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a matter of principle, I can't talk to half the group,''
said Gargan, who had traveled from his Cedar Key, Fla., home for
the occasion. ``This party is open to everybody, whether they have
a dollar or nothing or a thousand dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Gargan said he had come ``as a peacemaker.'' Explaining the
difficulty of his task, he began describing four major factions in
the national party, as if he were explaining the Middle East.
``We're learning a lot of things the hard way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Connecticut party's controlling wing dined on
sauerkraut and kielbasa in the ballroom, Gargan went downstairs to
eat with the rejects, who had come up from Fairfield County. Their
leader, Kenneth Jones, of Monroe, said he believed that his group
was being excluded because it had questioned whether Buchanan's
brigade would dilute the party's values.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any objection to Pat what's-his-name _
Buchanan,'' said Jones, 60, the owner of a fish-and-chips shop.
``But don't stack the deck.''
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut party chairman, Robert Davidson, defended his
handling of the matter. Standing beneath a sign that said,
``Admission by Ticket Only!'' with his national chairman-elect in
exile downstairs, Davidson said he was just concerned about
``people trying to promote their own agenda instead of the Reform
agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson said he was worried about paying for the hall, although
he had already sold more than the 65 tickets required to break
even. ``There was nothing done in a closet,'' he said. ``Everyone
knew the requirements.'' Davidson then offered to postpone Gargan's
speech until after the banquet, so the dissidents could be
included. Gargan accepted and spoke three hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing the party wrangling to the Cold War, Gargan called in
his speech for detente. ``Let's not kid ourselves,'' he said. ``We
have a severe problem in Connecticut.''
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrating the division, the parliamentary rules for the
convention were approved by a 50-to-46 vote. During one debate, two
members got into a hissing match, telling each other to shut up.
</P>
<P>
   At the back of the room, books by Ross Perot, the party's
founder, were being sold for 50 cents. Onstage, a banner said,
``Ross Was Right,'' and the past tense was pointed.
</P>
<P>
   The party offered delegates the chance to pose with a life-size
cardboard cutout of Perot for $4, but there were few takers.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was all about Buchanan. One of his longtime supporters,
Peter Sullivan, 60, of Fairfield, was attending his first Reform
Party event. He kept a red-and-white Buchanan cap in his pocket,
until he realized this was friendly turf and he could display it
freely.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Leka, 70, of Bridgeport, said Buchanan could help turn a
fledgling party into a major one. ``He'll give us legitimacy,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bowman, a retired Air Force lieutenant colonel from
Melbourne Beach, Fla., who is also seeking the party's presidential
nomination, said of Buchanan: ``He has a big name and big money.
That's just enough for a spectacular failed candidacy.''
</P>
<P>
   The keynote speaker was Pat Choate, who was Perot's running mate
in 1996 and Buchanan's main conduit to the party. Choate did not
mention his man's name, but provided a rationale for the party to
embrace Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are issues that we're not going to agree with each other
on,'' Choate said. ``But the real overarching thing that all of us
have got to focus on is real political reform.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
