<HEADLINE>
NICHOLAS SHOUMATOFF, 81, NATURE ENTHUSIAST AND MOUNTAIN CLIMBER  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC PACE   
 c.1995 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nicholas Shoumatoff, a nature enthusiast and mountain
climber who won praise for a book on Central Asia, died on Sept. 13
at Northern Westchester Hospital Center in Mount Kisco, N.Y. He was
81 and lived in Bedford, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications from a stomach tumor, his family
said.
</P>
<P>
   A butterfly subspecies, Shoumatoff's hairstreak, was named after
Shoumatoff, who served as president of the New York Entomological
Society.
</P>
<P>
   Shoumatoff, whose Russian family name is pronounced SHOO-ma-toff
in the United States, was a native New Yorker. When he was a
teen-ager, he went on entomological expeditions to Jamaica, N.Y.,
with his uncle, Andre Avinoff, director of the Carnegie Museum of
Natural History in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Shoumatoff received a bachelor's degree in 1939 in mechanical
and electrical engineering from the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology. After Navy service in World War II, he worked for years
in the pulp and paper industry and oversaw the building of mills in
more than a dozen countries.
</P>
<P>
   He also climbed mountains in Central Asia and elsewhere. He and
his wife, the former Nina Adamovitch, edited ``Around the Roof of
the World'' (1995, University of Michigan Press), an anthology of
writings about Central Asia by Russian scientists and climbers.
Publishers Weekly said in praise that ``armchair travelers'' could
``enjoy an exotic ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Another book, ``The Alps: Europe's Mountain Heart,'' which
Shoumatoff wrote, is tentatively scheduled to come out in May.
</P>
<P>
   He married his wife in in 1941. She died in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by two sons, Nicholas Avinoff Shoumatoff, of
Bedford, and Alexander, of Keene Valley, N.Y.; a daughter, Antonia
Shoumatoff-Foster, of Wassaic, N.Y.; and seven grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
