<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-HATTEBERG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HATTEBERG CATCHING UP ON THINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scott Hatteberg is trying to make up for lost time after elbow
surgery cost him most of this season.
</P>
<P>
   After catching Saturday's 4-1 Red Sox win over the Orioles,
Hatteberg was taking extra hitting and lifting weights. When he
appeared before the media, he was sweating and a bit out of breath,
but he had a look of satisfaction. The road back was long, but
finally some rewards are being reaped.
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg not only hit a solo homer, his first of the season off
Doug Linton to give the Sox a 1-0 lead in the third, he also threw
out fellow catcher Mike Figga in the third. Figga had singled to
right off Ramon Martinez and tried for second on a botched
hit-and-run with Mike Bordick at the plate. Hatteberg's throw gave
Martinez a three-batter inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that my arm is feeling stronger and stronger,'' said
Hatteberg. ``The last thing that comes is touch and finesse and
full feeling. It's getting closer to normal every day, when
everything just happens and the body goes back to what it's used to
doing. My arm feels great. It's just a matter of repetition.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg had thrown out 3 of 23 runners before nabbing Figga,
but considering the reconstructive surgery on his elbow in May,
what he did in late September was fairly significant.
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg hasn't missed a beat at the plate. He's hit safely in
nine of his last 10 games, at a .378 clip, since returning from the
60-day disabled list Aug. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel DHing for a few days and helping me see some live
pitching on a regular basis helped my swing and my timing,'' he
said. ``It's not quite as easy as riding a bike, but it feels
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his homer, Hatteberg said he got a good changeup to hit on a
1-and-1 count, and ``I got it up in the air and hit it pretty
well.'' Hatteberg hit it into the Red Sox bullpen, 415 feet away.
In the eighth, he drove in the fourth Boston run with a single to
right on a well-hit ball that took a ``Friendly Fenway'' hop and
darted past the infield.
</P>
<P>
   But his biggest job of the day was catching Martinez, whom he
caught during one of the pitcher's rehabilitation assignments in
the minors as well as a late-August simulated game at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish everybody could have seen him from where I saw him and
from where he began,'' said Hatteberg. ``He's come so far. Today
was another step along the way. That's a good lineup and he never
gave in.
</P>
<P>
   ``His velocity was better than it's been. He was outstanding.
His fastball was good, at times great. When he needed it, he hopped
it up a few miles an hour, and when you can do that you know his
arm is feeling good again.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg didn't have to signal for many pitches other than
fastballs. Martinez mixed only a few changeups and even fewer
curveballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was mixing it up some, but he threw a lot of fastballs
because his location was so good we didn't have to throw a lot of
changeups or breaking pitches,'' said Hatteberg. ``It's a big bonus
if he keeps throwing it like he did. If he can do this in the
playoffs, he can help us a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did today was he was able to throw a big pitch to
avoid a big inning. The guy has confidence in himself. He can draw
from his past experience in those situations. It was fun to catch
him.''
</P>
<P>
   It was fun for the Red Sox to watch Hatteberg hit, catch, and
throw the way he did in the past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
