<HEADER>
A6097 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-KICKERS-     09-25 2910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-KICKERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATS TAKE AIR OUT OF KICKERS' ARGUMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After two weekends of play, you were supposed to understand why
former Jets kicker Nick Lowery, a normally mild-mannered Dartmouth
graduate, threatened to slap a Patriot ballboy silly a couple of
years back for refusing to hand Lowery ``the other'' football
before an important kick.
</P>
<P>
   The ``other'' football, of course, was the loaded one. It was
the one that had been heated in a dryer or stashed next to a
hot-air blower on the sidelines or slammed and cuffed against a
concrete wall for 30 minutes or kneaded like a cramped muscle or
microwaved a few times. Or all of the above.
</P>
<P>
   It was the one that kickers all over the NFL kicked, especially
when they were playing at home. It was the hot ball or, more
correctly, the long ball. What it wasn't, according to the league's
guardian of the game, George Young, was the ball everyone else was
playing with.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we're asking is that the kickers kick with a regulation
NFL football,'' said the former Giants general manager and present
NFL senior vice president of football operations, explaining this
year's rule change. ``When they complain like they have been, what
are they saying? That they've been cheating all along?''
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, yes, but don't tell anybody. As more and more kickoffs
sailed into _ and in some cases through _ the end zone, fewer and
fewer were being returned. Same with punts, which more and more
were sailing higher and deeper and taking away one of the game's
most exciting plays.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the line of scrimmage for kickoffs was moved back to
the 30-yard line and the kicking tee was reduced in height, but
when that didn't make much of a dent in the problem, the league's
Competition Committee began looking into what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   When they did, they heard complaints about footballs being
pumped up until they nearly exploded, then deflated and re-pumped.
They heard stories about footballs being put inside a convection
oven and microwaved to soften the leather. They heard about
footballs bouncing around inside a dryer on game day, heating up so
they would expand, and then being deflated and softened.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time this was not considered a major problem. But
things got out of hand. Often the search for a loophole ends up
with a noose, and the place mentioned most often as the hangman's
corner was Minnesota, where punter/kickoff specialist Mitch Berger
had allegedly become the Dr. Frankenstein of kicking science.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kicking a new ball hurts your foot,'' said Patriots punter Lee
Johnson. ``It just doesn't go as far. Kickers would do anything to
try and soften the ball. I've heard of guys beating on them with
weights before a game or microwaving them, but in Minnesota it got
ridiculous. Look at Mitch's touchback ratio.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Berger blasted 40 kickoffs for touchbacks, an
average of 2 1/2 per game. That was an NFL record for touchbacks
since the kickoff was moved back to the 30, breaking John Hall's
mark by 11.
</P>
<P>
   This year, with the pristine ball, Berger has only four
touchbacks in two games, which would give him 32 for the year. That
comes despite his protests of innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic theory is they don't want us to do our jobs as well
as we do them,'' groused Berger's teammate, field goal kicker Gary
Anderson. ``A quarterback is going to throw one ball but as soon as
it comes time to punt or kick a field goal, they're going to whip a
different ball out there so we can't kick it as well. It's like
telling a tennis player with a really good serve, `We're going to
give you a soft ball so you can't serve as hard.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who was perfect as a field goal kicker last season
until he missed a key attempt in the NFC championship game, makes a
spirited defense of doctored footballs, but the reality is actually
the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the 36 game balls would arrive at the stadium on
Friday, and the quarterbacks and kickers would be free to work with
them for two days to get the sheen off and make them less slippery.
</P>
<P>
   But the doctoring _ or softening _ of the balls by some kickers
got so ridiculous, according to several old NFL hands, that
quarterbacks complained that they ended up with a ball that was
fatter than a pumpkin and softer than a bad tomato. In the NFL,
when the quarterback complains, people listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the quarterbacks to be comfortable with the balls we
use in a game,'' said Young. ``And we want everyone to be on a
level playing field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an anti-kicker rule. You have to have the same
rules for all. They don't like to hear it but the fact is some of
them were cheating and now it's coming out.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus began the purge of the ``other'' ball. Now the game balls
remain fresh and unopened until the officials get them on Sunday.
They work off the waxy film, mark the balls with a ``K,'' and keep
them under lock and key until game time.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of the new balls was supposed to be devastating, if
you believed the kickers. Some speculated that kickoffs would be
down 10-15 yards and teams would be starting drives regularly at
their 35-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   That was fine with most offensive coordinators, but it wasn't
appealing to the kickers' sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This rule will definitely detract from touchbacks,'' said
Baltimore kicker Matt Stover over the summer. ``The brand-new ball
goes a shorter distance, hands down. You don't get as much
compression on the ball or as much control.''
</P>
<P>
   In the exhibition season, statistics about length of kickoffs
and punts and return yardage were meaningless because teams were
using so many different kickers and special teams players. But now
the real kickers are kicking, and the kickers' fears have not been
realized. At least not unless your name is Mitch Berger.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the average NFL kickoff return was 22.3 yards. The
average punt return was 10 yards. The average punt was 43.2 yards
gross. This season, the average kickoff return is 21.8 yards. The
average punt return is 8.1 yards. The average punt is sailing 42.4
yards gross.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, returns are down. But what of kickoff distance?
According to the Elias Sports Bureau in New York, there has been
only a minimal change in where teams start their first drive, and
actually an increase in touchbacks (although not in Minnesota).
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the average drive after a kickoff began at the
26.3-yard line. This year, it is beginning at the 26.6-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   As for touchbacks, 16.3 percent of kickoffs resulted in
touchbacks last year. This year, that is up slightly to 17.2
percent. The only caveat, according to Elias, is that two games is
not a significant sampling, and kicking is always better in
September and October than November and December, when the air is
colder and the conditions often wetter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is what Young felt would happen all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did this to level the playing field, not to lengthen
returns,'' Young said. ``You don't want one or two teams having a
significant advantage over everyone else because of the balls, and
in the opinion of some of the players, they were rigging the balls.
They don't have a right to doctor the balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not mad at the kickers. People try to get an edge. We
try to bring it back when one side gets too much of an edge. I felt
all along it would work itself out. Under this rule the kickers who
kick well will do fine. The bad ones will struggle. They kept
saying there wouldn't be any more 50-yard field goals too. Who are
they kidding?''
</P>
<P>
   Just for the record, there have already been eight field goals
of 50 yards or longer. All were kicked with a pristine,
NFL-sanctioned, microwave-free football. But that doesn't mean
kickers didn't find something to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   Around the league, they're all whispering that the number of
missed field goals is up because of the slick new balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait until the weather gets bad,'' Green Bay kicker Ryan
Longwell said.
</P>
<P>
   What Longwell didn't know was that field goal accuracy also was
up slightly over last season.
</P>
<P>
   George Young was not surprised to hear that.
</P>
<P>
   Two feet are better than one
</P>
<P>
   The importance of field position after the kickoff couldn't be
clearer than it is in Jacksonville, where head coach Tom Coughlin
continues to employ two placekickers, Mike Hollis for field goals
and Steve Lindsey for kickoffs. In the exhibition season, Lindsey
put 11 of his 18 kickoffs into the end zone. In the seasons's first
two weeks, he put 8 of 15 there, with five ending up as touchbacks
. . . It appears that ex-Colts quarterback Art Schlichter has the
gambling bug about as bad as can be. Only a week after being
released early from an Indiana prison, where he had served nearly
two years on theft, forgery, and fraud charges in connection with
an $800,000 gambling debt, he was charged with using a prison pay
phone to bet on football and hockey games with a Las Vegas
bookmaker last November. Schlichter, who denies the charges, goes
on trial Nov. 17. While in prison, Schlichter, the former Ohio
State All-American, earned two degrees from Indiana University and
reportedly was working to turn his life around. He was suspended by
the NFL in 1983 after admitting he had been threatened by
bookmakers over a $150,000 gambling debt . . . San Diego's decision
not to put quarterback Ryan Leaf on injured reserve was not simply
a cave-in to the petulant Leaf, who threatened to demand a trade if
he was not on the active roster despite his shoulder injury. Fact
is, the Chargers expect him to begin soft-tossing next week and
full throwing under close supervision in about two weeks. He could
be activated by Nov. 7, the season's halfway point, although coach
Mike Riley has given him no assurances he will be on the field. To
keep Leaf involved, Riley has Leaf giving the signals from the
sidelines to the quarterback after he gets the play called from the
press box . . . According to Broncos publicists, former Denver
quarterback John Elway directed 18 fourth-quarter comebacks in his
first seven NFL seasons. Drew Bledsoe has directed 14, with 14
games to go in his seventh season . . . When Cleveland head coach
Chris Palmer was told about the rise of young Michael Bishop in New
England and the call of some fans and media members to get him into
the lineup, the ex-Patriot quarterback coach was incredulous.
``What? Drew hasn't won enough games for them?'' Palmer said . . .
Two conflicting streaks will be on the line Sunday when the
Chargers play the Colts. San Diego has not allowed a 100-yard
rusher since Nov. 30, 1997, a stretch of 20 games dating back to
the afternoon Terrell Davis rushed for 178 yards. Conversely,
Indianapolis running back Edgerrin James will try to become the
first man in NFL history to rush for more than 100 yards in each of
his first three games . . . Meanwhile, a limping and sore Ricky
Williams is getting little sympathy from Saints coach Mike Ditka.
Williams is playing with a bad ankle and now a hyperextended elbow,
but when Ditka was asked about Williams's health, he said, ``I
dislocated a shoulder and I played the next week. And it got
dislocated the next week and I played the next week with it and it
got dislocated again. Then I played the next week and it got
dislocated again. Then I got tired of it dislocating, so I put a
brace on it and I played the rest of the season and caught the
highest amount of passes I've ever ever caught in football. But
then, I'm Iron Mike.'' You gotta love that guy . . . The Buccaneers
have allowed a 100-yard rusher only 12 times since Tony Dungy
became head coach in 1996. They're 1-11 in those games, so when
Dungy says they have to stop the run, he's not kidding . . .
Speaking of the Bucs' defense, it is the first since 1986 to not
allow an offensive touchdown in the first two games of a season.
The last team to do it? The Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Raves for a Raven
</P>
<P>
   Remember Qadry Ismail? If you don't, that's not surprising. The
younger brother of Rocket Ismail went the last two years without
catching a single pass in the NFL, but just when it seemed he had
disappeared, he has roared back to be one of the few bright spots
for the Ravens. Ismail leads the Ravens after two games with eight
catches for 99 yards and a score. Those are not big numbers, but
when your line the previous two years was 0-0-0, any number is a
big number. ``These last few years were sort of a wilderness
experience,'' said Ismail. To his credit, he also blames his fall
on himself, claiming that while he was the third receiver in
Minnesota, he consistently refused to listen to the advice of Cris
Carter, one of the game's best and hardest-working receivers. Soon
he had gone from Minnesota to Green Bay to Miami to New Orleans to
the waiver wire to a new awakening that may pay off under his
former coach in Minnesota, new Baltimore head man Brian Billick . .
. Although TV ratings are soaring, problems persist around the NFL.
The league can't get anyone interested in paying to put a team in
Los Angeles; only a corporate ticket splurge prevented a blackout
in Jacksonville; the Raiders have not sold out a home game in two
years (19,000 were left by Thursday night for the home opener with
Chicago); and in San Diego, the city has already spent $1.7 million
to buy unsold tickets to two exhibition games and as well as the
home opener under an agreement that guarantees the team sellouts in
its remodeled stadium. Last year, 25 percent of all NFL games were
blacked out locally because of a lack of sellouts. Part of the
problem is the decision to put teams in towns like Jacksonville,
which has a 73,000-seat stadium but the second-smallest market in
the league, a metropolitan population of barely 1 million. Even
owner Wayne Weaver conceded, ``It appears we're going to have some
blackouts.'' And that's for a team that's 2-0 and facing division
rival Tennessee. The odd thing is, the only reason home games began
being televised in the early 1970s was that Washington politicians
couldn't get tickets to Redskins games and also couldn't see them
on TV. So they enacted a law requiring that sold-out home games be
televised, and now fans have grown so used to it that they're
forgetting the tickets have to be sold first . . . The Arizona
Cardinals opened the season in Philadelphia, while the Arizona
Diamondbacks were hosting the Phillies. Last Sunday, the Cardinals
played the Dolphins in Miami while the Diamondbacks hosted the
Florida Marlins. The Cardinals host the 49ers, while the
Diamondbacks are in San Francisco to play the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   49ers may get shifty
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers are contemplating some offensive line shifts after
quarterback Steve Young was hit 21 times last Sunday, including
five times for sacks. Derrick Deese may move from guard to right
tackle and Jeremy Newberry may be headed to the bench. Young has
been sacked nine times in two games . . . If you need another
reason to write off the chances of the Jets this season, consider
this. In his last 66 drives in the NFL, Rick Mirer has led his
teams to one touchdown. He was 1 for 52 with Chicago, didn't play
for Green Bay last year, and is 0 for 14 as a Jet. Anyone with
Scott Zolak's home number, send it to Bill Parcells . . . Ever the
master psychologist, Parcells went ballistic after his team's
lackluster effort in a 17-3 loss to Buffalo last week, but then he
came back and let the Jets practice in shorts and without pads all
week. His thinking? If they lay another egg, they can't complain
that they were overworked . . . Speaking of the Jets,
representatives of team, the Giants, and the MLS MetroStars met
with officials of the New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority
Friday to talk about installing grass in the Meadowlands full time
next year. Having lost Vinny Testaverde and All-Pro receiver Wayne
Chrebet to turf injuries without being touched, the Jets think it's
a little late . . . Once again, a new broom is sweeping clean. This
time it's in Green Bay, where new head coach Ray Rhodes has rid the
roster of 29 players Mike Holmgren left for him. He has 16 rookies
or first-year players . . . Here's two ends of the coaching
paranoia scale. Pete Carroll had workers tape brown shipping paper
over the windows of the media work room at Foxboro Stadium last
week so no one could watch his team's walk-through sessions. Out in
San Diego, Riley allowed a reporter from the San Diego
Union-Tribune to sit in on coaches' meetings (with the exception of
Saturday night) as the Chargers prepared for their season opener
with Cincinnati last week. The reporter was allowed in from the
time the first coach arrived at 6 a.m. until the last left around
9:30 p.m. each night. The Chargers won, 34-7 . . . Holmgren had
himself a rude awakening last Sunday in Chicago. With three of his
daughters living in Chicago and a fourth in Milwaukee, the
Seahawks' head coach looked into renting them a skybox for his
team's game with the Bears. He was told it would cost $5,000 plus
food costs. Although Holmgren makes $4 million a year, he used to
be a school teacher in San Francisco and still remembers the value
of a dollar. He got his daughters seats in the stands instead. The
Bears claim that when Ditka's Saints come to town, he'll have
friends in a box. And he'll pay the same fee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
