<HEADLINE>
ADVANTAGE GOES TO BC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PISCATAWAY, N.J. _ Advantage, Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   Before the season, coach Tom O'Brien vented his displeasure
about what he perceived to be four ``disadvantaged games'' the Big
East schedule-makers had forced upon the Eagles. O'Brien was
particularly upset that BC had to play three of its first five
conference games against opponents who had an extra week off to
prepare for the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday, it was apparent that Rutgers could have had a
month off to prepare and it wouldn't have mattered.
</P>
<P>
   What disadvantage?
</P>
<P>
   In almost every statistical category, BC held a distinct
advantage in its 27-7 victory before a crowd of 27,330 at Rutgers
Stadium. The Eagles improved to 3-0 overall and 1-0 in conference
with a balanced attack that netted 427 yards total offense (243
rushing, 184 passing) and a solid defensive effort that held the
Scarlet Knights (0-3, 0-1) to 307 yards and rang up three
interceptions, including two by by sophomore cornerback Jonathan
Ordway.
</P>
<P>
   For Rutgers, it was just the latest calamity. Last week, the
Scarlet Knights were forced indoors because of Hurricane Floyd and
lost practice time. On Tuesday, coach Terry Shea suspended five
players, including leading rusher Jacki Crooks, for violating team
rules when they missed a practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``All week long we heard that this was a big game for Rutgers
and I challenged the team to make sure we matched their
enthusiasm,'' said O'Brien. ``You have to give Rutgers a lot of
credit because of the hurricane and practice time and getting
organized with all the facilities and everything. Then they suspend
a couple of players and they did a great job and came out and
played extremely hard, but our kids did the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Junior running back Cedric Washington redeemed himself after a
subpar effort in last week's 14-10 victory at Navy by rushing 21
times for 147 yards and a pair of touchdowns (8 and 12 yards).
Meanwhile, junior quarterback Tim Hasselbeck continued to show
improvement, completing 17 of 22 passes for 168 yards, including a
21-yard TD pass to DuJuan Daniels that capped an impressive 74-yard
drive (three plays, 1:01).
</P>
<P>
   After BC expanded a 10-0 halftime lead to 13-0 on John Matich's
second field goal of the game, a 35-yarder, Syracuse junior
quarterback Mike McMahon capped a four-play, 72-yard march with a
56-yard TD pass to Errol Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles went them one better, needing one fewer play and 11
fewer seconds to cover almost the same distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always encouraging when you can answer the bell like
that,'' said Hasselbeck.
</P>
<P>
   And it sounded the death knell for the Scarlet Knights.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to salute them for coming right down the field and
scoring right after we scored,'' said Rutgers running back Dennis
Thomas. ``That right there was the knife in our hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   Showing remarkable poise in the pocket, Hasselbeck hit fullback
Ryan Burch with a 15-yard pass, then connected with wideout Dedrick
Dewalt for a huge 38-yard gain to the 21. Hasselbeck capped the
drive with a scoring toss to Daniels, who lunged into the end zone
to make his second TD catch in as many games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt so much more relaxed going into this game than I
did the Baylor game,'' said Hasselbeck. ``I felt like I had better
rhythm and better command of the offense and it always helps when
you're running the ball well, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Next up for BC: a home game Saturday against Northeastern.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, BC's coaching staff will be concerned about the team
losing focus and suffering a letdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone says this was a big game for the Jersey guys, because
they played against some of these guys in high school,'' Hasselbeck
said. ``But for me, this is my chance to play against guys I played
against in high school and guys I know really well.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're from the area, this is kind of the battle of Boston,
I guess, so I'm not going to need a kick in the butt to get ready
for those guys. I'm as excited to play them as anybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
