<HEADLINE>
FUTURE BRIGHTENS FOR NEMECHEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was, perhaps, the feel-good story of the NASCAR Winston Cup
season.
</P>
<P>
   And Joe Nemechek, outgoing driver of the Felix Sabates-owned No.
42 BellSouth Chevrolet Monte Carlo, was only too happy to put his
signature on it by winning the Dura Lube/Kmart 300 last weekend at
New Hampshire International Speedway. In his 180th start, Nemechek
authored quite a tome in winning the first Winston Cup race of his
career at NHIS, the same 1-mile oval where he recorded his second
Busch Grand National victory in 1992 _ in a stirring last-lap duel
with Dale Earnhardt, no less _ and where he made his Winston Cup
debut the following year.
</P>
<P>
   But it was also a bittersweet moment for the Lakeland, Fla.,
native who will celebrate his 36th birthday Sunday when he competes
in the MBNA Gold 400 at Dover, Del.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Nemechek's younger brother, John, died from
injuries sustained in a crash at a NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series
race at Homestead, Fla. Then, last month, Nemechek lost his ride
with Team Sabco as he and Sabates agreed to part ways at the end of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still looking for a job for the year 2000,'' said
Nemechek, who finished ahead of runner-up Tony Stewart, the runaway
leader for Rookie of the Year honors who the week before recorded
his first career victory at Richmond, Va. ``I don't know what I'm
going to be doing. Hopefully, this will definitely help. I'm
talking to a few people out there. Who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   Some speculated that Nemechek was the leading candidate to land
the No. 28 ride at Robert Yates Racing, but that opportunity
evaporated when Yates hired veteran driver Ricky Rudd to replace
Kenny Irwin. With his victory at NHIS, Nemechek could be among the
candidates for A.J. Foyt's team or that of CART owner Cal Welles,
whose sponsorship deal with Tide led to the demise of Rudd's own
operation, Rudd Performance Motorsports.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if Nemechek were to win Sunday's race at Dover, it
would make him a hotter commodity than Pokemon cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows? Felix may come back and start hammering me,''
Nemechek said jokingly. ``I don't know. It's kind of a unique deal.
(Crew chief) Tony Glover and Felix, they've got a heck of an
organization. We just struggled (posting seven top 10 finishes and
one top five in the previous two seasons). Now to have it all come
together, it's kind of disappointing. Who knows what's going to
happen?
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter where I end I up, I've got to be in a good quality
ride. If I can't make a step up, I don't know what I'm going to do.
I'll just have to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Glover believes Nemechek won't wait long for a ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be a driven force to be able to do this, and I
think the things that have happened in the last month have maybe
woken up a sleeping giant,'' said Glover. ``You're going to see a
lot more of Joe Nemechek the balance of '99, and I can assure you,
you'll see a lot of him in years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Conflicting reports
</P>
<P>
   Ray Evernham tried to dispel rampant rumors about his imminent
departure as Jeff Gordon's crew chief when he told John Kernan of
ESPN's ``RPM 2Night'' that he was not leaving Hendrick Motorsports.
Rumors swirled at NHIS last week that Evernham had called his last
race for Gordon because of perceived friction between Evernham and
John Hendrick, the brother of ailing team owner Rick Hendrick. But
Evernham told ESPN, ``There is no friction at all between me, Rick
Hendrick, and Jeff Gordon. We are giving each other our full and
100 percent support. The team is going to Dover this weekend to try
to win another race for Jeff Gordon and Rick Hendrick.'' Evernham,
however, was not in Gordon's pit during Friday's pole
qualifications at Dover, and CNN-SI reported Friday that Evernham
will soon be replaced by mechanic Brian Whitesell . . . Indy Racing
League driver Greg Ray has it all figured out. He knows his magic
number to clinch his first IRL title heading into Sunday's
Vegas.com 500 at Las Vegas Motor Speedway, the penultimate race of
the season. Ray leads Scott Goodyear by 44 points, 246-202, and
will clinch his first IRL title and the Pep Boys Million bonus if
he has a lead of 56 points after Sunday. ``If I finish 12 points
ahead of Scott, we mathematically win,'' said Ray, who vaulted
ahead of Goodyear Aug. 29 after his victory at Pikes Peak, Colo.,
his third win in four races. ``But you shouldn't count points. You
need to just concentrate and stay focused on the race. If you look
at the last couple of years, mathematically a couple of drivers
could have won the championship but they didn't have very good luck
at the end. So you never know what may happen.'' . . . Willy T.
Ribbs, a two-time veteran of the Indianapolis 500, will make his
IRL debut as driver of a McCormack Motorsports entry. Ribbs will
make history by becoming the first African-American driver to
compete in an IRL race . . . What at first appeared to be the IRL's
gain wound up being its loss when promoters of the Medic Drug Grand
Prix of Cleveland pulled the plug on CART June 29 and opted to go
with IRL. However, when IRL officials announced plans to stage a
race on an oval track at the Burke Lakefront Airport, Cleveland
Mayor Michael R. White withheld his support, citing concerns about
gaining approval from the Federal Aviation Administration for
construction of an oval. Last week, White announced that IMG
Motorsports, the race promoter, had reached a three-year agreement,
thus restoring Cleveland to CART's 2000 schedule. The IRL,
meanwhile, dropped its plans for Cleveland. ``I'm very pleased that
the parties went back to the table and inked this deal,'' White
said. ``This is great news for the city of Cleveland, CART and
racing's most loyal fans.'' . . . CART driver Bryan Herta will try
to give car owner Bobby Rahal his second victory in as many races
in Sunday's Texaco Grand Prix of Houston. Two weeks ago, Herta won
at Laguna Seca Raceway in Monterey, Calif., for the second
consecutive year. He teamed with third-place teammate Max Papis to
give Team Rahal its first ever double-podium finish. Herta's
victory, however, was marred by the death of Penske rookie Gonzalo
Rodriguez, 27, who died of massive head and neck injuries suffered
when his car veered off the course, crossed a gravel pit, slammed
through a tire barrier, and was catapulted into the air before
landing upside-down on a rocky hillside. ``I want to remember
Gonzalo,'' Herta said. ``We did the best thing we could to honor
him. and that was to go out and do the kind of racing he loved.''
In the winner's circle, Herta, runner-up Roberto Moreno, and Papis
opted not to spray champagne in celebration; instead they raised
their bottles in Rodriguez's honor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
