<HEADLINE>
RAMON AND RED SOX RETURN TO FORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has gone well beyond answering whether he can still pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is this: Will Ramon Martinez catapult the Red
Sox into the World Series, in a potential pitching rotation
anchored by Pedro the Younger and elevated further by the presence
of Bret Saberhagen and lefthander Kent Mercker, the only other Sox
players besides Ramon who own World Series rings?
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you feel pretty darn good, as far as your chances in
October,'' pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said after Martinez, backed
by home runs by Scott Hatteberg, Brian Daubach, and Butch Huskey,
won his first big league game in more than 15 months by beating the
Baltimore Orioles, 4-1, Saturday before another Yawkey Way sellout
(No. 36) of 32,107.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all guys who have been through the wars before, too,''
said Kerrigan. ``They're all different pitchers, and all have
different deliveries.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon the Elder, who at the start of the month lasted just three
innings against Kansas City in what looked like a one-and-out
chance to prove himself, was restored to the rotation only because
Pat Rapp had to fly home for the birth of his son Reid Patrick, who
arrived prematurely. Now, it appears that barring a sudden
breakdown in his surgically repaired right shoulder, Martinez has
made himself indispensable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see how it plays out, OK?'' Kerrigan said, cautioning
that the postseason rotation has not been set, even as the Red Sox'
magic number for clinching a wild-card spot was reduced to four,
pending the outcome of the A's game in Texas Saturday night. ``We
still have eight games to go.''
</P>
<P>
   But clearly, Kerrigan was as excited as Martinez, who
emotionally is the polar opposite of his excitable-boy younger
brother but thrust his fist overhead as he came off the mound after
finishing the seventh, his last inning of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of moments that I thought I would not pitch
this year,'' said Martinez, who underwent surgery to repair his
rotator cuff a year ago last June 30 and was deemed expendable by
the Dodgers, the team for whom he had won 123 games in his big
league career.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was something to me, in my mind, that I was going out
there deeper into a game, and that we had a chance to win, and I
did my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who threw 98 pitches, allowed the Orioles only four
hits and did not walk a batter. He was at his best in the fourth
inning, when he faced bully-bat Albert Belle with runners on first
and third and no outs and induced Belle to tap into a
pitcher-to-second-to-first double play. A run scored on the play,
but Martinez caught Derrick May looking at a called strike to end
the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the seventh, after B.J. Surhoff led off with a double
and took third on Belle's liner to right, Martinez induced May to
foul to Hatteberg on the first pitch, then retired Jeff Conine on a
one-hopper to Daubach at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you saw him in those situations,'' Kerrigan said,
``that's his M.O. He's known for making great clutch pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   When Martinez returned to the dugout for the high-fives from his
appreciative teammates, Kerrigan passed along this:
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him it was just like the old Dodger days, when I'd be
sitting in the opposing dugout watching him kick our butts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always had to get him early. If you didn't get him in the
first or second inning, he'd whip off 18 or 20 in a row. If you
didn't get him early, it was lights out.''
</P>
<P>
   For as long as Martinez waited between wins, Hatteberg tarried
between home runs. Giving regular catcher Jason Varitek a rare day
off, Hatteberg homered into the Boston bullpen to give the Sox a
1-0 lead in the third. Hatteberg, who missed more than three months
after elbow surgery, hadn't homered since Sept. 9, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   For Daubach, it only seemed that long. The Belleville Basher had
become the Belleville Blusher during a slump that has lasted more
than five weeks, a span in which he is hitting .125 (10 for 80)
with just three RBIs in 26 games. But he hit a 2-and-0 delivery
from Doug Linton into the screen in left-center, his first since
Aug. 14 and 20th of the season, joining Ted Williams and Fred Lynn
as the only lefthanded-hitting Sox rookies to hit 20 or more home
runs in a season.
</P>
<P>
   That's pretty fair company for a guy who supported himself by
selling sporting goods during a decade-long odyssey through the
minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only got one hit,'' said Daubach, who also drew a walk off
lefthanded reliever Doug Johns in the eighth and scored Boston's
final run on Hatteberg's single. ``That doesn't mean I'm out of my
slump, but it's a a start.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach said it helped that Jimy Williams gave him most of the
last week off, though some would have called his rest a benching.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been very important to this team,'' said Williams, who
was unafraid to pinch hit Daubach (who whiffed) in Friday night's
1-0 loss, then gave him his first start in 10 days. ``In recent
days he hasn't played, in recent times, but I believe in the kid, I
really do.''
</P>
<P>
   Huskey, who launched his 22d home run, seventh with Boston, to
give the Sox a 3-1 lead in the seventh, spoke with the zeal of a
believer when talking about the back-to-back performances by
Saberhagen and Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a confidence-booster,'' Huskey said. ``You
know that any time these guys can pitch a great game for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing for us is to score some runs behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   They scored enough, which made October loom even closer. Game 7
of the World Series is scheduled for Oct. 31. Anyone else wondering
if come Halloween, the Sox will be trick-or-treating in their
uniforms?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
