<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-PLAYOFFS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION FEELING THE BURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ The Revolution's 1-0 loss to Dallas Friday night
gave the impression of a team either unable or unwilling to follow
a game plan. More accurately, this was a group of players
uncomfortable with any philosophy of play except directness.
</P>
<P>
   The result was as predictable as the Revolution's offense.
Dallas simply absorbed pressure, then found a couple of holes in
the defense and exploited them. The pattern was similar to when the
Revolution visited Dallas June 25; they were playing very well, but
the Burn adjusted and won, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Revolution must hope for a Miami loss against Columbus
Sunday, then try to overtake the Fusion in the final two games
(against the MetroStars next Sunday and at D.C. United Oct. 9) for
the final Eastern Conference playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   Such a scenario is possible, since the Revolution have not been
suffering hugely demoralizing defeats, despite a 1-13-1 record in
the second half of the season. But there are signs that players are
losing faith in both themselves and their system of play. More
disturbing, the Revolution's ability to read the game has not
improved in three months. There is no balance between
power/strength and guile, pacing, subtlety.
</P>
<P>
   This realization seemed to greatly upset assistant coach
Giuseppe Galderisi, who has been probably the most credible and
supportive member of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Galderisi, replacing suspended Walter Zenga, seemed most
disturbed by the Revolution's unwillingness to be patient, which
stemmed from an inability to understand the circumstances of the
game. Galderisi thought the Revolution needed to stick to their
plan, to keep the game wide, away from the clogged midfield. They
needed to sometimes pull back, alter the pace, catch Dallas off
guard. But this team has not collectively understood how to do that
in nearly four seasons, and it was not about to apply any past
lessons.
</P>
<P>
   There were some basic soccer tenets at work. If you are facing a
hot goalkeeper, you might never score against him, but if you let
things degenerate into chaos, you will never gain anything. No
matter who the opponent, there are always vulnerabilities.
Sometimes you must probe for them, though, and they might not
become apparent until late in the contest.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution preferred to hammer at Dallas, constantly and
predictably pounding the ball into the penalty area and running
hard to catch up to it. Their frustration became apparent after
Oscar Pareja's 70th-minute goal, and they became even more
predictable, playing into the hands of the Burn.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas goalkeeper Matt Jordan had an excellent game, but the
Revolution could not figure out how to make his life difficult.
They played into Jordan's strength near the goal on corners and
crosses, instead of pulling the ball out and trying to catch him
off his line or with a difficult angle to cover. And once the
Revolution fell behind, they began rushing things even more, which
is acceptable if done without panic. A team can increase its speed
of play, but must retain its composure or risk appearing foolish.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a game we should have won,'' striker Giovanni
Savarese said. ``But it was a great night for the goalkeeper. Once
we got behind, we needed a goal and everybody went crazy trying to
score. But after that goal, they closed the spaces in the field and
made it more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we will get a break from Miami (Sunday) and we will
still have a chance to qualify for the playoffs. There is no
question we have the talent on this team and on the coaching staff.
The question is, when we step on the field, will we do what we are
supposed to do?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
