<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6104 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-MCGINEST     09-25 1446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-MCGINEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A RUSH JOB FOR MCGINEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ He knows they're waiting on him, but Willie
McGinest has been waiting on himself far longer. Waiting for two
years. Waiting for 28 years. Waiting to explode on the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Once that was a young boy's dream, one he shared with his
father, Big Willie, who dreamed it bigger than his son did. Dreamed
it when he would leash his son to the family dogs and take the boy
of 10 out to run the streets after a day of football practice, out
to run for his life.
</P>
<P>
   When Willie McGinest stopped running, the father kept going
knowing what would happen next. The dogs would keep going, too,
chasing the master of the house, dragging a small boy behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father told me I could keep up or get dragged,'' McGinest
said. ``You learn to keep up. He'd never had the chances I had in
sports but he could see my potential and he wanted me to reach
it.''
</P>
<P>
   So the boy kept getting up to run some more, half sprinting,
half being pulled along, until he was finally ahead of the pack.
All-State in football and basketball at Long Beach Polytechnic in
Southern California. All-Pac-10 and Playboy All-America at USC. No.
1 draft choice of the New England Patriots. All-Rookie team.
All-Pro two years later.
</P>
<P>
   Always running.
</P>
<P>
   Until he couldn't move.
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't move right. Couldn't move left. Couldn't move forward.
Couldn't have moved if the dogs had come back to drag him through
the dust.
</P>
<P>
   It's an odd thing, not being able to move when you've been
moving all your life. Odd, but not funny.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrating. But not funny.
</P>
<P>
   Not one bit funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did it hurt me not to play?'' McGinest said when asked to
recall the last two seasons, when a screaming groin muscle caused
him to miss 13 games _ nearly a full season. So many games people
began to wonder whether the dogs had gotten to him this time,
sending him down so often he would never get up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did it hurt me?'' he said again, a quizzical smile on his
face. ``I was wearing it every day on my face, man.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed he was.
</P>
<P>
   Anger. Worry. Frustration. All etched on the face of a young man
who one day was living his father's dream and the next was living
his own nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in that situation, you can't help but put pressure
on yourself,'' said Chris Slade, McGinest's friend and quarterback
sackmate. ``You try not to get caught up in it but he's a very
competitive guy. Of course it hurt to go from the Pro Bowl to not
being able to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurt though it might, that is the direction McGinest's life took
not long after his 9 1/2-sack season in 1996, the season he helped
lead the Patriots to Super Bowl XXXI, the second half of a two-year
blitz in which he registered 20 sacks and made clear he could do
some damage when things were right.
</P>
<P>
   Everything was rosy then, nothing but open road to Hawaii in
February ahead of him. And then, just when he thought he was
running free, his knee, his hamstring, and finally his groin began
to argue with him about life in the NFL. One after another they
conspired against him, dragging him down the way the dogs had all
those years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But as they did, McGinest kept remembering the lesson of the
dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Went down.
</P>
<P>
   Got up.
</P>
<P>
   Went down.
</P>
<P>
   Got up.
</P>
<P>
   Went down for the third time.
</P>
<P>
   Got up, but wasn't the same now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we've been here, he's only played in about half the
games,'' said Patriots defensive coordinator Steve Sidwell. ``In
some of those games he was just a shell of what he is now. He's
always given really good effort but at times he dropped out of
sight due to his injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a prototypical speed pass rusher. He has really rare
quickness and he really plays hard. But how well can you play when
you can't move?''
</P>
<P>
   Not too well and not too often. Not often enough or well enough
to justify to some the five-year, $25 million contract he signed
two years ago, a contract that sometimes had to seem as heavy as
some of the offensive linemen who hang on him whenever he's
fighting his way to the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Finally tiring of this cycle of injury, rehabilitation, and
reinjury, McGinest talked with Shaquille O'Neal after last season
had degenerated into another lost year with a balky groin that kept
him in street clothes for seven of the Patriots' 16 games. The
Lakers' center had come back from similar problems and he gave
McGinest the same advice Horace Greeley gave the country's young
men a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go West, young man,'' O'Neal said, although in this case it
was west-northwest to Vancouver, British Columbia. To an athletic
medicine man named Alex McKechnie.
</P>
<P>
   McKechnie, a physical therapist who specializes in lower-body
injuries, worked with McGinest to strengthen his inner thighs and
his stomach muscles, and when pain persisted, McGinest had team
doctor Bert Zarins perform a ``small procedure,'' as they like to
call surgery in the NFL, to relieve some of the pressure on the
groin muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was back to stretching and abdominal exercises and hope.
Hope that 1999 would be different.
</P>
<P>
   Two games into the year it has been, but two games are just the
start of the race. Although McGinest already has been named AFC
Defensive Player of the Week once (for his two sacks, one pressure,
forced fumble, and fumble recovery for a touchdown against the
Jets), he knows better than most that the dogs have just begun to
run.
</P>
<P>
   He always could keep up with Big Willie at the start. Same way
the past two years with the Patriots. But can he keep running all
season anymore?
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel quick, but it's too early to tell how it will go,''
McGinest said. ``It's only two games. I was on fire the first game
and I played pretty good in the second against a guy (Colts
quarterback Peyton Manning) who isn't going to get sacked ever,
even if you come scot-free. He just won't have it. We'll see how it
goes.''
</P>
<P>
   When McGinest is healthy and getting after the quarterback with
his speed rushes, things go pretty well for the Patriots' defense.
He is, when he's right and running, a disruptive force who can
change a game because he can destroy a quarterback's faith and an
offense's timing.
</P>
<P>
   McGinest knows this. Knows it because he has been that kind of
player all his life, all the way back to Pop Warner football when
playing the game seemed a lot less threatening than going for a run
with his father and the dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not overwhelmed to have a couple of sacks,'' McGinest
said. ``When I'm healthy, it's nothing new to me to make plays.
It's just hard to make plays on one leg. This is a violent sport.
People get hurt. I understand that. I just want to play 16 games
and be strong.''
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish that, McGinest continues the regimen of exercises
McKechnie taught him. To help, McKechnie sent a video to Patriots
strength coach Johnny Parker so he could monitor McGinest, who from
time to time still talks with McKechnie. But mostly he's on his own
now, doing the work when no one is watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I came back too soon and got hurt again and then
came back too soon again and the problem became chronic,'' McGinest
said. ``But not being out there on the field when I'm supposed to
be one of the people the team is counting on didn't make me feel
good. So I tried. People don't know the work I've done. That's why
the last two years I've been totally frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely he has and just as surely few people understood how hard
he was working to avoid that, although anyone who looks at him
shirtless understands this is a man to whom body fat is a foreign
concept.
</P>
<P>
   But now it is a new season. Two weeks old and counting. A season
that has started out well for everyone because McGinest has started
out on two good legs. If he can continue that way, without the dogs
of the NFL dragging him down again, Sidwell believes he knows what
will result.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around some good outside pass rushers now (having
coached Ricky Jackson and Pat Swilling, two of the best in history,
in New Orleans),'' Sidwell said. ``With his quickness, Willie's the
kind of guy who can be very disruptive to an offense. He's a guy
we're counting on.''
</P>
<P>
   They're all waiting on McGinest this year. Waiting for him to
explode. His opponents as well as his teammates. Waiting to see if
he can get up and run again.
</P>
<P>
   Willie McGinest is waiting too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm just happy to be out there,'' he said. ``Happy
to just play hard. I just want to stay silent and play violent.''
</P>
<P>
   If he does, it won't be silent around him for long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
