<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-DAFOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT REALLY A DEAD END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm crying ``Uncle.''
</P>
<P>
   I surrender. Put all of us out of our misery.
</P>
<P>
   Just sign Byron Dafoe. Sign him and put an end to this tap
dance, waltz, tango, game of chicken, or whatever you want to call
it.
</P>
<P>
   He's going to get somewhere close to $10.5 million over three
years, the middle point between the Bruins' offer and his demand,
so could we please just get it over with?
</P>
<P>
   The regular season opens Saturday. The Bruins' schedule through
the first 11 games is extremely difficult, with eight on the road.
</P>
<P>
   With the Eastern Conference destined to be a tighter-than-tight
race, a poor start could doom the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   When president/general manager Harry Sinden told a handful of
reporters Wednesday night in Worcester that the negotiating with
Dafoe was over, that there was nothing else to talk about, it was,
to quote Yogi Berra, deja vu all over again.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost a year ago, on Sept. 30 to be exact, and in the
very same place _ the Centrum press box _ that assistant general
manager Mike O'Connell said he didn't see any way the Bruins could
come to terms with center Jason Allison. One day later, after
marathon negotiations, Allison agreed to terms.
</P>
<P>
   The scenarios have played out nearly identically. We offer our
exhibits (see accompanying quotes).
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe is sticking around town for now, rather than head back to
Southern California, crossing his fingers that something will get
done.
</P>
<P>
   Something should, and now is the time.
</P>
<P>
   Without a doubt, Sinden is an entertaining quote as well as a
shrewd businessman. Remember when talks broke down in 1992 with
then-Canadian Olympian Joe Juneau, who was threatening to play in
Switzerland? Sinden said he should learn how to yodel. As we all
now know, Juneau came to terms.
</P>
<P>
   To a point, it's funny, interesting, and an expected yearly
ritual. And let's face it, a fair amount of criticism leveled at
Sinden regarding his fiscal practices is unfair and ill-informed.
However, the Bruins have had a revolving door of goaltenders
(mostly disasters) since the tandem of Reggie Lemelin and Andy
Moog. I'd list them all but then I wouldn't have room for anything
else.
</P>
<P>
   Let's concede that Dafoe made a mistake in not going to
arbitration. He does. Perhaps he was too trusting back in June when
he thought the Bruins were coming in high with their initial offer
_ only to find out it was their only offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The comments O'Connell made about letting us know that when
the offer was made, that's so far from the truth,'' said Dafoe.
``Do you think, if he would have told me that, I would've said,
`OK, I can make you move'? No. That was never said, that was never
an option, and if it was, I would've gone to arbitration. No
question. It doesn't take a rocket scientist to figure it out. That
was not said. It was an initial offer and a good starting ground. I
did not know that was it. Yeah, so if I look back and I'd have
known that, sure, I wish I could've gone to arbitration.''
</P>
<P>
   File that under the equivalent of ``a goal through the five-hole
from center ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone can make mistakes, and Dafoe and his agent made the wrong
call there. However, the longer this drags on, everybody pays. No
one has talked about the toll it will take on coach Pat Burns or
the young players on the team or the veterans like Ray Bourque, for
whom this will likely be the last chance at the Stanley Cup. And
Lord knows the fans have suffered enough.
</P>
<P>
   You've got a talented, personable young goalie who can stop the
puck. We've seen more than our share lately of those who can't.
It's time to do the right thing. Pull the plug on this, please. I
just can't watch anymore.
</P>
<P>
   You must be kidding
</P>
<P>
   The situation in Ottawa grows more absurd by the day. You have
to wonder whether the agent for Alexei Yashin, the malcontent
holdout who has refused to honor the final year of his contract,
gives his interviews backed by a laugh track. Mark Gandler's
comments are getting to be more and more of a joke. His latest
nonsensical charge is that the Senators won't renegotiate with
Yashin because they're ``bigots.'' Gandler is asserting that the
team, which includes a great many Europeans, is anti-Russian and
because they refuse to renegotiate (read: give him whatever he
wants), they're ``stoning Alexei to death.'' Are you kidding me?
The kid is due to be paid $3.6 million in US funds to play a game,
and that's the equivalent of stoning him to death? If I were an
agent, I'd be embarrassed to be in the same profession as this guy
. . . Former Bruin prospect Ben Clymer, who was declared an
unrestricted free agent Sept. 10 after not being able to come to
terms with Boston, was invited to the Lightning's training camp. In
his first practice, the defenseman took six stitches in his cheek
as a result of being clipped by a stick . . . The situation in
Phoenix appears identical to what we have in Boston. Goalie Nikolai
Khabibulin rejected a three-year, $9 million contract and late last
week the club took the offer off the table. Khabibulin, who made
$1.25 million last season, is seeking something in the
$5-million-a-year range. That's a big chunk of change for a guy
who's never won a playoff series . . . Guess how much it cost the
Capitals to acquire former Bruins backup goalie Craig Billington
from the Avalanche? One dollar. That's right. Colorado was looking
to pare its roster, so the Capitals wound up with a reliable backup
and good citizen. Starter Olaf Kolzig said he's looking forward to
working with Billington, who is a supportive influence and spent
the last three seasons as the No. 2 behind Patrick Roy. ``My
understanding is, if you can get along with Patrick Roy, I think
you can pretty much get along with anybody,'' said Capitals coach
Ron Wilson. ``I think Craig's going to be just what the doctor
ordered.'' . . . Veteran Bob Errey, who won two Stanley Cups with
the Penguins in 1991 and '92, was let go by the club last week, one
day after his 35th birthday. Errey, who went in without a contract,
had a good training camp, but there were too many left wings ahead
of him . . . Plenty of speculation on who will become the next
captain of the Canadiens. One candidate is former Canucks and
Islanders captain Trevor Linden. Linden said Saku Koivu would make
a good choice. Another possibility is Shayne Corson, said to be a
favorite of teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Dogged pursuit
</P>
<P>
   Detroit defenseman Uwe Krupp could be in some hot water over
allegations that he competed in dog-sled races while supposedly
sidelined with a back injury. A man named Cecil Houghton, who is
the dean of the sport in Michigan, said he saw Krupp racing six
Siberian huskies at a race in January. ``I thought, `What are you
doing out here?' '' said Houghton. ``I almost called the Red Wings
and said, `Hey, get out here and get a look at your invalid.' ''
Krupp is listed as a driver in results from four other races
between Jan. 2-Feb. 28. He signed a four-year contract worth $16.4
million and played only 22 games last year before his back injury.
He's currently under suspension by the club because he refused to
grant the Red Wings access to his medical records. The team finally
got them but Krupp remains suspended pending their review . . . Yet
another veteran has retired because of post-concussion problems.
Following in the unfortunate footsteps of Pat Lafontaine and Jeff
Beukeboom, Tampa Bay center Brian Bradley called it quits at 34.
Bradley, an intense competitor, said he still suffers from
headaches on a daily basis. ``I really appreciate the time spent in
the NHL and wish I could continue playing,'' said Bradley. With all
the technology out there, you'd think some manufacturer could come
up with a helmet that would better protect players . . . One of the
bigger names still without a deal is former Boston University
standout Mike Grier, who remains home in the Boston area instead of
with the Edmonton Oilers. Grier made $400,000 in Canadian funds
last year and reportedly is seeking about $800,000 US, much more
than the team is willing to pay . . . Ron Tugnutt may not be the
starting netminder for Ottawa, as he has a sore left knee. If he
can't go, Patrick Lalime will get the start in the season opener
Saturday in Philadelphia . . . Former Bruins first-round pick Kevyn
Adams, who could never come to terms with Boston on a contract,
appears to have gotten the message about what he has to do to make
it in the NHL. Adams, who made progress in St. John's last year and
was called up to play seven playoff games for Toronto, worked out
hard over the summer and bulked up. Toronto GM/coach Pat Quinn has
been impressed with Adams in camp. ``He certainly has a high
ranking in the grading we've been doing,'' said Quinn . . . Six
days to opening night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 2147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
