<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6106 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ADVANCE-     09-25 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ADVANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VINATIERI KICKS INTO GEAR EARLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ Kickers normally are the little guys, with the
lockers closest to the door, whom nobody pays much attention to
unless they miss a big field goal. They're separated from the rest
of the team during practice, doing kicking drills with the special
teams coach and dribbling balls with their feet. Then, they go play
golf. Nice life.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Patriots' two wins have come in large part because
of Drew Bledsoe's superb play, they wouldn't have been possible if
Adam Vinatieri hadn't nailed two game-winning field goals. Who
knows what Sunday night will bring against the New York Giants?
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri hasn't been called upon to kick a 58-yarder, as he did
in the final exhibition game against Carolina. His big kicks have
been from 23 yards, with three seconds remaining against the Jets,
and from 26 yards, with 35 seconds left against the Colts.
</P>
<P>
   They are considered virtual chip shots, but you must consider
the pressure of causing a loss with a miss.
</P>
<P>
   In his three-plus seasons in the league, Vinatieri has kicked
six winning field goals, two in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Might this season's early heroics indicate the type of season it
will be for the Patriots?
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know,'' said Vinatieri. ``There are a lot of good
teams out there. We've been playing well enough to win but we
haven't hit on all cylinders. Hopefully we'll win by more, but it
may be we have close games and so you have to be prepared for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri certainly has done that. While negotiating a
three-year contract in the offseason, he worked on improving the
length of his kickoffs, which were weak a year ago because he never
fully recovered from a groin pull. He started training camp off
slowly, and for a while punter Lee Johnson was the front-runner for
the kickoff job.
</P>
<P>
   But against Carolina, Vinatieri started to blossom, his kicks
going an extra 5-8 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into camp, we both knew whoever helped the team out the
most should do it,'' Vinatieri said. ``We even heard they might use
both of us, just to keep the competition going a little more. It's
something they might do to mess up return teams or whatever. It was
good competition but whatever was good for the team, we'd do.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of it was getting used to the new footballs, which the NFL
will not allow to be doctored anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a matter of concentrating a lot more _ since the balls
are a little harder _ on driving it more, getting good contact and
better follow-through and making sure I drive through the ball and
land on my kicking foot,'' said Vinatieri.
</P>
<P>
   He believes he wasn't getting the distance last season because
of the groin pull, and thus there were some long runbacks that
forced him to make nine tackles, some of which saved touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more follow through, the more penetration through the
ball, I think you get the better distance,'' said Vinatieri.
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri has had to get used to a new holder, Johnson, after he
had developed a bond with Tom Tupa, now departed to the Jets. It
sounds like a small thing, but good kicking is all rhythm and
comfort. One thing goes wrong _ a bad snap, a bad hold _ and the
kick is botched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tupa and Lee are very comparable. Both have good hands. They
hold very similar,'' said Vinatieri.
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri has settled on a comfortable routine. During the week
he kicks 300-400 balls, mostly on Wednesday and Thursday, and then
he tapers off Friday. He said there is such a thing as kicking too
much, just as a pitcher might throw too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the older guys don't kick much at all during the
week,'' said Vinatieri. ``My legs are still fresh and I want to
develop and I want to feel good coming into a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri doesn't spend as much time on his golf game as
Tennessee Titans kicker Al Del Greco, who is considered the top
golfer in the NFL. But he has those aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I want to be the best kicker,'' he said with a
smile, ``but in 10 years, with a little more experience, maybe I'll
be as good as Del Greco and Tupa on the golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Larry Whigham is expecting a big night on special teams against
the Giants. ``It's definitely been an emphasis,'' said Whigham . .
. With Kevin Faulk (ankle) unable to play, Tebucky Jones and Lamont
Warren will handle kick-return duty, and if that doesn't work, Troy
Brown will get the call.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
