<HEADLINE>
RUTH RAY HUNT, 82, DALLAS PHILANTHROPIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK DOUGLAS Jr. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ruth Ray Hunt, who was married to oil baron H.L. Hunt, died
Saturday at her Dallas home after an illness. She was 82.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hunt was the second wife of H.L. Hunt, who was believed to
have been one of the richest men in the world when he died in 1974.
They married in 1957, two years after the death of H.L. Hunt's
first wife, Lyda Bunker Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The family asked that the nature of her illness not be
disclosed, said Jim Oberwetter, a family spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hunt, praised as a philanthropist, had a circle of friends
that included social high-steppers, a president and needy children
who came to ``Granny Ruth'' for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will simply say that Ruth Hunt is one of the loveliest human
beings I have ever encountered,'' former President Bush once wrote.
</P>
<P>
   A statement issued by the family said Mrs. Hunt ``was a
practical jokester ... incorrigible poet and a gracious
entertainer, opening wide not only her doors, but also her heart.''
</P>
<P>
   George Cunyus, a family friend, said Mrs. Hunt was ``the heart
and spirit of Hunt Oil Company, through which she always honored
the accomplishments and memory of her late husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Her family said Mrs. Hunt often went to hospitals unannounced to
visit sick employees of the oil company and their families. Dallas
businessman Ray Hunt said of his mother: ``When we were teen-agers,
Mom would come rushing home late for dinner, after an afternoon
serving as a volunteer `candy striper' at Baylor Hospital, where
she cared for patients who were totally unaware of her social
prominence.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hunt, who grew up in Idabel, Okla., was ``deeply religious,
spending a portion of each day in prayer and Bible study,'' the
family said.
</P>
<P>
   Recipients of her gifts include a community center in Idabel,
the Boy Scouts of America, the H.L. and Ruth Ray Hunt Heart Center
at Baylor University Medical Center, the Ruth Ray Hunt Cancer
Learning Center and the Ruth Ray Hunt Center at the Cooper
Institute for Aerobics Research.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hunt raised a son and three daughters. ``Our mother
embodied a love that was larger than life,'' daughter Helen LaKelly
Hunt said.
</P>
<P>
   She is survived by her sister, Swann Lake Buckels; brother James
Ray of Idabel, Okla.; her children, Ray, June, Helen and Swanee
Hunt; 17 grandchildren and three great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   By his first wife, H.L. Hunt had six children: H.L. Hunt III,
Nelson Bunker Hunt, William Herbert Hunt, Caroline Hunt
Schoellkopf, Margaret Hunt Hill and Lamar Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral services are scheduled for 1 p.m. Monday at First
Baptist Church in Dallas. Visitation will be from 3 p.m. to 5 p.m.
Sunday at Sparkman/Hillcrest Funeral Home, 7403 Northwest Highway
in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   In lieu of flowers, the family has asked that donations be made
to the Ruth Ray Hunt Scholarship Fund, Criswell College, 4010
Gaston Ave. in Dallas, or Baylor Hospital, House Calls Program,
4004 Worth St. in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
