<HEADER>
A6109 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-ONBASEBALL-RMARTI     09-25 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ONBASEBALL-RMARTINEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMON SHOWS HE'S STILL A WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's all right to say it. The Red Sox have a winner in
righthander Ramon Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Not many people were sure about that March 11 when Ramon and the
Red Sox agreed to a two-year contract, what with Martinez coming
off surgery on his right shoulder. But he is back with the poise
and grace that once made him a 20-game winner for the Los Angeles
Dodgers. Martinez didn't work any miracles at Fenway Park Saturday.
But he won a major league game for the first time in 15 months, and
that's all that counts now.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning nobody expected Ramon, 31, to have a fraction
of the impact of his younger brother Pedro, a Cy Young winner in
1997 for Montreal and the Red Sox' star this season. The low-key
Ramon marched to his own drummer, making almost every stop in the
Red Sox system in an attempt to resume a career cut short by
surgery last year. It hasn't been easy. There's still no telling
for sure whether Saturday's 4-1 victory is the beginning of the
comeback trail or a pit stop not far from the end.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, as the Red Sox try to nail down a playoff berth,
there are just good feelings that will last until his next outing.
He has earned a spot in the new six-man rotation, and it may be
hard to unseat him come the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to watch,'' said pitching coach Joe Kerrigan, who
has kept on top of Ramon's recovery since spring training. ``For a
little while I was having flashbacks of the old Dodger days when we
used to see him pitch like that from opposing dugouts. He prepares
himself. He's as dedicated to conditioning as much as any pitcher
I've had.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Saturday's game, not many of the 32,107 at Fenway Park
had much idea of what Kerrigan was talking about. In 10 seasons
with the Dodgers, Ramon had compiled a 123-77 record and was
considered the ace of the staff, going 20-6 in 1990. He was a
two-time All-Star and had postseason experience in 1995 and '96.
Yet he was jettisoned by Los Angeles after the 1998 season for a
familiar reason. He suffered a torn rotator cuff in June after a
5-0 stretch and wound up needing surgery. The Dodgers had an option
on his services but lacked the patience to keep him around. In
December, he became a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   He was considered by many a gamble to sign, but with a sample of
the Martinez spirit already in the house, the Red Sox offered him a
two-year contract. Today they have no regrets. And neither does
Ramon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been our experience, that about 70 percent of the
pitchers who have this injury come back and pitch effectively,''
said Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette. ``There was a bit of a
gamble. But his work habits were good. He was in good shape prior
to the surgery and he won 60 percent of his games. He was
determined to come back. All those things sort of worked out in our
favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had not won at any level since a 7-4 victory last June
3 over St. Louis for Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The road back went through almost every Red Sox minor league
port _ Lowell, Sarasota, Gulf Coast, and Pawtucket. Martinez made
10 rehabilitation starts in all. He finally made it to Boston Sept.
2, but lasted just three innings of a 4-2 loss. In his second start
Martinez was better, lasting 4 2/3 innings. Boston won, 14-3, but
Ramon did not get the decision. No matter. He had made such an
improvement that the Sox didn't hesitate to put him in what has now
become a six-man rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just kept trying and believing in himself that he was going
to be able to come back this year and help our team,'' said manager
Jimy Williams. ``We had a workout in Oakland earlier in the month.
The determination was there. He wanted to show that he was still
working hard and if we needed him to pitch we were going to be
ready. That's what really showed me.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the (Pat) Rapp situation (who had to be with his wife,
who was having a difficult pregnancy), we needed a starter and in
my mind because of all the work, the man, his work ethic, and
everything else about him, I said give him the ball. He has come a
long way from basically from that first start.''
</P>
<P>
   When healthy, Martinez had a presence on the mound, an air of
confidence. Saturday it all came together again. He threw 98
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of moments in which I thought I wasn't going
to pitch this year,'' said Martinez. ``I felt and touched a sore
shoulder, and I said to myself I might not be able to make it. But
I kept working. I never stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the first game I pitched, there was a lot of questions.
There is a lot of excitement and a lot expectations. I lost, but
that game allowed me to see how (it was going to be) when I came
back and pitched and how I was going to react. After the second
start, I had more confidence. Today was much better. I knew we had
the pressure that we had to win. We'd lost three straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez showed something Saturday. He is not overpowering
like Pedro, striking out only three. Ramon's curveball is not a
strikeout pitch, but one designed to throw hitters off balance.
Ramon's delivery unwinds like a tall tree in a windstorm. The
hitter never knows which way it's blowing. Saturday, he threw eight
curves, 15 changeups, and 75 fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can go over 90 easy,'' said Ramon. ``But I don't have
a good feeling on the curveball yet. A lot of sinkers and straight
fastballs and changeups. I'm not worried about the postseason
roster. There are a lot of guys who've been here all year long. I
still have to do my job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to take advantage of whatever chance that I
have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
