<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-MCHALE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCHALE REFLECTS ON FORTUNE AND FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kevin McHale goes into the Hall of Fame Friday. It will be
another reminder of what we had _ and what we're missing.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it was Larry Bird's night. We had to be reminded of
how great he was _ and how he was coming off a season in which he
had been named Coach of the Year. This year, it will be a
McHale-fest; he's the only entrant being inducted as a player, and
you can be sure it will be Party Central at the Marriott. (McHale
is planning on being in the area for a week; Bird flew in and out
in a day last year.) And yes, we'll also note that the Timberwolves
will have the expensive tables and that McHale is calling the
basketball shots in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   But McHale is going in for the way he played. At least, that's
how most of us see it. The way he sees it, however, is that he's
going in as much as for where he played, and whom he played with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years removed,'' he said ``and I still feel that some
players are in the Hall of Fame because they were great players. A
lot of players, and I'm one of them, are in the Hall of Fame
because you played on great teams. It's something you share with
the guys you played with.''
</P>
<P>
   McHale rattled off the names of those guys, from Tiny Archibald
to Dee Brown and many, many in between. (We didn't hear Darren
Daye, though.) There should a decent Celtics contingent on hand for
the ceremony. Bill Walton has promised to attend, as have Scott
Wedman and Jerry Sichting. McHale isn't sure about Danny Ainge or
anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played with so many guys I really enjoyed _ and all for
different reasons. That was the best part about it,'' he said. ``We
not only had tremendous teams, we had tremendous personalities and
tremendous character, which helped us win. We had characters who
had character and when it was time to play, they played.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if they're not there in person, they'll be there in
spirit. You sit back and remember what you were able to accomplish
as a team, and the recognition I got from being on that team far
supersedes anything I did individually.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe. McHale doesn't think he'd be headed to Springfield
if the Utah Jazz had taken him in the 1980 draft, as then-coach Tom
Nissalke wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Utah? What fun would that be? I'd score more points, but
nobody remembers how many points you scored. They remember how much
you won,'' he said. ``That wouldn't have been anything. It would
not have been nearly as rewarding.''
</P>
<P>
   McHale has done a commendable job building the Timberwolves,
although he couldn't keep Stephon Marbury and didn't want any part
of an Elden Campbell/Eddie Jones offer for Tom Gugliotta. But you
just remember how dismal that team was when he stepped in, and
where it is now, and, well, you might wonder: Why can't we get guys
like this to run the Celtics?
</P>
<P>
   Don't think the thought hasn't crossed McHale's mind. It has.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might have been (an opportunity). But there was never
any offer, or anything else like that,'' he said. ``There was
nothing there for me to do. Had they offered, I might have stayed.
Boston was great to me and I loved being out there. But you don't
know until it happens and I kind of knew I'd have a television job
and work with the Timberwolves. So, I came back.''
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't regretted the move. But he paused when he thought
about the brain drain in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look back, it's too bad after everything that happened,
what with Larry and Danny (leaving). There were a lot of guys who
knew basketball and didn't stick around and work in the
organization,'' he said. ``I love M.L. (Carr), he was a terrific
teammate. But his job was to have the team play really bad, get
some high draft picks, and take the heat for the organization. And
he did. That's a no-win situation. If you're going to do that, you
better have a hell of an understanding with the owner. No one could
have won with the team he was coaching, I don't care who it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Do you feel a draft?
</P>
<P>
   Kris Clack, whom the Celtics aren't even bothering to bring to
training camp, was taken third overall by Dennis Johnson's La
Crosse Bobcats in last week's CBA draft. DJ was thought to have
said he couldn't believe Clack was available at No. 3. Derek Hood
of Arkansas, who went undrafted in the NBA, was the overall No. 1
pick. Three New Englanders who were undrafted by NBA teams _ Jamel
Thomas of Providence, Ricky Moore of UConn and Antonio
Reynolds-Dean of URI _ also were taken. In addition, three players
selected in the first round of the NBA draft were picked: Dion
Glover, Leon Smith, and Devean George . . . Minnesota coach Flip
Saunders, a longtime friend of McHale, won't be around to witness
his boss/buddy's induction. The T-Wolves open training camp that
weekend (they start early because they play twice in Japan) and,
well, someone has to be there for the fourth estate. But on that
same night, Saunders is being inducted into his high school Hall of
Fame. He was named the top Class A player in Ohio after averaging
32 points a game at Cuyahoga Heights High School. Alas, he'll be
inducted in absentia . . . Corliss Williamson may come to terms
soon with Sacramento, which leaves Shandon Anderson as probably the
most desirable/available free agent without portfolio. (We're
excluding the likes of John Stockton and Jeff Hornacek.) Utah owner
Larry Miller is wisely rejecting Anderson's rather outlandish
demands ($7 million per year) and is offering twice what Anderson
could get from either Houston or Indiana, his two presumed points
of interest. Miller also won't do a sign-and-trade, which further
limits Anderson's options. Anderson now has introduced the
``lifestyle'' issue, which, of course, is standard fare in Utah.
There are a number of players (LaPhonso Ellis, Sam Perkins, Derek
Harper, Rony Seikaly, Bison Dele) who, for one reason or another,
balked at signing with the Jazz. But that didn't stop Olden
Polynice, did it? . . . Among the other ``names'' still looking for
work, according to the NBA, are Sherman Douglas, Joe Kleine, Tyrone
Corbin, Chucky Brown, Mark West, Eric Riley and Ron Harper. Douglas
has drawn a lot of interest but is still looking for more money.
(He could get $1.1 million as a 10-year veteran.) Doesn't he
realize he got his big contract eight years ago? . . . The NBA
movers and shakers arrived in Vancouver this week, perfect timing
to comment on the sale of the Grizzlies to spurned Nuggets wannabe
honcho Bill Laurie. The league knows Laurie from his near-purchase
of the Nuggets and he has that most valued criterion: deep (as in
Wal-Mart) pockets. He also just bought the St. Louis Blues and the
Kiel Center and, well, you can see where this is going. It's been
31 years since the Hawks left St. Louis for Atlanta, or about as
long as it's been since the Hawks won a meaningful (as in
best-of-seven) playoff series (that would be 1969-70, their first
year in Atlanta). The Grizzlies' expansion agreement says that the
earliest Laurie could apply to relocate is May 15, 2000, meaning
there will be at least two more years of hoops in Vancouver barring
a rules change. Commissioner David Stern was asked if he could
offer any encouragement to Grizzlies fans and said, ``It is my goal
to see the Vancouver Grizzlies succeed and stay in Vancouver.'' Any
relocation would have to be approved by a majority vote of the
owners. Laurie's purchase of the Grizzlies, as well as the purchase
of the Nuggets by Donald Sturm, likely will get the owners'
imprimatur at a Board of Governors meeting in late October . . . A
jury has managed to be seated for a civil trial in California over
an automobile accident involving Latrell Sprewell. The judge said
that prospective jurors were questioned intensely to eliminate
anyone who may have ``hero worship'' or ``bad feelings'' for
Sprewell. How did they manage to find anyone? . . . NBA
generalissimo Rod Thorn went over the new rules changes at the
league meetings and said that, basically, the referees are being
told to enforce the old rules. But Thorn also made it clear that
the new rules _ designed to stop the Anthony Mason trend _ aren't
the only changes needed. Although he didn't say it, Thorn and most
everyone else know the real villains in this offensive drought are
the coaches. ``Of the 29 teams, 25 of the offenses are basically
the same,'' Thorn said, ``and I dare say that the majority of teams
don't have a secondary fast break in their playbook anymore.''
Secondary? Most of them don't have a primary fast break. ``We're
hoping this will get offenses to do some different things. We want
to see some different looks and attacks.'' Let's hope it works. We
may even see some 100-point games again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 2151EDT &QL; 
