<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-DAUBACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAUBACH GETTING OVER THE WALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yes, Brian Daubach ripped his 20th home run of the year to put
him in some pretty elite company. And yes, that homer provided the
winning run as the Red Sox broke a three-game losing streak with
Saturday's 4-1 win over the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   And the fact that the homer was into the net in left-center, an
opposite-field job, was a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   But, Daubach warned, one hit does not break a slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt great today,'' Daubach said. ``But I only got one hit.
It's a start. I'm not out of my slump, for sure. But it felt good
to help the team again for a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time since I really helped.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach has struggled mightily at the plate the last five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He was hotter than hot in the middle of August. After that, he
was not.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's home run was his first since Aug. 14, a day he went 5
for 5 against Seattle. Two nights later, his bases-loaded double in
the ninth scored three runs and beat Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   He was named the American League Player of the Week.
</P>
<P>
   But in September, Daubach had had two hits in 31 at-bats in
entering Saturday's game, and his average had dipped to .292.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was also his first start in 10 days. The last time he
was in the starting lineup, Daubach struck out four times against
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   He had a good pinch-hit at-bat Friday night, despite the fact
that he struck out. He fouled off pitch after pitch from Scott
Kamieniecki before being called out when the third base umpire said
he had gone around on a 1-and-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, he struck out twice, but he also worked a full-count
walk in the bottom of the eighth and eventually scored with the
fourth Red Sox run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not always a hit, sometimes it's a walk, or a ground ball
to the other side,'' said manager Jimy Williams. ``This kid's
worked real hard all year long. He's a fighter, he'll fight back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you find out what a person's really made of when
they maybe aren't going so good. He hasn't stopped. He hasn't
changed anything he's been doing just because he hasn't been
playing. If anything, he's worked harder. I tip my cap to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach became just the third Red Sox lefthanded hitter to reach
the 20-homer mark in his rookie season. The others? Fellas by the
name of Ted Williams and Fred Lynn.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget, those 20 home runs and 71 runs batted in are
from a 27-year-old who had no major league homers and three RBIs in
15 big league at-bats entering the season.
</P>
<P>
   The bench time in the last week or so helped him rest and relax
a bit, Daubach said.
</P>
<P>
   Getting ahead in the count against Doug Linton didn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got in a 2-and-0 count, finally,'' he said. ``Usually, I've
been behind all the time lately. I got a pitch I could handle. I
got a good pitch to hit and I didn't try to kill it, I just made
good contact.''
</P>
<P>
   That the homer went into the net in left-center may be a good
sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always hit the ball to left-center,'' Daubach said.
``Especially in Fenway it helps being a lefthander and going the
other way. When I'm swinging good, I hit the ball the other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lately, I haven't even been hitting the ball. I've been
striking out way too often. Hopefully, I'll turn that around.''
</P>
<P>
   The time is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only got a week left to start swinging the bat so I can
be in there come the postseason, if we're fortunate enough to get
that far,'' Daubach said.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, the better he's swinging the bat, the better the
chances that the Sox will be successful in the playoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
