<HEADER>
A6112 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-DELAHOYA     09-25 1881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-DELAHOYA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMATCH IS ONLY WAY FOR DE LA HOYA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oscar De La Hoya patterned much of his career after Sugar Ray
Leonard, the gold medal-winning star of the 1976 Olympics who went
on to parlay matinee-idol looks and fearsome hooks into one of the
greatest careers in boxing history, both fistically and
financially. That blueprint still applies this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen years ago, Leonard was faced with much the same
situation De La Hoya finds himself in today. Beaten by Roberto
Duran in a close welterweight title fight, Leonard was embarrassed
and adrift but still the bigger draw, with or without a
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the businessman, Leonard used his financial power to lure
Duran back into the ring only five months later by overpaying him.
He then embarrassed a fat and sassy champion with his boxing skill,
forcing Duran to quit in disgust in the eighth round when he was
unable to hit Leonard and saw that things were only going to get
worse. That was the night Duran uttered his now infamous, ``No
mas!,'' a remark he will carry with him to his grave despite his
greatness in the ring on so many other nights.
</P>
<P>
   Now, nearly two decades later, it is De La Hoya without a title
he feels he still deserves. He lost the World Boxing Council
portion of the 147-pound championship to Felix Trinidad in a
controversial majority decision last weekend in Las Vegas, and like
Leonard before him, De La Hoya was his own worst enemy that night,
but in a far different way.
</P>
<P>
   While Leonard abandoned his boxing skills to brawl with Duran in
an attempt to prove his machismo and thus played into Duran's
strength, De La Hoya built up what he thought was an insurmountable
lead by using his strong jab and superior hand and foot speed, then
went into a shell with three rounds to go.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing not to fight, De La Hoya simply ran, conceding those
rounds to the plodding, ineffective, but resolute Trinidad.
Unbeknownst to De La Hoya, he was also giving away his title
because two of the judges handed over just enough of the early
rounds to turn the tide by the slightest of margins _ a single
point on one card and two on another.
</P>
<P>
   Stunned, De La Hoya pleaded his case desperately at the
postfight press conference, claiming, ``I thought I had it in the
bag. How can you land 100 more punches (by CompuBox statistics) and
lose?''
</P>
<P>
   Most at Mandalay Bay Events Center gave De La Hoya seven or
eight rounds, which should have been enough for him to win a
decision, but his nonaggression pact with his cornermen in the
final three rounds made the fight closer than it should have been
and hence left room for doubt.
</P>
<P>
   After that disaster, the question is: Where does he go from
here?
</P>
<P>
   It won't be the new Staples Center in Los Angeles on Dec. 9, as
originally planned. De La Hoya had been penciled in to fight there,
perhaps for his fifth world title at 154 pounds, but only days
after he was defeated for the first time, De La Hoya told promoter
Bob Arum the only fight he wants is a rematch with Trinidad within
six months. That is the same plan Leonard followed, and it is a
wise one.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad and his promoter, Don King, were cackling all the way
back to San Juan, claiming they would demand purse parity or better
for a rematch. But King, at least, knows the real score. There is
no place his man can get anywhere near the money he would get from
a De La Hoya rematch, and after earning $10.5 million (less King's
$2 million promotional fee), it will be nearly impossible to
convince him to go back to fighting for a million here and a
half-million there.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the thought of a parity deal with King made Arum look like a
man who has just bitten into an apple and found half a worm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't got to be no negotiations,'' King said. ``Just take my
name and put it where Arum's is on the contract and put Arum's name
where mine is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That'll be the day,'' Arum snapped back, knowing that would
give Trinidad double his purse when it would still be his fighter,
not King's, driving ticket and pay-per-view sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tito (Trinidad) got the decision but it didn't make him a
star,'' cautioned Lou DiBella, HBO Sports senior vice president for
programming. ``The money for Tito Trinidad is still Oscar De La
Hoya. Oscar walked in a star and he walked out a star.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but not as bright a one as when the night began. It was
most certainly De La Hoya's star power that drove pay-per-view
sales to a record 1.25 million, a high for a nonheavyweight fight
and a number so huge that there was immediate talk of an even
bigger sale for the rematch. But he is a fallen champion now, and
there is a psychological weight that must be lifted, as Leonard
well knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the loser, this will be a disaster,'' Leonard had said
before the fight. ``No one can understand how bad he'll feel.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya now understands, and he has decided, wisely, not to
argue with Trinidad or King over money. According to sources,
within days of the loss, he privately told Arum he would accept
purse parity for a rematch. That would probably pay each man around
$15 million, a hefty payday under any circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya realizes that winning the titles back from Trinidad
is more important than maximizing his earning potential, regardless
of the fact that his drawing power was probably only slightly
damaged. It is important, because to be a champion, you must wear a
champion's belt, and to be a superstar in boxing, you must avenge
defeat and the sooner the better.
</P>
<P>
   Arum, on the other hand, is a businessman who was already
talking of De La Hoya moving to 154 pounds and fighting WBC
champion Francisco Castillejo for a meaningless title while
forgetting about Trinidad for the moment. His theory is that
Trinidad and King would soon see there is no other fight for them
that can compare with a De La Hoya rematch, and they would have to
negotiate a more reasonable share of the rematch's profits.
</P>
<P>
   Arum is probably right, but a lot of things can happen in
boxing, and fights not made when the time is right often don't get
made at all. More importantly, De La Hoya is already a
multimillionaire. Splitting the take of a rematch 50-50 will not
affect his lifestyle in the slightest, so this need not be about
money for him.
</P>
<P>
   As Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis showed when they quickly
agreed to a 50-50 split to set up a rematch after their
aesthetically displeasing draw, De La Hoya needs Trinidad for
psychic reasons as much as Trinidad needs De La Hoya for fiscal
ones.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and Holyfield understood the same thing Leonard understood
and, for the moment at least, De La Hoya seems to grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Had De La Hoya won, there would be no need for a rematch because
once again it would have been the same scenario Leonard followed
nearly 20 years ago with Duran and Thomas Hearns.
</P>
<P>
   When Leonard defeated Hearns in as good a welterweight fight as
there had been in 25 years, there was no rematch for eight years _
even though Hearns yearned for one _ because it was risky business
for Leonard. It was a risk he didn't need to take.
</P>
<P>
   When you lose _ no matter how questionable the decision _ the
risk is different. You must risk it all to get back the invincible
champion's aura because that is something money can't buy.
</P>
<P>
   All De La Hoya has to put on the line to get what he needs,
then, is the same thing Leonard put down in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Money.
</P>
<P>
   When you've already made $100 million, that's not a risk. It's
the cost of being in the superstar business.
</P>
<P>
   Short jabs
</P>
<P>
   Here's a story, told by a source close to him, that illustrates
why Mike Tyson is in the dire financial straits he is, despite
having made more than $200 million in purses. Tyson spied a new
special-order Bentley on the way to the gym one day and immediately
wanted it. But because he owes the Internal Revenue Service $12.5
million and counting and various other creditors millions more for
having advanced him money to pay off past debts, he had no cash or
borrowing power. So, the story goes, he traded the dealer several
cars worth more than $1 million for one worth $250,000. ``That's
the way the guy is,'' the source said. ``He's like a child.
Everything is instant gratification. When he wants something, he
doesn't think of the price.'' . . . Newly crowned World Boxing
Organization heavyweight champion Vitali Klitschko (25-0) makes his
first defense against American Ed Mahone (21-0-2) Oct. 9 in
Oberhausen, Germany. Both Klitschko and Mahone have won all their
fights by knockout . . . Lewis is already training for the
Holyfield fight in the Poconos. His manager, Frank Maloney, claims
he is going to run for mayor of London next year as an independent.
He says he'll announce his candidacy following the Lewis-Holyfield
rematch . . . Lewis's assistant trainer, Harold Knight, said
following De La Hoya-Trinidad that one thing was obvious: ``The
general public wants fighters to act like sharks. When they see
blood, they should go in for the kill. Holyfield will come out to
knock out or be knocked out. It will be the latter.'' . . .
International Boxing Federation junior middleweight champion
Fernando Vargas takes on mandatory challenger Winky Wright Dec. 4
in Las Vegas while his rival, World Boxing Association champion
David Reid, fights later in December. HBO may put them on
back-to-back weekends to begin drumming up interest in a 2000
showdown of the former Olympic teammates . . . Popular Arturo Gatti
returns to the ring on ESPN2 Dec. 10. No opponent has been
selected, but who cares when Gatti fights? . . . Pernell Whitaker
will fight his farewell bout in January in his hometown of Virginia
Beach, Va., but the fear among his handlers is that if he looks
good he'll want to keep fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Around and around
</P>
<P>
   Heavyweight contender Kirk Johnson (27-0-1, 19 KOs) will go into
his Oct. 7 fight against Rodolfo Martin (21-7) without trainer
Teddy Atlas. The two reportedly had a nasty falling-out that ended
in a gym battle between the two that left both hurting and Atlas
looking for a new heavyweight to train . . . Amid st continued
rumors Rumors continue that the Roy Jones-Graciano Rocchigiani
light heavyweight title fight scheduled for Nov. 6 will not come
off Nov. 6 as scheduled, and Jones failed to did not show up in
Manhattan Thursday for a planned press conference to announce the
fight. Worried organizers said it was merely a delay and will be
rescheduled this week, but HBO executives conceded admitted for the
first time that there may be a problem convincing Jones to fight
for what will ultimately be chump change . . . Although her male
opponent has pulled out, Margaret McGregor of Bremerton, Wash.,
still believes she'll become the first woman professional boxer to
fight a man on Oct. 9. Promoter Tom O'Malley said saw that Hector
Morales pulled out this week last week because he became
``increasingly uncomfortable'' with the publicity the bout had
attracted. Now Morales's trainer, Loi Chow, says he'll put his 3-0
record on the line if the Washington State Boxing Commission
approves the bout. Isn't this going a little too far, even for
boxing?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
