<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-DAY-TWO-1STLEDEWRITETHRU-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVE AND TAKE   PROVES TO BE   THE STORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Edits, updates throughout)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ There was a trace of electricity in the air
Saturday morning as the 33d Ryder Cup matches resumed with the
European side in command, 6-2, after Friday's opening matches.
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks broke quickly from the gate, but the brief dousing of
the course, which delayed things a bit, seemed to cool them off and
the morning foursomes ended with each side earning 2 points.
</P>
<P>
   It left the Europeans with an 8-4 advantage, the same as they
enjoyed after the rain-delayed second day two years ago at
Valderrama, Spain, where they ended up celebrating a 14 1/2-13 1/2
victory that kept the Cup in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the team of Phil Mickelson-Tom Lehman building a
3-hole through No. 10 on their way to taking Lee Westwood and
Darren Clarke for a point in the afternoon, the narrowest the US
side could close the gap was 8-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the guys to look up on the board and see us go 1 up, 2 up,
and 3 up, they could say, `let's keep on going,' '' said Lehman.
``I think for the rest of the team to see the lead group doing some
damage was very important.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, but it wasn't quite enough to lift the troops completely
out of the doldrums. Momentum definitely slipped away when Tiger
Woods missed from 6 feet on the 17th, allowing the irrepressible
Colin Montgomerie and British Open champion Paul Lawrie to chalk up
a huge point over him and Steve Pate, America's other winning
combination in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Garcia, who had missed makeable birdie putts on 15 and
17, sank the one that counted most on 18. His birdie from just
outside 6 feet enabled him and Jesper Parnevik to halve their match
with Davis Love-David Duval and remain undefeated for the weekend
with 3 1/2 points.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's team matches ended with Miguel Angel Jimenez
watching his potential winning putt die on edge of the cup on 18,
which locked up a halve for him and fellow Spaniard Jose Maria
Olazabal with Hal Sutton-Justin Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   So, with all said and done, the day ended as it began _ with the
Europeans up by 4 points. They led, 10 1/2-5 1/2, entering singles
matches two years ago at Valderrama.
</P>
<P>
   There were some brilliant shots over the closing holes Saturday.
Sutton, who had been absent from Ryder Cup play for 12 years,
nearly holed his tee shot on 16, and the Spanish Armada once again
ruled supreme: Garcia and Parnevik went 3-0-1 in four matches.
Jimenez, who was an assistant captain two years ago, completed a
1-0-3 trip, and Olazabal, whose career was in jeopardy just a
little over two years ago with a serious foot problem, has been
2-0-1.
</P>
<P>
   Woods and Pate started their morning (alternate-shot) match with
four straight birdies and would have gone 4 up had Dubliner Padraig
Harrington not rolled in a birdie putt to halve a hole. The
visitors then proceded to win the sixth, eighth, and 11th to pull
all square. This was the way it went until Woods rolled in a putt
for an eagle and a 1-up edge on the par-5 14th.
</P>
<P>
   The 17th, the most notorious hole at the Country Club for
swinging momentum, proved key again when Harrington's approach shot
to the severe slope in back of the pin refused to spin back to the
hole. ``I got robbed,'' said Harrington. ``I couldn't believe it
when the ball stopped on the slope. It was obvious it would have
been stone dead if it had rolled back.''
</P>
<P>
   The 18th wasn't pretty, but Woods lagged his putt to the lip for
a conceded par and the 1-up victory that left the Europeans with an
8-4 lead entering the afternoon fourball competition.
</P>
<P>
   After lunch, the US picked it up early and led all four matches.
Montgomerie put a temporary end to that, holing a birdie putt on
the third with partner Paul Lawrie at his side to square things
with Woods and Pate.
</P>
<P>
   There is little question Montgomerie is the inspirational
father-figure on the European side. He was at the heart of the
victory two years ago, and ``his contribution this week has been
enormous,'' said team captain Mark James. ``He's someone the
players look to, someone my assistants confide in. That was a huge
point he had. It's nothing I didn't expect from Colin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am happy to maintain our lead,'' said James, who played on
seven teams and made a run at making it an eighth this year. ``We
achieved our objective to play some good golf today, and to win
points they had to play well. They know what they are up against,
and we know what we are up against.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a question of relying on big guns. I have a feeling
that some players are playing slightly better than others and are
slightly more capable of shooting lower. It's a very narrow margin,
and I'm going with those players because they are doing a good job.
To change tactics would be dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   The team of Jim Furyk and Mark O'Meara, who are generally
regarded has having two of world's best short games, failed to
register a birdie in their 3-and-2 foursomes setback to Westwood
and Clarke. ``It's disappointing,'' said O'Meara, who sat out the
first two matches and didn't play in the afternoon. ``We didn't
play poorly, but we didn't make any putts. They birdied the two Par
5s (9, 14), where we had good drives and didn't make any birdies.
That was the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   And the overall difference between the teams still stands at 4.
</P>
<P>
   The great unknowns entering Sunday's singles matches are the
three players James hasn't played: Andrew Coltart of Scotland, who
was one of his two captain's selections; Jean Van de Velde, who let
the British Open slip away on the 72d hole; and Jarmo Sandelin of
Sweden. ``They've been tremendously supportive,'' said James.
``It's a shame they've been left out. I came here with the
objective of getting the most points I could out of this team. I'd
probably do it again the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   It's intriguing that sunday Sandelin will meet Mickelson in the
third match; Van de Velde will go up against Love in the fourth;
and Coltart will face Woods in the fifth match. The US trails by 4
points, and the Euros need to win just four matches to tie, 14-14,
and retain the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw, who advanced to the quarterfinals of the US Juniors at
The Country Club 31 years ago, left his interview with optimism.
``I'm a great believer in fate,'' he said, ``and I have a good
feeling about this.''
</P>
<P>
   He has to hope his leaders get off to a quick start and make the
event fun. ``I think our players have enough confidence,'' said
Crenshaw, ``and they know what to do. I had a talk with the team
last night, and there was a lot of confidence we can do it if we
just play our game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
