</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-SHAUGHNESSY-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUR GUYS ARE HITTING OUT OF ROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Edits, updates throughout)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ The Europeans are putting into cups the size
of paint cans. Our Guys are aiming at thimbles.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods is the best golfer in the Nike world, but he is the
Roger Clemens of Ryder Cups, winning only twice in nine starts
(2-6-1). The ``I'' of the Tiger seems in conflict with team
matches.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans, according to their captain, are ``somewhat
chuffed,'' which we think means ``pleased.'' Our Guys are gagging
on their wallets, their rankings, and some of their comments.
</P>
<P>
   When the sun went down over The Country Club there was a bad
moon rising and the Ryder Cup scoreboard read, Europeans 10, Our
Guys 6. Play resumes this morning, and unless the Yanks stage an
unprecedented rally (they need 8 1/2 of 12 remaining points), the
Europeans will put the Cup back on the Corcorde and take it across
the pond sometime monday. In some corners (of America), a European
victory will go down as the greatest upset in golf history.
</P>
<P>
   There was little Saturday to alleviate American fallout from
Friday's European rout. US wonderboys Woods, David Duval, and
Justin Leonard continued to struggle against the likes ot
19-year-old Spaniard Sergio Garcia and the ever-maddening Colin
Montgomerie.
</P>
<P>
   Monty will be No. 10 batter in Mark James's lineup Sunday
(facing Payne Stewart). The wide-body leader loves nothing better
than beating Woods, which he (along with teammate Paul Lawrie) did
in Saturday's best-ball match.
</P>
<P>
   Monty was somewhat riled by the local crowd and said, ``The
first two days were smellier. For me, I take the jeering as a
compliment because I am a threat, and I take that as a compliment.
. . . That's the best thing we can do _ silence the crowd by
outplaying them. . . . They need pumping up because they're losing
and they're losing badly.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. Start with Woods, who had a good excuse when he was
a Ryder rookie in Spain two years ago but has dropped three of four
matches in Brookline. He was playing well coming into the
tournament, but the Ryder Cup is becoming his personal nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've hit it beautifully all week and I've putted well, too,''
said Woods, who plays the well-rested Andrew Coltart Sunday.
``Unfortunately, it's just not enough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He battled his putter today, no question he did,''
acknowledged US captain Ben Crenshaw. ``We've got to get that
straightened out.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Leonard, a one-time British Open champ who is
winless (0-3-4) in seven career Ryder matches. The US had a good
thing going with the Hal Sutton-Jeff Maggert duo (two wins), but
Crenshaw elected to rest Maggert for the afternoon session and
replaced him with Leonard, who struggled mightily. Leonard gets
Jose Maria Olazabal Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's David ``the Ryder Cup is an exhibition'' Duval.
The No. 2 player in the world, Duval was on the bench in the
morning but played in the nightcap and, teamed with Davis Love,
managed to halve a match against Europe's awesome tandem of Garcia
and Jesper Parnevik. Credit Duval with 1 point of a possible 6 thus
far, while Garcia and Parnevik have rung up 7 of 8 possible points.
Sunday Duval faces the white-hot Parnevik.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a business luncheon Friday, the great Arnold Palmer
_ a veteran of nine Ryder Cup teams _ said, ``Maybe our guys are
too businesslike about what's happening. Maybe they're taking it
too seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Folks following the morning pairing of Stewart and Leonard
against Garcia and Parnevik might have come to the same conclusion.
Garcia and Parnevik are of different generations (Sergio is 19,
Jesper 34) and speak different languages, but they enjoyed one
another while the grim-faced Americans barely spoke. Messrs. Woods,
Duval, and Leonard walk the course like they're en route to an
appointment with their dentist.
</P>
<P>
   Duval and Love appeared to have the Swede and Spaniard beaten in
the four-ball, but Garcia won the 18th hole and the US had to
settle for half a point. It was devestating, emotionally and
competitively.
</P>
<P>
   Love said, ``No matter what we do, it seems like they do us one
better. It seems like a loss to us, and I'm sure it seems like a
win to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounding like captain Tom Kite after the loss at Valderrama two
years ago, Crenshaw said, ``I've never been so proud of a bunch of
guys in my life. They played their hearts out and will continue to
play their hearts out.''
</P>
<P>
   Droll Euro captain Mark James, who says he keeps his troops
fresh by feeding them chocolate, has used his roster much like K.C.
Jones did the 1985 Celtics: He's played only nine of his 12
players. Scotland's Coltart, Sweden's Jarmo Sandelin, and France's
Jean Van de Velde have not yet played. It's unprecedented for a
captain to keep three players on the bench Friday and Saturday, but
the Euros don't care about sparing players' feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Sunday, the US has more rested players (seven
Europeans have played every match) and a reputation for dominance
in singles match play. Two years ago at Valderrama, the Americans
were hopelessly behind going into the final day but made things
close winning 8 of 12 one-on-ones. They'll need more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw ended his press conference by saying: ``I'm a big
believer in fate. I have a good feeling about this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
