r s BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-S.-MISS     09-25 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-S.-MISS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KICKER, DEFENSE BAIL OUT TEXAS A&AMP;M AGAINST SOUTHERN MISSISSIPPI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Whit Canning 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ R.C. Slocum's most effective strategic
ploy last week probably occurred Wednesday, when he informed junior
placekicker Terence Kitchens that he was being put on scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he came into the office the next day, I told him he had
earned it and deserved it, and that's why I was doing it,'' Slocum
said. ``And I said, `Now don't go into the tank on me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   Kitchens kicked three field goals _ including a 62-yarder that
ties the third-best in A&AMP;M history _ and the Wrecking Crew defense
did the rest, as the fifth-ranked Aggies (3-0) cruised past
Southern Mississippi, 23-6, despite failing to score an offensive
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Teaming with punter Shane Lechler, who helped create 20 points,
Kitchens staked A&AMP;M to a 9-0 halftime lead and the Golden Eagles
(2-2) were finished off by interception returns of 41 yards by Jay
Brooks _ for a 16-0 third-quarter lead _ and 26 by Michael Jameson
to clinch it in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Despite 299 yards, the A&AMP;M offense could never put the ball in
the end zone. It was a day of immense futility for the Eagles, who
had accumulated 62 total yards when backup Cable Davis threw a
54-yard touchdown pass to Todd Pinkston 46 seconds deep in the
fourth quarter. USM, which nearly knocked off Nebraska last week,
rarely threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just up against a very good defense today,'' Slocum
said, ``but so were they. That looked like vintage Wrecking Crew
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, who came in averaging 354 yards per game, managed
only 18 yards on the ground and 111 through the air, on a 10-of-29
day with four interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   But through the first 30 minutes, the big story was Kitchens,
who kicked field goals at the end of two stalled drives and then _
on the final play of the half _ lined up 62 yards away, with
Lechler holding.
</P>
<P>
   ``When coach Slocum looked at me on the sideline, I held my
finger up in the air to let him know I wanted to try it,'' Kitchens
said. ``I knew how long it was, because they had just marked off a
\R17-yard\S penalty, and I looked to see where the spot was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kicked it well. Being put on scholarship this was a
tremendous thrill, because my parents have worked very hard to put
me through school, and this helps. Then I was able to help us win.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been an awesome week.''
</P>
<P>
   Lechler, who gave A&AMP;M new life on the opening field-goal drive
with a 22-yard sprint for a first down after fumbling a punt snap,
said he knew Kitchens had nailed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, he scrapes the grass a little,'' he said. ``You hear
the scrape and then a `pop' when he hits it. This time, I didn't
hear the scrape ... just a big pop.''
</P>
<P>
   Lechler wasn't exactly idle himself, pinning the Eagles deep in
their territory with punts of 66 and 62 yards and, finally, a
47-yarder that was killed at the 3. These kicks led to a field goal
and the interception returns by Brooks and Jameson.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a good scheme, and they're a great defense _ and my
numbers were Ug-ly,'' A&AMP;M running back Dante Hall (23 yards on 16
carries) said. ``I think, frankly, their defensive line dominated
our offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we won, and that's what matters. The defense saved us.''
</P>
<P>
   Just another day at the office, said linebacker Jason Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're supposed to do,'' he said. ``That's what the
Wrecking Crew is all about.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
