<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-PAIRS-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAIRING STRATEGY FAVORS THE EUROPEANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Edits, updates throughout)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ It is a difference of opinion as striking as
the Vardon grip vs. the interlock. Neither is wrong, both can work.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Crenshaw has chosen to use all 12 of his players in the
first two days of the 33d Ryder Cup Matches at The Country Club,
sticking with a philosophy that is typical for a United States
captain. European captain Mark James, on the other hand, has ridden
nine horses, and won't introduce the remaining three members of his
team until Sunday's singles matches. (Their names are Jarmo
Sandelin, Jean Van de Velde, and Andrew Coltart, in case you have
forgotten Thursday's opening ceremonies.)
</P>
<P>
   No one should be surprised by the differences in strategy,
because it's been the way the Ryder Cup has unfolded in recent
years. The US captain always has had the luxury of a deep, rich
talent pool, so dominant he could sit out key players, get everyone
in the lineup, and still win.
</P>
<P>
   Not so the European captain, so James did what Seve Ballesteros,
Bernard Gallacher, and Tony Jacklin did before him _ he saddled his
big horses and rode them hard. That's been the European way since
``The Fab Five'' of Ballesteros, Ian Woosnam, Bernhard Langer, Nick
Faldo, and Sandy Lyle arrived on the scene in the mid-1980s. They
embraced the Ryder Cup, made it a big deal, and challenged their
successors to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Consider it a mission accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend seven Europeans will play five matches each. It was
more than a gamble by James; it was the only choice he had. His
team boarded the Concorde last Monday with one game plan _ use
eight or nine players, get as big a lead as possible through two
days, and try to hang on in singles.
</P>
<P>
   James's only real decision was whether to play Jose Maria
Olazabal, a choice the Spaniard made for him by asking out of the
alternate shot foursomes matches. (Padraig Harrington moved in.)
Colin Montgomerie, Paul Lawrie, Darren Clarke, Lee Westwood, Jesper
Parnevik, Sergio Garcia, and Miguel Angel Jimenez all said, ``Give
us matching shirts, please, and point us to the first tee.''
</P>
<P>
   And if they were advised of what Jeff Maggert said (``It's a lot
to ask to play five matches'') perhaps they would laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Maggert had shined for three matches with Hal Sutton, but did
not play four-ball, a move that raised eyebrows. Ben Crenshaw said
the move, putting Justin Leonard in with Sutton, was ``a hunch,''
and critics can argue whether it was a good move, just as there
will be wolves coming down on James if his team falls apart Sunday.
Securing at least four points seems a simple task, but consider
this _ since 1987, 25 Ryder Cup competitors have played five
matches and their singles record is 8-13-4.
</P>
<P>
   Not a huge confidence factor, but the Europeans are a strong lot
and they know what challenge lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really tired Friday night,'' said Jesper Parnevik,
``but, for some reason, I don't know why, I had adrenaline
(Saturday). I felt fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Singles has never been the European strong point (Oak Hill, 1995
excluded). James _ and the Americans _ know this.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether fatigue and/or rust will be factors.
Call it wishful thinking, but the Americans think they could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely do,'' said Tom Lehman, who said Coltart,
Sandelin, and Van de Velde face huge tasks. ``Three players haven't
played, and that's a benefit (for the US), yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very tough to come all the way over, prepare to
play, then for two days sit and watch. I imagine it would be pretty
tough,'' said Justin Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is the bottom line, which is the score. Europe 10,
the US 6, and Lehman finds it hard to criticize James. ``If that's
what it takes to win, I would, too,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
