<HEADER>
A6234 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBO-BASEBALL-COLUMN-L     09-25 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SPITE OF TV, DODGERS KEEP PACKING 'EM IN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When they celebrate Fan Appreciation Day this
afternoon at Dodger Stadium, everyone should win the sailboat.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Arizona Diamondbacks clinched the National League
West on Friday, it is even more impressive that the Los Angeles
Dodgers also reached their magic number of 3 million fans the same
night.
</P>
<P>
   It is a number that is more important to the organization than
Jackie Robinson's 42. The Dodgers set that lofty attendance goal in
1978 and have gone over 13 times since. The Colorado Rockies blew
by them several years ago by drawing 4 million, back when Coors
Field was new and the team was good.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Rockies are bad and Coors has been a ghost town the past
month.
</P>
<P>
   Not here. To the Dodgers, three million fans represent success,
even if the wins and losses suggest otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   For many reasons, many of them found in Raul Mondesi's tirade
last month, it is amazing that the Dodger crowds kept coming all
summer.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a unique relationship between the team and this
city. Even with the unveiling of the new Staples Center in a few
weeks, there are plenty of seats available for opening-night games
with the Kings and Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, whom many think are L.A.'s team, will draw well, but
it wasn't too long ago they were playing to less-than-capacity
crowds at the Forum. NFL? Yawn. USC football? The Trojans play UCLA
at home, but Notre Dame is on the road. Not good.
</P>
<P>
   At Chavez Ravine, there is something special. How else to
explain it since the Dodgers went an entire season without getting
on a roll, never winning more than five straight.
</P>
<P>
   The soaring price of Dodger Dogs became front-page news. The
scoreboard blared ``DE-VO, DE-VO'' as though he were actually more
than an aging center fielder with a crick in his neck.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a bad marriage, but it survived. Is there any better
definition for unconditional love than the crowds that showed up to
watch Carlos Perez go 0-7 this season at Dodger Stadium?
</P>
<P>
   One-time Dodgers GM Buzzy Bavasi once said, ``Twenty thousand
fans would show up just to see why the lights are on.''
</P>
<P>
   And Fox might want to take credit for adding youthful music and
pyrotechnics between innings. But they paid $311 million for a team
that needs yet another overhaul because the stands are full and the
potential is limitless.
</P>
<P>
   Fox does deserve a bow for doing something most people in the
entertainment industry figured would make reaching 3 million in
attendance as extinct as a well-pitched game.
</P>
<P>
   They put them all on television.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly we are no longer in the era when former owner Walter
O'Malley only televised the nine road games from Candlestick Park.
TV is big money. But it also is viewed as a drain on the live gate.
</P>
<P>
   Until this year, the Dodgers used to entice fans by televising
the first game of a homestand. Vin Scully would say, ``Hope to see
you out at the ballpark,'' like he was planning to escort you to
your seat.
</P>
<P>
   It worked because there still is no substitute for a warm July
night at Dodger Stadium, whether Eric Young is in the lineup or
not. Fans get ripped here for leaving in the seventh inning. But
this is not Philadelphia, where they booed Mike Schmidt on his way
to the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   And in case you haven't noticed during all those games on cable,
fans everywhere are leaving in the seventh. Even at a baseball
shrine like Wrigley Field, the place empties after Sammy Sosa bats.
It doesn't matter if the game is still on the line.
</P>
<P>
   So after the game today, when they are giving away vacations to
Paris or Rome, the Dodgers will smile. They know their fans will
always come back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 2212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
