<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SMU-HAWAII-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAINBOW WARRIORS TURN ROAD WARRIORS IN VICTORY AGAINST SMU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Hawaii, which came to the Cotton Bowl with a 15-game
road losing streak and hadn't won a Western Athletic Conference
game away from Aloha Stadium in seven years, ended both skids
yesterday with a 20-0 victory against SMU.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't exactly have a history of winning on the road,''
Hawaii coach June Jones said after the conference opener. ``Right
now any road win for us is a big win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rainbow Warriors, whose last shutout victory came five years
ago against Southeast Missouri, forced three turnovers and
outgained the Mustangs, 394-231. SMU (0-3) also cost themselves
pointswith two penalties that negated touchdowns, anda fumble into
the end zone that ended a drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We turned the ball over and had too many penalties,'' SMU
coach Mike Cavan said. ``That's something we've been doing all year
and we just continue to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawaii took a 7-0 lead on its second possession and needed just
two plays to go 81 yards for the score. Rainbow Warriors
quarterback Dan Robinson, who threw for 304 yards, found receivers
open behind the Mustangs' defense on consecutive plays, the second
resulting in a 38-yard touchdown pass to Channon Harris.
</P>
<P>
   SMU had a chance to answer late in the second when it reached
Hawaii's 5-yard line. But on third-and-2, freshman Kris Briggs
fumbled into the Hawaii end zone and Nate Jackson recovered,
returning it to the Hawaii 20. Eight plays later, Eric Hannum hit a
career-long 50 yard field goal as the half expired for a 10-0
Hawaii lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mustangs' mistakes continued, beginning with the first play
of the second half. Rodnick Phillips appeared to have scored on a
70-yard run, but the play was nullified by an illegal block, and
SMU was eventually forced to punt.
</P>
<P>
   On the ensuing series, SMU's Tracy Hart intercepted a Robinson
pass and returned it 30 yards for a score only to have it called
back on an offsides penalty against the Mustangs.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Hawaii went on to seal the victory with a 42-yard
field goal by Hannum and a 13-yard scoring pass from Robinson to
Craig Stutzmann. Hawaii's defense held SMU to 81 yards rushing,
helping the Rainbow Warriors to preserve their first road shutout
since 1983, which came against UNLV.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time since we won a road game,'' said Hawaii
linebacker Jeff Ulbrich, who recorded 16 tackles. ``It's nice to
break a seven-year losing streak.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 2212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
