r s BC-100-MOST-MEMORABLE-TE     09-25 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-100-MOST-MEMORABLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NBA SHOT, AND TIMEOUT, HEARD 'ROUND THE WORLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MITCHELL KRUGEL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If a great moment in sports becomes one of the 100 greatest
moments in sports because it somehow changes the landscape, the
playing field or the rules, then Game 5 of the 1976 NBA Finals has
a momentous legacy.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the NBA hadn't changed its rules regarding calling
timeouts after the Boston Celtics 128-126 victory against the
Phoenix Suns, this triple-overtime, last-second-shot laden,
marathon of a game can make a claim to being the best NBA Finals
game ever played.
</P>
<P>
   The game evoked feelings never before seen in the mecca known as
Boston Garden, and that included more than Garfield Heard's shot
with less than a second left in double overtime that forced the
third extra frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know when it went in, I really felt something,'' Heard
said of the 20-foot turnaround jumper at the time. ``I don't know
what it was. But I felt something.''
</P>
<P>
   The shot ``Heard 'Round the World,'' as it has been called,
culminated a frenzy of activity. That the Suns defeated the
defending champion Golden State Warriors in the Western Conference
finals and reached the championship round despite a 42-40
regular-season record already had made for momentous drama.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on this June 4 night, Phoenix recovered from a 22-point
deficit against a Boston squad that featured Dave Cowens, John
Havlicek and Paul Silas, each of them NBA all-defensive team
selections in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Still, victory for the Celtics seemed all but assured when they
took a 109-106 lead with 15 seconds to play in the second overtime.
But Dick Van Arsdale hit a baseline jumper and Paul Westphal,
traded from Boston to Phoenix for Charlie Scott before the season,
came up with the next big play.
</P>
<P>
   On the ensuing inbounds pass, Westphal stole the ball. His steal
led to a Curtis Perry jumper and a 110-109 lead with four seconds
to play.
</P>
<P>
   Havlicek, however, dribbled the length of the floor and banked
in a jumper as time seemingly ran out. Celtics fans rushed the
floor to celebrate a 3-2 series lead.
</P>
<P>
   But referee Richie Powers put one second back on the clock.
Having to inbound from under their own basket seemed to assure the
Suns were all but set down. What's more, Phoenix had no timeouts to
call, and a timeout would have enabled them to inbound the ball at
halfcourt, at least, according to NBA rules.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal called one anyway. Phoenix was hit with a technical and
a free throw made it 112-110. But the Suns got the ball at
halfcourt. What led to Heard's heroics at that moment is still a
question for discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was supposed to be a lob to the basket, and I was supposed
to try and tip it in,'' Heard said. ``That was the designed play,
though I've heard about 15 others since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don Nelson was playing me, and he wouldn't let me go back
door. Curtis \RPerry\S just threw the ball into me. I just turned
and shot.''
</P>
<P>
   And made it.
</P>
<P>
   Triple overtime added its own exclamation point of drama. Former
top draft pick Glenn McDonald, who played little during the game,
scored six points in the final five minutes to lead Boston to
victory. The Celtics went on to win the best-of-seven series, 4-2,
McDonald went on to Milwaukee the following season and played just
nine more games in his NBA career.
</P>
<P>
   And the NBA went on to change the timeout rules. A team can no
longer call a timeout if it is out of timeouts, not even in
exchange for a technical foul.
</P>
<P>
   But, then, Game 5 of the 1976 NBA Finals is not remembered only
for a mere technical-ity. ``Tomorrow: The golden girls of the 1996
Summer Olympics''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 2236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
