<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6316 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-N     09-25 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAMPA BAY BEATS YANKEES, 2-1  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A massive homemade calendar takes up about a third of
the wall space in the office of Yankees Manager Joe Torre, and in
those boxes where the scheduled starting pitchers are usually
listed for the week ahead in blue ink, there are blank spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Torre and his coaching staff are in the process of aligning the
rotation for last week of the regular season and for the playoffs,
which begin next week. All the relevant information is in Torre's
hands after David Cone's solid six innings in a 2-1 loss to Tampa
Bay Saturday. It was the Devil Rays' first victory at Yankee
Stadium; they had been 0-9.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have assured themselves of at least a wild-card
berth, and with their magic number for clinching the American
League East at four, it appears that only time stands between the
Yankees and their third division title in four seasons. They came
from behind on Friday night and went on to beat Tampa Bay in extra
innings, and they were a millimeter from tying Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Hernandez, the Devil Rays' closer, had not blown a save
since June 30 before he faltered on Friday, and he jogged back to
the mound Saturday to try again. Jorge Posada led off the bottom of
the ninth inning, Hernandez _ whose fastball has been clocked at
100 miles an hour _ zipped a pitch over the middle of the plate,
and Posada smashed it.
</P>
<P>
   As Posada moved up the first-base line, he watched the Devil
Rays' center fielder, Dave Martinez, charge toward the fence in
left field, running, turning, until Martinez's back was facing the
infield. Posada's ball thumped near the very top of the padded
wall, bounced upward and fell to the warning track.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, the Yankees in their bullpen beyond the
left-center-field fence began screaming that the ball had struck a
support bar behind the fence _ that would make it a home run _
rather than the top of the wall.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen coach, Tony Cloninger, called the Yankees' dugout to
say what they had seen, and Torre moved swiftly onto the field to
argue as Posada stood at second base.
</P>
<P>
   But television replays showed that in fact, the ball hit the
very edge of the wall, leaving a divot in the padding. If Posada's
drive had gone any farther, it almost certainly would have skipped
off and over the wall for a game-tying home run. ``Everyone thought
it was a home run,'' Cloninger said, ``but the camera shows it
wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfonso Soriano ran for Posada and advanced to third on a
groundout, and Chili Davis pinch-hit for Scott Brosius and fouled
off the first-pitch fastball from Hernandez; Davis' at-bats lately
have hinged on whether he gets ahead in the count.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez went on to strike out Davis on three pitches, and
Chuck Knoblauch hit a fly to left, screaming furiously as he ran up
the line and watched the ball land in Terrell Lowery's glove for
the final out.
</P>
<P>
   Cone, the losing pitcher, was in the clubhouse by then. He has
not been credited with a victory since Aug. 8, sometimes because of
his inconsistency, and on other occasions because he has been
unfortunate. The Yankees have scored one or two runs in seven of
his last 11 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Cone struggled to find his command early in Saturday's game _
his slider and splitter were hanging and he got away with several
potentially disastrous pitches, perhaps because he was facing the
weak-hitting Devil Rays. But Cone slowed his pace, recovered and
pitched effectively in his last four innings. ``I found a pretty
good rhythm,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   He struck out eight, walked two and gave up two runs, and Torre
said he was pleased. Torre and the pitching coach, Mel Stottlemyre,
began discussing the Yankees' playoff rotation Saturday, and they
have more good options than any other team headed for the
post-season.
</P>
<P>
   But Torre faces several tough decisions as well. A few weeks
ago, he mentioned Cone as a possible starter for Game 1 of the
playoffs. Now Torre appears to be leaning toward starting Cone in
either Game 3 or Game 4. Cone may not be winning as much as he did
in the first half, but the Yankees have had success when he starts
_ winning 19 of his 30 outings, as Cone noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, Joe has slotted me in for Game 3,'' Cone said,
referring to the first round of last year's playoffs and the World
Series in 1996 and 1998. ``I wouldn't be surprised if that's the
case again _ or maybe even lower.''
</P>
<P>
   Without being specific, Torre mentioned before the game that he
had three starters who are capable of pitching Game 1, three
starters who are pitching well. Presumably, Torre was referring to
Orlando Hernandez (16-9), Andy Pettitte (14-11) and Roger Clemens
(14-9). Pettitte most likely will pitch Game 1 or Game 2 in Yankee
Stadium, because the Yankees will probably play Texas in the
Division Series and Pettitte has not pitched well in the Rangers'
park.
</P>
<P>
   The Game 1 starter also will have the responsibility of pitching
the fifth game if the three-of-five-game series plays out fully.
Since the trade deadline, when Torre and General Manager Brian
Cashman lobbied to keep Pettitte, the left-hander has been the
team's most consistent pitcher, going 7-3 with a 2.70 earned run
average.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez lasted a third of an inning in Seattle in early
August, but over his last nine starts, El Duque is 4-2 with a 3.46
e.r.a. Clemens, too, has shown marked improvement that has not
always translated into victories and losses. After allowing 138
hits and 60 walks in his first 1261/3 innings _ 1.6 base runners
per inning _ Clemens has surrendered 43 hits and 25 walks in his
last 551/3 innings, or 1.2 base runners per inning, with a 3.58
e.r.a.
</P>
<P>
   Torre almost always goes back to what he trusts, and he will
always trust Hernandez following his pivotal victory in Game 4 of
the Championship Series last year.
</P>
<P>
   It may be that when Torre sorts through his rotation, Hernandez
will start Game 1, Pettitte Game 2, Clemens and Cone in Games 3 and
4. Decisions, decisions. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
