<SLUG> BC-GOVERNMENT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOVERNMENT'S CURIOUS CASE AGAINST BIG TOBACCO  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The administration's decision to sue the
tobacco industry for tens of billions of dollars is based on
economic theory that is as mendacious as it is specious.
</P>
<P>
   The action is based on claims that tobacco producers impose
medical costs on society by selling goods that damage the public
health. Therefore, the theory goes, the public has a right to
relief because of the economic burden tobacco use creates for
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   This claim sounds plausible, which explains why so many tobacco
foes have embraced it without question. It is part of the
anti-tobacco crusade mantra, and has become a cornerstone of
government's efforts to add legal booty to the tax-revenue stream
from tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, all the available evidence points the other way. When
tobacco's critics make such assertions, they lack convincing
research to buttress such claims.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there is substantial support for the
contention that both the tobacco industry and smokers more than pay
the costs of dealing with smoking-related illnesses. The work of
Harvard Law School economist Kim Viscusi stands out, but is only
part of the considerable body of research done by credible
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   For those disposed to a fair-minded approach, this view should
be at least as plausible as the claim that nonsmoking taxpayers are
unfairly saddled with smokers' medical bills. It's difficult to
imagine either an industry or a consumer group more taxed than
tobacco producers and their customers. Philip Morris chief
executive Geoffrey Bible put the situation into perspective in
remarks at this year's stockholders meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excise taxes on cigarettes alone,'' he said, ``contribute more
than $13 billion a year to federal, state and local governments
(and) that's before the industry shells out some 40 percent of it
profits in corporate income taxes....At Philip Morris, we are so
heavily and so unfairly taxed that we were the largest single
(U.S.) taxpayer last year. We have also been among the largest
corporate sources of funds in many states....If the rest of the
country's top 150 companies paid as much to the federal government
as we do, (it) could just about eliminate the personal income
tax.''
</P>
<P>
   The other side of the equation is the morbidity factor. While
tobacco producers and consumers produce more than enough tax
revenue to pay for their medical care, their habit meanwhile
contributes to their early demise and thus saves the public money.
As recently as June, the Congressional Research Service, a federal
agency, issued a report concluding that premature deaths by smokers
actually saved the U.S. $29 billion annually in pension and
health-care outlays.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see how Justice Department litigators
deal with this sort of inconvenient data when attempting to prove
the administration's claims.
</P>
<P>
   Factual niceties aside, though, what's most curious about this
initiative from an economic perspective is how it risks killing a
goose that lays such huge golden eggs. Given that tobacco is an
incredibly lucrative source of revenue year in and year out, what's
the point of trying to further weaken its viability as an industry
with another potentially crippling lawsuit?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
