<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYFUL PUP LEARNS TO GET DOWN TO BUSINESS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Brittany pup, Cyrus _ 16 weeks old
tomorrow _ is finding his place in our family.
</P>
<P>
   He's the son of Holly's Bear, and a grandson of that fine old
hunter, Rufus, who sleeps now in an abandoned fence row at the edge
of a quail meadow, the grave marked by a carefully laid stack of
lichened stones.
</P>
<P>
   The talents of the paternal line, and also those of the mother,
Maggie, appear to have been transmitted in full measure. At age 8
weeks, the day after he came home, Cyrus pointed quite stylishly
the first quail wing put before him.
</P>
<P>
   For his sire, Bear, fatherhood has taken some getting used to.
</P>
<P>
   It was a week before he could bear even to look at the wretched
creature, and two more before he'd permit the youngster to
approach. Mostly he sat in the far corner of the yard, wishing he'd
known beforehand the penalty for a spring romance.
</P>
<P>
   Just in the last few days I have seen a change. He has touched
noses with Cyrus and even let the feisty pup torment him a bit,
although his tolerance for that is short and he soon withdraws
again.
</P>
<P>
   Bear's heart is softening, but clearly he's worried about where
such permissiveness might lead.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Pete _ Bear's brother and thus the pup's uncle _ is
wonderfully indulgent. Cyrus devils him endlessly. If Pete picks up
a stick to carry around the yard, a favorite activity, Cy scampers
along beside him, trying to seize the other end.
</P>
<P>
   If the long-suffering uncle decides to rest on the step outside
the breakfast room door, the pup clamps his needle-toothed jaws on
his leg or throat or ear. Sometimes I hear Pete groan a bit, but
mostly I think it brings back memories of his own puppyhood.
</P>
<P>
   Those two romp together endlessly and except for the difference
in size you almost could imagine them littermates.
</P>
<P>
   The older dogs and I are summer soft. We'll need to work at
getting fit. So on a recent chilly morning _ one that held fine
promise of the season's turning _ we made an outing past the city's
edge for some exercise together.
</P>
<P>
   At first Cyrus would have been glad enough to play, if either of
the others had had a mind to. But then he saw how they lifted their
noses to decipher any messages that might come to them on the crisp
air.
</P>
<P>
   And he saw how they plunged boldly into the thickest cover, and
how, when they'd been out of sight for several moments, they came
out of the brush and weeds to show themselves and check the
position of the man.
</P>
<P>
   The pup observed all this, and it spoke to some part of him that
wasn't puppyish at all _ some memory as old as the memory of his
kind. And in only minutes, his manner entirely changed.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of tagging along he was out ahead with father and uncle,
still patterning himself on them, but making independent excursions
of his own, reading the breeze for himself.
</P>
<P>
   It's certain that he'll be hunting in November _ not expertly
yet, but well enough to show his promise. He'll be in his sixth
month then. If a dog's year makes seven human ones, that means
he'll still be a tot of only 3.
</P>
<P>
   You've read about, or possibly even known, those amazing
youngsters who dazzle their elders by playing the violin, composing
symphonies or mastering the game of chess.
</P>
<P>
   No dog of mine has ever been gifted in quite that way. But as
luck would have it, I've never had one that wasn't a prodigy at the
work he was born to do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
