<HEADLINE>
AS YEN RISES, FISCAL POWERS DEBATE MERITS OF INTERVENING  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  
(SUBS for new top)  By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Japan on Saturday yielded to international pressure
and agreed to take some extraordinary steps to reverse the recent
and surprising climb of the Japanese yen against the dollar, which
has rattled Wall Street in recent days and threatened Japan's
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   After an all-day meeting here, the finance ministers of the
Group of 7 largest industrial countries issued a joint communique
saying the Japanese authorities had, in effect, agreed to even
deeper deficit spending and to begin printing yen to prompt
inflation. Interest rates in Japan are already virtually zero, so
the move represents a last-ditch effort to keep the yen's rise from
making the country's exports more expensive around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In return the United States and other major nations issued a
vague threat that they might jointly intervene in the markets to
weaken the yen and strengthen the dollar, a warning sign to
currency traders who have been dumping the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   If Japan actually begins trying to spur inflation _ in hopes of
weakening the yen and encouraging its own consumers to stop saving
and start buying _ it would be an enormous change of strategy.
Hyperinflation in the years before World War II still weighs
heavily on the country, and since 1945 Japan has been strongly
conservative, keeping inflation to an absolute minimum.
</P>
<P>
   The wording of the statement Saturday was deliberately
ambiguous, an effort to keep investors guessing and prevent them
from betting against the dollar. Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers Saturday night pointed to a paragraph that he said was
``very carefully worded,'' which referred to Japan's agreement to
``provide ample liquidity until deflationary concerns are
dispelled.'' But he said he would not ``interpret that remark,''
nor would he say whether the United States would finally join Japan
in intervening in the markets.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's finance minister, Kiichi Miyawaza, was asked Saturday
night if the United States and other countries had agreed to
intervene. He declined to offer a specific answer _ finance
ministers never do _ but said, ``You could feel and see for
yourself that full recognition of the situation has been gained.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting of the finance ministers and central bank chiefs did
not carry the high drama of their session a year ago, when Russia's
currency had collapsed and markets around the world appeared on the
precipice of disaster. Asia has since begun a slow recovery, and
even Japan has showed signs of pulling out of a recession that
began more than seven years ago. In fact, the renewed interest of
investors in putting their money into Japan is one reason the yen
has risen by more than 15 percent against the dollar since
mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   But big currency moves can also cause big problems. It was the
steady rise of the dollar from 1995 to 1997 that indirectly helped
start the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Until Saturday night, the United States had indicated no
willingness to join Japan in meddling with the currency markets by
pouring in yen, and trying to reduce the currency's value against
the dollar. Instead, the United States has been pushing Japan to
lower its interest rates even further _ no easy trick here _ and to
force it to keep spending heavily on new roads and other projects
to stimulate the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But the newly independent Bank of Japan declined to lower
interest rates earlier in the week, outraging Japanese politicians.
And Tokyo is now running up such huge deficits that it threatens to
get itself into the same kind of fiscal problem the United States
fell into in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The standoff on how to respond to the problem has become the
first big test for Summers, a former Harvard economist who became
Treasury secretary in July. ``This will be an interesting moment to
see how much Larry learned about timing, about how to keep the
markets guessing, and about how to keep the Japanese guessing,'' a
senior administration official said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Planning _ or feigning _ currency interventions is a bit like
threatening military strikes. Governments want to keep the markets
guessing a bit about the timing and size of the attack, in hopes
that just the fear of intervention will be enough to change the
market's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of the yen was not the only problem on the agenda.
Russian officials were invited to sit in on the end of the Group of
7 meeting, chiefly to receive a warning that the wealthy nations
will not be willing to extend further aid unless Russia agrees to
regular, far more intrusive audits into how it uses loans from the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional hearings this past week focused attention on the
widespread corruption in Russia, though so far there is no evidence
that the fund's money was diverted.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night's communique said Russia's central bank must take
steps to improve its ``internal controls and initiate quarterly
audits'' before getting any future IMF funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
