A6343 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-FBI[HEAD &QC; IMAGEOFTHEFB     09-25 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 [HEAD  IMAGE OF THE FBI IS BEING DESTROYED 2TAKES -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A half-century before black smoke rose above the Branch Davidian
compound near Waco, Texas, little boys sent fan mail to J. Edgar
Hoover. He led the good guys at the Federal Bureau of
Investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Mr. Hoover,'' wrote Mickey from New York. ``Please help
me and my friends start an FBI club. We need guns, bombs and other
things to surprise the crooks.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI's image today, as U.S. Sen. Charles Grassley describes
it, would surprise Mickey.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the top there's been a rush to judgment on high-profile
cases,'' said the Iowa Republican, one of Capitol Hill's critics of
the bureau. ``And that's destroying the image of the FBI.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency is under fire from former allies: Washington
politicians, Hollywood filmmakers, the far right. Grassley, like
Mickey, grew up at a time when the ``Junior G-Man'' craze was
embraced. Most Americans didn't know how the bureau really worked.
Decades would pass before Hoover's penchant for heavy handedness,
surveillance and cover-up would surface.
</P>
<P>
   FBI observers say the agency's troubles of late, including
evidence of a Waco cover-up, add fresh scars to a face that people
once thought was unblemished.
</P>
<P>
   Reckless sharpshooting at Ruby Ridge? Whistle-blowing at the
crime lab? Confessing to firing incendiary tear-gas canisters at
Waco after years of denials?
</P>
<P>
   Author and historian Richard Gid Powers said the agency's image
problems were mounting at an unlikely time.
</P>
<P>
   Since Louis J. Freeh became FBI director several months after
the 1993 siege at Waco, ``the primary in-house training has been in
the area of ethics,'' said Powers. ``They've developed a
zero-tolerance policy for lying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freeh is very serious about changing the culture,'' he said.
``And yet, you have all these stories coming out. It's got to be
demoralizing.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest story hit Thursday, adding to the public's confusion
about the FBI's investigation into China's theft of American
nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI last week derailed its three-year investigation of an
alleged Chinese spy, Wen Ho Lee, who had been dismissed from his
job at Los Alamos National Laboratory. A new inquiry will look at
more than 500 potential suspects at scores of nuclear research
sites across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Was Lee off the hook? Government officials told the Los Angeles
Times the inquiry was stalled for lack of evidence but the Justice
Department wasn't ruling out prosecuting Lee.
</P>
<P>
   With such embarrassments, some experts fear the FBI's efforts to
recruit agents could stall. The bureau's traditional immunity from
Congress' budget ax could end, informants may be less willing to
work with the FBI and juries might even think twice about
convicting suspects arrested by the agency.
</P>
<P>
   None of that has happened. But recent political attacks on the
bureau's credibility could bring it about, said retired Special
Agent Buck Revell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're teetering on it now,'' Revell said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, FBI spokeswoman Anita Dickens said the agency was
attracting the faithful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get roughly 1,000 applications a day from people wanting to
be agents,'' she said. ``People still believe we are the premier
law enforcement agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any organization is going to be criticized. My personal belief
is that the country is more cynical than it used to be. Among the
FBI's low points of the decade: In 1992 _ the year before Freeh
took over _ federal agents squared off with tax resisters at Ruby
Ridge, Idaho. During an 11-day standoff at Randy Weaver's ranch, an
FBI sniper shot and killed Weaver's wife. The marksman said he hit
the wrong target.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver, a white separatist, collected $3 million in a wrongful
death suit. A judge dismissed criminal charges against the sniper.
</P>
<P>
   The Waco disaster occurred the following April, after members of
David Koresh's armed camp killed four agents of the federal Bureau
of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms. The FBI's plan to overtake the
compound ended in a blaze, which the bureau says was set by the
Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   Koresh shot himself, and more than six dozen of his followers
died in the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Right-wing patriot groups and firearms enthusiasts point to Waco
and Ruby Ridge as proof that federal authorities are determined to
encroach on citizens' rights.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has heard it before, but from a different crowd. In the
1960s the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr._ a target of FBI surveillance
_ joined others on the political left in denouncing the bureau's
lack of concern for the civil rights of blacks and anti-war
demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this opposition from the right _ that's new,'' said
University of Wisconsin law professor Frank Tuerkheimer, a former
U.S. attorney. ``The very conservatives who ordinarily are pro-law
enforcement have become anti-government. And the FBI is
government.''
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents investigating the 1996 Olympics bombing in Atlanta at
first suspected security guard Richard Jewell. They planned to
trick him into talking.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming to be making a training film, agents questioned him
until director Freeh intervened, ordering them to read Jewell his
Miranda rights.
</P>
<P>
   FBI and U.S. Justice Department officials later exonerated
Jewell and apologized. Still, his name had leaked nationwide as the
key suspect in the blast. And the real culprit hasn't yet been
found.
</P>
<P>
   Also unsolved is the 1996 explosion of TWA Flight 800, in which
230 persons died. While Treasury Department investigators pointed
to a possible flaw in the aircraft's fuel tank, the FBI refused to
rule out sabotage. Grassley called the FBI's investigation ``a
model of failure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's inspector general in 1997 issued a
scathing report on ``inexcusable'' practices at the bureau's crime
lab. Some testing led to ``conclusions that incriminated the
defendants without a scientific basis,'' the report said. The roof
leaked and researchers stored evidence haphazardly.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, an FBI task force followed the false leads of an
imprisoned convict who had implicated himself in the murders of
three sightseers at Yosemite National Park. A fourth slaying
occurred in late July. A motel handyman named Cary Stayner, whom
authorities had questioned earlier, confessed to all four killings
and now faces trial.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh, Attorney General Janet Reno and other Justice officials
have been publicly contrite and insist they'll get to the bottom of
any problems within the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Their supporters point out the bureau's successes of the 1990s:
the conviction of mob boss John Gotti; the capture of Theodore
Kaczynski, the Unabomber; the peaceful resolution of the Montana
``freemen'' standoff in 1995; linking terrorist financier Osama bin
Laden to the U.S. embassy bombings in Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
