<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6353 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-FBI[HEAD &QC; IMAGEOFTHEFB     09-25 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 [HEAD  IMAGE OF THE FBI IS BEING DESTROYED 2NDTAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the World Trade Center bombing, the bureau corralled the
Muslim perpetrators before they could blow up the Lincoln Tunnel
and the United Nations building.
</P>
<P>
   If the FBI's image is hurting, the budget doesn't show it. Under
President Clinton the FBI's allocation has jumped 25 percent, to
about $3 billion now, while other agencies have watched funds
evaporate. The bureau's detractors in Congress, which approves the
spending, know that crime-fighting remains a popular campaign
issue, observers said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Grassley says he thinks the rank-and-file agents are honest
and doing a tough, commendable job.
</P>
<P>
   ``You listen closely to the Republicans, and nobody's really
taking on the FBI per se,'' said Tuerkheimer. ``They're taking on
the attorney general'' to get to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Others say the FBI's problems extend beyond partisan politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to recognize that institutions have cultures,'' said
Robert Unger, author of The Union Station Massacre: The Original
Sin of J. Edgar Hoover's FBI. ``The culture of the FBI has been
developing since Day One.''
</P>
<P>
   Unger's 1997 examination of the shootout at Union Station
suggested the bureau covered up mistakes that were 64 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Records from the 1933 investigation convinced Unger that Hoover,
in his zeal to propel his bureau to national prominence, relied on
slim evidence and ``dead wrong, flat-out lies'' in blaming
gangsters for the deaths of four lawmen. The Kansas City author
determined that most of the killing was done by the officers.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent ABC News poll, 57 percent of Americans said they
thought the FBI had been ``intentionally trying to cover up its
actions at Waco.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 23 percent said the agency made ``an honest mistake'' when
it denied using potentially flammable tear gas canisters. The rest
voiced no opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Such doubts about the FBI's credibility present a situation that
mobsters, drug traffickers and their lawyers have tried to create
for decades. Their task of convincing jurors to be wary of the
bureau may get easier if its image continues to fray, said ex-agent
Revell.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers across the country already have tried entering
into evidence news clippings of FBI blunders to sway juries into
thinking that their clients, too, were wrongly targeted. None of
these defense tactics has led to an acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Jones, attorney for convicted Oklahoma City bomber
Timothy McVeigh, tried but failed to convince his jury that
slipshod FBI work _ particularly at the crime lab _ allowed the
real killers to get away.
</P>
<P>
   History suggests the FBI will survive. For example, Clarence
Kelley helped restore accountability and honesty to the FBI after
Hoover's death, Powers said. Kelley, a former Kansas City police
chief, headed the bureau from 1973 to 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Today, FBI public relations officers still present a positive
image, but have relaxed when it comes to Hollywood's portrayal of
the bureau, many observers said.
</P>
<P>
   Jodie Foster's character in ``The Silence of the Lambs'' may
have been frightened while hunting a killer, but the number of
women recruits at the FBI soared after the film's release. The
bureaucrats portrayed in ``The X-Files'' and ``The Rock'' may have
been
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 2338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990925.0316 </DOCNO>
