</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV$03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Oct. 3)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE STORY OF AMERICAN FREEDOM &LR;  By Eric Foner. Norton, $15.95. A
historian argues that freedom is not a fixed set of principles but
a ``complex of values'' that have evolved over time as various
excluded groups have struggled for liberty. ``The book's strongest
claim to distinction lies ... in its succinct, information-packed,
wonderfully readable account of the twists and turns in
20th-century American history,'' Pauline Maier wrote in The New
York Times Book Review in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE POISONWOOD BIBLE &LR;  By Barbara Kingsolver. Harper Perennial,
$14. The story of a fanatical Baptist clergyman who uproots his
Georgia family and sets them down in the Belgian Congo in 1959 is
narrated by his wife and four daughters, each of whom abandons one
faith and discovers another as their lives unravel in the jungle.
This novel, selected as one of the best books of 1998 by the
editors of The New York Times Book Review, also has much to say
about America and its homegrown brand of missionary zeal. ``For all
its portraiture of place'' the narrative is ``shaped by keen-eyed
women contemplating themselves and one another and a village whose
familiarity it takes a tragedy to discover,'' Verlyn Klinkenborg
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CINDERELLA &AMP; COMPANY: Backstage at the Opera With Cecilia
Bartoli &LR;  By Manuela Hoelterhoff. Vintage, $14. This profile of the
Italian mezzo-soprano Cecilia Bartoli is also a withering look at
modern opera: the industry's youth-obsessed star-making machinery,
the intense egomania and raging insecurities, the brutal sniping.
The result ``is a naughtily witty tell-almost-all book,'' Terry
Teachout wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OPERA, OR THE UNDOING OF WOMEN &LR; , by Catherine Clement
(University of Minnesota, $17.95), is a scholarly critique by a
European feminist who argues that opera is one long tale of male
domination in which victimized women characters are consigned to a
``sung death.'' In 1989 the reviewer Paul Robinson called this ``a
highly original interpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE VOYAGE OF THE NARWHAL &LR;  By Andrea Barrett. Norton, $14. A
British naturalist embarks on a voyage of self-discovery when he
boards a vessel searching for clues to the mysterious disappearance
of Sir John Franklin's Arctic expedition of 1845. Last year the
reviewer Annette Kobak called this novel a ``marvelous
achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOO COOL &LR;  By Duff Brenna. Plume, $12.95. In this raw novel
about teen-age desperadoes in Colorado, a 16-year-old misfit named
Triple E escapes from reform school and gets stranded with his
girlfriend in a heavy snowstorm. The result is ``an unfaltering,
unflinching, piercing look into a tormented youthful heart,''
Richard Bernstein wrote in 1998 in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE NURTURE ASSUMPTION: Why Children Turn Out the Way They Do &LR; 
By Judith Rich Harris. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $15. Melding
research from many fields, a former writer of textbooks on
developmental psychology makes the provocative case that children
are shaped more by their own temperament and peers than by the
input of their parents. No matter which side of the argument
readers come down on, ``Harris writes beautifully, in a tone both
persuasive and conversational,'' Carol Tavris wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LUNCH-BOX CHRONICLES: Notes From the Parenting
Underground &LR; , by Marion Winik (Vintage, $12), is a frontline report
on child rearing by a commentator for National Public Radio. ``Take
Erma Bombeck, add the obsessions of a single mother ... and you
have Marion Winik, as companionable a writer as a crazed parent
ever found,'' Andrea Cooper wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MALINA &LR;  By Ingeborg Bachmann. Holmes &AMP; Meier, $15.95. A
Viennese woman plagued by violent dreams navigates difficult
relationships with two men, one of whom forces her to confront the
pain of her childhood. ``This courageous and important novel,''
originally published in German in 1971, ``is equal to the best of
Virginia Woolf and Samuel Beckett,'' Peter Filkins wrote in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MY YEAR OFF &LR;  By Robert McCrum. Broadway, $13. The author was 42
and the editor in chief of a major London publishing house when he
suffered a paralyzing stroke. This ``lucid, heartfelt'' account of
his arduous recovery ``is a testament to the parallel trials and
the courage of the family members of stroke victims,'' Abraham
Verghese wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MACKEREL BY MOONLIGHT &LR;  By William F. Weld. Pocket Star, $6.99.
This mystery novel by the former Massachusetts governor is about an
assistant U.S. attorney from Brooklyn whose shadowy past resurfaces
after he opts for a job in a white-shoe Boston law firm and a life
in politics. Last year the reviewer Donald E. Westlake admired the
``deft and devious story-telling.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THIRST &LR;  By Ken Kalfus. Washington Square/Pocket Books, $12.95.
Many of these stories are brief and jarring fantasies, including
one in which Marco Polo describes a series of indoor retail malls
to the emperor Kublai Khan. ``The displaced figures in `Thirst'
drift through worlds that are at once astonishing and familiar,''
Ron Carlson wrote last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-99 2338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
