<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLS STRUGGLING AT THE FINISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Three weeks ago Los Angeles Dodgers reliever Alan
Mills was hoping to keep his ERA under three. That goal was
revamped. Now, he wants to make sure his ERA doesn't jump above
four before the season runs out next Sunday in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   In a year in which everything's gone wrong, add the recent
struggles of Mills to the list of Dodgers' concerns heading into
what could be a tumultuous offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Mills, the right-hander signed to a three-year contract last
season, has experienced control problems of late. While the Dodgers
believe he is in a typical funk that plagues nearly every pitcher
at one point in a season, they want to see him break out of it. In
his past four outings he's allowed six runs and walked four in 32/3
innings. It's pushed his ERA from 3.27 to 3.90.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I'm healthy, what I'm going through right now, I'm
going to let it take care of itself,'' Mills said. ``I just need to
make adjustments. It's just a period where I have to get through it
and try not to make it last too long. You'd like to end on a good
note so you can at least go home with something positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Home at the Ravine: By watching most of the Dodgers' starters,
it was hard to tell Chavez Ravine is a pitcher's ballpark. But even
with home runs flying out at a record rate _ the Dodgers had
allowed 97 before Saturday, breaking the 1970 mark of 82 _
right-hander Kevin Brown proved it was more because of pitching
than atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who's 18 wins tie for the second most in his career, went
9-3 with a 1.95 ERA in 16 home starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some places the mound fits you and you feel comfortable,''
said Brown, who was 1-1 with a 2.70 ERA at Dodger Stadium before
this year. ``Maybe eating home-cooked meals. I don't know how to
explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   Crackerjack lineup: With little to do for the next week, Dodgers
manager Davey Johnson was reminiscing about his playing days with
the Baltimore Orioles under Earl Weaver, who liked to switch around
lineups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember telling the newspaper (reporters) that looking at
the lineup every day is like a box of cracker jacks,'' Johnson
said. ``You don't know what's you're going to get.''
</P>
<P>
   FYI: Dodgers left fielder Gary Sheffield's two-run homer in the
fourth inning was his 30th of the season. It's the third time in
his career he's hit 30, and the first since 1996.... Right fielder
Raul Mondesi entered the game with 90 RBI, tied for his career
best. He's already established a career high for homers (31) and
stolen bases (33).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
